<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEZBOLLAH GUERRILLAS RECLAIM SOUTH LEBANON AS ISRAELIS WITHDRAW
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for new third graf confirming Israelis have abandoned last
outpost in Lebanon; subs 4th graf for rewriting)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make one-time purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BINT JBAIL, Lebanon _ Draped with bandoliers, Shiite Muslim
guerrillas reclaimed the Israeli-occupied zone in southern Lebanon
on Tuesday, and as they giddily rode abandoned Israeli tanks
through village after village, they laid waste to Israel's plan for
an orderly, scheduled withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks before the Israelis planned to shut down the military
buffer zone they controlled along the border, the Lebanese
guerrillas accelerated their enemy's departure. By day's end,
Israel held only Beaufort Castle, on a bluff in Lebanon overlooking
northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   (Before dawn Wednesday, the Israelis abandoned that and all of
their outposts in Lebanon, and were bringing home their last
troops, Israeli military officials said. Shortly after sunrise, the
last tank rumbled across the frontier behind a column of armored
vehicles, and the border fence was locked.)
</P>
<P>
   With the troops leaving, Israel's occupation of a swath of
Lebanon, maintained since 1978, was ending in a far quicker and
more improvisational way than anyone predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is only one headline in Lebanon tonight,'' a broadly
smiling anchorwoman said on the official state television channel.
``The liberation of the land. The slinking, servile withdrawal by
Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli prime minister, Ehud Barak, has protested assertions
by the Hezbollah, or Party of God, guerrillas that Israel was being
chased out. He made a campaign pledge last year, he said
repeatedly, to end Israel's ``misguided'' involvement in Lebanon,
which has divided and troubled Israelis from the start.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday in Jerusalem, Barak declared an end to the ``18-year
tragedy'' dating from Israel's large-scale invasion of Lebanon in
1982, and his government declared that it has regained the
initiative in the halting Middle East peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Israel said that from now on it would hold the governments in
Beirut and Damascus, Syria, responsible for any attacks on northern
Israel from Lebanese territory.
</P>
<P>
   But Lebanon, flashing a nationwide victory sign, would have none
of that sort of talk on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   All day long, traveling with Hezbollah into the land so long
held by its Israeli enemies, a celebratory procession grew as it
wound its way from west to east through the rugged countryside. By
the road, elderly Lebanese women ululated and sprinkled the cars
with rose petals and rice as if at a wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Flashing V's and waving the yellow flags of their Iranian-backed
Hezbollah movement, the guerrillas trailed a miles-long parade of
supporters, including villagers returning to the south for the
first time in two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when birds fly out of a cage?'' said Abu Jaffa, 26, a
Hezbollah officer. ``That's how we feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Like sports announcers, local radio reporters gave a village by
village account of the ``liberation'' of the nine-mile-deep zone
over the course of the day. ``Yarun is now liberated,'' one said on
Tuesday morning, ``and I'm looking over into occupied Palestine.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel accelerated the disintegration of its control over the
zone by pulling out its troops and equipment in stages and turning
over many posts to the Israeli-backed South Lebanese Army. But town
by town, the Israeli-backed militia soldiers caved in to local
pressure. And those who did not seek to cross over into Israel
turned themselves over to local Hezbollah leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The tumble of events began last Thursday when the South Lebanese
Army deserted a small village. It picked up steam on Sunday, when
the militia left behind a more significant post. And then it
snowballed, catching everyone by surprise, including Lebanese
journalists who scrambled to set up television links in this
central town so that they could record the event that most had been
waiting a career to capture.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday night, about 620 of the 2,000-strong South Lebanese
Army militia had ``defected,'' according to Lebanese officials.
Many face charges of treason. Although it was made public that the
Lebanese army was now detaining them, no mention was made of where
or of what might become of them.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, Israel planned to blow up its posts before
completing the withdrawal, as it had done in the village of Jezzin,
abandoned last year. But the situation changed before they could
carry out their plans. In at least one instance on Tuesday, the SLA
soldiers disappeared so quickly that they left tanks with their
motors running and rice cooking on the stove.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah fighters quickly foraged through the deserted posts,
stocking up on Israeli rocket launchers, ammunition and gear before
Israel had a chance to do anything about it. In some cases,
Hezbollah fighters squabbled over the Hebrew-inscribed equipment
with members of Amal, another resistance group.
</P>
<P>
   As a honking convoy of newly captured Israeli tanks headed to
Bint Jbail in the zone's center. Israeli helicopters began buzzing
overhead. Soon, they were bombarding some of their own abandoned
posts. and the raids briefly detained the sweep through the
countryside.
</P>
<P>
   One man, Abed Taqoush, 50, died in the bombing. He was a veteran
taxi driver for the foreign press who helped reporters from around
the world cover the conflict in Lebanon for 23 years.
</P>
<P>
   As it resumed, the convoy converted a narrow road into a traffic
jam directed by gun-toting Hezbollah crossing guards. The Hezbollah
fighters, who kept a low profile in Lebanon as they fought the
Israelis, launching mortar attacks from citrus groves, surfaced
spontaneously and talked relatively freely.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``They have run in the end,`` said one youth who gave his name
as Jawad, speaking of the Israelis. ``We always knew they would,
but no one would have guessed it could happen so quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the battle was over, the young men said that that
decision was up to Hezbollah's secretary general, Sheik Hassan
Nasrallah. ``Our purpose is to be told what to do,'' another said.
``If Nasrallah says the fight is on, it's on. And if it's off, it's
off.'' His fellow fighter, however, noted that they had gotten as
far as they had because ``Jerusalem twinkles in our eyes'' _ a
comment that would chill many Israelis to the bone.
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, the southern zone was off-limits to most
Lebanese. Starting mid-morning, Lebanese army officers opened the
tightly controlled checkpoints and packed cars began rolling past
the gates that have divided the country.
</P>
<P>
   Many cars contained fighters for the Hezbollah movement and its
true believers, like Hala Smayel and a gaggle of young women
friends, who alternated jumping up and down with yelling
``Nasrallah forever.'' They dragged out his name into four
syllables, so that it sounded like `Nasser-Allah,'' a play on words
since nasser means victory and Allah is God.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going village and village to give congratulations,''
Smayel said. ``Hezbollah was able to bring the most important
military force in the Middle East to its knees. Every drop of blood
from the martyrs will grow into a child and this child will grow in
an adult and this adult will fight Israel and become another
martyr.''
</P>
<P>
   By late afternoon, villagers had stormed the Khiam prison, which
was run by the Israeli-backed militia and renowned internationally
for alleged human rights abuses. The militia guards had already run
away, turning the prisoners over to the International Red Cross,
and the villagers accompanied them out the gates and back into
Lebanese life.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials said they were surprised that the day went as
peacefully as it did. They attributed that partly to the advance
work of Hezbollah and Amal leaders who had been spending time in
Christian communities in the south, trying to convince them that
they all should stand together, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese political leaders said that the military battle would
now become a diplomatic one. They said that they would fight for an
Israeli pullout from the Shebaa Farms area at the foot of the Golan
Heights, even though the United Nations said this week that it
would certify the withdrawal as complete without it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever difficulties happen in life, after every one there is
a catharsis, a joyous moment of release,'' Foda Ramadan, a
returning villager, said on Tuesday. ``And then there are new
difficulties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
