<SLUG> BC-BKN-WISE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS MEET THEIR MATCH IN PACERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ With seven minutes left, Patrick Ewing wheeled
into the lane and, with the shot clock running down, positioned
himself to take an 8-foot jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Knicks were in desperate need of points, having
falling behind by 11 to the Indiana Pacers in Game 1 of the Eastern
Conference finals. They did not look worn down from their annual
apocalyptic series against Miami as much as they looked befuddled
by an offensive machine, a skilled team capable of putting up 100
points, easy.
</P>
<P>
   So Ewing, New York's most effective option with the
7-foot-4-inch Rik Smits on the bench in foul trouble, rose for that
shot with every intention to make it a game. Dale Davis rose, too.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana power forward leaped so high, he met Ewing's shot at
its apex _ and sent it back to the floor along with the Knicks'
aspirations for another improbable victory in enemy territory.
Austin Croshere provided the fireworks on the offensive end.
</P>
<P>
   A loud mob in the heartland whooped and hollered, the people of
Conseco Fieldhouse standing and applauding their small-market
heroes, who had taken care of Ewing and his rowdy playground gang,
102-88.
</P>
<P>
   Terre Haute and French Lick would sleep well on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Van Gundy? He has a few problems.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-eight hours after taking Game 7 from the Heat, the Knicks
were essentially done in by two significant Pacer runs.
</P>
<P>
   The first came in the first quarter, a 35-17 binge that forced
the Knicks to play catch-up from then on.
</P>
<P>
   The second was even more costly. They crept to within 2 at 68-66
in the third quarter and were then pounded in the fourth. Reggie
Miller, spotting up. Jalen Rose, knifing through the lane. And
Davis, putting a body on Ewing, doing anything he could to stop the
Big Fella from having a huge game.
</P>
<P>
   Given the travel and time to prepare, the Knicks recovered from
what could have been a devastating blowout. Still, several matchups
went Indiana's way, and if that trend continues, New York is
looking at an 0-2 hole on Saturday at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   They have to guard Croshere as if he were Miller, because he
absolutely killed them from beyond the arc. He finished with 22
points and made 4 of 5 3-pointers, consistently taking a kick-out
pass and burying long jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pick-and-roll coverage hurt us,'' Chris Childs said. ``You
can't double-team Mark Jackson and not rotate to Croshere. He's too
good. When he started coming off screens, we didn't stay with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Knicks were blaming their first-quarter collapse on
malaise. They didn't seem to realize they have another rival on
their hands, intent on extracting revenge for last year's upset in
the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't into that game,'' Latrell Sprewell said. ``Although
we almost got all the way back, we expended so much energy getting
there we didn't have anything left. We didn't have that fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell can excuse himself from that description. He ended with
22 points and matched Miller's long, cold stares with several of
his own. Their grade-school show of bravado began in the second
quarter, when Miller knocked down a 3-pointer over Sprewell and
kept looking at him, until Sprewell responded with his own stare.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was more than a little miffed by Miller's gum-flapping
before the series, especially the part about the Knicks not
respecting the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't particularly care for him, but hey, it's not about
Reggie,'' Sprewell said. ``Bottom line, he's a good player and I
respect him as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell threw down a hard dunk in traffic over the Pacers with
2 minutes 42 seconds left in the third quarter. He looked at Miller
for several seconds afterward, enough time for Rose, his man, to
sneak downcourt for a dunk.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a crucial basket, but it was indicative of how the
Knicks forgot to prioritize.
</P>
<P>
   Outplayed by Jamal Mashburn early in the Miami series, Sprewell
responded in the final two games. He and Ewing kept the Knicks in
the game on Tuesday night. For the first two quarters, he kept Rose
scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be on my shoulders somewhat to try to contain
him,'' he said before the game. ``Jalen is inside, outside. He can
post you, he can sit out there on the 3. He can face you. I should
be able to stay in front of him. But he has a spin move. He's very
good at going one way and spinning the other way, sort of like
Jamal does. So I'm going to have to slide my feet very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The two are friends, who met in 1993 through their mutual
friend, Chris Webber.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care that we're friends, I'm still going hard,''
Sprewell said. ``I respect him and we're friends. But this is
business. All of that's out the door now.''
</P>
<P>
   It is too bad some of the other Knicks did not have that
disposition in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``They outplayed us,'' Childs said. ``We were on our heels. We
gave them everything and took away nothing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
