<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO LAUGHING MATTER FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. - If the video montage of Monday night's
third-quarter collapse wasn't enough to stir the Lakers' misplaced
passions, then perhaps one ingrained memory from the game's closing
minutes will serve the purpose as they recover from their worst
loss of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Blow-by-blow footage of the Portland Trail Blazers' 20-0 run was
replayed during Tuesday's film session, and the technical glitches
were highlighted by coach Phil Jackson. But Jackson wants his
players to remember the way the 106-77 rout ended - with the
Blazers yukking it up on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the first big loss the Lakers have suffered in these
playoffs, just the most damaging. Even when the Lakers got
dismantled by Sacramento and Phoenix, they always had the security
of knowing they just had to win all their home games (and they
did).
</P>
<P>
   Now they can't even say that, having lost home-court advantage,
the Western Conference finals now tied 1-1. A loss in Friday's Game
3 at Portland would put them in a deficit for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has reacted well to adversity, I have to give them
credit for that,'' Jackson said Tuesday. ``This is a different
situation, this type of adversity that you have in a series. What
we remember is the attitude that Portland carried off the floor
yesterday. They were kind of jackals down there on the bench, and
we have to remember that when we go back up to Portland, that they
might have been just a little too much so.''
</P>
<P>
   So there's the emotional appeal. The rest is textbook
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers have to devise a plan to get Shaquille O'Neal (23
points) the ball with room to work. Same goes for Kobe Bryant (12
points). And when all else fails, they need their role players to
make open jump shots, a key ingredient in their Game 1 win and a
glaring weakness in their Game 2 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a matter of turning down shots, it was just we were
taking shots that weren't comfortable for us to take,'' reserve
guard Brian Shaw said. ``We'd bring the ball down and stop around
the 3-point line, they'd sink in Shaq's lap, and then it'd be like,
OK, I'm going to settle for this shot instead of swinging it to the
other side, moving their defense and then trying to punch it in. Or
taking that same shot later in the shot clock.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the offensive ``desperation'' Jackson referred to
Monday night. It was a direct product of the Lakers' lack of
production from O'Neal and Bryant. With lanky forwards Scottie
Pippen and Rasheed Wallace free to roam, the Blazers crowded the
Lakers' two top scorers like no other team has.
</P>
<P>
   When the ball did get dished off, no one could find the net.
Rice went 3 for 9, Robert Horry 1 for 5, Derek Fisher 1 for 4 and
Shaw 2 for 6. The Lakers' 3-point accuracy dropped from 9 of 19 in
Game 1 to 6 of 23 in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their rotation on the defensive end was much quicker than (in
Game 1),'' Glen Rice said. ``They were very attentive, they
realized that in order for them to beat us when they do double down
on Shaq or Kobe, they've got to really get out on the wings and
stop the guys from shooting the jumpers. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``You've just got to keep moving the ball,'' Rice said. ``You
keep them on defense as long as you can to try and wear them down a
little bit. Hopefully, you'll get an opening in there and once you
get that opening, you gotta take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep the Blazers' forwards from roaming, the Lakers will need
better production from Ron Harper (guarded by Pippen) and A.C.
Green and Horry (guarded by Wallace). Harper went 2 for 6 and
played just 15 minutes. Green went 3 for 5 but was a defensive
liability against Wallace and logged only 16 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A.C. did a great job the first quarter,'' Jackson said, ``and
I think it stymied them. And we got the momentum and we actually
went into that quarter in good stead. Robert didn't have a good
shooting game and those things happen some nights, and we just have
to play it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers will have three days to fix everything. And three
days to ponder how they could suffer a 29-point rout in their own
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just move on,'' Bryant said. ``We're professional
athletes, so it's very easy to focus on the next game. In this type
of situation, you have to. It's playoff basketball. No matter if
you lose by 1 or 20, it's still 1-1 (in the series). ... It's all
about challenges in this game. If this game didn't present any type
of challenge, I wouldn't play. It makes it more fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
