<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4051 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-WAGNER-HNS     05-24 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-WAGNER-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JEROME SOLOMON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
The Astros knew, or should have known, that their starting pitching
would not be as strong this year as it was last year. They had to
expect some tough outings; no surprise there.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And even with a potent lineup, all hitters endure slumps during
a six-month season. So an off night or two at the plate for Jeff
Bagwell and Co. comes as no surprise, either.
</P>
<P>
   Put those two together with more frequency than predicted, and
you have a 16-28 start.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing no one could have expected, and the Astros
certainly did not factor into their plans, was inconsistency from
closer Billy Wagner.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner, one of the most feared relievers in baseball, already
has four blown saves in eight opportunities after blowing just
three saves the entire 1999 season (in 42 opportunities).
</P>
<P>
   Wagner is supposed to be The Man the Astros' Superman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a point in every pitcher's career when you go through
that,'' Wagner said. ``It kind of puts everything back into
perspective to know that you're human.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wagner has gone about his business proving he's no mere
mortal. In his career, he has converted 101 of 119 save
opportunities (85 percent) while averaging a dominant 14.1
strikeouts per nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this point, Wagner had 12 saves in 13 tries with a
1-1 record. He had 34 strikeouts in 18 innings and had allowed just
nine hits (two home runs) and served up six walks. The Astros'
record: 28-16.
</P>
<P>
   While Wagner's walks are not notably higher _ eight in 19
innings _ his strikeout count is substantially lower (23).
</P>
<P>
   But Wagner insists the ``panic theories'' he has heard are off
base. His fastball is just as fast _ and it moves _ and his slider
still slides. He is doing nothing different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was just a special year,'' he said. ``You can't
expect to match that every year. The hitters are taking shorter
swings than they used to, and they are getting a piece of the ball.
Flares here, bloops there singles hurt me more than home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I feel good when I go to the mound. And when I go to
(catcher Tony) Eusebio, someone who should know, he tells me he
sees no difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker said about the only slight difference he
can point to is pitch location, but he doesn't see that as a major
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the problem for the most part has been inconsistent
work,'' Dierker said. ``We haven't had enough leads, so he hasn't
been in there two days in a row, then take a day off, then (pitch)
another day, then (take) another day off. So his control has not
been as good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year what really vaulted him from just a strikeout
pitcher to the Fireman of the Year was he could put his fastball on
the corner any time he wanted to, and he has not been able to do
that this year. He'll do that when we start giving him more leads
and he gets more consistent work.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker has a point.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner got the save in the Astros' opening-day win over
Pittsburgh on April 4, picked up a save in a win over Philadelphia
on April 8, then followed with another as the Astros topped St.
Louis on April 12.
</P>
<P>
   But it was nine games and 11 days before Wagner got another save
opportunity, which he blew against San Diego. Another nine games
and 11 days went by before Wagner was sent to the mound again with
a game on the line; this time he came through, retiring four
consecutive Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   More than a week later, Wagner was unsuccessful in back-to-back
save opportunities against the Reds at Enron Field as he gave up
three runs in 2 innings in a pair of crushing losses.
</P>
<P>
   His most recent blown save may have been the most disappointing,
when he was part of a seven-run collapse in the ninth inning of
Monday's first-game loss at Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker's theory is that the team has not been in enough winning
situations for Wagner to get into rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``That plays a part, but I don't want to use that as an
excuse,'' Wagner said. ``Whenever you get a save opportunity, you
need to go out there and do your job. I just think it's sort of
that my team's struggling and we're all just falling into that
trap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talking to some of the older players, they've heard about it.
It's not an easy thing to go through. You just have to continue to
go out and play hard, do the best you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the season, Wagner figured he would have a battle with
elbow problems that plagued him at the end of last year. But he
says his left arm feels fine, and that's a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   There is no injury to point to, just a run of tough luck _ for
him and the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``During spring training and the first two weeks of the season
it was tender, but now I'm just as healthy as ever,'' he said. ``I
feel good. It's kind of strange. I feel like I'm throwing the ball
where I want it. The velocity is good; everything seems to be
there. I just seem to catch enough of their bats for them to hurt
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (the problem) is physical, there's nothing you can do
about it. When it's just the luck of the draw, you just have to
battle through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said, ``I don't think he's worried about his elbow
anymore; now he's worried about his pitching. While I don't think
he's done his best, and that's obvious, I do think he will come
back and pitch as well as he has in the past.
</P>
<P>
   `` We need to present him with enough leads to where he can
think more about making pitches than about how bad the team needs
the win.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
