r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-24 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PANIC SHOWN BY JACKSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. - All was eerily quiet on the purple-and-gold
front Tuesday. Indeed, the media assembled in an undersized holding
pen at the Lakers' practice facility sweated more than the players
did.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Phil Jackson did not have his disciples practicing at the
crack of dawn as a kind of penance for their laggard play the night
before in a 29-point loss to the Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   He did not have Robert Horry taking liquid calories
intravenously, the better to bulk up so he can bang bodies with
Rasheed Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson did not order A.C. Green to run laps until he had shed
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   He did not make Shaquille O'Neal sit in the lotus position,
chanting until his body was frustration-free.
</P>
<P>
   As befits a man who reported to work wearing Birkenstock
sandals, Jackson trod airily around the Lakers' 106-77 loss in Game
2 of their Western Conference finals against Portland.
</P>
<P>
   He chose to ignore the panic and doubt gathering like wolves at
the door of the Lakers' sanctuary. Twenty-four hours after the
Trail Blazers had insolently defiled the Lakers' championship
veneer like garden-variety taggers, Jackson didn't try to whitewash
the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did he try to soothe his wounded pride by riding his players
extra hard. Those were Birkenstocks on his feet, remember, not
spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson made his players watch the videotape of their Game 2
fiasco, frame by merciless frame, and then he said, ``The
(best-of-seven) series is 1-1. Deal with it. Suck it up.``
</P>
<P>
   And that was that. No game plans were shredded or gangplanks
erected. Jackson did not throw out the season with the rubbish that
was Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   For $6 million, the Lakers hired a skipper who doesn't stray off
course after one squall. Jackson didn't win six NBA championship
rings with the Bulls by vacillating like a sports radio talk-show
host.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't guide the Lakers to the best regular-season mark in
his first year with the organization by pointing one of his
bedecked digits in the air to gauge which way momentum was blowing.
</P>
<P>
   At other times this season, the Lakers have been able to
navigate so the stiff wind in their faces was suddenly at their
backs. Remember the 24-point loss at San Antonio on Feb. 1? That
stood as their worst loss of the season, until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson didn't do anything drastic and the Lakers rebounded to
win their next 19.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the 13-point loss at Sacramento in Game 4 during
the first round of the playoffs. Jackson didn't demote starter
Green after he had zero points and only one rebound to show for 26
minutes and Green came back with 10 points and six rebounds in a
113-86 win in the deciding Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   And who can forget the 19-point loss at Phoenix in Game 4 during
the second round? Jackson stayed the course and the next game the
Lakers bloodlessly eliminated the Suns 87-65.
</P>
<P>
   After losing their home-court advantage to the Trail Blazers,
the Lakers are in danger of falling behind in a series for the
first time in the postseason. They have to play their next two
games in Portland, knowing full well they are 1-3 on the road in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   It's not nirvana but it's also a little too soon to be singing
``Happy Trails'' to the Lakers. Under Jackson, the team has been
nothing if not resilient. And still, everywhere he went Tuesday,
Kobe Bryant heard shades of Gene Autry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lose one game, it's like Armageddon,'' Bryant said, not
bothering to hide his bemusement. ``I'm waiting for Bruce Willis to
walk in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   We'd be really surprised if the Lakers didn't bounce back from
their terrible Game 2 to win one of the next two games in Portland,
starting Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Then the series will turn into a double-elimination duel, like
everyone was saying it would until the Lakers won Game 1 by 15
points and short-circuited everybody's perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole atmosphere at (Staples Center) before Monday's game
was like people had come expecting to see a crucifixion,'' said
forward Rick Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Little did anybody know it would be the Lakers' backs that were
nailed to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal picked up three fouls early and wasn't sent to the free-
throw line as often as he felt was deserved. Pretty soon his
composure was punctured and it was like all the air left his
Superman pecs.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates took quick shots and in doing so turned the
triangle offense into something in need of triage.
</P>
<P>
   And dare we say a sundial rotates faster than the Lakers did on
defense?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't pretty but Jackson will smooth out the wrinkles and
apply some rouge and make the Lakers glow again. It's his job. He's
essentially a make-up artist, one who is paid handsomely to conceal
the Lakers' blemishes by playing up their best features.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is measuring out how much energy guys have at this
particular time of the year,'' Jackson said. ``Players are under
duress. They've been playing basketball for nine months.
Physically, how much do they have left to give in practice, how
much do they have left to give out on the floor in a game? That's
what you have to measure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting them prepared to be quick to the ball or active or
physically feeling good about themselves so they feel like they're
attuned with each other,'' Jackson said, ``is part of my job.''
</P>
<P>
   It says here it's what he does best.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
