u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     05-24 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THESE PACERS COULD SCORE WITH NIELSEN 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ IT took one early play _ Mark Jackson passing in
the lane between his legs to Jalen Rose and Rose throwing outside
to Austin Croshere for 3 _ to remind us how expressive and joyful
this sport can be. It took one game to remember that basketball
with offense can still be fierce, and how much the National
Basketball Association owes the New York Knicks for saving it from
more Miami Heat.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when no one could have blamed the bedraggled Knicks
for waiting until Friday to compete, it took one electric
second-quarter run for them to let the Pacers know they too have
some weaponry to unload. After nearly climbing out of a 19-point
hole, the Knicks faded and lost Game 1 of the Eastern Conference
finals, 102-88. Don't worry, the Pacers know they are in for a
long, draining series _ ``a dogfight,'' said Reggie Miller _ and
one that will be infinitely easier on the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   It did get a tad pontifical during the last few days of the
Knicks-Heat war, with those proclamations of its being the most
hotly contested basketball since the invention of the ball. Though
his expression didn't change, you could hear the snicker in Larry
Bird's voice on Tuesday when he said, ``I can remember some pretty
tough series that I played in, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Thank goodness there can still be a team that embodies Bird's
creative soul. Mixing Rose and Croshere into the old, familiar
Pacers' equation was too much for the Knicks in Game 1, with the
court spread, the driving lanes open, the 3-pointers flying, with
10 connecting, with a half-dozen Pacers in double figures, with the
eye-opening total of 32 assists.
</P>
<P>
   If you are David Stern, you like this team and are not worried
about losing the New York market in the next round. If you are
Stern, whom would you rather market to America next month _ Bird,
possibly in Los Angeles against his most celebrated playing
opponent, or Jeff Van Gundy? The Hall of Famer who is about to ride
off into the sunset or the unglamorous lifer who drove a Honda to
work before it became a compacted movie prop in The Charter That
Ate The Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people aren't going to see Larry Bird playing when they
tune in,'' Jackson said, trying to debunk my inverted conspiracy
theory. The New Yorker in him still can't forget the Larry Johnson
4-point nonsense of last spring, and worries what the league may be
cooking up.
</P>
<P>
   New York is the preferred television market but the Pacers have
this beautiful Conseco Fieldhouse, with its heartland history and
cozy charm. They have Reggie, the 200-pound nerd who slips into a
phone booth and transforms himself into the playoff assassin. They
have a power forward named Dale and the center who looks as if they
lifted him from one of the trophy cases with the 1950s memorabilia.
Now they have the Sprewell-like Rose and this brash big kid,
Croshere, who leaped off the bench and capped a 35-point first
quarter with a circus shot and then lit up the perimeter the rest
of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was telling him that Camby was their X factor last year and
that he's going to have to do something this year,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Vast tracks of middle America can relate to these Pacers as the
mom and pop shop who have been shut down four times now in the
conference final by the well-heeled superstore, by a young brute
named Shaq and big-market bullies from Chicago and New York. After
the Knicks left them earthbound and broken last spring, they traded
the rugged Antonio Davis for a high school kid who collects his
allowance and sits on the bench, but they somehow have emerged _
take note, Coach Riley _ as a more versatile team.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were just better last year, and Van Gundy out-coached
Bird. Less than a great bench coach, Bird has nonetheless been a
strong leader, the perfect image-shaper for his home state team as
it built this unique arena that should help keep the franchise
humming against the big-market odds.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, Bird says this is it, three years and out. And if
the Lakers do survive Portland and the Pacers make it out to Los
Angeles next month, rest assured that Stern will be happy to live
with the Pacers in the finals, with a posed shot of Bird and Magic,
now a minority Lakers' owner, to beam around his global empire.
</P>
<P>
   It has never been a reach to think that an official might
subconsciously be influenced by his own perception of what's good
for the league. But that's where the conspiracy conversation should
begin and end. The Pacers have nothing to worry about if they
continue playing the way they did on Tuesday night, and neither
does Stern.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
