<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 00:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4055 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-JUDGES-POLITICS-SFCHR     05-24 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDGES-POLITICS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CRITICS SAY GOP TACTICS HOLDING UP S.F. LAWYER'S JUDGESHIP  &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Not a whiff of controversy arose when
environmental lawyer Barry Goode was nominated in June 1998 to the
federal appeals court in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But two years later, Goode's judgeship has gone nowhere. Though
not a single objection has been raised, his name has not budged
from the Senate Judiciary Committee. He has not been confirmed or
even had a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the San Francisco lawyer is victim to some of the
most bitter political infighting to have gripped Washington in
years.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to take over the White House next year, Republicans,
critics say, have staged a slowdown in confirming the Clinton
administration's judicial nominations in order to run out the clock
on President Clinton's final year in office.
</P>
<P>
   There was a temporary break in the logjam Tuesday. Senate
leaders struck a deal in which the Republicans agreed to clear 16
of Clinton's judicial nominees, and Democrats, in turn, will vote
on a Republican-backed nominee to the Federal Election Commission.
The vote is expected Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Goode, like many other judicial hopefuls, remains caught in
political limbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are still way behind in terms of historic rates of
confirmation, even in the final year of a presidency,'' said Sam
Chapman, chief of staff for Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, the Senate has confirmed only seven nominees,
while 80 judgeships are still vacant, including 46 before the
Senate or its Judiciary Committee. Typically, the Senate approves
at least 40 federal judges a year. Democrats as well as Bay Area
attorneys are furious over the tactic and have promised to push
through the nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're frustrated and upset,'' said Michael Kahn, a San
Francisco lawyer and a friend of Goode's. Earlier this month, Kahn
helped draft a letter signed by more than 100 California lawyers _
Democrats and Republicans _ calling on members of the Senate
Judiciary Committee to move on Goode's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., a Judiciary
Committee member who has tried to block previous appointments to
the federal appeals court in San Francisco, denied that there was
any deliberate attempt to stall the nominations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just politics,'' said John Cox, press secretary for
Sessions. The Democrats ``are trying to paint the Republicans as
inactive. It's untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he admitted that he was surprised that Goode's
nomination had been held up for two years, and he did not know the
reason behind it.
</P>
<P>
   While other nominees to the federal Court of Appeal in San
Francisco have come under fire from Republicans for their liberal
politics, their ties to the ACLU or their support of affirmative
action, there has been no such grumbling over Goode, a veteran
lawyer who is known to defend corporations in environmental
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Both plaintiff and defense lawyers refer to Goode as a bright,
honest man who would make an excellent judge. And except for
supporting Clinton in his 1991 presidential run, Goode is
considered apolitical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not heard that Republicans in the Senate oppose him
for any substantive reasons,'' said Chapman. ``With Barry Goode,
there's nothing to point to.''
</P>
<P>
   Political infighting in the nation's capital is not the only
roadblock to Goode's confirmation. He also has been caught up in
the controversy over the federal Court of Appeals in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past several years, there have been as many as 10
vacancies on the 28-member court. There are now four vacancies,
with nominees awaiting confirmation. But none waited for more than
a year _ except for Goode.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few weeks, Democrats have lashed out at
Republicans over the slowdown in confirming federal judges.
Democratic Sen. Patrick Leahy of Vermont noted that prior
Congresses have had no problem confirming federal judges during the
final year of an administration occupied by an opposing party. In
1992, the Democrat-controlled Senate confirmed 66 of President
Bush's nominees, and in 1988 it confirmed 42 of President Reagan's.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's breakthrough agreement came after a series of angry
exchanges between the two parties. In addition to the judicial
candidates now cleared, it paves the way for 48 White House
nominees to the State Department and Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   But the pact will not guarantee safe passage for other nominees,
including Goode. Last week, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
outraged by what he declared were attacks on his stewardship,
warned he would not allow another judicial nominee through unless
Democrats acted on spending bills now pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this batch is moved, if they don't cooperate with us on
these appropriations bills, they are not going to get another
judge. Period,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said Tuesday that he
was pleased to get the 16 judicial nominees through the Senate. He
vowed to use ``whatever forceful means required to continue to keep
up the pressure to resolve the remaining nominees.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; `Pending in Committee'
</P>
<P>
   Jeanne Lopatto, press secretary for the Senate Judiciary
Committee, said she could not comment on Goode's nomination except
to say it is ``pending in committee.''
</P>
<P>
   But she bristled at criticism of the committee, noting that the
members had approved 10 nominees in the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving those who are qualified and who understand the
proper role of a judge,'' she said. But if someone is a ``judicial
activist,'' or for some reason unqualified ``that nominee will not
and should not have the support of the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Goode was cautious about commenting on his predicament, except
to say he was honored by the letter of support from colleagues and
respected the careful way the Senate evaluates nominees. ``I am
hoping that the process brings my nomination forward at some
point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; 26 Years at Law Firm
</P>
<P>
   Goode, 52, is a Democrat who has spent his entire 26-year career
as a lawyer at McCutchen, Doyle, Brown &AMP; Enersen, one of San
Francisco's largest law firms. He represents primarily
manufacturers and trade organizations.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest case was representing Rohr Industries, a
manufacturing company that was a defendant in a huge toxic waste
lawsuit involving the Stringfellow dump in Riverside County.
</P>
<P>
   Some have speculated that part of Goode's problem is that there
is nothing controversial about him. ``If there was a point of
controversy, we could have identified it and addressed it,'' Kahn
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Goode has been in a state of limbo, doing his day job
and spending his off-hours glad-handing influential lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really had two jobs, and it's been very hard on him and
his family,'' said James Hunt, chairman of McCutchen.
</P>
<P>
   Friends say Goode has no hidden agenda _ he wants to be a
federal judge out of a sense of public duty. It certainly isn't for
the money. If he gets appointed, Goode will take a sizable cut in
pay. Federal judges make $149,900 a year, the salary some firms are
paying a lawyer fresh out of law school.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 0048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
