<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOPER LEADS ANGELS PAST TWINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS -- Brian Cooper arrived in the Angels clubhouse at
the Metrodome Tuesday afternoon and hadn't even unpacked his duffel
bag yet when greeted by manager Mike Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia took one look at Cooper's jet-black hair, a sharp
contrast to the light-brown hair he had in spring training, and
snapped: ``Who the heck are you? And what did you do with Cooper?''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia might have said the same thing after the game, a 7-4
Angels victory over the Minnesota Twins before a sparse crowd of
9,032. After all, the Cooper Scioscia watched Tuesday wasn't the
same pitcher Scioscia saw in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper struggled most of the spring and failed to win a spot in
the starting rotation. He took it with him to Triple-A Edmonton,
where he lost his first three starts. But because of injuries and
illness to the pitching staff, and a return to the form that made
him a candidate for the rotation in the first place, Cooper was
called up and made his first start with the big club Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   He earned the win after giving up four runs and five hits in six
innings, and attributed his newfound success to the hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was struggling, I had to do something,'' joked Cooper, one
of a few Edmonton pitchers to dye their hair. ``New clothes, a new
hairdo, mix it up. That's the key right there. I'm 3-0 with this
hair. ... As long as I keep winning, it's staying black.''
</P>
<P>
   And it certainly didn't hurt that the Angels got out to an early
lead, scoring all seven runs in the first four innings, including
four in the first inning. They jumped on Twins starter Joe Mays
(1-6), getting a two-run single by Tim Salmon and bases-loaded
walks from Scott Spiezio and Bengie Molina for a 4-0 lead in the
first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn (No. 16) and Darin Erstad (No. 7) hit solo homers, and
Garret Anderson had an RBI double. It was a change of pace from the
last homestand, when the Angels had to come from behind late in
games to have a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was telling the guys, 'Let's have a nice day today,' '' said
Vaughn, whose home run reached the fourth row of the upper deck in
right field. ``We got on 'em early. We need to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cooper worked out of a first-inning jam and held the
Twins scoreless until David Ortiz's two-out, two-run double in the
fourth. Cooper also allowed a two-run homer to Brian Buchanan in
the sixth. But that was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Edmonton pitching coach) Greg Minton got me back on track,''
Cooper said. ``I was struggling at the beginning of the year and I
couldn't find anything. I couldn't even throw strikes in the
bullpen. He worked hard with me and revamped my windup. I just got
back to the basics and it really paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought his arm action was great, he was free and easy, the
ball was coming out of his hand better, I liked everything about
him,'' Scioscia said. ``He got a little sloppy in the the last
couple of innings. But he was sharp with his off-speed stuff and he
sunk the ball well. And this is coming off four good starts at
Edmonton.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels will need another starter for Friday's game, and
there's a good chance they'll go to Edmonton again to find him.
Seth Etherton, who attended USC like Cooper, is a candidate to make
the start against the Royals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the situation with the starting pitching -- we got
guys hurt,'' Vaughn said. ``The main thing is the guys that are
coming up, they've got to do a job. It's not like we can lay down
or look back. We've got to look in front of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``This division, no one's going to run away with it. These guys
have got to do their job. It's definitely encouraging with a guy
like Cooper pitching like he pitched. He took care of the lead and
was aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper got relief help from Mike Holtz (1 1/3 innings),
Shigetoshi Hasegawa (2/3 innings) and Troy Percival (one inning,
13th save), who combined to shut out the Twins on two hits in the
final three innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
