<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIPKEN HOMER OFF MESA IN NINTH DERAILS LATE M'S COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ When Cal Ripken Jr. went deep for a game-winning
homer Tuesday night, it was natural for Orioles manager Mike
Hargrove to say, ``That's just Cal being Cal.''
</P>
<P>
   But of course, baseball is all about perspective, and that was
the Orioles' perspective. The Seattle perspective after a 4-2 loss
in the bottom of the ninth inning was more along the lines of,
``What, again?''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has been a terrific team at home in Safeco Field. And
that includes the bullpen. But let the Mariners wander far afield
and ugly things start to happen. And that's especially true of the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night it was Jose Mesa, stung by Ripken's homer. But on
the last road trip, Kazuhiro Sasaki gave up two walk-off homers,
one in Texas and another in Oakland. Division titles aren't won on
home games alone. Sooner or later, Mesa or Sasaki or Somebody is
going to have to step up in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Lou Piniella hinted after the loss Tuesday that Somebody
might be Arthur Rhodes. But that would only be if the left-hander
were in position to face a couple of the Orioles' big left-handed
bats _ say B.J. Surhoff and Harold Baines _ with the game on the
line.
</P>
<P>
   If not, it will be up to Mesa or Sasaki to get the job done.
Sasaki, who had a back problem flare up again Tuesday, wasn't
available. Mesa was, but he has never mastered pitching to Ripken,
and nothing Tuesday night changed that.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the Orioles third baseman, Mesa missed with a curve, then
missed with a slider. Rather than fall behind 3-0 in the count,
Mesa came in with a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Ripken gobbled it up and spit it into the left-field bleachers.
Game over.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Bryan Price is as aware as anyone of the problems
Mesa (2-3, 5.09 ERA) has had this season in the late going. But
Price's awareness extends to this: Mesa's in the bullpen, and for
the bullpen to help the Mariners, Mesa needs to believe he can do
the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't gotten down on Jose, and Lou keeps using him, so he
hasn't gotten down on Jose,'' Price said. ``As long as he doesn't
get down on himself, we've got a quality pitcher. But if he gets
down on himself, we're in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   And has he?
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen any evidence of that,'' Price said. ``He's not
walking around hanging his head.''
</P>
<P>
   There were many Mariners who were in full head-down mode
Tuesday. Most were hitters, none of whom could do much against
journeyman pitcher Pat Rapp, who started for the Orioles and
pitched seven shutout innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can score just four runs a game, we're going to have a
good chance to win with the pitching we've been getting,''
shortstop Alex Rodriguez said. ``Tonight we didn't do that. Rapp
was what they call `effectively wild.'''
</P>
<P>
   As always seems to be the case, the Seattle offense went south
with Gil Meche starting. Seattle has scored 18 runs for Meche when
he's been in the game this year, and half of those runs came in one
game. The Mariners did it to him Meche again, waiting until the
ninth inning to put together any semblance of offense.
</P>
<P>
   Brady Anderson and Harold Baines hit leadoff homers in the first
two innings for Baltimore, then Meche shut the door.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's hitters didn't get their feet in the door until Edgar
Martinez singled against former Seattle reliever Mike Timlin to
lead off the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Timlin, with his 95-mph fastball and 91-mph slider, is a nasty
customer. But, as the Mariners remember, he is also prone to
mistakes, and he made a whopper to Jay Buhner. After getting ahead
with two quick strikes, Timlin hung a slider, and Buhner parked it
into the cheap seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buhner did what he gets paid millions of dollars to do _ hit
hanging breaking balls out of the ballpark,'' Hargrove said.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, the Mariners were back in the game. In fact,
Seattle had a chance to take the lead, but with two out and runners
on second and third, Mark McLemore grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Mesa. And, just like that, the game was over. Mesa faced
three batters, got behind all three, and paid the price. Albert
Belle opened the inning with a bloop single on a 2-0 pitch, then
Baines popped out on a 3-1 serve before Ripken homered.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Ripken sounded more like a loser than a winner
because, after all, the Orioles are 18-25, mostly for having lost
just this kind of game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody would be lying to say it hasn't been frustrating,''
Ripken said. ``We've had some frustrating losses, and it does
affect you. Sometimes you forget how long the season is. Sometimes
it takes a lot of frustrating losses to get you over the hump.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why, in the other clubhouse, Price continued to have
high hopes for a Mesa turnaround even as frustration gnawed at his
innards.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
