</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXCUT-PROPOSAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOS IN CALIFORNIA SENATE PROPOSE SALES TAX REBATE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Saying they want all Californians to share in the
state's cash bonanza, Senate Democrats pitched a plan Tuesday to
rebate $1.4 billion each year in sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is designed to replace a $1.7 billion one-time
income tax cut proposed by Gov. Gray Davis, which Senate Democrats
said does not benefit all Californians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will spread money to all California taxpayers,'' said
Senate President Pro Tem John Burton, D-San Francisco, of the plan.
``People that need money and spend it for necessities are going to
get a bigger piece of this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's tax cut plan is the latest move by lawmakers to
establish their bargaining stance with the Democratic governor over
the shape of the state's $93.7 billion budget for the fiscal year
beginning July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Already Senate Democrats have beefed up spending for the state's
grant program to needy college students beyond what Davis wants and
made various changes in their spending plan counter to Davis'
wishes.
</P>
<P>
   In the Assembly's proposed budget, there is $2.4 billion
earmarked for tax cuts but the plan doesn't say what those cuts
would be.
</P>
<P>
   Davis wants to give single taxpayers a one-time check for $150
and joint filers a $300 check.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats say that many lower income Californians, who
don't pay income taxes, lose a higher percentage of their income
from sales taxes than higher earning Californians.
</P>
<P>
   They also noted that an income tax rebate from the state would
count as additional income on federal taxes so some of Davis' $150
and $300 checks would be lost in higher federal taxes.
</P>
<P>
   A study by the Washington D.C. based nonprofit Institute on
Taxation and Economic Policy found that 41 percent of the state's
families with children would receive no rebates under Davis' plan
because they pay no state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The study said that $250 million of the rebates would go to the
federal treasury because state income taxes are deductible from
federal income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' proposed rebate check would also count as income the
following year when a person pays their state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the case for sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats are still weighing two ways of doling out the
sales tax rebate.
</P>
<P>
   One would give each sales taxpayer $50 and their dependents
would get $25 -- up to a maximum of $150 per household, according
to Sen. Steve Peace, D-El Cajon, chair of the Senate Budget
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The other approach would offer a minimum rebate of $30
increasing to $80, depending on income with a $25 rebate per
dependent.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who pays income taxes would automatically get a rebate
check, Peace said. But about 5.8 million Californians who don't pay
taxes would have to apply for the money, Peace said.
</P>
<P>
   The rebates would remain in effect unless suspended by a
two-thirds vote of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to know both the Assembly and the Senate agree with
the governor that some portion of the surplus should be returned to
taxpayers,'' said Michael Bustamante, Davis' press secretary.
``Details of the tax cut will be part of budget discussions with
the governor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
