<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ROOFMAN ICED, YET QUAKEMAN FREE  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I'm Fed-Exing a Happy Meal to Roofman, with a
file cooked inside the burger patty. You deserve a break today,
Roofman.
</P>
<P>
   Roofman is Jeffrey Allen Manchester, arrested in North Carolina
and suspected of committing a series of burger-joint stick-ups. At
each place, he allegedly cut a hole in the roof, dropped down on
the employees, flashed a gun, took the cash, locked the people in
the freezer and split.
</P>
<P>
   He never took anything but company cash, never raised his voice,
was always polite, and always made sure the employees had jackets
and sweaters before he put 'em on ice.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, I'm no fan of armed robbery. But Roofman should be
let off with community service, giving seminars on courtesy to
fast-food employees.
</P>
<P>
   Roofman reportedly stole $100,000 in the 45 robberies. Let him
keep it. That's a class-action karma payback on behalf of every
poor schnook who ever got 10 miles down the freeway before
discovering that he didn't get any sauce for his Chicken McSawdust,
or that he got shorted two nacho cheese-licks, or that the Elmer
Fudd Militia Terrorist toy that his kid so desperately wanted
didn't make the bag.
</P>
<P>
   IF ROOFMAN is being held on $1 million bail, the FBI and Tommy
Lee Jones should be conducting a manhunt for Clogman, the corporate
head of the Burger-Industrial Complex whose mission is to clog up
the arteries of every American by politely selling us bags of
greasy, salted fat.
</P>
<P>
   HOW COME there's not a warrant out for Quakeman, the state
insurance commissioner who comes to the aid of ripped-off
earthquake victims by making TV commercials?
</P>
<P>
   Quakeman cuts a loophole in the roof and drops into the back
room of crooked insurance companies. He is always polite and neatly
dressed, always allows the wealthy companies to pay off potentially
massive fines with pennies on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Then, before making his getaway through the doggie door,
Quakeman locks earthquake-insurance-fraud victims in the deep
freeze, naked, and blames it on his attorney, Attorneyman.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S ENOUGH TO make you want to throw up, but if you reach for
the ipecac, be sure to check the expiration date.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pyle was cleaning out his medicine cabinet and came across
a vial of ipecac syrup. He noticed the bottle was stamped with an
expiration date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?'' wonders Rick. ``What happens if you drink expired
ipecac? Does it make you not throw up?''
</P>
<P>
   TODAY'S THEOLOGICAL stumper, from Gar Smith:
</P>
<P>
   ``To all those folks who believe that letting Jesus into your
heart can cure homosexuality, one question: Why doesn't it work on
priests?''
</P>
<P>
   FAMILIAR NAMES on the local law school graduation lists: Policy
and Alioto.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Policy, Stanford Law, is the daughter of Carmen and
Gail Policy. Carmen was the 49ers' salary cap wizard and overall
mastermind who played a major role in the '90s dynasty before a
major falling out with then-owner Eddie DeBartolo, which resulted
in Carmen going to Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Alioto, UCSF School of Law, is the grandson of the late
mayor Joe and son of maybe-future-mayor Angela.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen is going to work for an S.F. law firm and Joe is
staying, for now, with the D.A.'s office.
</P>
<P>
   SO COMEDIAN Dana Carvey didn't think it was so darn funny when
he found out that a San Francisco surgeon who performed a double
bypass on Carvey's heart in '98 made a mistake in re-connecting the
plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   I'm surprised that such snafus don't happen more often. You get
inside there, with all the blood and gunk, and those tiny arteries
look like the MacArthur Maze from the moon.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson is, never go to a surgeon whose shingle features
phrases like ``While U wait'' or ``In about an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   TOOTHPICK MAN, not to be confused with Roofman, or Hamburger
Arm, wins today's creative panhandling award.
</P>
<P>
   Hamburger Arm was the dude who raked in sympathy cash for months
by showing people his gruesomely gouged and bleeding arm and asking
for cab fare to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Toothpick Man, reports Scott McKellar, works the median strip on
Van Ness and gives you a show for your donation. He jams a
toothpick up his nose, then pulls it out of his mouth. Then he rams
the toothpick into his eye and pulls it out of his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``An illusion, I assume,'' McKellar says, ``but he's very
good.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd give the guy a buck  &UR; not  &LR; to do it. Hate to see a man make
an hors d'oeuvre out of his eyeball.
</P>
</TEXT>
