A4066 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-QUACKENBUSH-HEARING-S     05-24 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUACKENBUSH-HEARING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 QUACKENBUSH REFUSES TO TESTIFY AT SENATE HEARING  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Insurance Commissioner Chuck Quackenbush angrily
walked out of a Senate hearing Tuesday after accusing it of
orchestrating a political ambush.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic exit by Quackenbush and his top deputies left the
chairwoman of the Senate Insurance Committee, Sen. Jackie Speier,
D-Hillsborough, promising to ask for a subpoena to force them to
appear next week.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush's surprise departure came after he produced a
year-old e-mail between two legislative staff members that used the
word ``ambush.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I agreed to appear here voluntarily, despite my reservations
that this would be a political drill, not a reform-focused,
fact-finding discussion,'' Quackenbush, one of the state's two
Republican statewide officeholders, said in a prepared statement to
the committee. ``After receiving this document, along with some
other worrisome information that indicates some members of the
Legislature are aware of and actively participating in this
`ambush,' I decided to engage outside counsel _ Mr. Donald Heller _
to advise me.''
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush said Heller advised him not to participate in the
hearing. Then he walked out, to the applause of his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   After a 10-minute recess, Speier said she would request
subpoenas and resumed the hearing without the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush is under investigation by lawmakers and the attorney
general for allowing insurance companies to duck as much as $3
billion in fines for mishandling Northridge earthquake claims by
contributing far smaller amounts to a nonprofit foundation set up
by Quackenbush.
</P>
<P>
   The $11.6 million that insurers paid to the foundation was
supposed to finance earthquake research and consumer aid, but
Quackenbush acknowledged at an Assembly hearing last month that so
far, none of the money has gone to earthquake victims.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, money has been funneled to some of Quackenbush's
political operatives, to organizations such as the Greater
Sacramento Urban League and a football camp attended by two of
Quackenbush's sons. An additional $3 million was spent on
television commercials featuring the insurance commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   At Attorney General Bill Lockyer's request, a judge has
temporarily frozen the fund's remaining $6 million and is
considering making the order permanent.
</P>
<P>
   In a crush of news media outside the hearing room, Quackenbush
said he will proceed only on the advice of his attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``The e-mail represented that this has been a long-planned
political ambush on the office of the insurance commissioner and is
designed to damage me politically,'' he said. ``We're not going to
allow this to continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Quackenbush then quickly left as aides physically blocked the
hallway.
</P>
<P>
   Heller, a former assistant U.S. attorney, was one of the
prosecutors of Lynette ``Squeaky'' Fromme, who was convicted of
attempting to assassinate former President Gerald Ford in
Sacramento in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as a political lynching, and once again, it
reflects California politics at its worst,'' Heller said. ``I'm not
saying that there weren't mistakes made, and the commissioner has
candidly admitted making mistakes. But he is a decent, honorable
man, and he was trying to do the best for consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Speier, who has said she is interested in running for the
insurance commissioner post, denied that the investigation is
politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in an ambush, and I was almost killed,'' she said,
refering to the 1978 Jonestown massacre, where she was wounded.
``This is a piece of cake in comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   As Quackenbush walked out of the hearing, he released a copy of
a March 1999 e-mail from an Assembly staff member to Richard
Steffen, staff director of the Senate Insurance Committee, advising
him not to write a letter to Quackenbush ``on anything, we have to
set him up first ... if we do not completely ambush him, he will
slide out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Steffen said he was not the one who made such statements, but
stood behind his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all political animals here, whether we admit it or
not,'' Steffen said.
</P>
<P>
   The staff member who wrote the e-mail hung up on a reporter
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
