<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4068 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-STARS-H     05-24 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-STARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DANNY ROBBINS  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
DALLAS _ Watching the Dallas Stars defend their Stanley Cup
championship is like watching a heavyweight boxer let his opponent
fight himself out.
<TEXT>
<P>
   You see them back on their heels for a period or two. You see
their goaltender peppered with shots. And then you see them land
the knockout punch.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 5 of the Western Conference finals Tuesday night, the
winning blow was struck by Joe Nieuwendyk, who tipped the puck past
Colorado goalie Patrick Roy 12:10 into overtime to give the Stars a
3-2 victory over the Avalanche. Dallas holds a 3-2 lead in the
best-of-seven series, with Game 6 on Thursday in Denver and Game 7
_ if needed _ Saturday in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, on home ice at Reunion Arena, the Stars were again at
their deceptive best. They were outshot 31-20. They played
sluggishly in the first period. But in the end, they won, their
edges being goalie Ed Belfour and Nieuwendyk's stick.
</P>
<P>
   After Belfour had turned back another Avalanche assault through
three-plus periods, Nieuwendyk was able to work himself into the
right spot to deflect Richard Matvichuk's shot past Roy and end the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I remember it is seeing the puck back at the point,''
Nieuwendyk said. ``When you're in that situation, it's all a race
to the net. The puck found a lane right through. I was just able to
get my stick on it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of three Dallas centers, Nieuwendyk was forced to play more
than his usual allotment of minutes Tuesday because Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock had to reorganize his lines when winger Jamie
Langenbrunner went off with a knee injury in the first period.
Extra work in an intense, physical game on an unseasonably warm
evening might be difficult for some players, but Nieuwendyk, the
Most Valuable Player of last year's playoffs, was up to it. More
important, he had something left at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more he played the better he played,'' Hitchcock said,
``and we sure needed him tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Stars also needed Belfour, who has faced 110
shots in the last three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like last year, Eddie gets better as the playoffs go on,''
Nieuwendyk said. ``He's really focused. And when he goes against
someone like Patrick Roy, he gets fired up. He's made some great
saves, and we certainly need him to do that, because they're
getting quality shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Colorado team that enjoyed a 39-15 shot advantage in
Game 4 was the one that took the ice Tuesday, putting the rush on
Belfour immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took off like a rocket,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Only a marvelous play by Matvichuk kept the Avalanche from
scoring 10 minutes into the game. Colorado's Shjon Podein had a
shot at an open net, but Matvichuk swooped in to keep the puck from
crossing the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes later, the Stars weren't so fortunate. Jon Klemm was
in position to lift a rebound over Belfour, putting the Avalanche
on the board and ending a streak of 12 straight playoff games in
which the Stars had prevented their opponents from scoring in the
first period.
</P>
<P>
   In the first period, the Avalanche cranked out 11 shots on goal.
The Stars didn't produce a shot on goal in the first 12 minutes and
came out of the first period with just five.
</P>
<P>
   The fog finally lifted for the Stars 4:26 into the second
period. Jere Lehtinen, camped in front of Roy, was able to backhand
the rebound from a Brett Hull shot high into the net and make it a
1-1 game.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' second goal came 14:41 into the period and 20 seconds
into their third power play of the game. Darryl Sydor got the puck
to Mike Modano, who set up Hull perfectly for the blast that put
the Stars ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado came back to forge a tie early in the third period. Joe
Sakic made the play, working the puck into the Stars' zone and
flipping it in to Milan Hejduk, whose shot beat Belfour 2:19 into
the period.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche was handed an opportunity to end the game in
regulation when Modano was called for high-sticking with 3:37 left.
A team with one of the NHL's best power plays, Colorado managed a
final push, but Belfour hung in _ at one point turning back Sakic
in front of the net _ sending the game into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour stopped four shots in overtime, two from Sakic, before
Nieuwendyk put in the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got a two-on-one up top, threw the puck at the net, and
it got deflected,'' Colorado defenseman Ray Bourque said. ``It's
not always pretty in overtime. They threw the puck at the net, and
it was a tough break for us.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
