<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 01:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4069 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-T     05-24 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIEUWENDYK FLASHES MVP FORM AS STARS WIN IN OVERTIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The irony wasn't lost on Joe Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   Just when he finally stopped trying to be the player he was in
last season's playoffs, that's exactly who he started to look like.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk deflected a Richard Matvichuk shot past Colorado
goalie Patrick Roy with 7:50 remaining in overtime to give the
Dallas Stars a 3-2 victory in Game 5 of the Western Conference
Finals on Tuesday night at Reunion Arena. His goal, much like his
game, proved eerily reminiscent of his playoff-MVP performance of a
season ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's natural for everyone to judge on last year and the run
that I had in last year's playoffs,'' said Nieuwendyk, who had 10
goals, including six game-winners, and 11 assists in last year's
playoff but only five goals coming into Game 5. ``I think there was
a time period early in the playoffs where I was putting a lot of
pressure on myself to do that too.''
</P>
<P>
   What Nieuwendyk, who was double shifted a lot after winger Jamie
Langenbrunner injured his right knee late in the first period, did
Tuesday night was put the Stars one victory away from returning to
the Stanley Cup Finals. Game 6 is Thursday night in Colorado where
the Stars will try to do what the Avalanche could not last season:
finish the series with a victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars realize they'll need to play better to win, especially
with Langenbrunner definitely out, but their game seems to be
peaking at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Joe; he's so dangerous all the time, and he's working
real hard, and things weren't going right,'' Stars winger Brett
Hull said. ``All of a sudden, a couple go in and things change at
the drop of a hat.''
</P>
<P>
   And while Nieuwendyk scored the goal to set up the dramatics of
Game 6, Stars goalie Ed Belfour kept the game going until then. The
Stars needed a pair of spectacular saves by him midway through
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour stopped shots by Avs forwards Dave Andreychuk and Joe
Sakic 9 minutes, 48 seconds into overtime. Andreychuk took a shot
from the high slot. The rebound bounced to Sakic, who had snuck
behind the Stars' defensemen. He took a poke at it, but shoved it
under Ed Belfour's pads. The puck eventually trickled out but the
whistle had already blown.
</P>
<P>
   Roy couldn't answer at the other end.
</P>
<P>
   ``This round is about two of the greatest goalies in hockey
history,'' Avs coach Bob Hartley said. ``You are going to need a
perfect shot, a perfect tip to beat them. You are talking about
goaltending at its best.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were once again outshot, 31-20 this time They've been
outshot 110-56 in the past three games. And they've won two.
</P>
<P>
   They, once again, made their shots count, and Belfour made sure
Colorado's didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we did a whole lot to make his night tough,''
Colorado defenseman Adam Foote said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars certainly didn't bother Roy too much. They had five
shots in each of the first two periods, but turned that into two
goals in the second. Both were by the Hull-Mike Modano-Jere
Lehtinen/Brenden Morrow line. Hull, Modano and Lehtinen have scored
or assisted on eight of the Stars' 10 goals against the Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen struck first, getting a stick on a Hull rebound. With
Adam Deadmarsh on his back and Adam Foote on his side, Lehtinen got
the puck to his backhand and chipped the puck over Roy at 4:26 of
the period.
</P>
<P>
   Hull took care of matters himself on the Stars' second goal. On
a power play, Modano moved away from the slot then sent a pass to
where he had just come from. Hull was there for his classic
one-timer and a 2-1 lead at 14:41 of the second period. Modano
didn't have a shot but finished with two assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as Jere or (Hull) are doing it, we're all getting
involved,'' Modano said. ``Our line is certainly creating a lot of
goals the three games that we've won. I think that's all you can
really ask for.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had gone 14 consecutive home playoff games without
allowing a third-period goal.
</P>
<P>
   Avs forward Milan Hejduk stopped that streak when he scored at
2:19 of the third period to tie the game at 2-2. Colorado and
Dallas then proceeded to go seemingly forever without a shot. They
were merely saving their energy for a frenetic final couple of
minutes of regulation.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars and Avs traded tremendous chances. The only reason
none of them went in was because Roy and Belfour traded even more
spectacular saves, including a doozy by Belfour on Foote.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my job to come up with the big saves,'' Belfour said.
``I got a couple saves there I got maybe a little lucky, and we
needed that.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado looked to be on a crash course for another Game 4,
where shots didn't necessary equal goals, until defenseman Jon
Klemm finally scored at 12:11 of the first period. The Avs were
outshooting the Stars 9-0 at that point.
</P>
<P>
   The Avs could've had another goal if not for Matvichuk. He
swiped a Shjon Podein shot out just before it crossed the goal line
earlier in the period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not supposed to be behind Eddie by any means,'' Matvichuk
said. ``It's just one of those desperation plays, and I was in the
right position at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk said the same thing about his shot that Nieuwendyk
deflected for the game-winner. Matvichuk said he just wanted to get
the puck on net. Nieuwendyk said he could see it coming. The way
his luck had been going in the playoffs, he was just hoping to get
a stick on it. He figured he'd keep digging in the corners until
one finally went in.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the attitude I have,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``Just to keep
working and fighting and scratching for everything. Throughout my
whole career, if it hasn't been going in, the only way I know how
to rectify the situation is to keep battling.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is the attitude the Stars say they need to win Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk said this series is as hard, if not harder, than the
seven-game thriller these two teams engaged in last season. The
Stars realize they'll need to play better if they're going to win
Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``A minute after the game was over, our dressing room was quiet
as heck,'' Hitchcock said. ``We know what type of battle we're in
right now, and it's going to take everything this team has got.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
