r s BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-T     05-24 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S CRYSTAL CLEAR: BELFOUR THE BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For all of the daily knee-jerk analysis, for all of the
talk about Adam Foote's eye and Joe Sakic's plus-minus and Brett
Hull's timely resuscitation, the story remains the same in this
Western Conference Finals.
</P>
<P>
   It's no mystery novel _ Eddie Belfour three games, Patrick Roy
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``This round is about two of the greatest goaltenders in hockey
history,'' Colorado coach Bob Hartley said graciously after Tuesday
night's 3-2 Dallas Stars overtime victory.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Monsieur Bob, and your man is leaking.
</P>
<P>
   It would be a major misdemeanor to take anything away from Joe
Nieuwendyk's winning goal 12 minutes into the extra period.
</P>
<P>
   As Roy said, clinically, ``It deflected right in front of me,
and I made the save sideways, and after that I saw the puck hit the
post and then cross the line.''
</P>
<P>
   So which line can you see on the big chart, Patrick? Can you
read the big ``E''?
</P>
<P>
   Can you also read the D, D, I and E?
</P>
<P>
   It's handwritten right there on the wall. For all of the
preseries hype, for all of the Avalanche's indignation over
Belfour's alleged slight, and for all of Patrick's catty retorts
about not being able to hear because he had all those ``Stanley
Cups in my ears,'' the story in this year's conference finals is
shaping up to be the same as last year's.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you say?'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock answered, when
someone asked about his goaltender. ``He's been great. He's got a
strong focus. He's a proud guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``And right now he has to be the difference for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The more inconsistent that Hitchcock's team plays, the steadier
and more dependable that Belfour seems to get. In the midst of an
indifferent first-period by the home team Tuesday night, one where
the Stars went nearly 12 1/2 minutes without a shot on goal,
Belfour stopped 10 of 11 shots and otherwise sprawled and snared
the home team back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no surprise,'' said the resident elder, Guy Carbonneau.
``He's been playing this way since October.''
</P>
<P>
   It's so true. In this year after his first Stanley Cup, the only
thing that has stymied Belfour has been ... well ... Mace.
</P>
<P>
   Both goaltenders allowed second goals in Tuesday night's tensely
played contest. Belfour rebounded from Milan Hejduk's game-knotting
goal early in the third period and made some of his best saves in
the ensuing 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But Hull's one-timer blast off the feed from Modano _ the Stars'
second goal _ seemed to rattle the plumbing inside of Roy's rooster
head. When his attempted ``pass'' toward the right boards sailed
into the rich folks' seats, drawing a mandatory delay-of-game
penalty, the Reunion Arena crowd howled.
</P>
<P>
   With just under 10 minutes played in the extra period, Belfour
stopped a Dave Andreychuk drive, and then fell on the puck when
Sakic tried to hastily squeeze the rebound under Eddie's leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to drag the puck and get it under him, but I didn't,''
said Sakic, who remained fresh out of explanations.
</P>
<P>
   What we're seeing, though, is a different goaltender. It's been
one of the NHL's stories of the year, and the Eastern Conference
hockey literati has missed it.
</P>
<P>
   Since winning the Cup, Belfour has played with a quiet
confidence that no onrushing bands of Avs, Red Wings, Sharks or
Blues have been able to shake.
</P>
<P>
   As game-winner Nieuwendyk said, ``He is really focused, and when
he goes against someone like Patrick Roy, he really gets fired up
and wants to do well. He is really on top of his game and focused
out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's making a lot of great saves for us, and we certainly need
him to do that. They are getting quality chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously enough, the Stars aren't. They skate, they grind, they
scrum along the boards, hoping to kick loose a brief opportunity,
but the defending champs have seemed to swoon for stretches of this
series, unable to generate scoring chances.
</P>
<P>
   Which makes the fact that Roy is trailing in this series all the
more indicting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a couple of saves that were a little lucky,'' Belfour
said, ``but we need things like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The series is not over yet. We still have to win another game,
and it's going to take a lot of work.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but for the Stars, what once seemed to be such a starry,
faraway dream now seems like handwriting on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   E-D-D-I-E, it reads. Does the other guy even see it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
