r s BC-BBA-RANGERS-ROYALS-TE     05-24 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ROYALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' BULLPEN DELIVERS SEVENTH STRAIGHT WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Undaunted by early results, Rangers manager
Johnny Oates has kept his relievers in their appointed roles and
keeps bringing them in at the appointed time. Lately the results
have been much more gratifying, although still somewhat
nerve-wracking.
</P>
<P>
   Oates when through it last night when Jeff Zimmerman put the
tying run on second base with no outs in the eighth inning and John
Wetteland got in a first-and-third jam with one out in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   But both pitchers, showing their All-Star grit from last year,
kept their cool, their calm and the tying run from scoring,
allowing the Rangers to hold on to a 4-3 victory over the Kansas
City Royals at Kauffman Stadium last night.
</P>
<P>
   Their relief work allowed Rick Helling to improve his record to
7-1 with a 3.22 earned-run average and extended the Rangers'
winning streak to seven. The Rangers have also won 16 of their past
21, allowing them to move into a virtual tie for first place with
the Seattle Mariners in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a lot of fun,'' Wetteland said. ``Playing with these
guys and being around them every day, they look forward to coming
to the park. Guys are going out looking to win a baseball game;
they're not just interested in their individual stats. It's a fun
atmosphere to be around.''
</P>
<P>
   That atmosphere extends to the bullpen. During the seven-game
winning streak, Rangers relievers have allowed only two earned runs
in 22 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen it time and again,'' Wetteland said. ``A strong 'pen
gives a team a good feeling, guys coming in, getting the job done
night in and night out. Early in the season you could see
\Rhitters\S pressing. We'd have a three- or four-run lead and guys
would be trying to make it a 10-run lead. The offense was carrying
us early. ... They're still carrying us, but now we're doing our
part too.''
</P>
<P>
   Their part came up in the eighth. Home runs by Chad Curtis and
David Segui helped Helling take a 4-2 lead into the eighth, but
Carlos Febles started the inning with a home run of his own. That
made it 4-3, and Oates decided it was time for the bullpen, a much
safer decision now than perhaps 21 games ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to win, we're going to win with those guys doing their
job,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman, trying to harness his nasty slider, started his night
by giving up a double to Matt Sweeney. Mark Quinn followed with a
soft line drive up the middle that Zimmerman failed to catch. But
he did freeze Sweeney long enough to keep him from going to third
as the ball bounced to second baseman Luis Alicea for the first
out.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman then fell behind Joe Randa 3-0 before coming back to
get the strikeout, then retired Carlos Beltran on a fly to left to
end the inning. Through all of Zimmerman's struggles, he has still
been tough with runners in scoring position; opponents have just
three hits in 29 at-bats against him in those situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not as good as I want to be,'' Zimmerman said. ``I
struggled with command of my slider, but fortunately I was able to
make some good pitches. I'm taking small steps and as long as I
keep getting the ball, I'll take the positives out of it and go
from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland got into trouble when he gave up one-out singles to
Jorge Fabregas and Jermaine Dye, leaving pinch-runners Scott Pose
and Luis Ordaz at first and third. That brought up Johnny Damon, a
fast runner who is tough to double up.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland wanted to strike him out but instead jammed him
inside. Damon hit a slow grounder back to Wetteland, who threw home
to get Pose for the second out.
</P>
<P>
   ``John threw the ball right where I wanted him to,'' Oates said.
``Make sure of one. You don't have a shot at getting two with Damon
running.''
</P>
<P>
   Febles then flied out to short right to end the game.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
