<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-INJURY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS LOSE LANGENBRUNNER TO KNEE INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J. DOUGLAS FOSTER 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Injuries are nothing new to the Stars. They've fought
them, played through them and won in spite of them the entire
season.
</P>
<P>
   They had one more to deal with last night when winger Jamie
Langenbrunner pulled up in the middle of the Stars' offensive zone
with a knee injury. Stars coach Ken Hitchcock wasn't certain about
Langenbrunner's injury after the game, but said Langenbrunner won't
play tomorrow in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   That makes depth a serious concern, especially going into the
high altitude and thin air of Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock couldn't worry about that last night. In fact, he
didn't even see one of the game's biggest plays, when Richard
Matvichuk cleared the puck out of an empty Dallas net , because his
focus was simply having enough skaters to get through Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was too busy scrambling getting our lines together,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Without Langenbrunner, the Stars were forced to use three
centers and had several players, most notably Mike Modano and Joe
Nieuwendyk, playing longer shifts.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk responded, scoring the game-winner in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played him a lot tonight,'' Hitchcock said of Nieuwendyk.
``Joe was the guy who got double-shifted. The more he played, the
better he played. In the last half of the game we sure needed
him.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the loss of Langenbrunner, the Stars weren't the
team drained of energy in the extra period. In fact, they attacked
the Colorado net hard in the last few minutes leading up to
Nieuwendyk's goal.
</P>
<P>
   ```The best thing about this team is our depth,'' said Stars
captain and defenseman Derian Hatcher, who played one shift that
lasted nearly two minutes last night. ``We have plenty of people
who can come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said Jon Sim, who played in 25 regular-season games
but hasn't played yet in the postseason, could fill the roster spot
left vacant by Langenbrunner in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sim's a left shot but a natural right winger,'' Hitchcock
said. ``He's got the speed and the tenacity to match this type of
series.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
