<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4076 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-PHILLIES-ASTROS-H     05-24 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PHILLIES-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
They could talk about it until the mosquitoes stopped biting, but
until they actually did something about it, mere words would carry
no sting.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Holt got the message in a players-only meeting prior to
Tuesday's 10-2 victory over the Philadelphia Phillies, and
apparently he wasn't alone. For one night, the Astros were
everything they hadn't been during a season-worst seven-game losing
streak, which ended Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   They were resilient, relentless and fundamentally sound, bearing
no resemblance to the team that began the day with the worst record
in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one game,'' said first baseman Jeff Bagwell, who called
the meeting. ``It doesn't make the last 43 games OK, but it's a
start. This game was a step in the right direction, and it was good
to see.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point later in the season, the Astros would love to be
able to look back to Tuesday as the day they turned their season
around. If they do, the prevailing memory will be of Holt's
gut-check effort.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old righthander became the first Astro to pitch a
complete game at Enron Field and only the third pitcher overall to
go the distance at the hitter-friendly ballpark. He also drove in
two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Jon Lieber and Colorado's Pedro Astacio had the other
complete games at Enron. It was the second complete game of Holt's
career, both occurring this season.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most impressive was that he threw 138 pitches, easily
the highest total for an Astro this season. Shane Reynolds'
125-pitch effort against the Cubs on April 25 was the previous
high.
</P>
<P>
   Because Monday's doubleheader in Milwaukee took such a toll on
the bullpen, Holt's workhorse performance was exactly what the
Astros needed. Also, considering how unreliable the bullpen has
been, perhaps it was in Holt's best interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a command performance,'' manager Larry Dierker said.
``You're not going to see a guy step up and go all the way very
often. I kept asking him if he was tired, and he kept saying, `I
want to finish this thing.' That's good to hear.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt won for only the second time this season and the first time
since April 28, his last complete game _ a two-hit shutout at
Milwaukee. He has a 3.38 ERA over his last four starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tired, but you have to battle through it,'' said Holt,
who struck out a career-high seven batters, including five in a row
at one point. ``We needed to get a win, and I wanted to finish what
I started.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillies starter Randy Wolf came up way short in that
department, lasting just three innings and allowing six runs on
eight hits.
</P>
<P>
   He hardly looked like the same Randy Wolf who held the Astros to
a run on five hits in seven innings earlier this season at Enron.
Tuesday's performance matched the shortest outing of Wolf's career.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros, who won for only the second time in 10 games, put
together three-run innings against Wolf in the second and the
third. Holt's two-run single highlighted the second-inning rally,
which put the Astros on top for good. They were Holt's first two
RBIs of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou's two-run homer was the big blow in the third
inning, and Tony Eusebio also drove in a run with the first of his
two doubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry too much about my swing,'' said Eusebio, who
lifted his average to .227. ``I struggled in April, but I'm going
to be a good hitter again. I'm just waiting for my chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt, who was making his first start in 10 days _ he made a pair
of relief appearances in that span _ no doubt was waiting for the
day when the Astros would actually score more than a few runs in
one of his starts.
</P>
<P>
   Before Tuesday, the club was averaging four runs when Holt
started.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday they scored that many over the final two innings.
Craig Biggio had an RBI single in the seventh, and Richard Hidalgo
drew a bases-load walk from Jason Boyd to give the Astros an 8-2
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeno's two-run homer in the eighth provided the final
margin of victory for the Astros, who banged out 13 hits and scored
their most comfortable victory since beating Pittsburgh 11-2 in the
second game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Cedeno, who extended his hitting streak to five games, is
batting .342 in his last 20 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies' only scoring occurred in the second inning when
Holt issued a two-out walk to Mickey Morandini, followed by Desi
Relaford's double to right. Wolf drove both home with his third hit
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Holt allowed just four hits over the final seven innings. He
retired 15 of the last 19 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he got settled down, he did what he does best _ he got
ground balls,'' Dierker said. ``It's no secret that the key to
pitching here is to try to get ground balls.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
