   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-EMBARGO (Washington) _ Under pressure from farmers to open
new markets, Congress is considering softening the U.S. trade
embargo against Cuba to permit the export of food, medicine and
medical products. By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BIORESEARCH (Obolensk, Russia) _ The once top secret
research complex where the Soviet Union perfected dozens of strains
of deadly bacteria threw open its doors this week to demonstrate
its determination to conduct only such peaceful work as preventing
bioterrorism and curing disease. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-GORE (Washington) _ A look at Vice President Gore's
role on the China trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   UNSCHOOLING (Silver Spring, Md.) _ A look at unschooling, a
growing approach to home schooling whose practitioners say that by
honing in on their children's natural talents and curiosity, with
texts and curricula that best capture their impulse to learn, they
can guide them into the three R's when the children are most ready,
not when professional educators say they ought to be. By Peter T.
Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-CABLE (Undated) _ Looking at the effect of the Supreme
Court's cable ruling on Monday. By Jim Rutenberg.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NJ-FLORIO-PROFILE (Trenton) _ For all the countless, impassioned
speeches Jim Florio has delivered in his quest for Democratic
nomination for New Jersey's U.S. Senate seat, the most telling two
words in his campaign are the ones Florio has refused to utter:
``I'm sorry.'' Both admirers and critics say it is hardly
surprising that Florio is standing by the one act that has most
defined his political career and infuriated New Jersey voters: the
$2.8-billion tax hike he pushed through the state legislature two
months after becoming governor. The tax hike, enacted in 1990, set
off a tirade by angry voters. Florio was cast into exile, and the
Democrats lost control of both houses of the state legislature. But
if the political fallout is the one indisputible thing about
Florio's term as governor, the tax increase raises two far more
complicated issues about him: first, was it smart policy, and,
second, what kind of a governor was he overall?
</P>
