<P>
   AIR-MERGER-CONSUMERS (Undated) _ A look at the impact of the
proposed United-US Airways merger on travelers in the Northeast. By
Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-INTELLIGENCE (Undated) _ The story of the uninspired
student who goes on to make a name for himself is practically a
cliche. It is a paradox that has long frustrated educators. They
know that test scores often predict applicants' academic
performance on campus but are unreliable guides to career success.
As a result, psychologists and corporate recruiters alike have
longed for a systematic way to identify the campus goof-off who is
destined to become a corporate chief executive or the class brain
who is doomed to languish in middle management. Now, for what may
be the first time, a major university is using its own students and
applicants in a concerted effort to unlock the mystery. By David
Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECONOMIC-DATA (Tokyo) _ Japan's official economic
statistics have always been mistrusted, but they became even more
suspect recently when the government omitted an important piece of
information on quarterly growth. That information, as it turned
out, reflected startling weakness, suggesting that Japan's
financial institutions were spending little or nothing on upgrading
their businesses. The deliberate omission of the data has
invigorated critics, in and out of government, who have long
contended that Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party manipulates
economic data for political reasons. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-MERGER-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ A lot of investors who
thought they knew a bargain when they saw one have purchased US
Airways stock over the years, only to discover that cheap stocks
can get cheaper. Now those who held on can feel at least some
vindication. UAL said Tuesday night that it plans to acquire US
Airways for $60 a share in cash, more than twice the market price
of the shares. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
