<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER TOUGH LESSON FOR DODGERS' GAGNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Dodgers want to develop young right-hander
Eric Gagne, and they say they're willing to live with the
inconsistency that nearly every rookie fights through.
</P>
<P>
   Such ups and downs are part of the learning curve, but Gagne's
heard that enough and is ready for success. The frustrating part
for the 24-year-old is the learning is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case for Gagne this season, a few poor pitches
hurt dearly as he made just enough mistakes for the Cincinnati Reds
to take advantage of as the Dodgers lost 3-1 Tuesday at Dodger
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers managed three hits as their six-game winning streak,
their longest since 1997, came to an end.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne's had trouble with the long ball in most of his outings,
and again it was the case against the Reds. He allowed two homers
and three runs in six innings, walking three and striking out four.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne fell to 0-3, and the Dodgers are 1-5 in his starts even
though he hasn't allowed more than four runs in any his outings.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Hollandsworth led off the bottom of the first with a single
to center, but the Dodgers didn't have another leadoff runner until
pinch-hitter F.P. Santangelo walked to lead off the eighth against
starter Osvaldo Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Williamson relieved and walked Hollandsworth, but Mark
Grudzielanek grounded to third baseman Aaron Boone, who stepped on
the bag and threw to first for a double play. The Dodgers kept the
inning alive when Shawn Green walked, but Eric Karros struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez (1-0) allowed all three hits in seven-plus innings,
walking two and striking out four in winning for the first time
since he beat Houston on April 27, 1997, when he was pitching with
the San Francisco Giants. Danny Graves pitched the ninth for his
sixth save.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne, starting for the first time since May 7 and pitching for
the first time in nine days, battled with control at times.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers took a 1-0 lead in the first on Karros' sacrifice
fly in the first inning. It was Karros' team-leading 39th RBI.
</P>
<P>
   But Gagne surrendered a leadoff double to Benito Santiago in the
third, and after a bunt by Fernandez moved Santiago to third, Pokey
Reese had an RBI groundout to tie it. Barry Larkin, who left the
game in the seventh with a sore left hand, gave the Reds a 2-1 lead
two pitches later when the Reds shortstop hit his third homer of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr., stifled by the Dodgers this season, hit Gagne's
first pitch of the sixth inning over the fence in left field.
Griffey Jr.'s 14th homer was the 10th allowed by Gagne this season
in 35 innings. Only Carlos Perez, who's yielded 12 homers in 47
innings, has given up more.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, who missed the past two seasons because of a pair of
right elbow surgeries, made seven minor-league starts before being
recalled May 1. He fought through the first inning in which the
first three batters reached base but the Dodgers managed only one
run. After that, Fernandez showed no signs of a pitcher who allowed
seven earned runs in 12 innings in two other starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   He kept the Dodgers off balance and in the infield. Ten of the
next 15 outs he recorded were via ground balls. The only runner in
scoring position came when Shawn Green doubled with two outs in the
third. Fernandez then retired nine straight before Karros' two-out
single in the sixth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 0153EDT &QL; 
