<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4085 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-HNS     05-24 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-PACERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ Chalk one up for the hicks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers, who revel in their country-boy image,
blasted the city slickers from New York 102-88 Tuesday in Game 1 of
the Eastern Conference finals before 18,345 delirious fans at
Conseco Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   And wouldn't you know it, the Pacer who looks like the biggest
hayseed of them all is the one who did most of the damage, staking
Indiana to a 1-0 lead in the best-of-seven series that resumes here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Square-jawed Austin Croshere, who could easily stand in as
Jethro Bodine from the old Beverly Hillbillies TV show, scored 22
points, including four big 3-pointers, to give the Pacers their
first-ever Game 1 victory in the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   And true to his image, Croshere gave little more than ``aw,
shucks'' responses to the media horde that surrounded him after the
game, giving credit to just about everybody but the guy who mopped
the sweat off the floor during timeouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to give a lot of credit to Rik Smits, who
played excellent offensively (scoring 10 of his 16 points in the
first quarter),'' Croshere said. ``He forced them (the Knicks) to
double-team him inside, and there's only so much help defense like
that can do on the weak side (opposite the ball).
</P>
<P>
   ``We have Reggie (Miller) and Jalen (Rose) out there, and they
(New York's defenders) were concerned about them. I was the open
man, and I just knocked down the shots.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of shots.
</P>
<P>
   Left open by New York's rotating defense, Croshere hit seven of
his 10 field-goal attempts, including four of his five 3-point
tries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, he had a great all-around game tonight,'' said Indiana
coach Larry Bird of Croshere. ``Austin's been struggling, worrying
about his shooting, but about every shot he's been taking has been
right on the money. They just haven't been going in for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Tuesday, that is.
</P>
<P>
   And the same could be said of the entire Indiana roster. Dale
Davis had 14 points and a game-high 16 rebounds, Rose scored all 17
of his points in the second half, and Mark Jackson kept everyone
playing together, finishing with 11 points and 13 of the Pacers' 32
assists.
</P>
<P>
   That balance helped the Pacers get off to a quick start as they
knocked down 15 of their 29 first-period attempts. That offensive
excellence was highlighted when _ who else? _ Croshere caught
Jackson's missed 3-point heave in midair, glided under the basket
and flipped in a reverse layup as the buzzer sounded, putting the
Pacers up 35-17 at the end of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hole the Knicks were never able to escape. They made a
few runs, even cutting the Indiana lead to just two points late in
the third period. But they never did recover from that initial
blast from the Pacers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wasted a quarter tonight,'' said New York coach Jeff Van
Gundy. ``And when you waste a quarter in this league, you get
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Ewing, who finished with 21 points and eight rebounds
for the Knicks, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we gave them too much room tonight,'' he said. ``We
just didn't play strong enough defense from the beginning. I
thought that 88 points would be enough to win a playoff game like
this, but Indiana was hitting tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were led by Latrell Sprewell's 22 points, while Allan
Houston added 18 and Charlie Ward 14.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks appeared spent by their grueling series with Miami, a
seven-game affair that ended Sunday. It didn't give them much
turnaround time against an Indiana team that had been resting since
Friday, when it ousted Philadelphia in Game 6 of their conference
semifinal series.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks weren't going to say they were still worn down
from grappling with the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough series,'' Ewing said, ``but I can't use that as
an excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not, but the Pacers certainly suspected the Knicks might
be a bit out of sync after the quick turnaround, especially given
the physical nature of the Miami series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to get in the game quickly,'' said Miller, who
scored 19 points but made only eight of his 20 field-goal attempts.
``We understood they were coming off an emotional game with Miami
and thought they may be tired. They were, and we got into the game
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, who had been getting beaten badly by Smits early in the
game, suddenly woke up, scoring 11 of his 13 first-half points in
the final five minutes to rally the Knicks to within 52-48 at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana built a nine-point third-quarter lead, going ahead 66-57
on a dunk by Davis with 5:43 left in the period. But the Knicks
again rallied, pulling within 68-66 on Ward's 3-pointer with 3:17
remaining in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks appeared to run out of gas at that point. Jackson
responded just 15 seconds later, nailing a 3-pointer to spark a
10-5 run to close the period.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana kept pouring it on in the fourth quarter, putting
together a 12-3 run over the first 6:13 to blow the game open.
Croshere nailed a 3-pointer with 6:17 left to give the Pacers an
88-74 lead, and though the Knicks made a couple of halfhearted runs
in an effort to get back, Indiana pretty much kept up a
double-digit lead the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few years, the Knicks and Pacers have put on some
memorable shows, featuring some of the most high-profile stars in
the game in Miller, Ewing and Sprewell.
</P>
<P>
   But Croshere?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say enough about how Austin played,'' said Davis. ``If
we're going to win this series, that's the kind of effort we're
going to have to get.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
