<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4086 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-24 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
YES indeed, things can always be worse.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, these struggling Astros _ these
achy-breaky Astros _ could come from Philadelphia and call
themselves the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   But by the grace of the baseball gods, they are not. By the arm
of Chris Holt, too.
</P>
<P>
   If before Tuesday night you thought this Astros season had been
one bad trip after another, particularly if Montreal and Milwaukee
were on the itinerary, you were right.
</P>
<P>
   But compared to the Astros, the Phils could have looked more
dazed and confused only if Hunter S. Thompson had written the
script.
</P>
<P>
   Astros 10, Phillies 2 was riddled with seemingly rambling story
lines and incoherent twists, and none of them had to do with the
Astros. One feeble turn only seemed to be outdone by the next, and
none of them had to do with Doug Henry or Joe Slusarski.
</P>
<P>
   There was Phillies outfielder Bobby Abreu being waved around
third base in a 3-2 game after a Scott Rolen single in the third
inning. One problem: Abreu was thrown out so easily at the plate by
Jeff Bagwell that fans might have seen the Enron grass grow between
Abreu's strides.
</P>
<P>
   There was a nice throw from Phillies catcher Mike Lieberthal to
second base as he tried to nab Astros speedster Roger Cedeno trying
to steal. Another problem: No Phillie covered the bag, and the ball
rolled into center field.
</P>
<P>
   There was the keen if predictable intentional walk to Moises
Alou to load the bases in the seventh and set up a Phillies force
at any base. Yet another problem: Phillies reliever Jason Boyd
walked the next batter, Richard Hidalgo, to bring in a run and set
off the Astros romp.
</P>
<P>
   But isn't it strange how all these bad things happen to the
other guys when it's the Astros getting the kind of pitching
performance they've been craving since Dome Dogs?
</P>
<P>
   ``A command performance,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said of
Holt's complete-game, 138-pitch effort.
</P>
<P>
   And go heavy on the command.
</P>
<P>
   Holt's slider consistently slid over the outside corner on
righthanders, well out of reach. His fastball moved this way, then
that, bending knees and racking up K's for him _ five in a row
during one stretch, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   His location was right on, which might also describe the timing
of this win considering the Astros were coming off seven losses in
a row and the ever-ominous players-only meeting earlier Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Holt's arm probably will feel like it's going to fall off today
after grinding out the kind of marathon effort rarely seen since
the days of Movietone News highlights.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to see that kind of effort in this day and
age,'' Dierker said. ``But we needed it. The secret to pitching
here is to try to get the other team to hit the ball on the ground,
and that's exactly what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't it strange? On a night when Holt had all his stuff and
fought through fatigue in the heat and humidity, not only was the
other team the one that looked foolish, but the Astros looked
nothing like a team that bumbled through Montreal and Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody wrote `No Lucky' on my locker when we were in
Montreal,'' Holt said. It was a deserved nickname.
</P>
<P>
   Holt's fortunes in numerous outings have been hard-luck by any
standard. In his previous start, Holt went seven innings and left
with a 6-2 lead against Cincinnati, only to see the lead vanish
along with the Astros' win.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday night Holt was as fortunate in the early innings as
he was superb the rest of the way. Strange how that works out,
isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   Holt benefited from a double play in the second inning after
giving up a leadoff single. In the third, when he still couldn't
find his best stuff, he got the ill-advised wave home from Phillies
third-base coach John Vukovich that led to Abreu's being nailed at
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I easily could have been out of there in the third or fourth
inning,'' Holt said. ``I didn't really feel like I was at my best.
I was lucky with the way a few things went my way and the defense
early. But then I started feeling a lot better and started making
good pitches. You've got to have those things if you're going to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   This might not have been the start of a turnaround for the ages.
Twelve games under .500 still is only a fraction better than the
Phillies' 13.
</P>
<P>
   But the Astros got everything going their way Tuesday night, and
it all revolved around a guy you probably would least have expected
to spark something impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, call Holt lucky. But call him good, too.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
