<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TIRED' DODGERS FIZZLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two weeks of being on the road, followed by a
cross-country flight and a 14-inning game, apparently caught up
with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   And so did Cincinnati right-hander Osvaldo Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   With Gary Sheffield on the bench with a sprained right ankle,
the potent Dodgers lineup mustered three hits as the Reds won 3-1
Tuesday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez's first win since pitching for San Francisco three
years ago ended the Dodgers' winning streak at six, their longest
since the 1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked a little tired,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
said. ``We had a long day (Monday) and looked a little flat. We
didn't hit any balls hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie right-hander Eric Gagne (0-3) continued his solid
pitching but without results. He allowed three runs, including solo
homers to Barry Larkin and Ken Griffey Jr., in six innings, but is
still searching for his first win.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also aren't scoring a bundle of runs in Gagne's
starts. He hasn't allowed more than four runs in any of his
outings, but the Dodgers are 1-5 in his starts.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help on this night that Fernandez, who missed the last
two seasons because of a pair of elbow surgeries, looked more like
the renowned pitcher he was years ago pitching for the Cuban
national team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never really threw me the same pitch twice,'' said Dodgers
catcher Todd Hundley, who struck out four times, three of which
were against Fernandez. ``He struck me out with three different
pitches. He had great command of his fastball, great command of his
offspeed stuff. He wouldn't give in.''
</P>
<P>
   The only threat the Dodgers had against Fernandez came when Todd
Hollandsworth led off the first with a single, Mark Grudzielanek
was hit by a pitch and Shawn Green walked. Eric Karros gave the
Dodgers their only run with a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the next 15 outs Fernandez (1-0) recorded came via ground
ball. The Dodgers' only other hits were Green's two-out double in
the third and Karros' two-out single in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had a chance off reliever Scott Williamson in the
eighth, but Grudzielanek grounded into a double play with two on
and none out, and after Green walked, Karros struck out. Danny
Graves struck out the side in the ninth for his eighth save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a slider on the first pitch of the game, so that tells
you something,'' Hollandsworth said. ``This team's been fighting
all year. You can probably count on one hand games we didn't have a
chance to win. In the eighth, we had a chance, but things didn't
work out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds took a 2-1 lead in the third when Benito Santiago led
off with a double and eventually scored on Pokey Reese's RBI
groundout. Larkin, who left the game in the seventh with a sore
left hand, gave the Reds the lead two pitches later when the Reds
shortstop hit his third homer of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey Jr., stifled by the Dodgers this season, hit Gagne's
first pitch of the sixth inning over the fence in left field.
Griffey Jr.'s 14th homer was the 10th allowed by Gagne this season
in 35 innings. Only Carlos Perez, who's yielded 12 homers in 47
innings, has given up more.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Being tired) is not what it was,'' Dodgers shortstop Jose
Vizcaino said. ``(Fernandez) pitched a great game. He's been out
for two years, but he knows how to pitch. He's experienced. He's
pitched like that in San Francisco.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
