</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATVICHUK'S PLAY MAKES STRONG ARGUMENT FOR STARS' DEFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Fort Worth Star-Telegram staff 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ After surrendering 79 shots in two games in Colorado,
Stars coach Ken Hitchcock expected a better effort from his defense
in Game 5. After all, defense has been the Stars' strength for
several seasons and was a key to last year's Stanley Cup run.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock got it last night from all his defenders, most notably
Richard Matvichuk. Not only was Matvichuk second on the team in ice
time with 29:20 (trailing only Derian Hatcher), but he dished out
four hits and recorded a team-high five blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   And he most likely made the play that saved the game in the
first period. Ed Belfour had come out of the crease to make one
save, and when the puck got loose behind Belfour, Colorado's Shjon
Podein had an open net and fired.
</P>
<P>
   But Matvichuk got his stick on the puck just before it reached
the goal line, clearing it and saving a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we all had to play better,'' Matvichuk said. ``We knew
we had to even out the chances and keep their shot total low. We
need to be giving up 15 or 20 shots per game, not 40 or 45.''
\Nsubheds:Hot, hot, hot The Stars are hotter than you think. The
record-high temperatures aren't helping the ice in Reunion Arena.
It was hot outside and hot inside, turning the ice into slush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hot,'' Stars center Guy Carbonneau said. ``It's hot
outside, so obviously, at the end of the game it was hot. When the
ice gets soft, it does get chippy. You can see it a lot. They use
the flip a lot, and we use it a lot, and our defensemen were having
a tough time handling the puck. But both teams play on the same
ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Stars winger Brett Hull: ``Temperature-wise, it's the
hottest I've been in a long time.'' \Nsubheds:About faceoffs The
Stars may have won the war against the Colorado Avalanche in Game
5, but they're still losing a very important battle.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche won 42 of 71 faceoffs last night. Stephane Yelle
won 14 of 20, Peter Forsberg had a 15-12 advantage, and Chris Drury
won 10 of 17.
</P>
<P>
   For the Stars, Guy Carbonneau won just 26 percent (six of 23),
and Mike Modano lost 18 of his 31 chances. The Stars finally gained
the advantage in overtime, winning six of nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a point that we've tried to address,'' Modano said.
``We're just trying to get our wingers involved, if there are any
loose pucks around our feet, just trying to help us out as much as
possible. \RThe Avalanche\S have some strong faceoff guys.''
\Nsubheds:Gaining, stopping power The Stars took advantage of the
power play. Their second goal came while Colorado forward Serge
Aubin was serving a board-check penalty in the second period. The
Stars' first goal, by Jere Lehtinen, came just as Avalanche forward
Adam Deadmarsh, fresh off a high-sticking call, returned to the
ice.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were just as potent at stopping the Avalanche's
chances. The Avs went 0-for-4 last night, getting only four shots.
\Nsubheds:Quieted The Stars' locker room was silent during the
intermission after the game went into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a good read on \Rthe game\S,'' coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``I've never seen our dressing room that quiet, but
we responded well. One minute after the game, it was quiet again.
We know the type of battle we're in right now. It is taking
everything this group has to be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Stars forward Joe Nieuwendyk: ``You just need to get your
rest. The first three periods were awfully tough out there. You
come in the dressing room and you don't have much time to think
about it.'' \Nsubheds:Blurring the lines Ken Hitchcock kept the
lineup he had in Game 4. The lines? Well, not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of having the last change, Hitchcock used Mike
Keane and Guy Carbonneau together as a sort-of checking line. After
the Stars took a 2-1 lead in the second period, Kirk Muller joined
them, reuniting what had been the Stars' primary checking line in
Games 2 and 3.
</P>
<P>
   They were the first line on the ice after winger Brett Hull's
go-ahead goal. \Nsubheds:Briefly Since moving to Dallas, the Stars
have won six of seven series after winning Game 5. And since 1987,
the NHL team that won Game 5 in a series tied, 2-2, has won 63 of
the 74 series.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had not allowed a first-period goal at home in an NHL
record 12 consecutive games, but the Avs' Jon Klemm ended the
streak when he scored off a rebound 12:11 into the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars are 9-0 in the past nine games in which Brett Hull
scored. {Compiled by staff writers Jennifer Floyd, Charean
Williams, Cody Bailey, Mac Engel, J. Douglas Foster and Tracey
Myers.}
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
