A4103 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-BLOWNCH     05-24 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-BLOWN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLOWN CHANCES IN OT HAUNT SAKIC, COLORADO
</HEADLINE>
 CHANCES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Joe Sakic's blank face revealed the depth of this
growing mess. That's blank, as in no goals.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Avalanche captain has few words left, mainly tired
cliches about hanging in there, to explain his utter futility for
the second consecutive playoff series against the Dallas Stars. He
had two chances to win Tuesday night's Game 5 in overtime. He had
five shots altogether, and three others whizzed wide of the net.
</P>
<P>
   Sakic had a nifty third-period assist to tie the game, but his
efforts mainly came up empty as the Avs suddenly find their backs
against the wall after Tuesday night's 3-2 overtime loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which one? I don't know,'' Sakic said when asked which missed
chance irked him the most. ``Throw them all in.''
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't really matter. The Avs, once seemingly in control of
this series, are one loss from catching the season's final spring
skiing as one of the most prolific scorers in the game has
seemingly lost his touch.
</P>
<P>
   Sakic hasn't scored a goal since May 5 against Detroit. He has
only two in 15 playoff games. His first oh-so-close chance in
overtime was a rocket from the left circle. Stars goalie Ed Belfour
dropped to his knees and gobbled it up.
</P>
<P>
   If Sakic thought he couldn't believe his missed chance near the
left post in the first period of Game 4, his blown chance at the
9:48 mark of overtime might require the Avs to hire a team
therapist.
</P>
<P>
   Sakic corralled a rebound off Dave Andreychuk's liner from the
high slot. Positioned at the right side of the crease, Sakic had
the puck, he had time, but, again, he didn't have any luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to drag it by him (Belfour) and put it in,'' Sakic
said. ``I think it almost got under him, but it didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The puck hit Belfour's pad, went under his leg, but stopped
short of crossing the goal line. It was a cruel reminder of the
first period when Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk denied Shjon
Podein by sweeping the puck off the goal line after Belfour got
caught out of the net.
</P>
<P>
   That other Joe, as in the Stars' Joe Nieuwendyk, put in the
game-winner less than three minutes after Sakic's miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way it goes,'' Sakic said. ``You've got to park it
and try to do the same thing next game.''
</P>
<P>
   It gets more difficult with each denied chance to believe Sakic
and the Avs can simply park it, meaning leave the bad vibes behind
and move on. In the past three games, they've seemingly done
everything within the rules of the game to beat Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   They've fired 110 shots at him. Only five have gone in. The Avs
have not scored more than two goals in any of the five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are going to keep going, we have to find a way to score
more goals than that,'' Avs defenseman Ray Bourque said. ``We had
our chances to win in regulation and overtime. We are getting the
opportunities we need. The work is there, and we are playing good
enough to win a lot of these games.''
</P>
<P>
   They just need to put the puck in the net. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
