<HEADER>
A4196 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS25-2NDT     05-24 1412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS25-2NDTAKE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds. 2 of 2 files. RUNS WITH NEWS-QUESTIONS25-1STTAKE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Who runs the Big Game lottery?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Big Game is a collaborative endeavor on behalf of the
seven participating states: Georgia, Illinois, Maryland,
Massachusetts, Michigan, New Jersey and Virginia. Lottery directors
for each of the participating states ``run'' the Big Game and serve
as Big Game officials. Key duties are shared among the directors of
all seven states. Detailed information can be found online at
www.theofficialbiggame.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On the Lincoln penny, why does the portrait of Abraham
Lincoln face to the right, when all other portraits of presidents
on U.S. circulating coins face left?
</P>
<P>
   A: Lincoln's likeness is an adaption of a plaque executed by
portraitist and sculptor Victor David Brenner. The U.S. Mint
explained that his facing to the right simply was the choice of the
designer, and wasn't mandated. President Theodore Roosevelt was
said to be so impressed with Brenner's plaque design that he
recommended to the secretary of the Treasury that it be placed on a
coin to be issued in 1909, the Lincoln Centennial Year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sports announcers also often use the term ``bonehead play.''
Do you know its origin?
</P>
<P>
   A: As is often the case with slang, researchers are faced with
conflicting claims. But it appears that the original ``bonehead
play'' was made in September 1908 by Fred Merkle of the New York
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   His team and the Chicago Cubs were tied 1-1. It was the last of
the ninth, two outs, and the Giants had Moose McCormick on third
and Merkle on first. The next man up, Al Bridwell, singled to
center field and McCormick crossed the plate with what appeared to
be the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   The play wouldn't be complete, however, until Merkle touched
second base ahead of the ball. With two outs, no runs can score
until a possible force play has been completed.
</P>
<P>
   Presuming the game was over when McCormick crossed the plate,
Merkle stopped short of second base and veered to the clubhouse.
Johnny Evers of the Cubs signaled for the center fielder to throw
him the ball so he could tag second, forcing out Merkle. The
winning run was nullified, and the game wasn't counted in the
standings.
</P>
<P>
   A sportswriter referred to Merkle's blunder as a ``bonehead
play,'' and it caught on to forever more mean ``dumb play'' in
sports lingo.
</P>
<P>
   Merkle's play became all the more important later in the season
when the Cubs and Giants finished tied for first place, and the
Cubs won the pennant in a playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some months ago, a network TV news story concerning the
importance of each senator casting his or her vote mentioned an
instance when a member was brought into the Senate on a stretcher
to cast his vote. Because he was dying of a brain tumor, he
couldn't speak, and voted by making a gesture with his hand. Can
you confirm this?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's true. It occurred on June 19, 1964, when Sen. Clare
Engle (D-Calif.) was brought to the Senate by ambulance and wheeled
into the chamber. He feebly raised his arm in support of a motion
to end debate on the civil rights bill and proceed to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   A vote was required to break the filibuster, and Engle's
dramatic gesture provided the turning point. It was the first time
in history that the Senate voted for cloture (the cutting off of
debate) on a civil rights bill.
</P>
<P>
   Engle was elected to the House in 1944 from rural Northern
California. Often seen hurrying through the Capitol's corridors,
trailing a great cloud of cigar smoke behind him, he was known as
``Congressman Fireball'' and ``the only active volcano in the
House.'' He was elected to the Senate in 1958.
</P>
<P>
   He had undergone two brain operations, the first of which, on
Aug. 24, 1963, left his speech impaired and his right side
partially paralyzed. On April 24, 1964, a craniotomy was performed,
and four days later he dropped his candidacy for re-election. He
died at age 52 on July 30, 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With all the attention on gun control lately, I was
wondering: Are there any statistics showing the percentage of U.S.
households that have guns in them now, compared to, say, 50 years
ago?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Sourcebook of Criminal Justice Statistics, a publication
of the Justice Department, doesn't go back as far as 1950. Nor does
it have current statistics.
</P>
<P>
   But you can get an idea from its earliest figures, for 1959, and
its most recent ones, for 1997. In 1959, 49 percent of American
households reported having a gun in the home; 51 percent, no guns.
In 1997, 42 percent reported having a gun; 57 percent, no guns (the
remaining 1 percent listed ``no opinion.'')
</P>
<P>
   Q: How are Big Game lottery revenues allotted?
</P>
<P>
   A: About 51 percent accounts for the shared prize pool for all
seven participating Big Game states, which includes the jackpot
amount and eight other prize amounts, which range from $1 to
$150,000. After that, about 35 percent goes toward education; about
7 percent to retailers; and 7 percent to operating costs. The Big
Game states are Massachusetts, New Jersey, Maryland, Virginia,
Georgia, Michigan and Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Pope John Paul II celebrated his 80th birthday on May 18. In
light of his longevity, can you tell us who was the oldest pontiff,
and who served as pope the longest?
</P>
<P>
   A: Bill Ryan of the U.S. Catholic Conference in Washington said
he couldn't come up with a definitive answer for the first part of
the question because the ages of some early popes aren't known for
certain. However, he added this: ``Surely one of the oldest was
Pope Leo XIII, who was 93 when he died in 1903.''
</P>
<P>
   Pius IX, who was born in 1792, enjoyed the longest reign in
papal history: June 16, 1846, to Feb. 7, 1878. Leo XIII reigned
second-longest: Feb. 20, 1878, to July 20, 1903.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II, who is seventh on the list of
longest-reigning pontiffs, will move up to sixth in early October.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My co-workers and I are debating the metropolitan population
of Atlanta, compared to Charlotte. Some say they saw on the
Internet that Charlotte's metro area has 5 1/2 million, which would
be considerably more than Atlanta's 3.8 million. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: On its Web site (www.charlottecvb.org/visitor.cfm), the
Charlotte Convention and Visitors Bureau lists a population of
``more than 500,000 people'' within the city's borders, and about
1.3 million within the metro area. On its Web site
(www.acvb.com/atlanta5.html), the Atlanta Convention and Visitors
Bureau lists a population of 425,200 for the city, and 3.5 million
for the 20-county metropolitan statistical area.
</P>
<P>
   These are the numbers from the 1990 census: Atlanta, 394,017
(city); 2,833,511 (metropolitan statistical area); Charlotte,
395,934 (city); 1,162,093 (N.C.-S.C. metropolitan statistical area,
which includes Charlotte and Gastonia, N.C., and Rock Hill, S.C.).
New, official statistics eventually will be available from the 2000
census.
</P>
<P>
   Your Charlotte-boosting co-workers may have seen a reference on
that city's Web site to 6 million people ``within a 100-mile
radius.'' There's no comparable claim on the Atlanta CVB's Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the expression ``cracker,'' as in
Georgia cracker or Florida cracker?
</P>
<P>
   A: This question comes up often and never fails to sit up
debate, because there are several theories. The Facts on File
Encyclopedia of Word and Phrase Origins offers this information:
</P>
<P>
   ``Cracker'' refers to a poor white person, especially one from
Georgia, so called, perhaps, from his or her use of cracked corn.
The expression originally was ``corncracker,'' someone who cracks
corn to make grits or cornmeal. At one time cracker meant ``a
liar,'' but when, after the Civil War, many people in the South
became too poor to buy cornmeal and had to make their own, cracker
came to mean a backwoodsman and then a poor white, generally a
person living in Georgia and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Others say cracker originally was applied to Florida cowboys,
and derived from their cracking their whips as they herded cattle.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the term now is generally considered offensive. But
many people are proud to call themselves Georgia (or Florida)
crackers, as long as they're the ones doing the calling.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Bessonette at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Two of two takes
</P>
