</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS25-COX-1STTAKE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eds. 1 of 2 files. RUNS WITH NEWS-QUESTIONS25-2NDTAKE
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I understand that there has been some legal wrangling
involved in Sue, the dinosaur. Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: You may be referring to a dispute that evolved after skeletal
remains of the Tyrannosaurus rex were discovered in South Dakota on
land owned by Maurice Williams, a member of the Cheyenne River
Sioux Indians. The skeleton was found in 1990 by fossil hunter Sue
Hendrickson, who was employed by the Black Hills Institute of
Geological Research.
</P>
<P>
   The institute paid Williams $5,000 for the find, but two years
later the U.S. government claimed it owned the land and should have
custody of the skeleton. The matter wound up in a U.S. District
Court, which finally gave Williams the right to put the fossil
bones up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Sotheby's in New York arranged with Williams to auction
the bones on his behalf. The Field Museum of Chicago _ with
financial support from McDonald's and Walt Disney corporations and
the California State University System _ prevailed in a bidding war
with an offer of $7.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   A later dispute was settled more readily. The dinosaur first was
named Sue, after its discoverer. Then the Field Museum sponsored a
contest for a new name, coming up with Dakota. But after museum
lawyers advised that Dakota had the potential to cause legal
problems, museum officials went back to Sue.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why aren't the opening prayer in Congress and the motto ``In
God We Trust'' on coins deemed contrary to the separation of church
and state?
</P>
<P>
   A: In 1983, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that the practice of
opening sessions of Congress with a prayer didn't violate the ban
on establishment of religion expressed in the Constitution's First
Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The court noted that the practice dated to the first Congress,
the same Congress that adopted the First Amendment. ``The practice
of opening legislative sessions with prayer has become part of the
fabric of our society,'' the court stated. ``To invoke divine
guidance on a public body entrusted with making the laws is not, in
these circumstances, a violation of the Establishment Clause; it is
simply a tolerable acknowledgement of beliefs widely held among the
people of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In God We Trust'' is one of several inscriptions on coins
mandated by Title 31, Section 324, of the U.S. Code. In the case of
Aronow v. U.S. in 1970, the Ninth Circuit U.S. Court of Appeals'
decision upholding the slogan included this statement: ``It is
quite obvious that the national motto and the slogan on coin and
currency In God We Trust has nothing whatsoever to do with the
establishment of religion. Its use is of a patriotic or ceremonial
character and bears no true resemblance to a government sponsorship
of a religious exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have two MIA bracelets with the names of Capt. Hugh Fanning
(MIA 10/31/67) and M/Sgt. Edward Dodge (MIA 12/31/64). I would like
to know what happened to them. Where do I start?
</P>
<P>
   A: The P.O.W. Network _ online at www.asde.net/(tilde)pownet/ _
is a good resource. You enter the last name of the person you're
inquiring about, and are given a field of names, some of which are
identical. In the case of Fanning and Dodge, a lot of information
is available, but it's not conclusive on either one.
</P>
<P>
   Fanning and his bombardier were believed to have been shot down
over North Vietnam on a night mission Oct. 31, 1967. In August
1984, remains purported to be his were returned by the Vietnamese
and were buried with full military honors in Oklahoma City. But in
July 1985, his widow, Kathryn, acting on conflicting information
about the remains, arranged for them to be exhumed and examined.
The examiner concluded that they couldn't be scientifically
identified, so the official identification was rescinded.
</P>
<P>
   Dodge, based at Da Nang with a Special Forces group, flew on
Dec. 31, 1964, as observer on one of two aircraft that took off in
marginal weather conditions. They were to make a delivery to a
Special Forces camp in the A Shau Valley. Dodge's aircraft was
observed by personnel aboard the other aircraft turning and
becoming obscured by clouds, not to be seen again. While some
returned POWs speculated that Dodge may have been taken captive,
there was no proof, so his case continues to be unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I don't foresee most people wanting to carry many dollar
coins in their pockets or pocketbooks, as opposed to the
easier-to-handle paper dollars. So why is the Mint producing them?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Mint claims that demand has increased for a dollar coin
in commerce. Because the government's supply of Susan B. Anthony
dollars is nearly exhausted, it was believed that a new coin was
needed. And to make it easily distinguishable from other change, it
was decided that it should be ``golden.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mint explained that the increase in demand is attributable
to ``a growing recognition in the vending industry of the benefits
of dollar coins, including the convenience that comes from more
rapid transactions.''
</P>
<P>
   Paper dollars obviously aren't going away, so if you like them
better, the choice is yours.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is kudzu, the vine that is so predominant in the South, the
same thing as ginkgo, which is an ingredient of some vitamin
supplements? What are their scientific names?
</P>
<P>
   A: They aren't the same. Kudzu (scientific name: Pueraria
lobata) belongs to the pea family, Fabaceae or Leguminosae. Ginkgo
(scientific name: Ginkgo biloba) makes up the division Ginkgophyta
and the ginkgo family, Ginkgoceae.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whatever became of David Stockman, the budget director in
President Reagan's administration?
</P>
<P>
   A: On Aug. 1, 1985, after serving as director of the Office of
Management and Budget from 1981 _ and being given a large share of
credit for steering the Reagan administration's tax reductions and
domestic spending cuts through Congress _ Stockman resigned to
become a managing director at the New York investment banking firm
Salomon Brothers in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, he left Salomon Brothers to become senior managing
director at the Blackstone Group, also in New York, a company
involved in leveraged buyout investments.
</P>
<P>
   And last September Stockman, who is now 53, left Blackstone to
form Heartland Industrial Group, a private equity firm focusing on
undervalued industrial companies.
</P>
<P>
   Heartland, by the way, made headlines in business circles
earlier this month when Cynthia Hess, one of Detroit's top-ranking
female automotive engineers and a key architect of the Chrysler PT
Cruiser, jumped from DaimlerChrysler to join Heartland.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard that singer Marvin Gaye's father served little to no
jail time for murdering his legendary son. Is this true? And where
is he now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Marvin Gay Sr. _ his singer son added the extra letter to him
name when he launched his Motown singing career _ died at age 84 in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1984, he pleaded no contest in Los Angeles Superior
Court to voluntary manslaughter in the shooting death of his son
the previous April. The charge was reduced from first-degree murder
on a plea bargain. A coroner's report showed that drugs were found
in Gaye's system, and photos showed that the elder man had been
beaten by his much larger son. Judge Gordon Ringer suspended the
prison term and placed Gay on five years' probation, saying:
``Sending Gay to prison or requiring additional county jail time
would be a death sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   Gay Sr., a retired apostolic minister, had surgery in May 1984
for a nonmalignant tumor in his skull.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How many African-American players are there in the National
Hockey League?
</P>
<P>
   A: The NHL prefers to use the term ``minority players.'' These
were among those listed by the NHL on 1999-2000 rosters: Paul
Kariya, Anaheim Mighty Ducks; Rumun Ndur, Atlanta Thrashers; Anson
Carter, Boston Bruins; Grant Fuhr, Jarome Iginla and Fred
Brathwaite, Calgary Flames; David Tanabe, Carolina Hurricanes;
Blair Atcheynum, Chicago Blackhawks; Sean Brown, Mike Grier and
Georges Laraque, Edmonton Oilers; Peter Worrell, Florida Panthers;
Jamie Storr, Los Angeles Kings; Scott Gomez and Sheldon Souray, New
Jersey Devils; Gino Odjick and Jamie Rivers, New York Islanders;
Jason Doig, Theoren Fleury and Manny Malhotra, New York Rangers;
Joe Juneau, Ottawa Senators; Sandy McCarthy and Craig Berube,
Philadelphia Flyers; Jamal Mayers, St. Louis Blues; Donald
Brashear, Steve Kariya, Kevin Weekes and Harry York, Vancouver
Canucks; and Chris Simon, Washington Capitals.
</P>
<P>
   An article in the Oct. 4 issue of Sports Illustrated said
Edmonton's Grier is the only American-born and American-trained
black player in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My son is studying the Civil War in his history class. Is
that where the expression ``Don't shoot until you see the whites of
their eyes'' comes from?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. It dates to the American Revolution. The Oxford
Dictionary of Quotations traces it to the American Gen. Israel
Putnam (1718-90), who issued this order: ``Men, you are all
marksmen. Don't one of you fire until you see the white of their
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you give us any background information on Edward Egan,
the new archbishop of New York? I haven't seen much about him other
than the fact that he was chosen to succeed the late Cardinal John
O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   A: Archbishop-designate Egan, 68, who has led the Bridgeport,
Conn., diocese since 1988, was auxiliary bishop to O'Connor from
1985 to 1988 and had been widely predicted as his likely successor.
</P>
<P>
   Egan was born April 2, 1932, in Oak Park, Ill. After theological
studies at the Gregorian University in Rome, where he later
received a doctorate in canon law, he was ordained in December 1957
to the priesthood for the Chicago archdiocese.
</P>
<P>
   His positions have included assistant chancellor of the
Archdiocese of Chicago; assistant vice rector of the North American
College in Rome; an auditor of the Sacred Roman Rota, which is the
ordinary court of appeals for canonical cases appealed to the
Vatican, particularly regarding the validity of marriage; judge of
the Tribunal of the Rota; and professor of procedural law on the
law faculty of the Rota. In 1983, he was a member of the committee
of six canonists who reviewed the final draft of the New Code of
Canon Law with Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   Described as an uncompromising defender of traditional Vatican
teachings, Egan will become the 12th archbishop of New York when he
is formally installed June 19. He is also widely expected to be
elevated to cardinal by Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When I was a kid, I used to take a big passenger train from
Atlanta to Savannah. Do you know the name of that train?
</P>
<P>
   A: It was the Central of Georgia's Nancy Hanks. It ended its
Atlanta-Macon-Savannah runs on April 30, 1971, after 24 years of
service.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Bessonette at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ONE OF TWO FILES
</P>
