<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-GRAPEVINE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAPEVINE: Rumors, gossip from the world of wrestling
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Troubles in Extreme Championship Wrestling continued this week.
It's weekly TNN show had its lowest ratings since its debut. Going
head-to-head with the NBA playoffs is believed to be the culprit.
</P>
<P>
   ECW will move his September pay-per-view ``Anarchy Rulz'' to
October. No reason was given.
</P>
<P>
   Head honcho Paul Heyman offered Raven his unconditional release.
The move come after Heyman refused to use Raven in the ECW's latest
pay-per-view. Heyman has been vocal in his displeasure with Raven
work ethic since his return to ECW after a falling out with Bill
Busch and WCW. The expected departure comes at a bad time for ECW,
which also just lost Lance Storm to WCW last week. Meanwhile, Raven
will be beating down Vince McMahon's door looking for a job with
the World Wrestling Federation, but he could also find a position
with WCW now that Vince Russo and Eric Bischoff are calling the
shots.
</P>
<P>
   _ McMahon might want to scoop up Raven quickly because his
charges are losing wrestlers at an alarming rate. The Big Show will
be out of action for up to a month with knee surgery. Chris Benoit
and Perry Saturn both dragged themselves out sick bed to wrestle at
the ``Judgement Day'' pay-per-view. Benoit had the flu, while it is
suspected that Saturn may have had a case of food poisoning. But
the worse news is that 'Stone Cold' Steve Austin may be nowhere
near returning to the ring. Reports out of Texas are that Austin's
doctors have advised him to push back any hope for a ring return at
least another three months to the Survivor Series. The
disappointing news may be the result of rushing Austin back for an
appearance last month at the ``Backlash'' pay-per-view.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of ``Judgement Day'', it wasn't a very good day for
following the script. The match between Edge, Christian and Kurt
Angle against Too Cool and Rikishi ended later then expected
because of a kick out by Edge when he was suppose to be pinned.
Also, the main event - ``Iron Man'' one-hour match _ ran a little
longer than the 60 minutes. The Undertaker's surprise run-in came
when the clock on the television was at 60:08, that was suppose to
cause the DW of The Rock and give the title to Triple H. One
problem, the match is over at 60:00.
</P>
<P>
   _ The return of the Undertaker will also mean a new joint
venture for the WWF. Rapper Kid Rock will debut his single
``American Badass'' on Monday's Raw is War. His CD will be released
the next day. The single will become the entrance theme music for
the Undertaker.
</P>
<P>
   _ While Storm has left ECW, his valet, Dawn Marie, is still in
ECW and looking for a new wrestler to latch onto. Steve Corino's
group might be a good match, although it would be interesting to
and chance to move in a different directions with his gimmick if
popular Jerry Lynn were to add the annoying Marie to his act.
</P>
<P>
   _ Injury problems are not limited to the WWF. Arn Anderson broke
a bone his his foot during a recent Thunder taping.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expect to finally see Goldberg when WCW has its Nitro in
Atlanta on June 5. He probably will not wrestle but he will be in
person.
</P>
<P>
   _ Speaking of Goldberg, he was the guest of Lakers superstar
Shaquille O'Neal for a recent Lakers-Suns playoff game. The
friendship may amount to something this summer, when the Lakers
season is over. O'Neal may find a limited role in the WCW, much
like Dennis Rodman did a couple years ago.
</P>
<P>
   _ WCW will begin ``WCW Classics'' on Turner South soon. Former
NWA champion Dusty Rhodes is scheduled to host the highlight show.
</P>
<P>
   _ Wrestling movies are continuing their run. WCW's ``Ready to
Rumble'' has grossed $12.27 million in six weeks. By comparison,
John Cusack's critically acclaimed ``High Fidelity'' has earned
twice that during the same amount of time. Of course runaway hit
``Gladiator'' made $52.5 million its first weekend. Meanwhile, the
documentary ``Beyond the Mat'' is up to $2.047 million despite
running in many less theaters. But the number of theaters showing
the behind the scenes look at wrestling has steadily increased each
week and could reach 100 this week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
