<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 10:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4205 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      05-24 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW'S THE TIME FOR NOBODY TO COME TO OUR NATION'S AID 

</HEADLINE>
   By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congressman Tony Schnell is a man completely without principle,
a witless, soulless, gutless good-for-nothing who came out of
nowhere and has done zero, zilch, zippo since. He's a nobody, a
nonentity, a big, fat goose-egg.
</P>
<P>
   Think I'm being harsh? Eh, I say these things about Tony because
I love the guy. In fact, I like the good-for-nothing galoot so
much, I'm now running his re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Tony, I'm convinced, is a man for our times. A steady stream of
no-accounts and n'er-do-wells flows through our nation's capital,
but fellows like him don't drift by often. We need to grab his tie
and hold on.
</P>
<P>
   Let me give you an example of Tony's abilities: He has never,
ever uttered a word on the floor of the House of Representatives,
but he's so feared by his colleagues that they recently passed a
bill designed to shut him up permanently. A guy like that, you just
gotta believe in.
</P>
<P>
   Congressman Schnell is an empty suit of the truest sort. He
doesn't exist. He's the creation of Internet pranksters.
</P>
<P>
   A year or so ago, messages began circulating on the Internet
warning computer users of a dastardly plan to charge them extra to
send e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings came from a loquacious lady named Kate Turner,
ostensibly an assistant to Richard Stepp of the law firm of Berger,
Stepp and Gorman.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service, Kate said, is losing $230 million a
year in revenue because of the Internet, prompting a plan to offset
losses by imposing a five-cent surcharge on each piece of e-mail
sent.
</P>
<P>
   The author of this bill was none other than Congressman Tony
Schnell, a technological know-nothing who _ according to some
versions _ ``has even suggested a $20 to $40 per month surcharge on
all Internet service'' on top of the nickel-an-e-mail charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't sit by and watch your freedoms erode away!'' Kate said.
``Send this e-mail to EVERYONE on your list, and tell all your
friends and relatives to say `No!' to Bill 602-P.''
</P>
<P>
   The messages spread rapidly and began to mutate. Some versions
identified Tony as a Republican in the U.S. House, while others
made him a liberal ``backbencher'' in Canada. The U.S. Postal
Service began to share the blame with the Federal Communications
Commission. In time, Tony grew agitated with e-mail sapping profits
from long-distance telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Postmaster, the FCC and, for all I know, the Royal
Canadian Mounties all issued statements saying the proposal was
bogus, that nobody was talking about a special Internet tax, that
Tony Schnell was a nobody.
</P>
<P>
   But on Capitol Hill, the e-mail, letters and phone calls poured
in. ``The reality is that more people are communicating with us on
this than any other subject _ more than abortion, more than Elian,
more than gas prices,'' says Rep. Fred Upton, a real, live
Republican from Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   So Upton wrote a bill to block the nonexistent Schnell's
nonexistent proposal. And it passed, despite some objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are considering today is a fabricated solution to an
imaginary problem,'' Rep. John Dingell, a real, live Democrat from
Michigan, intoned on the House floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue is not bogus,'' Rep. W.J. ``Billy'' Tauzin, a real,
live Republican from Louisiana, retorted. ``There are real lawyers
litigating in the courts on this issue today.''
</P>
<P>
   The FCC, for its part, politely called Upton's bill
``superfluous.'' Congress, a commission spokesman said, ``has a
right to legislate policy, and we respect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily, I'm not a big fan of Internet hoaxes. But the saga
of Tony Schnell is making me reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't you like to see Congress finally do something to shore
up Social Security? Wouldn't you like to see campaign finance
reform?
</P>
<P>
   Why not get the fake Schnell to write fake bills proposing, say,
that the Social Security Administration send out cans of cat food
instead checks every other month, or that the Federal Elections
Commission issue candidates big boxes of Glad trash bags to carry
away campaign donations?
</P>
<P>
   Before you can say, ``You've got mail,'' real, live congressmen
will jump into action and stop Tony.
</P>
<P>
   I already have a slogan for his re-election: ``What the hell.
Maybe it's time for Schnell.''
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
