<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGURING THE COST OF RAISING A CHILD 

</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Department of Agriculture has figured that an average,
middle-income family will spend more than $160,000 to raise a child
born in 1999 through age 17.
</P>
<P>
   This seems like an incredibly low figure as my wife and I figure
we spent at least $150,000 on diapers and ear-infection medicine
before our son turned 2.
</P>
<P>
   According to the USDA, a two-parent family with a pre-tax income
of between $30,000 and $66,600 will spend $53,310 on housing,
$27,990 on food and $22,990 on transportation by the time their kid
turns 18.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, does not include the cost of college (roughly
$22,500 a year for a private school; $10,500 a year for a public
school), nor does it figure your costs if, God forbid, your child
continues to live at home after he or she turns 18.
</P>
<P>
   As you might expect, the cost of raising a child goes up each
year. It will cost about $4,000 less to bankroll a 1998 baby
through high school than it will a 1999 baby. Also, children become
progressively more expensive as they age, indicating that the
cheapest way to go is to adopt a child at age 17, keep it confined
to a playpen until its next birthday, then send it out to the
convenience store for cake and quickly change the locks.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, few of us are that clever, meaning that we wind
up financing our kids for the full 18 years, if not a great deal
longer.
</P>
<P>
   Even more unfortunately, you've got to keep in mind that the
USDA figure of $160,000 for a 1999 baby is an average (possibly of
Quaker children) and that your personal costs may be higher. Much
higher.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the USDA figures you will spend approximately
$12,000 to clothe your child from the time he or she is born until
the time he or she finishes high school or drops out to pursue a
career in grease-trap management, whichever comes first.
</P>
<P>
   I cannot speak for the parents of girls (though I can feel
sympathy for them), but I know that a $12,000 clothes budget for a
boy is ridiculously low. My 14-year-old is into skateboarding and
goes through $60-a-pair skateboarding shoes the way Homer Simpson
goes through doughnuts. One pair lasted all of two weeks. While we
waited for the Money Fairy to wave her magic wand over our bank
account, the boy had to go to school wearing shoes patched with
duct tape. While this was embarrassing to us, the other boys at
school thought this was ``cool'' and pretty soon everyone was
walking around with duct-taped shoes.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what the moral of this story is. Perhaps there is a
fortune to be made by manufacturing $60 skateboarding shoes made
entirely of duct tape, I don't know. All I know is that if I buy
him $60 shoes every two weeks between now and the time he turns 18,
I will spend $6,000, not including duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of my own personal clothing budget, which I figure to
be somewhere in the neighborhood of $27.50 a year, that would be
enough to last me until I'm 266 years old, or approximately the age
I'll be when I finish paying for his college education.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA also figures you will spend slightly over $18,000 on
``miscellaneous'' between the time your child is born and his or
her 18th birthday. The USDA does not spell out the meaning of
``miscellaneous,'' but you've got to think it includes Christmas
presents, birthday presents, Beanie Babies, Pokemon cards, baseball
cards, Barbie dolls, G.I. Joes, Nintendos, CD's, CD players and
makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Also $100 baseball gloves, $150 bats, basketball hoops, soccer
goals, skateboards, roller blades, $40 Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtle
assault vehicles that disintegrate into a million pieces of flimsy
plastic before you've finished your first cup of coffee Christmas
morning, $400 BMX bikes, comic books, Hot Wheels, Smurf's shampoo
and one or more Furbies.
</P>
<P>
   Just to be on the safe side, you might also want to figure about
$19.99 for school supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The point I'm trying to make is that while $160,000 may sound
like a lot of money, it doesn't go very far when raising a kid for
18 years.
</P>
<P>
   What's really shocking is that I've heard rumors that some
parents actually have more than one child.
</P>
<P>
   How you people manage is beyond me.
</P>
<P>
   But I bet it involves a lot of duct tape.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
