<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN--NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT HAPPENS NOW THAT THE MARCH IS OVER? 

</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They gathered. They marched. They gave the NRA hives. Now what?
</P>
<P>
   Elise was a marching mom last week. She opted for the smaller
and rainy day Oakland version of the Million Mom March, and she
considers herself one of the lucky ones. She wasn't carrying a
photo of a dead loved one.
</P>
<P>
   Violence, however, has visited her family. Last summer Elise's
college student son invited a young woman over for dinner and a
video. While he began cooking she went to her car to retrieve the
movie. Two men drove by, slowed and looked at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She told me later that they gave her a look,'' says Elise,
shaking her head, knowing the look.
</P>
<P>
   The two men burst through the back door, demanded drugs and
money, beat up on Elise's son and forced him and the young woman
into separate rooms. While one shoved Elise's son face-down on the
floor, the other raped the woman. Then they switched.
</P>
<P>
   It was over in less than 20 minutes _ long enough to turn an
ordinary night into something that altered lives forever.
</P>
<P>
   One of the suspects grabbed a butcher knife from the kitchen
counter. One looked to be carrying a gun and Elise's son wasn't
sure if it was a gun or knife at his back as he lay on the floor,
hearing the cries from the other room.
</P>
<P>
   Police found a gun on one of the suspects when they arrested
them later that night.
</P>
<P>
   Elise walked in the rain in Oakland with her husband, daughter
and another son because she knows that ``violence can happen to
anyone at anytime. You can't just worry about the problem, sitting
on your couch. You have to show up, do something,''
</P>
<P>
   Listening to the heartbreaking stories of other marchers,
Elise's family felt grateful. ``We saw a family that looked just
like us but they were carrying a sign with a photograph on it of a
young man in a tuxedo, looking like he might be going to a prom. He
was shot and killed a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   She's not sure what the solution to stemming violence is, but
she believes ``what's going on in our country right now is nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Elise attended the trial of her son's alleged attackers,
listening to the couple recount the terror of their ordeal. Family
members of the suspects were also there and when one of the men, a
parolee with a history of sexual and violent assaults, was
sentenced to prison, the man's mother let out a long wail.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I wanted to hate her for not doing a better job at
raising her child,'' said Elise, ``but I don't know her story.''
Elise prays, too, for the suspects. ``They could have killed them,
but they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   To Elise the challenge is more than what to do with guns, but
what to do about ``our beliefs, our culture and how we're
desensitizing people to violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to march in anti-war protests but back then we were
trying to stop a war that was over there. Now it's here. This is
our civil war.''
</P>
<P>
   Elise's brother is a member of the NRA and told her that her son
could have saved himself and his friend that night if he'd had a
gun in his apartment. She says, ``The only way having a gun would
have made a difference was if he were holding it in his hand and
waiting for someone to break through the back door.''
</P>
<P>
   Elise says she's always been anti-gun. When her kids were little
she wouldn't let them play with toy guns. But she allows gun
control is a complex issue and doesn't believe guns should be
outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, she's trying to think up other strategies for herself
and other mothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to do it with money because that's the quickest way to
make a difference in this country. My friend's been urging me to
invest in the stock market and when I heard Congress arguing about
trigger locks and how they wouldn't work, I had an idea. I'll find
out which high tech company knows how to make a trigger lock that
yields only to the thumb of the owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if a bunch of us decided that we'll only invest in
companies that are working to end violence?''
</P>
<P>
   What if?
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
