<HEADER>
A4212 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-DR.LAURA-COLUM     05-24 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-DR.LAURA-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICISM OF DR. LAURA ONLY AIDS SHOCK DOC 
</HEADLINE>
   (Repeating for all needing. For use Tuesday, May 23, or
thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of the ROEPER-COLUMN.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Laura Schlessinger is not an easy listen.
</P>
<P>
   I've tried, on a number of occasions, but I'm always put off by
her strict treatment of the very listeners who worship her. They
call to tell her about their bad marriages or their loveless lives
or their addictive tendencies or their problems on the job or with
relatives, and she responds by scolding, lecturing, judging and
mocking them for their weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   And then they thank her and hang up.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the shock doc's response to two calls I heard on a
recent program. First was a woman in her early 40s who was involved
with a man in his late 50s. The man was recently divorced after a
37-year marriage and wasn't interested in getting involved in
another serious relationship. Was this normal?
</P>
<P>
   ``Who cares if it's normal!'' Dr. Laura barked. She followed
that with some verbal vinegar telling the woman it was up to her if
she wanted to be with a man who didn't want a commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Next was an 8-year-old girl, who in a tiny trembling voice said
she was living with her mommy but she was thinking about moving in
with her daddy to see if it would be different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it would be different!'' Dr. Laura thundered. ``But
one's not going to be Disneyland and the other one's not going to
be hell!''
</P>
<P>
   After quizzing the poor kid about how often she saw her father,
Dr. Laura claimed in a cold voice that she felt bad for the child
and then said, ``Now go do the right thing!'' before moving on to a
break.
</P>
<P>
   Hate to quibble with the methodology of the advice goddess, but
didn't it occur to her to ask an 8-year-old child a few things
like: what are you doing home in the middle of the day, where's
mommy, who's watching you, do you make it a habit to dial up
nationally syndicated radio hosts, etc. I'm not quite sure how
pulling a Cruella Deville on an obviously confused little girl and
then cutting her off to hit that break at the top of the hour
constitutes responsible counseling.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just me.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, we must give Dr. Laura her props. What I find to
be a shrill, joyless, narrow-minded program is also a tremendously
successful juggernaut _ by some accounts the most-listened-to show
on the air, surpassing the listenerships of Imus, Limbaugh, Stern,
any of the big boys.
</P>
<P>
   If people want to listen to her show and buy her books and
purchase her magazine and scarf up her precious souvenir
merchandise, e.g., the Dr. Laura board game and the Dr. Laura
coffee mug and the Dr. Laura T-shirt and the Dr. Laura license
plate holder, go to it. Whatever gets you through the day.
</P>
<P>
   Same thing goes for the upcoming TV show. Perhaps Dr. Laura will
succeed where Rush Limbaugh failed in translating her strong
personality to a telegenic success; perhaps not. One thing beyond
debate is that she has the right to give it a shot _ despite the
organized efforts by some gay rights activists to have the show
killed in development.
</P>
<P>
   Rightfully outraged by some of the not-so-good doctor's comments
on homosexuality (``If you're gay or lesbian, you're a biological
error''; ``I call homosexual practices deviant''), the ``Stop Dr.
Laura'' movement is engaging in a sustained campaign to pressure
broadcasters and advertisers associated with the TV program, set to
air this fall via Paramount.
</P>
<P>
   The StopDr.Laura.com web site updates Schlessinger's latest
comments on gay-related issues, provides the phone numbers and
addresses of broadcast executives and sponsors, and lists the sites
and dates of upcoming protests in various markets.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate goal: cancellation of the program before it ever
hits the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   That's troubling. It seems hypocritical to me to say:, ``We're
here, we're queer, get used to it!'' and to follow that with:
``She's there, we're scared, so muzzle her!''
</P>
<P>
   Keep it up, and you're going to turn Schlessinger into a
free-speech martyr. Not to mention the mountains of free publicity
she's receiving for a TV show that might not even attract a sizable
audience on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some reports claiming Paramount will not aggressively
promote Dr. Laura's show or pursue favorable time slots in major
markets, executives for the company say they haven't wavered in
their support and will proceed with a Sept. 11 launch date
supported by considerable advance advertising muscle.
</P>
<P>
   I'm looking forward to it. Schlessinger could turn out to be the
most villainous doctor we've seen on TV in a long time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for
the Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
