<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hey, George, I want free treats, too
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush's plan to give away
free trigger locks to gun owners sounds cool, but what about us
people who don't pack heat?
</P>
<P>
   Don't we deserve a complimentary gift? I mean, if you're buying
votes, grease my palm, too. How about at least a free beer opener,
George, or a snow globe, for the rest of us?
</P>
<P>
   No, wait. I've got a better idea. Instead of just giving out
free trigger locks to the gun-totin' public, Bush should expand the
program to hand out free bulletproof vests to people who go around
unarmed.
</P>
<P>
   I sure would feel better about the trigger lock program if I
were getting a freebie out of it. And a flak jacket would make a
great costume come Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   I could go down to Sixth Street as a gun nut.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says he'll hand out free trigger locks to gun owners in
Texas, and, if elected president, he will hand out free trigger
locks to gun owners nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Swell, but what about us people who aren't into guns? What about
us folks who don't spend our weekends dressed up in camouflage
going to gun shows? Shouldn't we get a little souvenir, too?
</P>
<P>
   How about a free Charlton Heston T-shirt? Did you ever wonder
why this man needs a gun? The guy parted the Red Sea with a stick.
What's he need a gun for?
</P>
<P>
   Don't think I'm going to pose as a gun guy to try to fool Bush
into giving me a free trigger lock, though. I swore when I got out
of the Army in 1973 that I was never going to wear olive drab
again. And I'm not going to start now just so I can get a
complimentary trigger lock. Besides, have you ever wondered why
they call these events gun ``shows''?
</P>
<P>
   It would be a gun show if they had a couple of howitzers set up
on stage and they blew away a Camaro in the parking lot. I could go
for something like that. They don't really show off the guns at gun
shows, though. They sell guns at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   So why don't they call them what they really are _ gun sales?
They don't call them garage shows, do they? No, they call them
garage sales, because people aren't showing off their old clothes
at garage sales. They're selling them.
</P>
<P>
   I'd be a little more enthusiastic about this trigger lock
handout if there was something free in it for me. Instead of just
handing out trigger locks to these pistol-packing NRA types, why
not have them made into key chains and give them out to everybody?
There's all sorts of things a non-gun owner could do with a free
trigger lock. A pair of them would make great earrings for a woman
running for Miss Trailer Park.
</P>
<P>
   People love to get free stuff, and a program to hand out trigger
locks exclusively to gun owners leaves out a lot of Americans. I
was at the grocery store the other day and they were handing out
beer co-- zies to everybody. This guy had a card table set up and
he was asking everybody who walked by if they wanted a beer coozie.
But he wasn't asking people if they drank beer to see if they
qualified for a beer coozie.
</P>
<P>
   So why should someone have to own a gun to get one of Bush's
free trigger locks? I mean, they're a $10 value. So I want one.
Although I'd prefer a pair of fuzzy dice.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso's humor column appears weekly. He can be reached at
512-445-3606 or at jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
