<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 10:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4223 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN25-COLU     05-24 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN25-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reverend still rattled by church bombing, deaths
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The Rev. Fred Shuttlesworth has no trouble
remembering Christmas night, 1956, when his parsonage was blown to
bits by 15 sticks of dynamite.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttlesworth, the leader of the civil rights movement in
Birmingham, Ala., was flung to the basement. His children had been
sleeping in the next room.
</P>
<P>
   When a police officer advised, ``Reverend, if I were you, I
would get out of town, as quickly as possible,'' Shuttlesworth
replied, ``There's a war on. The battle has just begun, and I'm
here for the duration.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuttlesworth, 78, doesn't flinch when recalling what it was
like to be firehosed by Birmingham police, the water's force
stinging like whips.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't hesitate to describe being beaten with bicycle chains
and baseball bats by an angry mob while trying to enroll his
daughters in the all-white Phillips High School.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this renowned civil rights leader, a man often described as
``fiery'' and ``fearless,'' seems pained by the effort of
remembering the funeral of Carole Robertson, one of four girls
killed in the Sept. 15, 1963, bombing of the Sixteenth Street
Baptist Church in Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember,'' he said at first.
</P>
<P>
   In Spike Lee's moving film, 4 Little Girls, Shuttlesworth is
described as ``fearless and courageous to the point of almost being
insane.'' Yet when Shuttlesworth heard the news of the church
bombing, he broke down and wept.
</P>
<P>
   A mass funeral service was held for the three other victims, but
Carole's family wouldn't agree, saying, ``We feel her loss was
personal to us.'' The historical accounts show that Shuttlesworth
eulogized Carole as an innocent victim and as a soldier in the
battle for justice.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttlesworth relates a more personal memory from the funeral:
``I had the problem of comforting the sorrowing, while being aware
there were some in the congregation who were thinking, 'Had it not
been for that so-and-so, we wouldn't be here.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And yet, I had to speak the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   And he had to fight for justice, no matter what the cost to
himself, his family, or even innocents like Denise McNair, Carole
Robertson, Addie Mae Collins and Cynthia Wesley.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttlesworth felt more sorrowful than jubilant after the arrest
Wednesday of two former Klansmen, Thomas E. Blanton Jr. and Bobby
Frank Cherry, in the bombings. ``It makes for good copy the country
is doing something to meet justice,'' he said. ``But the FBI knew
then what it knows now. Justice delayed is justice denied.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the late FBI director J. Edgar Hoover who declined to
prosecute, Shuttlesworth recalled, ``but that decision should have
been made by state officials. There was so much collusion between
Hoover and the police.''
</P>
<P>
   Still an active pastor at the Greater New Light Baptist Church
he founded in Cincinnati in 1966, Shuttlesworth admits, ``I think
about retiring, but there is still too much to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrests in Birmingham shouldn't make us complacent,
Shuttlesworth warned: ``We make a mistake in thinking we've come
very far. Look at the controversy over the Confederate flag.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, the murders of the four girls shook much of the nation
out of its complacency about the civil rights struggle,
Shuttlesworth said: ``It was the innocents crying out from the
ground to the God of justice, crying out to the country _ which
only listened briefly and scurried off to do other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of congratulating itself on the arrests last week,
Shuttlesworth said, the nation should listen again: ``In the
creative moment in the '50s and '60s, America thought we could get
justice. We told ourselves, 'Let's get justice, let's put justice
on the front burner.''
</P>
<P>
   And look where we are today, he laments: ``Today we are
fostering the Martin Luther King Jr. holiday without pressing for
what King stood for, without fighting for the beloved community.
Justice isn't on our front burner anymore; the economy is on our
front burner. Who wants to be a millionaire? Everyone does. But the
real question is, 'Who wants justice?'''
</P>
<P>
   Justice was on Shuttlesworth's front burner from the moment he
arrived in Birmingham in 1953 to become pastor of the Bethel
Baptist Church. ``You can't preach who God is without talking about
justice,'' he explains. He founded the Alabama Christian Movement
for Human Rights and mobilized the struggle to end segregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord gave me a hard skull because I lived in hard times,''
he jokes now. When celebrated in Birmingham in 1988 with a street
named after him, Shuttlesworth remarked, ``You couldn't kill me, so
now you're honoring me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the '50s and '60s, it was no joke. Bethel Baptist Church was
bombed twice. ``There were eight or 10 occasions when I quite
literally could have gotten killed,'' he recalled. ``Everybody
thought I would get killed before Martin. Martin thought I would
get killed first.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it was Birmingham,'' Shuttlesworth replied, with the
patient tone of one explaining rudimentary history. ``Because of
the bombings, beatings, and castrations. Because of Bull Connor,
the chief of police who said 'I am the law down here.'''
</P>
<P>
   How could he so fearlessly put himself and his family in such
danger?
</P>
<P>
   ``If all of us got killed, I figured God would exact that as my
contribution,'' Shuttlesworth said. ``The Scripture says that he
who loses his life for my sake shall find it.''
</P>
<P>
   Faith casts out fear, he believes, as surely as fear puts a
damper on faith: ``We fear each other, we fear tomorrow, we fear
this evening, we fear losing our families, we fear speaking the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuttlesworth makes no apologies for putting such a spiritual
cast on the question of social justice: ``It's a spiritual problem.
We need to look up and look within more than we do. We need to
fight the urges to yield to the spirit of meanness and hatred in
this country. It is the seeds sown in that era that we are reaping
now, with the skinheads, militia groups and schoolchildren who have
no regard for the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the photos of four little girls once again appeared
on the front page of our nation's newspapers. In their blossoming
faces, as well as the chiseled visage of the old warrior, we can
read the challenge:
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put justice back on the front burner.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
