<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV14-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV14 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: For use Wednesday, June 14, or thereafter.)  
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: ARTICHOKE RISOTTO; GREENS AND
VINAIGRETTE  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by 20MINUTE-MENUS clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, see end of text. 
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just when you had a good handle on the kind of rice you should
buy to make risotto, the goal posts are being moved. When risotto
moved out of Italian restaurants into American home kitchens every
one went in search of arborio rice. A few years later other names
began to appear in the shops, like vialone nano and carnaroli.
</P>
<P>
   I have tried them all and have come to the conclusion that
arborio is just fine and makes an absolutely delicious creamy
risotto. But if you want to go the extra step, for an even creamier
version, you might want to see if you can find carnaroli in your
grocery store. It makes a difference, however slight.
</P>
<P>
   I could eat risotto once a week but since not everyone feels the
same I try not to impose the dish on this column too often. However
when I came across freshly cooked artichokes packaged in water in
the market where I shop the other day, I couldn't resist. It is a
vegetable that I love but seldom take the time to cook.
</P>
<P>
   Because the artichokes were stored in ordinary water, there was
no vinegary taste that you find with some jarred artichokes and
there was no oil, another preserving medium.
</P>
<P>
   Risotto came immediately to mind.
</P>
<P>
   Artichoke Risotto
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 cups no-salt-added chicken or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces whole onion or 4 tablespoons chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 cup arborio or carnaroli rice
</P>
<P>
   8 or 9 ounces cooked artichoke hearts (or frozen)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces Parmigiano Reggiano (7 heaping tablespoons coarsely
grated)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces thinly sliced prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1. In saucepan heat the stock to a simmer.
</P>
<P>
   2. Chop the onion. Heat the oil in a deep, heavy-bottomed pot;
add the onion and saute until it takes on a little color.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add the rice to the onion and stir until well coated.
</P>
<P>
   4. Add about one cup of the simmering broth to the rice and cook
over medium-high, stirring often, until the broth is absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   5. Continue adding broth as it is absorbed into the rice, while
stirring almost continuously.
</P>
<P>
   6. Meanwhile rinse the artichokes, drain and cut into bite-size
pieces. Grate the cheese and cut the prosciutto into small pieces.
</P>
<P>
   7. After adding the last of the liquid, (you may not need all of
it) cook until the rice is al dente but very creamy. Stir in the
artichokes and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   8. Remove the risotto from the heat and stir in the cheese and
prosciutto. Season with pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GREENS AND SESAME VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces mixed greens like mesclun
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons toasted sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1. Wash and dry the greens.
</P>
<P>
   2. In serving bowl whisk the oil and vinegar. Add the greens and
mix well to coat.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   GAME PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Prepare risotto through step 2
</P>
<P>
   Prepare salad through step 1
</P>
<P>
   Continue with risotto through step 4
</P>
<P>
   Finish salad
</P>
<P>
   Finish risotto
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Onion
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Whole black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Toasted sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   Rice wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 cups no-salt-added chicken or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   Bag arborio or carnaroli rice
</P>
<P>
   8 or 9 ounces cooked artichoke hearts (frozen OK, too)
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces Parmigiano Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 ounces thinly sliced prosciutto
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces mixed greens or mesclun
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 725 calories, 25 grams total
fat, 2.5 grams saturated fat, 35 milligrams cholesterol, 545
milligrams sodium, 100 grams carbohydrate, 11 grams fiber, 30 grams
protein.
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Marian Burros by electronic mail. Her
address is: marbur(at)nytimes.com. The (at) represents the symbol
on your keyboard. Please include your name and daytime telephone
number. Questions of general interest will be answered in this
column. &QL;
</P>
