<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AMUSEMENT-RIDES (Queensbury, N.Y.) _ The force of modern
amusement rides is attracting worldwide attention, including
hearings in Congress. Officials and some experts are wondering at
what point the gravitational pushes and pulls known as G-forces
turn from ``Gee Whiz'' to G-dangers. By MIKE HUREWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-TRAINER (San Antonio) _ The Texan is back. Decades
after the AT-6 ``Texan'' was used to train Army Air Corps and Navy
pilots during World War II, a new plane with a similar name landed
Tuesday at Randolph AFB. The T-6A ``Texan II'' was billed as a
cheaper, quieter and friendlier aerobatic alternative to the aging
T-37 ``Tweet,'' a small jet-powered craft that's been the service's
prime trainer the past 34 years. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   EXPLORER-MEMORIAL (San Francisco) _ It has taken 224 years for
Spanish explorer Juan Bautista de Anza to make his way back to
Mission Dolores. Only this time, the tenacious scout for colonial
Spain won't be arriving at the old mission on horseback. Most
likely he'll get there on a flatbed truck. Oh, and in the form of
an 8,000-pound bronze statue cast in his likeness. By RACHEL
GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   LA-SCHOOL-SUPERINTENDENT (San Antonio) _ Henry Cisneros, a
former San Antonio mayor and one-time Clinton administration
official, is on the short list of superintendent candidates for the
huge and beleaguered Los Angeles Unified School District. By
RUDOLPH BUSH.
</P>
<P>
   SF-SCHOOL-SUPERINTENDENT (San Francisco) _ The San Francisco
school board approved a four-year contract for new superintendent
Arlene Ackerman that will pay her $197,000 a year to head
California's fifth largest district, $12,000 more than her
predecessor. The announcement of the terms of Ackerman's unsigned
contract at Tuesday night's school board meeting drew an immediate
chorus of loud boos among teachers and parents in the audience. By
RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-MEDICS (San Antonio) _ For a good many Americans, memories
of the Korean War stem from the flickering images of characters
such as ``Hawkeye'' Pierce and ``Hot Lips'' Houlihan. The widely
popular, wisecracking television series ``MASH'' helped immortalize
the dedicated doctors and nurses who served at the front lines of
the Korean conflict. Those who experienced the war firsthand say
the show's screwball comedy in the midst of mayhem was, for the
most part, an accurate portrayal of life in a Mobile Army Surgical
Hospital unit. By NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   FIOM-REVIEW-IMPOSSIBLE (Undated)_ Don't look now, but the``
Mission Impossible'' franchise has been officially Wooed. What
constitutes Wooing? Several elements. For a film to be properly
Wooed, it must exploit slow motion at moments of exaggerated drama.
It must feature loving close-ups of a rugged hero, be he Chow
Yun-Fat or Tom Cruise, looking unflappably self-possessed. It must
contain action sequences of extended violence and elaborate
choreography, and it must do so using an endless quantities of
bullets. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GRILLING-GADGETS (Undated) _ Here are gadgets and gizmos that
can make outdoor grilling cleaner and easier. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ A federal judge ordered lawyers
in the antitrust suit to block the Hearst Corp.'s plans to sell The
Examiner and buy the San Francisco Chronicle to answer questions
about the papers' profit-splitting agreement and clauses that
allegedly thwarted other firms from buying the papers. By SETH
ROSENFELD.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-EXPLORER (San Antonio) _ Is it a car, a truck or a
sport-utility? Try all three. That's the feeling I got behind the
wheel of the all-new 2001 Ford Explorer Sport Trac, which from the
nose to behind the rear seat is a Ford Explorer sport-utility
vehicle. G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SOC-WOMEN'S-SOCCER (San Francisco) _ There will be only one
women's professional soccer league going forward after all. The
Women's United Soccer Association (WUSA), which put in its bid with
U.S. Soccer to run the league last winter, will work with the
cooperation of Major League Soccer to get their league off the
ground next spring. By MICHELLE SMITH.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Poor, rich little George W. Bush.
The liberal media conspiracy will never stop picking on him for his
youthful mistakes and privileges. The Boston Globe dug up young
Bush's service record in the Air National Guard and claims it shows
that, in his final year of military service in 1972-73, he didn't
do any flying and never showed up at the regular drills required of
guardsmen. You or I probably would be sent to the brig if we missed
our reservist or guard meetings, but not a favorite son _ that's
the implication of the story. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
