<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT'S SELF-INFLICTED WOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Isometimes use this space to defend Microsoft Corp. against the
US Justice Department. I do so for three reasons:
</P>
<P>
   --Much of the case against Microsoft is bogus.
</P>
<P>
   --To the extent that the company has done wrong, dismantling it
is a grossly disproportionate response.
</P>
<P>
   --And finally, why bother? If Microsoft continues its recent
idiocies, it will end up eviscerating itself.
</P>
<P>
   First there's the antitrust case, which the company could have
settled painlessly a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Love Bug virus that attacked millions of
Microsoft-based computers worldwide, because Microsoft
intentionally left dangerous security holes in its products.
</P>
<P>
   And now comes Microsoft's legal threat against Slashdot, one of
the Internet's most respected technology sites. The company's
behavior is as clueless as it is brutish. Here's the story:
</P>
<P>
   Everybody knows about the free Linux operating system, the most
famous open-source product, but there are many others. Kerberos,
for instance, is a data protocol designed to let people communicate
with computer networks without worrying their data might be
intercepted by bad guys. It was created at MIT, which freely offers
it to any software companies that want to add it to their products.
Kerberos has become quite a hit with businesses that rely on
versions of the Unix operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, sensibly enough, added Kerberos support to its
high-end corporate operating system, Windows 2000. But in standard
Microsoft fashion, the company also wanted to ``improve'' it, by
adding features to Kerberos that would make it work better with
other Microsoft products.
</P>
<P>
   People in the open source software community howled, and not
without reason. According to the notorious ``Halloween documents''
leaked to the public in 1998, Microsoft considered this very tactic
to undermine the popularity of open source software products like
the Linux operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft could add open source features to its own products,
but make changes in them. The open source features would still work
with other companies' products, but would work even better with
other Microsoft products. This would give Microsoft customers a
reason to stay loyal.
</P>
<P>
   The US Justice Department, suing Microsoft for antitrust
violations, said the Kerberos move was an unfair tactic to maintain
Microsoft's dominance of the software industry.
</P>
<P>
   They're correct, except for the ``unfair'' part. Microsoft has
every right to improve on existing products in ways that give them
an edge on rivals. As long as Microsoft's Kerberos still works with
other versions, I figure they're in the clear.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Microsoft promised to publish the details of its
changes to Kerberos. That would give other software makers a chance
to make their products compatible with Microsoft's.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's Kerberos document featured a bizarre legal
notice that said, in effect, ``Everything you read here belongs to
Microsoft. Don't try it at home.'' Microsoft published the data as
a ploy to show its ``openness,'' but ordered open source
programmers to act as if they'd never seen it.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when the popular Slashdot Web site published the
Microsoft document with the copyright warning removed, Microsoft
e-mailed Slashdot and threatened to sue if the offending materials
weren't removed. So far, Slashdot has refused. Perhaps it's eager
to see if Microsoft, a company on the verge of being ripped apart
for antitrust violations, would be stupid enough to pick a fight
over Kerberos.
</P>
<P>
   For a mature response to open source software, consider IBM
Corp.'s decision to offer Linux on its S/390 mainframes, the
machines that run banks, factories and the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   IBM will provide full corporate-grade support for Linux running
on its top-of-the-line hardware. Big Blue has had to upgrade Linux
to work on mainframes, but it's giving away its improvements at no
charge. Indeed, IBM has teams of programmers writing new and better
open source software, and giving it away.
</P>
<P>
   It's not altruism, of course. IBM makes its money selling
computer services, and can afford to give away software to get a
foot in the door. It's the same gambit Microsoft used with its Web
browser. Microsoft was right to do it, no matter what the courts
say. And IBM is right to embrace Linux.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Microsoft reacts to the open source challenge with an
unseemly blend of spite and panic. When you're as self-destructive
as Microsoft has been in recent years, a court-ordered breakup
begins to seem almost academic.
</P>
<P>
   Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-18-00 1304EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
