<HEADLINE>
3-D GAMING NOW RULE, NOT EXCEPTION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Electronic Entertainment Expo, or E3, is
always a treat to attend. Each year, the vision of the future of
entertainment becomes just a bit clearer.
</P>
<P>
   For the 2000 gathering, held this month at the Los Angeles
Convention Center, two things became apparent. First, 3-D
technologies are now the rule in computer and video gaming, rather
than the exception. And the hard-core game audience is no longer
the prime market for developers, who are now going after the
mainstream, casual player.
</P>
<P>
   Advances in and the proliferation of 3-D graphics hardware have
made it possible for those who write game programs to craft
elaborate, realistic worlds even for the simplest of games. Nearly
every PC sold in the past two years has a graphics card powerful
enough to run most of the games seen at E3 this year; and many of
those sold in the past three years can also handle them.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, most of the games being released for personal
computers have some kind of multiplayer or Internet component.
These are usually free _ you don't have to be a member of a service
to find opponents.
</P>
<P>
   For example, remember Frogger, the classic 1980s 2-D video game
in which you guided a frog across busy highways and swift-running
rivers? Hasbro released an updated version a while back, and soon
will offer Frogger 2, which fans of the original will barely
recognize.
</P>
<P>
   In Frogger 2, your little green friend is rendered in three
dimensions and has graduated beyond merely crossing freeways. He
now traverses jungle temples and platforms in space, dodging odd
creatures and tiles that drop from beneath his webbed feet. The
game, due to be delivered later this year, also lets players
compete over a network.
</P>
<P>
   This is a game for a mass audience, but relies on fairly
advanced graphics technology. Hasbro wouldn't be able to design the
game this way if it were not for the pervasiveness of 3-D graphics
cards.
</P>
<P>
   Another example: LucasArts' Monkey Island series of
tongue-in-cheek adventure games have traditionally been in 2-D. But
the next title, Escape from Monkey Island, moves to a 3-D style
that's in keeping with the cartoonish look of past games. This
game, due out in the fall, continues the adventures of
``swashbungling'' hero Guybrush Threepwood as he battles his
longtime nemesis, the villainous pirate, LeChuck.
</P>
<P>
   Games that have traditionally been created in 3-D _ such as
action, strategy and first-person shooters _ looked even better
this year. The realism in some cases was breathtaking, although
these were shown on state-of-the-art graphics cards that are just
now becoming available. They may or may not look as good on your
system when you bring the games home from the store.
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive first-person games I saw use id Software's
Quake III engine. That engine, which is at the core of id's own
Quake III Arena death-match game, is being used in three
high-profile games _ Electronic Arts' The World is Not Enough,
based on the James Bond film of the same name; Activision's Star
Trek Voyager: Elite Force, the first shooter to bear the Star Trek
name; and Gray Matter's Return to Castle Wolfenstein, a remake of
the game considered the original first-person shooter.
</P>
<P>
   The capabilities of the Quake III engine make all three titles
incredibly realistic. The Borgs you must battle in the Star Trek
game are creepily rendered _ you can see their ruined faces and the
detailed cyber-components of their exoskeletons. The exotic
settings in the James Bond title are part of an environment that
can be affected by what you do. Shooting at the wrong place on a
balcony can send it crashing down upon you, for example.
</P>
<P>
   But the most realistic of these three games is Return to Castle
Wolfenstein, which updates the original Wolfenstein 3D _ the
precursor to Doom and the original Quake _ in dramatic fashion.
Developers at Gray Matter photographed walls and floors in Europe
to create realistic textures for the Nazi stronghold dubbed Castle
Wolfenstein. The Quake III engine has been tweaked for even more
realism _ you can see the stubble on the chins of your opponents,
and cobwebs waft gently in midair. It is easily the most convincing
3-D environment I've seen yet in any game.
</P>
<P>
   Console games are also increasingly rendered in 3-D, and new
hardware is being developed with that in mind. Sony's Playstation
2, available now in Japan and coming to the United States in
October, is excellent at this. But it pales in comparison to what
will be offered by the latest player in this market: Microsoft's
X-Box.
</P>
<P>
   In closed-room demos for the press, Microsoft showed off the
X-box running at about one-tenth of its power capabilities. Even at
that low level, it was impressive. The detail shown on flowers in
an onscreen garden was rich _ I felt I could reach out and feel the
petals. The Microsoft representative running the demo claimed that
rendering one large flower in the garden used all the power that is
found in Playstation 2, indicating that the X-Box should run rings
around the Sony product.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in the overheated atmosphere of E3, it's important to
take all such comments with large grains of salt. But visually, the
X-Box demo beat out anything I saw running on the many Playstation
2 systems at E3. If Microsoft can deliver this quality when it
ships the X-Box sometime next year, the 800-pound gorilla of the PC
world will have made a formidable mark in the console universe.
</P>
<P>
   Send e-mail to dwight.silverman (a) chron.com. Silverman's Web
site is at www.dwightsilverman.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
