<HEADLINE>
COMMUNICATION GEAR MAKER TO SEAL ALLIANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Cisco Systems agreed earlier this month to acquire
Arrowpoint Communications, a maker of switches for Internet
communications, for about $6 billion, some analysts interpreted the
deal as a blow to Arrowpoint's main competitor, Alteon Websystems.
</P>
<P>
   But in the world of communications equipment, in which the
torrid pace of growth is matched only by the ferocity of
competition among giants like Cisco and Nortel Networks of Canada,
small companies with attractive technology can almost always find
friends. Reacting to Cisco's acquisition of Arrowpoint, Alteon
intends to announce this week that it has enlisted two powerful
allies: Lucent Technologies and Akamai Technologies.
</P>
<P>
   As Dominic P. Orr, Alteon's chief executive, put it last Friday:
``Up to 10 days ago, when Cisco acquired Arrowpoint, we were pretty
neutral and worked with any backbone builder. Now Cisco has gone
directly into our area. So now all enemies of Cisco are friends of
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   There is certainly no bigger enemy of Cisco than Lucent, the
former equipment arm of AT&AMP;T that has stumbled recently, even as
Cisco, the No. 1 maker of Internet communications gear, has become
one of the world's most valuable companies.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent, which has roots in the manufacture of telephone
switches, has spent billions trying to break into the data
communications arena. This week, Alteon intends to announce that
Lucent has agreed to sell Alteon's gear under the Lucent brand.
</P>
<P>
   Alteon and Arrowpoint each make equipment that sits between
communications networks and the big computer servers that support
Web sites and other Internet systems. The gear made by the two
companies helps distribute requests for Internet information among
the various servers within a facility, and helps the owners of
those servers use the computers more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Alteon, based in San Jose, Calif., hopes to benefit from
Lucent's extensive sales force pushing more of its systems into the
market. And Lucent, by putting its brand on Alteon's products, adds
another arrow to its own quiver.
</P>
<P>
   Such deals can be mutually beneficial. But some other small
communications equipment companies have come to believe that such
arrangements favor the bigger player by allowing the giant access
to the start-up's technology, while discouraging the smaller
company from developing its own sales force.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Lucent deal, Alteon also intends to announce this
week that it has struck a partnership with Akamai under which
Akamai will sometimes encourage its customers to purchase Alteon
equipment. Akamai, based in Cambridge, Mass., helps Web sites
distribute information to users more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-21-00 1856EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
