<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4300 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-SERVICE-PROVIDERS     05-24 1614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-SERVICE-PROVIDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENTING SOFTWARE AND THE SKILLS TO GO WITH IT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By LAURIE J. FLYNN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last year, Rave Sports, a small, privately-held maker of
inflatable water trampolines that is based in St. Paul, has been
scrambling to keep up with its sales.
</P>
<P>
   The last thing its executives wanted was the expense of hiring a
computing staff to manage the company's accounting and sales
management systems. So as a lot of other small-business executives
do these days, Rave's chief financial officer, Pat Golden, decided
to ``rent'' its main business software from one of a growing number
of Internet companies known as ASPs.
</P>
<P>
   An ASP _ short for application service provider _ uses the
Internet to offer a range of software and technology-related
services that would otherwise be performed by internal departments
at the customer's company.
</P>
<P>
   Some customers are contracting with application providers to
handle a few computing functions, like accounting, while others,
including Rave, are finding that it pays to farm out just about
everything, including e-mail, human resources management and online
travel booking.
</P>
<P>
   By signing up with an application provider, ``we've eliminated
having to spend a lot of cash upfront,'' Golden said.
</P>
<P>
   The trend has caused an explosion of young companies
specializing in the service, with the leaders including Rave's
provider, Agiliti, as well as Corio, Futurelink and Managed
Opportunity. But the demand has also led to hefty investments by
big telecommunications carriers, including Sprint and Qwest, which
plan to expand into the market. Meanwhile, many of the the nation's
Internet service providers, such as the Concentric Network Corp.,
are moving into the business to make themselves more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time, there were only a few dozen companies
calling themselves ASPs. By the end of this year, analysts predict,
there may be several hundred application providers clamoring for
the attention of small and midsize businesses, as well as the
information technology departments at bigger corporations.
</P>
<P>
   And the clamor is likely to fall on receptive ears, as
businesses seek to let somebody else deal with the headaches of
operating a computer network, dealing with frequent software
upgrades and running out of data storage space.
</P>
<P>
   Although Rave is now one of only a few thousand small businesses
that use an application service provider, the number is expected to
rise to 136,000 companies by the end of next year, according to
Cahners In-Stat, a market research company. And by the end of 2004,
according to Cahners In-Stat's forecast, more than three million
small businesses will be using application providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fundamentally changing the way information technology
is purchased and delivered,'' said Tom Kieffer, chief executive of
Agiliti, based in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Small businesses typically look at application providers as a
way to ``take away all the pain,'' of computing services, Kieffer
said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, big corporate computing departments are also rushing
to strike deals with application providers to shed at least some of
their applications. National Airlines, for one, has discovered that
it can keep its technology costs down by contracting out not only
basic services, like e-mail, but some of its more complex tasks as
well, like operating its frequent-flier program.
</P>
<P>
   And it may not be long before the trend touches consumers, too.
Instead of buying the latest new calendar software, a customer
could simply subscribe to a calendar program, accessing it over the
Web so that it would hog memory on a server computer rather than on
a PC, Palm hand-held device or, eventually, even a telephone. The
only requirement is a device with a Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   Several Web sites already offer consumers scheduling and other
basic software. Still missing is the business model that enables
companies to offer consumers a full range of software services at a
profit.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of all this activity, though, the application
provider business is among the fastest-growing information
technology categories today _one whose growth rate will only
accelerate, analysts predict. In 1998, revenues for application
service providers totaled about $400 million in North America,
according to the research firm Dataquest. Last year, that figure
rose to just over $1 billion, and it is expected to double this
year, to $2.4 billion. And in 2001, revenues will more than double
again, to $5.3 billion, Dataquest predicts.
</P>
<P>
   A major force behind the predicted surge is the expected arrival
in the market later this year of Sprint, Qwest and other
communications carriers. Those companies are investing
substantially in systems that will let them supply application
services, even as they roll out high-speed networks capable of
carrying voice, data and images.
</P>
<P>
   As the carriers enter the market, a rash of partnerships is
likely to break out among the various players. By the end of the
year, in fact, analysts are predicting that some companies will be
offering a package of rented software and high-speed Internet
access.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T, for example, has already signed a deal with
USinternetworking to deliver application services over AT&AMP;T's
planned high-speed networks through an AT&AMP;T program called
Ecosystem. Eventually, analysts predict, buying a busines network
computing service will be like choosing a telephone calling plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businesses aren't going to say, `I want a DSL line,''' said
Kneko Burney, director of markets and computing for Cahners
In-Stat, referring to a type of high-speed Internet connection.
``They'll say, `We want these business services.'''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say another factor driving growth is an increasing
confidence that businesses have with the security of online
communications. Because of that confidence, they are willing to
make the offerings of application providers available to more
employees.
</P>
<P>
   And businesses say they are reaping substantial savings by
renting software remotely rather than buying it and installing it
on site. An e-mail system, for example, can cost a company several
hundred dollars for each employee to operate internally each month.
By contracting with an outsider, some businesses say they can get
the cost down to about $100. Other services, like travel booking
and expense management, are often priced for each transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts predict that only the most mundane and basic
computing programs, like word processing, are likely to remain on
the hard disks of office computers as ASPs gain momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Rave, with 55 employees, has contracted with Agiliti to provide
and maintain the company's e-mail, accounting and order management
systems _ all for a monthly per-employee fee.
</P>
<P>
   Golden, Rave's chief financial officer, says the Agiliti
contract has allowed Rave to avoid hiring the additional technical
staff the company would have needed to handle those activities.
Because of the Agiliti deal, Rave's entire internal computing
operations can now be performed by one staff member, working
half-time. Rave's information-technology spending is only 2 percent
of sales, rather than the 5 percent Golden had been budgeting
before signing with Agiliti.
</P>
<P>
   Contracting with an application provider has also meant that
Rave can afford to use the latest accounting software, which would
otherwise have been too expensive to buy for each employee, Golden
said.
</P>
<P>
   Among bigger businesses, the construction company Morrison
Knudsen decided to farm out management of its e-mail system after
its acquisition of another company required adding nearly 6,000
e-mail addresses virtually overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine how long it would take to do that ourselves,'' said
Brian Bertlin, information services director of Morrison Knudsen,
based in Boise, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   Morrison Knudsen also handed off operation of its online travel
booking a few months ago to Unisys and is about to let Unisys take
on the company's travel expense accounting system. The aim, Bertlin
said, is to reduce costs in areas that do not directly generate
revenues for the company.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the application provider business is similar to
the network PC business model that concerns like Oracle and Novell
tried to have companies embrace a few years ago. Under that plan,
stripped-down personal computers were to function as terminals for
software resources stored on remote computer servers. But some
full-scale PCs became available for only a few hundred dollars, and
the network PC model never took hold.
</P>
<P>
   The application provider is also reminiscent of elements of the
mainframe era, when companies paid to time share the resources of
giant systems owned and run by companies like IBM and Digital
Equipment In the time-sharing systems of the 1970s, small and
midsize companies found it more economical to rent the resources of
a mainframe computer company rather than invest in
multimillion-dollar systems of their own, with all the attendant
support and staffing costs.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to the predominance of desktop PCs at most
modern business, as opposed to the few, closely guarded mainframe
terminals of yesteryear, there is at least one other key
difference: in hiring an application provider, the customer is
paying for the knowledge and skill of the supplier, not simply the
software and server computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, it's not about economies of scale but about economies
of skill,'' Burney said. ``It's all about expertise and the right
operating environment.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-21-00 1842EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4303 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-BOOK-DEAL-MEDIA-A     05-24 1784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-BOOK-DEAL-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN MARY HIGGINS CLARK LURE HER FAITHFUL TO E-BOOKS? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV:  Photo NYT1  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
 Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mary Higgins Clark, the blockbuster mystery writer
who lives in a mansion in Saddle River, N.J., and a Manhattan
apartment with commanding views of Central Park, grew up in the
Bronx, off Pelham Parkway. Her father owned a bar, called Higgins
Bar and Grille, and he died suddenly one Sunday morning while she
was at church.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, my mother had a total of $2,000 and three kids,''
Clark said in a recent interview in her pied-a-terre on Central
Park South, an emerald the size of a Chiclet on the third finger of
her left hand and an oil portrait of herself in rich pastels on the
wall behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Clark's mother, to make ends meet, rented out rooms. ``She put
up a sign that said, `Furnished rooms, kitchen privileges,''' Clark
said. ``But the neighbors thought the second phrase brought down
the tone of the neighborhood, so they asked my mother to cut it off
the sign. So she did. She was terribly enterprising.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clark, 72, has not lost the Bronx-Irish lilt to her voice
or her love of Irish jokes (A favorite: ``You know how an Irishman
proposes? `Nora, would you care to be buried with my mother?'''),
she has come a long way from those early Bronx days. Her latest
contract with Simon &AMP; Schuster, announced last month, is believed
to be a record-breaker.
</P>
<P>
   At five books for a total advance of $64 million, the contract
made her the highest-paid female author in the world, per book,
according to most industry estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the numbers, Clark is in some ways an intriguing
experiment for Simon &AMP; Schuster. Though the publishing house, a
unit of Viacom, says the author's possible appeal in the digital
world was not a factor in the negotiations, the company this week
will release the electronic version of ``Before I Say Good-Bye'' _
her newest best seller _ and nine of her other books in electronic
versions that will be available for laptops and desktop computers,
electronic reading devices and personal digital assistants.
</P>
<P>
   It is not yet clear if the mass market will find e-books
approachable. But Clark is a proven weapon. Her 22 hardcover books
_ usually critically unacclaimed mysteries that feature heroines
through whom housewives around the world can live out fears and
fantasies _ have all been best sellers. Her first suspense novel,
``Where Are the Children?'' published in 1975, has gone into 70
printings and has sold too many millions of copies for her agent or
publisher to estimate. By 2005, Clark will have received $160
million from Simon &AMP; Schuster.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Romanos, president and chief operating officer of Simon &AMP;
Schuster, said that as mass-market paperback sales atrophy across
the industry, one way to reconnect with readers may be to make a
mass-market author like Clark available in electronic formats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, No. 1, if you ask anybody our goal in the next few
years, it is going to be to intelligently guide the predominantly
print-oriented consumer publishing company into the electronic,
digital publishing world that's around the corner,'' Romanos said.
``The potential for the digital future still comes back to words.
The book may have just been a container. And we may now have to try
to reach readers on a screen, not in a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of mass-market paperbacks _ a medium in which the entire
Clark canon has traditionally been available _ are suffering across
the industry, which is struggling to reconcile its musty,
old-fashioned medium with the copyright and distribution issues of
the electronic and digital era.
</P>
<P>
   ``The core audience for the mass-market paperback is shrinking,
and that is something we have to think about every day,'' Romanos
said. ``The baby boomers, the `paperback in your back pocket'
people of the 1960s and 1970s, are now older and more affluent and
are buying hardcovers and walking around with reading glasses in
their back pockets. And that is coupled with the fact that we are
losing ground to the electronic media, which young people are
turning to for their leisure time.''
</P>
<P>
   And Simon &AMP; Schuster itself is also in a state of transition. In
1998, Viacom sold the publishing house's highly profitable textbook
and reference division to Pearson for $4.6 billion. And over the
coming year, the remaining part of Simon &AMP; Schuster, its trade-book
division, will be absorbed into the larger corporate structure of
the merged Viacom and CBS and will become an even smaller slice of
the corporate pie.
</P>
<P>
   The new contract gives Clark advances of $15 million each for
four mysteries, and $4 million for a memoir, which is to be
published in 2001 and which she has tentatively titled ``Kitchen
Privileges'' in homage to her mother. (Her last deal, in 1996, was
for three books at $36 million, or $12 million each.)
</P>
<P>
   Her editor, Michael Korda, and her agent, Eugene Winick of
McIntosh &AMP; Otis, both said that Clark made money for Simon &AMP;
Schuster above and beyond what it paid her. But other editors and
executives at Simon &AMP; Schuster said she was considered more of a
break-even author whose best sellers help ease the rest of the
Simon &AMP; Schuster list into bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Each of Clark's books sells about 700,000 hardcover copies,
which retail for $29 and on which she earns as much as a 15 percent
royalty, and about 1.5 million paperbacks at $7.99 with a 10
percent royalty.
</P>
<P>
   Because publishers do not release sales figures, it is
impossible to gauge how much she contributes to Simon &AMP; Schuster's
bottom line. One factor that adds to Clark's value is what is, to
some, her mystifying popularity overseas: she is, for example, the
best-selling fiction author in France, where the paperback rights
to her books regularly sell for more than 3 million francs (about
$420,000), said a foreign publishing scout based in New York who is
acquainted with her French contracts. Simon &AMP; Schuster retains
world rights to her novels, and sells foreign rights in individual
countries like the Netherlands, Italy, Britain and Germany,
countries where she is also very popular.
</P>
<P>
   John Baker, the editorial director of Publishers Weekly, the
trade journal, compared her books' popularity with foreign readers
to Sylvester Stallone movies that fare poorly in the United States
but generate substantial income in foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``For authors who are enormously successful but generally
critically spurned, as I am afraid poor Mary tends to be, there is
a lot of money to be made overseas,'' Baker said. ``I mean, they
name streets after her in France. It's a sort of Jerry Lewis
syndrome, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark's new books also can spur sales of her backlisted books
around Mother's Day each year, when her novels are published.
Unlike some other blockbuster authors like Patricia Cornwell, for
example, who have switched publishing houses during their careers _
all her books are under one roof.
</P>
<P>
   The one area in which Clark makes very little money, compared to
blockbuster authors like John Grisham or Stephen King, is in movies
or television.
</P>
<P>
   Baker said Clark's books are neither violent enough nor sexy
enough for Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her audience is romance readers who want a little suspense
thrown in,'' he said. ``They are not teenaged boys, which seems to
be the Hollywood market these days.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the future, given the vagaries, opportunities and threat
of the digital world, a traditional publishing company may be happy
to know that at least one of its blockbuster authors will be
sticking around for at least another half-decade.
</P>
<P>
   David Gernert, the agent and editor for Grisham, who is
published by Doubleday, said: ``In five years, a Clancy or a King
or a Grisham could walk up and say to their traditional publisher,
`I'm going to publish my own books on the Web and I'm going to
charge $20 a copy and of that $20 I will take home $18.' Well,
that's a little different from the model that book publishers are
offering. There's nothing like a long-term contract, because the
future is a little uncertain.''
</P>
<P>
   There is usually little left to uncertainty in a typical Clark
book. They usually follow a sleuthing protagonist _ always a
self-made woman with a career that lends itself to investigation,
like an attorney, television producer or reporter _ as a mystery,
such as a murder, a kidnapping or a bomb investigation, unfolds
around her.
</P>
<P>
   There is a symmetry between her plots and her own self-made
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is in each book a heroine, and there are certain
similarities to what we know about Mary,'' said Korda.
</P>
<P>
   After attending secretarial school, Clark worked as a secretary
and then as a Pan Am stewardess before marrying a childhood
neighbor, Warren Clark.
</P>
<P>
   She sold her first short story when she was 29, but interrupted
her writing to raise her children. Her husband _ who had a heart
condition that made him uninsurable _ died when Clark was 37,
leaving her with five children. She went to work writing radio
scripts to support the family, and rose at 5 a.m. every day to work
on a novel. (She remarried several years ago.)
</P>
<P>
   She sold her first suspense novel in 1975 for $3,000. For her
second in 1977, she got more than $1 million for all the rights,
and the first thing she did was buy a Cadillac to replace an
Oldsmobile with 146,000 miles on the odometer. Clark returned to
school and graduated from Fordham University in 1979. The
university gave her an honorary doctorate in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said the secret to her novels was that she explored the
fears of regular women, and used her heroines to reconcile those
fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``My people are never looking for trouble,'' she said. ``The
example I use is this: a young woman is in a see-through blouse and
a black leather miniskirt and walks along Ninth Avenue at three in
the morning. Something happens to her, You say, `My goodness, that
is terrible.'
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, if you take the same young woman, and she's
in her home, and she looks at her watch and says, `Oh gosh, it's
time to pick up the baby from Mother's,' and she gets in the car
and at the end of the driveway, from the floor of the back seat
someone says, `Don't turn right, dear. Turn left,' then she is your
sister or your daughter and you become emotionally involved in it.
I write about nice people whose lives are in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-21-00 1649EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1154EDT &QL; 
