<HEADLINE>
NEW ECONOMY: LAW FIRMS SEE A BILL COME DUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider this logic problem: Event A causes Event B. B then
causes C, and C causes D. Now assume A had never happened. Would D
have ever occurred?
</P>
<P>
   This is the multimillion-dollar hypothetical question that the
nation's top corporate lawyers find themselves uncomfortably
pondering after a wild five months that have altered the American
legal industry. If the answer to the question is no _ and there is
some strong evidence to support that conclusion _ then the
country's most prestigious law firms appear to have given
themselves an unnecessary and expensive headache.
</P>
<P>
   In their pain are lessons about the problems that overvalued
equity prices can cause even for businesses that seem to have
little relation to the stocks in question.
</P>
<P>
   The legal world's chain reaction had its beginnings last year in
Silicon Valley. With fast-growing Internet companies desperate for
employees, the Bay Area's law firms became prime hunting grounds.
Dozens of young, well-educated associates were more than happy to
accept the offers, leaving behind legal work that can resemble
drudgery to receive stock options that could be worth millions.
Turnover at the law firms soon hit new highs.
</P>
<P>
   The young lawyers' bosses began responding just before the new
year. Gunderson Dettmer Stough Villeneuve Franklin &AMP; Hachigian, a
small firm in Menlo Park, Calif., led the way, increasing
associates' salaries as much as 40 percent. Larger Bay Area firms
quickly matched and, to avoid morale problems, extended the raises
to lawyers in offices around the country.
</P>
<P>
   That was the key moment, the one that turned a local problem _
the dot-com talent war _ into a national phenomenon. The biggest
New York firms, which had always paid the highest salaries in the
nation, then had little choice but to match the increases or risk
losing their best lawyers to the East Coast branches of their
California rivals. By the spring, first-year associates at top
firms across the country were earning $125,000 a year, not
including annual bonuses that often exceed $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, however, something ironic was happening. At the
very companies stealing the lawyers, stock prices stopped rising.
Between Jan. 1 and April 1, the Morgan Stanley Internet index fell
5 percent. In April, as everybody now knows, the real drop came.
The index lost an additional 30 percent of its value in the first
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of dot-com companies, running through their cash and no
longer confident of being able to turn to the capital markets for
another infusion, began to conduct business differently. Private
companies had to delay their initial public offerings, making them
less able to offer rich salary packages. Suddenly, the value of
millions of stock options was in question.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rapid change from the two previous years, when many of
the lawyers who left behind law firm life for the Internet quickly
became millionaires, at least on paper. ``It appeared to people for
a while that if you reached for the brass ring, you grasped it,''
said Frederick Muto, a partner who oversees the San Diego office of
Cooley Godward, one of the firms with headquarters in Silicon
Valley. ``That perception has changed already.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is predictable: Turnover at many California law firms
has returned to normal levels. The big raises have surely played
some role in the decrease, but both partners and associates say the
biggest factor has been the technology slump. After all, notes
William F. Lee, the managing partner of Hale &AMP; Dorr in Boston, ``we
could never pay people enough'' to match the upside of stock
options.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what happened in the San Francisco office of Brobeck
Phleger &AMP; Harrison, another big California firm. On April 14 _ the
same day the Nasdaq hit its low for the year _ the lawyers there
held a going-away party for a senior associate who was quitting to
join an Internet company. On Saturday, a venture-capital firm
backed out of a large investment it had been planning to make in
the company. On Sunday, the lawyer called a partner to ask if she
could have her job back. On Monday, she was sitting in her office
again ``as if nothing had ever happened,'' said Tower C. Snow Jr.,
the firm's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Brobeck's turnover rate for associates is running at an
annual pace of about 16 percent this year. Because many fewer
lawyers have left in the last two months than in January and
February, Snow said he expected the final number to be close to 11
percent, the same as in 1998. Last year, by contrast, nearly
one-fourth of all Brobeck associates quit the firm.
</P>
<P>
   So the match that started the brush fire that grew into a forest
fire has now been extinguished. The lawyers who run the large firms
are reluctant to say they regret giving the raises _ which would be
tantamount to saying their own employees are overvalued _ but many
partners agree that had the market downturn come sooner, salaries
might not be at their current level.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question the environment would have been
different,'' said Alan S. Jaffe, the chairman of Proskauer Rose in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Snow added: ``A lot of the firms were very, very unhappy to make
the adjustments. I'm sure they're even more unhappy now.''
</P>
<P>
   One could argue that the firms overreacted in the first place
and that the decline of many technology stocks in early 2000 should
have suggested that the associate exodus would soon slow. On the
other hand, any individual firm that did not give raises risked
losing lawyers immediately, as would probably happen if the firms
now tried to scale back salaries to their earlier levels.
</P>
<P>
   For the most profitable firms, the raises may do little other
than cut the partners' annual pay by a hundred thousand dollars or
so. But some firms are already considering steps that include
raising their billing rates, cutting back on hiring, using
lawyer-for-hire agencies more often and even withdrawing from some
areas of the law. The drying up of the market for initial public
offerings and the Federal Reserve's recent interest-rate increases
could make cost-cutting more urgent if the lawyers' revenue begins
to slow, too.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the nation's biggest law firms are learning a
tough lesson about a downside of the new economy. For everybody
else, the moral of the story may be more familiar: Be wary of
accepting investment advice from your lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-21-00 1816EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
