<HEADLINE>
COMBATTING VIRUSES A NEVER-ENDING TASK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JACK WARNER   
 c.2000 Cox News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There are times, like a couple of weeks ago, when it's
nice not to be on the cutting edge.
</P>
<P>
   I refer to the weekend when most of the computerized world was
struggling with the I Love You virus. Yours truly was also
struggling, of course, but with an older and evidently lesser
virus.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody sent me the I Love You virus. There would have been no
point in it. The memsahib and I have been married 43 years now, and
we don't exchange e-mails with I Love You in the header. Call us
unromantic if you will, but e-mail seems to lack something in terms
of intimacy. I can still recall those lightly perfumed letters I
got from her during our courtship.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, if I should see ``I Love You'' amongst my messages,
at home or at work, I would assume it to be from a child seeking
money or an ad for a porno site. While it has been one of my
lifelong ambitions to be a sex object, only dogs and an amorous
goat in North Georgia have shown any inclination to follow me
around.
</P>
<P>
   As a practical matter, I'm also leery of opening attachments
unless I know who they're from. Eudora Pro automatically saves
every attachment I get at home, so every so often I go through and
dump them all. Unfortunately, since I subscribe to several busy
mailing lists, there are a lot of them.
</P>
<P>
   The advent of the I Love You virus reminded me that it's been
awhile since I updated my Norton Anti-Virus protection. Upon doing
that, the system informed my that FNEBJ.EXE, in the Windows/System
directory, was infected with a virus called Back Door SubSeven22.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how long this little fellow has been lurking in my
computer, but he didn't seem to cause any trouble until he was
found. After many system lockups and reboots, Norton agreed to try
to repair the file but could not, suggesting quarantine instead.
</P>
<P>
   The program reports that Back Door SubSeven22 is a rare virus, a
``Trojan horse that creates a security hole into your system.'' Now
that the file is in quarantine, Windows squawks about it every time
the system is booted. Removal from WIN.INI helped, but Windows
still complains.
</P>
<P>
   Try as I might, I couldn't find FNEBJ.EXE anywhere on the
Windows 98 install disk, so one assumes it is created upon
installation. Whatever the case, Windows seems to run all right
without it.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after updating the virus information, Back Door
SubSeven22 showed up again, but this time Norton grabbed it.
</P>
<P>
   The moral? Update your virus definitions regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-22-00 1405EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
