 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Global Show-'n-Tell on the web
 &HT;    By Robert W. Gee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ www.telenaut.com/gst _ Post your original
artwork and view other kids' art in virtual galleries on the Global
Show-'n-Tell home page. Each of the five galleries, organized by
age group, are named after an endangered species with links to
learn more about those species. The artwork, however, doesn't seem
to be restricted to nature motifs.
</P>
<P>
   www.kidlink.org _ The well-established site based in Norway is
celebrating its 10th anniversary this month. It claims more than
135,000 kids from 135 countries have participated over the years.
The site aims to facilitate a global dialogue for children over the
Internet _ through e-mail lists, chat rooms and various Web-based
dialogues in 15 languages _ in an effort to engender understanding
among cultures and, simply, to make new friends. To participate, a
child must answer these four questions: Who am I? What do I want to
be when I grow up? How do I want the world to be better when I grow
up? What can I do now to make this happen?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
