 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Neostream Interactive is a multisensory delight
 &HT;    By Omar L. Gallaga
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   www.neostream.com _ Just when you think you've seen everything
there is to see on the Web, here comes Neostream Interactive, a
multimedia firm from Sydney, Australia, whose Web design will blow
you away. This award-winning site is beautiful, with every link and
button a feast for the eyes, ears and mouse-clicking finger.
</P>
<P>
   www.garage.com _ On June 5-6, Garage.com, a Silicon Valley
company, will be at the Austin Convention Center to talk about
Internet start-ups. In the meantime, you can check out its site,
which contains information for investors and entrepreneurs in the
form of resources, forums and a newsroom. Use it to get that crazy,
economically unsound idea off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   www.historychannel.com/tdih _ If you're already addicted to the
History Channel, you can get a daily dose of it in the form of
``This Day in History,'' a Web page from the channel that shows you
big events for that date in history. There's also a searchable
database, including a ``What happened on your birthday?'' feature.
</P>
<P>
   members.tripod.com/(tilde)storyofjoe/index.html _ G.I. Joe is
real, and if you don't believe us, check out Austinite Timothy
(Zach) Laine's Web site devoted to G.I. Joe's interactions with
Laine's U.S. Army unit. Joe does pushups for the drill sergeant,
goes out on field exercises and meets an untimely end at the hands
of a defective plastic parachute. Funny, with well-posed pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
