<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4337 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      05-24 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREEDY, BOLD MAN AND THE SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - He is a poor fisherman who dreamed of greatness, like
the old man in the famous novel by Ernest Hemingway. Only his name
is not Santiago, it's Donato. And he is not old, but middle-age.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago was an unschooled Cuban who was nonetheless skillful
and wise. Donato is a high-school dropout from Poughkeepsie who is
not Cuban but has learned to play one on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago and Donato fished the same waters off the coast of
Florida and dreamed of hooking a fish so grand their names would be
renowned.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago spent his life at sea. Donato, according to news
reports, was at sea once, when he went fishing with his cousin, Sam
Ciancio, last Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   There is a boy in Santiago's life, and there is a boy in
Donato's life.
</P>
<P>
   The boy in ``The Old Man and the Sea'' is named Manolin. The boy
in Donato's story is named Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago sometimes fished with young Manolin. Donato and his
cousin fished young Elian out of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   To Santiago, Manolin was a friend and apprentice. To Donato,
Elian was a gold mine and, most recently, bait.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest moment in Santiago's life occurred when he hooked a
marlin. The greatest moment Donato's life occurred Monday, when he
used Elian to hook an even bigger fish _ the United States
government.
</P>
<P>
   Donato Dalrymple filed suit against Attorney General Janet Reno,
Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder and Immigration and
Naturalization Service Commissioner Doris Meissner. He is seeking
$100 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complaint alleges unnecessary and excessive physical
force,'' said Tom Fitton, president of Judicial Watch, the
conservative group that constantly fishes for ways to get its hooks
into politicians like Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Donato Dalrymple was in the Little Havana house where relatives
had been keeping Elian when federal agents broke in. They removed
the boy from the home and reunited him with his father. A picture
of Donato holding Elian while an armed officer confronts them
appeared in all the papers.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Old Man and the Sea,'' Santiago struggles with the huge
marlin for days, only to lose it, bite by bite, to hungry sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Donato, hoping not to lose his enormous catch, hired the sharks
to work for him.
</P>
<P>
   He claims his Fourth Amendment right against unreasonable search
and seizure was violated, as well as his Fifth Amendment right to
due process.
</P>
<P>
   Since the TV cameras have begun pointing in other directions,
Donato Dalrymple has had to go back to cleaning houses, which is
what he did for money before claiming he was selected by God to be
Elian's ``savior.''
</P>
<P>
   Strangers in Miami shouted ``pescador,'' Spanish for fisherman,
when they saw him on the street. Now they are able to shout
``sanguijuela.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloodsucker.
</P>
<P>
   In life as well as fiction, the principal character in a story
often speaks of a conquering hero after whom he would like to model
his life.
</P>
<P>
   In Ernest Hemingway's book, Santiago the fisherman admires the
skill and instincts of the baseball player Joe DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   In modern America, Donato Dalrymple greatly admires the skill
and instincts of O.J. Simpson's former house guest, Kato Kaelin. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
