<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4366 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-ARMY-MEDICS-HNS &LR;      05-24 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARMY-MEDICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     IN REAL LIFE, CHAOS REIGNED IN `MASH' UNITS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Note optional trim)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By NICOLE FOY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ For a good many Americans, memories of the Korean
War stem not from the battlefield or history books, but from
flickering images of characters such as ``Hawkeye'' Pierce and
``Hot Lips'' Houlihan.
</P>
<P>
   The widely popular, wisecracking television series ``MASH''
helped immortalize the dedicated doctors and nurses who served at
the front lines of the Korean conflict. Those who experienced the
war firsthand say the show's screwball comedy in the midst of
mayhem was, for the most part, an accurate portrayal of life in a
Mobile Army Surgical Hospital unit.
</P>
<P>
   But actor Alan Alda may never have reached the degree of fame he
did without the hand San Antonio had in molding the concept the
television series showcased. In 1948, the Medical Field Service
School at Fort Sam Houston played a lead role in designing the MASH
model, said John Greenwood, chief of the U.S. Army surgeon
general's Office of Medical History.
</P>
<P>
   Working with the surgeon general's office, the service school _
which trains combat medics and medical technicians _ helped with
the original design of the MASH, Greenwood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were trying to create a structure that was more
responsive to the front and much more mobile,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For those without the touchstone of battle, the television
series, book or movie, a MASH was a multitent surgical hospital
normally established about six to 15 miles from the battlefield's
front lines. Its main mission was to revive and stabilize the
seriously wounded so they could survive a trip to another facility,
usually an evacuation hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of a mobile treatment hospital evolved from World
War II, when the military created portable surgical hospitals
containing 25 to 30 beds, said retired Lt. Col. G.A. ``Scotty''
Knight, curator of the U.S. Army Medical Department Museum at Fort
Sam Houston in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The original mobile surgical hospitals in Korea had 60 beds,
but, by necessity, several bulged to 200 by the end of the
conflict, Knight said. Although it was but one piece of the medical
treatment system during the conflict, the MASH units were critical
in saving the lives of soldiers fighting on the front lines,
retired Lt. Col. John Catalano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't look at a MASH as a total entity,'' said Catalano,
who served as a platoon leader in Korea. ``But they sure did do
good work, considering the hostile situation they were operating
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Being close to the battlefront, the units _ which could span the
length of a football field _ often were forced to pick up and move
at a moment's notice. Evacuation could be frantic, especially when
the unit was continuing to receive and treat the wounded as it
attempted to move out of harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   In one month alone, the 8063rd MASH zigzagged up the rugged
Korean peninsula, covering 300 air miles on the ground. Each time
the unit moved, it took with it provisional and medical gear as
well as its 14 physicians: three surgeons, two anesthesiologists,
three assistant surgeons, two internists, one radiologist and three
general medical officers.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital also had 12 nurses, two medical service corps
officers and 93 enlisted men.
</P>
<P>
   Although health conditions such as malaria besieged the U.S.
military, it was Mother Nature who did the worst damage, according
to several historical accounts of MASH life. Temperatures as cold
as 30 degrees below zero took troops by surprise, causing hundreds
to freeze to death and sending scores of frostbite injuries to MASH
units.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A published history of the 8076th MASH recalled one of the first
winter days in 1950 when the temperatures plummeted below zero and
snow blanketed the battlefields:
</P>
<P>
   ``There were men who were fighting in nothing more than fatigues
and field jackets. During six days, there were 1,836 admissions to
the hospital and on one day, (there were) 661 admitted. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``The patients were arriving in such a large number that
literally there was no place to put them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the ambulances would arrive they would just have to leave
the patients lying in the snow, where unfortunately, some froze to
death before they could even be brought into the hospital tents.
However, being brought inside was no assurance against freezing,
because the temperature in the tents was so low that patients froze
there, their resistance being lowered as a result of their
injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the sudden influx of cold-related injuries was so great
that the MASH could not care for all of them, medical officers were
forced to make one of the ``most difficult decisions ever,'' the
history recounted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the more seriously injured patients were given
sufficient medication to prevent suffering and then they were put
aside to die while the hospital's attention was focused on those
casualties who could be saved,'' according to the historical
account.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was amid such chaos that MASH units worked to stabilize the
wounded for movement to evacuation hospitals. Eventually, many
patients also were transferred to Brooke Army Medical Center in San
Antonio for care.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Korean War, combat medicine has continued its
trend toward more mobile medical teams. The Army's last MASH _ the
212th _ was phased out last year, and in its place the next time
U.S. troops go to war will be a Forward Surgical Team.
</P>
<P>
   The smaller and more efficient FAST unit, as it's known,
consists of 22 people and occupies an area only 20 by 30 feet. The
idea emerged from a post-Gulf war demand for lighter, more mobile
medical units that can be placed as far forward as possible near a
battlefield.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
