<HEADER>
A4372 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-DAEDALUS-2NDTAKE-     05-24 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DAEDALUS-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPEATING SECOND TAKE FROM MONDAY NIGHT FILE FOR ALL WHO MISSED 
</HEADLINE>
   UNDATED: them artificially.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Daedalus genius probably will not be implemented in building
a machine that replaces the water in corpses with silica to turn
them into stone replicas suitable as funerary statues. Nor is it
likely that anyone will undertake a Daedalus-inspired investigation
as to whether an alcoholic suffering from delirium tremens could
draw from racial memory to visualize snakes and bats, even without
ever having seen such creatures in reality.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   A more practical idea might turn out to be a Daedalus proposal
to use the ``junk DNA'' incorporated in the genomes of all living
creatures, including microbes, as a vehicle for storing vast
quantities of information.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Although he denies the existence of any philosophic agenda in
his columns, Daedalus sometimes applies mischievous
pseudo-scientific analysis to explanations of supernatural
phenomena, including religion.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the genre was a column published on Nov. 17, 1994, in
the journal Nature (and included in the new book), examining ghosts
and poltergeists, which ``pose a severe challenge to science.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggests that there are two worlds, one material and one
spiritual, and that a poltergeist ``is a local leakage or coupling
between these two worlds.'' The chill experienced by people while
being haunted, Daedalus surmises, could be explained by assuming
that the spirit world is cold _ perhaps 3 degrees Kelvin, the value
of the cosmic microwave background left over from the Big Bang. In
Daedalus' thermodynamic analysis that follows, he concludes that a
poltergeist could be exorcized using an ordinary microwave oven
rigged to operate with its door open.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Jones acknowledged in an interview that some of his zany ideas
had outraged readers. In a column in 1993, Daedalus outlined a
scheme for measuring the velocity, direction and quantum-mechanical
spin of a soul as it leaves a body at the instant of death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main gainer will be theology,'' he wrote. ``Traditional
theology, perhaps, predicts that the soul of a sinner would depart
downward, and would weigh less than that of a righteous believer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Daedalus soul meter could shed light on a host of matters,
including the precise moment when a soul enters a fetus.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the soul turns out to enter the fetus quite late in
pregnancy,'' he wrote, ``the religious arguments against
contraception and early abortion will be neatly disproved.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones admits that the latest book of Daedalus columns is not for
everyone, even though the science in them is written to be
accessible to nonscientists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine that anyone who is strongly against evolution,
or who believes that intelligence is not inherited, or whatever,
would ever read the book,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even people with no understanding of science may enjoy it,
he believes.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on a quotation from Thomas Beecham, the eminent British
conductor, Daedalus said of the English, ``They don't understand
music, but they like the noise it makes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't understand science,'' he added, ``but
they like the noise it makes, so to speak. I try to address them as
well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
