<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4382 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-AMUSEMENT-RIDES-HNS &LR;      05-24 1061
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMUSEMENT-RIDES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ROLLER COASTER SAFETY CONCERNS RISE WITH G-FORCES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Fla., N.Y., Ohio, Texas)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MIKE HUREWITZ  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUEENSBURY, N.Y. _ Andy Schoonover was sluicing along on a
Jurassic Park River amusement ride in Florida last month when the
ride plunged into a pool of water, as it was supposed to. What
followed wasn't supposed to happen: He fractured two of his ribs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't anticipate stopping so suddenly,'' said the
41-year-old resident of Clinton Park, N.Y. ``I was thrown forward
and my chest hit a padded bar.''
</P>
<P>
   The force of modern amusement rides is attracting attention in
Congress and elsewhere. Officials and some experts are wondering at
what point the gravitational pushes and pulls known as G-forces
turn from ``Gee Whiz'' to G-dangers.
</P>
<P>
   In the rush to build bigger, faster, loopier rides, these
officials fear the industry is pushing the envelope on the limits
of human tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   In recent hearings, Massachusetts Rep. Edward J. Markey, who is
the ranking Democrat on a congressional consumer safety panel, said
the industry should take a more cautious approach. He cited a spike
in recent years of injuries from amusement park rides.
</P>
<P>
   Markey's office said the number of injuries resulting from
G-force cases is small _ only 15 cited in the medical literature
worldwide from 1966 to 1999 and only five in the United States. But
most have occurred since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Markey's office said most of the injuries were in the nature of
brain bruises and were treatable.
</P>
<P>
   In the related issue of ride safety in general, in one
catastrophic week last August four people died in roller coaster
accidents across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Germany is about to adopt limits on how much force should be
allowed on rides, said David Moulton, Markey's chief of staff. He
said German officials initially planned to adopt a standard of 5
Gs, but instead imposed a limit of 6.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, he said, several coasters in the United States,
including one in Texas, claim to be above 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is the industry in Germany telling us there are rides there
that are not safe that might be operating here?'' Moulton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Escape park in Queensbury features five roller
coasters. Park officials declined to supply the G-forces of those
coasters, but a spokesman for the park's parent corporation said
they aren't as powerful as some of the newer and more controversial
coasters.
</P>
<P>
   Great Escape's coasters include ``The Comet,'' a 95-foot-high
classic wooden ride moved to the park and rebuilt in 1994. ``The
Nightmare at Crack Axle Canyon,'' which made its debut last year,
is 45 feet high and attains speeds up to 34 mph as its twists and
turns in complete darkness inside a six-story building. There also
is the ``Alpine Bobsled,'' with a maximum height of 65 feet, the
``Boomerang Coast-to-Coaster,'' a high-tech backward-looping steel
coaster that attains speeds up to 45 mph, as well as the
74-foot-high ``Steamin' Demon.''
</P>
<P>
   John Collins, general manager of the park, said the rides go
through a four-step process to ensure their safety. The New York
Labor Department inspects the rides each spring. Great Escape's
insurance agency conducts several independent inspections, and the
park hires an independent auditor to conduct additional
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   And every day, before the park opens, employees conduct ``a
comprehensive checklist to make sure the rides are safe from an
electrical, mechanical and operational standpoint,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy McCormack, a spokesperson for the state Labor Department,
which oversees park safety, said G-forces are not recorded or
regulated by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to the engineer who designs the ride and the ride
manufacturer,'' McCormack said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Premier Parks' Six Flags Corporation, the parent
company of Great Escape since 1996, said the rides here, while
thrilling, are nowhere near the cutting edge of the high-tech
offerings at some of the newer, larger parks.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which often moves rides from park to park, wouldn't
hesitate to bring in a bigger coaster, spokeswoman Debbie Nauser
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't have any qualms about having the same coasters as
at Magic Mountain or Six Flags over Dallas, because they are all
safe rides,'' Nauser said.
</P>
<P>
   This year the new Millennium Force at Cedar Point in Sandusky,
Ohio, will break what had been a 300-foot barrier by 10 feet. That
means the coaster is higher than the Statue of Liberty. It will
reach speeds of 92 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the engineering society that sets standards for the
industry in the United States is looking at the issue of G-forces
and whether it would be prudent to impose limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We routinely do accelerometer testing of G-forces,'' said
Nauser, adding that a key to the safety of the experience is the
brief duration of the more extreme stress on the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to wear a flight suit to regulate your blood
flow. This isn't NASA,'' she added. ``On a roller coaster you are
probably going to experience a high G-force for maybe a 10th or a
100th of a second.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nauser said tests have shown this is less stress than the forces
of a human sneeze, which actually measures anywhere from 5 to 9 Gs.
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Israel, a spokeswoman for Zemperla, which manufactures
about one-fourth of the rides in the Six Flags chain, said that
while the Italian-based company has long made family-oriented
amusement rides, it is now moving increasingly into the thrill-ride
category. The trend is ``pushing the envelope'' with such rides,
she said, but she insisted that the company has the testing and
technology to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are more sophisticated with the testing, more rigorous with
the manufacturing. What you can do quickly these days in modifying
and making changes is light years ahead of where we were,'' Israel
said.
</P>
<P>
   As for Schoonover, the sore ribs from his Florida trip will
likely keep him off the coasters of the Great Escape this year, but
he is already looking forward to ``getting back on the horse'' next
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the thrill, I like the speed,'' he said, ``and I assume
that if they're running, that they've been adequately tested.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
