<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAKING THE DAILY GRILL EASIER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does your grill drool grease or sputter sparks? At one time or
another most grills become the source of a deck-top mess. Instead
of pressure washing wood or stone after every cookout, why not buy
a bib for the barbie?
</P>
<P>
   The ``Original'' Grill Pad, manufactured by DiversiTech Corp.,
is little more than a pad of thick, feltlike material coated in
colored concrete. But it's big enough (30-by-42-inch rectangles or
30-inch rounds) to protect the deck and can be cleaned off with a
shot from the garden hose. Prices range from $25 to $40 depending
on size. Look for it at area home centers and hearth and patio
stores.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   GET A GRIP
</P>
<P>
   OXO, the company that made kitchen utensils comfortable, has
expanded its line of tools with large, rubber-gripped handles for
outdoor cooking. OXO's Barbecue Tool Set includes a stainless-steel
turner, fork and tongs at a suggested retail price of $34.99. The
pieces are also available individually with prices from $9.99 to
$14.99.
</P>
<P>
   If sauces and corn-on-the-cob are usually part of your cookout,
a matching stainless-steel basting brush ($9.99) and
corn-on-the-cob holders ($5.99 for eight) are also available.
</P>
<P>
   Look for the line in area kitchen stores.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   CHARCOAL, NATURALLY
</P>
<P>
   More and more folks are saying ``to heck with briquettes'' and
opting for natural charcoal, wood that has been burned in a
controlled process. Unlike the bagged stuff, natural charcoal
starts easily and burns evenly and hot. The fire also suffocates
more easily and the remaining charcoal can be relighted. It's also
safer to store, since it's not presoaked in lighter fluid.
</P>
<P>
   On the down side, natural charcoal produces more soot, needs
lighter fluid to start and can be hard to find.
</P>
