<HEADER>
A4407 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-FILM-REVIEW-IMPOSSIBL     05-24 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-IMPOSSIBLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VIOLENCE ABOUNDS IN `M:I-2,' BUT IT'S A GAS TO WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don't look now, but the ``Mission: Impossible'' franchise has
been officially Wooed.
</P>
<P>
   What constitutes Wooing? Several elements. For a film to be
properly Wooed, it must exploit slow motion at moments of
exaggerated drama. It must feature loving close-ups of a rugged
hero, be he Chow Yun-Fat or Tom Cruise, looking unflappably
self-possessed. It must contain action sequences of extended
violence and elaborate choreography, and it must do so using an
endless quantities of bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The hero must, at points of apocalyptic violence, shoot
two-fisted at the villain while dodging (in slow motion) an
assortment of handguns, rifles, bazookas, grenades, speeding
vehicles, exploding vehicles and knives. Hand-to-hand combat must
be bloody and crisp; doves must be plentiful; villainous hideaways
must be subterranean. At all costs, motorcycles must be used as
deadly weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Such are the demands of a formal Wooing. And ``Mission:
Impossible 2'' _ that's ``M:I-2,'' in advertising parlance _ bears
in every way the stamp of John Woo, the Hong Kong director
(``Face/Off,'' ``Hard Boiled'') renowned for turning low crime into
high opera. And while Woo's films are surely an acquired taste (if
you hate movie violence, don't even try), there's no question that
this hard-driving, stylish sequel is both more entertaining and
less confusing than the original. Put it this way: You won't
scratch your head till your scalp bleeds. And that's a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission: Impossible 2'' offers Tom Cruise reprising the role
of Ethan Hunt, agent extraordinaire for the Impossible Mission
Force. Hunt is relaxing on the side of a cliff when he gets word,
via souped-up sunglasses, from the IMF boss in Seville. Said boss,
played by an uncredited Anthony Hopkins, tells Ethan to dump his
vacation plans and hightail it Spain, where he'll hook up with a
comely thief named Nyah Hall (Thandie Newton) for some
as-yet-undisclosed mission.
</P>
<P>
   Ethan goes to Seville. He encounters Nyah and, after a few
scenes of deliciously sexy double-entendres, finds himself in the
thick of an affair. Then he meets up with Hopkins' smooth jefe, who
informs him that Nyah must bed an old boyfriend, Ambrose (Dougray
Scott, much skankier here than in ``Ever After''), in an effort to
retrieve a hijacked super-virus from his clutches. Ethan balks.
``She's got no training for this kind of thing,'' he says. ``I
don't think I can get her to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the astute _ and somewhat amazed _ cinema dweeb
will recognize the above-described scene as a paraphrase of the key
set-up in Alfred Hitchcock's ``Notorious,'' in which Cary Grant's
G-man, having embarked on a torrid fling with Ingrid Bergman,
learns from his boss that she must bed the exiled Nazi (Claude
Rains) who has a crush on her. Grant says ``I don't know if she'll
do it'' and ``she's had no experience'' and ``she's never been
trained for that kind of work'' and goes off in a huff to Bergman;
in the painful balcony scene that follows, Bergman agrees to seduce
Rains.
</P>
<P>
   In ``M:I-2,'' Ethan returns in a huff to Nyah _ and in the
painful (but crucially altered) balcony scene that follows, she
agrees to seduce Ambrose. Other nods to ``Notorious'' follow: when
Nyah meets Ethan surreptitiously at the race track, when a
purloined item leads Ambrose to suspect that his prodigal
snuggle-bunny is actually an agent in disguise. There are touches,
too, of ``To Catch a Thief'' (the sexy repartee; the suicidal
driving maneuvers) and ``North by Northwest'' (Ambrose's sprawling
home looks suspiciously like a Frank Lloyd Wright), all of are
worked delightfully into the script.
</P>
<P>
   Credit such sneaky touches to Woo and his screenwriter, Robert
Towne (``Shampoo''), who enlivens the script with a good deal more
wit than he brought to the original ``Mission.'' The plot is no
shocker, but there are twists enough, and plenty of
latex-face-peeling, to keep us clamoring summer drones engaged.
</P>
<P>
   As for Woo's breathlessly over-the-top action setpieces, they're
absolute killers; the motorcycle tricks alone are masterpieces of
vehicular stuntwork. Technonerds will be pleased to learn that the
current film is almost as gizmo-centric as the earlier one _ Ving
Rhames is still holed up in his van with a laptop.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its PG-13 rating, ``M:I-2'' is a colossally violent
movie. The final cut lacks the rumored bed tango between Cruise and
Newton, so there isn't any sex to speak of, and there isn't much
profanity, either. But it is a Woo film, and Woo films aim for
overkill _ literal and figurative. They're shoot-'em-ups on
steroids, movies addicted to the adrenal punch of gunpowder.
They're bloody. They're loud. And sometimes, they're a gas to
watch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her electronic mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
