<HEADER>
A4412 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-24 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     W., THE INFREQUENT FLIER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Poor, rich little George W. Bush. The liberal
media conspiracy will never stop picking on him for his youthful
mistakes and privileges.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Globe dug up young Bush's service record in the Air
National Guard and claims it shows that, in his final year of
military service in 1972-73, he didn't do any flying and never
showed up at the regular drills required of Guardsmen.
</P>
<P>
   You or I probably would be sent to the brig if we missed our
reservist or Guard meetings, but not a favorite son _ that's the
implication of the story.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe also cites Bush's skipping the boring monthly meetings
as further evidence of his being an underachiever as a young man.
</P>
<P>
   As if anyone needed more proof.
</P>
<P>
   But man, is he an overachiever now. What Joe Six-Pack doesn't
identify with youthful underachievers who later make good on almost
no effort at all? The heck with that silver spoon, whatever orifice
it was used on.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he did not use illegal drugs after 1974. Whew. Who
would have wanted him flying an expensive taxpayer-purchased
airplane in 1973, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals are up to their
attention-getting ways again. In Wisconsin, cheeseheads are furious
because PETA has placed ads saying ``Got Zits?'' to convince
teen-agers that milk and cheese cause acne.
</P>
<P>
   If you think that's bogus, how about PETA's notion that not
buying milk will save cows' lives? Sorry, not buying milk will just
lead to the creation of more meat.
</P>
<P>
   PETA is still pushing its ``Got Beer?'' campaign, an effort to
get media attention by urging young people to drink beer instead of
milk. Never mind the outrage PETA received from that other
media-attention group, Mothers Against Drunk Driving.
</P>
<P>
   PETA's www.milksucks.com Web site has a list of reasons why beer
is better than milk, including ``Beer has zero fat; milk is loaded
with fat.''
</P>
<P>
   Come on. How about these? Nobody ever danced to ``Louie, Louie''
around a keg of milk. Nobody ever squished an empty milk can
against his head. Nobody ever got wasted on milk.
</P>
<P>
   That's why you got beer, and afterward you go out to some
farmer's field and tip over his cows.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court struck down a federal law requiring cable
systems to limit sexually explicit channels to late-night hours.
That didn't come as a big surprise to me.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise was that there is a thing called ``signal bleed,''
in which cable systems fail to scramble their signals well enough
to keep lascivious programming from leaking through to
non-subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   My cable company doesn't let anything through but old movies,
comedy shows from 1991 and reruns of Hitler rerunning over Russia.
The signal often fails entirely, providing the only blue material I
ever see _ an entirely blue screen.
</P>
<P>
   How can I get signal bleed from the Adam and Eve Channel, and
what can the Supreme Court do about it?
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   What does California Gov. Gray Davis have against the New York
Times? Our great national newspaper ran a front-page story Tuesday
on how tough California's governor is on crime, noting that Davis
refused numerous requests for interviews, on the grounds of being
too busy.
</P>
<P>
   Well, here's what happens when you decide you're too big to fit
all the news fit to print. The Great Gray Lady, as the Times is
known, referred to Davis twice as ``Mr. Gray'' (I guess the Times
has a Freudian slippage defense on that one). The newspaper also
brought back Davis' one memorable campaign line, the one about how,
on issues of law and order, he considers Singapore ``a good
starting point.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a Democrat, must love the lash indeed. He's trying to
create an imperial aura by not talking to reporters and not holding
news conferences, so reporters are waling on him.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a big-money guy, you can talk to Mr. Green, er, Mr.
Gray, er, Mr. Davis. On Tuesday he was in Las Vegas speaking at the
meeting of the International Council of Shopping Centers.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times does everything on purpose, I think. In its
Tuesday obit for Mark R. Hughes, 44, founder of the nutritional
supplement firm Herbalife, appeared the sentence: ``His death
appeared to be from natural causes, a spokesman for Herbalife
said.``
</P>
<P>
   Naturally.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
