<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4415 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-EXPLORER-HNS &LR;      05-24 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-EXPLORER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FORD OFFERS A NOT-QUITE-A-PICKUP PICKUP 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it a car, a truck or a sport-utility?
</P>
<P>
   Try all three. That's the feeling I got behind the wheel of the
all-new 2001 Ford Explorer Sport Trac, which from the nose to
behind the rear seat is a Ford Explorer sport-utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   From the back of the rear seat, it gets a bit different. Ford
has chopped off the top of what would have been the cargo area in
an Explorer and created what amounts to a four-by-four-foot pickup
bed.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we who know our pickups know that no real pickup would have
a bed just four feet long. Six feet, maybe, but not four. You could
barely get half of a sheet of plywood in that bed, and you would
need to tie one of those little red flags on the end of it to keep
other motorists from running into it.
</P>
<P>
   Ford isn't calling it a pickup, so neither will I, despite a
point-well-taken comment about the Sport Trac from one of our
readers, who insists that if it quacks, it must be a duck, and if
it has a bed, it must be a truck.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford has a good reason for not calling the Sport Trac a
pickup. According to the company's marketing literature and news
releases, the Sport Trac is designed to appeal to people ``who
would never consider buying a truck.'' So if we don't call it that,
perhaps we can sneak it past these anti-truck consumers, who surely
must not be from Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   Truck or not, the Sport Trac can carry stuff in its non-pickup
bed that you wouldn't want inside the passenger compartment of your
nice, clean, fancy Explorer _ like muddy off-road toys, hiking
boots, kayaks or camping equipment. And you can put stuff back
there that would be just way too tall to go in your regular
Explorer, such as a personal watercraft, motorcycle, or a muddy
all-terrain vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   What you don't have, though, is a nice, secure, dry,
weatherproofed place to put the things you would put in the cargo
area of your Explorer if you were on a cross-country trip with your
family, for instance. You'd have to toss everything _ suitcases and
all _ into the non-pickup bed, and worry about those storm clouds
looming on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Ford sells a lockable hard cover to go over the non-pickup bed,
however, so perhaps that's the route to take. But what happens if
you need to carry something taller than the non-pickup bed, yet
also need to keep something else covered up and out of the weather?
Maybe one of those car-top carriers like they sell at Sears or rent
at U-Haul would do the trick. That's how many of our parents
carried the family's luggage on summer trips when we all had those
big station wagons with the third seat.
</P>
<P>
   I remember a trip to North Carolina in my parents' '56 Ford
wagon once, with the luggage stacked on top of the car, covered by
a tarp. We hit a bump on some two-lane highway and my father
watched in dismay through the rearview mirror as a couple of the
suitcases fell off and went bouncing down the road. One of those
was mine, so I ended up having to share my two sisters' clothes for
the rest of the trip, but that's a whole other story.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, if you can overcome all of these little problems that
might crop up with an Explorer Sport Trac, then it just might be
the car/truck/SUV for you.
</P>
<P>
   Close your eyes while behind the wheel of the Sport Trac, and it
feels just like you're driving an Explorer, a vehicle that has
become very carlike over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Our test model came with a 4.0-liter V-6 engine that turns out a
respectable 205 horsepower and 240 foot-pounds of torque. I don't
think I'd want to try to pull a large horse trailer or cabin
cruiser with that engine, but for most people it will have adequate
power.
</P>
<P>
   Ride comfort is truly car- or SUV-like; it really doesn't feel
as though you're riding in a pickup. The rear end doesn't bounce
all over the road when you hit a bump, for instance. The seats are
carlike, and so are the instrument panel and most of the other
interior components _ including the leather-covered front bucket
seats (part of the $1,495 leather comfort group) and Berber floor
mats. When's the last time you drove a pickup with Berber mats? I'm
not sure I would want to climb into this vehicle with muddy shoes
on, for fear of ruining those mats.
</P>
<P>
   Our test vehicle came with part-time four-wheel drive and a
five-speed automatic transmission with overdrive, both included in
the $25,270 base price (plus $575 destination). A limited-slip axle
option ($355) helped turn this nontruck into a capable off-road
performer, and the $195 cargo cage at the rear of the non-pickup
bed would be a good place to tie down the picnic cooler and camping
gear to keep it secure while bumping over rocks on your favorite
unpaved trail.
</P>
<P>
   And this vehicle is intended to be used that way. Ford says the
Sport Trac is designed for people in their 30s and 40s with active
lifestyles, who go skiing and off-roading in Colorado or
beach-running in Baja.
</P>
<P>
   There were lots of other amenities on our Sport Trac that might
not come on the average compact pickup, including 16-inch
cast-aluminum wheels (part of a $700 ``premium sport group'' that
also brought fog lights and all-terrain tires), a power moon roof
($800), power windows and door locks (and a power rear window,
too), roof rails, a locking tailgate, speed-sensitive intermittent
wipers, a composite cargo bed, electric remote outside mirrors,
AM/FM/six-disc CD audio system ($270), privacy glass, and both
interior and exterior tie-downs.
</P>
<P>
   The vehicle can be operated in two-wheel-drive mode, or shifted
into four-wheel drive for off-road driving. There is a
four-wheel-drive low range for the transmission that allows the
vehicle to negotiate serious off-road hills.
</P>
<P>
   Four-wheel antilock brakes are standard, as are front air bags.
Side air bags for the front occupants are optional. Power
rack-and-pinion steering is standard.
</P>
<P>
   Maximum payload is 1,460 pounds (1,500 pounds with two-wheel
drive), and the vehicle is designed to tow a trailer of up to 5,040
pounds with four-wheel drive or 5,260 pounds with two-wheel drive.
Overall length is 205.9 inches, which is 17.4 inches longer than
the standard four-door Explorer. The wheelbase is a bit longer than
the four-door Explorer's, too _ 125.9 inches vs. 111.5 inches.
</P>
<P>
   Total sticker on our vehicle was $30,535, which is about what a
decently equipped regular Explorer costs. You can trim out some of
the extras and get a fairly well-equipped four-wheel-drive Sport
Trac for about $27,000, or a two-wheel-drive model for about
$25,000.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel economy is about average for an SUV in this class: 15 miles
per gallon in the city and 19 mpg on the highway. The Sport Trac
has a 20.5-gallon gasoline tank.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
