<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Thursday, May 25:
</P>
<P>
   BAHAMAS-OLDMONEY (Lyford Cay, Bahamas) _ Here on ``Lifeless
Cay,'' as many residents have called it, there are no stores, no
restaurants, no Manolo Blahniks. At least, not at the moment. Like
Southampton, N.Y., Greenwich, Conn., and most recently Palm Beach,
Fla., Lyford Cay is being invaded by the young and the feckless.
And almost nobody likes it. By Monique P. Yazigi.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ARTISTS-HOUSING (New York) _ Two original residents of
Westbeth _ the grand experiment in subsidized artists' housing that
opened in 1970 _ sat side by side on a wooden planter in front of
the entrance. One had a long graying beard and a brown fedora; the
other was missing some teeth and wore a fisherman's hat. Like them,
Westbeth is showing its age. The buildings look a little seedy: the
Corbusian curved balconies seem to be rusting away; the industrial
metal windows whistle; the inner courtyard is bleak. The fountain
on the outer courtyard has been cemented over. Yet on its 30th
anniversary, Westbeth is poised to reinvent itself. By Tracie
Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   MEIER-ARCHITECTURE (New York) _ Richard Meier, the
world-renowned, Pritzker Prize-winning architect, is promoting his
glassy new condominium in Greenwich Village _ his first building in
Manhattan in 30 years. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Gardening questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPEAN-PORCELAIN (New York) _ In a gesture that could be
interpreted as either the last straw for minimalism or an inspired
embrace of refined product design, several hundred pieces of
porcelain, conceived in the 18th century at the Nymphenburg factory
in Bavaria but still in production, were on display at Moss, the
SoHo store and purveyor of avant-garde modernism. By Julie V.
Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA-OUTDOORS (Vero Beach, Fla.) _ Windsor, a planned
community created here in 1989 by the husband-and-wife team of
Elizabeth Plater-Zyberk and Andres Duany, is meant to encourage
outdoor living. But unlike Celebration and Seaside, other Florida
planned communities where leisure time is spent on front porches
and stoops, Windsor is a place where outdoor time is lived out
back, in courtyards and on loggias, patios and verandas. By Martha
Baker.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTCHGARD (Undated) _ While experts argue the efficacy of
building America's space-based Strategic Defense Initiative, here
on earth one of the nation's most trusted defense systems will, by
the end of the year, be dismantled. Scotchgard, the soil retardant
and stain repellant spray manufactured by the the 3M Company of St.
Paul, Minnesota, is being ``phased out,'' the company announced on
May 16, because of environmental concerns about its
perfluorooctanyl chemistry. The same stuff that makes it easy to
lift a blob of chip dip off a carpet is, it turns out, harder to
get off the planet. Scotchgard does not decompose. By William L.
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   With howto drawing.
</P>
