<HEADER>
A4429 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ERITREA-ANALYSIS-BOS &LR;      05-24 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ERITREA-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORN OF AFRICA WAR HAS DEEP ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The war between Ethiopia and Eritrea may seem like a just
another senseless waste of lives and resources in the agonized
history of the Horn of Africa, but this fight is not about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the characteristically acute antagonisms of
allies-turned-enemies, beyond the negligible value of the
blood-soaked ground, lie important issues of geography, economics,
and politics.
</P>
<P>
   The founders of the first post-Marxist government of Ethiopia
and of the first government of independent Eritrea were allies in
the struggle to topple the dictator Mengistu Haile Mariam, who from
the late 1970s to the early 1990s ruled an Ethiopia that included
Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   The Eritrean People's Liberation Front had been fighting since
1960; their comrades in Ethiopia's northern province of Tigray, the
Tigray People's Liberation Front, had been struggling for Tigrean
autonomy since 1974. They finally toppled Mengistu in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Mengistu fell, Meles Zenawi, the Tigrean leader, was
able to make himself not just boss of Tigray but president of
Ethiopia. One of his first major moves was to recognize the
independence of his Eritrean allies and end the civil war.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the struggle against Mengistu, Meles and Isaias
Afwerki, president-to-be of Eritrea, became friends, ``as close as
Churchill and Roosevelt in their feelings for each other,'' says
Robert I. Rotberg, of Harvard's Kennedy School of Government.
Consequently, ``they made the kind of promises that people make
when they are close.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tigray insurgents and their comrades in Eritrea, many of
whom are ethnic Tigreans, committed Ethiopia and Eritrea to free
trade, a common currency, and the ideal of an integrated economy
for the region. So trusting of the relationship were the Tigreans
that they willingly gave up Ethiopia's access to the Red Sea. So
confident of the relationship were the Eritreans that they did not
worry about having their own currency or defining their new
borders.
</P>
<P>
   When they set the terms of the new state-to-state relations,
says James C. McCann, an Ethiopia specialist and director of
African studies at Boston University, they did not lay down a
realistic basis for the long-term relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war is not about a barren border area,'' he said, but
about frictions over tariffs, currencies, and access to the sea
that grew out of the poor initial agreements.
</P>
<P>
   The Ethiopians began routing their shipping through Djibouti.
The Eritreans developed a separate foreign exchange policy. The
Ethiopians began insisting on hard currency. The Eritreans issued
their own currency and, provocatively, named it after Nak'fa, scene
of their climactic defeat of Ethiopia during the independence
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   McCann, who returned to the Boston area from Ethiopia last
weekend, said the naming of the currency was symbolic of a long
period in which the Eritreans disrespected the Ethiopians, and
ultimately underestimated them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Eritreans bet that Ethiopia, which has scores of very
different linguistic and ethnic groups, was not a place, and would
fall apart rather than fight this war,'' McCann said. ``They
overplayed their hand and found themselves faced with a united,
determined, and powerful Ethiopia.''
</P>
<P>
   Some outside observers said Ethiopia will not try to add
substantially to its territory, but will attempt to destroy
Eritrea's capacity to threaten it militarily. They also said
Ethiopia would restore an outlet to the sea that cannot be readily
cut off by the Eritreans.
</P>
<P>
   McCann suggested Ethiopia could achieve this without annexing
Eritrean territory by orchestrating autonomy for the Afar, a Muslim
group that is dominant around the port of Assab. Bure, a border
town on the road to Assab, was a center of the fighting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the confusion in which the conflict is shrouded for
people outside the region surely is caused by the combatants
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Ethiopia insists that it really is fighting only about the
barren borderland.
</P>
<P>
   Many Eritreans assert the war was fomented by Tigreans because
their hold on power in Ethiopia is slipping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1442EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
