<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC SCHOLARS PUSH FOR ADVANCED STUDIES INSTITUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An elite group of Catholic scholars is proposing to form a
top-flight academic institute to strengthen the quality of Catholic
intellectual life in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Institute for Advanced Catholic Studies, which may
be located in Boston, comes at a time of some turmoil for Catholic
scholars, who are divided over social policy issues and worried
about the Catholic hierarchy's attempt to assert more control over
the teaching of theology.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the institute have raised $13 million of the $60
million they say they will need to start the project, which would
offer one-year fellowships to scholars in subjects related to
Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   Among the members of its founding board are three leading
Catholic intellectuals from Massachusetts: the Rev. J. Bryan Hehir,
dean of Harvard Divinity School, Lisa S. Cahill, a theologian at
Boston College, and David J. O'Brien, a historian who heads the
Center for Religion, Ethics and Culture at the College of the Holy
Cross in Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a couple of Catholic universities really reach the level
of first-rate research, and even there, outside of theology, they
often are under pressure to do work that is indistinguishable from
that in the secular US,'' O'Brien said. ``This is something that
needs to be done for the future of Catholic intelligence in the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Cahill said the institute would provide an opportunity for
scholars who don't ordinarily interact to work together. About 25
scholars would be fellows at the institute each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inspiration for this was the value of having a place for
Catholic scholarship to proceed in an interdisciplinary way,
without any particular ideological bias, and outside the control of
any particular institution,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The institute is the brainchild of the Rev. James L. Heft,
chancellor of the University of Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we have many Catholics with PhDs, but we don't have many
Catholic intellectuals, Catholics who in their bones, whatever
their discipline may be, instinctively draw on their faith
tradition to raise ethical and theological questions,'' Heft said.
``Scholarship in the Catholic intellectual tradition reinforces
that instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   The institute would not be a university, because it will not
grant degrees, and it will not be a think tank in that it will not
promote policies. The institute would be loosely modeled after
secular programs such as the Woodrow Wilson International Center
for Scholars in Washington and the Institute for Advanced Studies
in Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   The institute would not be governed by church hierarchy, and its
scholars would apparently be exempt from any requirement for church
approval of theological teachings because they would not be
teaching students. But the institute is seeking support from the
hierarchy, and its supporters included the late Cardinal John
O'Connor of New York and his successor, Archbishop-elect Edward
Egan, as well as the archbishops of Malines-Brussels, Cincinnati
and Los Angeles and the bishop of Oakland and the current or former
presidents of Catholic, Georgetown, Notre Dame, and Sacred Heart
universities and Carroll and Williams colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters have won a $10 million grant from a European
foundation and are attempting to double that by Christmas. They
have run into some roadblocks raising money because, although
Catholics are increasingly affluent, there are numerous Catholic
academic, religious and social service programs seeking money.
</P>
<P>
   ``A problem that we have faced from the beginning is that, while
there are donors interested in Catholic issues, they tend to be
more attuned to practical needs, such as working with the poor, and
Catholic missionary endeavors,'' Cahill said. ``There is an
important connection between academic life and the practical life,
but it's not as immediately engaging for some donors.''
</P>
<P>
   The institute would most likely be located in one of five
regions, chosen largely for the quality of their research libraries
and for their attractiveness to academics: Boston, Chicago,
Princeton, San Francisco and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not in opposition to Catholic colleges and
universities, nor is it a critique of what they're about,'' said
Hehir. ``The possibility is to be able to have the time and space
and a limited but very carefully chosen team put together to try
and illustrate the significance and relevance of the Catholic
vision to the rest of humanistic and secular knowledge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
