<HEADLINE>
WHAT SOX CALL `PARTNERSHIP' SOUNDS MORE LIKE WELFARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The only change in the official proposal by the Red Sox
for a new Fenway Park is that they want far more public money than
before.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the project was supposed to cost $550 million, with
the team covering $350 million. Now the Red Sox say the baseball
park will cost $627 million. The team will still cover only $352
million. The public portion has risen from a speculated $200
million to a confirmed $275 million.
</P>
<P>
   The $627 million would be the most costly single sports stadium
project in the history of the United States. The Sox are bragging
and moaning in the same breath that it is the largest
``investment'' by a team. What they do not want the public to dwell
on is that the $275 million from the public is alone more than the
cost of 10 of the 15 baseball stadiums built in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   This is depravity. No way should Fenway be built this way.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of their turpitude, the Red Sox brass came to the
Globe Friday to explain why some millionaire ballplayers, a wealthy
family trust, and rich limited partners deserve $275 million of
welfare. Red Sox CEO John Harrington, General Manager Dan Duquette,
and their hit men in dark suits tried to pawn themselves off as
Brooks Brothers businessmen.
</P>
<P>
   They quickly blubbered into a Blues Brothers self-absorption.
Their display charts, which looked pretty but said nothing, only
made them seem ever more the infant wailing for milk, the teenager
asking for new rollerblades after totaling the car, or the college
student begging for cash after smoking up the credit card. In
pining for a stadium, they acted as if they were as broke as
residents of the Pine Street Inn.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing that several members of the Globe were underwhelmed with
this lame presentation, Sox officials emitted a stream of alarms:
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is of the essence.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is coming in on us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We really do not have the option of the status quo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last site available to us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Status quo is not one of the options we have.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last site.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Status quo is not an option.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer we wait, the farther we fall behind in our
competiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're maxed out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We only broke even.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The players expect a modern facility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the gateway to Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a new ballpark to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   The alarmist stategy is utterly status quo. The Sox are just
another team in America that is making an extraordinary call for
public money with the least public participation, trying to ramrod
a stadium through the Legislature and Boston Mayor Thomas Menino
before the summer recess.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $275 million, $135 million would come from the state and
$140 million would come from Boston. The state would build parking
garages for $82 million. Garages could be fine, assuming the state
controls enough parking revenue to pay itself back. More dubious is
the $53 million in state road and transit improvements and in
utilities. It is unclear whether improvements would benefit
residents on a daily basis, such as a nicer subway stop, or which
ones the Sox ought to pay for themselves as the sole beneficiary.
</P>
<P>
   Far more insidious is Boston's $140 million. As it is now, it
would be a gift. The team would have no obligation to pay a penny
back to the city. The city would spend the $140 million to buy land
from private landowners, clean it up, prepare it, and then hand it
over to the Sox for the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox project $45 million a year in new revenues from a
new ballpark. The team's market value would skyrocket. Local
taxpayers would be left with at least $13 million in annual debt.
They and tourists would face more taxes to benefit the Sox while
Boston's after-school programs reach only half of its eligible
students and officials voted to cut $1 million from bilingual
education. Bilingual education these days is to help the Sox pay
Pedro Martinez so the Globe can keep running Martinez game stories
in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox hope we are all illiterate. The Sox say they will
``privately'' fund $352 million, but much of their private sources
for money are the fans who buy tickets and use the parking and
concessions. The Sox call this a public-private ``partnership.'' It
is a lie. Subtract the money from luxury suites, broadcast rights,
naming rights, and advertising, and it becomes clear that the team
wants a stadium with relatively no hard cash of its own.
</P>
<P>
   True partners share the risks and rewards. The Sox want $140
million a year to make $45 million more a year, while Boston goes
in the hole $13 million a year at a time when huge percentages of
its children are failing standardized tests. That is not a
partnership. That is depravity.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
