<HEADLINE>
THE SCREECHER VS. THE GLIDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is small and light, but since 1935 the Social Security card
owned by every American voter has been a blunt instrument, the
weapon of choice wielded by Democrats against Republicans. So it is
in the contest between Al Gore and George W. Bush, but this year
the weightiest factors may not be actuarial tables or market
projections, but tone, emphasis, and body language.
</P>
<P>
   Character will count more than 16-point programs in this, the
longest general presidential election in American history. (Not so
long ago, parties chose nominees in June, July, or August.)
</P>
<P>
   Although their strategies sometimes obscure their qualities,
both candidates are competent and likable. How they react to each
other will answer a question undecided voters will ask: What sort
of guy is he?
</P>
<P>
   Since wrapping up the Republican nomination in March, Bush has
been gliding toward the center the way some critics contend he
glided through life: short on specifics, long on charm.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who had a relatively easy time winning the Democratic
nomination, does not glide, but screeches full throttle into
endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   Gore resembles Eddie Mayehoff, a character actor who worked in
movies with Dean Martin and Jerry Lewis. Mayehoff was a football
coach or an Army sergeant, whose rules were relentless: Hit 'em
hard, hit 'em low, and if they get up, hit 'em again.
</P>
<P>
   This is Bush's first national campaign, but Gore's fourth, after
his own run in 1988 and two with President Clinton. The vice
president has learned the rapid-response lesson of the 1992
Clinton-Gore campaign. His campaign's ``war room'' is on full 24-7
alert. Rapid-response intensity can alienate some voters when it
sounds ``partisan,'' a word that became pejorative when a
Republican Congress tried to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's intensity can convert an adjective into a heat-seeking
missile. Bush wants a tax cut? ``Risky.'' School vouchers?
``Risky.'' Changing Social Security? ``Risky.'' In the debate over
privatizing part of Social Security, Gore can exploit the two
emotions that rule Wall Street: greed and fear. But he is also
stuck with an old Democratic theme: trust the government.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, voters equate risk-taking with leadership. Bush made
his Social Security speech in the southern California district
represented by Jim Brulte, the state Senate Republican floor
leader, who endorsed Bush after a trip to Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a candidate I'm proud of because he's willing to use
his political capital to help fix a program that every one of us
knows is broken, every one of us! It's the big elephant in the room
no one wants to talk about,'' Brulte says. ``Bush didn't have to
raise the issue, but that's what he did in Texas on schools and tax
reform. He had a huge approval rating, but what's the point of
being in a position to make things happen if you're not willing to
spend political capital?''
</P>
<P>
   Brulte's question brings to mind the political reality that a
vice president has no capital to spend. A veep's assets are bundled
with those of his one-man constituency, the fellow in the Oval
Office. Being vice president also means inheriting the party
machinery. Martin Van Buren, Richard Nixon, Hubert Humphrey, and
George Bush did so, but only Van Buren in 1836 and Bush in 1988
succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   For victory, a vice president needs a popular president like
Andrew Jackson or Ronald Reagan, but Dwight Eisenhower's popularity
wasn't enough for Nixon in his 1960 race against a young,
inexperienced opponent whose ideas were considered ``risky.''
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy won that election by promising ``to get this
country moving again'' and by standing against the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   If today's status quo declines economically, so does Gore. If
his assets become liabilities, he has no role model in taking
sensible risks in Clinton. Also the code of the vice presidency
forbids risk. Gore is, in effect, still risking his future on the
other fellow's riskiness.
</P>
<P>
   Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
