<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV'S TALKING HEADS FIND A HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Alan Dershowitz scored a four-fer.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of one day, the ubiquitous Harvard Law School prof
appeared on NBC's ``Today'' show, on MSNBC, on ``Larry King Live''
and Chris Matthews's ``Hardball,'' holding forth on an Arkansas
disciplinary committee's decision to strip President Clinton of his
law license. Thanks to modern technology, he did all this without
leaving his chair _ a chair sitting inside a rehabbed steam car
factory on a back street in the Boston suburb of Watertown. Called
VideoLink, it's a television studio that is Ground Zero for the
Boston Commentariat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best hangout in town,'' says Dershowitz, VideoLink's
unofficial First Citizen. ``It's better than any bar in Harvard
Square. Where else can you bump into Doris Kearns Goodwin, Bob
Reich, and Alan Simpson all on the same day?'' In fact, the Dersh
did bump into Goodwin at VideoLink on Tuesday; he was taping a 7
a.m. ``Today'' appearance, while she was on at 8.
</P>
<P>
   Dershowitz loves the Link. During last year's impeachment
crisis, he taped as many as five television appearances a day from
Watertown, all in one sitting. ``My only fear is that some day it
will lift up into the clouds and disappear, because of all the hot
air pumped in by the Cambridge intelligentsia.''
</P>
<P>
   Perfectly situated between Cambridge and the affluent western
suburbs, VideoLink is the venue of choice for the Harvard
professorate and the suburban intelligentsia. (Both Goodwin and
Dershowitz have timed their home-to-VideoLink commutes. Hers is 26
minutes. His is 6.) Have you ever seen a talking head opining from
Boston with that harbor skyline behind them? That fakey view of
Rowes Wharf, which could have been photographed only from a
helicopter or from the Logan airport control tower, is probably the
most-seen Hub landmark since 50 million TV fans ogled the
``Cheers'' awning back in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan Dershowitz practically lives here,'' jokes VideoLink
manager Andrew Kelley. And Kelley's staffers take pains to make the
studio a second home for the Dersh. Upon arrival, he is served his
beverage of choice (chamomile tea), and his beloved York mints
await in the green room, where make-up is applied. Like Goodwin and
fellow heavy user John Kerry, the Dersh even rates his own
custom-fitted audio earpiece. VideoLink keeps copies of
Dershowitz's books on hand, for convenient on-air brandishing.
``They provide everything,'' says the longtime law prof. ``With
them, all I have to bring is my mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Such creature comforts breed near-fanatical loyalty. Goodwin
says she doesn't travel any more to do television. ``I've been in
studios all over the world, and they are by far the best,''
Dershowitz says. ``When CNN opened up their new studio in
Brookline, I told them to forget about it. The only place I'm going
is VideoLink.''
</P>
<P>
   The brainchild of broadcast entrepreneurs Doug Weisman and Dean
Gaskill, VideoLink's business took off in 1997, during the Louise
Woodward ``killer nanny'' trial. ``Everybody had to get talking
heads from Boston,'' says manager Kelley. ``And we could deliver
them.'' ABC, NBC, PBS, CNN, and Fox News all conduct interviews out
of VideoLink, with the likes of Anthony Lewis, Republican
consultant Charley Manning, and Democratic commentator Mary Anne
Marsh, at the rate of eight to 10 a day. In the summer, Geraldo
Rivera motors up from Marion in his black Rolls Royce and
broadcasts his nightly talk show. . . live from Watertown!
</P>
<P>
   VideoLink offers convenience and economy; a half-hour in their
studio costs about $1,000, less than half the price of a rented
satellite truck. But just as important, it is a luxury motel for
the 24/7 gasbags. For the Stahkhanovites of the Ready-Opine-Think
business, no detail is spared. Dershowitz gets his tea and mints;
Goodwin gets Altoids and Diet Coke _ and her favorite make-up
artist, when available.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, Kelley's staffers place fresh flowers in the green
room, and make happy talk to distract guests if someone else is
eating into their airtime. The fresh coffee comes from Starbucks;
the fresh muffins from nearby Lilly's bakery. Hubby got the car?
VideoLink will pick you up.
</P>
<P>
   Last week at VideoLink, Goodwin logged her own four-fer _ one
PBS, one NBC, and two MSNBC appearances. Although she was taping
her comments on a sunny afternoon, viewers would see her in the
evening. Kelley and the New York producers thought about sliding
the ``Boston by Night'' panel in behind her. In the end, they opted
for ``dusk,'' which worked fine. (VideoLink also has separate
background panels of fake law books and medical tomes, to lend
gravitas to lawyer and doctor guests.)
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for her close-up, Goodwin banters with make-up artist
Phoebe Rambler. They are pals. Rambler has heard Goodwin's son's
rock band play at a club. Goodwin has shared her primo Red Sox
tickets with VideoLink staffers. Rambler will monitor Goodwin
throughout her broadcasts _ three before dinner, and one after _
brushing up her lips, or adusting the part of her hair when needed.
</P>
<P>
   On the set, Goodwin winds up her group discussion with Michael
Beschloss and Haynes Johnson on Social Security for the PBS
NewsHour, and then plunges into her notes. No one disturbs her.
After a few moments, Goodwin looks up and asks, ``Have we switched
over yet?'' From the control room, Kelley tells her that NBC's
``Nightly News'' is running late. Also, for the next shoot, could
she please turn her head slightly to the left? On screen, this will
look as if she is actually being interviewed by Andrea Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, an NBC producer comes on the line to conduct the
interview about the media's coverage of political sex scandals.
This is real TV, not PBS. Without prompting, Goodwin cuts her
answers from 40 seconds down to 20 seconds, and punctuates each
insight with a radiant smile. With time running out, an MSNBC
producer slips in a few questions about ``Clinton Nostalgia'' for a
10-minute long ``in-depth'' segement with anchor Brian Williams.
</P>
<P>
   In the control room, Kelley makes sure NBC liberates Goodwin by
5:30. She will make her downtown speaking engagement, and then
re-appear in Watertown one more time before going home. ``These
people are great,'' Goodwin enthuses as Kelley escorts her to her
waiting car. ``They are like family to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
