<SLUG> BC-AIR-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED ANNOUNCES PURCHASE OF US AIRWAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN and DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The world's largest airline, United, officially
announced Wednesday that it had agreed to acquire the biggest
carrier in the northeast United States, US Airways, for $4.3
billion in cash. The deal would create a carrier with by far the
largest share of passengers from Boston to New York to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are clearly a lot of hurdles in front of us, but we
anticipate this transaction can be completed in the first quarter
of 2001,'' James Goodwin, the chairman and chief executive of UAL
Corp., the parent of United, said Wednesday at a news conference in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The deal ``creates the first truly efficient nationwide network
in this country,'' Goodwin said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Wolf, chairman of US Airways Group, immediately tried to
allay fears that US Airways employees might harbor about the
buyout, saying that ``our employees will have the opportunity to
participate in an unparalleled venture in aviation history.''
</P>
<P>
   If the acquisition is approved by shareholders and government
regulators, United will carry almost 500,000 passengers a day, have
hubs in nine U.S. cities from Philadelphia to San Francisco and
employ 145,000 people. The acquisition represents the first merger
of two large U.S. airlines since a wave of consolidation in the
1980s, and analysts said United's new strength could force other
airlines to consider deals.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to exude confidence, both Goodwin and Wolf spoke while
standing near model airplanes representing their companies.
</P>
<P>
   UAL Corp. officials said on Tuesday that the combination would
allow millions of travelers in the Northeast _ long the company's
weak spot in the United States _ _ to tap into its vast network of
flights to the Midwest and West Coast and, on partner airlines, to
Europe and Asia. The company also pledged not to raise fares on
some domestic routes for at least two years except for price
increases needed to cover inflation and higher fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, UAL Corp. said it intended to shed many of US
Airways' routes at Ronald Reagan National Airport near Washington
and sell them to Robert L. Johnson, a member of the US Airways
board and the founder of Black Entertainment Television. Johnson
plans to operate a new airline with those planes, employees and
routes. But it will not include US Airways' lucrative shuttle
service between Washington, New York and Boston, which United would
continue to operate.
</P>
<P>
   The step is intended to satisfy regulators who might become
concerned about market concentration in the Washington area, where
United is the largest carrier at Washington Dulles International
Airport and US Airways is in a similar position at Reagan Airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1451EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
