<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-MISSION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUISE TAKES `M:I-2'' A LITTLE TOO SERIOUSLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   M:I-2 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by: John Woo &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Screenplay by: Robert Towne &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Tom Cruise, Dougray Scott, Thandie Newton, Richgard
Roxburgh, John Polson, Brendan Gleeson, Rade Sherbedghia, Ving
Rhames &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 124 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 (violent action and some sensuality)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tom Cruise is Hollywood's clenched fist. He's an overwound kind
of guy _ tight, serious, intense. In ``M:I-2,'' Cruise's ``Mission
Impossible'' sequel, he hangs by his fingernails from a rock face,
rides a motorcycle through a wall of fire, parachutes off a
skyscraper, and drops from a cable into a biotech sanctum to keep a
deadly new virus out of a terrorist's grip. Egged on by
transplanted Hong Kong actionmeister John Woo, who eggs with the
best of them, Cruise takes a licking and keeps on ticking until he
turns ``M:I-2'' into a triumph of over-the-topness that figures to
demolish the competition for a few weeks. Still, high-powered as it
is, it's more driven and silly than giddy and exuberant.
</P>
<P>
   The action is just as preposterous as it was the first time
around. Understandably, ``M:I-2'' forgets about logic for long
stretches at a time. All you have to keep in mind about the plot is
that if you're injected with the red stuff, you die in 20 hours. If
you're injected with the green stuff, you live. Handy color-coding
for a stop-go plot tooling around Sydney and surrounding patches of
Australia. But what really counts are the set pieces, starting when
a guy who looks like Cruise rips off a latex mask and is revealed
to be the bad guy in disguise. Woo overdoes the mask bit, a habit
he apparently got into after directing ``Face/Off.''
</P>
<P>
   e But what am I saying? Overdoing it is meat and drink to this
film, as nothing else is. When Cruise's superspy meets up with
Thandie Newton, as a larcenous love interest whose thieving
abilities he needs, they enjoy the automotive equivalent of rough
sex as they play bumper cars on a narrow road hugging the side of a
cliff. Woo ups the ante by having Cruise's Ethan Hunt clash more
than once with Dougray Scott's heavy, a renegade agent turned
big-time biothief and global shakedown artist. There are of course
the usual car chases and shootouts, with Woo making copious use of
slo-mo as this or that body hurtles through the air, gun in each
hand, blazing away.
</P>
<P>
   The slo-mo, once original and even flecked with a certain visual
poetry, is starting to look old, and there's nothing quite as
spectacular here as the sight of Cruise clinging to the top of a
train in the first ``Mission Impossible.'' Not that anybody is
going to complain of somnolence here. Still, hard-driving and
propulsive as it is, the film is unable to hide the fact that Woo
seems not only to be repeating himself, but parodying his earlier
films on a much bigger scale, more crudely and coarsely. You're as
likely to laugh at ``M:I-2'' as with it, especially if you know
Woo's earlier films.
</P>
<P>
   When we see a doorway framed in flames, we know Tom Terrific
will soon be framed by it, too. At a certain point during one
shootout, one of Woo's signature white doves flies out of an
alcove, providing as much ironic comment as this film is interested
in providing. After a motorcycle joust, Cruise's white knight and
Scott's dark one square off on a beach, where they provide a
scientific demonstration of the number of times a star can get
kicked in the head without loss of speed, much less function. Or
teeth. Still, ``M:I-2'' does have a certain integrity. At least it
doesn't insist that Cruise's character and Newton's are supposed to
have anything like real feelings for one another.
</P>
<P>
   The weakness of ``M:I-2'' is that it's too humorless to embrace
its preposterousness. On the surface, it has a certain James Bond
quality. But Bond would have winked at a lot of the stuff that just
makes Cruise set his jaw more firmly here. Scott holds the screen
ably against Cruise, considering that we know at the start that
he's going to lose. Anthony Hopkins puts in only the most
perfunctory appearance as Cruise's boss, although he has the film's
best line when Cruise momentarily balks. Under the circumstances,
Newton does a game job of projecting naughtiness and vulnerability.
``M:I-2'' has all the fireballs, forward motion, latex masks, and
views of Sydney harbor you could hope for. There's not much there,
but with what there is, the film hits hard. At heart, it's a huge
comic strip. But nobody seems to have reminded Cruise of this.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1451EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
