<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4457 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOLIVAR-COLLECTOR-ART     05-24 1508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOLIVAR-COLLECTOR-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 INTEREST IN SIMON BOLIVAR FILLS A LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Maury Bromsen, 81-year-old Boston manuscript dealer,
bibliographer, and collector of Latin American materials, is
showing a visitor a few of the treasures in his living room. There
is the French cello made in 1743, with a carved head of a plumed
cavalier, created for Louis XV, still bearing the original label;
the late-17th-century refectory table used in a monastery,
perfectly preserved; the elegant bust of the Marquis de Lafayette,
circa 1790.
</P>
<P>
   His voice swells with pride with every item he points out. But
then comes the real prize. He retrieves a leather-bound volume from
a back room, bearing it toward a visitor like a gem on a velvet
pillow. It is his humble junior high school autograph book. He
turns to the ``Your Favorites'' section. Whom did the 13-year-old
Bromsen list as his ``favorite hero'' back in 1932? Babe Ruth,
perhaps? George Washington?
</P>
<P>
   How about Simon Bolivar?
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-century revolutionary leader in the struggle for South
American independence was hardly an obvious choice for a
13-year-old Jewish kid from New York City who'd traveled no farther
than Long Island. What makes it even more unusual is that his
reverence for Bolivar lasted a lifetime. Bromsen went on to amass
this country's largest and most significant collection of original
Bolivar-related art, manuscripts, and iconographic materials.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Bromsen officially parted with his beloved collection
of ``Bolivariana,'' valued, he says, at ``several millions of
dollars,'' donating it to the John Carter Brown Library at Brown
University. The library is devoted to the preservation of
historical materials related to the Americas, and the collection is
now lodged in its newly inaugurated Maury A. Bromsen-Simon Bolivar
Room.
</P>
<P>
   It includes not only paintings of Bolivar but the document
Bromsen calls ``the crown jewel of my collection.'' Dating to 1825
and signed by Bolivar, it announced the appointment of Antonio Jose
de Sucre as Grand Marshal of Ayacucho. Sucre commanded the
revolutionary army in the final battle of the war for independence
in Spanish America; Ayacucho, in Peru, was the site of this
decisive battle.
</P>
<P>
   The significance of such a document might be lost on the average
American, but never Bolivar groupie Bromsen. The battle of
Ayacucho, he says emphatically, ``is like Waterloo. It's like the
last battle of Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   He bought the document in 1963 directly from a descendant of
Sucre, in Quito, Ecuador. The price? ``I won't tell you,'' he says
immediately. ``But everybody wants it. In fact, the former
president of Venezuela asked me if I'd give him the document and
said he would send for me in an airplane and bring me to address
Congress, and give me the Order of Simon Bolivar, in the first
degree.'' He smiles triumphantly. ``I didn't fall for it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `80 percent joy'
</P>
<P>
   Bromsen, a compact man, says he feels ``80 percent joy'' at his
decision to relinquish his collection to Brown. ``It's 80 percent
because I know it is safe, it has purpose, and since I didn't need
the money, I didn't have to sell it,'' he says. ``I wanted to keep
it together.''
</P>
<P>
   But then there is the other 20 percent, the part that is
``sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been ``de-Bolivarized,'' Bromsen says glumly, who is
meticulously dressed one recent afternoon in a dark suit and
golden-yellow tie with a matching silk pocket handkerchief. He
gestures at the walls of his elegant living room. (Decorated, he
indicates, with authentic hand-embroidered 18th-century curtains
that once hung at the estate of a French nobleman.) The apartment
is one of three suites Bromsen occupies in downtown Boston to house
his prodigious antiquarian collection and book inventory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sadness,'' he says, ``is when I look on my walls, I have
no more Bolivar.'' No more prized oil portrait of Bolivar painted
``anonymously in Lima in 1822 or early 1823,'' the ever-precise
Bromsen points out. No more Bolivar miniatures, including one
painted on ivory in Haiti in 1816 by renowned native artist
Jacques-Marie Legros. No more pencil drawing by Jose Maria Espinosa
made in Bogota in 1830.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the paintings were expeditiously replaced by others
in his collection, including his Gilbert Stuart portrait of
Commodore Oliver Hazard Perry and his painting of St. Cecilia by
Rembrandt Peale.
</P>
<P>
   However, Bolivar will remain forever in his heart, if not his
apartment and vault. What, a visitor inquires, drew him to Simon
Bolivar in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   Bromsen seems literally taken aback by the question. He winces
in his chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you got someone better to collect?' he wants to know. ``I
wanted a titanic, challenging subject and the greatest figure of
Latin America was Bolivar.''
</P>
<P>
   He enumerates his hero's numerous attributes. He was a man of
ideas as well as action. He believed in legal equality for
everyone, despite being a man of great wealth, and he freed his own
slaves in 1821. He dreamed of the freedom of America from Spanish
control, and of social and economic reform. He was a brave and
daring military leader. He was the Spanish counterpart to George
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Never one to resist a digression into detail, the inveterate
bibliographer suddenly switches gears. ``He was a little man, only
about 5 feet 4 1/2 inches tall,'' Bromsen points out cheerfully.
``He was the size of President Madison, who was the shortest of our
American presidents. Lincoln, of course, was the tallest.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to his original subject, he adds: ``It might have been
presumptuous of me (to have collected Bolivar), but I'm glad I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Work as progeny
</P>
<P>
   Bromsen, a 1945 Harvard graduate, has had many other passions in
life besides Bolivar. As it turned out, marriage and family life
were not among them. He has always been single. ``It was one of the
reasons I was able to do all the things I have done,'' he says.
``My collection and work were my children.''
</P>
<P>
   His work has been multifaceted. There is Bromsen the book dealer
and manuscripts expert, specializing in Latin American materials,
whose clients have included the family of William Randolph Hearst.
Among his coups were acquiring a copy of Walt Whitman's ``Leaves of
Grass'' in 1970 for what was then the highest price ever paid at
auction for a printed volume of American literature ($9,000); and
the discovery _ amid the personal letters of the Hearst family _ of
a copy of a 1787 invitation to the 13 governors of the United
States to a meeting that led to the drafting of the US
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   There is Bromsen the bibliographer, who has such an
extraordinary memory for detail he is like a walking catalog card.
``When I was 8, I could say all the presidents of the United States
and can still do it within one minute,'' he boasts, and proceeds to
demonstrate. He still works seven days a week on the ``exceedingly
difficult and unpleasant task'' of cataloguing his voluminous
acquisitions of Latin American books, checking them against
numerous references to establish their historical authenticity. He
once spent eight days to catalog one book.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a workaholic,'' says his Venezuelan personal assistant
of 20 years, Fredy Quevas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a kind of genius, and I don't like to use that word too
loosely,'' says Norman Fiering, director and librarian of the John
Carter Brown Library. ``He has such a well-stocked mind.''
</P>
<P>
   He is also a man of no small vanity. ``I have the greatest
collection of Cuban books in private hands, you know'' is a typical
Bromsen declaration. Or, describing his reputation at major auction
houses: ``I was the Prince Charming of the Latin American room.
When I entered the room, everyone interested in Latin America would
get up and leave.''
</P>
<P>
   But his achievements have made him a prosperous man, and a
generous one. He has endowed two funds at the Boston Public
Library, one for the acquisition in Latin American materials and
the other for an annual lectureship in humanistic bibliography.
This year's lecture took place last Saturday night, featuring
historian Arthur M. Schlesinger Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Bolivar has been safely housed in a room of his own,
Bromsen can turn his full attention to the work of bibliography.
Alas, at 81, his memory, while still ``remarkable,'' is ``maybe 85
percent of what it used to be,'' he says. It worries him sometimes
because in his field, ``you have to retain things or you sink and
drown.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he can't afford the luxury of slowing down.
``I have such a tremendously valuable inventory that, if I lived
till 200, I could never sell it all,'' says Bromsen. ``There is so
much to do, I dare not die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
