<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODIES, SMALL AND LARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How's this for irony? You have to slog through 275 pages, many
of them featuring very-thin, curve-free women with too little body
fat, to get to Glamour's three-page examination of Hollywood and
society's unhealthy obsession with very-thin, curve-free women with
too little body fat.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Hollywood Starve Wars,'' writer Megan McCafferty tells us
what we already know _ namely, that actresses like Calista
Flockhart, Lara Flynn Boyle, and Jane Leeves are so thin, you
almost want to launch a food drive on their behalf. With some
actresses now striving to wear a size 0, in certain circles a
once-enviable size 4 is now considered huge. But McCafferty
contends the obsession to be thin can be contagious _ how else to
explain Flockhart's incredibly shrinking ``Ally McBeal'' co-stars
Courtney Thorne-Smith and Portia de Rossi? (Thorne-Smith has since
left the show.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about peer pressure,'' says Bernie Brillstein, one of
Hollywood's most prominent managers. ``If an actress is thinner
than the rest of the cast and successful, the women are going to
feel compelled to diet down to her size, thinking, `If it works for
her, why not?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The same thing, McCafferty finds, is happening among sorority
sisters, sports teams, even in the armed services, where body image
is important and pressure to conform is high. ``A member may know
the group's behaviors are unhealthy, but not want to be an outcast,
and over time, she starts starving and purging, too,'' says Arizona
State University nutrition professor Melinda Manore. About 10
percent of anorexics die from medical complications or suicide _
how long before some Hollywood starlet with visions of size 0 in
her eyes starves herself to death?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of all the hip-hop tragedies _ the AIDS death of Eazy-E, the
still-unsolved shootings of Tupac and Biggie _ the passing of
Christopher ``Big Punisher'' Rios in February may be the saddest of
all. At 28 he died of a heart attack blamed on years of extreme
obesity.
</P>
<P>
   But how did this happen, and did those around him, including his
wife and friends, fail to get him the help he so desperately
needed? That's the question posed by Riggs Morales and Kim Osorio
in The Source as they examine how the platinum-selling rapper,
despite the concerns of others, essentially ate himself to death.
</P>
<P>
   His wife of 10 years, Liza, says her husband associated every
emotion with food. He'd eat as salve for an argument, he'd eat to
celebrate, he'd eat when he was bored. His unusually slow
metabolism, coupled with his aversion to physical activity,
contributed to a tripling of his weight in six years.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly didn't help that success allowed him to surround
himself with sycophants who catered to his whims and pampered him;
on tour, they would even get wheelchairs for him so he wouldn't
have to walk. Pun was aware of his weight problems, and last summer
was convinced by his friend and fellow rapper Fat Joe to join Duke
University's acclaimed weight clinic. He lost 80 pounds, but once
he returned home, he fell into old habits, gaining twice as much
weight as he'd lost. Joe recalls Pun telling him to ``mind my
business. Whenever I want to I could lose this weight.''
Tragically, he never did. At the time of his death, Big Pun weighed
698 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Message to Indiana University president Myles Brand: IU
basketball coach Bobby Knight should have been fired. Sacked.
Terminated. Kicked to the curb. Forget the three national
championships.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine years of obnoxious, threatening, and boorish
behavior toward players, assistants, and generally any human being
in his path should have been more than enough reason for IU to give
Knight the bum's rush. But last week, Knight convinced IU officials
that he can change, and university officials, after professing a
``zero tolerance'' edict for any future stupidity, allowed Knight
to keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   In Sports Illustrated, Alexander Wolff takes hard-edged look at
Knight, and especially the university that flinched when they
should have flexed. Says IU psychology professor David Pisoni of
Knight's reprieve, ``It's an embarrassment to the state and the
university. This demonstrates the priorities of the university.
Athletics come before moral and ethical conduct. The revenue stream
is more important than credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Even a videotape of Knight choking a player wasn't enough to get
him fired. ``To be sure, the administration found itself in a
pickle,'' Wolff writes. ``How much was Knight really at fault when
the school had been his enabler, deep in a denial of its own? The
chain of command had long ago gone kerblooey.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the hoop-crazy Hoosier state where Knight is king, that
doesn't seem to matter. As incoming IU freshman Jared Jeffries
says, ``If we win a lot of games, all this will die down. People
love winners.'' Even, apparently, when they're losers like Knight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
