u f BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-24 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING GOOD EMPLOYEES   IS A CHALLENGE THESE DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Job counselors agree: the key to retaining top employees in a
tight labor market is to treat them well.
</P>
<P>
   Given a national unemployment rate of just 4 percent, the lowest
in three decades, you may think retention of staff is an uphill
battle. You may also think it's a battle you are likely to lose.
Not so, says career counselor Barbara Moses, author of ``The Good
News About Careers: How You'll Be Working in the Next Decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Most employers in the new economy want workers who are
autonomous, can take initiative, and are independent
problem-solvers, says Moses. The problem, however, is once they've
attracted workers with these qualities, many have trouble holding
onto them, because employees with such traits are by nature
initative takers _ people less likely to stick around when their
needs are not being met.
</P>
<P>
   Today many workers, regardless of their ages, tend to have
similar needs:
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about employability: Will this job give me the skills I
need to insure a decent living in the future?
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about commitment: Does this company offer the chance to
commit to my work, team members, or profession rather than blind
loyalty to The Corporation?
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about work-life balance: Will I be able to manage this
job and still have time for my family, friends, or personal
interests?
</P>
<P>
   Job counselors say a tight labor market coupled with
dissatisfaction with compensation and any one of those areas of
concern have helped fuel the current job-hopping craze.
</P>
<P>
   The US Labor Department reports that job retention among
employees ages 25 to 34 has steadily declined, dropping from 3.0
years in 1983 to 2.7 years in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Younger workers, who watched their downsized parents struggle to
get along, are not waiting around for the axe to fall. Those with
cutting-edge skills are looking for workplaces that offer freedom,
flexibility, and the opportunity to expand. And, as the market
tightens, older workers who have acquired sought-after skills are
finding they, too, can successfully market themselves.
</P>
<P>
   John Challenger, president of Challenger, Gray &AMP; Christmas, an
outplacement firm in Chicago, says workers have developed an
independent, free-agent mentality in the wake of layoffs. As a
result, they see their skills as permanently up for auction.
</P>
<P>
   Moses, in an interview while in town last week, agreed. ``Right
now, a person might have a full-time job, but to survive they must
also have the mindset of a temp,'' she said. ``They now know that
they must always have money in the bank, they must always be
prepared for the next new challenge. They cannot afford to rest on
their laurels.''
</P>
<P>
   In a push to retain and attract employees, some companies are
offering cars, money, travel, and other expensive perks. But that
might not be enough. A recent study by Indianapolis-based Walker
Information, a research firm and think tank, found employers spend
too little time showing workers that they matter. Lack of
communication and a lack of interest in new ideas and contributions
were seen as key reasons for switching employers.
</P>
<P>
   Moses believes expensive gifts are probably a waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the death of corporatism, employers should focus on
other, more successful ways to attract and retain good people,''
she said, adding that many perks can be tailored to fit the
individual needs of employees and are more likely to have broad
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Some examples:
</P>
<P>
   Skill-building opportunities: ``Skills can be acquired in a
number of different ways, even in apparently dead-end jobs,''
writes Moses. ``Managers can encourage the process by matching
workers with people they can learn from, giving workers
opportunities to participate in cross-departmental task forces,
setting up opportunities for them to shadow other workers in other
jobs, and promoting cross-functional training.''
</P>
<P>
   Tying compensation to learning opportunities: ``One life
insurance company, which takes its learning organization credo
seriously, gives staff a percentage of their salary to use for
developmental purposes such as courses, travel to conferences, or
books,'' says Moses. An example: A major hotel chain offers a small
sum of money as a reward for top performance. Those chosen to
receive the perk can apply it to courses, spa services at the
hotel, skiing or golf lessons _ any endeavor they choose that
allows them to learn something new, regardless of whether that new
skill can be directly applied to the job.
</P>
<P>
   Offering sabbaticals: Everyone needs to recharge himself,
especially in the current go-go economy. Even two months away can
be beneficial, says Moses. ``Sabbaticals shouldn't be tied to
levels of hierarchy in an organization or length of service,'' she
says. ``They should be used to recognize that in the new work
landscape people will have an ongoing need to retool and recharge.
This means that weary baby-boomers grappling with mid-life crises
and 20-somethings and 30-somethings seeking time off to travel or
to test themselves in new ways are equally likely to welcome a
sojourn from their everyday lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Promoting and building on personal relationships: Moses believes
individuals are more concerned about the personal relationships
they build on the job and within their professions than
profit-and-loss statements and year-end results. ``It is
extraordinary how often it is the small and often banal gestures
that are the most meaningful,'' she says in her book. ``People will
often say things like, `I'm not really happy, but I'm not yet
prepared to jump ship because my boss was really good to me when my
mother was sick.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Employers can promote personal relationships by offering breaks
during work or after when they can mix, talk, and socialize.
Companies that sponsor bowling, basketball, or softball teams
understand the importance of community. At the same time, social
events are even more effective in creating workplace bonds when
rapport develops naturally among colleagues during the course of a
regular work-week.
</P>
<P>
   Offering flexible benefits: More and more companies are
beginning to understand that new workers are less likely to
sacrifice their personal lives for the job. They are also realizing
the importance of flexible benefits and flexible scheduling, and
they are providing workers with a menu of benefits from which they
can choose.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are working 80 hours per week and the important
relationships in your life are suffering, then you are paying a
huge price for work,'' Moses noted in an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are now evaluating the effort-reward equation
differently,'' she said. ``They are now asking themselves, `If I
work that hard, what do I sacrifice?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Diane E. Lewis can be reached by e-mail at work(at)globe.com, or
at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
