<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4485 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-FRY'S-NERDVANA-BOS &LR;      05-24 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRY'S-NERDVANA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SATURDAY NIGHT FEVER, SILICON VALLEY STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAL0 ALTO, Calif. _ It's Saturday night at geek central. You can
get dizzy checking out the beige cables and motherboards at Fry's
Electronic. And you can almost smell the testosterone of the
techies who trek here for supplies to build their computers from
scratch. These guys don't do Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Once a grocery store chain, Fry's has evolved into an
institution both loved and loathed in Silicon Valley. Its massive
stores are Nerdvana, stocked to the rafters with peripherals,
parts, and gadgets. But its reputation for poor service is also
legendary. Spurned customers have spawned numerous anti-Fry's Web
sites, complete with chat rooms and bulletin boards.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the ability of Fry's to draw a full crowd on a Saturday
evening is testament to its strange hold over the Valley's
hard-core techies who, for better or worse, tend to be male.
</P>
<P>
   Where else can a geek wander down aisle after aisle of
semiconductors, urgent memory chips, line transformers, and CPU
coolers? There are parts so obscure they're identified only by
letters and numbers, such as the ``SCR-200 nVRM, 4.0A.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fry's is a cultural icon,'' said Peter Monta, a graduate of
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology who is an engineer at
Terayon Communications Systems in Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Monta stopped by on a recent Saturday to look at the latest
motherboards and pick up a couple of toner cartridges. He, like
many elite engineers, eschews the Microsoft Windows operating
system in favor of Linux when he builds his computers from parts.
``Fewer compatibility problems,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Monta explains that the service at Fry's can be ``actively
hostile.'' Its employees often aren't versed in techno-speak. ``You
have to know what you want before you come here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It is advice often heard about Fry's which, since its start in
Sunnyvale in 1985 has grown to 17 stores in Arizona, California,
Oregon, and Texas. It is rumored to be one of the most successful
electronics retailers in the country, with estimated annual sales
of over $1.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But no one knows for sure, because Fry's remains a closely held,
family owned and run company that steadfastly refuses to reveal
much information. Analysts have been escorted out of its stores,
and film is confiscated whenever managers discover that pictures of
its stores are being taken. Company officials declined to be
interviewed for this story.
</P>
<P>
   Its chief executive, John Fry, a former math major and football
star at Santa Clara University, is the son of a successful grocer,
Charles Fry, who gave each of his three children $1 million after
selling his food stores for about $14 million in 1972. Led by John,
the Fry brothers pooled their money and founded the electronics
store.
</P>
<P>
   Their roots in the grocery business are apparent in their
merchandising and retail philosophy. Their stores stock
hypercaffeinated soft drinks, toiletries, magazines, and junk food
_ ideal fare for techies heading off to all-night programming
sessions. Loss leaders are heavily advertised in local newspapers,
selection is prodigious, and prices generally low.
</P>
<P>
   Each store is bizarrely decorated along fantasy themes. The
Fry's in Campbell, Calif., for instance, is modeled after ancient
Egypt and decorated with a 20-foot sphinx and tomb replicas. Others
feature ``Alice in Wonderland'' themes, a UFO crash site, and
ancient Rome.
</P>
<P>
   The Palo Alto store is ``Wild Bill's Wild, Wild West.'' Here, an
enormous buffalo head eyes customers from behind a phalanx of 45
cashiers at the checkout stand.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the whimsy, however, is a dead-serious attitude toward
theft. Each store is monitored by dozens of cameras, and bags are
checked and receipts examined upon exit. Returns require waiting in
two separate, often lengthy lines so that identification is checked
twice. Employees are searched before they leave their shifts.
</P>
<P>
   A San Franciscan who goes by the screen name of Yoda replied to
a bulletin board inquiry about Fry's shoppers. He wrote that he has
``an intense love-hate relationship with the place . . . Lines can
be staggering, returns are painful. And yet, I think Fry's is ideal
for techies. They offer a mountain of goods on the cheap . . .
Techies don't want the cute pastel-colored Friendly Computer. They
want the screaming home-built hot rod bristling with gadgets and
tweaked to their specific tastes. And Fry's hits that demographic
dead-center.''
</P>
<P>
   In Silicon Valley, that demographic is largely male, many of
them single. According to the most recent Census figures, there
were 237,800 men who had never been married in Santa Clara County,
as opposed to 166,206 unwed women. In engineering schools across
the country, where Silicon Valley draws much of its talent, it is
not unusual for men to outnumber women by three to one.
</P>
<P>
   At the Fry's store in Palo Alto one Saturday evening, there were
19 men at the checkout line but only three women. This is something
the owners of Fry's have undoubtedly picked up on. Copies of
Playboy magazine sit alongside titles such as Low Rider, MacAddict,
and the C/C++ Users Journal. There are razors and ties decorated
with pictures of tiny cell phones and pagers.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Torres, a bank marketing officer in San Jose and
self-described ``Fry's junkie,'' explained the store's allure for
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've ever watched the show `Home Improvement' that
depicts the fascination men have with power tools and such, it is,
to me, much the same kind of thing at Fry's,'' Torres said. ``You
can look at all these parts and gizmos and think `More Power!' ''
</P>
<P>
   But as with most comments about Fry's, the topic of Fry's
treatment of its customers inevitably comes up. ``Fry's isn't
perfect,'' Torres said. ``The service can best be described as
poor.''
</P>
<P>
   Fry's is aware of the criticism. ``We certainly understand that
some people are not as satisfied as we would like them to be,''
said Manuel Valerio, its community relations manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is partly the nature of retail. Anytime you deal with
customers, there will always be some individuals that will not be
easy to satisfy. We will go out of our way to try without, of
course, putting Fry's at a competitive disadvantage in terms of
financial losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Valerio said Fry's this year joined the Better Business Bureau
to ``clear up any backlog of concerns our customers may have
expressed to the Better Business Bureau in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the customers come in droves. Tour buses often unload at
a Fry's store where the uninitiated gawk at the merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Evgeny Devyatyh, a 23-year-old software engineer, brought to the
Palo Alto Fry's two childhood friends visiting from his hometown in
Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second night in a row Devyatyh had found himself in a
Fry's store. This time, he was buying the parts to put together his
own computer. He swung by the software aisles, which carried
thousands of titles and were populated by over a dozen men and two
women, one of whom was a store clerk. Devyatyh picked up a copy of
Linux, then headed off to the cash register, where he threw in a
bag of candy and a soda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this place,'' he said with an approving nod.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
