<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4486 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-LESLIE-PROFILE-BOS &LR;      05-24 1700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LESLIE-PROFILE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LISA LESLIE HAS FOUND BASKETS FULL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   She was going to be famous. Amid the bleakness and blight of
poverty-ravaged Compton, Calif., this was her refuge.
</P>
<P>
   She was going to be a fashion model. And a television news
correspondent. These ambitions sustained her while her mother, a
truck driver, was on the road and the little girl was left in the
care of a live-in housekeeper who, she would recall, treated her
and her sister unkindly. To transport herself from the grim present
into the boundless future, to prepare for that day when she would
emerge from a dreary childhood into full-fledged celebrity, she
would practice her autograph. She would write over and over until
she had the signature just right, each capital ``L'' flowing into
the rest of the word, each small ``e'' and ``s'' a study in
symmetry, so that the name rolled off the paper as she imagined it
would roll off the tongues of those who would trumpet her
achievements:
</P>
<P>
   ``Lisa Leslie.''
</P>
<P>
   She knew this was inevitable, just as certainly as she knew one
other thing.
</P>
<P>
   Her beacon of escape would not involve basketball.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She has become a prominent fashion model, a runway and photo
fixture. The high-powered Wilhemina agency signed her in 1996, and
since then, she has been featured in a Herb Ritts portfolio for
Vogue, a Newsweek spread, an Annie Leibovitz shoot, and shows for
Anne Klein, Armani, and Tommy Hilfiger, among other glossy
appearances. She shares the cover of the latest issue of Sports
Illustrated For Women with her good buddy Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   She has become a TV news correspondent, though her reporting for
``NBA Inside Stuff'' would be considered far more TV than news.
Beyond that, she has established a niche as a guest star on sitcoms
such as ``Sister, Sister,'' ``Hang Time,'' and ``Moesha.''
</P>
<P>
   The dream has followed her schoolgirl blueprint, with one
exception. Basketball is at its core, the linchpin of the entire
publicity machine. Her striking 6-foot-5-inch beauty and sparkling
glibness around microphones and cameras would not be nearly as much
in demand were it not for the fact that, six weeks shy of her 28th
birthday, Lisa Leslie is one of the greatest players ever to square
up to the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche of attention
</P>
<P>
   She has been a national name since scoring more than 100 points
in one half of a high school game. She dominated women's college
basketball at the University of Southern California, a career
framed with NCAA honors as Freshman of the Year in 1991 and Player
of the Year in 1994. She became a cult figure in Italy for one
season in 1994-95, hailed as ``Grande Lisa'' (``Big Lisa'') by
adoring hordes while playing for Alcamo in Sicily. And her fame
blossomed into worldwide proportions in 1996, when she led the
United States to the Olympic gold medal in Atlanta as the fulcrum
of the American attack, owner of Olympic records for points in a
game (35 against Japan) and tournament (156, 19.5 per game).
</P>
<P>
   That triggered the avalanche of individual attention from
outside sources and, on a more cosmic level, helped spawn the
Women's National Basketball Association, an adjunct of the NBA that
has become a viable enterprise in its own right as it taps off its
fourth season Monday. Leslie, a three-time All-Star, will be the
guiding force of the Los Angeles Sparks during the 32-game schedule
and playoffs, which will funnel directly into the Olympics at
Sydney, where she again will be an American mainstay in the title
defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's probably the most versatile player in the world,'' said
Leslie's Olympic coach, Nell Fortner, during the recent US Olympic
Committee Media Summit in Houston. ``She's a 6-5, any-position
player. She presents the most problems for anyone we play. Also,
her experience'' is a major asset.
</P>
<P>
   Such experience was something Leslie never envisioned while
growing up in Compton, ``which most people know is a pretty bad
neighborhood,'' she said. ``But it's only what you make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Christine Leslie-Espinoza, made sure Lisa didn't
make it a training ground for drugs and despair, Compton's calling
cards. She set strict limits, and the housekeeper enforced them
while Christine was behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were (bad) things going on,'' said Lisa. To avoid them,
``you had to be in the house before the street lights came on.''
</P>
<P>
   Until curfew, she would play kickball or jump rope ``like a
normal kid,'' but physical endeavors were mere pastimes, not
passionate pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really wasn't into sports as a kid,'' said Leslie. ``I never
had any aspirations to be in sports, just loving the sport. That's
not my background.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, her focus was greatly influenced by her aunt Judy, who
lived in nearby Carson and took in the Leslies when Lisa was 13.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Simpson was ``a beautiful lady,'' said Lisa, ``and she was
really into fashion. I think that's where I got a lot of my fashion
sense from, like it's OK to be aware of your body and your
appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   But along the way, Leslie had discovered that her body could do
wondrous things on a basketball court. The revelation occurred by
accident.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taking to the game
</P>
<P>
   By seventh grade, Leslie had sprouted to 6-1 and was looking for
social outlets. An older girl, Sharon Hargrove, suggested an
unlikely one: basketball. Sharon was extremely popular. She played
basketball. She invited Leslie to try it. Leslie figured, well, if
it worked for this girl . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, in junior high, you just get there in the seventh
grade and you don't know anyone,'' Leslie said. ``And everybody
knew her.''
</P>
<P>
   So Leslie went out for the team, with meager ambitions: ``I just
told the coaches, `I'm going to fall down now. Keep playing.' ''
</P>
<P>
   She didn't fall down. She became consumed by the game: ``I feel
basketball was my destiny.'' And she overcame a lonely experience
when she was introduced to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first day,'' she said, ``I'm actually lefthanded, and the
coach said, `All the righthand kids get on one side and all the
lefthand get on the other.' And I was the only one over there by
myself. And I said, `When I come back tomorrow, I'm going to be
righthanded.' So I actually play righthand now.''
</P>
<P>
   She soon found that she also played at a level above her peers.
This development dismayed Aunt Judy to an extent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd get my hair done and I'd go play,'' said Leslie. ``My hair
would be all over my head, and she's like, `I just got your hair
done.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But she wasn't forsaking her aunt's fashion tenets, merely
incorporating them into her new parlay for success: glamour and
grit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that kind of balance of who I am today,'' said Leslie.
``Just trying to take care of yourself, but you can still go out
and play sports. That's OK. I'm probably a little more feminine
than most basketball players you've ever seen, but that's just my
background. It helps, but it can hurt you, because people think I
don't live up to my potential because I'm trying to be cute or that
I'm too feminine or fragile or whatever. But I get the job done and
I work hard on defense and offense, and I'm not worried about my
nails or my hair. But I'm also a woman first, and I feel like when
I come off the court, there's no reason I can't put on a skirt and
be a lady.''
</P>
<P>
   But make no mistake. Leslie is a terror on the court, as
epitomized by her triple-digit epic for Morningside High in
Inglewood, Calif., where the family moved when Leslie was 14. It
was a team tradition to give a senior a showcase game, in which she
would be constantly fed the ball. Leslie was chosen for the honor
against South Torrance High, but she approached it with
apprehension: ``I'm thinking, `OK, I could stink up the gym here.'
''
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, she lit it up for 101 points in 16 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a few layups and made some jump shots and made some
turnaround jumpers,'' she said. ``And then I started getting hot
and just making everything, and they were fouling me and I made
about 35 free throws.''
</P>
<P>
   By halftime, Inglewood led, 102-24. There was no second half
because South Torrance was down to four players after its
foul-plagued first two quarters. But that game served as Leslie's
transcontinental springboard, and she has been soaring ever since.
</P>
<P>
   The game has become not only her foundation for personal gain
but a forum for community outreach. Back in Inglewood, Leslie has
translated her endorsement deal with Nike into funding for various
youth programs. She also is a regular presence in her old
neighborhood, making herself accessible to the kids, delivering a
message that transcends the standard lip service because she has
lived their experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just talking about it when the camera's on,'' she
said. ``It's actually going there and saying, `Hey, I've sat in
these same seats. I've been there.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And now she's here. At the top.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not a finished product
</P>
<P>
   There is still work to be done. Leslie is a tireless crusader
for the game she stumbled into by happenstance. She believes it is
imperative for the US women to prevail in Sydney to maintain the
momentum established in Atlanta. The WNBA is on the upswing, but
the average salary is $55,000, dwarfed by the six-figure European
contracts, and Leslie wants to see the US league attract more men
as fans, escape the nether reaches of the sports section, mushroom
into a prime-time TV staple.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there have been giant strides of credibility. Many NBA
players are fans of the WNBA. Leslie recalls an encounter with
Minnesota Timberwolves All-Star Kevin Garnett. Seeing him at a
Sparks game, she approached him with what she considered necessary
deference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Mr. Garnett,'' she said. ``How you doing?''
</P>
<P>
   Garnett laughed as he admonished her, ``Don't call me that. I
know who you are.''
</P>
<P>
   The childhood fantasies have been fulfilled thanks to the plot
line that wasn't in the grandiose script. Lisa Leslie is famous.
Because of basketball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
