<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BOARD APPROVES NEW SUPERINTENDENT AMID CRITICISM FROM
TEACHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAY DELGADO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The San Francisco school board approved a
four-year contract for new superintendent Arlene Ackerman that will
pay her $197,000 a year to head California's fifth largest
district, $12,000 more than her predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement of the terms of Ackerman's unsigned contract at
Tuesday night's school board meeting drew an immediate chorus of
loud boos among teachers and parents in the audience. ``Shame on
you'' they chanted before the board voted 6-0 to approve the
contract. Board member Dan Kelly abstained because he wanted more
time to see the contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board keeps telling us that they don't have the money to
pay us, but they found it for (Ackerman),'' said Jennifer Bloom, a
first-grade teacher who wore a hat to the meeting that read ``Pay
me to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're throwing money out to get her and we're begging to
have a living wage,'' Bloom added.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the contract, Ackerman's salary goes into
effect on Aug. 1 and includes vacation time, sick leave, health
benefits, life insurance and moving expenses from Washington, D.C.,
where she has headed that city's troubled school district for two
years. A clause in the contract also allows Ackerman an unspecified
amount of leave time to complete a doctorate degree at Harvard
University, said Deputy City Attorney Mark Barmore.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman was hired last week to run the 64,000 student district,
ending a nationwide search.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials and school board members said Ackerman's salary
is competitive with other superintendents at major city school
districts. Superintendent Bill Rojas, Ackerman's predecessor in the
San Francisco post, left the district two years ago to head Dallas'
school district for an estimated salary of $275,000 a year. His
last salary in San Francisco was $185,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Several school teachers who attended the meeting said they were
aware of the pressure board members were under to hire a
superintendent, but they now need to approach teacher raises with
the same sense of urgency or expect that teachers will leave the
district to make more money elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I have to do is add 20 minutes to my commute and I can
make $12,000 more a year,'' said Stacy Stephens, a social studies
teacher at Lincoln High School.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
