<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISK WOULD BE WORTH IT FOR IRA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Problem: risk and Vanguard Index 500
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Age: daughter, 43
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q &LR; . I recently convinced my daughter to start an IRA in the
Vanguard Index 500 fund. I know this is a fairly high-risk fund,
but in view of the fact she has 22 years before retirement, she has
to take some risk. We recently sold a house that we jointly owned,
and she will make a fair profit. I want her to put this in one of
Vanguard's money market funds and then each year transfer money
into the IRA account. Does this make sense?
</P>
<P>
   J.R., Attleboro, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A &LR; . The investment in Vanguard Index 500 is a solid one, but I
would not characterize it as high-risk. The fund simply holds the
500 stocks of the Standard and Poor's index, proportionally to
their market weight in the index. Basically, an investment in Index
500 is a bet on the fortunes of America's dominant public companies
_ a solid holding, especially for a long-term investor such as your
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   You do not say how much she will net from the house sale. If
it's sizable _ say, more than $10,000 _ I would suggest that far
from being too risky, the plan you outline is too cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Let's suppose your daughter nets $26,652. If it were invested in
Vanguard's Prime Money Market fund and $166.66 a month were
withdrawn and put into her IRA, she would have enough money to fund
the IRA payments for 264 months, or 22 years, provided the yield on
the fund averaged 5 percent. Given that she already has $2,000 in
Vanguard Index 500, if that fund averaged 10 percent returns during
those 22 years, her accumulation at age 65 would be $176,697.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's suppose she had the same $26,625, plus the $2,000
already in her IRA, and she simply bit the bullet and put all of it
into a taxable holding in Index 500, each month transferring
$166.66 from the taxable account into her IRA. If Index 500
produced the same 10 percent average annual returns, her
accumulation at age 65 would be $256,195.
</P>
<P>
   Is what I am suggesting riskier? No question about it. Moreover,
you can argue, the large-cap stocks that have driven Vanguard Index
500 to its current 24.1 percent five-year average annual returns
are pretty expensive right now, and in the opinion of many market
watchers they are due to take a breather. I agree with that
thinking, but I also think that 22 years is simply too long for a
dollar-cost averaging program when all of the funds are available
at the outset. If you take the long view, a single investment now,
or at the most cautious, a dollar-cost averaging program that would
get all of the money invested over four or five years, is a better
bet.
</P>
<P>
   Another option: a variable annuity invested in Vanguard Index
500. Just as an IRA does, a variable annuity serves to defer the
income tax obligation on earnings until they are withdrawn. (The
initial investment, being after-tax money, is not taxed upon
withdrawal.) There is an element of insurance in variable annuity
contracts, and the cost of the insurance tends to reduce the
returns by about 0.5 percent, compared to the similarly invested
mutual fund, but even if returns averaged only 9.5 percent, the
22-year accumulation would be $213,652, and she would have a
further $17,883 in the IRA that you persuaded her to open,
presuming 10 percent average growth. Of course, one advantage of
the annuity plan is she would still be eligible to contribute up to
$2,000 of her annual earnings to the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Problem: How much of my savings can I spend?
</P>
<P>
   Age: 81
</P>
<P>
   Social Security: $860 monthly
</P>
<P>
   Savings:
</P>
<P>
   $15,418 Washington Mutual fund
</P>
<P>
   $12,400 Washington Mutual IRA
</P>
<P>
   $12,070 Capital Income Builders
</P>
<P>
   $12,400 Capital Income Builders (IRA)
</P>
<P>
   $4,007 Growth Fund of America (IRA)
</P>
<P>
   $2,598 New Perspective fund (IRA)
</P>
<P>
   $692 bank IRA; $18,436 CD; $3,000 checking account
</P>
<P>
   Other: $10,000 personal loan to daughter
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q &LR; . My daughter fears I am not invested in the best funds for
my situation. Am I? I would like to move to a retirement home near
where my daughter lives. How much can I safely spend from my
investments without running out? Obviously it matters how long I
live, so use ages 90 and 95.
</P>
<P>
   L.W., Brea, Calif. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A &LR; . Excluding both the personal loan and your checking account
balance, you could withdraw $1,107 a month from your $86,755
portfolio to exhaust the funds at age 90; if you took the more
conservative course, withdrawals of $835 a month would mean the
pool would last until age 95.
</P>
<P>
   I used a projected portfolio return of 7.5 percent annually. I
did this because I agree with your daughter _ you are much too
reliant on the stock market for your comfort, especially since you
are relying on these funds for a good piece of your income. I tally
67.2 percent of your total portfolio is in stocks, a calculation in
which I credited 62 percent of the positions in Capital Income
Builders as stock holdings. My suggestion would be to confine the
stock position to the two taxable accounts, in Capital Income
Builders and Washington mutual. This would have the effect of
cutting your reliance on the stock market to a little more than 26
percent.
</P>
<P>
   You could look among the many fixed-income funds within the
American fund family, but at this point _ and particularly for a
person such as yourself who cannot afford a great deal of risk _
the high CD rates available now look mighty attractive. Entering
this week, the nation's best rate on a five-year CD was a flat 8
percent, available at Capital One FSB in Falls Church, Va.
(800-564-7426.) You can find a list of the highest rates on the
Data Bank page of the Sunday New York Times. But shop around,
because the highest rate and the national average differ widely.
(The national average was 6.06 this week.)
</P>
<P>
   My suggestion: Move all of your IRA money to such a CD, a
transaction which would cause you no short-term tax problems
(although with the higher yield on the CD than from your fund
holdings, your taxable income would increase).
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I'd suggest that you use the more conservative
projection that you will live to age 95. As for the income you
expect from the personal loan you made, I suggest you just salt it
away as emergency funds _ and I suggest you salt it away in a
similar CD, but this time in a taxable account. The balance would
eventually amount to a tidy sum upon which you could rely in the
event _ horrors! _ that you blow out all of the candles on your
96th birthday cake.
</P>
<P>
   Problem: Choosing an annuity for great grandchildren, ages 4, 6,
8, 10
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q &LR; . I want to invest $5,000 each for my four
great-grandchildren. What would be the best way? My bank wants me
to buy a variable annuity for each one. If I do this, should I
specify large-cap or small-cap?
</P>
<P>
   A.J., Phoenix &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A &LR; . Without knowing specifics, I would suggest a large-cap
investment. Since you are interested in annuities, I presume you
intend this money to represent a head start on retirement planning
for each of the great-grandchildren. These are handsome gifts. If
the oldest child's investment returns average annual gains of 10
percent, his or her accumulation would be $1,196,682 at age 65;
since the younger kids have more time, their accumulations would be
greater.
</P>
<P>
   Over the very long haul, small-caps have provided better
returns. But it is also more difficult to manage a small-cap fund,
and that means many opportunities for disaster. Large-caps,
presumably, have weathered many storms and built dominant
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Second, over half a century, the typical mutual fund will go
through many managers, so even if you choose a well-managed
small-cap fund,there's no guarantee things will remain that way.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box
2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
