<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4514 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-LA-SCHOOL-SUPERINTEND     05-24 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-SCHOOL-SUPERINTENDENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FORMER HOUSING SECRETARY DOWNPLAYS INTEREST IN L.A. SCHOOLS
POST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUDOLPH BUSH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Housing Secretary Henry Cisneros is on the short list of
candidates to head the huge and beleaguered Los Angeles Unified
School District.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, whose last foray into public life ended when he
resigned as secretary of Housing and Urban Development in 1996,
said he is not interested in the superintendent's position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've indicated that I'm not a candidate, and I took my name
out of circulation Sunday,'' Cisneros said. He added, however,
``that's my present position,'' and he plans to consider the idea
more thoroughly.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles district, one of the largest in the country with
more than 700,000 students, has been plagued by management
troubles, low test scores and a monumental scandal over what was to
have been the country's most expensive high school, the Belmont
Learning Center.
</P>
<P>
   The $200 million Belmont project was abandoned, half-finished,
because it was built on an old, toxic oil field.
</P>
<P>
   Being considered with Cisneros are former Colorado Gov. Roy
Romer; Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan; Liam McGee, president of
Bank of America in Southern California; Houston school
Superintendent Rod Paige; and Adam Urbanski, the head of the
Federation of Teachers in Rochester, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, who lives in Southern California, is the president and
chief operating officer of Univision, a Spanish-language television
network.
</P>
<P>
   To re-enter the public sector, he would have to give up a large
salary, bonuses and stock options he receives at Univision.
</P>
<P>
   The salary range for the superintendent's position ranges from
$190,000 to $250,000, said Roger Rasmussen, a spokesman for the
school district. The district hopes to hire a new superintendent as
soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Cisneros earned $4.5 million from his Univision post:
$600,000 base salary, $600,000 in bonuses and a profit of $3.3
million from the sale of stock options.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros can cash in additional stock options for about $5.2
million, according to the Univision proxy statement filed with the
U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   If he were to stay with the company, other stock options, now
worth $15.4 million, would mature in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros, Univision's president since 1997, renewed his contract
with the media company through 2002 with a base salary of $600,000
for each of those years, according to company documents filed with
the government.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros is credited with helping Univision capture the
spotlight and major advertising dollars with its popular soap
operas and solid ratings in several major markets, including Los
Angeles, Miami and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The company raised its advertising rates 33 percent last year
without driving away advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Although he says he does not plan to return to politics,
Cisneros has been particularly visible at rallies for congressional
candidates in Texas and California.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year alone, Cisneros' name was mentioned as a
potential candidate for Texas governor, Senate and chancellor of
the University of Texas System. Cisneros is a former mayor of San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure as President Clinton's housing secretary,
Cisneros was under investigation for reportedly lying to the FBI
about payments he had made to a former mistress in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros pleaded guilty on Sept. 8, 1999, to a single
misdemeanor charge of lying to the FBI during routine background
checks on nominees for Cabinet posts.
</P>
<P>
   Cisneros paid a $10,000 fine. In exchange for the guilty plea, a
federal judge dropped 18 felony counts that could have sent him to
prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
