<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-DEBT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER JAPANESE FIRM ASKS FOR DEBT FORGIVENESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ For the second time in less than a month, a large
Japanese company beseeched its banks Wednesday to forgive billions
of dollars' worth of debts, intensifying pressure on Japan's
financial system.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Hazama Corp., a general contractor, to request
400 billion yen, or $3.7 billion at current exchange rates, worth
of debt forgiveness is yet another sign that the bad loan problems
of Japanese banks are far from over.
</P>
<P>
   On April 26, Sogo Co., a faltering Japanese retail company, sent
its bankers reeling by asking them to write off 639 billion yen, or
roughly $6 billion, in debts. That was the biggest amount of debt
forgiveness ever sought in Japan, where the practice is still far
from standard.
</P>
<P>
   The shock of Sogo's request was magnified a few days later when
the senior executive in charge of the retailer's financial
restructuring plans was found dead in his home of an apparent
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Just Tuesday, the company's lenders postponed a decision on
Sogo's request, although the largest lender, the Industrial Bank of
Japan, has said it is willing to comply.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of Sogo's outstanding debts to the bank, 180 billion
yen, or $1.7 billion, is roughly equivalent to one year's worth of
operating profits, according to James P. Fiorillo, senior banking
analyst at ING Barings in Tokyo. Nor does the bank have sizeable
unrealized gains on its securities portfolio to offset such a write
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question of whether to forgive these debts or not is a big
one,'' Fiorillo said.
</P>
<P>
   In Hazama's case, Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, its largest lender, is
apparently willing to waive 90 billion yen of the construction
company's loans, according to the Nihon Keizai Shimbun, Japan's
leading business daily.
</P>
<P>
   Changes in accounting standards are intensifying the pressure on
troubled companies. In the fiscal year that began April 1, they
must value their real estate and securities holdings at market
value. The new rules also strictly limit their ability to hide
their debts in the accounts of affiliates by forcing them to report
their results on a consolidated basis.
</P>
<P>
   Including Hazawa and Sogo, more than 10 large companies have
asked for debt relief this year. The biggest numbers seeking such
forgiveness have come from the construction industry, and analysts
warn that many more contractors are in similarly weak shape.
</P>
<P>
   Like Hazama, they took on loads of debt to finance real estate
purchases in the 1980s only to watch the value of that real estate
plummet when Japan's economic bubble burst.
</P>
<P>
   But whether debt forgiveness will really help ailing companies
to regain their footing is a matter of much debate here. Unlike in
the United States, where creditors of distressed companies can
force radical changes onto businesses in exchange for debt relief,
Japanese creditors have very little power to force change. ``It
would be much better if these companies went bankrupt,'' said
Tadashi Nakamae, a prominent economist here. ``Debt forgiveness is
only going to prolong their problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
