<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEERNUT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSISSIPPI MUD BLACK AND TAN: LET THIS ONE GO DOWNSTREAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you've ever had an occasion to encounter the mud along the
Mississippi, particularly near the delta, you know it isn't very
attractive. After draining about half the United States, the river
coughs up a gooey, sticky, oily and chemical-smelling mess.
</P>
<P>
   That said, one wonders why someone would try to sell a beer
called Mississippi Mud, particularly when what we have here is more
about gimmicky packaging and marketing than it is about beer.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi Mud purports to be a ``black and tan,'' which is a
dark porter or stout typically thinned out with a lighter,
amber-colored beer.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, with that name you would expect something dark, thick
and strong, and Mississippi Mud fails to deliver on any level.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting color from this combination isn't bad. Mississippi
Mud produced an attractive reddish-brown color.
</P>
<P>
   But the taste left not only much, but nearly everything, to be
desired. It had a pleasant hoppy aroma, but the taste was very
thin. There was no finish to speak of. There wasn't much of a
beginning either.
</P>
<P>
   Real Mississippi mud would taste better.
</P>
<P>
   The best we can say is that it is a brownish liquid that smells
and tastes vaguely beerlike.
</P>
<P>
   But then, this is a dishonest brew from start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   The label says it is produced by Mississippi Brewing Co. in
Memphis.
</P>
<P>
   But what we actually have here is something concocted by AriZona
Beverage Co., which isn't even in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   AriZona is a ``New Age'' beverage company in Lake Success, N.Y.,
and its real business is selling herbal tea, coffee, fruit juices
and elixirs in fancy bottles.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi Mud Black and Tan comes in 32-ounce jugs ($3) and
16-ounce jugs designed to look like a backwoods jug that might
contain moonshine.
</P>
<P>
   If you want a real black and tan, simply mix equal parts of
Guinness and an amber beer or ale. Bass or Harps works fine.
</P>
<P>
   I rate Mississippi Mud Black and Tan a 0.4 on the international
0 to 5 scale, which puts it smack between ditch water and a flat
Big Red soda.
</P>
<P>
   (Paul Bourgeois is beer critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1601EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
