<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4536 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     05-24 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY MAY BE SORRY THAT RUDY IS GONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton doesn't have Rudy Giuliani to kick around
anymore. So she's exhuming the cold political corpse of Newt
Gingrich to use as a scarecrow in her New York campaign for the
U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rep. Rick Lazio was barely off the bench and into the
game as Giuliani's replacement before Clinton's strategists were
accusing Lazio of being a Gingrich ``puppet'' who hauled water for
the ex-House speaker after the Republican takeover of Congress
during the mid-'90s.
</P>
<P>
   The accusation isn't true, but then truth has never been a
priority in the Clinton household. Past performance suggests that
Hillary Rodham Clinton, like her presidential husband, Bill,
subscribes to the theory that a lie is always preferable to the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   No, the dishonesty of her opening salvo against Lazio isn't
surprising in the least. What's surprising is the first lady's
apparent belief that there is still political mileage to be gained
by railing about Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   There must be voters in New York state who don't remember
anything about the Gingrich speakership, or even remember that
Gingrich led the so-called Republican Revolution that produced the
Contract With America and other high-profile conservative
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   And there must be lots of voters, in New York and all across
America, who wouldn't dream of voting for or against a
congressional candidate because of some real or alleged connection
between the candidate and a former speaker who has fallen so far
off the political radar screen that the late-night TV comics don't
even tell jokes about him anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But you never know. Bill Clinton and the Democrats had plenty of
success demonizing Gingrich, his ideas and just about everyone who
agreed with his ideas. Maybe Hillary and political gurus such as
Harold Ickes know what they're doing; maybe they can defeat Lazio
by hanging Gingrich around his neck.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, of course, will be reluctant to let them get away with it
_ and he is well-armed with facts to refute the Clinton attacks.
According to several news reports about Lazio's entry into the race
after Giuliani dropped out to deal with prostate cancer, the
four-term congressman has won praise from liberals as well as
conservatives and moderates for his independent views on a variety
of issues.
</P>
<P>
   If the Clintonites intend to create the perception that Lazio is
a right-wing ideologue who adheres to the gospel of Gingrich, how
will they explain his past support from environmental activist
groups and his vote for the Brady law regulating purchases of
handguns?
</P>
<P>
   By the time Election Day rolls around, Hillary Clinton might be
wishing that Giuliani had stayed in the race.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City mayor is no hard-line conservative, either,
but Clinton did enjoy thrashing him over New York cops' proclivity
for gunning down unarmed minorities _ and Giuliani's penchant for
occasionally rubbing salt in the wound by suggesting that the
shooting victims got what they deserved.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to imagine Lazio lapsing into the almost snarling
insensitivity that Giuliani is prone to display. If his recent TV
appearances are any indication, Lazio has a permanent smile etched
on his face.
</P>
<P>
   His amiability suggests a personality far different from the
edgy Giuliani's _ and from Clinton's. The first lady often seems to
talk with her teeth clenched, as if suppressing the urge to start
yelling at someone.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that Lazio isn't tough. Responding to the
Clinton campaign's attempt to tie him to Gingrich, Lazio
counterpunched with the dreaded L-word and a sharp jab at Hillary's
potential Achilles' heel: the ``carpetbagger'' problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``My opponent is a liberal and a proud one, and I respect her
for that,'' he said. ``But make no mistake, she is no more a New
Democrat than she is a New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, I would have bet that Giuliani's departure from the
race would crush Republican hopes of keeping Clinton out of the
Senate. Now I'm thinking that Lazio just might be up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1602EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
