<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4537 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     05-24 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CAKE THAT'S FLUFFY AND A CAKE THAT'S FLAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Donna Estus of Weatherford, Texas, sent the recipe for the cake
with mandarin oranges.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Sullivan e-mailed, looking for a recipe for a pancake like
that served at Old South Pancake House in Fort Worth. Although
they're called German pancakes there, more often they're found in
cookbooks under the name of Dutch baby pancakes. Here are two
versions of that pancake that we ran in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   NANCY WARE CAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12-14
</P>
<P>
   18.5-ounce yellow cake mix
</P>
<P>
   11-ounce can mandarin oranges, undrained
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients and mix with electric mixer until orange
slices are broken up and batter is fluffy _ 3 to 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Divide batter among 3 greased and floured 9-inch cake pans. Bake
at 350 degrees for about 20 minutes or until cake tests done. Cool
on rack. When layers are cool, frost between layers, then sides,
then top.
</P>
<P>
   Frosting:
</P>
<P>
   20-ounce can crushed pineapple with juice
</P>
<P>
   8- or 9-ounce container nondairy topping
</P>
<P>
   3-ounce package instant vanilla pudding
</P>
<P>
   Blend all ingredients until well mixed. Frost cake and then
refrigerate up to 2 days to blend flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 357 calories, 18 grams fat, 46
grams carbohydrates, 4 grams protein, 61 milligrams cholesterol,
284 milligrams sodium, 45 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN PANCAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   3 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sifted flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons butter, melted
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1/2 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Sifted powdered sugar
</P>
<P>
   Beat eggs; gradually add flour, salt and milk, blending after
each addition. (A blender works well for this.) Spread half of the
melted butter in a 12-inch iron skillet and pour in batter. Bake at
450 degrees for 12 to 15 minutes, until browned and puffed. Combine
lemon juice with remaining butter and pour over pancake. Sprinkle
with powdered sugar and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 288 calories, 22 grams fat, 15
grams carbohydrates, 7 grams protein, 210 milligrams cholesterol,
539 milligrams sodium, 69 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN PANCAKES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup skim milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Grease two 9-inch round cake pans. In mixing bowl, beat eggs
slightly. Add remaining ingredients; mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Pour batter into pans. Bake at 400 degrees for 20 minutes;
reduce to 350 degrees and bake 10 minutes. Slide onto plates and
serve with fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 233 calories, 12 grams fat, 21
grams carbohydrates, 10 grams protein, 213 milligrams cholesterol,
381 milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
