<SLUG> BC-FAME-ANDFORTUNES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY MAKES FOR UNTIED FAMILIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Put money, fame and family together, and it can make for a
volatile mix.
</P>
<P>
   The current example features Texas teen country-pop star LeAnn
Rimes; her divorced parents, Wilbur and Belinda; and several
million dollars that Mama and daughter say Daddy (and co-manager
Lyle Walker) skimmed over the past several years.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, filed in Dallas on May 2, casts a new shadow over
Rimes' career, causing heads to shake and rumors to fly throughout
the country music community.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the $7 million quoted in the lawsuit is just a
``base'' figure: Rimes' attorneys say that the total that LeAnn
lost and deserves to regain is more, but that they don't know how
much more because there's been no true accounting of the money she
earned.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling the dispute is that Wilbur and Belinda have been
divorced for three years, and a counterallegation that LeAnn's
company owes money to her father and Walker. And there are the
comments from a hurt-sounding Wilbur Rimes that he did everything
for his little girl, which makes the saga sound like a
pedal-guitar-sweetened tabloid-ready court drama.
</P>
<P>
   The Rimes case is not an aberration in the showbiz world. Child
celebrities who accused their parents of mismanaging or embezzling
money include silent-film star Jackie Coogan, Shirley Temple and
Mimi Gibson, who had a role in ``The Three Faces of Eve'' and
starred with Cary Grant and Sophia Loren in ``Houseboat.'' When
Gibson turned 18, she found out that her mother had squandered her
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Gibson has sponsored a bill in California that would
automatically put 15 percent of a child star's earnings into a
trust fund that can be withdrawn only when the child turns 18.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at some of the more recent examples of child
celebrities who say they were fleeced by one parent or both:
</P>
<P>
   The most famous case in recent history involves actor Macaulay
Culkin, a lavish lifestyle, and more than $17 million he earned as
the child star of the ``Home Alone'' movies. Culkin's parents were
also divorced. The Culkin case, which also involved a custody
dispute, centered on who would control his fortune. In March 1998,
after extensive and costly legal wranglings, Manhattan Supreme
Court Judge David Saxe fired dad Christopher Culkin and mom
Patricia Brentrup and put the family's accountant, Billy Breitner,
in charge of the money until Culkin turned 18.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Coleman's case didn't involve divorce, but it did involve
an eight-figure fortune. Coleman was the star of NBC's ``Diff'rent
Strokes'' between 1978 and 1986; at one point he was making $70,000
per episode _ which afforded him homes in Denver and Arizona and a
train set with 30 miles of track.
</P>
<P>
   The show ended when Coleman was 17; three years later, he fired
his parents as his trustees and took them to court, saying that
they misspent his money, including an amount set aside in a trust
fund. He won the case in 1993 and was awarded $1.3 million, a far
cry from the $18 million he once had.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman declared bankruptcy in August, listing debts of $71,890
and assets of $19,850. In September, he told ``People'' magazine he
had sold his two homes and was living in an $800-per-month
apartment in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Pop star Tiffany's troubles were with her mom. The fresh-faced
vocalist released her eponymous debut in 1987 when she was 15, and
enjoyed several fluffy hits, among them ``Could've Been Me.'' Her
mom, Janie C. Williams, contended that Tiffany and manager George
Tobin conspired to prevent her from handling her daughter's career.
</P>
<P>
   In spring 1988, according to the ``Los Angeles Times,'' Tiffany
didn't return home from Tobin's studio. Williams filed a missing
person report; Tiffany, 16, filed an emancipation action the next
week. A few weeks later, the court appointed her aunt, Julie Abbas,
as temporary guardian until the emancipation request was heard. A
Los Angeles Superior Court judge eventually removed Tiffany's
mother as trustee. The judge also increased from 30 to 50 percent
the amount of Tiffany's earnings to be placed in a trust fund and
named the Bank of California and an accounting fund as her
trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the messiest child/parent battle involved gymnast
Dominique Moceanu and her father, Dumitru. At 14, the American-born
Dominique was the youngest member of the U.S. women's gymnastics
team that competed in the 1996 Summer Olympics in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Her parents, who had been on the Romanian Olympics gymnastics
team before defecting to the United States, moved her to Houston in
1990 so Dominique could train with renowned coach Bela Karolyi.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu, 17, sued her parents in October and sought to be
declared an adult, in part to find out what had happened to her
money. She alleged that her parents spent part of her trust fund on
personal items. The trust fund also paid for a 70,000-square-foot
gym.
</P>
<P>
   Her former coach, Luminita Miscenco, left Houston in November
after police told Moceanu that they were looking into reports that
her father had hired a hit man to kill Miscenco, according to a
story in The Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Dumitru Moceanu denied that allegation but took the Fifth
Amendment when questioned under oath. A protective order was
granted Dec. 9 that would keep father and daughter separated for a
year. Dominique has moved to Florida to resume training.
</P>
<P>
   To Tom Rhodus, one of Rimes' attorneys, these sorts of cases
spring from two main factors: Kids grow up faster nowadays and are
more aware of their rights as individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children have greater access to courts than 30 to 40 years
ago,'' Rhodus says. ``But also, in the last 20 years you've seen an
explosion in lawsuits, and that's part of it, too. That can be seen
as a bad thing, but it's good, too, because it speaks of greater
awareness.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhodus says greed plays a role, too. ``All human beings are
similar in one regard: We tend to be selfish, even the best
people,'' he says. ``We're all capable of finding reasons to
justify what we do _ and this is true of everyone from serial
killers to somebody stopped for a speeding ticket. And it's much
easier to do it when it's just money.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
