<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUDGE IN S.F. NEWSPAPER CASE RAISES NEW QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The federal judge hearing the antitrust case
filed against the proposed sale of the San Francisco Examiner
ordered lawyers to answer questions about the profit-sharing
agreement between San Francisco's two daily newspapers and clauses
that allegedly thwarted other companies from buying the properties.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Vaughn R. Walker posed the queries as the
lawyers on Wednesday filed their final legal briefs in former
mayoral candidate Clint Reilly's antitrust suit to prevent the sale
of The Examiner and the purchase of the San Francisco Chronicle by
The Hearst Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's suit claims the plans will result in Hearst owning the
only major metropolitan daily newspaper in San Francisco, an
alleged illegal monopoly that would reduce editorial voices and
increase advertising and subscription rates.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's questions indicated that the judge is considering a
wide range of potential legal remedies in the trial, the nation's
first to challenge the breakup of a joint operating agreement
between newspapers. They are among several he has asked while
hearing the case, in which closing arguments are set for May 31.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph M. Alioto, Reilly's lawyer, has asked Walker to bar
Hearst's proposed purchase of the Chronicle for $660 million. He
wants the judge to order the Chronicle Publishing Co. to offer the
paper for sale anew to other potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto claims Hearst misused its position in the joint operating
agreement to ward off other buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, The Examiner and the Chronicle since 1965
have evenly shared their combined revenue, costs of production and
remaining profit.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement is allowed under the Newspaper Preservation Act,
an exemption to antitrust laws meant to keep alive economically
failing newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst and Chronicle representatives have denied Reilly's
contentions and say the deals should be allowed to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst claims that outside the agreement, its afternoon Examiner
would be an economically failing firm and that as a result it may
buy the Chronicle and sell or close The Examiner without violating
antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Walker issued two orders, one page each, and asked
one question aimed at the contentions.
</P>
<P>
   In the first, Walker asked the lawyers to brief him on the
validity of a restriction in the joint operating agreement that, in
effect, bars the owners of each paper from selling to any other
firm operating a paper within 60 miles of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The question also asked the lawyers to address another
restriction that gives each partner the ``right of first refusal,''
or the chance to outbid any potential buyer of the other partner's
paper.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto contended in an interview Tuesday that Walker should
disallow the two restrictions on the ground that they have nothing
to do with operating the newspapers or serving the purposes of the
Newspaper Preservation Act.
</P>
<P>
   He claimed the clauses violated antitrust law because they were
designed for ``fencing out competitors'' who might otherwise buy
one of the papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's plainly an anti-competitive device,'' said Alioto, who
has argued that Hearst used the provisions to strike a deal to buy
the Chronicle at below-market cost.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge disallowed the restrictions and ordered the
Chronicle put up for resale, companies owning papers within 60
miles could bid for the Chronicle, Alioto said.
</P>
<P>
   These include Knight Ridder, owner of the San Jose Mercury News;
the New York Times, owner of the Santa Rosa Press Democrat; and the
Alameda Newspaper Group, owner of the Oakland Tribune.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Halling, a Hearst lawyer, could not be reached for comment.
J. Thomas Rosch, a Chronicle Publishing lawyer, declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's second question asked whether Hearst and Chronicle
Publishing should be allowed to continue their joint operating
agreement, even if Hearst's Examiner could be made into a
financially sound business using changes proposed by the Fang
family.
</P>
<P>
   The Fangs have agreed to buy The Examiner in a deal under which
Hearst would give them a subsidy of up to $66 million over three
years to defray publishing costs.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Fang, publisher of the free San Francisco Independent, has
testified that he believes he can make The Examiner financially
successful by focusing it on city readers and advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Walker's question seemed to ask whether a newspaper must remain
a financial failure to continue as a partner in a joint operating
agreement, said David Balabanian, a lawyer for the Fangs.
</P>
<P>
   Balabanian said he believed the Newspaper Preservation Act
specifies only that a paper is failing at the time it enters the
agreement. The Act does not require that the papers continue to be
a failure, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
