u i BC-MEXICO-DEBATE-0525-CO     05-24 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-DEBATE-0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GAME OF POLITICAL CHICKEN LEAVES MEXICANS WONDERING ABOUT
PRESIDENTIAL RACE
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Already buzzing over the hottest election year
ever here, Mexicans have been left guessing whether three fierce
rivals for the presidency will show up for a possible debate Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate most under pressure is conservative party
contender Vicente Fox Quesada, who is running the most successful
opposition campaign in recent Mexican history.
</P>
<P>
   After orchestrating a televised mini-debate with rivals early
Tuesday evening to try to revive a scheduled debate that was
postponed, Fox surprised the public by declaring that he wasn't
sure he would attend a debate his two rivals suggested they hold
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The game of political chicken, some observers here say, could
backfire on Fox if the other candidates show up and he doesn't.
With less than six weeks to go before the July 2 election, polls
are showing that Fox has a shot at defeating Mexico's ruling party,
which has controlled the presidency for 71 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going out to campaign,'' Fox said in a radio broadcast
Wednesday. ``There is no decision yet (on Friday).''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, leftist Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, and Institutional
Revolutionary Party candidate Francisco Labastida Ochoa were
supposed to have met Tuesday for the second of two formal televised
debates before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was widely hailed as the winner of the first debate in
April.
</P>
<P>
   The second debate was postponed because neither Cardenas nor
Labastida would agree to Fox's insistence on a more free-wheeling
encounter, with questions from reporters and an improvised speaking
order.
</P>
<P>
   Fox accused Labastida of fearing spontaneity and wanting to
``control'' the debate.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning Fox phoned his rivals while reporters
watched, challenging them to meet personally later that day to
revive the debate. The three showed up at Cardenas' headquarters,
where they squabbled on live television _ an unusually frank event
for Mexico's stodgy political culture.
</P>
<P>
   Fox insisted on going ahead with the debate Tuesday night as
scheduled. ``Today,'' he repeatedly told Cardenas, pointing out
that two television networks pledged to be ready.
</P>
<P>
   But the other candidates said there wasn't time Tuesday to
prepare. If their campaign teams can iron out details, they agreed
to debate Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Fox appeared irritated because the president of Mexico's
television-industry association showed up with Labastida to attend
the meeting. The executive, whose group is often criticized as too
pro-Labastida, met privately with Labastida and Cardenas before Fox
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Normally an able spontaneous speaker, Fox appeared stubborn
during the televised meeting, said Joel Estudillo of the Mexican
Institute for Political Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may have had some good points, but he wasn't able to get
them across,'' Estudillo said. ``Now he's in a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Labastida attacked Fox's character after the patio debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all my years in politics,'' he told reporters, ``I don't
think I've ever seen such a spectacle with such little seriousness
as today.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.wola.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
