u a BC-FEEDER-SCHOOLS-NYT &LR;      05-24 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEEDER-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEEDER SCHOOLS IN NORTHEAST FEEL THE PINCH AS IVY LEAGUE
APPLICATIONS RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They attend top high schools in the New York region and the
Northeast, and, within that rarefied group, they are
better-than-average students. Banking on the reputations of their
schools alone, they would most likely have been snapped up by many
of the top colleges they dreamed of attending _ if only they had
applied three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   One is a New Yorker about to graduate from a storied New England
boarding school who was rejected by all seven colleges to which he
applied this year _ including Trinity and Tufts _ despite a College
Board score in the high 1300s out of 1,600 and a B-plus average.
</P>
<P>
   Another attends one of the most rigorous prep schools in New
York City, but her record _ a mix of A's and B's and a College
Board score in the mid-1200s _ earned her only one acceptance, at
Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   A third had a straight-A average at a public high school in one
of Long Island's wealthiest communities, a College Board score of
nearly 1400, and extensive volunteer work with the homeless and
disabled, but she was rejected outright, in an early round, by the
University of Pennsylvania. She then applied to only one other
institution, of less cachet, and was immediately accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Though the sting of this exceptionally competitive college
admissions season was felt in homes across the country, it has
often been sharpest in New York, New Jersey and around New England
_ particularly at high schools so well known that their names alone
once provided all the necessary collateral for even a middling
applicant to secure a good spot.
</P>
<P>
   In part, those students most disappointed in the results of
their college quests this year were victims of a simple numbers
problem: applications at places like Harvard, Columbia and
Middlebury are up, but not necessarily the number of seats.
</P>
<P>
   But with the nation's students now able to visit, and apply to,
virtually any college with the click of a mouse, more applications
are streaming into the most prestigious Northeastern universities
from the Midwest, West and South. This is a welcome rain for
colleges looking to broaden their ``geographical diversity,'' but
sometimes it comes at the expense of longtime feeder schools in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were certainly schools that were easier for our students
to get into a year ago that are more difficult now,'' said Carol
Katz, the college adviser at Stuyvesant High School in Manhattan,
one of the best public high schools in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are there more disappointments this year?'' Katz added. ``Yes.
What we once thought was a safe school is no longer a good bet. And
what we once thought was a good bet has become more of a long
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Katz, like her colleagues elsewhere, would speak only in the
blandest generalities about a process that gives so many students
and parents so many sleepless nights. Other advisers would relay
their stories only on the condition of anonymity (theirs and their
students'), given the high emotions involved.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Leana, an education counselor and the former director of
college counseling at Trinity School in Manhattan, said that the
process had become ``a little more pressurized for Manhattanites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When given a choice among equally qualified applicants, these
colleges are more likely to pull in that kid from North Dakota or
the remote part of upstate New York then from the densely
populated, highly qualified New York City pool,'' he said. ``It's
just a different ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, such hand-wringing is as regular a part of each
spring as the emergence of the crocuses, because even the most
skilled counselors are routinely stymied by their attempts to
outthink a process that is, at its root, often arbitrary, with more
than 10 students applying for each seat in the freshman class at
some institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some New York-area high schools detected little dip in
their college tallies this year.
</P>
<P>
   Montclair High School in Montclair, N.J., for example, reported
that its students had fared better in the admissions race this year
than last, at least as measured by the 11 students, out of a
graduating class of 350, bound for Ivy League colleges.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no denying that the competition from within New
York state alone, which often fills more spots than any other state
at top colleges, has tightened in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that the 2,900 applications submitted to Columbia
University by New York State students this year represent an
increase of 53 percent since 1997. And, in a finite game of musical
chairs, those New York students are being pitted not only against
one another but also against more applicants from around the
country and the world, who have become convinced that admission to
a top college guarantees nothing less than success in later life.
</P>
<P>
   It is telling that Carol Gill, a college counselor in
Westchester County whose client base once extended no farther than
the 10-mile radius centered on Dobbs Ferry, now regularly consults
with families in Louisville, Ky., and Cleveland, as well as Athens,
Greece, and London.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have an easier time of it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Bass, the editor and publisher of ``The Private School
Insider,'' a monthly newsletter that reports on schools in the
metropolitan region, says that some New York students whose egos
have been battered by Northeastern colleges have wound up looking
farther from home than their predecessors did _ often to
universities like Emory in Atlanta and Vanderbilt in Tennessee,
which, however well regarded, are not the applicants' first
choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point being made,'' Bass said, ``is that you just can't
say anymore, `This is my safe school.' You have to want to go to
all of the schools.''
</P>
</TEXT>
