A4551 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-SOC-WOMEN'S-SOCCER-HN     05-24 0460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN'S-SOCCER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BIDDERS FOR WOMEN'S SOCCER LEAGUE AGREE TO COMBINE EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MICHELLE SMITH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ There will be only one women's professional
soccer league going forward after all.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's United Soccer Association (WUSA), which put in its
bid with U.S. Soccer to run the league last winter, will work with
the cooperation of Major League Soccer to get their league off the
ground next spring.
</P>
<P>
   MLS was expected to put its own bid to run a league, but has
backed off that plan and will help the WUSA with their efforts
instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came very close and had our bid application ready to go,''
said MLS commissioner Don Garber. ``But at the 11th hour we had a
meeting of the minds that makes sense. This agreement is simple and
practical and the entire soccer community believes this
relationship makes a whole lot of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The two entities will collaborate on marketing, promotion,
scheduling and development of soccer-specific stadium sites. There
are also preliminary plans of joint efforts for expansion and
co-ownership of teams.
</P>
<P>
   The WUSA is scheduled to debut in April 2001 in eight cities:
Atlanta, Boston, New York, Orlando, Philadelphia, San Diego, San
Francisco and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. team member Carla Overbeck spoke for her teammates _ all 20
players backed the WUSA plan from the start _ in expressing relief
that there will be no divisive competition for the right to launch
the women's league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are excited (the WUSA) is the plan that's going through
with help from the MLS side,'' Overbeck said. ``As we've seen with
other women's pro sports, having two leagues is not what's best for
the game or its growth. The plan we were hoping they would sanction
is going to move forward with the experience the MLS brings to the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   The growth of both the men's and women's professional games in
the United States is in the common interest of both parties. MLS is
in its fifth season, and the WUSA hopes to benefit from that
operating experience.
</P>
<P>
   The men's league, on the other hand, would like to take
advantage of the corporate media support the WUSA has amassed. The
WUSA is backed by Time Warner, Comcast, Discovery Communications
and Cox Communications, and already has a television deal in place
with TNT and CNN-SI. The MLS will be offered advertising time on
those media outlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very mutual agreement with both benefiting from the
strengths of the other,'' said WUSA chairman John Hendricks.
``There is equal value on both sides. We are offering multimillion
dollars worth of media time and we will benefit from the years of
operation of MLS.''
</P>
</TEXT>
