r l BC-SUBWAY-DIET-TEX     05-24 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBWAY-DIET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH 245 POUNDS TO LOSE, HIS WAY WAS THE SUBWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Carolyn Poirot 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jared Fogle blames fast food, and lots of it, for the extra 245
pounds he lugged around for years.
</P>
<P>
   He credits fast food, specifically Subway sandwiches, for
helping him shed those 245 pounds and go from a 60-inch waist to a
34 in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Now known as ``The Subway Diet Guy'' and ``Subway Sandwich
Man,'' Fogle, 22, graduated this month from Indiana University, is
beginning a new job as a pricing analyst with American Trans Air,
has a great girlfriend and is a friendly, self-confident young man.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen months after losing all that weight, he's still at the
190 pounds he wants to be and is still surprised at all the
attention he has received since his dieting success made the front
page of his college newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The story caught the attention of ``Men's Health'' magazine,
which published it with a collection of ``Crazy Diets that Work.''
Then someone at Subway's corporate office saw the magazine and
contacted Fogle about making a commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could never have imagined people would care so much and be
so interested in me and how I lost the weight,'' Fogle says. ``I
knew my family and friends would be happy about it, but it's become
a craze. I've been interviewed by the BBC and reporters from
Australia and Canada.''
</P>
<P>
   Fogle says Subway ``helped save my life and start over,'' but
those sandwiches were also part of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   In his fast-food heyday, he lived next door to a Subway shop,
and several times a week would eat his favorite foot-long steak and
cheese sub with double meat, double cheese, heavy on the mayo,
along with regular chips, a large soft drink and maybe a cookie or
two.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that a lot of pizzas, cheeseburgers, french fries and
tacos, and he had a real problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lack of movement and a lot of late-night pizza. It
was never about beer. I never partied,'' Fogle says. ``I never
really had a social life.''
</P>
<P>
   He painfully recalls how he spent a lot of time figuring out how
to avoid anything that might be embarrassing. When he went
anywhere, he parked as far away as he could walk so no one would
see him trying to get out of the car, and he chose college classes
based on the type of seating available.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked into a restaurant, I would scan the seating to
see if there was a place I could fit into or if I should insist on
going somewhere else. I was so scared of being embarrassed,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   One day, when he stopped by the sandwich shop to pick up a
takeout (he couldn't fit into a booth), Fogle noticed a sign
promoting ``Seven Under Six,'' the company's seven subs with less
than 6 grams of fat.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly calculated the fat and calories involved and decided
on a new diet: a 6-inch turkey sub for lunch, loaded with ``tons of
lettuce, green peppers, banana peppers, jalapeno peppers and
pickles, topped with spicy mustard _ no cheese or mayo'' _ with a
package of baked chips and a diet soft drink.
</P>
<P>
   For dinner, he had a foot-long vegetable sub and another diet
drink _ fewer than 1,100 calories each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would switch off between whole wheat and white bread,
deciding on which one had baked up to look bigger that day,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   He knew he was losing weight, but didn't know how much until he
went home to Indianapolis to visit his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hadn't seen me in two months, and they were amazed,''
says Fogle, whose father is a doctor, a general practitioner. ``My
dad took me to his office to weigh, and neither of us could believe
it. There were tears in his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   In two months, the Subway Diet Man had lost 95 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   After that visit, he weighed and had blood work done each time
he was home. His cholesterol dropped, and all his other blood
counts remained good.
</P>
<P>
   Fogle began walking to his nearby college classes.
</P>
<P>
   Before the initial loss, he says, he often fell asleep in class
and could barely move around, much less exercise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard at first. I would get really hungry, but I knew I
was doing something good for myself, and I was determined,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Fogle stuck with the diet, ``cheating'' only a couple of times,
including Thanksgiving Day 1998, when he ate turkey and dressing,
no gravy, and a small dessert.
</P>
<P>
   He says he knew it was time to quit when he reached his goal of
180 _ 245 pounds down from the initial 425 _ and felt he was just
too thin for his 6-foot-2 frame.
</P>
<P>
   He deliberately regained 10 pounds, then went on a cruise to St.
Thomas, St. Martin and the Bahamas to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   He says he still eats several low-fat Subway sandwiches a week,
but he usually doesn't have to pay for them.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time he completed the diet, in March 1999, he met
his girlfriend, Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll be together for quite a while,'' he says.
``She's the greatest reward of all. If it were not for the weight
loss, I might not have ever met her,'' Fogle says. ``I think this
was the way I was supposed to be. I was just hidden while I was
that heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
