<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4555 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-EVERETT-NYT &LR;      05-24 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-EVERETT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERETT MAKES RELUCTANT RETURN TO NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carl Everett begins the discussion by claiming that he does not
speak to New York reporters, then turns to a befuddled Boston Red
Sox teammate for confirmation that it has been three years since he
did an interview with anyone from New York. When Everett is
reminded of an article in a New York newspaper two months ago, the
new villain for New York Yankees fans insists that he must have
been quoted from a group interview.
</P>
<P>
   As Everett declines to be interviewed, he talks about his
reasoning. It is not totally clear if Everett is serious about
being silent, but he seems rather serious. Finally, Mike Stanley, a
former Yankee, is asked to mediate, and he assures Everett that he
will be quoted accurately. Seconds later, the verbal faucet is on
and Everett agrees to answer questions.
</P>
<P>
   Everett explains why he despises the Yankees, who drafted him in
the first round in 1990. He explains why the disparaging remarks he
made about Derek Jeter and Paul O'Neill this spring were
misinterpreted, but he still sounds critical of them. He blames
ignorance for the allegations of child abuse levied against Everett
and his wife while he played for the New York Mets in 1997. He
scoffs at the notion that he will be berated when the Red Sox visit
Yankee Stadium on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about that,'' Everett said earlier this month.
``People can say and do whatever they want. But just don't put your
hands on me. That's all. Don't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't touch Everett. Don't ask Everett about his five children.
Don't try to convince Everett that the Yankees have won three of
the last four World Series in part because they have developed
enormous talent in their minor-league system. That will not jibe
with Everett, who was acquired from the salary-dumping Astros and
has helped turn an already dangerous team into even more of a
contender to dethrone the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez is the king of the hill and Nomar Garciaparra is
the king of the lineup, but Everett has made it three kings on the
Red Sox. That is an accomplishment. Everett has arguably been the
most important acquisition of the off-season in baseball and, with
a .328 average, 13 homers and 37 runs batted in going into Tuesday
night, he already has more home runs than Red Sox center fielders
had all of last season.
</P>
<P>
   Everett deserves attention for what he does on the field and,
sometimes, for what he says off it, too. He is the perfect fit for
the Red Sox, and he has endeared himself to fans with his hits, his
hustle and his hatred of things New York. The Yankees-Red Sox
rivalry never needs spicing, but Everett might hate the Yankees
more than fans who have endured dreary Octobers for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wonder why I dislike the Yankees,'' he said.
``There were people there who didn't want to help you. There were
people who didn't want me to succeed in the minor leagues. They
worked for the organization when I was there. They were envious
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett did not specify whom he was referring to, and Mark
Newman, the Yankees' vice president for baseball operations who was
a minor-league coordinator then, did not return a message. But
Everett, who turns 29 next month, said he never wanted to be
drafted by the Yankees out of Hillsborough High School in Tampa,
Fla. Since he never rose above Class A in three years with the
Yankees, he was glad to be picked by Florida in the 1992 expansion
draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knew if you came up in their farm system, it was slim
or none that you were going to make it,'' he said. ``I wanted to go
somewhere else and show what I could do. It didn't matter what I
did in the Yankee system, it wasn't going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   When Everett was reminded that the Yankees have excelled because
of home-grown players like Jeter, Bernie Williams, Mariano Rivera,
Andy Pettitte, Ramiro Mendoza and Jorge Posada, he shook his head.
Instead, Everett mentioned how it took Shane Spencer nine years to
get to the majors and how Ricky Ledee is ``as good a hitter as
anyone'' and cannot get established.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you weren't there,'' he said, ``you might not understand
how I look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Understanding Everett can be a challenge. Less than a month into
spring training this year, Everett said the Yankees win even though
they do not have superstars. When a reporter asked about Jeter,
Everett said Jeter is not a superstar because he does not change
games in an instant. Everett listed Mark McGwire and Ken Griffey
Jr. as superstars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people want to misinterpret me saying he's not a superstar,
go ahead,'' Everett said. ``He's a great player, a good player.
But, if I'm a pitcher, I'm not worried about him hitting a
three-run homer or changing the outcome of a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeter handled Everett's barbs with aplomb, saying: ``Everyone is
entitled to his opinion. But what about the stuff he said about
O'Neill?''
</P>
<P>
   Everett ran his finger across his throat in a slicing motion in
March as his way of saying the 37-year-old O'Neill was done. But
Everett tried to recant his criticism of O'Neill, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said when a guy is getting at the end of his career, he has
to work harder to get where he wants,'' he said. ``That was left
out, and it looked like I was dogging O'Neill.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill chuckled over the criticism and said he cared only about
what Manager Joe Torre said about him. Still, O'Neill, a proud
player who has become more age-sensitive, might have been playing
coy, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everett is having a great year for them,'' he added. ``Isn't
he?''
</P>
<P>
   He is. Everett is immersed in Boston and is happy that he signed
a three-year, $21 million contract extension. He usually stops
outside the players' entrance at Fenway Park and signs autographs.
Four other Red Sox players breezed by without signing autographs
earlier this month, but Everett signed and posed for pictures for
15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every place I've played, Boston outweighs them in terms of fan
support,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As chatty as Everett eventually was, he was brief when asked
about having allegations of child abuse brought against him and his
wife, Linda, in 1997. A child-care worker at Shea Stadium noticed
bruises on one of Everett's children, Shawna, who was 5 years old,
and she and Carl, who was 4, were placed in city custody while
Everett and his wife went to Queens Family Court.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ruled that Linda, Shawna's stepmother, used
``excessive corporal punishment'' and that Carl failed to take
``appropriate action.'' The couple had to attend parenting classes
and undergo mental health evaluations before their son was returned
to them, but Shawna was ordered to live with a grandmother. Everett
blames that situation on New York, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people do things to hurt others, and they don't care,''
he said. ``Even if they were wrong, they say, `Oh well.' That was
the case with me in New York. That's what people did to me. I had
to deal with all of that garbage when I was in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett visits again this weekend, but only because he must.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1629EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
