<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4560 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-MILITARY-TRAINER-HNS &LR;      05-24 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-TRAINER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MILITARY INTRODUCES A NEW, HIGH-TECH `TEXAN' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Texan is back.
</P>
<P>
   Decades after the AT-6 ``Texan'' was used to train Army Air
Corps and Navy pilots during World War II, a new plane with a
similar name landed Tuesday at Randolph Air Force Base in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The T-6A ``Texan II'' was billed as a cheaper, quieter and
friendlier aerobatic alternative to the aging T-37 ``Tweet,'' a
small jet-powered craft that has been the service's prime trainer
the past 34 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The aircraft is very student-friendly, it's very
instructor-friendly, and it's very environmentally friendly,'' said
Gen. Lloyd W. ``Fig'' Newton, head of the Randolph-based Air
Education and Training Command.
</P>
<P>
   The T-6A was unveiled before a crowd of 350 at Randolph. A T-37,
the original T-6 and a Navy T-34 were parked on a runway ramp
behind the dais, with a model of the new T-6 flanking the podium.
The audience cheered as the plane buzzed over the runway and banked
to the right.
</P>
<P>
   Rear Adm. Michael Bucchi, chief of naval air training at Corpus
Christi Naval Air Station, called the plane ``the perfect trainer
for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department has ordered 740 T-6As at a total cost of
$4 billion. The planes will replace the T-37 by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Built in Wichita, Kan., by Raytheon Aircraft, the T-6A sports a
single turboprop engine, a pressurized cabin, stepped tandem
cockpit, all-digital avionics and ejection seats that can be used
on the runway _ vast improvements over the T-37, AETC spokesman
Dave Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to read across the cockpit like in the Tweet
and start switching knobs,'' said Lt. Col. Steve Van Sciver, an
18-year Air Force veteran who began his career with training in the
T-37. ``Everything's right in front of you or easily within reach
for the biggest and the smallest person.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texan's cabin is flexible, capable of accommodating men and
women of all sizes, a major development given the growing role of
women in the services.
</P>
<P>
   If it feels like a luxury car in the cabin, the T-6A is a fuel
miser on the road. The old T-37 has a range of 460 miles and
guzzles 152 gallons per hour. The T-6A, though, can fly 1,000 miles
on one tank and burns just 71 gallons per hour.
</P>
<P>
   The plane will be jointly used by the Air Force and Navy, which
have ordered 372 and 339 Texan IIs, respectively. Another 29 T-6As
have been ordered for use in Air Force-Navy navigator training
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Bucchi said the Texan would boost the ``confidence and
competence of its warriors'' as they learn to fly. But the T-6 is
likely to be noticed less as instructor pilots learn their trade at
Randolph, thanks to its quiet Pratt &AMP; Whitney engine.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the Tweet's high-pitch, the Texan had a warm, even
pleasant buzz the crowd could talk over.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Sig Christenson by e-mail at sigc &LR; express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
