<HEADER>
A4562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-TOUR-BUSES-NYT &LR;      05-24 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TOUR-BUSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TO ASK JUDGE TO SUSPEND TOUR BUS LINE AFTER FATALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   By C.J. CHIVERS and JUAN FORERO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City officials said Tuesday that they would
ask a judge to suspend the license of New York Apple Tours
immediately, a day after one of its double-decker tour buses
fatally struck a 71-year-old pedestrian in Midtown, an accident
that once again set off concerns about a company with a long record
of environmental, safety and traffic violations.
</P>
<P>
   New York Apple Tours, which operates scores of buses out of
Midtown Manhattan, rapidly increased its business during the city's
tourism boom of the 1990s, operating a sort of London-on-the-Hudson
tour of New York from its familiar red double-decker buses.
</P>
<P>
   But as the company has expanded, it has been the subject of a
growing number of complaints, and since October the city's
Department of Consumer Affairs has been trying to revoke its
license, citing a pattern of abuses of city, state and federal
laws.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Joseph Lhota said Tuesday that at the next
regularly scheduled hearing in the matter, set for Thursday before
Administrative Law Judge Judith Gould, the city would seek the
immediate suspension of the company's license, pending the outcome
of the case. In the accident on Monday, the driver was not licensed
to operate a bus and was driving on a residential street where
buses are generally not allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were moving against them because of the number of traffic
violations and the number of accidents they have had,'' Lhota said
Tuesday. ``The tragedy yesterday is provoking us to take the
revocation hearing that we are going for and ratchet it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's promise of action came as a second driver for the
company was cited by the police for driving without a license in a
case separate from the accident on Monday, which killed Randolph
Walter, an actor.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Dwyer, a lawyer for Apple Tours, said, ``Our hearts go
out to the family and friends of the victim.'' The company could
not discuss specific allegations, Dwyer said, but he said Apple
Tours was cooperating with investigators looking into the accident.
He also said the company adheres to safety regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``New York Apple Tour buses are inspected regularly and pass New
York state Department of Transportation safety inspections every
six months,'' he said. ``We have an excellent safety record, and
our drivers go through a rigorous training course which includes a
driving test, written test, video instruction and medical test.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the city's move to halt the company's operation
immediately was welcomed by those who have long battled Apple
Tours, many of them questioned why the administration took so long.
</P>
<P>
   In its nine years of operation, the company has been the source
of continuous neighborhood and consumer complaints. Since 1996, the
company has received 1,800 nonmoving violations and been in 140
accidents, Lhota said.
</P>
<P>
   It has also been cited by the state for circumventing vehicle
safety inspections, and it pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court
last fall to claiming falsely that 70 double-decker buses imported
from Britain did not have to comply with federal safety and
environmental standards because the vehicles predated those
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a pitched battle since they started to do business
in the City of New York,'' said state Sen. Thomas Duane, who as a
city councilman first proposed legislation in 1994 to keep the
buses off residential streets. ``They've broken every rule and
regulation they could possibly break. They have lied to the
community and us. They've broken every promise. But the city
continued to reward them, with more stops and more permits.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, since residents of Greenwich Village first complained in
1993 about the noise and pollution caused by the company's fleet,
the list of objections has continued to grow.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1995, the City Department of Consumer Affairs ordered
the company to take all its buses off the streets after the company
was accused of illegally switching permits at state inspections.
The company's buses were back on the road after it paid a $100,000
fine and agreed, among other things, to remove its vice president,
Harry Grant, as an officer.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in September, the company admitted to the U.S. attorney's
office in Newark, N.J., that it had lied about the ages of its
vehicles to avoid meeting federal safety and environmental
standards. The company, which was then based in Fort Lee, N.J.,
pleaded guilty to falsifying documents with three federal agencies,
the Customs Service, the Department of Transportation and the
Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Tours had told the agencies the buses were made in 1967
and were therefore exempt from federal safety and emissions
standards, but the buses were actually newer. In a plea agreement,
the company pledged to pay an $800,000 fine and bring its buses
into compliance with federal emissions and safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   However, the company has not paid the fine. Under the plea
agreement, the penalty is to be paid upon sentencing by U.S.
District Judge John Bissell, but the company has not been sentenced
because it has continued to dispute the terms of its plea
agreement, said Michael Drewniak, a spokesman for the U.S.
attorney's office in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Past and current city officials said that the case in New Jersey
gave the city the grounds to begin trying to put the company out of
business, and that the accident strengthened its case.
</P>
<P>
   Jules Polonetsky, who was the city's commissioner of consumer
affairs last fall when the case began, said New York Apple Tours
had been the source of complaints for years. But he said many were
about pollution, parking or traffic violations, and because the
department's mandate is to protect consumers, the complaints did
not directly fall under its jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   But when the company admitted falsifying documents, he said, it
allowed the city to assemble a much stronger case, incorporating
the federal action with the hodge-podge of city and state
complaints to show that the company was irresponsible and
deceptive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new evidence of their smuggling buses into the county gave
the department grounds to begin a serious license revocation
action,'' Polonetsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing this action, Lhota said complaints from the community
about the city's pace in seeking to close the business were
unfounded. ``The long and the short of it is we actually are in a
revocation hearing right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said that in response to Randolph's death, the
city's Traffic Control Division deployed a bus inspection team near
Columbus Circle Tuesday, and the officers arrested Richard Burks,
32, saying he was driving the double-decker bus with a suspended
license.
</P>
<P>
   Burks, who was taken into custody at 3:10 p.m. as tourists were
stepping off the bus at Central Park South and Seventh Avenue, was
held overnight pending an arraignment Wednesday on charge of
aggravated unlicensed operation of a vehicle, said Officer Louis
Cruz, a department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The company also faces the possibility that it will be forced
out of the city's tourism agency, which it joined in 1992 and to
which it has been paying dues ever since.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
