<SLUG> BC-CIR-WESLEYAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COLLEGE LEADS THE WAY IN REQUIRING ONLINE APPLICATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By LISA GUERNSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Using the Internet to apply to college has become a popular
option among high school seniors over the past few years. But
online applications have always been just that _ an option.
</P>
<P>
   If students wanted to rely on typewriters or their own
handwriting, they could fill out paper forms.
</P>
<P>
   Now at least one undergraduate institution is doing away with
paper applications. Starting this fall, West Virginia Wesleyan
College will be requiring applicants to fill out and send in their
forms online.
</P>
<P>
   A few graduate schools have the same requirement, but according
to Embark.com, the company that is providing the online service,
West Virginia Wesleyan is the first college to make online
applications mandatory for undergraduates.
</P>
<P>
   Most colleges have shunned such a requirement because they do
not want to exclude students who do not have easy access to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody may not have equal access to this technology,'' said
Joyce Smith, director of the National Association for College
Admission Counseling. ``There may be some students who are
disadvantaged by the requirement.''
</P>
<P>
   But officials at West Virginia Wesleyan, a private liberal arts
college of 1,500 students in Buckhannon, W.Va., said they were
confident that the requirement would not be a limitation. The
university receives about 1,600 applications a year.
</P>
<P>
   The requirement, university officials said, is part of the
college's push to be technologically advanced.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the college provides laptop computers to every new
student and plans to provide wireless Internet access on campus
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Haden, the college's president, said that admissions
counselors who visit high schools would make their laptop computers
available to students who wanted to fill out applications and that
alumni might be able to provide computer access. He expected that
computers in churches, public libraries and high schools would also
be available.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives us the comfort that we can have this requirement
and not have it be a barrier to access,'' Haden said.
</P>
<P>
   The college does not require essays, and officials expect that
most students will be able to fill out the applications in less
than half an hour. Most of the supplementary material included with
admissions applications, like high school transcripts and teacher
recommendations, will still be completed on paper and sent through
the mail, Haden said.
</P>
<P>
   The college has already been criticized by some advocates for
people with disabilities. Some say that online applications have
not been built to work with screen-reading software for the blind
and that they cannot be easily filled out by people who are unable
to operate a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Haden said that the college would find alternatives
for students who could not fill out the online applications because
of disabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will work to find solutions to such a situation,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
