<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEOGRAPHY-BEE-0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    13-YEAR-OLD IS A WORLD CLASS CHAMP IN NATIONAL GEOGRAPHIC BEE
 &HT;    By MIRIAM GARCIA
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He hasn't traveled widely, but the 13-year-old
winner of the National Geographic Bee proved Wednesday that he
knows a lot about the world.
</P>
<P>
   Felix Peng of Guilford, Conn., took first prize _ a $25,000
scholarship _ by correctly naming the three largest sections of
Denmark: Jutland, the nation's mainland peninsula, and Sjaelland
and Fyn, its two largest islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel relieved. It's finally over,'' Felix said after waving
the scholarship check in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Felix said that during the final rounds, he felt as stiff as the
answer cards he held in his hands as he battled two other
finalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to do any more tie-breakers. I was nervous,''
Felix said.
</P>
<P>
   Second place winner George Thampy, 12, of suburban St. Louis,
received a $15,000 scholarship and third place winner Jonathan
Janus, 13, of Ravenel, S.C., won a $10,000 scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   The final round had been narrowed to 10 male contestants from
the 55 who started Tuesday, of which only two were female. The
11-to-15-year- old students represented the 50 states, the District
of Columbia, Puerto Rico, the U.S. Virgin Islands, the Pacific
Territories and schools at U.S. military bases around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The National Geographic Society created the contest 12 years ago
to reawaken the nation's interest in geography and increase its
curriculum in American schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not geography nerds, these are bright multitalented
students,'' said Alex Trebek, the emcee of the competition who
hosts the popular television program, ``Jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Felix's interest in geography was ignited at the age of two when
he began to open books, said his father Richard Peng, a 47-year-old
dentist. ``He started looking at books and maps before he could
even talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Felix's parents were born in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Felix placed 19th last year and was determined to take the first
prize this year, his father added.
</P>
<P>
   In this week's competition, contestants sometimes answered
questions before Trebek was finished asking them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows a great deal. I have respect for the kind of
education the kids are obtaining,'' Trebek said.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the final contestants were home-schooled, including the
second and third place winners.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-place finisher Robert Schleifer, 14, of Gillsville, Ga.,
is among those home-schooled. His mother, Tina, a microbiologist
and homeschool teacher, said she worked extensively with him to
ensure his success.
</P>
<P>
   ``My children have been able to concentrate on the areas they
want and (they) excel. We just want to give them the best education
we can,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Garcia can be e-mailed at: miriamg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
