<HEADER>
A4579 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-INK-NYT &LR;      05-24 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-INK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOLECULES ENGINEERED WITH AN INKJET PRINTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By IAN AUSTEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When scientists want to build very tiny structures on silicon
chips or other surfaces, they usually have to figure out how to
nudge atoms and molecules into the right shape _ and that can mean
building a special factory for $100 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   But scientists at Sandia National Laboratories say they have
found a way to do the same thing by putting molecules into a
solution that is squirted onto various surfaces with an inkjet
printer to form patterns designed by a computer. Once on the
surface, the molecules assemble themselves into the desired shapes,
with no prodding necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The Sandia scientists call their transparent solutions
``intelligent ink,'' and their approach may turn out to be a
practical way to build the tiny molecular scaffolds called
nanostructures.
</P>
<P>
   Nanotechnology, the production of these tiny structures, could
someday have as big an impact on technology as silicon-based
microelectronics has. Such extremely tiny creations could lead to
the making of computer chips that would be thousands of times more
powerful than the chips available now. They could also lead to
chips that merge biology and microelectronics to create, in effect,
biochemical labs no bigger than a microchip that could analyze
drops of blood.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligent ink could put such technology within the reach of
researchers without big budgets, said Dr. C. Jeffrey Brinker, the
senior scientist who leads the Sandia research team. ``I wanted to
make it a power-to-the-people sort of thing,'' said Brinker, a
materials scientist who is also a professor at the University of
New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Nanotechnology researchers work on building objects that are 1
to 100 nanometers wide (a human hair is typically 10,000 nanometers
thick or less). To outsiders, they may seem to be trying to build
ships in a bottle, but their motivation is more practical.
</P>
<P>
   ``This work is going to pretty quickly come into the health
field,'' Brinker said. His intelligent ink could be used to build
blood analyzers that would be inexpensive enough for home use, he
added. ``You'd put a drop of blood in,'' Brinker said, ``and it
would be able to know everything about your body and send the
results by telemetry to your doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   The secret behind Brinker's ink is that his molecules behave
much like detergent molecules. While not exactly like the molecules
in a box of Tide, Brinker's silicon-based molecules share one basic
property: one part of each molecule loves water, while the other
hates it. ``They're schizophrenic,'' Brinker said.
</P>
<P>
   In a watery solution, the water-hating part of the molecule
immediately reacts by tucking itself into the center of the
molecule, as far from the water as it can get. That leaves the
water-loving part on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   When the solution containing such molecules is sprayed onto a
surface, the liquid evaporates, leaving the molecules locked into
their nanostructure pattern, connected by nanopores, which form
tiny channels. Such channels could provide a path for light to
follow in an optical computer chip or could function as optical
switches. Or they could provide sensor channels for sophisticated
chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Sandia, a Department of Energy laboratory operated by a
subsidiary of Lockheed Martin, may use Brinker's work to create
ultrasensitive sensors for detecting nerve gas and biological
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, Brinker could write out designs using a fountain pen
filled with self-assembling molecules, although the results would
be fairly crude. Instead, he first created patterns for the
nanochannel structures by using PowerPoint software on a personal
computer. He replaced the conventional ink cartridge on a
Hewlett-Packard printer with one holding the self-assembling
molecules in solution. The printer was modified so that it would
print Brinker's patterns on silicon wafers rather than on paper.
</P>
<P>
   The next step for Brinker's research will be to move up to a
color inkjet printer. While his solutions are not really inks, he
will be able to mix and match solutions of different molecules by
using an inkjet printer with four cartridges instead of one. Using
several solutions at a time will let Brinker create complex
structures with tiny pore channels of different sizes.
</P>
<P>
   But the most ambitious goal for Brinker and his printer is an
attempt to marry the biological and digital worlds. His team of
researchers is trying to use the water-loving and water-hating
parts of molecules to surround yeast cells; the entire assembly
could then be printed onto chips.
</P>
<P>
   The pores created by the molecules could be used to deliver food
to cells and whisk away their waste products. Such
biological-digital hybrids could one day be used as exquisitely
sensitive detectors for various molecules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could develop devices with lifelike properties, incredible
sensory abilities,'' Brinker said. While cells inside such gadgets
might live for only a few weeks, the ability to create inexpensive
replacements with printers would make that less of a concern, he
added.
</P>
<P>
   For those who may be inspired to do a little nanostructure
creation at home, a word of warning: Brinker believes that using
his intelligent ink voids all inkjet printer warranties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1704EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
