<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4581 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-BEETLE-BAILEY-HNS &LR;      05-24 0430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEETLE-BAILEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     U.S. ARMY HONORS CREATOR OF `BEETLE BAILEY' CARTOON 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. Army, often the butt of jokes by the
cartoon strip ``Beetle Bailey,'' awarded its top civilian honor
Wednesday to the cartoon strip's creator, Mort Walker.
</P>
<P>
   Army Secretary Louis Caldera bestowed on Walker the service's
decoration for distinguished civilian service and celebrated the
50th anniversary of the popular strip.
</P>
<P>
   Before presenting the award, Caldera said the cartoonist's
``ingenuity in portraying the Army in a humorous manner has
contributed to the morale of soldiers, past and present, throughout
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The award recognizes not only his comic view of the Army but
also his contributions to the military through the years,'' Caldera
said. ``We also want to recognize his distinguished service in
World War II and his support of the effort to build a World War II
Memorial on the National Mall in Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who said he was ``deeply honored'' by the award, asked,
``Who said the military doesn't have a sense of humor?''
</P>
<P>
   He said most of the strip's characters ``are based on real-life
people and experiences'' from his service days from 1943 to 1946.
``So I guess I also owe the Army a debt of gratitude for giving me
so much inspiration and fertile material to work with over the
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who lives in Stamford, Conn., and Boca Raton, Fla.,
started the cartoon strip in 1950. Beetle Bailey then was just a
college cut-up, but he stumbled into an Army recruiting station in
1951 and became a military cut-up.
</P>
<P>
   Circulation first began climbing when the Tokyo edition of the
Stars And Strips newspaper, which reports on military news, dropped
the cartoon because it supposedly encouraged a lack of respect for
officers. After the U.S. news media attacked the move, the Bailey
strip quickly added another 100 newspaper clients, according to
King Features, which syndicates the cartoon.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, when African-American Lt. Jack Flap appeared as a major
character with Bailey, some southern papers dropped the cartoon,
but, again, 100 more papers signed on, said Caludia Smith, a
spokeswoman for King Features.
</P>
<P>
   The strip's characters _ including Sarge, Gen. Halftrack, Zero
and Miss Buxley _ have inspired dozens of games, toys, puzzles and
greeting cards.
</P>
<P>
   The strip, which originally ran in 50 newspapers, is now
distributed by King Features, a part of the Hearst Corporation, to
more than 1,800 newspapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
