<SLUG> BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM'S NEW THINKPADS: THE LAPTOP BECOMES AN SUV 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By PETER H. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a world where nearly everything seems to be getting
miniaturized, the new IBM. Thinkpad T20 portable computer is
traveling in the other direction. If it were any larger, IBM could
have equipped this impressively redesigned laptop with folding legs
and offered it as a card table.
</P>
<P>
   It would be an expensive card table, to be sure, given that the
fastest model starts at about $4,000, not counting the broad array
of options that IBM. is offering for it. But hey, thanks to the
games built into the Windows operating system, this is a card table
that comes with its own game of solitaire.
</P>
<P>
   But in a neat bit of sleight-of-hand, IBM trumps the generous
proportions _ 12 inches by 10 inches, to accommodate a 14-inch
display screen _ by making the T20 surprisingly thin and light, at
about five pounds, including its DVD-ROM drive. And it is not even
the biggest or the most expensive of the new ThinkPads. That honor
goes to the ThinkPad A20p ($3,900), a high-performance portable for
the expense-account crowd, with a 15-inch screen that adds an inch
to the computer in both width and depth.
</P>
<P>
   Another model, the A20m, is aimed at a more budget-conscious
audience, with prices starting at $1,800.
</P>
<P>
   The T20 and A20p models have powerful Intel mobile Pentium III
microprocessors operating at 650 or 700 megahertz, making them
among the most powerful laptops on the planet. (The A20m comes in
models with either an Intel Celeron or Pentium III chip.)
</P>
<P>
   The new ThinkPads really ought to have been called ReThinkPads
because it is clear that in revamping and streamlining its entire
line of laptops, International Business Machines spent considerable
time rethinking the idea of the portable computing device.
</P>
<P>
   On one level the new models represent the next evolutionary step
in a venerable, popular and award-winning line of notebook and
laptop computers. On another level, however, IBM has recognized
better than most PC makers that a laptop is not just a desktop
computer that has been squeezed to fit into a briefcase and rigged
to run on batteries. Instead, it is a mobile information device
with peculiar requirements and capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the T20 that I tested has a new array of
color-coded buttons just above the keyboard that trigger specific
mobile applications, including a ThinkPad button that automatically
connects the user to an Internet-based service center, assuming the
laptop is connected to a network, of course. The idea is to harness
the power of the Internet to improve the overall experience of
working with the computer.
</P>
<P>
   The online services include animated demonstrations and a lot of
the reference materials that IBM left out of the rather
disappointing user's manual. There are also tips for maximizing
battery life, for adding and removing software features and even
for how to create a better PowerPoint presentation _ as if the
world needed more PowerPoint presentations.
</P>
<P>
   IBM has also created an online area where ThinkPad users can
share tips and experiences. The ThinkPad site has links to all
sorts of practical travel information, which is an unexpected but
logical step, considering that the ThinkPads are often used while
traveling.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how the average ThinkPad user will benefit from
tales of exotic computing adventures in Tibet or the polar regions,
or the knowledge that there are two million saunas in Finland, but
it shows that IBM is literally thinking outside the box _ thinking
about the customer, that is.
</P>
<P>
   Another example of this is in the keyboard design. The ThinkPad
keyboards were already the best of any laptops, but IBM has added a
feature called ThinkLight, which uses a subtle light-emitting diode
to illuminate the keyboard when the user is working in dark rooms
or airplanes. The glow from the screen itself illuminated the
keyboard almost as well as the ThinkLight, but the lighted keyboard
is indicative of IBM's attention to detail. It's the thought that
counts.
</P>
<P>
   Volume controls for the CD or DVD drive are also conveniently
placed on the keyboard, a feature not unique to ThinkPads but
executed well. Travelers like to use their laptops to listen to
audio CD's or to watch DVD movies. Besides controls to turn the
volume up and down, there is also a mute button.
</P>
<P>
   The ``T'' in T20 officially stands for ``thin' _ the model is
less than an inch and a half thick _ but it could also stand for
titanium, the strong, lightweight metal that is used along with
carbon-fiber-reinforced plastic in the body of both the T20 and
A20.
</P>
<P>
   The titanium composite shell armors the ThinkPads against two of
the laptop's natural enemies: clumsy handling and the unexpected
attack when the person in the airplane seat in front of you
suddenly reclines. Many laptop screens have been crushed to death
on airplanes, but the new ThinkPads are designed to be more
tolerant of rough handling than most.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the fact remains that the size of the new ThinkPads
makes them unsuited for use in the coach class of airplanes _ even
in the Exit row, which is where I tested the T20.
</P>
<P>
   While portability is the main reason that someone would spend so
much money for a computer, the new T20 and A20 ThinkPads are also
worthy of consideration as replacements for desktop computers,
especially when equipped with an optional docking station ($499) or
port replicator ($149).
</P>
<P>
   With these ThinkPads, IBM has introduced an Ultrabay 2000
expansion bay that allows the user to add an extra battery or a
variety of optional drives, including a DVD-ROM or CD-ROM drive or
an Imation SuperDisk 120-MB removable drive that doubles as a
floppy drive. The Ultrabay devices can be used with both the T and
A series laptops and with IBM's new line of NetVista desktop
computers.
</P>
<P>
   An UltraPort connector above the center of the ThinkPad screen
allows the integration of an optional USB digital camera (about
$100), which can be used for capturing quick still images or as a
simple video camera for videoconferencing. IBM says the UltraPort
will also be used for short-distance, wireless radio networking
technology called Bluetooth when a Bluetooth module becomes
available later this year. Bluetooth is expected to become a
standard for wireless connections to printers, cellular modems,
handheld computers and other devices, replacing cables.
</P>
<P>
   A Communications Bay on the bottom of the ThinkPads can be used
for a variety of connectivity options, supplementing the built-in
Ethernet and phone connectors.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of other specs, the T20 I tested came with 128 MB of
memory, 8 MB of video memory and an 11.2-gigabyte hard disk. The
lithium-ion battery ran about three and a half hours between
rechargings, which is impressive given the level of work it does.
It is more than sufficient for watching a DVD movie on the big (for
laptops, at least) screen.
</P>
<P>
   The screen has a maximum resolution of 1024 by 768, which
translates, depending on how you calculate pixels, to hundreds of
thousands of screen elements. So if just two of the pixels were bad
_ as they were on the machine I tested _ it would presumably be
hard to complain. But the two bad pixels manifested themselves
annoyingly as perpetually white dots in the center of the screen.
Laptop makers have varying standards on what constitutes a bad
screen, but generally two bad pixels are not enough to fail the
screen or warrant a replacement.
</P>
<P>
   The chip in the flagship 700-MHz-model T20, which is expected to
be available in about a month, will be modestly faster than the
650-MHz Pentiums, which until now were the fastest
portable-computer chips in the Windows world.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has made a big deal out of the SpeedStep technology in its
new Pentium portable chips, which operate at maximum speed when
connected to an external power source but ratchet down to a slower,
more energy-efficient speed when running on battery power. The
Apple Powerbook has had the same technology for years.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
