<HEADLINE>
DIVINITY SCHOOL GRADUATES SEARCH FOR THE PERFECT CHURCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TARA DOOLEY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Bennie Braddick is interviewing for a family
_ a church family.
</P>
<P>
   The recent divinity school graduate has begun a search that she
hopes will end not just in a job, but also a community of faith.
And although she soon may be weighing benefit packages,
congregation sizes and locations, she will ultimately rely on God
to lead her to the right church, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you just have a feeling, and you know whether or not
it's where you belong,'' Braddick said.
</P>
<P>
   For Braddick _ and all those who will collect ministerial
degrees this year _ job prospects are good. With clergy shortages
that verge on critical in some mainline Protestant denominations,
those entering church ministries often have choices.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble for some is finding the right fit, rather than any
fit at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the job market is very, very good for ministers,''
said Stephen Sprinkle, who teaches theology and helps graduates
find jobs. ``We are producing more ministers than we have ever
produced before, but we cannot meet the demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Brite Divinity School at Texas Christian University
in Fort Worth graduated 26 students. Nineteen of those students
plan to enter jobs in church ministry, Sprinkle said. Some already
have jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Across Fort Worth, Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary
graduated 387 students May 12. Dallas Theological Seminary awarded
189 degrees April 29, and Southern Methodist University's Perkins
School of Theology expects to confer 86 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Even with those numbers, opportunities abound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting the gifts of the people to match the jobs is tough,''
said Richard Faling of the Baptist General Convention of Texas, who
oversees the staff information service, a resource for job
candidates and church leaders. ``But there are a lot of jobs out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, many jobs are available for students willing to
move into small-town churches, seminary placement directors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had 100 people who wanted rural churches, I could plug
them in all over the place,'' said Bob Kaumeyer, director of
placement at Dallas Theological Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   About 80 percent of Kaumeyer's job-seekers already have a post,
he estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Some students enter the seminary with a job already lined up.
</P>
<P>
   Take David Mallory, pastor of First Christian Church of Albany,
Texas, a town of about 2,000 just east of Abilene.
</P>
<P>
   When Mallory was getting ready to leave his job as the
administrator of a Tyler clinic to attend Brite Divinity School,
the Albany church was looking for a part-time youth minister, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, I had the same qualms as everyone else,'' Mallory
said. ``I had no interest in going to West Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   But the church invited Mallory, his wife and two children out
for an interview. In pursuit of a weekend getaway, the Mallorys
accepted the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   And they decided to return.
</P>
<P>
   After Mallory served three months as youth minister, the pastor
resigned and the leadership called on Mallory to take the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be in a church where it is a good fit, where we can
do ministry together, where I like their style and they like my
style,'' Mallory said.
</P>
<P>
   The move to Albany has meant four years of driving 122 miles one
way to classes at Brite Divinity School. But Mallory will already
have a job when he completes his degree in December.
</P>
<P>
   Adjusting to life in a small town was not that hard, Mallory
said. Sure, fast-food restaurants were scarce, but his children
could play in the neighborhoods without fear and his wife easily
found work as an accountant.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd liked the Piney Woods'' Mallory said, referring to East
Texas. ``But we've realized that there really is a sunset, and
there is a sunrise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no intentions of coming here in the first place, but at
this point in time, I have no intentions of leaving.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding the right pastor/church fit sometimes requires that the
job applicant cast a wider net.
</P>
<P>
   For Howard Wayland, a recent graduate of Southwestern Baptist
Theological Seminary, the search for a place to found a church took
him from Florida to Oklahoma and finally to a job offer at Life Way
Baptist Fellowship in Atoka, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me and my wife picked all the states we would go to and prayed
about it,'' Wayland said. ``Tennessee was not one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   When Wayland, his wife and three children arrived, Life Way
Baptist Fellowship was nothing but an idea founded and funded by
the Tennessee Baptist Convention and First Baptist Church in
Covington, the nearest big town.
</P>
<P>
   Although familiar with small-town life from a stint living in
rural Arkansas, the Waylands grew up in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our case, we weren't going to an established church, and we
didn't know what to expect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Tennessee, the Waylands are surrounded by cotton and wheat
about 40 miles north of Memphis, Wayland said.
</P>
<P>
   Although they knew few people when they arrived in town, the
Waylands set to work building a congregation and community, Howard
Wayland said. They hosted fish fries, Bible studies and burger
dinners. Wayland prayed in each of the neighborhoods and knocked on
doors, introducing himself to the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a little harder for the children,'' Wayland said. ``...
It is hard for them to make friends, because they were new.''
</P>
<P>
   Matching pastor and pulpit is no easy feat for church leaders,
said Robert Montgomery, an elder at First Christian Church of
Albany, where Mallory is the pastor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this time of healing whatever the reason was that the
minister left,'' Montgomery said. ``Then you have a new
relationship to build, and that trust isn't just immediately
there.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mallory willing to move into the pulpit, the church leaders
knew they had someone who fit in with the ``personality'' of the
congregation, Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is kind of like a marriage,'' he said. ``There are only a
handful of people who are going to fit the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Braddick, 30, will soon move from Brite Divinity School to the
pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, she serves as a youth minister at a Christian Church
(Disciples of Christ) congregation in Longview, Texas. She will be
ordained in the denomination as a minister next week and hopes to
become pastor of a church with an average attendance of more than
100.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need help _ they need a spiritual link in their
lives,'' Braddick said. ``I want to be a part of that. I want to
help people live the best possible life they can.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, Braddick would like to find a post near a large city in
a church that has growth potential, she said. But that could lead
her away from the state she has called home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the scary part,'' said Braddick, who grew up in Port
Arthur. ``I don't know where I will go. I may not even stay in
Texas.'' .MDBR/.MDNM/ (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDNM/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1709EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0166 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4585 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ASTRONOMY-SIMULAT     05-24 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ASTRONOMY-SIMULATOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM GETTING A FASTER WAY TO DETECT WHEN STARS COLLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Computer-game players know that a graphics card is a necessity
to give a game a realistic look.
</P>
<P>
   Astrophysicists who study the behavior of globular star clusters
_ dense masses of a million or so stars that are scattered through
galaxies like so many lumps in a heap of mashed potatoes _ need a
graphics card of their own.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than shaping the contours of Lara Croft's face, their
card must calculate the gravitational interactions among all the
stars in the cluster. It is a daunting proposition. To make such a
calculation for any point in time requires on the order of a
million million individual operations.
</P>
<P>
   Such a card exists, and next week the astrophysicists at the
American Museum of Natural History in New York will receive the
latest version. Known as Grape6, the card is a specialized
processor that can perform only one kind of operation _ calculating
the gravitational attraction between two bodies. It can do this
work at a speed of about half a teraflop, or half a trillion
floating point operations, per second.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it among the faster computers in the world even
though, unlike a general-purpose computer, it is of no use to
anyone outside of astrophysics.
</P>
<P>
   Those limits are part of the machine's beauty, said one of its
designers, Piet Hut, a professor of astrophysics at the Institute
for Advanced Study in Princeton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it can do only one thing,'' Hut said, ``but it is
exactly the thing you want it to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Grape (which is short for ``gravity pipeline'') originated about
15 years ago, when Hut was hanging out, as he described it, with
computer scientists at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
One of the scientists, Gerald Sussman, had created a
special-purpose machine to calculate the evolution of the solar
system. Hut thought the same concept could be applied to star
clusters.
</P>
<P>
   But a computer used to calculate star clusters would need to be
much faster than a solar system machine (the solar system, after
all, only has 10 bodies, not a million, and at 4.5 billion years
old is less than half the age of the typical cluster).
</P>
<P>
   So with the help of a Japanese graduate student, Jun Makino, Hut
set out to design a special-purpose chip. ``It was a gravity card,
so to speak,'' he said, ``that would set Newtonian calculations in
silicon and let the data stream through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Their first board, developed like the others at the University
of Tokyo, had a peak speed of about 240 megaflops. They broke the
gigaflop barrier in 1991 with Grape3, and speed increases have
continued since.
</P>
<P>
   The Grape6 board that is being donated to the natural history
museum is among the first of several hundred that are being
produced by Toshiba. Sometime next year, about 200 boards will be
combined at the University of Tokyo to make a machine with a speed
of 200 teraflops.
</P>
<P>
   The museum has been promised computing time on that machine, but
in the meantime will use the board, which is about a foot square
and connects to a regular, though rather powerful, PC, in its
studies of what happens when stars in a cluster collide. (The board
is being donated during a conference on stellar collisions at the
museum's Rose Center for Earth and Space.)
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a million stars whizzing around, some of them
run into each other,'' said Michael Shara, curator and chairman of
the department of astrophysics. ``And near misses are just as
important as collisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the brute that it is, the board just provides raw data for
this kind of work. ``All the Grape does is let you calculate where
the star is, how fast it's moving,'' Shara said.
</P>
<P>
   From that data, it becomes clear that two stars will pass near
each other, or collide. ``Then you take a completely different
computer and study what happens to the stars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
