<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D.BIERSDORFER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I use Windows 98 and at times I have several windows open on
screen. Is there any simple way to close them all at once instead
of clicking the X on the window bar or repeatedly pressing Alt-F4?
</P>
<P>
   A. Although Macintosh users can close all open windows on screen
by pressing the Command-Option-W keys, Windows users do not have
such an easy time of it. As you have found, pressing Alt-F4 will
close each active window one at a time.
</P>
<P>
   To minimize everything that is open quickly, including open
programs and windows, press the Windows key and M on your keyboard.
Pressing Shift-Windows-M will undo the minimization. Another option
is to press Windows-D, which will minimize all the open windows and
reveal your desktop.
</P>
<P>
   There are at least a couple of shareware programs that will let
you close all the windows with a click of your mouse.
</P>
<P>
   If you are interested in a software solution, you might want to
try Closer, a $10 program that will let you maximize, minimize and
close all windows with one click on your taskbar. (Pressing
Control-Windows-Tab will let you jump from the Start menu through
the Quick Launch bar to the System Tray, and the left and right
arrow keys will then move you from item to item.) You can download
Closer at www.coolest.com.
</P>
<P>
   Another option, also named Closer, is freeware that can be
found &QC; at www.chat.ru/(tilde)anddch/closer.html.
</P>
<P>
   Keyboard shortcuts can save time and energy, and if you want to
learn more of them, search for ``keyboard shortcuts'' in your
system's Help feature, which you can get by pressing F1 on your
keyboard. You can also find a list of keyboard shortcuts in the
support area of Microsoft's Web site
(search.support.microsoft.com/kb), by searching for article No.
Q126449.
</P>
<P>
   Mac users can find a list of keyboard shortcuts by searching in
the Tech Info Library on Apple Computer's Web site
(til.info.apple.com) for ``keyboard shortcuts.'' A list of common
shortcuts can also be found in the Apple Guide, (the Mac's Help
file), which users can usually find under the question mark icon in
the Mac's menu bar or by pressing the Help key.
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I change the picture that appears on my screen when
the computer starts up?
</P>
<P>
   A. Adding a touch of personalization when you start your
computer is fairly simple to do for either a Windows or Macintosh
machine, as long as you save the picture file in the right format.
A Windows user needs to save the desired picture in the BMP
(bitmap) format so the system can read it, while a Mac owner should
save the files in the PICT format.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have image-editing software on your computer, many
shareware sites on the Web have sections devoted to alternative
start-up screens and graphic converter programs that will help you
get personal pictures into the right format for either platform.
</P>
<P>
   Windows users should first rename the existing Windows logo file
by typing Control-F to call up the Find utility and typing LOGO.SYS
in the Named box. The file should be in the C: drive, so click Find
Now. Once the file pops up, right-click on it, select Rename and
call it something different, like LOGO.OLD, to disable it. Find the
picture file that you want to use and change the size to 320 x 400
pixels, with 256 colors or less. Rename it LOGO.SYS and save it on
your hard drive (the default C: drive, in most cases), then reboot.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to change the screens that appear when you shut down
your computer _ ``Please wait while your computer shuts down'' and
``It's now safe to turn off your computer'' _ you can do that by
renaming the old files and replacing them with your new choices.
LOGOW.SYS is the ``Please wait'' screen, and the ``It is now safe''
message is LOGOS.SYS in the Windows folder.
</P>
<P>
   A Mac user who wants to change the start-up screen should change
the name of the desired PICT file to -StartupScreen (just one
word). Put that file into the System Folder and restart the Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 West 43rd
Street, New York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to
Q&AMP;A(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
