<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4590 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-CROSSGENDER-CHAT-     05-24 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CROSSGENDER-CHAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOYS WILL BE BOYS, AND SOMETIMES GIRLS, IN ONLINE COMMUNITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By BRUCE HEADLAM    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may be true, as a well-known cartoon in The New Yorker
claimed, that on the Internet, no one knows you are a dog. But
according to the first studies of gender switching on the Internet,
everyone probably has a pretty good idea of what kind of dog you
are.
</P>
<P>
   A study in the current issue of the journal Information,
Communication and Society said that 40 percent of participants in
online communities have engaged in some form of gender switching,
the practice of pretending to be someone of the opposite sex. Of
those, about half have given up the practice. The authors of the
study say the results show that gender switching is, in fact, far
less popular than some social scientists had claimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means that if someone tells you online that they're female,
they probably are,'' said Dr. Malcolm Parks, an associate professor
of speech communication at the University of Washington and a
co-author of the study. ``What we found was that gender switching
wasn't nearly as common a phenomenon as people had thought. Most of
the people we studied hadn't tried it, and those who did didn't do
it for very long.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, titled ``The Social Geography of Gender-Switching in
Virtual Environments on the Internet,'' surveyed 400 participants
in online communities called MOOs (multiuser object-oriented
systems). Sixty percent of participants in the study said they had
never engaged in gender switching online and had no intention of
doing so. Nineteen percent had previously dallied with gender
switching but had stopped. The remaining 21 percent were actively
posing as a person of the opposite sex at the time the study was
taken. But the majority of active gender switchers spent only about
10 percent of their online time disguised as the opposite sex.
</P>
<P>
   The figure that 40 percent of online users have masqueraded as
the opposite sex could strike many people as alarmingly high, not
low. Parks conceded that the results are up for interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can probably take these numbers several ways,''
Parks said. ``I don't find it remarkable that many people take
advantage of the Internet to experience life as the other gender.
It's just that it tends to be a temporary experience and not a
comment on their offline sexuality.''
</P>
<P>
   Gender switching became a popular topic because of what
academics and Internet commentators believed it said about
sexuality. For some Internet anthropologists, gender switching was
an example of how fluid the idea of identity has become in the
modern world. Some feminists saw it as another way of breaking down
socially constructed gender roles. At the other end of the
political spectrum, some critics of the Internet regarded the
practice as a threat that every 14-year-old online girlfriend is
really a 45-year-old ex-convict with three-day stubble.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the anecdotal evidence about gender switching, no
one had produced hard numbers, Parks said. ``I was skeptical of the
extreme speculation on all sides,'' he said. ``A lot of pundits had
talked about it, but nobody had done any research. We tried to get
a more systematic handle on what was really going on, rather than
just take part in an ill-informed debate.''
</P>
<P>
   To collect data, Parks and Lynne Roberts, a doctoral candidate
at the Curtin University of Technology in Australia, conducted two
random samples of participants in two MOOs, one dedicated to
socializing and the other to role-playing. They wrote to users by
e-mail, asking them to fill out a questionnaire on a protected Web
site. Parks said they sent out 2,200 requests and got 400
participants, a response rate of just under 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found that people tended to assume other sexual
identities for what Parks called ``benign reasons.'' The most
common reasons were that the respondents were in role-playing MOOs
or that they switched genders out of curiosity, for fun, to avoid
sexual harassment or as a challenge to their online acting skills.
</P>
<P>
   The most common reasons that respondents did not want to assume
other sexual identities were that they had no interest, that they
found the practice of gender switching to be deceitful and that
they wanted to present their real selves online. A reason given
slightly less often was doubt about being able to pull off the
ruse. ``It's a little like that line of Mark Twain's: It's always
easier to tell the truth, because you don't have to remember what
you said,'' Parks said.
</P>
<P>
   The most common reason for people to drop the practice of
switching sexual identities was that it stopped being interesting
or that their curiosity had been satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   The study also found little difference between those who
practiced what has been called ``online transvestism'' and those
who had not. Switchers and nonswitchers showed no significant
differences in the categories of shyness, extroversion or
neuroticism. The main predictors of switching seemed to be the
amount of time a person had spent in a MOO, but not the amount of
time spent on the Internet overall.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Haynes, a professor at the University of Texas at Dallas
who has studied and created MOOs, said she was not surprised by the
numbers. ``It is something people experiment with but do not
continue with,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Haynes, who met her husband at an educational MOO, said gender
switching received a disproportionate amount of attention because
of fears about pedophiles roaming chat rooms in disguise. ``I don't
dismiss that it happens in rare cases,'' she said, ``but that kind
of press misrepresents most people's experiences online.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Annette Markham, a professor of communication studies at
Virginia Tech in Blacksburg, Va., and the author of ``Life
Online,'' said the study may in fact overstate the phenomenon
because gender switching is currently in vogue. ``Whenever you are
asking people to respond via a survey,'' she said, ``you're going
to get mixed findings.''
</P>
<P>
   She agreed, however, that most gender switching is temporary.
``It's a popular belief that people get lost in their online
personas,'' she said. ``But that doesn't really hold up when you
really study what people are doing online. They have a lot more
balance than we think they do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
