A4601 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-HNS &LR;      05-24 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUSTICE OFFICIAL DENIES RENO PRESSURED HIM TO ABANDON PROBE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Contradicting the sworn testimony of an FBI agent,
a Justice Department prosecutor on Wednesday denied that Attorney
General Janet Reno had pushed him to abandon the federal
investigation of 1996 Democratic fundraising because her job might
be at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Career prosecutor Lee Radek, called before a Senate subcommittee
to explain remarks he made about the investigation during a 1996
meeting with FBI officials, told the panel that he didn't remember
the disputed conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Radek, chief of the Justice Department's Public Integrity
Section, headed the department's initial investigation into
allegations that President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore may
have violated campaign finance laws. During the investigation,
Clinton was still weighing whether he would retain Reno as attorney
general in his second term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have said that I got pressure from the attorney
general to do a thorough job, to do it vigorously and to do it well
but I would never have linked that pressure and my decision on the
investigation to the attorney general's job,'' Radek told a Senate
Judiciary Committee panel investigating 1996 campaign finances.
</P>
<P>
   Radek's comments differed sharply from testimony from FBI
Assistant Director Neil Gallagher, who also was present at the Dec.
6, 1996, meeting in the office of the FBI's then-deputy director,
William Esposito, to determine whether the FBI should be brought
into the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher told the panel that Radek made clear during the
meeting that the investigation was ``extremely sensitive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were comments that there was pressure on the Public
Integrity Section and that the pressure was because the attorney
general's job might be hanging in the balance,'' Gallagher said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he was sure of his memory, Gallagher
answered, ``Quite sure,'' and proceeded to describe where each man
was sitting during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Radek's disputed comments first came to light as part of a memo
by FBI Director Louis Freeh, turned over belatedly to Senate
investigators last week.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 memo included remarks from Esposito regarding the
department's campaign finance probe. In the memo, Freeh, who was
not at the meeting, recounted Esposito's description of Radek's
comments, saying ``that there was a lot of `pressure' on him ...
regarding this case because the attorney general's job might hang
in the balance (or words to that effect).''
</P>
<P>
   Freeh wrote the memo to Esposito after reportedly meeting with
Reno about the investigation. In the memo, Freeh said he told the
attorney general about Radek's comments and suggested ``on that
basis'' that she and Radek step aside from the probe.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the memo said that the Justice Department's Public
Integrity Section could not conduct a thorough investigation and
that the department should name aggressive outside investigators _
whom Freeh called ``junkyard dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., chairman of the subcommittee, read
the memo at the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Under lengthy questioning from Specter and other Republican
senators, Radek repeatedly said he could not ``remember'' the
meeting with Esposito but that he was ``sure'' he would not have
made the comments attributed to him.
</P>
<P>
   Following leaks of the memo last week, Reno said she never bowed
to political pressure. ``I call it like I see it, regardless of the
consequences. I've got a month-to-month lease on my apartment, and
I've been prepared to go home from the beginning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reno added that she did not recall Freeh briefing her on Radek's
purported remarks or ``talking about pressure because of the job.''
</P>
<P>
   In December 1997, Reno rejected the appointment of an
independent counsel to investigate fund-raising phone calls by
Clinton and Gore. Reno reached her conclusions after probing
allegations that campaign finance practices went awry in the 1996
race, including accusations that China tried to influence American
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Both the president and vice president were questioned under oath
about their fund-raising practices.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's case, Reno said investigators examined 68 donors
who they suspected could have been telephoned by the president.
Reno said investigators found only three instances in which Clinton
made fund-raising related calls.Twice he made thank-you calls. A
third involved solicitations, but those were made from the White
House residential quarters, which is not considered to be official
government property under a 114-year old law prohibiting officials
from soliciting contributions for their re-election campaigns from
federal offices. In Gore's case, investigators found that the vice
president had placed about 45 fund-raising calls from his White
House office. But Reno said Gore believed that each of the calls
was intended to raise money for general party purposes, known as
soft money. Reno said that Gore did not know that some of the money
was transferred into what are known as ``hard money'' accounts used
to pay for direct re-election efforts _ something Reno had said
previously might be illegal.  &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
