<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4602 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BILLBRYSON-INTERVIEW-     05-24 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLBRYSON-INTERVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S DANGEROUS DOWN UNDER _ AND DANGEROUSLY WELCOMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Bryson might just be the most popular unknown writer in
America. His wry, Everyman-in-over-his-head musings are savored in
much of the world, but the travel writer/humorist only recently
scaled the bestseller lists in his native land.
</P>
<P>
   After taking readers on tours of Europe (''Neither Here Nor
There,'') the United States (''The Lost Continent,'') England
(''Notes From a Small Island'') and the Appalachian Trail (''A Walk
in the Woods''), Bryson continues his wanderings in his latest
book, ``In a Sunburned Country'' (Broadway Books, $25), which
chronicles his meanderings through Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Like his previous books, this one (which arrives in bookstores
June 6) combines sharp-edged humor with history and more than a few
insights on ecology and endangered species. Bryson's challenge has
always been to strike a balance between entertaining and educating
his ever-growing ranks of fans, most of whom feel by the end of his
books that they are the author's close, personal friends.
</P>
<P>
   Bryson, 49, touched on many subjects in an early-morning phone
interview from his home in New Hampshire. Despite being jet-lagged
(he had returned from England the night before), he was quite
chatty, his unique hybrid Midwestern/British accent crackling
cheerfully over the wire. (Bryson spent much of his adult life
living in England before moving his family back to America five
years ago.)
</P>
<P>
   QUESTION: In the last few years, you've evolved from cult
favorite to bestselling author, especially with ``A Walk in the
Woods.'' Any idea why?
</P>
<P>
   BRYSON: It's tough for a writer to gauge, as opposed, say, to a
television celebrity. I mean, if you stopped 100 people in the
street, how many do you really suppose would know John Updike or
someone like that? I think it may be more a matter of travel
writing being a literary genre in America whose time has arrived.
Why it took so long, I don't know. Maybe Americans are traveling
more, getting away from the ``me''-obsessed '90s when they were
engrossed in piling up money.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, why did you pick Australia as the subject of the new
book?
</P>
<P>
   A: It began when I went there 10 years ago, to a literary
festival. I didn't expect to be drawn to Australia in any big way,
but it is absolutely a delightful country very few non-Australians
seem to know much about. It has a great climate, the people are
extraordinarily extroverted and welcoming, and Australia has all
this amazing stuff about it: natural wonders, barren deserts,
reefs.
</P>
<P>
   I really knew nothing about Australia before I went out for this
book. It is such an astonishment to be there and to look around, to
learn about its landscape and history and the problems presented to
people settling there. It was, and is, a hard, hard country to
conquer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Quite a bit of ``In a Sunburned Country'' concentrates on all
the things in Australia that can kill you, from snakes to
undertows. Did survival take up a lot of your attention?
</P>
<P>
   A: My first rule in Australia was to touch nothing. I was
careful to always stay on concrete. My thinking was, don't lean
your hand against a tree so something won't bite it. You have to
remain alert. But, really, the people there think of the snakes and
such things like I used to think of terrible storms when I lived in
the Midwest. Yes, these are things that can kill you, but you can
also go your whole life without running into one.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Despite the deserts and snakes and riptides, ``In a Sunburned
Country'' makes it clear you ended up loving Australia.
</P>
<P>
   A: You know, it is such an exotic place, and yet also familiar.
You drive out of the city and within minutes are in the middle of
totally alien, very fierce Death Valley-type stuff, where if you
get lost you could die within hours. Yet afterwards you drive back
into town, stay at a very normal motel, go to a pub or a restaurant
and eat steak and french fries, all familiar things. To me, exotic
and familiar at the same time is very appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Longtime readers might think there's less humor and more
education in this new book. Is that accurate?
</P>
<P>
   A: For the first couple of travel books I did, I was learning my
way as a writer. I felt, reading these books later on, that there
were perhaps too many jokes, that I was trying too much just to
make people laugh. I think people want something more solid amid
the frothiness. They want to put down a book feeling they learned
something as well as being entertained. And Australia was such a
fascinating subject in so many ways that I often found myself
getting sidetracked on some topic or another, to the point where
sometimes I lost interest altogether in making jokes. But I hope
there are still lots of places where people will laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Now that ``In a Sunburned Country'' is about to be published,
what book will you work on next? Or, should we say, what country is
next?
</P>
<P>
   A: I have a couple amorphous ideas, but they will have to wait.
The way publishing works these days is, you spend a year or 18
months researching a book, a year writing it, and a year on the
road selling it. For most of the next year, I will be promoting
``In a Sunburned Country.'' The year 2000 will not be productive
for me in terms of research and writing.
</P>
<P>
   But I'd like my next book to have a sort of ``whole Earth''
theme, taking our planet as a global entity. I want to view us as a
space alien would. You see, travel writers are always looking for
differences _ ``Here I am in France or China, and the people are
quite curious.'' Well, I believe all human beings, whatever their
nationality or race, would look essentially the same to a Martian.
We mostly have things in common. I would like to write about that.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
