<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4603 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BOOK-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      05-24 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHOP AROUND THE CORNER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Independent bookstore. Say it, and the words conjure up a dusty
place with a tumble of books, an owner with a passion and a small
staff with a love of literature and an uncommon knowledge of it, at
times even a snobbishness about what is considered good enough to
be displayed in the window, which of course fronts on a tree-lined
Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   Is this romance in book publishing over? Not quite, but at a
moment when there is a lot of continuing and justifiable
anxiousness over small, independent general bookstores being sucked
down one at a time in the whirlpool of the large chains, it would
seem quixotic, if not outlandish, to get into the independent
bookstore business.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in 1995 the American Booksellers Association, the
trade group of the independents and the small chains, had more than
5,500 members with about 7,000 stores; now it has 3,100 members and
4,000 locations. Mostly the disappearing stores have been X'd out
by the arrival in the neighborhood of a Barnes &AMP; Noble or Borders
store. (The sale of books on the Internet hasn't helped either.)
</P>
<P>
   But nonetheless Peter Greeman, 68, a retired advertising
executive, has bucked the trend _ a sort of bookish equivalent of
``man bites dog'' report _ and has purchased a barely surviving
independent in the New York City suburb of Larchmont. And while he
doesn't see this as an act of intellectual expiation _ ``it's
almost like a charity,'' he said _ he is pleased with what he has
done, and so, too, are his neighbors. So just why has he leaped
onto eroding terrain and bought Anderson's Book Shop?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a place in my heart for this particular bookstore,''
Greeman said. ``I grew up in Larchmont, and so did my father, and
the bookstore was there, and Mr. Anderson wrote my college
recommendation. I wanted to do Larchmont a favor. All my friends
and acquaintances bemoaned the fact that they thought it would go
under, and the store's manager,'' Annabelle Siegel, ``lives across
the street from me, and she's a dear friend.''
</P>
<P>
   If the book business is full of people cradled in the arms of
Morpheus, Greeman is confident he is not one of them. This new
entrepreneur said that that the man he purchased his store from,
Jim Miller, had owned it for 10 years and that it wasn't bankrupt.
Greeman added: ``Jim was making a living but didn't have much to
invest in the future. Maybe he thought there wasn't any future to
invest in in this business. I said to myself there can be
exceptions, particularly in a town like Larchmont where people like
to shop locally.'' Greeman said he planned to renovate the store
and increase its inventory from the 15,000 titles it has now to the
40,000 it had during its best years, a good percentage of the
accretion to be in children's books. And there won't be a coffee
shop in his store.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not this works commercially in the Darwinian world,
the salvaging of Anderson's Book Shop, although it is but one, is
celebrated by book publishers. Independent bookstores still have an
importance beyond the actual number of titles they sell. The best
marketing for books remains word-of-mouth passion, and often the
first mouths to send the word with fervor are the independent
bookstores, particularly for literary fiction and literary
nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   Independent bookstores ``are littered with people like Mr.
Greeman who have made them a second career,'' said Oren Teicher,
the CEO of the booksellers' association. ``They share a passion for
their product, which sets them apart from people who own drugstores
and hardware stores. They are teachers and librarians and
bankers.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Liebmann, director of independent bookselling for Random
House, explained: ``The indies are where lots of books start.
They're actively looking for books to fall in love with, and they
share that passion with their customers. They are tremendous
readers, and they can generate a lot of talk in the life of a book,
early on.''
</P>
<P>
   An example: Three weeks ago her department sent out several
hundred reading copies to independent bookstores of ``Driving Mr.
Albert'' (Dial Press), the true story by Michael Paterniti of the
transporting of Albert Einstein's brain in two Tupperware
containers in the trunk of a car in the 1990s from Princeton to
California. ``Within four days, it was read, and e-mails were
flying around the country, and suddenly there there was huge
excitement about a book nobody had heard of four weeks ago,''
Liebmann said. ``That chemistry can get a book started.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is scheduled to be in stores in July with a first
printing of 25,000 copies. It has already been sold to the movies.
</P>
<P>
   The independents are involved in their own sort of jihad against
the large chains and have a court case pending in California in
which they charge the chains with making special promotional
allowances and other deals with publishers. This in turn allows the
large chains to reduce their costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's axiomatic that this will drive small stores out of
business,'' Teicher said. Still, the association has made a
settlement with the publishers, all of whom now claim that the
playing field for independents and small chains has been leveled.
</P>
<P>
   Are things looking up for the independents? Perhaps. Their
association, which is holding its annual convention in Chicago next
month, reinstated at its last gathering its classes for people who
want to learn how to operate an independent bookstore. This year 45
people have signed up for the course.
</P>
<P>
   Greeman said he was confident that there was no commercial space
in Larchmont for a large chain branch, and that at any rate the
population (6,200 in the 1990 census) was too small.
</P>
<P>
   But across Westchester County from his store is the Mount Kisco
Book Co. in Mount Kisco, population 9,100. It was not just a store
that sold books and such but also a community gathering place so
popular that local residents banded together to bring it back from
a fire four years ago. A two-minute walk away is a shopping center
and a Borders. The Mount Kisco Book Co. will close on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
