</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Eat, drink, give them money
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee expects to set a one-day
fund-raising record, taking in about $25 million thanks in part to
unions, lobbyists and others with issues before the government. The
total will beat the Republicans' $21.5 million of last month. In a
preview of the gala at the MCI Center in Washington, President
Clinton thanked about 60 of the party's biggest donors for raising
the money that he said will put Al Gore and the Democrats on even
footing with the Republicans. Just a few blocks away, at the
Washington Convention Center tonight, the Republicans' expect to
bring in $11 million at their annual Senate-House dinner, topping
the $8 million raised at last year's affair. Helping to raise money
for the congressional Republicans will be Bob Dole, the party's
1996 presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   NO, NOT THAT KIND OF DISARMAMENT
</P>
<P>
   Responding on a Washington radio show today with something
between a chuckle and a snicker to the National Rifle Association's
recent declaration of war, Al Gore said he has ``no intention of
proposing or supporting policies or allowing policies that disarm
America.'' At last weekend's NRA convention, Charlton Heston lifted
a musket above his head and challenged Gore, saying the weapon
would have to be pried ``from my cold dead hands.'' Reminded by
NPR's Diane Rehm of that scene, Gore replied with a laugh that ``I
would not do what he accuses me of planning.'' Gore had racked up a
pro-gun voting record in his days in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   THE HIGH-TECH MONEY RACE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is trouncing Al Gore in the race for high-tech
donations, according to an independent group that tracks campaign
contributions. Between January 1999 and March 2000, Bush received
about $815,000, and Gore about $363,000 from the computer industry
and ``dot.coms'' that sell products and services, the nonpartisan,
Washington-based Center for Responsive Politics reported. Reform
Party contender Pat Buchanan received nearly $17,000.
</P>
<P>
   STEP ASIDE? NOT EXACTLY
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to media reports the past few days, Howard Phillips
says he's not offering to step aside as Constitution Party
presidential candidate in favor of Alan Keyes. This, according to a
party e-mail sent to media outlets. The Constitution Party is
wooing the Republican presidential candidate, who has vowed to
leave the GOP if it should choose a vice presidential candidate who
is pro-choice on the abortion issue. The Constitution Party,
formerly known as the U.S. Taxpayers Party, had opened its arms to
the former envoy to the United Nations, saying he could be
considered a running-mate for Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   INTERESTING FOOTSTEPS TO FOLLOW
</P>
<P>
   Idaho's four-term lieutenant governor won the Republican primary
and the right to run for the House seat held by ultraconservative
GOP Rep. Helen Chenoweth-Hage. Lt. Gov. Butch Otter, a millionaire
businessman, trounced Dennis Mansfield, who co-founded the
religious-right Idaho Family Forum with Chenoweth-Hage, 48-26
percent. Six other Republicans split the rest. Chenoweth-Hage, who
fulfilled a campaign pledge to retire after three terms, built her
career on opposition to big government and ``environmental
extremism.'' Her remarks after the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing were
viewed as sympathetic to militias. She also once claimed that
minorities don't like northern Idaho because it's too cold.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE RUNOFF IN ARKANSAS
</P>
<P>
   A crowded field of Arkansas Democrats hoping to challenge
embattled GOP Rep. Jay Dickey failed to produce an outright winner.
There'll be a runoff June 13. State Sen. Mike Ross drew 44 percent,
but second-place was less clear, with two candidates at 22 percent.
With 99 percent of precincts reporting, ex-TV reporter Dewayne
Graham had 20,838 votes, ex-state Rep. Judy Smith, who lost to
Dickey in 1998, had 20,288. A fourth candidate got 11 percent of
the vote. To avoid a runoff, the winner had to get more than 50
percent. Dickey was criticized earlier this year for telling black
farmers he could do little to help them because they didn't support
him politically.
</P>
<P>
   SAME GENDER, DIFFERENT RACES
</P>
<P>
   In Kentucky, state Rep. Eleanor Jordan defeated two candidates
to win the Democratic nomination to challenge two-term Republican
Rep. Anne Northup in a district that is 2-1 Democratic. Jordan, the
only black woman in the state Legislature, hopes to become
Kentucky's first black member of Congress. Northup had no primary
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   LET'S START THE FEUD!
</P>
<P>
   A Republican pro-abortion rights group, whose leadership
includes top backers of George W. Bush, is trying to turn the
abortion battle into a Bush family feud. ``Listen to your mama,''
says the punchline on a radio ad, noting that former first lady
Barbara Bush wants the GOP to drop the anti-abortion plank from its
national platform. The ad, produced by Republicans for Choice, will
run in Philadelphia, site of the Republican National Convention, as
the summer event draws near. Bush has said he favors maintaining
the GOP plank calling for a constitutional amendment banning
abortion, though it differs with his position that abortion should
be permitted in cases involving rape, incest or endangerment of the
mother's health.
</P>
<P>
   UNION CHIEF LOOKS AT NADER
</P>
<P>
   With the House approaching its hard-fought vote on granting
China permanent normal trade relations, one labor leader suggested
that the Green Party's Ralph Nader would be preferable to Al Gore.
By supporting the China bill, Gore is siding with ``multinational
corporations against workers here and abroad,'' said United Auto
Workers President Stephen Yokich. ``It's time to forget about party
labels and instead focus on supporting candidates ... who will take
a stand based on what is right, not what big money dictates.'' The
UAW had declined to choose between Gore and Democratic rival Bill
Bradley, and so far is not choosing between Gore and George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   SUBWAY RIDE TO RECOGNITION
</P>
<P>
   While Hillary Clinton attacked her new Senate opponent on gun
control and taxes, Rick Lazio rode the New York subway in search of
votes _ and name recognition. Lazio criticized Clinton for tooling
around in ``chauffeured limousines.'' ``This is the way most New
Yorkers travel,'' he said as he rode the No. 6 train uptown. Lazio
shook hands in Grand Central Terminal, then took the subway up to
East Harlem and went on a walking tour. ``Hi, I'm Rick Lazio. Hope
I can count on your support,'' he said over and over.
</P>
<P>
   ATTACKING THE MESSENGER
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to cost, mean-spirited verbiage and manipulation
by out-of-state interests, Michigan nay never have seen a race like
the current one for the Senate between the incumbent freshman
Republican, Spencer Abraham, and his Democratic challenger, Rep.
Debbie Stabenow. The contest, which could be crucial in deciding
control of the Senate next year, is so hot and tight that even the
latest poll, showing Stabenow taking a 4-point lead, has become an
issue. Abraham's take: The pollster, Edward Sarpolus, can't be
trusted because he once worked for some Democrats. Sarpolus' reply:
Most pollsters have done some work for candidates, and the senator
is being ``childish.''
</P>
<P>
   IS IT LISTED ON THEIR RESUMES?
</P>
<P>
   Top aides to members of Congress have long helped raise campaign
funds for their bosses, but
</P>
<P>
   their activity reportedly is intensifying. Interviews with more
than 20 House chiefs of staff by The Hill indicated that the
practice is widespread, even as many members employ full-time
fund-raising professionals. And for many chiefs of staff and
administrative assistants, it's one of the most common requirements
of their jobs _ but also the least discussed. They say they raise
campaign funds out of the office, and it usually doesn't occupy
more than 10 percent of their work schedule.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
