<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Nick Tate, Shane Harrison
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Binaural''
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Jam. Epic. 13 tracks
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Restrained. Cerebral. Experimental. Pearl Jam? Believe it.
Grunge's last men standing defy expectations on their sixth studio
album by turning down the volume and dropping the angry-youth
ranting that defined PJ's early '90s anti-pop. ``Binaural'' rarely
engages the white-hot fury unleashed on '97's ``Yield.'' Most
tracks cultivate a smoldering angst that never quite catches fire.
Prog-rock atmospherics and acoustic guitars enhance the mood as
Vedder's fog-cutter vocals ruminate on such grown-up concerns as
mortality, loss and Columbine. Nods to rockabilly
(``Breakerfall''), Eastern folk (``Of the Girl'') and art-rock
(``Nothing as It Seems'') may rankle fans hoping for another
``Evenflow.'' But ``Binaural'' should be recognized for what it is:
a natural evolution for a band that's outgrown the mosh pit.
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : www.fivehorizons.com/
</P>
<P>
   www.sonymusic.com/artists/PearlJam/
</P>
<P>
   Pearl Jam plays Aug. 7 at Philips Arena (tickets on sale June
24).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``Mystery White Boy''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Buckley. Columbia. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   The late Jeff Buckley was a mesmerizing live performer, and
``Mojo Pin'' and several other tracks make that clear. That magic
often eludes capture on tape, though. On a couple of tracks, his
usually powerful, free-flowing voice sounds tired. Leonard Cohen's
``Hallelujah,'' which was bone-chillingly beautiful on ``Grace,''
is particularly disappointing, even with the insertion of a snippet
of the Smiths' ``I Know It's Over.'' Get ``Grace'' for a fuller
understanding of what we lost when Buckley drowned in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : www.jeffbuckley.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``All Hands on the Bad One''
</P>
<P>
   Sleater-Kinney. Kill Rock Stars. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Sleater-Kinney offers a reminder of how beautiful simplicity can
be, getting maximum mileage from its guitar-drums-bass lineup. From
the pumped-up rant of ``Youth Decay'' to the sumptuous harmonies of
``Leave You Behind,'' the riot grrl survivors balance the abrasive
and the beautiful with punk-fueled precision. Five albums into
their career, these three women sound more excited about making
music than just about anyone with a record contract. They mean it,
man.
</P>
<P>
   Sleater-Kinney plays Saturday at the Echo Lounge.
</P>
<P>
   _Shane Harrison
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : www.killrockstars.com/bands
</P>
<P>
   /sleater-kinney
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
