<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-PEARL25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Best of three worlds turn out a soulful gem
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   This new collaboration between members of three super groups
puts incredible organic grooves first and lyrics, well _ who dances
to lyrics?
</P>
<P>
   Real cool hip-moving is the priority for Raphael Saadiq, front
man of one of the few successful R&AMP;B bands of the past two decades,
Tony Toni Tone. By his side are Dawn Robinson, the powerful singer
who neared Aretha Franklin's sassiness in model R&AMP;B quartet En
Vogue, and Ali Shaheed Muhammad, the smart beat provider for the
pioneering hip-hop act that melded rap and jazz, A Tribe Called
Quest.
</P>
<P>
   Not that those two weigh too heavily here.
</P>
<P>
   Saadiq's indelible, soulful and yet nasal voice makes this
melange of memorable hooks (``Dance Tonight'') and clear '70s Sly
Stone influences (``Every-day,'' ``Hollywood'') sound like one of
the better Tony albums. At other times it feels like an acid jazz
album by the Brand New Heavies that these three are just
guest-appearing on.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of which does much for creating an identity. But as for
a soundtrack to a Saturday get-together, you could do worse than
having this in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   'Lucy Pearl'
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Pearl / Pookie-Beyond / 15 tracks / Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Pearl will perform
</P>
<P>
   June 1 at Variety Playhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Lucy Pearl: www.lucypearl.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
