<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4609 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-STEAK25-COX     05-24 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-STEAK25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As summer cookout season gets under way, it's time to turn up
the heat to medium under a juicy, inch-thick steak for a royally
good time
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   By now, the grill has been pulled from its winter cover and
scrubbed. Some backyard chefs have already smoked theirs up a few
times, grilling ribs or burgers or maybe some fish.
</P>
<P>
   But Memorial Day weekend is the official coronation of the
grilling season, so it's time for the king of the grate _ the
steak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beef is still the meat of choice,'' said Tom Perini, author of
``Texas Cowboy Cooking'' (Time Life Books, $24.95). ``And if it's a
special occasion, then it's got to be steak.''
</P>
<P>
   Perini would be a bit partial. For 17 years, he's operated the
Perini Ranch Steakhouse in Buffalo Gap, Texas, which is about 15
miles south of Abilene. ``Just get on I-20 and head west,'' he
urged in a recent interview, as if driving halfway across the
country is nothing when there's a good steak waiting at the end of
the road.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, folks from Dallas often make the 3 1/2-hour trek to
Perini's ranch for his beef. He started as a rancher, developed
cooking skills operating chuckwagons for his crews and then quit
ranching and started cooking full time.
</P>
<P>
   His reputation sizzled as each steak was served. He's cooked for
Texas Gov. George W. Bush and taken his chuckwagon kitchen on the
road to special events across the country and across the ocean to
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   The secret to great steaks? Great meat, for starters. Perini
recommends USDA prime or choice meats for grilling. Prime is the
top grade, but ``choice is really fine for home cooks. That's (the
best possible grade) most will find in their grocery stores,''
Perini advised. Look for cuts of beef labeled USDA choice, which
are sometimes pre-packaged but often kept at the meat counters of
finer grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   Next, choose a cut that grills well. ``The sirloin is an
excellent family steak. You can cook two _ one at medium rare, one
at medium _ cut up and serve,'' Perini suggests. ``And the ribeye
is my personal favorite for grilling because of the marbling of
fat. Some marbling is important for flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Perini also recommends the porterhouse/T-bone cuts, both of
which have a loin and a tenderloin side separated by bone. (The
porterhouse will have a bit more meat on the tenderloin side than
the T-bone.) Perini doesn't like flank steaks or round steaks
because they demand some attention ahead of time (for marinating).
He prefers a quick rub and then to the grill.
</P>
<P>
   But for many, a marinated chuck, round or flank steak can be an
economical crowd pleaser. ``They can be very juicy or tender, but
they do require a different type of cooking than a ribeye or
loin,'' said Jennifer Dunn, nutritionist and spokeswoman for the
Georgia Beef Board. ``If you marinate them for 4 to 6 hours, it
will break down some of the connective tissue and make them more
tender. And they can be full of flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference in cost may be worth the extra effort. A quick
check of prices on webvan.com showed top round steaks and flank
steaks ranging from $3.77 a pound to $4.57 a pound. The cost for a
New York strip was $6.27 a pound and for a ribeye $6.87 a pound.
</P>
<P>
   Thickness also is important. Dunn did a master's degree research
project on how the thickness of steak affects cooking. She prefers
a 1-inch thickness; superthin steaks are likely to be overcooked,
and a very thick steak can take a while and be trickier to cook
evenly.
</P>
<P>
   The debates over charcoal, wood or gas apply to steak as to
anything else. Perini prefers wood, but no matter what's used, it's
important to start with an even heat that's fairly high so the meat
will sear. But not too high, unless you like black char on the
outside and cold meat in the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go with a medium-high heat. Place your hand 3 inches above the
coals. If you can keep it there five seconds without pulling back,
you're ready,'' said Dunn.
</P>
<P>
   Both Perini and Dunn warn that the most common mistake is
overcooking. ``When you start cooking a steak above medium, you are
in harm's way,'' said Perini. The harm, of course, is not a food
safety concern, but rather a flavor concern. Steaks cooked past
medium become tough and dry. Inside, we offer some tips for getting
it right _ but the best advice is to practice, practice. (A meat
thermometer can really eliminate the guesswork.)
</P>
<P>
   Pull the steak off the grill before it's perfect. ``If it's
perfect on the grill, then it will be overdone when you are ready
to eat it,'' Perini said. That's because of ``hangover heat,'' as
the cowboy describes it. The heat from the exterior is going to
continue to cook the interior. A steak can cook another five
degrees once it's pulled off the grill. So the final step _ and do
not overlook this _ is to let the steak rest five to 10 minutes
before serving. It completes cooking and allows the juices to come
together.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, we share Perini's steak rub, along with methods for
cooking several cuts of steaks and pairings with delicious
marinades, sauces, condiments and sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be afraid to grill steaks. Enjoy it,'' Perini urges.
``And always cook a little extra. Cold leftover steak is great for
sandwiches and salads.''
</P>
<P>
   THE FIVE SECRETS OF GREAT STEAK
</P>
<P>
   1. Buy prime- or choice-grade meats.
</P>
<P>
   2. Marinate tougher cuts.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cook over an even, medium-high heat.
</P>
<P>
   4. Pull steak off the heat just before it reaches desired
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   5. Let it rest 5 to 10 minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
