<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-EUROPEAN-PORCELAIN-AR     05-24 1265
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPEAN-PORCELAIN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
18TH-CENTURY ROCOCO A RAVE IN TECHNO-TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The young man, whose dapper mustache and
cream-colored Prada raincoat proclaimed him to be a seeker of the
most up-to-the-minute design truths, was transfixed. ``It's so
exciting,'' said David Kimelman, 22, a student at Pratt Institute.
``This is design based almost purely on body language. The paint
job is so beautiful, but the gestures are what's really cool.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't talking about any of the new furniture being
introduced this week at the International Contemporary Furniture
Fair, or the experiments in techno-gel, felt or polyester open cell
foam on show there. He was enthusiastic about a breakthrough of a
different order: 18th-century porcelain figurines.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of 8-inch figures elaborately costumed in gold-trimmed
waistcoats, floral dirndls and other exotic garb and flashing coy,
dimpled glances, mock surprise or drawn daggers were capering on
the tables at Moss, the SoHo design shop and purveyor of
avant-garde modernism. ``I was definitely taken aback when I first
saw them,'' Kimelman said. ``That was the best part.''
</P>
<P>
   In a gesture that could be interpreted as either the last straw
for minimalism or an inspired embrace of refined product design,
Murray Moss spread out several hundred pieces of porcelain, which
were conceived in the 18th century at the Nymphenburg factory in
Bavaria and remain in production.
</P>
<P>
   The pairing itself was provocative: Moss, the high priest of
modernist retailing, dressed as always to code in solid black and
white (``I haven't worn a pattern in years and years!''), and those
exquisitely high-priced rococo knickknacks favored by German
aristocrats for 250 years.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, about 200 design fans arrived at the opening of
Moss' paean to porcelain, ``White Gold, a Fragile Eccentricity.''
The exhibition, which also features contemporary works in porcelain
by Ted Muehling and Konstantin Grcic, will be on display through
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Muehling's Nymphenburg collection is on display at Bergdorf
Goodman, and the work of another designer, Bodo Sperlein, from
Germany, is being featured at Breukelen at 68 Gansevoort Street in
Greenwich Village. But only Moss is showcasing the classic
figurines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I surprise myself by liking them,'' said Robert LaValva, 36,
an architect, peering at a mincing masked harlequin figurine robed
in orange and yellow striped pajamas overlaid with black and blue
diamonds. ``They're so well crafted, so clearly from another era,
but also so timeless. The intense colors remind me of the Sistine
Chapel after it was cleaned.'' First produced in 1747, Nymphenburg
porcelains are not as famous or as collectible as those from
Meissen, an older and larger porcelain works in Germany. But from
the start, Nymphenburg's figurines, plates and table services have
been laboriously handmade, some pieces taking six weeks to
complete. Each ribboned bow is added with tweezers; each colored
glaze is fired separately at a different temperature.
</P>
<P>
   The Nymphenburg Porcelain Factory can claim one of the greatest
porcelain artists ever to have worked the complex mixture of china
clay, quartz and feldspar known as white gold: Franz Anton
Bustelli. He made porcelains for only eight years, until his death
in 1763, but it is his creations (in reproduction) that are being
celebrated at Moss.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was Nymphenburg's key modeler,'' said Jody Wilkie, head of
European ceramics and glass at Christie's. ``His figures are
wonderfully alive. There's a very distinctive elegance and
sophistication to Bustelli pieces. Once you've seen one, they pop
out at you as different from anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, $75,000 Bustelli originals and $2,900 newly painted
porcelain plates are not an easy sell in these days of mass
production and low, low price points. Besides, collecting figurines
is for ``a rather old-fashioned taste,'' as Wilkie put it. ``Every
time I organize a sale I wonder, Who am I going to find to buy this
stuff?'' she added, noting that 18th-century pieces rarely come on
the market.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, when Egbert Freiherr von Maltzahn took over as
president of the factory, he set out to woo a younger crowd. ``We
can't live anymore off the old aristocracy,'' he said, sipping a
glass of Champagne at the Moss opening. ``We have to find more
customers, like Gucci did.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, he started commissioning young designers, like
Muehling of New York and Grcic of Munich, to make their own designs
at the factory, which is on the grounds of the 17th-century
Nymphenburg Palace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked to see that these remarkably graceful things
were still in production,'' Muehling said. ``The part that isn't
kitschy'' is extraordinary, he added.
</P>
<P>
   After almost two years of learning, among other things, how to
shape a single egg that wouldn't collapse when baked at 2,500
degrees, Muehling has brought forth a 17-piece porcelain collection
with near-transparent shell-shaped dishes, spoons that look like
bleached, porous coral and blue oval vases so like eggs that they
might fool a robin. (They're available for $70 to $700).
</P>
<P>
   Nymphenburg's interest in such designers dovetails nicely with a
new generation discovering the handmade. Marcel Wanders, the Dutch
designer often associated with Droog, the hypermodern design
collaborative, said he wants to start working at Nymphenburg soon.
He blanched, however, when asked about the inherent conflict
between a royal factory created to serve the king's court and
modernism's high-tech, available-to-all agenda. Don't they cancel
each other out?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not coming from our generation!'' he said. ``Our
generation wants to do the full gamut, from plastic to handmade
porcelain.''
</P>
<P>
   As designers raised on injection-molded plastics start exploring
the incandescent beauty of things handmade, Moss is at the ready to
be their bald John Ruskin, the 19th-century aesthetician who
glorified English crafts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I miss in today's object culture is narrative, things
that have a story to tell,'' Moss said, as he showed a guest a back
room where his stock of Nymphenburg porcelains (white plates, $91;
commedia dell'arte figurine with ornately painted bodice and skirt,
$23,000) are stored draped in notes saying, ``Do not touch, or
die!''
</P>
<P>
   Moss explained his newfound passion for the porcelains: ``I
reached a point where I have things around me with no surface
decoration, no emotional qualities. It's all indestructible
stainless steel, carbon-fiber, techno-materials. I'm looking for
things with more humanity, things that are fragile and not so
replaceable. Why not have some things that if they broke you would
feel a personal loss? Why not own something that you love and that
if it weren't there you would be sad? We do it with people _ why
not with an object?''
</P>
<P>
   Von Maltzahn would be content to see his company's stagnant
sales climb. As the crowd threatened to overwhelm the plates spread
out as they once were for royalty along a long white lacquered
table at the center of Moss, the president of the Nymphenburg
porcelain factory remained sanguine. No matter that a figurine or a
plate, painted by an artisan free to express a flower or bee
slightly differently from the last, might not make it through the
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything breaks, it's OK,'' von Maltzahn said. ``They're
insured.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
