<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4611 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-STEAKRECIPES25-C     05-24 3254
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-STEAKRECIPES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Perfectly done steak a sizzling summer treat
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   How can you tell if a steak on the grill is done?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just make a little cut in it and peek,'' suggests Mumbo Jumbo
chef Shaun Doty. ``It's OK to do that. Really. Just don't make too
many cuts or it will end up looking like Freddy Krueger,'' he
advised, referring to the horror film character in ``Nightmare on
Elm Street.''
</P>
<P>
   His advice serves a larger purpose _ to remind home cooks to
relax and use a little common sense when grilling steak. Witness
the information on cooking times below. There are a number of ways
to tell, from exact (meat thermometer) to thereabouts (the thumb
test). Experiment with them all and see which way works best for
you.
</P>
<P>
   Same goes for the turning rule. Most recipes and directions
advise turning only once for all but the largest cuts. I probably
always turn twice, searing both sides and then moving the steak to
a bit lower heat to finish cooking. Works for me. You'll know what
works for you when you get the ``perfect'' steak by your standards.
The trick is to pay attention while you are grilling, and then jot
down what you did.
</P>
<P>
   We give you plenty of scrumptious steak ideas below to aid in
your summer research project. So get sizzling.
</P>
<P>
   How to tell if steak is done
</P>
<P>
   There's so much advice out there on how to tell if a steak is
``done,'' it's enough to make your brains sizzle. Seems the easiest
way is simply to get a meat thermometer _ 140 degrees for rare, 160
degrees for medium and 170 for well-done.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the steak will continue cooking for a few minutes after
it comes off the grill. I like to take the steak off when it
registers 145 degrees so that the final cooking temperature will be
about 150 degrees, somewhere between medium-rare and medium.
Instant-read meat thermometers can be picked up at most grocery
stores for just a few bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe you'd prefer a Therma-fork, which is a battery-operated
steak fork with a light that will read medium-rare, medium, etc. We
spotted them at Bed, Bath and Beyond for $9.99.
</P>
<P>
   Many experienced cooks can tell when the steak is ready by
touch. One guide is to touch your index finger to your thumb,
forming an O. Turn palm side up and, with a finger of your other
hand, feel the firmness of the thumb muscle by poking at the base
of the thumb. This is what a raw or barely cooked steak will feel
like.
</P>
<P>
   Now, touch the other three fingers to the thumb one at a time
and notice how the thumb muscle firms up. The middle finger is
rare, the ring finger is medium-rare and the pinkie is medium to
well-done. A rather inexact method, but one some pros swear by.
</P>
<P>
   Time charts also can be helpful, but they are only a guide.
Below, we provide the chart from Weber grills, found at
www.weberbbq.com. But as Weber points out, the guide is based on a
70-degree day with no wind. How often do we have those in Atlanta?
Certainly not in June. So that's why all cooking times on charts
are approximate.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, the time varies greatly, depending on the heat of
the grill. Try the hand test _ it's ready when you can leave your
hand 3 inches above the heat for 4-5 seconds before pulling away.
</P>
<P>
   Timely reminders for fixing your steak
</P>
<P>
   Cut Thickness/ Rare Medium Well-done
</P>
<P>
   Weight (140 degrees) (160 degrees) (170 degrees)
</P>
<P>
   Flank steak 1-1 1/2 inches 10-15 mins 15-19 mins
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. strip 1 inch 8-10 mins 10-12 mins 12-14 mins
</P>
<P>
   Porterhouse 1 inch 6-7 mins 7-9 mins 9-11 mins
</P>
<P>
   Ribeye 3/4 inch 5-7 mins 7-9 mins 9-11 mins
</P>
<P>
   T-bone 1 inch 6-7 mins 7-9 mins 9-11 mins
</P>
<P>
   Tenderloin 2 inches 15-17 mins 17-19 mins 19-22 mins
</P>
<P>
   Learning the cuts of steak
</P>
<P>
   Tom Perini, author of ``Texas Cowboy Cooking'' (TimeLife Books,
$24.95) offers this take on the different cuts of steak.
</P>
<P>
   Flank/London broil: A popular cut, but can be very fibrous and
tough if not properly prepared. It's best to marinate, to tenderize
and season. Better not cooked rare or well-done. Slice across the
grain.
</P>
<P>
   T-bone/porterhouse: A classic cut of steak that's a little like
having two steaks in one. There's a bone running down the middle,
and on one side you have the strip and on the other the filet.
There is some fat and flavor around the bone, while the steaks
themselves are lean. Look for a good 1 1/2 inch thickness.
</P>
<P>
   Strip/top loin: The strip is a lean cut from the top loin that's
quite popular. Because it has less marbling, it also can have less
flavor. A great choice for those watching fat content. Usually sold
an inch thick or more.
</P>
<P>
   Sirloin: A larger cut of steak with wonderful flavor because the
bone is in. Cooks nicely on the grill, then can be divided into
smaller servings or sliced, so it's nice for a family.
</P>
<P>
   Ribeye: A cut with quite a bit of marbling (and Perini's
favorite for the grill). It's really the same cut as the prime rib,
only it's cut into steak for the grill (instead of roasted and
sliced). The marbling gives flavor and tenderness.
</P>
<P>
   Tenderloin/filet mignon: Cut from the tenderloin, the filet is
the leanest cut of meat. It takes a little longer to cook because
it's the thickest cut. Because of the leaness, it can lack flavor,
which is why they are often wrapped in bacon. For cooking
medium-well or well-done, butterfly the steak first.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN-DISH SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Beef and Romaine Salad With Blue Cheese and Anchovy Dressing
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Steak and blue cheese have a surprisingly wonderful affinity for
each other; the tart greens and tomatoes help cut their richness. A
great way to use up leftover steak, it's also impressive enough to
serve for company.
</P>
<P>
   For the dressing:
</P>
<P>
   1 garlic clove
</P>
<P>
   4 anchovy fillets
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red wine vinegar or balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh oregano or 1 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   For the salad:
</P>
<P>
   1 large head romaine lettuce, washed, outer bruised leaves
removed and discarded, remaining leaves torn into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   2 vine-ripened tomatoes, cut lengthwise into wedges
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces blue cheese, such as Danish blue, Maytag blue or
Roquefort, crumbled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 to 1 pound cooked steak or roast beef, cut into
1/4-inch-by-1-inch-wide strips
</P>
<P>
   Chopped chives or green onions
</P>
<P>
   To make the dressing: Put garlic and anchovies in a food
processor and process to a paste. Add mustard, vinegar, oregano and
pepper. With the motor running, pour the oil through the feed tube
to make a creamy dressing.
</P>
<P>
   For the salad: Pour dressing over the romaine and tomatoes and
toss with the cheese to coat the leaves. Lay the beef strips on top
and garnish with chives or green onions; serve. _ From: ``The
Complete Meat Cookbook'' by Bruce Aidells and Denis Kelly (Houghton
Mifflin, 1998)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 244 calories, 15 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 70), 4 grams carbohydrates, 39
milligrams cholesterol, 422 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Bloody Mary London Broil
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 15 minutes Marinating time:
30 minutes Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Although usually flank steak, the term London broil can be used
for any thin cut of meat that is broiled or grilled and sliced on
the diagonal, or bias.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups tomato juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Worcestershire sauce
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons prepared commercial horseradish
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons dry sherry, vodka or pepper vodka
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons crumbled dried marjoram
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon crumbled dried basil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   3 1/2 pounds London broil, about 1 1/2 inches thick, trimmed
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   Stir together tomato juice, Worcestershire sauce, horseradish,
sherry, marjoram, basil and pepper in a small bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Place steak in a single layer in a glass or ceramic dish. Spoon
the tomato juice mixture over the meat, spreading to cover. Turn
the meat to coat the other side. Cover and refrigerate at least 2
hours or set aside at room temperature for no longer than 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare a charcoal or gas grill. Lightly spray the grill rack
with vegetable oil cooking spray. The coals should be moderately
hot to hot.
</P>
<P>
   Lift the meat from the marinade. Discard the marinade. Grill the
steak for 8 minutes. Turn the steak and grill for 7 to 10 minutes
longer for medium-rare, or until it reaches desired doneness.
</P>
<P>
   Let the steak rest at room temperature for about 5 minutes
before slicing on the diagonal into thin strips. _ From: ``Prime
Time: The Lobels' Guide to Great Grilled Meats'' by Evan, Leon,
Stanley and Mark Lobel (MacMillan, 1999)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 359 calories, 54 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 34), 1 gram carbohydrates, 144
milligrams cholesterol, 187 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Steak Fiorentina
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 8 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This T-bone put Florence, Italy, on the steak map. For the
authentic taste, a fire of wood and vine cuttings is best; charcoal
will do; gas is out. In Italy, this steak is usually served in
solitary splendor, with only bread at hand for mopping up the
juices.
</P>
<P>
   4 T-bone steaks (about 12 ounces each), cut 3/4 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 lemons, each cut into 8 wedges
</P>
<P>
   Remove steaks from the refrigerator and allow them to come to
room temperature. Trim any excess fat, pat dry and coat lightly
with olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat grill or prepare a hot charcoal fire.
</P>
<P>
   Place steaks on grill.
</P>
<P>
   Cook to sear one side, 2 minutes. Turn and season the cooked
side with salt and pepper. Sear the second side for 3 minutes.
Turn, season the second side with salt and pepper and continue
cooking until the steak is well-crusted and medium-rare, about 3
minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   (A Tuscan never would cook Fiorentina to medium, but if you
must, lengthen the final stage to 4 or 5 minutes.)
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the steaks to large plates or platters, garnish with
lemon wedges and serve. _ From: ``Steak Lover's Cookbook'' by
William Rice (Workman, 1997)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 443 calories, 58 grams protein, 21 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 43), 1 gram carbohydrates, 155
milligrams cholesterol, 127 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Giant Porterhouse With Sherry-Shallot Vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time:
14-16 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Garlic, sherry and shallots combine for a lovely steak sauce
that's great on grilled veggies, too.
</P>
<P>
   2 porterhouse steaks (about 1 1/2 pounds each), cut 1 1/2-inches
thick
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   2 shallots, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons sherry vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the coals for grilling.
</P>
<P>
   Allow the steaks to come to room temperature; pat dry and coat
both sides with olive oil. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the mustard, shallots and garlic in a small bowl. Whisk
in the sherry and the sherry vinegar. Pouring slowly, whisk the oil
into the shallot mixture. Season with salt and pepper and set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   When the fire is hot enough for you to hold your hand at grill
level for only 5 seconds, place the steak on the grill and sear one
side until nicely browned, about 3 minutes. Turn and sear the
second side for 3 minutes. Move the steak, to keep the tenderloin
away from the most intense heat, cover the grill and cook for 3
minutes. Then turn and move the steak again. Season the steak with
salt and cover the grill. Cook for 3 minutes, turn it, season with
salt. Cook, covered, for 2 minutes more for medium-rare or 5
minutes more for medium.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer to a cutting board and let the steak rest for 5
minutes. Remove the bone and carve the meat into 3/4-inch-thick
slices. Stir the sauce and, if desired, heat it briefly in the
microwave. Divide the meat among warm plates, spoon the sauce over
and serve. _ From: ``Steak Lover's Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 578 calories, 34 grams protein, 48 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 75), 1 gram carbohydrates, 133
milligrams cholesterol, 120 milligrams sodium, less than 1 gram
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Balsamic-Glazed
</P>
<P>
   Strip Steak
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Marinating/standing time: at least 3 hours
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   There are debates about whether to salt a steak before or after
cooking. The concern is that salt can drain the juices from the
meat. Here, the salt comes at the end of cooking. But most chefs we
asked said it's OK to salt ahead, but just a moment before the meat
goes on the grill.
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 plump garlic cloves, chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 (14- to 16-ounce) strip steaks, about 1 1/2 inches thick, at
least choice grade
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt or other coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Sprigs of fresh herbs such as rosemary, sage, thyme or parsley,
for garnish
</P>
<P>
   At least 2 1/2 hours and up to 6 hours before you grill the
steaks, combine vinegar, oil and garlic in a medium bowl. Place
steaks in a plastic bag or shallow dish, pour marinade over them
and refrigerate. Turn occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   Fire up the grill for a two-level fire capable of cooking first
on high heat (1 to 2 seconds with the hand test), then on medium
heat (4 to 5 seconds with the hand test). Remove steaks from
refrigerator and drain, straining the marinade into a small,
nonreactive saucepan. Let the steaks sit uncovered at room
temperature for 30 minutes. Bring marinade to a boil over
medium-high heat and boil vigorously until reduced to 1/2 cup
syrupy glaze. Blot the steaks and sprinkle both sides with salt and
pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Grill steaks uncovered over high heat for 2 1/2 to 3 minutes per
side. Move the steaks to medium heat, turning them again, and
continue grilling for 2 1/2 to 3 minutes per side for medium-rare.
The steaks should be turned a minimum of three times, more often if
juice begins to form on the surface. Brush the steaks with the
glaze in the last few minutes of cooking on each side. If grilling
covered, sear both sides of the meat first on high heat uncovered
for 2 1/2 to 3 minutes; finish cooking with the cover on over
medium heat for 5 to 6 minutes, turning the steaks once midway.
Brush the steaks with glaze when you turn them and again when they
come off the grill. Serve the steaks hot, garnished with herbs. _
From: ``Born to Grill: An American Celebration'' by Cheryl Alters
Jamison and Bill Jamison (Harvard Common Press, 1998)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 406 calories, 23 grams protein, 34 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 75), 1 gram carbohydrates, 93
milligrams cholesterol, 60 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Grilled Sirloin Steak
</P>
<P>
   With Green Chili Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Marinating time: 1 hour to overnight
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 1 hour, total
</P>
<P>
   A sirloin is a crowd-pleaser, and this sauce really gives it
some zip.
</P>
<P>
   For the steak:
</P>
<P>
   3 3/4 to 4 pounds boneless sirloin, about 2 inches thick
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon crushed cumin seed
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   For the sauce:
</P>
<P>
   6 fresh Anaheim green chiles
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon canola oil
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, halved and thinly sliced crosswise
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the steak: Trim the outer fat from the steak, or ask
the butcher to do so. Rub entire surface of the meat with olive
oil. In a small bowl, combine the cumin, oregano, thyme, garlic,
salt and pepper. Using your fingers, rub evenly on both sides of
the steak and place the steak in a shallow glass or ceramic dish.
Cover and refrigerate for at least 1 hour or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the sauce: Prepare a charcoal or gas grill or preheat
the broiler. If using a grill, the coals should be moderately hot.
</P>
<P>
   Set the chiles over the heat or under the broiler and grill or
broil for about 5 minutes on each side until lightly charred and
fragrant.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from the grill or broiler and set aside in a paper bag or
cover with paper towels to cool.
</P>
<P>
   When cool enough to handle, peel the skin using your fingers or
a dull knife. (Do not peel the chiles under running water or their
flavor will be diluted.) Cut off and discard the stems and caps.
Slit the chiles, scrape out the seeds (don't worry if a few remain)
and slice the chiles. You will have about 1 cup of chiles.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prepare a charcoal or gas grill for the steak.
Lightly spray the grill rack with vegetable oil cooking spray. The
coals should be moderately hot to hot.
</P>
<P>
   Heat canola oil in a skillet over medium heat. Add the onion and
garlic and cook, stirring, for about 5 minutes, or until the onions
are softened.
</P>
<P>
   Add the chiles and cook for 3 to 4 mintues longer, or until
fragrant.
</P>
<P>
   Increase heat to medium-high and add the half-and-half. Cook,
stirring, for about 10 minutes, or until the sauce is reduced by
half. Cover and set aside to keep warm while grilling the steak.
</P>
<P>
   Grill the steak for 10 to 12 minutes. Turn and grill for 10 to
12 minutes longer for medium-rare, or until it reaches desired
degree of doneness. Let the meat rest for a few minutes before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   Set the pan with the sauce over low heat.
</P>
<P>
   Add the cream cheese and stir until smooth. Stir in the sour
cream and season with salt.
</P>
<P>
   While stirring, heat the sauce just until hot. Do not let the
sauce boil. Serve immediately with the steak. _ From: ``Prime Time:
The Lobels' Guide to Great Grilled Meats'' by Evan, Leon, Stanley
and Mark Lobel (MacMillan, 1999)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 547 calories, 60 grams protein, 30 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 49), 7 grams carbohydrates, 194
milligrams cholesterol, 170 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   CONDIMENT
</P>
<P>
   Perini Ranch Steak Rub
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 1/4 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Tom Perini, author of ``Texas Cowboy Cooking'' (TimeLife Books,
$24.95) calls this his ``magic dust.'' We tried it on his favorite
_ the ribeye _ and thought it delivered a robust black pepper
flavor. The ribeye, by the way, was a prime cut from Star
Provisions that was about $17 a pound. It was probably the most
tender and flavorful steak I've ever eaten. We had plenty of rub
left over for future steaks. (Keep extra in a plastic baggie in the
freezer.)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon cornstarch or flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup coarsely ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon granulated beef stock
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the cornstarch, salt, black pepper, oregano, garlic
powder, paprika and beef stock. Either sprinkle on or rub into the
meat.
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 15 calories, 1 gram protein, trace fat (percent
calories from fat, less than 5), 4 grams carbohydrates, trace
cholesterol, 362 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
