<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-HOLLOW25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Hollow' filled with shivery fun
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heads up: Tim Burton is back. The director's latest is a blend
of scary swordplay, witchcraft and self-spoofing humor served with
tongue planted firmly in cheek.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Depp is geekily effective as Ichabod Crane, who's sent to
investigate a series of beheadings in 1799 Sleepy Hollow. But the
real star is the extraordinary art design; most of the movie was
shot on London sound stages. The movie's steady comic relief is a
useful balance for the Headless Horseman's single-minded attacks,
which spare no one.The DVD ($29.99) includes wide-screen
presentation and Burton's amiable, giggly commentary; you won't
learn a whole lot from his comments, except how much he loved the
old Hammer horror flicks.
</P>
<P>
   `Sleepy Hollow'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray writes for the Atlatna Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More about ``Sleepy Hollow'' and other
headless ghosts: www.webhost.avint.net
</P>
<P>
   /hardticket/sleepy.htm
</P>
<P>
   OTHER RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Mighty Peking Man'' (PG-3) _ This cheesy 1977 Hong Kong
``King Kong'' knockoff is a delirious, nonstop 90 minutes of
no-budget camp. In this '70s spectacle of lousy special effects and
howlingly rotten dialogue, the putative star is the guy wearing the
ratty ape suit, but Evelyne Kraft steals the movie. As Peking Man's
nature-girl protector Ah Wei, she's a dumb blonde whose
nearly-not-there costume made of animal skins is itself worth
renting the tape for. Awesomely awful! Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For links to ``Mighty Peking Man'':
www.starseeker.com/films/1999film/mightype.htm
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``American Movie'' (R) _ Meet the man who's the Ed Wood of
independent filmmakers. Chris Smith's documentary is alternately
hilarious and horrifying as it chronicles Mark Borchardt's attempts
to make his autobiographical magnum opus, ``Northwestern.'' The
30-ish Borchardt _ a high school dropout with three kids who still
lives with his mother _ is a portrait of the artist as a
not-so-young, incredibly selfish film geek. The movie never
comments on Borchardt's choices; it simply records them. Which
makes ``American Movie'' funny, scary and as compulsively watchable
as a train wreck. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Eye of the Beholder'' (R) _ Boredom, like beauty, is in the
eye of the be-holder. What begins as a hypnotic riff on the
surveillance classic ``The Conversation'' ultimately veers off into
nowhere. Too bad, because the film is as stylishly acted as it is
directed. An isolated British surveillance agent (Ewan McGregor)
be-comes more involved than he intended in the case of a diplomat's
son and a mysterious femme fatale (Ashley Judd). Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Source'' (unrated) _ This impressionistic look at the
Beat is best appreciated by those already in the know. Chuck
Workman's film documents how the Beat poets changed not only the
way America wrote, but the way we lived, with their works ``On the
Road,'' ``Howl'' and ``Naked Lunch.'' But as the film be-bops from
film clip to dramatic reading to off-the-cuff quote, its jazzy,
improvisational approach becomes wearying. (Priced to buy: $19.98
VHS, $24.98 DVD.) Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Train of Life'' (R) _ Another wish-fulfillment comedy with a
Holocaust theme. In 1941, some Eastern European Jews decide to beat
the Nazis at their own game. They create a train and stage their
own deportation, fooling the Nazis into thinking they're headed for
a concentration camp. The cast overacts, and much of the plot is
worthy of a ``Hogan's Heroes'' episode. But the premise is
inventive, and there's a kick-in-the-gut coda that makes up for
much that went before. In French with subtitles. Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   _Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
</P>
<P>
   DVD SPOTLIGHT
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Blue Velvet'' (R). There's no commentary or special goodies
on David Lynch's bloody 1986 classic. But the new release presents
the psychosexual thriller in its original wide-screen format,
restoring the full effect of Lynch's creepy compositions,
previously butchered by the pan-and-scan format. Suggested retail
price: $24.98.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For DVD release dates:
www.reel.com/reel.asp?node &QC; dvd/comingsoon
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
