<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4613 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-RINGEL25-COX     05-24 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to relive school days, painlessly
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Diplomas and proms. Caps and gowns. Smells like teen spirit to
me. There's nothing like the end-of-school days to bring out the
nostalgia _ the fear and loathing? _ in anyone who's been through
it or is going through it. Here are some films that may bring it
all back _ from a safe distance.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Carrie'' (1976): The prom-night movie. Sissy Spacek, buckets
of blood, flying sharp objects, a pre-breakthrough John Travolta.
Plus a whammy of a finale that's been ripped off so many times
since that it's gone from gimmick to classic movie moment.
``Carrie'' itself went through a similar transformation, from
slightly trashy horror flick to cultural phenomenon. Both Spacek
and Piper Laurie, who plays her spacey mother, earned Oscar
nominations. The film grossed 15 times what it cost, earning
director Brian De Palma a place as a Hollywood contender. Which, in
another context, was the first step in a long road leading to last
spring's abyssmal ``Mission to Mars.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Prom Night'' (1980): The other prom-night movie ... sort of.
Well, not really. Actually, it's just one of a dozen or so splatter
movies that drenched theaters in the early '80s. Riding the crest
of her newfound scream-queen fame as the star of ``Halloween,''
Jamie Lee Curtis once again let herself get chased around by a mad
slasher. The climax _ on prom night, natch _ has everything from
Jamie Lee doing a Travolta imitation to a decapitated head rolling
on the dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``American Graffiti'' (1973): George Lucas' movie has
virtually become synonymous with senior year swan songs. The year
is 1962; the place, small-town California. The streets are filled
with cruising teens. Among them: Ron Howard, Cindy Williams,
Richard Dreyfus, Candy Clark, Paul Le Mat, Charles Martin Smith,
McKenzie Phillips and, in a small role, Harrison Ford. The film's
tone is one of unabashed nostalgia and affection _ a kind of
willfully blinkered innocence that, hitting theaters in the
not-so-innocent early '70s, captivated audiences and critics. It
still does.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``If ... '' (1968): Lindsay Anderson's explosive film captures
the anti-authoritarian spirit of the late '60s with breathtaking
ease. Malcolm McDowell _ soon to become an emblem of disaffected
youth in Stanley Kubrick's ``A Clockwork Orange'' _ leads some
fellow British schoolboys in a revolt against the system as
embodied by the power structure at a tony boarding school. Their
actions move from antic to all-out anarchy, culminating in an
end-of-term massacre that, in light of Columbine and its ilk, seems
eerily prescient. The difference is, Anderson's characters are
acting out a kid revolutionary's fantasy engendered by a moralistic
anger. Sort of, flower power packing heat. ``If . . . '' is about
bucking the system _ the system as it existed in the '60s; it's not
an endorsement of personal revenge scenarios. Still, the resonances
are unavoidable and disturbing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dazed and Confused'' (1993): Set on the last day of school
in 1976, Richard Linklater's movie isn't about graduation per se,
but about the agendas, rituals and mega reefer use of two distinct
groups of students: the fresh-out-of-junior-high kids who will be
freshmen the next fall and the soon-to-be-seniors of the class of
'77 who plan to make their lives hell. Like a toked-up ``American
Graffiti,'' the picture follows an amazing assortment of characters
and, like the Lucas film, it has a kind of strange innocence.
Mostly, it just lets us hang out in the ultimate hang-out decade.
When one young idealist declares that the '80s will be
``radical!!,'' it's very funny. And somehow very sad.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For a comprehensive analysis of ``American
Graffiti'': www.filmsite.org/amerg.html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
