<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4614 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATIONS     05-24 1609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATIONS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHOPPING DESTINATION: Parrott
 &HT;    Take it easy in town where `past meets present'
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARROTT, Ga. _ If you find yourself in this speck-on-the-map
town off Ga. 520 between Columbus and Albany, you'll swear you just
stumbled onto an 1890s movie set of the Old West.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome, partner. You're in Parrott, population 186.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, ``The Long Riders'' _ the film based on the
exploits of the Jesse James gang _ was shot in this sleepy hamlet,
featuring the acting brothers Quaid (Randy and Dennis), Carradine
(David, Keith and Robert), Guest (Christopher and Nicholas) and
Keach (Stacey and James).
</P>
<P>
   Parrott, named for John Lawson Parrott, a Confederate veteran,
planter and businessman, was chosen as one of the sets because
nothing had changed since the town's founding in 1889. This
included the blood-red brick buildings with tin roofs, the raised
sidewalks, the wooden train depot and the dirt streets.
</P>
<P>
   Today, after much restoration, the turn-of-the-century
drugstores, cotton warehouses, banks and grocery stores have
morphed into 17 antique shops, restaurants and art galleries. The
streets are paved. Petunias and geraniums grow in baskets and the
tiny town in Terrell County is now living up to its slogan ``where
the past meets present.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most intriguing shops in this easygoing town about
155 miles from Atlanta is Sound Play, featuring musical
``playscapes.'' Owner Bond Andersen designs and builds permanent
outdoor installations of tuned musical instruments. His playscapes
and sound sculptures are found in parks, museums, back yards and on
school grounds, including the Greater Atlanta Christian School in
Norcross, Webb Bridge Park in Alpharetta and Holy Innocents School
in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Other stores _ Mollie Jane's, Dunn Roam'n, James Bridges, the
Mint Julep _ are must stops for antique lovers, while Small Wonders
features dolls, doll houses and miniatures for kids of all ages.
And Stamp Your Art Out, owned by Kim Curry, carries rubber stamping
supplies for scrapbook enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   One of the newest shops is the Pottery Depot, located in the old
train depot. Self-taught potter Huey Wheeler does the throwing, and
his wife, Anne, handles the artwork, which ranges from functional
dishes to decorative totems. You can also admire his one-of-a-kind
containers in the Inn Lobby at Callaway Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Ed Wade and his wife, Kathy, have been one of
the driving forces behind the town's rebirth. A native of Parrott,
Ed moved his family to Atlanta, where he worked for Delta Air
Lines, after graduating from Georgia Tech. But the family always
loved returning to Parrott for visits. In '93, they came back _ for
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were afraid the whole town would be torn down,'' says Ed.
So he began buying up buildings and restoring them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He bought me the drugstore for our 13th wedding anniversary,''
says Kathy, who grew up in Dawson, about 10 miles from Parrott.
``It was my grandfather Arnold's at one time.'' The couple owns and
operates Maridean's Marketplace, which rents to dealers who sell
antiques, art and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   The Wades credit Bill Russell of the University of Georgia's
Small Business Development Center for putting Parrott back on the
map. ``He helped develop a marketing plan and kept us focused,''
says Ed Wade. ``And he brought in people from Georgia Power who
also gave us guidance and who are currently printing brochures for
the Terrell County Welcome Center.''
</P>
<P>
   Another longtime backer is Mary Sue Alston, who was born and
raised in Parrott. ``I love Parrott,'' says the owner of the
building that houses Country Charm gift shop. ``The pace is slow
and I know everyone on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we are getting an influx of new people and visitors, which
is good for our little town.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourists are discovering Parrott because it sits right on Ga.
520, a major route for those traveling north from Florida. That's
how Ernie LoPreste and her friend from Hamburg, Germany, Gudren
Hemme, found themselves at Deborah Ann's Antiques and Gifts on a
recent Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am from Jacksonville, Fla.,'' says LoPreste, ``and Gudren
and I were driving to Callaway Gardens. We saw this cute little
main street from the highway and thought, `Isn't that neat. Let's
stop.'''
</P>
<P>
   If you need a breather from shopping, a must stop is Miss Nan's
Ice Cream Shop. Proprietor Nan Riegle, who also owns Emporium
Antiques &AMP; Collectibles, is known for yummy scoops of Moose Tracks,
butter pecan and mint chocolate chip.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to come in with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   A sign in Riegle's shop window reads, ``If you are grouchy,
irritable or just plain mean, there will be a $10 charge for
putting up with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Quips Riegle: ``I've had several people come in and say, `I
think I owe you some money.'''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Take I-85 south to I-185 to Exit 1 at Columbus.
Then proceed east on U.S. 280 and follow signs to Cusseta. This
will become Ga. 520 East, which takes you to Parrott.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Most shops are open 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesdays-
</P>
<P>
   Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Ample free parking.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: Available in shops; also public restrooms behind
City Hall on College Street.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Accessibility: Wheelchair accessible.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Chamber of Commerce 912-995-2011; or Maridean's
Marketplace, 912-623-4123.
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chinaberry Cafe: This down-home restaurant in the former post
office might dish up fried chicken, roast beef or salmon croquettes
with real mashed potatoes, okra and tomatoes or steamed cabbage
(one meat and one veggie, $3.95). For lighter appetites, try the
homemade chicken salad served with lime fluff, pear salad or copper
pennies (carrots) for $5.50. And if you're lucky, local baker Mary
Perry will have made her caramel cake (a slice is $1.50). Also
tasty: the peanut butter and pecan pies (each slice, $1.50). Owners
Mabel Knight and Jean Jones keep refills of sweetened or
unsweetened tea coming to the tables. 11 a.m.-3 p.m. Tuesdays,
Thursdays and Sundays; 11 a.m.-9 p.m. Fridays-Saturdays. 118 E.
Main St. 912-623-2233.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nothin' Fancy: The name says it all. It's located in Leary,
about 23 miles from Parrott, out in the middle of nowhere. But it's
well worth the trip for Paul Cassels' fried catfish, oysters, fried
or boiled shrimp, mullet and chicken strips. If you like catfish,
opt for the fillets ($10). Shrimp lovers can have their shrimp
fried or boiled ($10). All dinners are served with light-as-air
hush puppies and two sides: cheese grits, fries, slaw, onion rings
or baked potato. Save room for a piece of homemade cake ($1.50).
The napkins are paper and the utensils plastic but the restaurant
is first-class. Expect to wait for a table. 4-9:30 p.m.
Thursday-Saturdays. At the corner of Ga. 55 and 234, Leary. Call
Paul Cassells for directions. 912-792-6420.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Twin Palms Bed and Breakfast Motel: Take a trip back in time
and stay in this utterly cool '50s motel. The former Parrott motel
has been painted a bright yellow by owners Alan Wilson and Al
Seely. They refurbished the 11 rooms _ with private baths and air
conditioning _ in retro style with authentic lava lamps, blond
laminated furniture and vintage fabrics. Note: No TVs are in the
rooms. In the morning, you'll be served a huge country breakfast of
eggs, sausage or bacon, homemade biscuits and bread and a fabulous
grits casserole that even non-grits eaters will like. $65-$125. On
Ga. 520 East in Parrott. 912-623-4820, twinpalmsbandb.com.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   Nearby attractions, within a 35-mile drive of Parrott include:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chehaw Wild Animal Park. Experience Georgia's piney woods at
The Parks at Chehaw. For example, walk on the wild side at the Wild
Animal Park by viewing naturalistic exhibits with native and exotic
animals. Enjoy Creekside Park, with its nature trails and fishing,
and have a picnic at Play Park. Another venue is Bike Park where
you can get in shape on mountain trails. Located on Ga. 91 one mile
north of Albany and Parrott is about 30 miles from Albany.
Admission to Parks: $2 per car; $5 per van; $10 per bus. Park
hours: 9 a.m.-5 p.m. Sundays-Saturdays. Admission : $2 adults; $1
ages 3-11. Wild Animal Park hours: 9:30 a.m.-5 p.m.
Sundays-Saturdays. 912-430-5275.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Westville. Step back in time at this 1850s museum village. You
can stroll down dirt roads, see crafters ply their trades and chat
with Westville citizens.The village consists of more than 25
historic buildings, including 11 houses depicting various styles
and economic classes during this period. On U.S. 27, 1/2 mile south
of Lumpkin and 27 miles from Parrott. $8; $7 seniors; $4
kindergarten through 12th grade. 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesdays-Saturdays;
1-5 p.m. Sundays. 1-888-733-1850 or 912-838-6310.
</P>
<P>
   Shop talk
</P>
<P>
   Alston's Trading Co., 9416 Columbus Highway
</P>
<P>
   James Bridges Antiques, 117 E. Main St.
</P>
<P>
   Country Charm, 104 Railroad St.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Ann's Antiques &AMP; Gifts, 127 E. Main St.
</P>
