<HEADER>
A4616 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-MEIER-ARCHITECTURE-NY     05-24 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEIER-ARCHITECTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICHARD MEIER BUILDS IN MANHATTAN. AT LAST. 
</HEADLINE>
   By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Richard Meier, the world-renowned Pritzker
Prize-winning architect, is promoting a glassy new condominium in
Greenwich Village _ his first building in Manhattan in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is there an apartment in New York City with four
exposures and these views,'' he asked, gazing at a building model
showing floor-through multimillion-dollar apartments. ``Uptown to
the Empire State Building and the Chrysler Building. Over there is
Westbeth ...''
</P>
<P>
   Westbeth? Not perhaps a stop on every tourist's itinerary. But
certainly a landmark for Meier. In the late 1960s, he transformed
the old Bell Telephone Laboratories into low-cost rental housing
and work space for artists, which in turn helped make the far west
Village a community and the young Meier a celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, all of New York was about to lie at his feet.
</P>
<P>
   Except that it didn't. Although his office was in Manhattan, the
telephone calls came from other places entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why hasn't anyone asked me?'' he said. ``I've lived and worked
here all my life. I've designed buildings in Italy, Spain, France,
Luxembourg, Holland. Look at New York City: bar none, the greatest
city in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But in New York, he said, ``architecture is not high on the
agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   He marched a visitor to a window in his sixth-floor office, with
its sidelong view of 11th Avenue and the Hudson River. ``Look at
that,'' he said, gesturing toward mundane, red-brick-banded
apartment skyscrapers still under construction. ``That's what's
being built now.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused. ``I look out the window, and it hurts me,'' he said.
``There is such constant change. There is no city in such
extraordinary flux. What an opportunity! Another opportunity
missed! It hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald J. Trump has periodically talked about hiring Meier for
one of his mega-projects. ``Yeah, he told me, too,'' Meier said.
``I'm still waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   But he is not waiting for Trump anymore. Meier is, in a sense,
coming home.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of next year, he hopes to have overseen completion of
a pair of 14-story condominiums, with 28 apartments in all, on one
of the most coveted corners in town.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Born, Ira Drukier and Charles Blaichman, three relative
unknowns in the rough world of New York real estate, are the main
developers of the $50 million project, although Meier will own a
piece of the pie (less than 10 percent, he said).
</P>
<P>
   Given two relatively narrow sites that flank Perry Street at
West Street, Meier has designed gleaming white buildings with huge
expanses of clear glass, punctuated by frosted-glass balconies.
Although they are the same height, one is slimmer and consequently
more delicate, to accommodate a narrower lot.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the floor, the prices will range from $2 million to
$8 million. The condominiums will be delivered with open, loftlike
floor plans, but Meier flipped through blueprints to show more
refined, partitioned spaces, saying buyers could hire his firm to
finish them off.
</P>
<P>
   Meier, still selling, said there would be amenities galore: a
couple of concierges, a cafe on the ground floor of one building,
parking in a building right behind, maybe even a health club. (An
earlier plan for a hotel on top of the garage is in abeyance, and
the future of a proposed restaurant, run by Jean-Georges
Vongerichten in the cafe space, is uncertain, the architect said.)
</P>
<P>
   While designed to be glamorous, the buildings are far from
Meier's biggest commission: he has done courthouses and museums.
The Getty Center in Los Angeles, a vast white complex of buildings
high over the San Diego Freeway, has come to be regarded as the
epitome of Meier style, a tourist attraction of the first order.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wanted to put me on the shelf after the
Getty,'' he said. ``Well, the Getty is great, but you move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Even during those 13 years, he said, there were other things
going on: ``the city hall in the Hague, the Museum of Contemporary
Art in Barcelona and a lot of other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, his firm's most highly publicized project is probably
the Church of the Year 2000 in Rome (which, the architect said
wryly, he hopes will be finished by the end of the year 2000).
There is also a single- span bridge he has designed for
Alessandria, Italy, to be started in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there are ... the twin towers. Well, maybe not towers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tiny project,'' Meier said. ``Instead of 14 stories,
I could be doing something 10 or 20 times bigger with the same
amount of effort.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least it's a beginning, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope so,'' he said. ``It's a beginning of the next
phase, a phase that will deal with urban issues.''
</P>
<P>
   On Perry Street, four- and five-story brick walk-ups abound,
along with short, stubby warehouses. A few blocks north, Meier's
first New York venture, Westbeth, is about the same height as the
Perry Street buildings. But Meier's materials will be different: so
polar white, so glossy.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the big developers were afraid to hire him, sure that
they would get a ``Richard Meier'' signature building _ with white
metallic-looking walls and glass grids _ which might or might not
blend in.
</P>
<P>
   Meier nodded; he's heard it before. ``But contextuality doesn't
mean it has to look like what's around it. The scale and materials
can be appropriate, but it doesn't have to be a clone. That's why I
think these new buildings are contextual. They may not match what's
around _ thank goodness. They are more contextual than some
pastiche.''
</P>
<P>
   The towers will be built ``as of right,'' which means that the
developers don't have to ask the city for special zoning favors, so
there is no official place in the process for neighborhood input.
</P>
<P>
   But even if the neighbors turn out to be unhappy about the
buildings' juxtaposition of white glass to faded red brick and gray
cinder block _ their Meiericity, so to speak _ the buyers don't
seem to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half of the apartments are already spoken for,'' Meier said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
