A4618 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-ART-ANDARTIFICE-TEX     05-24 0568
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-ANDARTIFICE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINGS ARE DECEPTIVELY NORMAL IN THE ART OF ARTIFICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW MARTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
``Natural Deceits''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today-Sept. 10 at the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth, 1309
Montgomery St.
</P>
<P>
   Free
</P>
<P>
   Information: (817) 738-9215
</P>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Normally, mendacity does not flatter
artistic expression. After all, one measure of great art is its
ability to serve as a vessel for inspired truths. And yet, such is
the effectiveness of ``Natural Deceits,'' the current exhibit at
the Modern Art Museum of Fort Worth, that half-truths actually
become subversive and humorous mirrors to what is painfully real.
</P>
<P>
   United by a penchant for slightly disturbing narrative, the 11
Texas artists whose works make up the exhibit employ a range of
media that is never less than intriguing. From familiar photography
and drawing to the sublimely wacky use of a refrigerator and a
whole turkey, ``Natural Deceits'' makes the medium not just the
message but the star.
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long time since one actually climbed a scaffolding
ladder to participate in, and observe, an art installation. But
it's not every day that Leandro Erlich sets up ``The Swimming
Pool.'' This 1998 bit of aquatic whimsy suspends 2 inches of water
on a clear platform above a backyard pool. Visitors are encouraged
to walk on the bottom of the pool and stare up through the scrim of
rippling water. At that moment, it is perfectly ambiguous as to who
is on the inside looking out and vice versa. The exposition's first
deceit has been launched.
</P>
<P>
   Erlich's pool has been installed near Francesca Fuchs' faded
brown tulip mural, which conveys all the sensuality of a hospital
ICU unit. Other examples of Fuchs' painting style replicate the
tight web design of cheap pool furniture. The entire installation
smacks of a seemingly innocuous suburban back yard, a strip from
Pleasantville in which deception lies in the sinister normalcy
sneering underneath blades of artificial grass. It is in just this
sort of landscape that the epoxied flies of Vernon Fisher's
``Eclipse'' would thrive, looking so jarringly real yet clearly
manufactured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Natural Deceits'' is an edgy, darkly witty show, pushing the
boundaries of ``mixed media.'' An inventory of materials used by
Helen Altman for ``Snowhead'' includes ice, a bloated snowman's
head, a gnarled carrot for a nose, and a beat-up electric freezer.
Appliances continue to play a central role in Altman's ``Phoenix,''
in which a vintage refrigerator is left open to reveal an uncooked
turkey sitting in a roasting pan.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no artist takes the theme of faux nature to its mocking
edge better than Bill Davenport. His ``Alpine Lake Replica'' has
the artistic probity to sell itself as a ``replica'' of a natural
setting. But then Davenport undercuts all the candor by offering a
grove of foam pine trees bordering an aluminum-foil lake. At first,
one giggles at the hubris of passing off a piece of childlike art
as social commentary.
</P>
<P>
   But then the giggles stop. Davenport's simple expression begins
to make ``Natural Deceits''' more sophisticated point that we have
contented ourselves with ersatz nature, and that even the most
remote concoction of reality has become a mollifying substitute.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
