<SLUG> BC-EXPLORER-MEMORIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STATUE OF SPANISH EXPLORER TO GET NEW HOME IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RACHEL GORDON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It has taken 224 years for Spanish explorer Juan
Bautista de Anza to make his way back to Mission Dolores.
</P>
<P>
   Only this time, the tenacious scout for colonial Spain won't be
arriving at the old mission on horseback. Most likely he'll get
there on a flat-bed truck. Oh, and in the form of an 8,000-pound
bronze statue cast in his likeness.
</P>
<P>
   The statue of Juan Bautista de Anza, presented to San Francisco
in 1967 by Luis Encina, then-governor of Sonora, Mexico, has spent
the past few years locked in an Arts Commission storage room since
the Embarcadero roadway project forced its removal from Justin
Herman Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   But now, a new home for the 11 1/2-foot-tall statue has been
found: the grassy median strip in front of Mission Dolores at
Dolores and 16th streets.
</P>
<P>
   The location is fitting, since it was Anza who helped pick the
site for the mission in 1776 _ the same year the founders of the
United States of America, busy on the other side of the continent
thinking their revolutionary thoughts, declared independence from
the British throne.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the bronze Anza on the median strip will be King Carlos
III, the Catholic monarch of Spain (in statue form, of course). The
king ordered the building of the mission and the Presidio in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Like the statue of Anza, the one of King Carlos III _ a
2,000-pound gift to San Francisco from Spain's King Juan Carlos I
in 1976 _ also got the boot from Justin Herman Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Lehane, program director of the civic art collection for
the San Francisco Arts Commission, is excited that the statues will
land in a more appropriate setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting away from `plop' art, just plopping it down
somewhere. These (statues) have a relationship to Mission Dolores,
a connection to San Francisco history,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The venue change will cost taxpayers about $56,000 to pay for
the move and construction of new concrete foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Brother Guire Cleary, curator of Mission Dolores Basilica,
approves of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relocation of these statues,'' he said, ``will help
celebrate a 224-year relationship between this, the oldest intact
Franciscan Mission in California, and our Spanish heritage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
