A4622 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-0525-C     05-24 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNCERTAINTY ALONG THE ISRAELI-LEBANON BORDER, ABOUT THE FUTURE
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KFAR KILA, Lebanon _ Crowds of euphoric Lebanese Wednesday
taunted Israelis through the barbed-wire fence that now separates
them, defining the new boundaries of the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours earlier, the last convoys of Israeli troops sped out
of southern Lebanon, ending nearly two decades of occupation.
</P>
<P>
   The nonviolent confrontations at the fence posed the question of
whether Israel's northern border will be peaceful even though its
army has left the so-called ``security zone'' buffer. And, whether
southern Lebanon will finally see peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enjoy your celebrations for a couple of days. But enough is
enough,'' shouted an Israeli taking pictures of the opposing crowd
through the wire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you born here?'' countered Avdel Kareem Shour, 42, from
the Lebanese side. ``Go back to your fatherland!''
</P>
<P>
   Steps away, a uniformed Hezbollah guerilla, fully equipped with
his M-16 rifle, scope and laser sight, paid no heed to the Israeli
army vehicles passing beyond the fence just 12 yards away. Some
were just curious to see their adversaries up close. Some
video-taped their neighbors, and a few scolded a youth who lobbed a
rock through the fence, saying that it wasn't necessary today.
</P>
<P>
   Israel controlled both sides of the fence before a pre-dawn
withdrawal on Tuesday. Now, Israeli troops and civilians stay to
the south on a border patrol road and Lebanese stay to the north
gawking.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first day of a new and uncertain Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese guerillas staged impromptu military parades with the
abandoned tanks they managed to start.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lebanese civilians waved flags and posed for pictures
by signs marking cities from which they had been separated for
years. A proud father posed his 3-year-old son on the barrel of an
abandoned tank. Artillery posts and fortresses that had held the
population in fear just the day before were toured by parents and
children as if they were museums.
</P>
<P>
   The new-found freedom also allowed for solemn reminders of the
darkest aspects of the occupation.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-inmates returned to the Al Khiam prison where they had been
tortured and beaten by the Israeli-paid militia, the South Lebanon
Army. The SLA had abandoned the controversial prison, cited for
years by human rights advocates, the day before.
</P>
<P>
   For Israelis, it was a day of anxiety and controversy. They had
long ago tired of the casualties their soldiers faced in their
``security zone.'' Prime Minister Ehud Barak promised to end the
occupation by this July. However, the SLA disintegrated earlier
this week and Israel hurriedly removed its last few hundred troops
who were followed to the border by Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   Ariel Sharon, the leader of the opposition Likud Party and
director of Israel's 1982 Lebanon invasion, called the withdrawal a
``shameful retreat.''
</P>
<P>
   But some were just happy to have the troops home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prayed for this day,'' said Orna Shimoni, a leader of the
``Four Mothers'' grassroots movement that led the push for a
unilateral withdrawal, and whose own son Eyal was killed in Lebanon
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Barak tried to calm public anxiety about Hezbollah's new
proximity with a stern warning Wednesday that any over the border
attacks would be met with retaliation unprecedented in its
severity, and would be felt ``across Lebanon.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on the Lebanese side there were tensions. Hezbollah
searched Wednesday for remaining members of the SLA, many of whom
were still surrendering themselves to Lebanese government
officials. Some gathered in churches for protection during their
surrender.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese government, with a mixed Christian-Muslim make-up,
considers the SLA traitors deserving trial.
</P>
<P>
   And there was sad reflection.
</P>
<P>
   At the hilltop Al Khiam prison, the corduroy hoods that had been
used to blind and stifle inmates for days at a time, were still
scattered near the dark and fetid booths used for solitary
confinement. Hezbollah sheiks, government officials and families
came to look Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Hassan Kussan, a paunchy middle-aged man, spent two years in the
prison during the 1980s without ever being charged or tried.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bitter, harsh, experience. It was beyond the
imagination,'' he said. ``I just came to remember how much I
suffered, because this is something that is unforgettable in the
first place.''
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Kaplow's E-mail address is: larryk(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
