<HEADER>
A4623 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-STAR-WARS-ART-NYT     05-24 1430
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-STAR-WARS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY FAR FAR AWAY IS BECOMING FULLY DIGITAL
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By IAN AUSTEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the director George Lucas and the producer Rick
McCallum recently shot screen tests for ``Star Wars: Episode II,''
there was a problem. At the end of the successful shot, McCallum
said, Lucas couldn't use the traditional director's cry of ``Cut!
Print!'' because he was shooting on digital videotape, not film.
After a moment's hesitation, McCallum said, a new finale was
proposed: ``Cut! Can we take a quick look at it?''
</P>
<P>
   When ``Star Wars: Episode II'' starts production next month in
Australia it will be the first major motion picture created mostly
using high-resolution digital videotape rather than film. And while
McCallum is reluctant to declare that the all-digital Jedi warriors
will bring death to film, he is confident that the production is
the beginning of a major shift in movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be pretty brain dead to be involved in film at
this time and not realize that we are going through a very serious
evolutionary step in how we acquire images,'' he said. If
everything goes according to plan, the move by Lucasfilm Ltd. to
digital imaging should go unnoticed by theater audiences, who will
still view the goings on in ``a galaxy far, far away'' the
old-fashioned way with projected film.
</P>
<P>
   But those results will be closely scrutinized within the film
world, where the decision by Lucasfilm has sparked an intense
debate. Steven Poster, a director of photography and vice president
of the American Society of Cinematographers, said he thought the
technology still wasn't good enough for the big screen. For one
thing, digital images contain somewhat less detail than traditional
film images. ``We've seen through Imax how audiences are just
thrilled with a big, more visceral experience,'' he said, referring
to the jumbo-screen, film-based movie technology. ``There is a very
positive use of this digital technology in television. But when it
comes to motion pictures, we're adopting a technology that hasn't
been audience tested. If you start with less of an image, you wind
up with an even lesser image on screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without digital cameras, the ``Star Wars'' films have
increasingly become products of digital imaging. For example,
nearly all of the 2,200 shots in ``Episode I: The Phantom Menace''
were scanned into a computer for editing. Lucas had decided to use
fully digital cameras in 1997, after viewing demonstrations of
high-definition digital systems that Sony designed for television.
Officers at Sony in Japan had contemplated a similar digital system
for the big screen, ``there were sections of the company that
weren't entirely sure that there would be a marketplace of any
size,'' said Laurence Thorpe, vice president for acquisition
systems at Sony Electronics' broadcast and professional products
group.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas told Sony that if the company created a digital system for
theatrical films, he would use it to make ``Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the nudging factor,'' Thorpe said. ``Having a luminary
give us encouragement spurred us into action.''
</P>
<P>
   The equipment was called the Sony Digital Film System, but that
name is slightly misleading. The system actually uses videotape
cassettes, slightly smaller than VHS tapes. The camera captures an
image with its lens then passes it through a prism that breaks it
down in red, green or blue light. Three light-sensitive digital
chips then analyze the image, and the data is converted into
digital form and recorded on the tape (although, in theory, the
data could be stored on any digital recording media, like a hard
drive, for example). Once on tape, the images are transferred to
the hard drives of specialized computers for editing and special
effects. When all the post-production is finished, special laser
printers expose the image onto photographic film used to generate
prints for theater projectors.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a digital system for movies was not a straightforward
proposition. To start with, Sony had to design its system to
operate at 24 frames per second _ the rate of movie theater
projectors _ rather than the 60 frames per second used in
television. In addition to the cameras, that re-engineering project
involved the equipment needed to edit, adjust and manipulate the
images.
</P>
<P>
   Because it was probable that future productions would still mix
in conventional film with digital images, Sony _ working with
Lucas' film effects company, Industrial Light and Magic _ also had
to write software to make the digital images match the appearance
of various types of film.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's greatest shortcoming, however, was not electronic but
mechanical. The new motion picture system (now known as 24P) was
based on the design of a camera, intended for television news
crews, that outwardly looks little different from the Betacams made
by the company since the 1980s. Not only were its viewfinder system
and controls unsuitable for feature film crews, but the weight of
film production lenses was enough to rip the front off the camera.
None of those lenses could be used in any case. Because the
camera's light-sensitive charged coupled device is smaller than the
format used for 35-millimeter films, exceptionally precise optics
had to be developed.
</P>
<P>
   The delays meant that the new camera would not be ready for
``Phantom Menace.'' To solve its mechanical and optical problems,
Sony partnered with Panavision, which designs, builds and rents
film cameras and lenses. The two companies had collaborated in 1989
on a digital film camera that was unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   In January Panavision delivered the first prototype camera to
Lucasfilm and Industrial Light and Magic. For four months,
technicians shot technical tests with conventional film cameras
rolling beside the digital upstart. The digital images were then
converted to 35-millimeter film using three techniques: a Sony
laser printer that writes directly onto film, an in-house process
developed by Industrial Light and Magic and a laser printer made by
E-Films, a Los Angeles company. The conventional film was also put
through all the steps it would encounter during actual production.
</P>
<P>
   The results were shipped to Lucas for side-by-side projections
at the Skywalker Ranch's private theater in Marin County, Calif. On
March 10, Lucas blessed the digital results despite having some
misgivings about the camera design. Thorpe recalled Lucas saying:
``I'll accept the physical limitations of the camera, as you've got
to start somewhere. I hope you'll listen to me when you design your
next generation of camera.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several kinds of scenes that will still require film
cameras in ``Episode II'' because the Sony system in its current
form will operate only at 24 frames per second. Most of the
trademark ``Star Wars'' light-sabre battle scenes are shot with the
camera running more slowly than normal to make the action appear
faster and presumably more swashbuckling when projected on the
screen. Stop-action animation (the frame-by-frame manipulation of
three-dimensional models to simulate movement) is also impossible
with the digital system.
</P>
<P>
   But the digital system has some significant advantages. For
``Episode I,'' McCallum estimated that it cost upward of $1.7
million to buy, process and transfer film to digital tape for
post-production and special effects. For ``Episode II,'' he is
budgeting $15,000 for tapes. Similarly, a film camera races through
a standard 1,000-foot film magazine in 11 minutes. Each digital
tape can store up to 50 minutes of images. And fewer production
steps could mean less deterioration in image quality. ``Film is
alchemy,'' McCallum said. ``Every time a print is made, the quality
is less and less.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Lucas' endorsement, both Sony and Panavision emphasize
that the digital system is a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that someone like George Lucas has made such a strong
commitment to this technology gives it credibility it would
otherwise have to earn,'' said John Galt, Panavision's senior vice
president for advanced digital imaging. ``But I'm still of the
opinion that we have to prove that it works.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether that will improve the quality of what moviegoers see
at the local multiplex is still an open question. McCallum said:
``Digital is just a tool. It doesn't mean that films are going to
get any better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
