<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-OUTDOORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE HOUSE ITSELF LOLLS AT POOLSIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARTHA BAKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Windsor, a planned community created here in
1989 by the husband-and-wife planning team of Elizabeth
Plater-Zyberk and Andres Duany, is meant to encourage outdoor
living. But unlike Celebration and Seaside, other Florida planned
communities where leisure time is spent on front porches and
stoops, Windsor is a place where outdoor time is lived out back, in
courtyards and on loggias, patios and verandas.
</P>
<P>
   Windsor's large houses, built to the edges of their property
lines, are set on deep, narrow lots. But the homes hardly offer
typical suburban living, with chats over the backyard fence. Nor
are swimming pools segregated in their own fenced-in patios.
Following the model of Spanish and Italian homes, these spaces are
cloisters, shielded from neighbors by wraparound houses and walled
gardens. Their pools, above, lap right up to the loggia or offer a
fantasy of Venice.
</P>
<P>
   In these Windsor courtyards, the distinction between indoors and
outdoors blurs and ultimately disappears. Plants move inside,
antiques move out and fireplaces are, as in the Southwest, welcome
indoors and out. It is a way of living that, come Memorial Day,
would appeal to almost any householder, even on a small scale.
</P>
<P>
   One veranda, shown at right, was designed by Clemens Bruns
Schaub, the architect for many of the homes here. The house, also
below and at far right, was built on a double lot with a large
courtyard, considered by the owners to be the principal living room
of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Moving indoor elements outdoors _ tables, chairs, a coffee
table, fans, light fixtures, cushions, even a daybed and a
footstool _ gives a warm, old Mediterranean feel. The veranda,
which spans the property, has a high ceiling and a large masonry
fireplace, making it feel both intimate and spacious. From it, a
lawn leads down to an Olympic-size pool edged with intricately
paved brick walkways, which carry the eye to the far end of the
courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   Schaub has said that his ambition at Windsor was to satisfy
``the needs, desires and fantasies of its owners.'' Sometimes
homeowners' fantasies include a quiet family oasis, meant for
private lolling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
