<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BURGERS0525-COX     05-24 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURGERS0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Building a BETTER burger
 &HT;    By Ann Heller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The first burger of summer is a pleasure on its
own. Grilled until crisp on the outside and still juicy inside,
with its hint of smoke, all the burger needs is a simple toasted
bun.
</P>
<P>
   Says who?
</P>
<P>
   We want to start summer with a bang, and Memorial Day is the
unofficial beginning of the season in this part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The hamburger has to be memorable. So we rounded up some
favorites with additions that will bring big flavor to that patty
of plain ground beef.
</P>
<P>
   Before going any further, let's make that ground chuck _ not
ground beef. In taste test after taste test, ground chuck wins the
hamburger championship.
</P>
<P>
   Figure on three hamburgers to a pound for the best, juiciest
varieties. Don't handle the patties much; just form lightly with
your hands and press gently to flatten to about one inch thick,
which is an adult-sized hamburger. Approximate cooking time is
about five minutes per side, but grill fires are variable.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that those who like their hamburgers medium or medium
rare are choosing to ignore well-publicized health concerns. That's
their choice, but for the record, 160 degrees is the recommended
interior temperature for safe burgers. That translates into gray _
not pink _ meat that is medium well to well done.
</P>
<P>
   For kids' safety, make their burgers thinner and cook them
longer, until well done. And for taste's sake, keep theirs plain
and let them add the condiments.
</P>
<P>
   But for the grown-ups, it's time to experiment.
</P>
<P>
   The basic formula is a teaspoon of salt and a half-teaspoon of
pepper per pound of beef. Here are a half-dozen winning variations:
</P>
<P>
   _ This one suits the seasons, for the secret ingredient is one
big Vidalia onion. No, not sliced or diced. The onion is run
through a blender until it's chopped to a mush. Combine the onion
with a pound of ground chuck, season with salt and pepper, and
grill. The onion adds moisture as well as flavor; some caramelized
onions on top will double the pleasure. Make them ahead of time:
Just heat a half-and-half mixture of butter and oil in heavy
skillet, add sliced onions and cook slowly over medium low heat for
about 30 minutes, stirring often, until they are a deep caramel
color. You can splash a cup of red wine into the onions and let
them cook down to a marmalade consistency. Or go for simplicity and
just slather the onion burger with gutsy Dijon mustard, which is a
perfect partner for onion.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Blue Burger is a classic and requires just a little
advance preparation. Blend a cup of crumbled room-temperature blue
cheese with a tablespoon of softened butter and use it to stuff
hamburgers before grilling. You can skip the butter if you use
soft, melting blue such as Saga or Cambozola. An optional addition
is 1/4 cup of finely minced green onion. Spread at least a
tablespoon between two thin patties, then seal them together.
Sprinkle both sides with salt and pepper, then refrigerate until
ready to grill. Up the ante and make a double-blue burger by adding
a dab of blue on top just before serving. Let it melt in and taste
the testimony that excess can be good.
</P>
<P>
   _ Take the same approach with Turkey Burgers. Season the ground
turkey with salt and pepper and tuck a tablespoon of herbaceous
Boursin cheese in between two thin patties. Seal them well,
pressing the edges with your fingers, and grill. Now that will give
that boring turkey some flavor. For toppings, try grilled onion
slices. Brush thick slices with oil and herbs and grill alongside
the burgers. Thread a wooden skewer all the way through so the
rings don't separate. Put the grilled onion on the turkey burger
and pull out the skewer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mushrooms are perfect with beef, but we're not talking those
slices of canned mushrooms. Here's a secret ingredient that will
bump up the flavor: dried wild mushroom powder. OK, you can't find
it at the neighborhood convenience store, but when I do spot it I
stock up and keep it in the pantry. Just sprinkle a tablespoon of
mushroom powder over a pound of ground beef, season with salt and
pepper, and mix lightly with a fork. Form into patties and grill.
The obvious topping is fresh mushrooms cooked in butter with a bit
of garlic. Even better is real Italian Fontina, which melts
beautifully, and is not to be confused with the domestic product.
Place a slice on top for the last couple minutes of cooking.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chipotle peppers will give burgers a smoky flavor even if it's
too rainy to cook them on the grill. Chipotles canned in adobo
sauce are widely available in supermarkets. Mince one or two with a
little of the sauce. Combine with a tablespoon of cream to help
disperse the flavor and pour over a pound of ground chuck. Season
with salt and pepper and stir with a fork before shaping the
patties. Grill, broil or pan-fry. After turning, top with slices of
smoked cheese such as smoked Gouda and let it melt while the
burgers finish cooking. You'll swear the burger was cooked over an
open fire.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Portobello Burger is everybody's answer for vegetarians,
but you can improve on it. Portobellos can suck up the
vinegar-based marinades used in many restaurants. Skip that step.
Instead, squeeze a clove of garlic through a garlic press and mix
it with some olive oil. Brush that on the mushrooms while grilling,
about 3 minutes to a side. Sprinkle with salt and pepper. Now
that's the burger, but you need more. A half a roasted red pepper _
available ready-to-eat in jars and some supermarket delis _ can be
laid on the bun to add another meaty dimension. Spread the other
side of the bun with lemony mayo (just blend some lemon zest, about
a half teaspoon into a 1/4 cup of mayo and add snipped fresh herbs
from the garden.) Or, if the taste of tomato is what you want, run
some oil-packed dried tomatoes through a mini blender with a dash
of balsamic or sherry vinegar and spread that, sparingly, over the
inside of the bun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
