u l BC-SCOTCHGARD-NYT &LR;      05-24 1278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTCHGARD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAR STAINS ON THE EASY CHAIR, AS SCOTCHGARD FADES AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Minn.)   By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While experts argue the efficacy of building America's
space-based Strategic Defense Initiative, here on Earth one of the
nation's most trusted defense systems will, by year's end, be
dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   Scotchgard, the soil-retardant and stain-repellent spray made by
the 3M Co. of St. Paul, Minn., is being ``phased out,'' the company
announced on May 16, because of environmental concerns about a
chemical used to make it, perfluorooctanyl. The same stuff that
makes it easy to lift a blob of chip dip off a carpet is, it turns
out, harder to get off the planet. Scotchgard stain prevention
products do not decompose.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   As Prof. Ned Brainard, played by Fred MacMurray in the 1961
movie ``The Absent-Minded Professor,'' said of flying rubber, or
Flubber, ``It's a substance whose behavior is disturbingly
nonclassical.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   The company's move to discontinue Scotchgard was voluntary, but
the Environmental Protection Agency said on May 18 that it had been
poised to remove it from the market if the company had not taken
action. Manufacture will not stop for some months, 3M says;
availability will depend on store inventories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would advise consumers to adopt a precautionary approach,''
said Stephen Johnson, deputy assistant administrator for the
agency's office of prevention, pesticides and toxic substances.
``Given the agency's concerns about long-term exposure, people
should exercise judgment as to whether to use the materials.''
</P>
<P>
   The dirt of the ages appears to have won a round. Though there
are other protective products, including DuPont's Stainmaster, the
Scotchgard announcement left many vendors and consumers unprotected
from the vision of a future without soil retardance or stain
repellence in clothing, home furnishings and floor coverings: three
huge textile categories (with an estimated $45 billion in annual
sales, according to the Census Bureau) in which the product is
ubiquitous.
</P>
<P>
   With an air of national emergency, Heloise, the syndicated
household-hints columnist, was scrambled like a fighter pilot by
the ``Today'' show for a not very reassuring appearance two days
after 3M's news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked around my hotel room that night,'' she said, reached
on a car telephone in Texas. ``Carpeting, drapes, bedspread _
probably all fabric protected.''
</P>
<P>
   Heloise, who had previously advised Bryant Gumbel and Matt Lauer
to use fabric protector on favorite neckties, found herself
confronted with an anxious public after the show. ``Everyone from
my CPA to flight attendants has said: `Oh, we saw you. Are they
taking it away?''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The news will only get worse, the columnist hinted darkly, her
voice crackling from the highway. ``The first ramification is that
the can is going away,'' she said, speaking of the home-application
sprays available in hardware stores. Those three products are
Scotchgard's Protector for Fabric and Upholstery, Protector for
Rugs and Carpet and Protector for Leather. (Scotchgard cleaning
products are not affected.)
</P>
<P>
   Scotchgard, which represents $300 million, or 2 percent, of 3M's
$16 billion in annual sales, is more typically applied
commercially, at the industrial level. ``In the manufacturing
process, if you're going to get a new couch, and you have three
kids under the age of 10,'' Heloise asked, ``are you going to be
out of luck?''
</P>
<P>
   Good question.
</P>
<P>
   From popular midpriced furniture manufacturers like La-Z-Boy to
Hickory Chair, which licenses collections from decorators like
Thomas O'Brien and the late Mark Hampton, soil and stain protection
is prevalent in upholstered products. Ninety percent of La-Z-Boy's
stain-preventive fabrics are treated with Scotchgard. The company
has called 3M in for a meeting to discuss the strategy and
timetable for withdrawing Scotchgard and for assurances about the
product's safety, said Greg White, vice president for merchandising
at La-Z-Boy.
</P>
<P>
   In a spectacular piece of bad timing, 3M introduced a national
magazine advertising campaign late last year extolling the
Scotchgard-protected life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got a life? Gotta ask for Scotchgard,'' the ad reads in the
current issue of Martha Stewart Living. In the picture, a child
playing on a carpet is spilling juice on her doll.
</P>
<P>
   The Scotchgard brand enjoys the highest consumer recognition of
any protective finish, according to a 1999 survey of brands by HFN,
a home furnishings industry publication. DuPont's Teflon was No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Teflon's chemistry, which does not include the perfluorooctanyl
in Scotchgard, is the effective agent in DuPont's competitive
product, Stainmaster, a popular carpet fiber with protective
chemicals integrated into the fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Wolk, DuPont's vice president and general manager for
global flooring and nylon in North America, said that despite
Scotchgard's withdrawal, the company has no plans to introduce
home-application protective sprays, which are not now a part of
DuPont's product line.
</P>
<P>
   Scotchgard, which has a toll-free telephone service center that
answers consumers' questions on its products and warranties (for
``Scotchgard Soil and Stain Release'' carpet protection, a
five-year guarantee against common food and beverage stains,
including bearnaise and hollandaise sauce), reported an increase in
queries, and concerns about both supply and safety.
</P>
<P>
   Housekeeping experts, including Heloise, agreed that there are
no traditional recipes for similar soil and stain protection _ only
wisdom about stain removal.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   In an informal experiment, an unpeeled white potato that was
sprayed with Scotchgard on one side but not the other displayed
admirable, indistinguishable soil water and stain repellence on
both sides, suggesting that, apart from environmental and toxicity
issues, Scotchgard's absence will be bad news for couch potatoes,
but not potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Apparently the peace of mind promised by products like
Scotchgard was invented with them in the 1950s, by laboratory
researchers like Patsy Sherman, who got the idea for a
stain-prevention product when a colleague at 3M accidentally
splashed a fluorochemical-latex emulsion on her tennis shoes. The
doused shoes repelled water and solvents. (Presciently, the team
never discovered a way of getting the gunk off the shoes.)
Scotchgard was introduced to consumers in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Sheep could be the big winners in a world without it. Wool is
water- and stain-resistant.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   ``With wool it's not an issue,'' said Mark Saley, marketing
director of floor coverings at ABC Carpet &AMP; Home in New York.
``It's inherently stain-resistant, because of the lanolin in the
wool. And it repels dirt, because it's porous, not solid fiber like
nylon. It's mostly a nylon issue.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Wolk at DuPont, which could be the other clear winner with
Scotchgard's demise, estimated that nylon carpet manufacturing was
a $6.4 billion a year business.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Salant, the owner of the Budget Plastic Cover Co. in the
Bronx, which has made plastic slipcovers for 30 years, believes in
his product but isn't waiting for history to reverse itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's impervious to anything,'' he said of a plastic slipcover.
``Stain protection isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Salant said that the introduction of fabric protectors never
affected his sales. ``Certain people are plastic slipcover
people,'' he said. ``I see very little impact.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1747EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
