<HEADER>
A4635 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-DYNAMITE-DINOMATION-T     05-24 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DYNAMITE-DINOMATION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINOSAURS FROM THE DAWN OF MOVIE TIME TO THE PRESENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the dawn of history, or at least the dawn of movies,
dinosaurs have intrigued filmmakers _ from some of the earliest
animators to the makers of the new mega-movie ``Dinosaur.'' Since
nothing puts us in a mind to think about evolution more than these
Mesozoic megaliths, we present the evolution of dinosaur movies.
</P>
<P>
   THE PIONEER EPOCH
</P>
<P>
   1914
</P>
<P>
   ``Gertie:'' Newspaper cartoonist Winsor McCay, who has already
done a couple of animated films, decides to animate a dinosaur to
prove that his drawings are moving. He incorporates the film into
his vaudeville act, interacting with Gertie, who eats, drinks,
plays and even cries.
</P>
<P>
   1925
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lost World:'' Willis O'Brien, director of some early
dinosaur-related shorts, brings his stop-motion animation to full
flower as the special-effects supervisor on this adaptation of an
Arthur Conan Doyle story about a professor who discovers dinosaurs
living in a remote section of Africa. No relation to Steven
Spielberg's ``The Lost World: Jurassic Park.''
</P>
<P>
   1933
</P>
<P>
   ``King Kong:'' O'Brien also did the effects on this, which
although most notable for its impressive stop-motion animation of
the title ape, also includes some cool dinosaur fights.
</P>
<P>
   1939/40
</P>
<P>
   ``One Million B.C.:'' Showman Hal Roach is credited with
directing this caveman saga, which pits the ugh-sayers against
dinosaurs and one another. Although it's mediocre, it's dazzling
(for the time) special effects provide stock footage for dino
movies for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCHLOCK EPOCH
</P>
<P>
   1951
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lost Continent:'' Considering that the cast includes Cesar
Romero, Hugh ``Ward Cleaver'' Beaumont and cultural curiosity
Acquanetta, maybe this B-movie featuring fake-looking dinos and a
lot of rock climbing is an example of dinosaur-movie de-evolution.
</P>
<P>
   1966
</P>
<P>
   ``One Million Years B.C.:'' Stop-motion whiz Ray Harryhausen
provides some great-looking dinosaurs, who are upstaged by
fur-bikini-clad poster girl Raquel Welch.
</P>
<P>
   1975
</P>
<P>
   ``The Land That Time Forgot:'' Poor production values (and
not-very-convincing special effects) hurt this adaptation of an
Edgar Rice Burroughs story about German and British troops who
discover dinosaurs on a South Pacific Island during World War I.
</P>
<P>
   THE WARM-AND-FUZZY EPOCH
</P>
<P>
   1988
</P>
<P>
   ``The Land Before Time:'' In a plot that sounds suspiciously
similar to that of ``Dinosaur,'' a young orphan dinosaur must
travel with the herd to a verdant valley, and meets several pals
along the way. The difference is that this is a cartoon directed by
Disney refugee Don Bluth, whose 'toons always seem to lack that
``something special'' that puts Disney 'toons over the top. But it
spawned a video series that keeps kids entertained.
</P>
<P>
   1992
</P>
<P>
   ``Barney &AMP; Friends:'' He's the warmest, fuzziest dino of 'em all
_ largely because he's made out of some sort of fabric. The big,
purple galoot is a hit with small children and their parents,
doubling as a teacher of values and an ersatz baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   THE COMPUTER EPOCH
</P>
<P>
   1993
</P>
<P>
   ``Jurassic Park:'' Scientists and paleontologists fool with
Mother Nature, and the Industrial Light and Magic and Stan Winston
Studios fool us with computer-generated visual effects that present
the most realistic movie dinosaurs to this point.
</P>
<P>
   1998
</P>
<P>
   ``T. Rex: Back to the Cretaceous:'' IMAX, probably the only film
format than can do full justice to dinosaur size, gives us a big,
green eating machine in this typically enlightening and lightweight
entry.
</P>
<P>
   APRIL 2000
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking With Dinosaurs:'' Picking up where ``Jurassic Park''
(and its 1997 sequel, ``The Lost World: Jurassic Park'') left off,
this Discovery Channel documentary uses computer-generated imaging
to detail the story of the prehistoric critters. The DVD is
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   MAY 2000
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinosaur:'' Like ``Walking With Dinosaurs,'' this places
computer-generated dinos in real-life locations. But it also
bestows them with human qualities: i.e., they can talk, they can
feel, and they have the most expressive eyes in animation history.
They're so awesome-looking that you might not care that their story
is ... well, prehistoric. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sources: Van Eaton Galleries Web site (www.vegalleries.com); Film:
An International History of the Medium by Robert Sklar; Leonard
Maltin's 2000 Movie &AMP; Video Guide; the Internet Movie Database
(imdb.com); our own cluttered minds.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4640 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-WOMEN-HOLLYWOOD-SLATE     05-24 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-HOLLYWOOD-SLATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO WRITE A BOOK ON WOMEN IN HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Slate commentary)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)
</P>
<P>
   (Judith Shulevitz writes Slate's ``Chatterbox'' column)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BY JUDITH SHULEVITZ &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The first rule of book reviewing is: Review the book that was
published, not the one you wish had been written. I will now
violate that edict.
</P>
<P>
   Premiere magazine writer Rachel Abramowitz's ``Is That a Gun in
Your Pocket? Women's Experiences of Power in Hollywood'' is a long,
gossipy, blow-by-blow account of seemingly every single career move
ever made by the first two generations of women to succeed in
Hollywood, including studio chiefs Dawn Steel and Sherry Lansing,
agent Sue Mengers, actress/director Jodie Foster, director/writers
Nora Ephron and Elaine May, and producer Paula Weinstein.
</P>
<P>
   ITAGIYP isn't terrible, exactly, but it is the kind of book that
induces in the reviewer such weighty thoughts as, ``Ought this kind
of book to exist? Does the world require more proof that all
humans, male or female, have a propensity for deal-making,
backstabbing and power worship? Can Abramowitz really justify the
effort on the grounds that she's written a history of female
consciousness in the movie industry?''
</P>
<P>
   The answers to those questions are no; probably; and of course
not. The replies would have been different, though, if the book had
been independent-minded instead of worshipful and not written in
the gee-whiz jargon of celebrity profiles.
</P>
<P>
   There is, in fact, an interesting case study to be written about
women and Hollywood. Complain all you like, but as industries go,
the movie industry is relatively open to women and other outsiders.
Sure, Hollywood looks white and male, given the frat-like male
bonding that goes on in film crews and the networking that tends to
shut out minority executives, but that appearance is misleading.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to, say, brokerage firms, studios tend to be places
where people are judged more on their work product _ their
box-office results _ than on their sex or social profile. That
means Hollywood can often assimilate new networks _ black,
Hispanic, female, Australian, subcontinental Indian _ before other
businesses can. The process is slow and fraught, obviously, and
people from one network may have difficulties striking up the
necessary relationships with people from another. But the existence
of movies like ``Thelma &AMP; Louise'' tells us something of how far
women have come.
</P>
<P>
   You get a sense of how movie studios differ from other
workplaces when Abramowitz tells the tale of Marvin Davis, the
Denver oilman who bought Fox and couldn't grasp, on first meeting
Sherry Lansing, that she was Fox's head of production.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the oil business we only work with guys,'' he explains. ``I
never worked with a broad. So I thought she was supposed to get the
coffee.'' In other words, Hollywood looked like the land of radical
feminists from where Davis was sitting.
</P>
<P>
   In the book about women and Hollywood that people should read,
the writer's main task would be to disentangle sexual
discrimination (a structural flaw) and the clash of personalities
(which can happen in any group at any time). Unbundling the two
would be as rewarding in literary terms as it would be helpful
politically.
</P>
<P>
   Conflating them, on the other hand, as Abramowitz tends to do,
has the effect of reducing the larger-than-life qualities of
foul-mouthed telephone-slammer studio chief Dawn Steel or the
vulgar ball-busting agent Sue Mengers into something suitably
female, like insecurity, anxiety, the need to out-shriek the men,
or lack of socialization.
</P>
<P>
   Did their careers swing up and down because they were women,
because Hollywood is just like that, or because they were capable
of being completely, deliriously intransigent? What would it take
for a woman to gain recognition for being as big a monster (or
genius) as Samuel Goldwyn, Irving Thalberg, or Louis G. Mayer,
anyway?
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   Visit Slate on the Web at: http://www.slate.com
