<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, May 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, hail and damaging winds affected parts of the
interior Northeast as a potent jet stream disturbance swept across
the region. On Thursday, a cool front associated with the
disturbance will intercept a humid air mass, setting the stage for
more storms over the Carolinas and southern Appalachians. Farther
west, the front will become stationary, causing recurrent
thunderstorms in the southern and central Plains. Local flooding is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Gusty breezes will direct drier air into the Northeast. Amid
plentiful sunshine, daytime temperatures will reach seasonably warm
levels from Washington to New York City. However, moist air
circulating around low pressure will bring showers to New England
early Thursday. Sunshine will return to coastal sections Thursday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest will stay hot. Spotty thunderstorms will form over
some of the peaks of the southern Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WET AND DRY
</P>
<P>
   While concerns about drought are increasing in parts of the Deep
South, Binghamton, N.Y., has had the wettest start of any year on
record. Through Wednesday morning more than 22 inches of rain had
been recorded there. Typically, Binghamton gets about 15 inches of
rain in the first five months of the year. While areas that have
been exceptionally wet or dry always garner more attention, most of
the nation east of the Mississippi River is within the normal
historical range of precipitation this year.
</P>
