<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4651 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-TV-SHOWTIME-SPI &LR;      05-24 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SHOWTIME-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWTIME FIGURES YOUR BRAIN NEEDN'T GO ON HOLIDAY THIS WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stories are as different as black and white, but the similar
themes running through ``Dirty Pictures'' and ``On the Beach'' stir
up the gray matter like few films ever do on the big networks.
</P>
<P>
   One of the movies isn't even that good. But both manage to
instigate those little scholarly debates that rage inside the head
like a personal arts-and-lectures series whenever a provocative
idea is presented. It's what smart TV is about, and a tribute to
Showtime and its ``No Limits'' slogan, which apparently isn't just
a piece of advertising fluff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dirty Pictures'' is a gritty exploration of the obscenity case
involving the Cincinnati museum director whose decision to display
a controversial exhibit of photographs by the late Robert
Mapplethorpe made him the darling of First Amendment champions a
decade ago. ``On the Beach'' is a 1999 remake of the 1959 film
about people in Australia who have survived a nuclear war but
pretty much know their demise from radiation poisoning is only a
matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   Airing them a day apart may seem an odd choice, but Showtime
often does this sort of thing if only to prove that its programmers
are indeed interested in engaging the viewer's intellect. A concept
as foreign to the major networks as humility is to Frasier Crane,
it only makes Showtime look that much smarter on a holiday weekend
when the networks assume no one is watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   The jewel in this unlikely pairing, Saturday's ``Dirty
Pictures,'' features James Woods as Dennis Barrie, director of
Cincinnati's Contemporary Arts Center during the Mapplethorpe
dustup. His commitment exacted the kind of personal toll that
usually goes unnoticed when people are thrust into the spotlight
for standing on principles not shared by everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Barrie believed Mapplethorpe's exhibit, which included
photographs of naked children and scenes depicting homoerotic
activity, should not be censored or shut down simply because it
offended people. His defense of a person's right to see the
exhibit, free of intervention by the government or any group bent
on playing community guardian, caused him and his family
considerable harassment at the hands of bullies incapable of civil
discourse.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is enormously effective as a reluctant crusader torn
between storming the battlements and running from the fray. Diana
Scarwid is even better as Barrie's wife, Dianne, a woman wondering
if her staunch support of her husband against obscenity charges
will ultimately mean the loss of their home and irreparable harm to
their two young sons.
</P>
<P>
   Intercut with documentary-style interviews of prominent figures
on both sides of the issue, ``Dirty Pictures'' offers a keen
observation of what it takes to demonstrate courage, compassion,
honor and loyalty, and an even keener realization that noble
virtues don't always fit conveniently into the same jar on the
shelf of family values.
</P>
<P>
   Though far less successful as a dramatic piece, Sunday's ``On
the Beach,'' a three-hour Australian production, places the same
issues in an even more frightening setting. Anyone who can stay
with the over-theatrical presentation to the end should at least
come away with a stimulating set of ``what would I do?'' and ``with
whom would I do it?' questions if he or she were facing certain
death from nuclear fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Updated to 2006 to give currency to a concept most of us see as
an outdated vestige of the Cold War, the three-hour film remains
generally faithful to the original Nevil Shute novel about the last
days of civilization on this planet.
</P>
<P>
   Armand Assante plays Dwight Towers, the stony American submarine
commander thrust into post-apocalyptic Australia, the only place
where the bombs didn't hit. Dealing with the knowledge that his
family back in the States has been vaporized, Towers tentatively
tests the roiling waters of a relationship with a boozy floozy
named Moira Davidson, who likes him back but keeps her options open
with former flame Julian Osborne, one of Australia's best and
brightest and not ashamed to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be an Aussie film without Rachel Ward (Moira) or
real-life husband Bryan Brown (Julian), but neither manages to lift
``On the Beach'' off the carpet. The best performance comes from
Jacqueline McKenzie, who plays Mary Holmes, Moira's married sister,
with the only emotion that seems convincing and not shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``On the Beach'' poses tough, relevant questions about
personal obligations and choices, which isn't a bad reason for
remaking a movie.
</P>
<P>
   Dirty Pictures. Ninety-minute TV movie about an obscenity trial
arising from a Robert Mapplethorpe photography exhibit in 1989.
Starring James Woods, Diana Scarwid and Craig T. Nelson. Saturday
night on Showtime cable. MPAA rating: R.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   On the Beach. Three-hour TV movie about survivors of a nuclear
war confronting their likely demise. Starring Armand Assante,
Rachel Ward, Bryan Brown, Grant Bowler and Jacqueline McKenzie.
Sunday night on Showtime cable. Parental guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
