<P>
   PANDAS _ BEIJING _ Chairman Mao and the giant panda. Both are
icons of China. And it should come as no surprise that the tourists
from the hinterlands flocking into Beijing these days pay tribute
to both. Two stops are musts for Chinese tourists visiting their
capital city, says Liu Yingling, a representative of the All China
Journalists Association. One is Tiananmen Square, where the
visitors may see Mao's tomb and will certainly pause to have their
picture taken before his portrait that looms over the massive
plaza. The second mandatory stop is the panda compound of the
Beijing Zoo. No giant portrait looms here. But if one did, it
should perhaps show Wang Wanmin. Wang knows little of power
politics and perhaps is a little hazy even on efforts to preserve
the few remaining pandas in the wild. But 22 years ago his
government assigned him to a job feeding the pandas at the zoo and
he has taken to the task with total devotion. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ALAMIN-TAPES _ A newly obtained tape of radio traffic the night
Fulton Deputy Ricky Kinchen was killed, along with a transcript of
information provided to dispatch, suggest the possibility of a
fourth person on the scene. One caller reported seeing an injured
man one block away from the shooting scene begging for a ride. The
injured man was seen near the house that cops followed the
mysterious drops of blood to when they were searching for Kinchen's
killer. The defense is sure to make a big deal of this. (Good,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   FLY-LAWSUIT _ Lawyer F. Lee Bailey is geering up to sue the
county over it's rule that prohibits pure jet aircraft from flying
into the Lantana Airport. Bailey, who is rumored to want the ban
lifted for his own personal jet use, is representing a guy who owns
an aircraft upholstery business. That guy, Al Collie, was
threatened last month by the airport when it was discovered that he
was working on a plane that was banned from landing at the airport.
(Caputo, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
