<P>
   PARKS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's task force on
conservation is months away from issuing recommendations on state
parks, wildlife, private lands, urban sprawl and outdoor
recreation. A legislative panel reviewing the Texas Parks and
Wildlife Department is deliberating similar matters to guide
lawmakers when they convene in January. But two broad points of
debate have already emerged: money and politics. It is also clear
that any major conservation initiative would need the governor's
backing to win legislative approval. ``This session is potentially
going to be a make-it-or-break-it for parks and conservation in the
state. A lot of it rides on Bush,'' said Andy Jones, Texas program
coordinator for the Conservation Fund, a national land-conservation
group. (Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman)
