<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4653 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-WINE-COLUMN0525-COX     05-24 0425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-COLUMN0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nondrinking customers finally get a financial break at wine
dinners
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _
</P>
<P>
   Triple-tiered kudos this week:
</P>
<P>
   _ Lo those many years ago, when I started this wine-writing gig,
I tried to go to as many of the wine dinners around town as my
wallet would allow. And sometimes, depending on the menu and the
venue, I would persuade my wife _ who likes neither the taste nor
the effect of wine _ to join me, even though it meant paying the
full wine-and-food price for someone who was only going to consume
the food.
</P>
<P>
   After a while, emboldened by the awesome prestige that comes
from this position, I suggested to a few select organizers of these
wine dinners that perhaps they should offer a slightly discounted
price for nondrinking friends and spouses.
</P>
<P>
   Without exception, they looked at me as if I had just staggered
off a spaceship. I got the message and ceased my whining.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine my surprise when I saw the notice for Fairfield Wine's
upcoming $48-per-person wine dinner that included the following
addendum: For nondrinkers or designated drivers the cost is $35.
</P>
<P>
   Fairfield Wine proprietor Dennis Hall said he got the idea for
the two-tier pricing from customers whose spouses don't drink or
whose wives are pregnant and abstaining.
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure that small restaurants with a limited number of seats
for a wine dinner might have to charge full freight for every seat
to ensure the event recoups its costs. Still, it's nice to not feel
discriminated against because my dining companion chooses not to
drink. Maybe other folks will pick up on this suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, I guess, ideas _ like grapes _ just need time to
ripen.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Miami Valley's only four-star restaurant is making it
easier for customers to taste some of the finest wines in the
world. L'Auberge has launched what it calls its ``Four-Star
Spectator Wine Bar'' that offers bottles, glasses and tastes of
highly rated wines from 1997 Chalk Hill Chardonnay ($14 a glass, $7
a taste) to 1996 Robert Mondavi Reserve Cabernet Sauvignon ($35 a
glass, $18 a taste). Proprietor Josef Reif developed the idea, and
customer response has been overwhelmingly positive, according to
l'Auberge General Manager Alex Mchaikhi. The restaurant expanded
the selections this week, adding a California zinfandel, a
Washington State riesling and a ``real'' red Burgundy from _ yes _
France.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
