<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-0525-COX     05-24 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JUDGE MOVES TO BREAK UP MICROSOFT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON A federal judge Wednesday abruptly wrapped up the
Microsoft antitrust trial, setting the stage for a swift appeal of
a likely order to splinter the world's largest software company
into two or more parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not contemplating any further processes,'' U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson told John Warden, the lead defense
counsel, at the end of a four-hour remedy hearing called in
response to Jackson's sweeping April 3 ruling that Microsoft had
stifled innovation and harmed consumers by its anti-competitive
monopolistic practices.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson asked David Boies, who had prosecuted the case for the
Justice Department and 19 state attorneys general: ``How quickly
can you get me a final judgment in a form that reflects what
happened in court today?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we could have it in your hands by Friday,'' Boies
replied.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson then granted Microsoft's request for 48 hours to comment
on the final government draft.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers must now decide how best to revise their
April 28 plan to cleave the software giant into two separate firms:
an applications arm that markets such popular products as Office
and a Windows arm that markets the flagship Windows operating
system.
</P>
<P>
   During the hearing, Jackson repeatedly praised what he termed an
``excellent'' 65-page friend-of-the-court brief recently submitted
by two trade groups, the Software and Information Industries
Association and the Computer &AMP; Communications Industry Association.
</P>
<P>
   It proposed creating yet a third firm that would control
Microsoft's Internet businesses, such as Microsoft Network and its
Internet Explorer browser.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect of a bisection would, in effect, create two
separate monopolies,'' Jackson said. ``Tell me how that would
effectively inspire competition?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to divide the company into three Windows clones,
you would not have the kind of competition that would produce
innovation,'' Boies said. A two-way division would end Microsoft's
``control over both the applications and operating system,'' which
it used ``to protect each franchise,'' he argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two-part divestiture is also simpler to implement,'' Boies
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would appear to me that this is anything but simple to
implement,'' Jackson retorted. ``...Do you think Microsoft would be
a willing participant?''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson retains the freedom to craft his own set of remedies
under a timetable of his own choosing.
</P>
<P>
   But a shaken Microsoft team emerged from the courtroom convinced
that Jackson would issue has final order swiftly and that it would
track closely with, if not entirely reflect, the amended government
draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``From everything that was said and done today it would appear
that's the way the judge is headed,'' said Mark Murray, a Microsoft
spokesman who had sat through the 78-day trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very near the appellate phase of this controversy,''
Microsoft general counsel William Neukom said. ``On appeal,
Microsoft will be raising challenges to the procedures used
throughout this trial, including the remedy phase. We will be
challenging the findings of fact, the conclusions of law, and the
nature of any relief the judge might enter.''
</P>
<P>
   In spurning Microsoft's plea that it be granted up to six more
months to hold, in effect, another trial focused on the remedial
impact, Jackson noted tartly that ``this case has been pending for
two years.'' He found it ``ironic'' that the firm was asking for
more time in court instead of moving quickly to get to an appeals
court.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, the judge rose from the bench to end the
proceedings, prompting Murray, the Microsoft spokesman, to say:
``That's it. We're going to the (U.S.) Court of Appeals. We always
knew we'd end up there anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I submit this remedy is so extreme ... it will go a very long
way to ensure that Microsoft is the one company that won't win''
the next round of competition in the software industry, Warden had
argued.
</P>
<P>
   On major financial markets, Microsoft shares closed up $2.38 at
$65.56.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.doj.gov; www.microsoft.com/presspass/trial
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
