<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4656 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-WELFARE-TO-WORK-TEX     05-24 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-TO-WORK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPOWERING WOMEN WITH PRACTICAL WELFARE-TO-WORK HELP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It's been a long time since Rochelle Bunch
felt hopeful about the future.
</P>
<P>
   But when the 38-year-old mother of three encountered Lovie
Anderson recently at the Texas Department of Human Services,
Bunch's outlook on life changed dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard her say something about empowering women, and that got
my attention,'' Bunch said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Bunch was in the midst of an on-again-off-again
relationship with the state welfare system that had lasted nearly a
decade. Without public assistance, she could barely eke out a
living.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with help from Anderson's More Than Conquerors
organization, the Fort Worth mother is hoping to end her dependence
on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit More Than Conquerors organization seeks to
encourage economically disadvantaged women to improve their lives
by providing support. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bunch is one of more than 50 women enrolled in More Than
Conquerors. Anderson, a former welfare mom, started the group in
1994 shortly after she and her husband separated after 10 years of
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly a single parent with a son, living in Kansas, far from
her home in Temple, Texas, Anderson returned to school. ``I wanted
to become self-sufficient,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After earning a bachelor of science degree in sociology from
Kansas State University, Anderson took a job with the university
working with single parents and displaced homemakers.
</P>
<P>
   She moved to Fort Worth to be near her father, who was ill. A
supervisor at Cook Children's Medical Center encouraged her to get
her license in social work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to do something to help empower women,'' said
Anderson, who has since reconciled with her husband. ``I felt like
if I could do it, they could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of her own experiences on welfare, Anderson said, she
could motivate women to make the move from welfare to work.
</P>
<P>
   Since More Than Conquerors began in 1994, nearly 200 women have
received assistance through the organization's Support Network or
Success Boutique. The boutique provides free business suits to
women facing a Catch-22: They need appropriate clothes to get a
good job but cannot afford the clothes without a job.
</P>
<P>
   Women can also participate in Project SALES, (''Successfully
Activating Leadership and Employable Skills''), a professional
image and retail sales training program.
</P>
<P>
   The Support Network, Anderson said, helps participants overcome
a variety of obstacles, among them substance abuse and
dysfunctional family relationships.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, nearly a dozen women have gathered in a room at
J.A. Cavile Place, where the retail-training arm of the program is
held. They will hear from representatives from Mervyn's department
store and Kentucky Fried Chicken about the fine points of landing a
job.
</P>
<P>
   What do companies like these look for in prospective employees?
How important is experience? Appearance? What kind of benefits do
the companies offer? And most important, are they hiring?
</P>
<P>
   Jade Grasmeyer, who receives Aid for Families with Dependent
Children to help support her 6-year-old son, said she hopes to get
a managerial position in the retail business.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old single mother enrolled in the program in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to further my education and have better self-esteem,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bunch, who works as a data clerk and assistant dispatcher, said
that $7 an hour is the most she has ever earned, not nearly enough
to support her three children. Her husband is in prison, she said,
so public assistance has been as necessary as breathing.
</P>
<P>
   But with the help of More Than Conquerors, Bunch said, she
realizes she has more skills than she imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Managing my three children, being able to make and keep
appointments are little things I never saw as strengths,'' she
said. ``Being able to grocery shop and budget your money is a
skill.''
</P>
<P>
   Because substance abuse has devastated her family and community,
Bunch said, her long-term goal is to become a drug and alcohol
counselor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen drugs destroy so many people, especially where I
live,'' she said. ``I want to educate people about addiction. Maybe
I can help empower someone else.'' .MDBO/.MDNM/ (Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
