<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 18:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4661 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CANNES-FILM-2TAKES-NY     05-24 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANNES-FILM-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATIVE USE OF MUSIC ENLIVENS FILMS AT CANNES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANNES, France _ When the film festival here features as many
major directors taking their work in new directions as this year's
did, that's notable.
</P>
<P>
   The collection included a soulful action film by the master of
comedy of manners, Ang Lee, ``Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon,''
which featured Chow Yun Fat brimming with physical grace and was
held together by an ethereal calm as its battlers soared through
the air. There was ``Nurse Betty,'' a comedy with a warm touch by
the director-provocateur Neil LaBute.
</P>
<P>
   And there were movies from three major filmmakers that tried to
expand the horizons of the musical: Lars Von Trier's ``Dancer in
the Dark,'' Wong Kar-wei's ``In the Mood for Love'' and Joel and
Ethan Coen's ``Oh, Brother, Where Art Thou?'' Two of those musical
departures, ``Dancer'' and ``Mood,' received major recognition from
the jury at the festival, which ended on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancer,'' which won the Palme d'Or and the best actress award
for its star, Bjork, in her acting debut, is a melodrama with
musical elements. For Von Trier, trying something new did not seem
to cause the slightest furrow in his brow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm completely sure I'm doing wonderful things,'' he said, a
nervous smile playing around the corners of his mouth. ``That's
because my mother always said I was doing wonderful things. Even
Napoleon's mother said: `No, no. You're tall!'''
</P>
<P>
   It is the first time that Von Trier has used musical scenes in a
film, and he disturbed some conventions of the form. Except for the
musical numbers that erupt from the imagination of Bjork's
character, the film has no music, not even an underscore. Such
music irritates him, he said, calling it cheap manipulation. ``I'm
cheating people in smarter ways,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dancer'' had its first public showing here, and the movie, in
which Bjork plays Selma, a woman slowly going blind and working
several shifts to raise money for an operation that can save her
son's sight, left the audience sobbing. The film has plot gambits
that would have seemed shameless even in the silent era. Selma
plays the leading role in her small town's production of ``The
Sound of Music'' _ it's one of the few things that keeps her going
_ and she stars in big musical numbers in her imagination.
</P>
<P>
   This could be Von Trier's ``Pennies From Heaven,'' the BBC
series by Dennis Potter in which full-scale musical numbers
exploded in the characters' minds as a way of relieving the gloom
of their existence. But Von Trier said: ``I wasn't fond of
`Pennies.' I don't like making fun of genres, which maybe he was.''
</P>
<P>
   The character of Selma in ``Dancer'' carries on the tradition of
the suffering female protagonist. ``She loves Technicolor musicals
and human beings with flaws,'' Von Trier said. The decisions she
makes send her spiraling into tragedy. ``From a logical point of
view, the women have a choice,'' he added. ``From their point of
view, they don't have a choice. It's a very romantic thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Von Trier may have found his battles with Bjork neither romantic
nor logical. She submerged herself so deeply into the character
that she seemed to feel he was her torturer. The director said he
had feared that the strains would wreck his career and his
marriage. As a line goes in a song she sang with her old band, the
Sugarcubes: ``This wasn't supposed to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Bjork is evidently as controlling and stubborn as he is, though
in ``Dancer'' she chose to play a character with no control, one
whose life contrasts with her own powerful and affirming pop music.
Perhaps the most striking thing about her speaking voice is how
similar it is to her singing.
</P>
<P>
   The picture introduces Selma and others rehearsing ``My Favorite
Things.'' It's a moving, rough-hewn opening that will feel like a
new Bjork demo to her fans. To the uninitiated it will be a
riveting insight into Selma's fervor. Von Trier has an instinct for
drawing audiences into his work.
</P>
<P>
   NO MONOLOGUES
</P>
<P>
   For LaBute the Cannes festival provided a rare chance to present
a film that he hadn't written. ``Nurse Betty'' received the writing
award for its script by John C. Richards. ``I read it and thought
it was more charming than anything I'd write,'' the director said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betty'' is a road comedy starring Renee Zellweger as a
traumatized woman who believes she's a character from her favorite
soap opera and who heads west to meet the show's star, played by
Greg Kinnear, while being followed by a pair of hit men, played by
Morgan Freeman and Chris Rock. ``This movie has the first girl
character in one of my movies who's not a victim, and maybe that's
because I didn't write it,'' LaBute continued. ``I liked that
aspect and didn't want to muddy the waters by getting my hands in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   This film has a thematic similarity to LaBute's ``In the Company
of Men'' and ``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' in that the
protagonist is looking to change her life and intent on finding
what she needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true, everyone is searching for an ideal in this one,''
he said. ``It's something I see in myself.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute said he was intrigued by the script because the central
character, Betty, was an innocent who survived because of her
purity, embodied by Zellweger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie really is so much Renee,'' he said. ``I know it's a
cliche, but that is who she is. But it's also so much Morgan, who
tests you, and in the best way, I think. He doesn't suffer fools,
and I don't either.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBute said he had felt he needed to take on someone else's
material for a change. ``Directing a script I didn't write is less
emotional and more analytical for me,'' he added. ``I was much more
able to look at it and see what worked. There are no monologues in
this movie, and I'm known for that in my work. I checked that
impulse and cut scenes that had them. I like movies that push
buttons, and `Nurse Betty' will push a set of different ones: `Is
he a sell-out?' Oh, it's nice. Maybe I was wrong about him.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A NEW GRAMMAR
</P>
<P>
   ``Betty'' wasn't the only likable and noteworthy comedy here.
The director Roy Andersson's stylized, eccentric and funny ``Songs
From the Second Floor'' won one of two Jury Prizes. This deadpan
comedy is built around beautifully composed frames captured by a
stationary camera: It's a series of bleak but comic vignettes about
faith and alienation that might have been conceived by Gary Larson,
creator of the ``Far Side'' newspaper cartoons.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the major moments at the festival came from directors
engaging in sudden twists and turns. There were a number of
noteworthy Iranian films, including ``Blackboard,'' which won the
other Jury Prize. This drama, with flickers of comedy and startling
flashes of violence, is the work of a young director, Samira
Makhmalbaf.
</P>
<P>
   There were several impressive sophomore efforts: ``Requiem for a
Dream,'' adapted from Hubert Selby Jr.'s novel by Darren Aronofsky,
and ``The Yards,'' directed by James Gray with a stately moodiness
and a socialist punch right out of Visconti.
</P>
<P>
   And there was ``In the Mood for Love,'' the director Wong
Kar-wai's gorgeous romantic drama, which won the best actor prize
for its star, Tony Leung. Wong thinks with a camera and with each
film he seems to be inventing a new grammar for the medium. No one
can cut within a scene the way he can, using edits to express
shifts in feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Cannes had such an intriguing range of films that, by the final
night, when the awards were handed out, there was no consensus
about the Palme d'Or. People were divided between ``Dancer,'' which
won the prize, and ``In the Mood for Love.'' Both films were highly
anticipated and made the biggest impact here. Both, not
incidentally, wrung new twists from the use of music to delineate
the melancholy of the characters.
</P>
<P>
   The festival was proof that a director's vision can resuscitate
any genre. Already the buzz is that westerns will be the next to be
rescued, but let's not get ahead of ourselves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
