<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4664 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-VIEQUES-CLAIMS-HNS &LR;      05-24 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIEQUES-CLAIMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VIEQUES RESIDENTS SEEK DAMAGES FROM NAVY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Stands for VIEQUES-LAWSUIT)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A lawyer representing residents of the Puerto Rican
island of Vieques said Wednesday his clients are seeking at least
$40 million in damages from the Navy, which has used the island as
a target range for decades.
</P>
<P>
   John Arthur Eaves Jr., a lawyer from Jackson, Miss., said he is
filing more than 200 claims this week asking the Navy to repay
residents for years of bombings that the attorney alleges have
contributed to higher rates of cancer and other illnesses among
residents than among inhabitants of nearby islands.
</P>
<P>
   If the Navy does not agree to compensate the residents within
six months, Eaves said, his firm will file a lawsuit to recover
damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to Vieques, every family in some way has had to deal
with cancer,'' Eaves told a news conference in Washington. ``The
60-year bombings on Vieques are causing these people to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaves said he expects the U.S. government will pay his clients
between $200,000 and $15 million each in damages for lost health,
future medical monitoring and pain and suffering.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is working with Congress to provide
$40 million in economic development assistance to Vieques, plus
another $50 million if islanders approve a referendum to resume
live-fire training at the bombing range. Currently, the military is
limited to inert munitions in its training exercises.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has used Vieques as a training ground since 1941,
firing live ammunition and dropping bombs on the eastern part of
the island and in the water along its coast.
</P>
<P>
   The 9,300 residents of Vieques live on about one-third of the
island, removed from the military site.
</P>
<P>
   Residents have long claimed that the bombings churn up dust
contaminated with toxins that are blown onto the inhabited portion
of the island.
</P>
<P>
   But the Navy says Vieques, to the east of the main island of
Puerto Rico, is the only viable site in the region that allows for
realistic combat training.
</P>
<P>
   However, Vieques was closed to the military in April 1999 after
a Marine-piloted plane dropped two bombs off target, killing a
civilian security guard employed by the Navy and wounding four
other civilians. The Navy reopened the range earlier this month to
renew military exercises after federal agents removed protesters
from the training site.
</P>
<P>
   Eaves urged the military to vacate the island permanently, but
said such a step would not be sufficient compensation for
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``These families have sacrificed more than their fair share of
freedom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eaves suggested the Navy had targeted Vieques because of it is
part of the commonwealth of Puerto Rico and not one of the 50
states and because its inhabitants are predominantly Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would the residents of Long Island, Miami Beach or Martha's
Vineyard tolerate this bombing?'' he asked. He charged that
``environmental racism'' is the only reason the Navy has chosen
Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two-year-old Milivy Adams Calderon and her parents, Jose and
Zulayko, joined Eaves and two physicians at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Zulayko said through a translator that his daughter was
born with cancerous tumors and has undergone several courses of
chemotherapy. He said she has already had a brain operation and
still needs another operation. Jose blamed the Navy for dangerous
conditions on the island that led to his daughter's illness.
</P>
<P>
   Eaves is seeking more than $15 million from the Navy for the
girl, including money for medical monitoring, personal injury and
``fear and fright.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Carmen Ortiz-Roque, one of two physicians appearing with
Eaves, said residents of Vieques had higher cancer rates and
incidences of heart disease, liver disease and hypertension than
residents of mainland Puerto Rico and the nearby city of Fajardo.
Although she admitted the areas are not comparable in size, wealth
or quality of medical care, she said the differences in instances
of illness so large that ``this is not a chance event.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Neftali Garcia-Martinez said he discovered larger amounts of
harmful substances such as lead in soil samples on the military
part of the island and in lowlands where sediments accumulate.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the evidence points to the Navy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
