<HEADER>
A4666 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-LOOKBACK0525-COX     05-24 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LOOKBACK0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Last season's winners and losers
 &HT;    By Kevin Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   TV WINNERS
</P>
<P>
   Who wants to be like Regis? Everyone!
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants To Be A Millionaire'' : Huge ratings, Reege's GQ-ish
suits, easy questions. ABC's monster game show and the season's
most-watched program single-handedly saved ABC and made ``Is that
your final answer?'' the nation's hottest (and most tiresome) catch
phrase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Malcolm in the Middle'' : Not only did Fox's killer comedy
revive a stale genre, it made me howl in laughter each week. It
also earned my instant respect by daring not to play by the
standard sitcom rules. After all, how often do you see hairy, naked
dads getting shaved in front of their kids? Or asthmatic,
wheelchair-bound black kids playing . . . hockey?
</P>
<P>
   ``WWF Smackdown!'' : More than 7 million viewers tuned in to see
``The Rock &AMP; Co.'' each week. With a jaw-dropping combination of
sex, soap and in-your-face physicality, Smackdown! put the
directionless UPN on the network map.
</P>
<P>
   James Marsters: As the acid-tongued, blond-haired Spike on
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' the scene-chewing Marsters is often
sharper than one of Buffy's stakes. Cheers to the WB for beefing up
Spike's role.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Locklear: She's blonde, beautiful and surprisingly
funny. Who knew? As the Mayor's bumbling campaign manager on ``Spin
City,'' Locklear proved to be a dead-on comedienne.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of ``Friends'' : A serious pay raise at a staggering
$750,000 an episode for two years. Need I say more?
</P>
<P>
   TV LOSERS
</P>
<P>
   Why did anyone want to marry Rick?
</P>
<P>
   Rick Rockwell and Darva Conger: C'mon . . . is an explanation
really necessary? The ``stars'' of ``Who Wants To Marry A
Multi-Millionaire?'' made even reality TV programmers embarrassed.
And that's hard to do!
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Love Hewitt: Despite her nice impersonation of Audrey
Hepburn in a TV movie, ratings for Hewitt's dismal ``Time of Your
Life'' were smaller than Mini-Me. But Hewitt gets a second chance
when ``Time of Your Life'' _ ugh! _ returns June 14.
</P>
<P>
   WB: OK, so ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer and Angel'' are two of
TV's best shows. But this once rising network lost serious ground
to UPN _ UPN, for crying out loud!
</P>
<P>
   Teen shows: ``Freaks and Geeks,'' ``Wasteland, D.C.'' and
``Brutally Normal'' were booted. ``Felicity'' and ``Roswell ``
almost were, and ``Dawson's Creek'' and ``Popular `` struggled. See
a trend here? TV shows should grow up and stay out of high schools.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of ``Falcone'' : Unfortunately, CBS' fine mob drama
fell victim to unfavorable comparisons to ``The Sopranos'' and the
network's questionable programming strategy. This show deserved a
better fate.
</P>
<P>
   Minority actors: I see white people. Once again, the networks
left actors of color woefully underrepresented on television. After
getting blasted by TV critics and the NAACP, producers of such
shows as ``The West Wing'' scrambled to add more black and Latino
actors to their casts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
