<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, May 25 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ In one of the most significant and
hotly debated foreign policy decisions that Congress has faced, the
House voted Wednesday to grant China permanent normal trading
relations, handing President Clinton a major foreign policy
triumph. After an intense debate that encompassed human rights,
protection of American jobs and national security, the House voted
237-197 in favor of the bill. By Eric Schmitt and Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-ASSESS (Washington) _ With his narrow victory
Wednesday on trade with China, President Clinton has finally
defined his imprint on U.S. foreign policy: As the president who
conducted the post-Cold War experiment of using American economic
power to foster political change among America's neighbors and its
potential adversaries. It is a path he set out on in 1993, when 10
months into his presidency he defied his own party and pushed
through the North American Free Trade agreement with Mexico and
Canada. A news analysis by David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The federal judge trying the
Microsoft antitrust case raised serious questions about the
government's plan to break up the company during a court hearing
Wednesday, but seemed to be suggesting that he did not think the
plan went far enough. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   LEBANON-SCENE (Marjayoun, Lebanon) _ This hillside Christian
village, with its church spires and sweets shops, was the
picturesque military center of the Israeli occupation of southern
Lebanon for two decades. Before noon Wednesday, the morning after
the occupation zone prematurely collapsed, its stores were
shuttered and its cobblestone streets nearly empty but for two
young men with a clipboard. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT1,2.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM-PARTY (Tucson, Ariz.) _ The growing likelihood that Pat
Buchanan will become the presidential nominee of the Reform Party
is producing a backlash from some party members and leaders around
the country. Efforts are under way to derail him, and even those
who recognize the inevitability of it all wonder what the party
will look like in the future. Some want Ross Perot to run again,
although that appears unlikely; some like Ralph Nader, and some
think the party should have no nominee at all this year. By Michael
Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-PINOCHET (Lima, Peru) _ A Chilean appeals court has
stripped the immunity of retired Gen. Augusto Pinochet, removing an
important obstacle to his possible trial on charges that he was
involved in the kidnapping, murder and torture of thousands during
his 17 years as Chile's dictator. The decision is subject to a
Supreme Court reversal and it could take years of legal wrangling
before any trial could begin. The decision, voted in private
Tuesday but leaked to the local media, demonstrates that Chile's
courts are willing to take independent stands. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SCHOOLS-TURNOVER (New York) _ Shante Proctor, a fifth-grader
at PS 190, has had four teachers this year. In four years, her
school has had three principals. Her classmates have also changed
regularly. Poverty _ in the guise of evictions, job changes,
assignment to homeless shelters _ has kept them on the move. For
every 10 students at PS 190 who started with Shante in September,
four were gone by June. Low-performing public schools are often
criticized for flabby curriculums, petty politics and lack of
rigor. PS 190 is no exception. But mobility has become a growing
concern for school systems across the country as housing costs
rise, families immigrate or change neighborhoods, and teachers
leave the profession or shift schools. By Lynette Holloway.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
