<HEADLINE>
CUPPA JOE MAY PROTECT THE BRAIN FROM PARKINSON'S  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 475-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By JEREMY LAURANCE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Coffee drinkers who rely on a regular caffeine shot
to get them through the day may also be protecting their brains
from the effects of premature aging.
</P>
<P>
   Research indicates that the world's most popular beverage not
only provides a temporary boost to mental alertness but may also
help prevent brain degeneration.
</P>
<P>
   After a number of studies suggesting that coffee increases the
risk of heart attacks, the new findings are the first to suggest it
has long-term beneficial effects.
</P>
<P>
   The study of 8,000 middle-aged Japanese-American men in Honolulu
who have been followed for 30 years found those who consumed most
caffeine had the lowest incidence of Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Men who drank most coffee _ equivalent to four to five ordinary
cups or two large ones a day _ had one-fifth of the risk of
Parkinson's than those who drank none. A similar relationship was
found for men who consumed caffeine from other sources, including
cola, chocolate and tea.
</P>
<P>
   Caffeine is known to improve short-term memory, boost muscle
power and increase alertness. The link between coffee and heart
disease has been shown but is nothing to do with the caffeine it
contains. Caffeine is broadly thought to be safe but there is
debate about how much is too much and whether there is a real risk
of caffeine addiction.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors say that for most people up to 400mg a day of caffeine _
equivalent to four cups of fresh coffee or six of instant _ is
unlikely to cause side-effects. Above that the risk of such
symptoms as anxiety, trembling and headache increases but tolerance
varies widely.
</P>
<P>
   Anxious, nervy people are most strongly affected and some, such
as pregnant women, are slower to metabolize the drug, so that with
repeated doses blood levels rise. Doctors say that to describe
those who regularly consume more than 400mg a day as addicted is an
abuse of the term.
</P>
<P>
   In the new study, published in the Journal of the American
Medical Association, researchers from the Department of Veterans
Affairs who analyzed data from the 8,000 men enrolled in the
Honolulu Heart program in the mid-1960s found that by the mid-1990s
102 had Parkinson's.
</P>
<P>
   It was found that the risk of Parkinson's declined consistently
with increasing quantities of coffee or other caffeine-containing
beverages. ``It appears caffeine may be the constituent responsible
for the observed reduction in Parkinson's disease,'' the authors
say.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers offer two possible explanations for their
findings. The first is that men who drank little or no coffee may
have had an intolerance to caffeine that could be related to a
higher propensity to develop Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   The second explanation is that ``regular exposure to caffeine
over many years might counteract the aging-related degenerative
processes that cause loss of dopamine neurons, the brain pathology
associated with Parkinson's disease.'' &QL; 
