<HEADLINE>
A TIN OF SARDINES IS NATURE'S PROZAC  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 250-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By JEREMY LAURANCE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ People seeking a non-drug alternative to
antidepressants should visit their fishmonger, an expert on brain
development said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have long known the benefits of oily fish in the fight
against heart disease but it is just as vital as a brain food,''
Professor Michael Crawford, the director of the Institute of Brain
Chemistry and Human Nutrition at North London University, England,
said.
</P>
<P>
   The world is in the grip of a global epidemic of depression,
which has followed the global epidemic of heart disease, and could
be linked to eating less seafood than previously, Crawford said.
</P>
<P>
   He was commenting on a survey commissioned by the British Trout
Association, which shows that one-fifth of the population eat no
oily fish, rising to one-third of those aged 15 to 24. Most people
eat half the amount they would have eaten 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford said that the findings were ``extremely worrying.''
Oily fish, such as sardines, mackerel, trout, tuna and salmon,
contain Omega-3 fatty acids, vital for a healthy brain and nervous
system.
</P>
<P>
   A World Health Organization report last year identified
depression as the number one cause of disability in the U.S. and
the third biggest, behind heart disease and strokes, in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In cutting down on fatty foods against heart disease, people
``have got rid of the thing which really protects the brain... oily
fish and seafood,'' Crawford said. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 250-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
