<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4681 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MUSIC-COPYRIGHT-925(2     05-24 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-COPYRIGHT-925(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.) 
 MUSICIANS TAKE COPYRIGHT ISSUE TO CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A brief amendment to the copyright law has pitted musicians
against recording companies over the question of who owns
recordings: the companies that finance and market them or the
musicians who perform them?
</P>
<P>
   At stake is control over recordings beginning 35 years after
recordings were first released, when many of them are still
extremely valuable. The debate is highly technical, but it has
inflamed passions and turned musicians into political organizers.
</P>
<P>
   The musicians want the copyright law changed to designate them
the legal authors of their recordings. With this designation they
would be able to reclaim the rights they often granted to recording
companies when they were young and inexperienced and take control
of assets that have generated billions of dollars for those
companies. They could sell the rights to new bidders or exploit
them themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But if the recording companies are held to be the authors _ as
they are under the amendment that was enacted last year _ they will
retain those rights for the full length of the copyright, 95 years.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment, which was advocated by recording companies, was
inserted without debate into an unrelated bill in Congress last
November. It has spurred protests by musicians and organizations
like the National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences, which
presents the Grammy Awards; the American Federation of Musicians;
the American Federation of Television and Radio Artists, which
represents vocalists; and AmSong, a songwriters' organization. A
House subcommittee is to hold hearings on the issue Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The four-line amendment explicitly added sound recordings as a
category of copyrighted materials that can be considered ``work
made for hire'' under the 1976 Federal Copyright Act. To come under
this category, the work would have to be defined that way in
musicians' contracts with recording companies. Although such
language often has been included in contracts _ usually in cases
when fledgling musicians have little bargaining power _ many
musicians and their lawyers have questioned whether the
work-for-hire provisions were ever valid under the copyright law.
The amendment ends those questions.
</P>
<P>
   Works for hire are collective works, like movies or atlases,
that are commissioned by studios or publishers as employers; the
employers have the rights of authors for copyright purposes. Most
recordings are also collaborations; they involve producers,
engineers, packagers and backup musicians as well as the performer
whose name is on the cover.
</P>
<P>
   Recording companies had written into typical contracts that
sound recordings are works for hire, commissioned by the company or
made by performers and technicians hired as employees. Otherwise,
they say, contributors to a recording might claim joint authorship
and create a chaos when the copyright reverts to its listed authors
in 35 years.
</P>
<P>
   For contracts dated Jan. 1, 1978, the copyright act promised
authors a second chance by allowing them to reclaim their
copyrights after 35 years by exercising what the law calls a
termination right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the new law,'' Marybeth Peters, the register of
copyrights at the U.S. Copyright Office, told the industry
publication Billboard recently, ``artists absolutely had the right
to reclaim them.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters said that with the change in law, ``U.S. recording
artists are the most unprotected segment of the entire world of
copyright.''
</P>
<P>
   But the recording companies' trade group, the Recording Industry
Association of America, contends that the amendment is simply a
clarification of the 1976 copyright bill, which, they say, covered
recordings under the wording ``collective works'' and
``compilations.''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Baumgarten, who helped draft the 1976 law, served as general
counsel for the Copyright Office and has represented the industry
association on other matters, said: ``This is not a major change in
the way things have been since 1976. The typical sound recording,
an album, fits precisely the category of collective work, and if
the artist signs a contract acknowledging that it should be treated
as a work for hire, that's the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Goldstein, a professor at Stanford Law School and the
author of ``Copyright,'' a basic legal text (Aspen Law and
Business), supported this view. ``I don't know that the second
chance was there to begin with, given the way Congress designed
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But many musicians and their lawyers disagree. ``This is a
seismic shift in the copyright law,'' said Michael Greene,
president of the academy of recording arts and sciences. ``You
don't do this in the dead of night without participation from the
people who are writing the songs.''
</P>
<P>
   Many musicians' lawyers had assumed that because sound
recordings were not specifically named as a category of works for
hire, performers still retained the rights of authorship even if
they signed contracts that said otherwise. In the event of a
dispute, they expected that a court would resolve the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new amendment, if a musician has agreed to
work-for-hire status in a contract, the recording company becomes
the author. The author of, for example, the next Sheryl Crow album
would be not Crow but Interscope Records. Crow is scheduled to
testify at Thursday's hearing before the Judiciary Committee's
Subcommittee on Courts and Intellectual Property.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The rise of the Internet has made the music business even more
litigious than usual. In battles with online music companies, the
industry association has presented itself as an advocate for
musicians. But the copyright change points to where the interests
of recording companies and musicians diverge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public needs to understand that the RIAA does not and
never has represented recording artists,'' said the songwriter and
musician Don Henley, referring to the recording industry
association. He is a founder of the Artists' Coalition, a
musicians' trade group galvanized by the copyright change.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment was placed in the unrelated Satellite Home Viewer
Improvement Act in response to an industry request by a staff
lawyer for the House subcommittee. It was attached to an omnibus
spending bill that was passed last November.
</P>
<P>
   Hilary Rosen, president of the recording industry association,
conceded that the way that the change was adopted had angered
musicians. ``I am no longer willing to defend the process,'' she
said. ``The issue is about where we go from here on the substance.
People in the record industry have always believed that sound
recordings were eligible as works for hire. That's why this
amendment did not seem outrageous to them. It's not about stealing
authorship.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1976 copyright law, rights to recordings would begin
to revert in 2013. It is hard to predict how broadly the recording
companies would be affected.
</P>
<P>
   A 1994 article for ``Entertainment, Publishing and the Arts
Handbook'' (West Group), by Randy S. Frisch and Matthew J. Fortnow,
called the situation a ``time bomb'' for recording companies. It
pointed out that for the labels, sales of older recordings are more
profitable than sales of new releases, since costs have been
recouped and older contracts have lower royalty rates.
</P>
<P>
   The amendment sets out to defuse the time bomb. If the
recordings are works for hire, author's rights would continue to
belong to the recording company for the full term of the copyright:
95 years for a work for hire or 70 years after the author's death.
Depending on whether the amendment is considered a technical or
substantive change _ a matter still undecided _ it will either
cover recordings made after 1978 or since its passage last year.
</P>
<P>
   Crow said that her contract called her recordings works for
hire. But she does not consider herself an employee commissioned by
the recording company. ``As an artist,'' she said, ``I author the
material, I hire my musicians, I book the studio time, I hire my
engineer, I compose the work, I hand it in.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Howard Coble, R-N.C., chairman of the Subcommittee on
Courts and Intellectual Property, who scheduled Thursday's
hearings, said that all of the conference members _ Democrat and
Republican _ had approved the amendment and that the process had
not been unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, it was my belief that opponents of the
work-for-hire language were overreacting,'' Coble said. ``I may be
wrong; maybe they're not overreacting. I'd like to hear from both
sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Jake Seiwert, a White House press spokesman, said that while the
Clinton administration was aware of the issue, it had not yet taken
a position.
</P>
<P>
   Musicians hope to see the provision repealed after the hearings.
``I'm sympathetic with everybody who's unhappy with this,'' Rosen
of the industry association said. ``I'm looking for a way out, but
I'm not sure what that is right now. It would be nice to find a way
not to have people feel so cheated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
