<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4683 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-HENLEY-LIGHTENS-UP-TE     05-24 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HENLEY-LIGHTENS-UP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLDER, HAPPIER DON HENLEY HAS LIGHTENED UP _ JUST A TAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don Henley's sincerity was never in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was his determination: The Texas native helped make the
Eagles rock icons and then released three solo records that became
synonymous with radio-friendly, mature pop-rock.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was his talent questioned: There's no denying the care and
craftsmanship that went into songs such as ``The Heart of the
Matter, The End of the Innocence'' or ``The Boys of Summer'' _ or
all those Eagles hits he co-wrote, usually with Glenn Frey.
</P>
<P>
   And there was his commitment to worthy projects: He tirelessly
spearheaded the successful efforts to save Walden Woods, raising
millions through benefit shows and the sales generated by ``Common
Thread: The Songs of the Eagles.''
</P>
<P>
   No, the questions that begged to be asked where Henley is
concerned is: Would he ever just lighten up? Could he?
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, after all, were adept at exposing the ravages of
excess that loomed behind the sun-kissed California good times and
enormous wealth that came with success. Be careful what you wish
for, say their most famous songs, ``Hotel California'' and ``Life
in the Fast Lane,'' because it'll eat you alive if you get it.
</P>
<P>
   And while he could have been basking in his success in the late
'70s, Henley was hunkered down in a recording studio for several
years, giving himself an ulcer while finishing the band's final
studio LP, the tired, strained ``The Long Run.''
</P>
<P>
   Henley's solo career has made clear that he was largely
responsible for the Eagles' often-dour outlook. With the release of
three solo albums between 1982 and 1989, Henley added a
synthesized, bulked-up, often dance-ready sheen to his tales of
failed relationships and the ennui of aging '70s partyers and
dropped in some pointed references to Ronald Reagan and the
troubles in Central America. Presto! Here was a catalog of smart,
hummable, politically correct music that people in their 30s could
relate to, pop that refused to be dumbed down.
</P>
<P>
   Right down to his trademark style of wearing a lumberjack shirt
loose over a tucked-in T-shirt, Henley became something of an icon
for people picking their way through the realities of growing up
wild in the '70s and trying to become useful _ if still cool _
adults in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   No, Don Henley will never be Mr. Happy-Go-Lucky, and those
looking for everything's-great tunes should look elsewhere than his
new CD, ``Inside Job,'' his first since 1989's ``The End of the
Innocence.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this a surprise? No. And Henley knows it. The CD's leitmotif
is ``Everything Is Different Now,'' which details why there's a
(relatively) sunnier outlook on ``Inside:'' Henley's marriage in
May 1995 to his Dallas girlfriend, Sharon Summerall.
</P>
<P>
   And in fact, ``Inside'' is the most subdued CD he's ever done.
There are a few danceable tracks _ most notably the opener,
``Nobody Else in the World but You'' _ but many more quieter songs;
one, the countryish ``For My Wedding'' is destined to be played at
wedding receptions from now until, probably, the end of time.
</P>
<P>
   But back to ``Everything.'' The song opens with the lines ``I
hate to tell you this, but I'm very, very happy/And I know that's
not what you'd expect from me at all.'' The catch is, Henley
delivers those lines in a low, almost sneering near-whisper; he
makes the best news he's had in more than a decade sound like he's
daring us to step outside and just try to kick his behind.
</P>
<P>
   Don Henley doesn't trust happiness or easy answers and doesn't
think we should, either. The closest thing to sheer fun on
``Inside'' is ``They're Not Here, They're Not Coming,'' a catchy
little tune whose theme is that aliens aren't going to help us
humans out until we clean up our own mess.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when pop music from 'N Sync to Eminem to Britney to
Christina to Korn caters almost exclusively to people 25 and under
_ often way under _ it will be interesting to see how ``Inside
Job'' fares. After all, critics can sing the praises of mature
singer/songwriters such as Randy Newman, Richard Thompson and Tom
Waits all day, but they don't sell records. Not many, anyhow.
Henley has a leg up on them in terms of pop success and mass name
recognition, but as ``Inside'' hits the shelves there are only two
other solo male artists in the ``Billboard'' Top 30: One is Carlos
Santana, and the other is Dr. Dre.
</P>
<P>
   Henley would seem not to care. Perhaps because he's already very
rich, or perhaps because he feels no need to prove himself again,
``Inside'' makes no concessions to the current rock marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary. The title track, ``Workin' It'' and ``Nobody
Else in the World but You'' look askance at the very
me-me-me/blink-and-you-miss-it culture of chattering cellphones and
surface beauty and on-and-gone pop stardom. Henley sees much of the
populace as disconnected from one other, obsessed with how much can
be bought, never content, unable to sustain anything for longer
than a few minutes, spinning our wheels as America's best days (and
ours as individuals) fade.
</P>
<P>
   All three songs are built on the idea that people are being
force-fed things that are bad for them, that we've become far too
sheeplike. Like Patti Smith on her recent ``Gung Ho,'' Henley rails
against how far we've come to accept letting other people make our
decisions for us.
</P>
<P>
   This is not exactly the kind of material that will fit easily
between ``Oops! ... I Did It Again'' and that thong song. And to be
sure, ``Inside Job'' _ although intelligent, faultlessly
constructed and passionately performed _ has moments when it feels
more stern than hopeful. One or two more upbeat songs would have
done wonders, even something with the nasty aftertaste of a ``Get
Over It'' or ``All She Wants to Do Is Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there's a pleasing, settled maturity of outlook at
work here, one that makes sense if you're growing older and coming
out of your own wild days and content in a long-lasting
relationship. The CD's final song, ``My Thanksgiving,'' winds the
record down beautifully. It's a wonderfully simple song that
celebrates self-knowledge and appreciating each day _ and
recognizing that it's the good and bad together that give a person
character and point of view.
</P>
<P>
   This may be a hard sell to a 20-year-old, but for all of us who
decided to step back from the edge before our bad habits killed us
and who don't equate growing older with a terminal disease,
``Inside Job'' is a record that provides a certain measure of
comfort. As Carl Perkins once said, if there weren't any rocks in
the river, the water wouldn't have no song.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
