<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4687 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-TV-AWARDS0523-COX     05-24 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-AWARDS0523-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TV Awards for the 1999-2000 season
 &HT;    Kevin D. Thompson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _
</P>
<P>
   WHAT WERE THEY THINKING?
</P>
<P>
   Networks make dumb moves all the time . . . so do TV stars.
</P>
<P>
   NBC for ever allowing the no-talent Elle Macpherson to
guest-star on ``Friends.'' Stick to the runways, honey, where you
don't have to talk.
</P>
<P>
   CBS for bringing JonBenet's grisly murder to television in
``Perfect Murder, Perfect Town.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Williamson for leaving ``Dawson's Creek,'' a buzz-heavy,
well-acted drama, to create ``Wasteland,'' ABC's laughably
atrocious teen drama. I still have laughing fits whenever I think
about Rebecca Gayheart's horrendous Southern accent.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Priestly for believing he could cut it as a tough
detective in ``Homicide: The Movie.'' Get real. . . Mickey Mouse
could do better interrogations.
</P>
<P>
   ABC for its ill-advised attempt to recapture the magic that
existed between Mary Richards and Rhoda Morgenstern on ``The Mary
Tyler Moore Show.'' The TV movie ``Mary and Rhoda'' didn't make it
after all.
</P>
<P>
   ABC gets another for replacing the irreverent ``Sports Night ``
with the insipid sitcom ``Talk to Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Juliana Marguiles for turning down a reported $27 million to
stay on ``ER `` for two more seasons. Did she miss George Clooney
that much?
</P>
<P>
   Fox for canning the absurdly funny ``Family Guy.'' No other
animated comedy _ and that includes ``The Simpsons'' _ packed more
laugh-inducing yuks in 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   THE GUEST IS A STAR!
</P>
<P>
   Some great one-shot appearances:
</P>
<P>
   Jane Alexander was wonderfully delicious on ``Law &AMP; Order'' and
``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit'' as an icy matriarch willing
to do anything to protect her family's good name. ``You come after
me, I'll crush you,'' she barked to McCoy. And, as you know, no one
barks at McCoy.
</P>
<P>
   As a hard-charging ratings consultant, William H. Macy gave the
sagging ``Sports Night `` a much-needed boost. ``I come in, I do my
job, I do it better than anybody else, I get out.'' Too bad he
didn't stay longer.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Coles was always daffy on ``Living Single.'' She was that _
and then some _ as a Roz's you-go-girl radio personality
replacement on ``Frasier.''
</P>
<P>
   Old pro James Garner pumped new life into ``Chicago Hope'' as
the hospital's new CEO. While Garner managed to save the hospital,
unfortunately he couldn't resuscitate the series.
</P>
<P>
   One day Molly Shannon will get her own NBC comedy. She deserves
it after two hilarious stints as ``Will &AMP; Grace's'' wacky neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   BEST AND WORST, ETC.
</P>
<P>
   Best Drama: ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' continues to amuse,
frighten and delight with shocking regularity. From Willow's
lesbian relationship to downright scary voice-stealing demons, no
show reinvents itself better than Buffy.
</P>
<P>
   Best Actor in a Drama: Martin Sheen is so good as President
Bartlet on ``The West Wing,'' if he ran for real, he'd get my vote.
</P>
<P>
   Best Actress in a Drama: Sela Ward for making Lily Manning a
complex, full-bodied (no, I don't mean that literally) character on
``Once &AMP; Again.''
</P>
<P>
   Best Comedy: Sorry, ``Friends'' and ``Everybody Loves Raymond
,'' but no comedy made me lose it as often as ``Family Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Best Actor in a Comedy: ``Will &AMP; Grace's'' Sean Hayes is
considered a supporting actor, but his goofy antics (no one does
off-the-cuff Cher impressions better!) make him the star of NBC's
rib-tickling comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Best Actress in a Comedy: It's about time Patricia Heaton gets
the respect she deserves for her hilarious work as Ray's stressed
wife on ``Everybody Loves Raymond.''
</P>
<P>
   Best TV Movie: If you didn't get teary-eyed watching a
wonderfully magnificent Jack Lemmon in ``Tuesdays With Morrie,''
check your pulse.
</P>
<P>
   Best Miniseries: HBO's ``The Corner'' was gritty, realistic and
unforgivingly graphic. A film about the harsh world of drug dealing
was made poignant and funny by making the characters achingly
human.
</P>
<P>
   Worst programming moves: Gosh, there were so many. Two stick
out, though. NBC's bone-headed decision to air ``Freaks and
Geeks,'' the charming teen comedy/drama on Saturday nights. I might
be wrong, but isn't that the night most teens go out? Also, the
WB's decision to move ``Felicity'' to Sundays almost killed the
series. Of course, the blame-shifting network attributed falling
ratings to Kerri Russell's shorter 'do.
</P>
<P>
   Best show to get canceled: ``Action,'' a right-on satirical take
on greedy Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Worst show not to get canceled: Someone on the Popular set must
have blackmail pictures of influential WB suits.
</P>
<P>
   Best show with no buzz: Did you know over 14 million viewers
watch ``JAG'' ? Do you know what ``JAG `` is?
</P>
<P>
   Best sexy star to lose a series: Ah, Gina Gershon. Those lips.
That smile. Those lips. Let's hope the naughty-looking ``Snoops ``
star gets another series real soon.
</P>
<P>
   Best surprise hit: ``Titus.'' Who would've thought that a show
about a boozing dad, an institutionalized mom and an unknown
standup comic would keep viewers in stitches?
</P>
<P>
   Best hot TV couple: The chemistry between ``Roswell's'' Max and
Liz was out of this world. Perhaps that had something to do with
him being an alien, and all. ``Once and Again's'' Rick and Lily
come in a close second.
</P>
<P>
   Worst TV couple: Two worms generate more heat than Greene and
Corday on ``ER.''
</P>
<P>
   Best naked rear scene: Women nationwide were no doubt screaming,
``Omigod!!!'' while ``NYPD Blue's'' hunky detective Baldwin rolled
around the sheets with a comely newspaper reporter (''Showgirls' ``
Elizabeth Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Best shocking season finale: ``
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files' ``season ender was a doozy. Scully's pregnant!
Mulder's abducted! Cancer Man's dead! Or is he?
</P>
<P>
   Worst miniseries moments: The boyish looking Guy Torry as a
hardened Black Panther in NBC's The '70s; Lisa Nicole Carson
running around an underground subway tunnel. . . . with makeup
intact in CBS' ``Aftershock: Earthquake in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Stupid TV movies that were fun to watch: The absurd Y2K made
little sense, but moved like a speeding bullet; ``Satan School For
Girls'' was one of those campy, guilty pleasure movies no one dare
admit they enjoyed _ even though we know many people did.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1838EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
