<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIJI-MATTERS-OPED-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIJI: TROUBLE IN PARADISE SHOULD BE TAKEN SERIOUSLY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editorial)   (This 425-word ``separate-buy'' editorial is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 By THE EDITORIAL BOARD OF THE INDEPENDENT  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ The coup attempt in Fiji is a fine specimen of the
``trouble in paradise'' news story. Seen from the other side of the
world, it is opera buffa beneath the coconut palms, set to the
gentle music of the southern seas as they lap the white sands of a
tropical archipelago.
</P>
<P>
   A failed businessman hires a band of gunmen and then takes
hostage the prime minister and half his government, then appears
before the world's press dressed in a traditional sulu skirt to
announce that if Fiji's great council of chiefs so decrees, he will
call the enterprise off.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow these goings-on lack the gravitas of, say, Israel's
withdrawal from south Lebanon, or the future of the Anti-Ballistic
Missile Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   However, spare a second to consider a few facts.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji belongs to the Commonwealth _ but the same Commonwealth
that gets so exercised when Pakistan, Nigeria or Zimbabwe
misbehaves is silent now.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji may be best known for its rugby team and top-of-the-market
tourist brochures. But almost 1,000 Fijian peacekeepers (more than
a quarter of the country's armed forces) are on duty in the Middle
East, 600 of them with the United Nations in that same south
Lebanon, currently one of the most dangerous places on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji, in short, is more than doing its bit for what the British
Foreign Office sententiously refers to as the ``international
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Its domestic turmoil, therefore, deserves to be taken a mite
more seriously than it has been by that international community.
</P>
<P>
   Events in Fiji are of relevance to us all. However obscure its
exact motives, the coup led by George Speight is yet another
example of racial tensions threatening to tear a country apart; in
this case the resentment of the indigenous Fijian majority, which
Speight claims to represent, towards the ethnic Indian community.
</P>
<P>
   It is no coincidence that the rebellion began on the first
anniversary of the election of Mahendra Chaudhri, Fiji's first
prime minister of Indian ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   Worryingly, Fiji's president, Ratu Sir Kamisese Mara, has hinted
that he may not reinstate Chaudhri, if that is what is required to
secure a peaceful resolution of the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Human motives may explain that stance, since President Mara's
daughter is among the hostages. But that would be to sanction a
gangster's challenge to the constitution, and add Fiji to the list
of countries where power issues from the barrel of a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the South Pacific, that sort of thing matters. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this pithy 425-word editorial from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London, it must be purchased from the New York Times
Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or
fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
