r a BC-PUTIN-POLICESTATE-IND     05-24 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUTIN-POLICESTATE-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS KREMLIN PLANNING A NEW RUSSIAN POLICE STATE?  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 625-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By HELEN WOMACK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Five of the seven ``super governors'' appointed by
Russian President Vladimir Putin to discipline Russia's regions are
military, police or security service officers, it has emerged.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are divided on whether the new Kremlin leader's efforts
to exert central control over the vast country will run into the
provincial mire or whether a police state is being born under their
noses.
</P>
<P>
   Like an old Communist leader, Putin was touring the former
Soviet republics of Central Asia last Friday, leaving the
politicians in Moscow to digest his ``proposals'' for regional
reform and the appointments he made late on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   His choice of Sergei Kiriyenko, a young reformer who was briefly
prime minister, to represent him in the Volga region will encourage
those who trust Putin to use tough methods only as a way of making
Russia ultimately freer.
</P>
<P>
   But other appointments were more disturbing to anyone with
liberal values and prompted The Moscow Times to headline its story
on the subject: ``Men in Uniforms to Rule Districts.''
</P>
<P>
   With the war continuing in Chechnya, it was perhaps
understandable that Putin named General Viktor Kazantsev, currently
commander of Russian troops in the battle zone, to supervise the
new North Caucasus Federal District, which includes the breakaway
region.
</P>
<P>
   But it was less clear why he needed senior officers from the
forces as his representatives in four more of the seven large
federal districts into which he carved Russia by decree last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Those concerned for human rights were likely to be particularly
worried about the appointment of Viktor Cherkesov, first deputy
director of the Federal Security Service (FSB), to oversee the
regions of the northwest from a base in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Former dissidents remember that when repression was going out of
fashion under Mikhail Gorbachev, Cherkesov was one KGB officer who
continued to make enthusiastic use of the laws against
``anti-Soviet'' activities.
</P>
<P>
   Men who built their careers in the army, police or security
services were also sent out to impose Putin's will on the Central,
Urals and Far Eastern Federal Districts. That left Leonid
Drachevsky, the new presidential envoy to Siberia, as the only
other civilian apart from Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
   Former deputy prime minister, Boris Nemtsov, a liberal, said
order should be brought to Russia's anarchic regions but the
country needed good administrators, not generals who would ``bark
out commands.''
</P>
<P>
   The role of the president's men will be to make sure that the
elected governors in all of Russia's 89 regions obey federal law,
so that citizens from Moscow to Vladivostok can count on living in
equal conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Under former President Boris Yeltsin, some of the governors
became a law unto themselves, like medieval princes, and often this
``independence'' meant less rather than more freedom for their
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Except the mayor of Moscow, Yuri Luzhkov, and the president of
Ingushetia, Ruslan Aushev, who both protested, most governors
cautiously welcomed Putin's initiative, although privately many
must be planning to sabotage it.
</P>
<P>
   They would have been further angered by the president's call
last Wednesday for constitutional changes to deprive them of their
seats in the upper house of parliament and of their immunity from
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   One person who heartily welcomed what he saw as Putin's attempt
to restore the Soviet-era ``power vertical'' going down from the
Kremlin to the regions was Alexander Lukashenko, the authoritarian
leader of Belarus.
</P>
<P>
   The kind of society he has built was made clear when a Minsk
court sentenced the former Belarus prime minister, Mikhail Chigir,
to three years in jail, suspended for two years, for ``abuse of
power.''
</P>
<P>
   West European diplomats said the trial was a purely political
process against a man who had dared to oppose Lukashenko. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 625-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
