<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4691 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHILE-PINOCHET-540&AMP;AD     05-24 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILE-PINOCHET-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILEAN COURT STRIPS PINOCHET OF IMMUNITY FROM PROSECUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ A Chilean appeals court has stripped the immunity
of Gen. Augusto Pinochet, removing an important obstacle in the way
of his possible trial. He faces charges that he was involved in the
kidnapping, murder and torture of thousands during his 17 years as
Chile's dictator.
</P>
<P>
   The decision of the Court of Appeals is subject to a possible
reversal by the Supreme Court, and even lawyers working to
prosecute Pinochet say it could take years of legal wrangling
before any trial could begin, and that is assuming that the
general, now 84, lives that long. He has circulatory problems and a
history of strokes and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless the 13-9 decision by the appellate judges, voted in
private Tuesday but leaked to local reporters, demonstrates that
Chile's courts are willing to take independent stands after decades
of subservience to the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   It also demonstrates the commitment of President Ricardo Lagos,
the recently inaugurated Socialist, to allow the mechanisms of
justice to go forward despite friction with his military commanders
and threats by congressional conservatives to bottle up much of his
program if the prosecution of Pinochet continues.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Salinas, acting legislative director of Amnesty
International USA, said: ``Throughout Pinochet's captivity in Great
Britain, the Chilean government repeatedly insisted that he be
returned for prosecution in Chile. This appears to be the first
step toward the Chilean government making good on its promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet's legal troubles began in earnest in late 1998 when he
was arrested in London on a Spanish warrant charging him with human
rights violations. The general, who is a senator for life under a
constitution written while he ruled, and thus has immunity, was
released by British authorities in February after doctors said he
was not physically and mentally fit to stand trial.
</P>
<P>
   Pinochet now faces 108 criminal complaints filed mostly by
family members of about 3,000 people who disappeared after his
violent 1973 coup against Socialist president Salvador Allende
Gossens.
</P>
<P>
   Through a spokesman, Pinochet recently said, ``I never ordered
anybody to be killed or tortured.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Juan Guzman, who is prosecuting the retired dictator, has
anchored his case on 19 people who have been missing ever since
they were dragged out of prisons by soldiers led by some of
Pinochet's top aides in the weeks after the coup.
</P>
<P>
   The 19 people _ who were among 75 prisoners believed to have
been summarily executed _ have never been found, but the Supreme
Court has accepted Guzman's interpretation that they should be
considered kidnap victims, rather than dead. If the court
determined they were dead, the crimes would have been covered by a
general amnesty decreed to cover most rights violations committed
during the early years of the dictatorship from 1973 to 1990. But
if they are considered kidnapped, that offers a loophole for the
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Congressman Pablo Longueira of the Independent Democratic Union
party who is opposed to the general's prosecution, recently called
the legal interpretation behind Guzman's prosecution ``a ridiculous
joke.'' He added, ``We all know those people are dead.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Independent Democratic Union and another conservative party
had been in negotiations with Lagos to rewrite sections of the
constitution that limit the president's appointment powers over
military commanders and that give the military power to appoint
senators. But the talks have bogged down as Lagos refused to
interfere in the judicial proceedings and as government attorneys
joined in the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos has been equally forceful in displaying his resolve as top
military commanders in recent months at various times showed
displeasure with the prosecution of their former commander in
chief. After a high-level lunch of top military and police
commanders on May 15 was interpreted as a show of defiance, Lagos
publicly scolded them in a diplomatic, but pointed statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not necessary to demonstrate the unity of the armed
forces,'' said Lagos, the first Socialist elected president in
Chile since Allende's overthrow, ``since they are united behind the
president of Chile.'' No military commander contradicted him,
perhaps aware that Lagos' standing in the polls has been rising
since his March inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Pinochet case has hardened the military's stand in a
dialogue with human rights lawyers seeking help in finding the
remains of the missing. Just before Lagos' inauguration, the
officers and lawyers appeared close to an agreement that might have
led to the military's organized help in identifying clandestine
burial places for political victims.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this month, military officers offered a much weaker
proposal, closing the possibility that the military would mount a
serious effort at finding missing bodies. The new proposal would
merely open the way for individual military personnel to volunteer
to help find the graves.
</P>
<P>
   Since his return from Britain, Pinochet has been keeping as low
a profile as possible. He is not been attending Senate sessions,
even for important votes, and he has not spoken out on the issues
of the day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
