<SLUG> BC-OBUCHI-DAUGHTER-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S DIET, ONE OF WORLD'S MOST EXCLUSIVE FAMILY CLUBS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (This 750-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD LLOYD PARRY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   TOKYO _ Yuko Obuchi, soon to become MP for Gunma Prefecture's
Number Five Constituency, may turn out to be an able and dedicated
politician, but from her record so far there is not a single reason
to think so.
</P>
<P>
   At the age of 26, Ms. Obuchi is neither an economist nor a
public servant nor an entrepreneur. Her experience of the world is
limited to a short stint as a TV researcher and a few months
working as her dad's secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs show a pleasant-looking young woman, with an elegant
dress sense, neatly cut hair and a nice set of teeth. And yet, in a
month's time, Ms. Obuchi will almost certainly become a legislator
in the second richest country in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The explanation is simple: Yuko is the daughter of the late
Keizo Obuchi, the Japanese prime minister who died ten days ago
after a sudden stroke six weeks before.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, officials of Obuchi's Liberal Democratic Party (LDP)
announced that they are adopting his daughter as their candidate in
the safe seat he has left vacant.
</P>
<P>
   And so, in the general election expected to be held on June 25 _
barring an unexpected upset _ Yuko Obuchi will become a hereditary
member of the Japanese Diet, one of the most exclusive family clubs
in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Many other national parliaments contain some second generation
politicians, but few are quite so dominated by them as Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, 38 of the 500 seats in the Japanese Diet's lower
chamber belonged to the children of MPs. Forty years later the
figure has tripled to 122, and it could climb even higher.
</P>
<P>
   In next month's general election, at least 145 hereditary
candidates will stand, among them some of the most powerful
politicians in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The current cabinet alone contains half a dozen second- or
third-generation MPs, and four of the last seven prime ministers
fell into the same category.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi's predecessor, Ryutaro Hashimoto, can boast a grandfather
who was an MP, a father who was a minister, and a younger brother
who is a regional governor.
</P>
<P>
   But the phenomenon is not restricted to the LDP and its
coalition partners; the leader of the opposition, Yukio Hatoyama of
the Democratic Party, had a foreign minister father, a prime
minister grandfather, and a great-grandfather who was speaker of
the house.
</P>
<P>
   Among Japanese voters, the idea of hereditary MPs does not
appear strange or improper and second generation candidates do
little to justify their ambitions. The reasons given by Ms.
Obuchi's supporters were feeble.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to choosing Obuchi's successor,'' said one of
his constituency workers, Shichiroji Arikawa, ``we have no choice
but to accept someone from Obuchi's family as the person who would
best inherit his political wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Yuko herself admitted that she had no interest in politics
before her father's sudden illness. ``I made up my mind when I saw
his face shortly after he died,'' she revealed Tuesday, rather
disconcertingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to decide who to vote for based on who the candidate
is, not what family they are from,'' Japan's most liberal
newspaper, Asahi Shibum, patiently urged last week. But for this
election a more vigorous campaign is afoot to raise the calibre of
parliamentary candidates and hold them to higher standards.
</P>
<P>
   Following the example of a grass-roots movement in South Korea,
a group of activists have set up a group called Wave 21, dedicated
to ``driving out the now rampant abuse of authority, greed and
corruption committed by politicians from the Diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Wave 21's Web site invites visitors to award ``red cards'' to
candidates considered unfit for office, and publishes the results.
They include the new prime minister, Yoshiro Mori, the finance
minister, Kiichi Miyazawa and the veteran opposition leader, Ichiro
Ozawa.
</P>
<P>
   In last month's Korean elections, most of the candidates named
by the campaigners in Seoul lost their seats as a result, although
whether Japan's less fiery voters will react in a similar way
remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the likes of Ms. Obuchi will be under scrutiny. ``We
shall expunge such bad politicians whose minds are dominated by
self-preservation, self-interest for power and money,'' reads Wave
21's ferocious manifesto. ``Blacklist (a candidate) with whom you
never ever want to share the same air under heaven!'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 750-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
