<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4700 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MARTINS-DANCE-ART-$AD     05-24 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTINS-DANCE-ART-$ADV28-675(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE BOYS CAN LEARN TO SHAPE UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 28) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT21 was sent May 23 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LAURA LEIVICK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even some of the harshest critics of Peter Martins'
regime at New York City Ballet troop eagerly to the annual workshop
performances of his company's academy, the School of American
Ballet. Year after year, in the dancing of the latest crop of
advanced students, the workshops present a glimpse of ballet's
ideals.
</P>
<P>
   In the 17 years since Martins succeeded Balanchine as the
company's ballet-master-in-chief and the school's chairman of
faculty, his every move at the company has been debated. Changes at
the school, however, go pretty much unremarked outside its sanctum
in the Samuel B. and David Rose Building at Lincoln Center. The
move in 1991 to those hushed new quarters, with dormitories for 64
students in the Meredith Willson Residence Hall above, marks the
biggest institutional change in the Martins years.
</P>
<P>
   Today, this academy, established in 1934 to train ballet
dancers, period, publishes its intention to act in loco parentis
for the students and provides things like nutrition counseling.
Beneath the recent revival of curiosity about the private lives of
the school's students, triggered by scenes in Nicholas Hytner's new
dance film, ``Center Stage,'' may lie plain dislike of what Lincoln
Kirstein, co-founder of the school and company, celebrated as
ballet's ``credo of self-denial at the moment when egos are
inclined to feel their first selfhood.''
</P>
<P>
   The school under Martins has also been affected by the death of
Kirstein, in 1996, and of teachers representing the full span of
the Balanchine era _ Stanley Williams, Alexandra Danilova, Muriel
Stuart and Elise Reiman. Martins has brought in guest teachers like
Mikhail Baryshnikov; he recruited retired company dancers,
including Peter Frame and Katrina Killian, and active dancers like
Darci Kistler (his wife), Jock Soto and Peter Boal, for the
faculty; and he asked others, like Kyra Nichols and Damian Woetzel,
to pitch in as guest teachers. Martins himself teaches the advanced
men on Wednesdays. ``When he walks into the studio and takes off
the blazer, it's the most intimidating thing in the world,'' says
one boy.
</P>
<P>
   Martins also made Kay Mazzo, a former partner who taught under
Balanchine, his co-chairman of faculty. ``Kay is a woman whom I
have always adored,'' Martins says. ``She has impeccable judgment,
and she is a very, very fine person.'' The soft-spoken Mazzo loves
her job but can't remember what it's called: ``Titles are for the
birds,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   As for the curriculum, such as it is _ the school has no written
syllabus, just an oral tradition _ Martins has added classes in
ballroom dance, mime, contemporary partnering techniques and weight
training for the men. If he has a larger project in view, it seems
to be evolving ad hoc: upgrading the training for men.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Martins began a special program for boys: the school
announces its open auditions to 8- to 11-year-old boys in the
city's public schools; classes in the children's division are no
longer co-ed, and boys under 14 attend tuition-free (this year's
tuition for girls ranged from $1,067 to $2,412); and they are
allowed to wear shorts instead of tights. It is too soon to see the
results of these changes, though for nearly a decade, most of the
boys in the party scene in City Ballet's annual performances of
``The Nutcracker'' have been boys, not the disgruntled little girls
of Christmases past.
</P>
<P>
   A dancer's training takes about 10 years, and SAB, unlike the
state academies abroad, does not have a stable population:
twice-weekly auditions are held at the school year-round, students
outside the United States may send audition tapes, and an annual
25-city audition tour selects some 200 students for the summer
session. There is a constant winnowing (perhaps 20 of the 200
summer kids will be invited to return in the fall). Of the current
group of 29 advanced men, for example, only 7 have trained more or
less exclusively at the school.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
