<HEADER>
A4701 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-KILLER-QUAKE-SEATTLE?     05-24 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLER-QUAKE-SEATTLE?-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE'S ALL SHOOK UP OVER NEW EARTHQUAKE OMENS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Washington State, Pacific NW)   (This 850-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREW GUMBEL  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Ever since it emerged from its gentle provincialism to
become a powerhouse of the new digital economy, the city of
Seattle, Wash., has worried about becoming just a little too much
like Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   First came the upscale chain stores, then the four-wheel-drive
cars and clogged highways, then _ heaven forbid _ a touch of Los
Angeles-style smog.
</P>
<P>
   And now it turns out Seattle has another thing in common with
California: risk of destruction by a killer earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Like L.A., a city forever on the verge of a seismic breakdown,
and like San Francisco, which is within shuddering distance of the
long, potentially lethal San Andreas Fault, Seattle has developed
its own fear of the Big One.
</P>
<P>
   Earthquakes and volatile shifts in geological strata are hardly
unknown in the Pacific Northwest. Seattle, after all, is less than
100 miles away from Mount St. Helens, which erupted to devastating
effect 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And the area has suffered a couple of uncomfortable shakes in
the last half-century: once in the Seattle-Tacoma area in 1965 and
once a little further south in the state capital, Olympia, in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, however, it was believed that the seismic fault
lines were buried either too deep beneath the surface of the earth,
or too far away in the Pacific Ocean, to threaten much more than a
few cracked buildings and a handful of victims in the worst of
cases.
</P>
<P>
   All that has changed with the discovery of the Seattle Fault,
which runs as little as six miles beneath the surface along a
lengthy east-west stretch from Issaquah, in the foothills of the
Cascades, through the heart of Seattle and across Puget Sound to
the old naval shipyard at Bremerton.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have known about this fault for a few decades, but
for a long time refused to take it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the research evidence mounts, they believe it could
trigger a quake as high as 7 on the Richter scale _ the same force
unleashed by last year's devastating tremors in Turkey and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the geological layout of the area, the effect of any
earthquake is actually going to be worse than the Richter number
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole Seattle basin is going to have such an extra kick
it's going to shake like a bowl of Jello,'' said Craig Weaver, who
coordinates earthquake monitoring in the Pacific Northwest for the
U.S. Geological Survey.
</P>
<P>
   What set the alarm bells ringing was the accidental discovery of
an ancient Douglas fir a few years ago during the expansion of a
local sewage works on Elliott Bay. A combination of carbon dating
and geological analysis led scientists to conclude that a
devastating earthquake had struck the Seattle area somewhere
between 900 and 930 A.D.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the land, now heavily populated, rose as much as 16
feet. The shores of Lake Washington, site of many desirable homes
including Microsoft chief Bill Gates's, were devastated by
landslides.
</P>
<P>
   And Bainbridge Island, now an affluent bedroom community with
easy ferry links across Elliott Bay to downtown Seattle, was tipped
up so violently that a whole new corner emerged from the deep. The
south-facing ledge is now a nine-hole private golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is understandably perturbed by the revelations. Last
year, about 100 researchers set off depth charges in the city's
watery surrounds _ to the consternation of building dwellers on
shore who felt the tremors _ and concluded there were in fact three
or four sloping faults all feeding into the main Seattle fault.
</P>
<P>
   Just a month ago, scientists postulated the existence of another
deadly fault, this time running north to south from the Hood River
Bridge on the Olympic Peninsula, through several populated areas on
Puget Sound west of Seattle, and down to the port city of Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   A certain paranoia is creeping in. When demolition men came to
knock down the Kingdome, longtime home of Seattle's beloved
Mariners baseball team, in January, seismologists and newspaper
editorial writers felt compelled to assure the populace there was
no danger of the explosions setting off an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, one of Seattle's leading hospitals, the
Harborview Medical Center, came begging for $257 million in public
funds to protect itself against earthquake risk. (Several critics
later accused the hospital of trying to stir up earthquake fears as
an excuse to expand and modernize at the public's expense).
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Northwest may fancy itself as the antithesis of
Southern California in many ways, but fear of the Big One _ and
exploitation of that fear _ is manifesting itself in much the same
way as it does in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver, of the Geological Survey, even believes that a quake
along the San Andreas fault could have a knock-on effect reaching
all the way to Seattle in a chain reaction of geological tremors.
</P>
<P>
   If his theory is correct, it provides another demonstration of
an uncomfortable home truth: California is a lot closer than many
locals like to think. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 850-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4707 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     05-24 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     DON'T EXPECT MUCH FROM THE U.S.-RUSSIA SUMMIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, May 28)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After the tributes have faded, U.S.-Russian summit
meetings, such as the first formal meeting between Bill Clinton and
Vladimir Putin in Moscow next weekend, become hard-nosed
negotiating sessions at which pledges of cooperation sometimes are
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   The participants often contend in the exaggerated language of
joint communiques that they have strengthened the movement toward
peace. The reality is that in the 63-year-history of such summits
sometimes they have and sometimes they have not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Clinton) Moscow visit can make progress if it begins the
process of treating Russia as a serious power,'' former Secretary
of State Henry Kissinger said in an opinion-page piece for the
Washington Post on May 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will fail if it becomes the occasion for disquisitions on
Russia's domestic structure or for arms-control schemes doomed to
failure in America.''
</P>
<P>
   To succeed, Kissinger said, the two leaders must begin to
formulate a new U.S.-Russian relationship. Thus, Clinton must not
try to reform Russia's social system, and Putin must not try force
an arms control agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is confronted by additional difficulties that could
prevent the summit from producing serious long-range results.
</P>
<P>
   First, he and Putin, a former KGB agent who is new to the
Russian presidency, have not had the opportunity to know each other
as did Clinton and Boris Yeltsin, or Ronald Reagan and Mikhail
Gorbachev or Richard Nixon and Leonid Brezhnev.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Clinton is a lame duck with a mere eight months left in
office, and Putin undoubtedly understands enough about the American
system to realize that the president cannot make long-range
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   Third, any agreement Clinton and Putin might craft on nuclear
arms control probably will be rejected by the Senate because of
opposition from Jesse Helms, the powerful chairman of the Foreign
Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   In a Senate speech April 26, Helms warned that ``this
administration's time for grand treaty initiatives is at an end.''
The 79-year-old senator added that he would be against any arms
agreement that Clinton and Putin might negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton were to bring home such a pact, the duel between the
Democratic president and the Republican Senate patriarch could
become a mini-reincarnation of a bitter battle in 1919. It was
fought between President Woodrow Wilson and Sen. Henry Cabot Lodge,
the Republican chairman of that same committee, over the Versailles
Treaty that ended World War I and created the League of Nations to
protect the peace.
</P>
<P>
   Lodge won the battle when the League was defeated in the Senate.
But history has not been kind to him and it will not be kind to
Helms if he blocks a worthwhile U.S.-Russian arms pact simply
because of his partisanship and dislike of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   After Helms' announcement, the administration passed the word to
reporters last week that it expects little progress on nuclear arms
matters at the summit.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Clinton and Putin achieve any long-term agreements is
probably less important than the fact that they are trying to
strengthen the friendship of recent years between the onetime Cold
War foes. Putin is said to be seeking U.S. help in resuscitating
Russia's economy.
</P>
<P>
   The start of America's rocky relationship with Russia came in
1917 when the communists deposed Czar Nicholas II and killed him
and his family. At that time, Wilson sought to befriend the
Bolsheviks and urged that they adopt democratic principles similar
to those he proposed for the peaceful settlement of World War I.
</P>
<P>
   In his biography of Wilson, August Heckscher explained that V.I.
Lenin, the Bolshevik leader, was contemptuous of Wilson and all
other heads of capitalist countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``And so the two great polar figures were to stand in fateful
opposition,'' Heckscher wrote, ``at the fork in the road where the
destiny of the 20th century was being decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson refused to grant diplomatic recognition to the Soviet
Union. So did his three immediate successors _ Warren G. Harding,
Calvin Coolidge and Herbert Hoover. But in 1933 Franklin D.
Roosevelt established diplomatic relations with the communist
regime.
</P>
<P>
   It took World War II, however, to bring U.S. and Soviet heads of
state together face-to face. That happened in Tehran in 1943 when
Roosevelt and British Prime Minister Winston Churchill met with
Josef Stalin to plan their military campaign against Nazi Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as the war was ending in Europe, they met at Yalta in
February 1945 to plan post-war strategy. It was there that Stalin
promised, at the urging of Roosevelt and Churchill, to restore
democracy to Poland and other countries bordering the Soviet Union.
But when FDR died two months later, Stalin had made no effort to
keep his promise.
</P>
<P>
   Then in July 1945 Roosevelt's successor, Harry Truman, and
Churchill conferred with Stalin in Potsdam. But with the Red army
occupying Eastern Europe, Stalin was not about to permit democracy
to flourish in any country there.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet leader did agree, however, to join the fight against
Japan and he kept that promise.
</P>
<P>
   But in the wake of World War II, the Cold War began. As
Churchill declared a year later in Fulton, Mo., ``an iron curtain''
had descended across Europe ``from Stettin in the Baltic to Trieste
in the Adriatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Since that time, every American president has met with a Soviet
or Russian leader. Each time, hope has soared and then often faded
into disillusionment.
</P>
<P>
   Summits are worthwhile because they permit the leaders to take
their measure of each other. They also can produce breakthroughs
toward a more cordial relationship between the two superpowers. The
problem is: We expect too much of such meetings and therefore are
disappointed with the results.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert E. Thompson can be reached at 202-298-6920).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1844EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
