</P>
<P>
   All that has changed with the discovery of the Seattle Fault,
which runs as little as six miles beneath the surface along a
lengthy east-west stretch from Issaquah, in the foothills of the
Cascades, through the heart of Seattle and across Puget Sound to
the old naval shipyard at Bremerton.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have known about this fault for a few decades, but
for a long time refused to take it seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the research evidence mounts, they believe it could
trigger a quake as high as 7 on the Richter scale _ the same force
unleashed by last year's devastating tremors in Turkey and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the geological layout of the area, the effect of any
earthquake is actually going to be worse than the Richter number
suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole Seattle basin is going to have such an extra kick
it's going to shake like a bowl of Jello,'' said Craig Weaver, who
coordinates earthquake monitoring in the Pacific Northwest for the
U.S. Geological Survey.
</P>
<P>
   What set the alarm bells ringing was the accidental discovery of
an ancient Douglas fir a few years ago during the expansion of a
local sewage works on Elliott Bay. A combination of carbon dating
and geological analysis led scientists to conclude that a
devastating earthquake had struck the Seattle area somewhere
between 900 and 930 A.D.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the land, now heavily populated, rose as much as 16
feet. The shores of Lake Washington, site of many desirable homes
including Microsoft chief Bill Gates's, were devastated by
landslides.
</P>
<P>
   And Bainbridge Island, now an affluent bedroom community with
easy ferry links across Elliott Bay to downtown Seattle, was tipped
up so violently that a whole new corner emerged from the deep. The
south-facing ledge is now a nine-hole private golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is understandably perturbed by the revelations. Last
year, about 100 researchers set off depth charges in the city's
watery surrounds _ to the consternation of building dwellers on
shore who felt the tremors _ and concluded there were in fact three
or four sloping faults all feeding into the main Seattle fault.
</P>
<P>
   Just a month ago, scientists postulated the existence of another
deadly fault, this time running north to south from the Hood River
Bridge on the Olympic Peninsula, through several populated areas on
Puget Sound west of Seattle, and down to the port city of Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   A certain paranoia is creeping in. When demolition men came to
knock down the Kingdome, longtime home of Seattle's beloved
Mariners baseball team, in January, seismologists and newspaper
editorial writers felt compelled to assure the populace there was
no danger of the explosions setting off an earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, one of Seattle's leading hospitals, the
Harborview Medical Center, came begging for $257 million in public
funds to protect itself against earthquake risk. (Several critics
later accused the hospital of trying to stir up earthquake fears as
an excuse to expand and modernize at the public's expense).
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Northwest may fancy itself as the antithesis of
Southern California in many ways, but fear of the Big One _ and
exploitation of that fear _ is manifesting itself in much the same
way as it does in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver, of the Geological Survey, even believes that a quake
along the San Andreas fault could have a knock-on effect reaching
all the way to Seattle in a chain reaction of geological tremors.
</P>
<P>
   If his theory is correct, it provides another demonstration of
an uncomfortable home truth: California is a lot closer than many
locals like to think. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
