<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4702 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MARTINS-DANCE-ART-$AD     05-24 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARTINS-DANCE-ART-$ADV28-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the school.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year, many of these hand-picked 14- to 19-year-olds will be
featured in Balanchine's ``Stars and Stripes'' at the workshop
performances June 2 and June 5 at the Juilliard Theater. One recent
afternoon, Suki Schorer, one of Balanchine's appointees and a
former City Ballet principal, was running a rehearsal for the
all-male Second Regiment section (``Thunder and Gladiator'') like a
high-strung drill sergeant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see the whole stage move!'' she shouted above the
rousing Sousa march, sweeping her arm in a huge arc. The soloist
leading the 12-boy regiment was Daniel Ulbricht, a cheerful
16-year-old from Florida now in his first term. He tore across the
studio diagonally like a gymnast heading for a handspring, took off
like a cannonball, hit a pose in midair _ knees tucked up, saluting
briskly _ landed, ran to the far corner, turned smartly and did it
again.
</P>
<P>
   The group ran the taxing six-minute dance straight through and
marched off, eyes right. ``OK,'' said Schorer brightly; then she
turned on a kid who showed up late, and didn't know the
choreography, and was he chewing gum?
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Kirstein likened SAB to West Point with good reason.
These boys work as if there's no tomorrow. Ulbricht describes his
daily schedule: three academic classes at the Professional
Performing Arts School (along with three independent-study
classes); three SAB classes; then rehearsals till as late as 9.
Somehow the plan also accommodates appearances with the company,
like his recent performances as one of the three Court Jesters in
Martins' ``Sleeping Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   For boys who like that sort of life, of course, that's just the
sort of life they like: male enrollment at the school is at an
all-time high, 82 out of a student body of 343. Yet ask Martins
whether he's overhauling the boys' program at SAB, and he replies:
``I'm not. I'm just introducing our time, as one should, updating
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there is nothing revisionist about sweetening the pot
for young men in Balanchine's academy. Just as certainly, however,
male dancing was not Balanchine's first priority; he was a
ballerina man. ``Put 16 girls on a stage, and it's everybody _ the
world,'' he said, famously. ``But put 16 boys, and it's always
nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet not only did important dancers like Edward Villella, Arthur
Mitchell and Ethan Stiefel emerge from SAB; established stars from
Martins himself to his teacher Erik Bruhn to Rudolf Nureyev and
Baryshnikov beat down the door to dance for Balanchine.
</P>
<P>
   A belief in the stature of the Balanchine legacy lends both joy
and anxiety to the school's task of preparing dancers to be
civilized members of the ballet world. The charming Andrei
Kramarevsky, a Balanchine hire known as Krammy, lets the top boys,
a tuition-free class of 13 called ``special men,'' try the bravura
steps one of them calls ``the things we see on the videotapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking sharp in shirts, slacks and jazz shoes, they join the
other advanced and intermediate men to do the merengue with the
advanced girls in ballroom class. Courtesy prevails: many teachers
address the boys as ``Gentlemen''; in the courtly Boal's classes,
you can hear a pin drop.
</P>
<P>
   The idea that the stylization variously called Balanchine
technique and Balanchine style is enforced at the school is
shrugged off by Mazzo. Hard-line classicists have long said that
SAB dancers overcross positions, overarticulate elbows and wrists,
shift their hips out of alignment to raise the leg in extension and
let their heels off the floor too soon in plie, the luxurious ready
position that gives ballet steps their spring and lilt. ``I'd
rather say it's a way of getting a dancer to move fast and make it
look easy,'' she says. ``Details like how you use your arms are not
even insisted on in B's choreography.''
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere you look at SAB, some danseur-in-the-rough is sorting
out something, watching himself critically in the ubiquitous
mirrors. Waiting for pas de deux class to begin, Ulbricht tries a
pirouette and delivers eight perfect revolutions, then calmly
closes fifth position. In Frame's weight-training class, intended
to help the men avoid injury while partnering, he has them stand,
face front and answer questions about their views on art. Asked
which dancer inspires him, one boy chooses American Ballet
Theater's Julio Bocca, whom he had just seen in the Broadway hit
``Fosse'': ``He was totally transformed. You can use your technique
to do anything.'' And how would he apply this to his own work?
``You have to make every plie the most important thing in the
world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a workshop ballet, he got a chance to make good. Nikolaj
Hubbe, a City Ballet principal, was rehearsing ``Konservatoriet,''
an 1849 ballet by August Bournonville.
</P>
<P>
   The cast _ in this scene, 14 girls and 4 boys _ begins in first
position, bras bas (their arms low and rounded), with a plie. To
teach them the lovely Bournonville arm positions, Hubbe has them
walk through whole passages of choreography, only indicating the
dance steps, but doing the port de bras full-out. ``Don't
allonger'' _ that is, elongate _ ``the arms and fingers,'' he tells
them. They try again. ``Ah, when you do like this _ so, so soft and
gentle _ it's heavenly,'' he responds. ``Now, let's try it with
steps, but still elegant and gentle. Don't kick it!''
</P>
<P>
   Later, the four boys come forward, stand in fifth position and
begin a difficult academic dance: brisk beats; quick, precise
turns. One boy, a dark-haired, sober 15-year-old named David
Blumenfeld, after a few corrections, executes a perfectly balanced
triple attitude turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're hired!'' Hubbe exclaims with a laugh, and the students
join in. It's a joke with an edge because, for the older students,
the workshop serves as an audition for City Ballet or the other
companies that send scouts.
</P>
<P>
   Hubbe is called away for a moment, and while two boys start
trying turns and coax a girl or two into partnering experiments, a
few of the students take the opportunity to lie down on the floor,
like puppies; one girl rests her head on a friend's flank, eyes
open in plain fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We forget they are children,'' Hubbe says later. ``This is
such a rigorous profession.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
