<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV11-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., JUNE 11, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 Copyright 2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: My kitchen faucet leaks around the base where the swivel
spout meets the body of the faucet, and it also drips slightly when
turned off. This is a single handle ball-type faucet that has no
regular faucet washers that need periodic changing.
</P>
<P>
   Can I repair this faucet, or must I call in a plumber to replace
it completely?
</P>
<P>
   A: These faucets can be repaired, but it is sometimes difficult
to locate the precise cause of a leak or drip.
</P>
<P>
   Your best bet is to buy a repair kit made for that particular
brand of faucet and then follow the directions supplied to replace
all the parts subject to wear.
</P>
<P>
   You will need a large pair of pliers to unscrew and remove the
cap under the handle, after which you can lift off the swing spout.
</P>
<P>
   A little tool supplied with these kits will enable you to remove
the cam and cam washer, then use a pair of needle nose pliers to
lift out the inlet seals and springs.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the rubber O-rings around the outside and replace these
with the new ones in the kit. Then install all the new parts as you
reassemble the faucet.
</P>
<P>
   Q: We have some dark greenish-gray spots on our exterior vinyl
siding and someone told us that this is some kind of fungus like
mildew. We have had a very wet spring, and he says this is what can
cause it.
</P>
<P>
   Do you think this is the problem, and if so, what can we do to
clean these stains off?
</P>
<P>
   A: It could be mildew, which is a type of fungus.
</P>
<P>
   If it is, you can probably remove it by mopping on a solution of
fresh laundry bleach and water (one part bleach mixed with three
parts water).
</P>
<P>
   Apply with a soft brush and allow to dry on the surface, then
rinse off with lots of water. (Also remember to thoroughly hose
down any shrubs or plantings nearby that the bleach may have
dripped on.)
</P>
<P>
   You can repeat this if some stains still remain.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Our old white bathroom sink has lost much of its gloss and
there are places where the porcelain has actually worn off, showing
dark spots of bare metal.
</P>
<P>
   We do not want to replace this sink, so can you tell me if there
is any way I can restore the glaze?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are two-part epoxy paints you can buy that can be used
to refinish the sink, but you must follow directions exactly _
especially as to the need for thoroughly cleaning the surface
beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   Remember that once you paint the sink you will probably have to
re-do it periodically, depending on wear. Although, these finishes
often last for years if properly done.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have some old cane chairs I bought recently that are still
in comparatively good condition.
</P>
<P>
   What can I do to protect the caning from the weather and to keep
this material from drying out and cracking?
</P>
<P>
   A: The caning can be painted with an enamel, but most people
prefer a clear finish such as a clear varnish or similar coating.
</P>
<P>
   This will not only protect it from the elements, it will also
help shed dirt and soil, and will protect against fading and
discoloration.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Drawing captioned ``BALL FAUCET'' goes with this column.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTION: Replacement kit for ball-type faucet will contain all
parts needed to repair or replace worn parts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
