<HEADER>
A4722 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-RUSKIN-THEATER-ART-$A     05-24 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSKIN-THEATER-ART-$ADV28-1,280(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TWISTED VICTORIAN LOVE STORY THAT WON'T DIE OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 28) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT34 was sent May 23 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LUCINDA FRANKS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``The Countess,'' a drama about a sensational sex
scandal involving three prominent Victorians _ John Ruskin, the
most famous art critic of his day; John Everett Millais, Ruskin's
protege and an artist who would later gain his own fame, and
Euphemia Gray, the beautiful Scotswoman who came between them _ has
quietly defied theatrical convention. With little fanfare and
limited financing it has become the longest-running new drama of
the 1999-2000 season and is now ensconced at an Off Broadway
theater four times the size of the one where it started.
</P>
<P>
   Written by an aspiring New York novelist, produced and directed
by a former English actress who mortgaged her theater to keep it
going and supported by Millais descendants eager to finally realize
the vain efforts of their ancestors to clear their
great-great-grandmother's name, the play, at the Lamb's Theater,
has become a cause in more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   This year is the centenary of Ruskin's death at the age of 80. A
demigod in the mid-19th century who dictated artistic opinion in
England, he is still an object of veneration, and thus the play is
causing consternation among devotees loath to see the details of
his unhappy marriage revealed.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in Ruskin and his era is evident in the current
celebrated show at the Tate Gallery in London about the work of
Ruskin and the Pre-Raphaelite painters, a movement that Millais
helped found and that Ruskin championed. An exhibit of Ruskiniana
at the Grolier Club in New York ended last month. In September, the
Morgan Library will open its own collection of original Ruskin
manuscripts along with correspondence known as the Bowerswell
Papers _ 100 years of letters by Ruskin, Millais and Euphemia, or
Effie, and their families and friends. A new edition of Ruskin's
``Stones of Venice,'' his third major volume of criticism, has been
published, as has the two-volume biography ``John Ruskin'' by Tim
Hilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Countess,'' based on historical fact, begins in 1853 as
Ruskin, who had married Effie in 1848, when he was 29 and she 19,
prepares for a trip with his wife and Millais to the Scottish
Highlands. Millais is to paint the critic's portrait. But in their
small cottage, Ruskin indulges in his perverse habit of
compromising his wife by leaving her alone with Millais. The
painter becomes blocked about the portrait and instead sketches
Effie. He is disturbed by Ruskin, a man who can bring audiences to
their feet with his resounding exhortations that ``beauty is in the
ordinary, the raw truth of life,'' but at home demeans Effie,
writing down her faults in his journal to read to his parents, who
dominated the marriage, and finally making Effie believe she was
going mad. Eventually, all that Millais understood was that he was
falling in love with his mentor's wife. What he did not yet know
was that the Ruskins had never consummated their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   On his wedding night, it is possible that Ruskin expected to
gaze upon the embodiment of a marble statue, but when he slipped
off the nightgown of his young wife, he was aghast to see the woman
beneath. ``Though her face is beautiful ... there were certain
circumstances in her person which completely checked passion,''
Ruskin later stated in court papers involving his marriage
annulment. No one, perhaps including Ruskin himself, knew why. That
he was overly fascinated by young girls in the way that another
Victorian author, Lewis Carroll, was, is known.
</P>
<P>
   The play ends as the desperate Effie, back in London with
Ruskin, leaves her husband in 1854. A little more than a year later
she and Millais were married. They would have eight children.
Ruskin never married again. In middle age he fell in love with a
10-year-old girl; her death at 24 would ultimately help plunge him
into the madness of his last years.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it is not surprising that scholars have tended to sweep
this material into biographical afterthought, for in his time,
Ruskin's impact, his elegant interweaving of art and social theory,
was so great that he influenced men like Proust, Wilde and Gandhi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know that Gandhi could not put Ruskin's book `Unto This
Last' down during a train trip across Africa and said it changed
the whole course of his life?'' asked Dyke Benjamin, a member of
the Grolier Club. A tall courtly man who resembles his hero in
manner and eloquence, Benjamin was cradling a cream-colored book,
``Remembering John Ruskin,'' that he produced using original
Scottish fonts to memorialize Ruskin's most indelible phrases. The
book served as the catalog for the Grolier exhibit, which included
Benjamin's collection of Ruskin material. ``It is a gross injustice
for this genius to be depicted as a strident, shallow misogynist in
some Off Broadway play,'' Benjamin said.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Murphy, the author of ``The Countess'' _ the title comes
from Millais' nickname for Effie _ came upon the story in the book
``Parallel Lives: Five Victorian Marriages'' by Phyllis Rose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so fascinating,'' said Murphy, who is 48. ``Here was a
man who talked about beauty and art, who married this incredibly
beautiful woman, and then set about trying to destroy her. It's
about the difference between the ideal and reality. I was
interested in finding out the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``Once I discovered that the Bowerswell Papers
were at the Morgan Library, I wanted to look at them.'' Studying
the more than 1,000 letters, Murphy remembered, ``I saw Effie being
damaged year after year, coming to believe that she had some awful
internal disease, watched her handwriting go from a sturdy Scotch
script to a shaky scrawl.'' He added, ``I think Ruskin would have
destroyed her without the help of Millais and Effie's confidante
Lady Eastlake. Eastlake was a writer of the period who was
disparaged for her feminist views. She is in my play because she
was able to unlock the secret of the Ruskin marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the annulment, Effie did not marry Millais for a year
but stayed at her family home in Bowerswell, Scotland. She is
always described as shallow and a social climber. That is
completely fictitious. Ruskin's parents described her that way. But
it persists. She left Ruskin, a very wealthy and influential man,
and married Millais, an artist who was then almost penniless. If
she were a social climber she never would have done that. When
Ruskin partisans talk about his marriage they never address the
issue that Ruskin married her and then refused to sleep with her.''
</P>
<P>
   About five years ago, Murphy had a reading of ``The Countess,''
and one of the actors told Ludovica Villar-Hauser, who owns the
small Greenwich Street Theater in the South Village, about the
play. Villar-Hauser, 39, a tall, reedy Englishwoman of Spanish and
Austrian descent, had directed a number of plays about women and
thought Murphy's play could work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't let it go,'' Villar-Hauser said. ``It stayed with
me. I identified with the script, like many women who come to the
show. I had been involved with a wonderful but very cold man. I
found it just amazing that after 150 years, they are still dragging
the woman down! She happened to be a very talented woman. She was a
pianist and fluent in three languages, but instead of leaving her
mark on the world, she was the backbone for the husbands who did.
Even the encyclopedias dismiss her as a social climber.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminded me of Princess Diana, with Prince Charles under
the spell of his mother, the attempts to keep Diana down and then
to paint her as mad. In Victorian England, it was almost as bad to
be seen to do something bad as to actually do it. I thought it time
to set the record straight.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Villar-Hauser presented the seven-character play in a nonprofit
showcase produced by the Villar-Hauser Theater Development Fund at
her 74-seat theater in March 1999. The cast included the three
actors who are currently in the principal roles: James Riordan as
Ruskin, Jennifer Woodward as Effie and Jy Murphy as Millais. ``Our
audiences were wonderful,'' the director said. ``We had people
crying, asking me afterward whether Ruskin was gay or what was
really wrong with Effie.'' In fact, when Effie was examined by
doctors to ascertain her virginity before the annulment, they
declared her ``naturally and properly formed with no impediments''
to sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became obsessed,'' Villar-Hauser recalled. ``We weren't
filling the house. Any play has a natural death, but this one
wasn't ready to die. What kept us going was the audience response
and the review in The New York Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing in The Times, Anita Gates called the play a ``serious
but wonderfully witty period drama'' with an ``excellent'' cast.
</P>
<P>
   Limited by a small advertising budget, Villar-Hauser decided to
build interest by holding weekly Victorian Nights for audiences,
with the cast, the creators, refreshments and a Victorian expert on
hand. She commissioned and displayed in the lobby a portrait of
Woodward as Effie in Pre-Raphaelite style, as well as a copy of the
letter Effie wrote her father asking him to rescue her from her
marriage. Volunteers worked the box office and became permanent
ushers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had gained a kind of cult support group but it was crazy,''
Villar-Hauser said. ``I was working 24 hours a day, seven days a
week as general manager, company manager, producer, director and
ticket seller.'' But audiences continued to grow and on March 19,
at the Samuel Beckett Theater on Theater Row, the company
celebrated its 352nd performance. It had opened there in June 1999
to generally favorable reviews.
</P>
<P>
   When the Samuel Beckett closed in March, along with other
auditoriums on Theater Row, because of construction, Villar-Hauser
decided to see whether she could reopen the play as a commercial
engagement: ``I hadn't had time to go out and meet the right money
people, not that I even knew who or how to meet them anyway. Nobody
wanted to invest in a straight play about an obscure Victorian
without pyrotechnics and dancing and car crashes. I called
everyone, even people I met on a bus.''
</P>
<P>
   Small investments arrived and then one man pledged $250,000.
This enabled ``The Countess'' to move to the Lamb's Theater on West
44th Street. But 10 days before previews were to begin on April 24,
the large donor, hurt by a dip in the stock market, pulled out.
Villar-Hauser took a loan on her Greenwich Street Theater to save
the show.
</P>
<P>
   At the Lamb's, where the play's script is sold, she still
welcomes the audience and chats during intermission. ``We are
trying to create the feeling of bringing the audience into the
play,'' she said. ``The energy has to go back and forth from stage
to audience for this play to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of ``The Countess,'' of course, traveled to England and the
descendants of Effie and Millais. ``We had been told so much about
great-great-Grandma and it was so moving to see her brought to
life,'' said Tara Millais in a telephone interview from London. She
and her brother Joshua saw the play twice at the Samuel Beckett.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bear no grudge toward Ruskin,'' Millais said, ``but as a
family we knew the BBC documentaries and the books did not tell the
truth about her. She was exiled from Queen Victoria's court for
defying the ridiculous moral code that dictated that a woman must
endure in silence whatever her lord and master dealt her.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members have become so involved in ``The Countess'' that
Millais, a film producer, said she was in the beginning stages of
turning the play into a British period costume movie. For his part,
Joshua Millais, a portrait photographer in London, has done some of
the publicity photography for the show and has spoken at several
Victorian Nights.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ruskin, a viewer of the many letters at the Morgan, their
vellum paper shimmering against the mahogany tables, can see the
passionate declarations with which his marriage to Effie Gray, who
happened to be a distant cousin, began. A thrifty Scot, Effie often
``crosshatches,'' writing two pages on one by inscribing in both
directions to save paper, if not the reader's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   But some letters hint at the things that would inevitably divide
them. Writes Ruskin, in his thick tight script: ``My own Effie, my
mistress, my friend, my queen, my darling, my only love ... I can't
answer you a word today. I am going into town with my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   At a recent Grolier Club dinner celebrating Ruskin, Robert
Parks, the curator of the Bowerswell Papers at the Morgan, spoke
about the marriage. His listeners, a group of cosmopolitan
rare-book collectors, digging into plates of roast lamb, seemed to
agree among themselves that it was unfair to ``diminish'' the
reputation of an unusually complicated man, even if his life
directly contradicted his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``What many people don't realize,'' said Benjamin, who was
present, ``is that Ruskin supported many girls' schools and had
very deep friendships with women _ among them Kate Greenaway,'' the
artist and illustrator. ``He championed Kate Greenaway's art and
she was in love with him. He rejected her because she was frankly
not very pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruskin also asked her to send him her illustrations of little
girls stripped of their clothes. She ignored him.
</P>
<P>
   As the Grolier evening ended, Benjamin expressed satisfaction
with at least one development. ``During the exhibition of my Ruskin
collection in April, one day there suddenly appeared little
brochures on a table for `The Countess.' And apparently at the
theater, there were fliers for my exhibition. I registered a mild
complaint to the club management and I don't know what transpired.
All I know is that after that, I never saw any more brochures.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
