<SLUG> BC-POPEYES0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Popeyes to enter Indonesia
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Popeyes Chicken &AMP; Biscuits has signed an agreement
with an Indonesian company to open 56 restaurants within five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Popeyes, a subsidiary of Atlanta-based AFC Enterprises, inked
the five-year development deal with Pop Indo, which operates other
restaurants and manufactures restaurant equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for as many as three Popeyes to open by the end
of the year in Jakarta and Bandung.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fairly aggressive development schedule for
Indonesia,'' said spokesman Scott Hudler. ``Asia is one of our
strongholds in terms of brand presence.'' He said the company is
also targeting Central and South America for further development.
</P>
<P>
   Popeyes, which had 1999 systemwide sales of $1 billion, has more
than 1,425 restaurants in the United States and 21 other nations.
</P>
<P>
   Popeyes, which specializes in Cajun food, also unveiled a new
``Heritage'' building design at an Old National Highway restaurant.
All restaurants developed after July 1 will sport the new look, and
the company expects to convert all its restaurants within six
years, with balconies and other features found in New Orleans'
French Quarter. The chain was founded in New Orleans in 1972 and
acquired by AFC in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Popeyes also operates the Cajun Kitchen and Popeyes Cajun Cafe
concepts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
