<SLUG> BC-NY-ARTISTS-HOUSING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTBETH, A CANVAS STILL TAKING SHAPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.D.)  (Eds: also see MEIER-ARCHITECTURE) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two original residents of Westbeth _ the grand
experiment in subsidized artists' housing that opened in 1970 _ sat
side by side on a planter in front of the entrance. One had a long
graying beard and a brown fedora; the other was missing some teeth
and wore a fisherman's hat.
</P>
<P>
   Like them, Westbeth is showing its age.
</P>
<P>
   The buildings, which wrap around Bethune and West Streets, look
seedy: the Corbusian curved balconies seem to be rusting away; the
industrial metal windows whistle; the inner courtyard is bleak. The
fountain on the outer courtyard has been filled with concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, on its 30th anniversary, Westbeth is poised to reclaim its
original vision. As the oldest tenants die or move out, a new wave
of artists are taking their place. A recent residential rent
increase, sanctioned by the federal agency that controls the
property, paid for much-needed roof and sidewalk replacement.
Long-term commercial leases with rents at a fraction of current
market rates _ in one case, $4 a square foot versus $20 now _ are
about to expire, clearing the way for Westbeth finally to earn some
real money.
</P>
<P>
   On the artistic front, the Westbeth Gallery, which is a showcase
for tenants' work, has begun a retrospective series that some
artists say has sparked creative fervor.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are just now starting to rethink what it is Westbeth
should be doing,'' said Jack Dowling, a resident for 22 years and
the new director of the gallery. ``There's a lot of stuff happening
here now.''
</P>
<P>
   With real estate agents buzzing around the West Village like
angry hornets in search of a place to land, Westbeth residents, who
pay $350 to $650 a month for lofts with 13-foot ceilings, can count
themselves among Manhattan's luckiest: something comparable nearby
runs at least $2,000 to $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   When artists first applied, rents were as low as $99 a month. In
those idealistic days, a lot of things were taken on faith _ like
the applicants' verbal agreement with the interviewing committee
that, after a few years, they would move out, clearing the way for
struggling new artists.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone nodded and smiled. Hardly anyone left.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be a fool to move out, with these rents and this
location,'' said George Cominskie, a photographer's agent who moved
in 17 years ago to join his partner, an artist, and remained when
his partner left. Now, the tenants' council is debating hiring a
full-time social worker to address the needs of elderly artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was conceived, we hoped Westbeth would be a way
station, an incubator,'' said Joan Kaplan Davidson, whose family
foundation, the J.M. Kaplan Fund, helped create Westbeth and who
served as its first president. ``Artists would get established and
move on. That hasn't always happened.''
</P>
<P>
   A 13-building complex with 383 apartments, Westbeth was the
novel idea of Roger Stevens, the first chairman of the National
Endowment for the Arts, and Jacob M. Kaplan, a Manhattan
philanthropist who had made his money from grape juice. In the late
1960s, the two elderly men combed the city for a site that could be
converted into subsidized lofts for artists to live and work in.
They ultimately found a whole block: the vacant shell of the famous
Bell Telephone Laboratories, where color television and the
transistor radio were developed.
</P>
<P>
   They hired Richard Meier, a friend of Kaplan's son and, at 33,
an architect looking for his big break. Seed money from the Kaplan
Fund, plus a 3 percent, $12 million mortgage from the Housing and
Urban Development Department, would finance the conversion. Artists
would be vetted, and any tenants whose income rose above the limits
would pay a surcharge. HUD would regulate, advised by an
``insider'' council of artists-residents.
</P>
<P>
   Within two years, the adaptation was finished, and the critics
were ecstatic. On May 10, 1970, Ada Louise Huxtable, then the
architecture critic of The New York Times, wrote that Westbeth
``bent (but did not break)'' almost every bureaucratic rule and
called Meier's conversion ``exemplary.'' In an interview last week,
Huxtable said Westbeth, which remains the largest artists'
live-work complex in the world, seemed at the outset ``virgin,
beautiful: both the dream and the architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   But Westbeth at 30, while still innovative in many ways, is no
longer so innocent.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 19 suicides, some tenants say, starting with
Diane Arbus, who slit her wrists in her loft a year after Westbeth
opened. In a 1995 documentary video, ``Westbeth Growing Up,'' by
Allison Prete, one resident called the place ``Death-beth.'' Prete,
who grew up there, taped children of longtime tenants complaining
of Westbeth's ``dark side,'' which included walking to school past
bodies of people who had thrown themselves from the roof.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, others spoke of the ``combustibility'' and
``volatility'' of tenants with artistic temperaments living side by
side. They point to the lawsuits: Within the last decade, TUC
Management, which runs the building, has paid out more than $1
million in legal fees, a significant chunk of it trying to evict a
handful of tenants who didn't pay their rent or who carried out
illegal alterations, and defending the building when these tenants
countersued. HUD threatened to foreclose on the property several
times, because so many tenants were behind on their rent.
</P>
<P>
   Westbeth has not always been in such turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   When the first residents moved in, many left their doors open in
the spirit of community. Artists came together over potluck
dinners; dancers worked out, in the courtyard. But that kind of
love fest ended after a rent increase was imposed in the mid-1970s,
and some tenants mounted a rent strike.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that animosity lingers, aggravated by a mid-1980s plan
to raise money by turning the building into a co-op. The co-op
proposal, which would have allowed tenants to buy their apartments
at low prices, was narrowly defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the wrangling over financial matters, Westbeth is in
many ways a success. There is a 10-year wait for apartments, which
under the rules can be rented only to low- and middle-income
artists and their families. The current earnings limit is $34,200
for a three-person family and close to $50,000 for a family of six.
Artists who earn more after they move in are hit with a surcharge
of up to 60 percent. ``There are people earning millions, er, a lot
of money,'' said Bradford Winston, president of the management
company.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the atmosphere, many tenants say, is exactly what it was
designed to be: conducive to creativity.
</P>
<P>
   The Merce Cunningham Dance Company, a commercial tenant since
1971, rehearses on the 11th floor. Hans Haacke, a longtime
resident, set in motion an art-world shock this spring when his
piece for the Whitney Museum's Biennial, ``Sanitation,'' linked
Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani to the Nazis. The photographer Evelyn
Hofer still lives here. After Joseph Chaikin, the actor and
director and a Westbeth resident, had a stroke in 1984, Sam Shepard
drove cross-country to welcome him home from the hospital, and the
two locked themselves in the bedroom to finish up ``The War in
Heaven,'' a monologue subsequently performed by Chaikin, despite
his aphasia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Samuel Beckett came to a reading I gave of `Texts for
Nothing,''' Chaikin recalled in a halting voice. ``That was right
here in this apartment.'' Artists of all ages and degrees of career
success say that although Westbeth has been a significant part of
their creative life, it hasn't eliminated their travails.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been able to make a living doing painting,'' said
Barbara Prete, a painter who raised her three children in a
1,100-square-foot loft. She took on freelance writing and editing
to bolster her uneven income from art. ``The majority of artists
here are still struggling,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   As for the ones who are struggling just to get into Westbeth?
``If you've waited eight or 10 years,'' Prete said, ``you're
probably no longer a young artist.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
