u l BC-NY-ARTISTS-HOUSING &LR; - &UR;      05-24 0406
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ARTISTS-HOUSING </SLUG>
 - 2NDTAKE-NYT 
NEW YORK: young artist.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barton Lidice Benes, 57, is a collagist who has been assembling
found objects in his one-room studio at Westbeth for more than half
of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Although his is not a household name, he has achieved a fair
degree of success: a New York gallery represents him and he
recently attended an opening of a show of his works in a Swedish
castle.
</P>
<P>
   Benes is HIV positive, and although his health is fine for the
moment, some of his most recent work has death as its leitmotif.
Other works stacked in the small space are acid comments on fame.
</P>
<P>
   Within wooden cubbyholes, he has placed symbols of death _
funerary ashes and other reliquaries. In one slot he has placed a
dried rose. The label reads: ``From the Rose Garden, Village of
Lidice, Czech Republic, Destroyed by the Nazis, 1942.'' (He was
born that year and named after the town.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe what people send me: Here's a piece of
O.J.'s famous glove,'' he said, brandishing a well-worn brown glove
sent by Alan Dershowitz, the lawyer. In the master cubbyhole over
his desk, where he stores objects before incorporating them into
final works, there is a piece of Jamie Lee Curtis' string bikini
and a twig from what is said to be the broom that swept Mao's room
when he was a student.
</P>
<P>
   Benes says he has willed his entire apartment _ a mix of his own
work and his friends' and African paintings and masks _ to the
North Dakota Museum of Art in Grand Forks, to be installed in the
museum as a work of art.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1960s, Benes was eking out his artistic existence in
a $400-a-month walk-up apartment on East 18th Street. When he read
about Westbeth in The Village Voice, he jumped at the chance, even
though that part of the West Village was rife with drug dealers and
transvestite prostitutes. At Westbeth, he paid $99 a month. ``We
were only supposed to stay five years,'' he said. ``Thank God they
never enforced it.''
</P>
<P>
   Benes doesn't look for trouble; he doesn't sit on any committee
or enter the fray of Westbeth politics, which can be rugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a loner,'' Benes said. ``I'm friendly, but I'm a loner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning, they had big plans _ everyone kept their
doors open and everybody loved each other,'' he continued. ``But it
doesn't happen that way in life, especially life among artists. I
have a nice place to do my work. I'm pretty happy here.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
