<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-MISSIONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER BRINGS OPPORTUNITY FOR EYE-OPENING CHURCH YOUTH TRIPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAIME JORDAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike McDonough couldn't believe the poverty he saw in the small
villages outside Nairobi, Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   The 16-year-old saw people living in homes that could fit inside
his bedroom. They were without the luxuries of dependable
electricity or supermarkets filled with every food imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they survive and they're happy, the happiest people in the
world,'' said McDonough, 18. ``The material means nothing to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonough and other young people from Woods Chapel Baptist
Church in Arlington, Texas, spent part of last summer putting roofs
on unfinished churches in Kenya during a mission trip.
</P>
<P>
   He plans to go to Nicaragua with his church this summer, joining
the thousands of youth who participate in mission trips in and out
of the United States each year.
</P>
<P>
   The mission trips McDonough takes are organized through the
Challengers program, sponsored by Texas Baptist Men.
</P>
<P>
   It's a program for young men in grades seven through 12, said Al
Wise, pastor at Woods Chapel. Churches determine where the greatest
need is and gather volunteers to meet it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time period is a spiritual rite of passage,'' Wise said.
``This is a chance for them spiritually to grow, so when they do
become adults doing missions, it's like breathing. It just comes
naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   Curt Grice, youth minister at First Baptist Church in Arlington,
said the trips prepare young people for a life of service.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us as a church, it helps to train missionaries,'' he said.
``It gives life experience to kids who will be concerned about
their world as adults because they had this experience as
teen-agers.''
</P>
<P>
   First Baptist's high-school-age students will take trips to
Mexico and the border town of Laredo. Its junior-high youth will go
on a weekend trip to Houston, which will prepare them for the more
intense 10-day trips in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Other religious-group youth trips focus on educational
enrichment.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish youth often participate in cultural exchanges to Israel
during the summer, said Rabbi Jeffrey Kaye of Congregation Beth
Shalom. The trips are taken through the Jewish Reform Movement.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, high school sophomores join with others from across
the country and spend six weeks in cultural-exchange programs with
Israeli teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Literally, there are thousands of Jewish teens from all over
the country that participate,'' Kaye said.
</P>
<P>
   For teens, trips abroad are important because it exposes them to
different cultures, Grice said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The obvious thing is, it causes them to re-examine their
life,'' he said. ``It helps them appreciate what they have. It
helps them realize they don't need everything they want, and it
gives them a concern for the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The trips that Grice's groups take usually center on manual
labor, evangelism and Scripture distribution, backyard Bible clubs
or vacation Bible schools. When the group goes to Mexico this
summer, it will hold a basketball clinic for the native youth, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The toughest work for the group is the construction or
renovation of buildings for church sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year in San Antonio, the junior high kids spent two days
landscaping a little church down there, and that's as hard as most
of them have ever worked in their life,'' Grice said. ``In fact, it
may have been as hard as I've worked in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the stumbling blocks for youth is the cost. The trips can
be as much as $2,500 per person, he said.
</P>
<P>
   First Baptist tries to subsidize its trips. Churches often have
funds set aside for trips and can guide youth toward fund-raising
opportunities, he said.
</P>
<P>
   World Changers, a program under the North American Mission Board
in Georgia, charges $235 for its trips to cities in the United
States and in other countries, Stephanie Lim said. The cost covers
food and lodging while the youth are working, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many churches undertake fund-raising projects throughout the
year to offset the costs. This summer, high school students from
First Christian Church in Arlington will do flood-relief work in
North Carolina for a week. The church recently held a yard sale to
raise money for the trip and other projects.
</P>
<P>
   Working toward a goal, as well as eye-opening experiences with
different cultures, are all part of the spiritual journey, Wise
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the reasons we are what we are, because of
missions,'' he said. ``It gives them the opportunity to have
firsthand experience. It helps them to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
