<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4740 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-OPERA-HEROES-$ADV28-A     05-24 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-HEROES-$ADV28-ART-1,200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE ROOM ON OLYMPUS FOR TODAY'S SACRED MONSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 28) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT27 was sent May 23 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leontyne Price, the reigning diva of the 1960s and '70s, was
chatting with National Public Radio during intermission in a
broadcast from the San Francisco Opera. Who, the interviewer asked,
were the singers who had shown Price the way? The last of the names
she rattled off in the tones of an empress was ``La Callas.'' She
had turned opera into something people really cared about, Price
said, ``like baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Like baseball, all the arts need their heroes. But the art of
opera, unlike baseball or hockey or skiing or even tennis, belongs
to a frightening degree to custodians who choose to live in the
past. ``The garland briefer than a girl's,'' A.E. Housman called
the athlete's glory in a famous poem; in sports, records exist to
be shattered. But the vestals of opera (critics, biographers, a
vocal clique of reactionary fans) treat the starry dead like so
many Babe Ruths, and the living like riffraff from a farm team in
an age when the major leagues have ceased to exist.
</P>
<P>
   The public at large wants nothing more than to be swept away in
real time, as the nightly, obligatory ovations in our major opera
houses prove. To some, those ovations merely prove how deep the art
has sunk. ``Madame So-and-So was just a house soprano in the Polish
provinces,'' say the censorious, who are incapable of enjoyment but
cannot stay away. ``If she came along today, she could write her
own ticket from Vienna, Milan and London to New York and San
Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, yes. And if we could travel back to any era we liked, what
would we find? A few real divinities here and there, working their
miracles against the backdrop mostly of mere routine if not
mediocrity and incompetence. Much has changed in the world, but not
this. Chronicles of those who were there make this truth very
clear. So, in their way, do field trips to the provinces, where
time stands still. (Try Parma.)
</P>
<P>
   For Price, Callas was no death's head but a spur to greatness.
Why should it be otherwise today? The most important lesson Callas
taught her fellow artists was that at the level of genius, a
performer is as much a creator as a playwright, a composer, a
choreographer. The same sovereignty of imagination that transforms
experience into an ``original'' work of art may be brought to bear
on the realization of the words and notes on the page or the steps
of a dance in performance. Such art is perishable _ it is consumed
in its creation _ but it is not of a lesser order. And it leaves
its traces.
</P>
<P>
   What opera needs, at least as much as great voices, is great
personalities. Not ``divas,'' in the debased sense of egomaniacs
with mannerisms, but intrepid explorers of the human condition,
each a Ulysses who has traveled far, seen much, felt deeply.
Explorers who convey the fullness of experience through music, word
and gesture, touching, in ways unique to themselves, the chord of
the universal. At this level, singing a role is no more an act of
``reproduction'' than writing it in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   A current truism of operatic commentary (echoed also in
criticism of instrumentalists and conductors) is that
conservatories and young-artist programs are churning out
interchangeable nonentities, good boys and girls who are well
prepared but anonymous. The old Countess of Tchaikovsky's ``Queen
of Spades'' speaks for fogies of all ages as she mourns the gilded
memory of her youth: ``Who are the dancers now?'' she asks. ``Who
sings? Little nobodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Little nobodies? Actually, there are quite a few candidates for
induction in the Olympian hall of fame out there, at or near their
prime. The bewitching Cecilia Bartoli, the Dickensian Bryn Terfel
and the glamorous Renee Fleming are three whose names come
instantly to mind, but they are not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Looking no farther than the Metropolitan Opera, we have seen
within recent seasons the radiant Finnish soprano Karita Mattila as
Elsa in ``Lohengrin,'' the sumptuous Russian mezzo-soprano Olga
Borodina as the Philistine siren in Saint-Saens' ``Samson et
Dalila'' and the German Rene Pape, noblest of basses, as a pair of
Wagnerian kings.
</P>
<P>
   As for Jane Eaglen, the heroine of Wagner's ``Tristan und
Isolde'' and ``Der Ring des Nibelungen'' this season, is she the
long-awaited Real Thing or the next Rita Hunter? That singer _ not
so towering as Eaglen but equally larger than life _ was another
dramatic soprano from England, praised to the skies by the
Anglophile music critic Andrew Porter, whose English translation of
the ``Ring'' she sang and recorded with the English National Opera.
Porter did his vain best to sell her to the American public but had
to admit that her appearances in New York never lived up to the
showing she made in London.
</P>
<P>
   To do her justice, Hunter gave value for money in daunting
assignments when no one else was at hand to do better. So does
Eaglen. But does she leave a lasting imaginative stamp on the
characters she plays? It may be too soon to say.
</P>
<P>
   As the doll in ``Les Contes d'Hoffmann'' _ visibly expecting,
whirling on point while tossing off the most brilliant, intricate
and altitudinous roulades _ the French coloratura soprano Natalie
Dessay did so for sure. Catherine Malfitano's Emilia Marty in ``The
Makropulos Case'' was an electrifying creation, hailed as such by
critics and audiences alike. The Carmen of Waltraud Meier, slammed
in the press, struck me as no less authentic and persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   Across the plaza at the New York City Opera, Lauren Flanigan
this season found in Susan B. Anthony, of Virgil Thomson's ``Mother
of Us All,'' an assignment to justify the sometimes hyperbolic
praise her fierce, unsentimental, even bitter interpretations
regularly generate. The countertenor Bejun Mehta, breathing fire in
music of Handel at City Opera, and even more in his out-of-the-blue
debut with Millennial Arts Productions, has demonstrated decidedly
mythic potential. Alas, Angela Gheorghiu's Violetta in ``La
Traviata,'' once announced by the Met, never materialized
hereabouts; but in a video from Covent Garden, her disarming
portrayal combines the personal beauty and warmth of a Julia
Roberts with the haunting vocal pathos of a Claudia Muzio. We
definitely missed something there.
</P>
<P>
   Argue as we may about particulars, Olympians are very much with
us. And among them, there is a particularly rare, particularly
fascinating subspecies, metaphorically the most operatic of them
all. Call them the sacred monsters. As the term suggests, there is
in these uncompromising, stubborn, even nettlesome creatures at
least a touch of the demonic. They are laws unto themselves. They
must have their way. Olympians go the distance. Sacred monsters go
too far. They conquer and divide.
</P>
<P>
   Terfel is one, though less controversial than some. His
performances have of late taken on a histrionic, highly italicized
character some critics suggest he might tone down. Terfel knows
what they think and proceeds his way, undeterred.
</P>
<P>
   With more dubious wisdom, Gheorghiu once refused to manage a
phrase of Verdi's as Georg Solti gently insisted, setting her own
naive, literalistic notions above the experience and expertise of
his long lifetime. Talent and a rage for control may be two sides
of a single coin.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The epitome of the sacred monster at the moment is surely the
Argentine tenor Jose Cura, 38. So far, New Yorkers have seen him
just three times, in a single production, as the Sicilian lothario
Turiddu in Mascagni's ``Cavalleria Rusticana,'' amid the wreckage
of the once picturesque staging by Franco Zeffirelli, woefully led
by Carlo Rizzi and partnered by the uncongenial Santuzza of Dolora
Zajick. Thanks to Placido Domingo in his capacity as artistic
director of the Washington Opera, audiences in the capital have
taken Cura's measure in two of his signature roles: Saint-Saens'
Samson and Verdi's Otello.
</P>
<P>
   In the biblical spectacular, he bore the destiny of the
despondent Chosen People on heroic shoulders, his prophetic song
ringing forth with dark, blazing grandeur. His authority was total.
But his last Washington ``Otello'' this spring was an altogether
more daring affair. Of the British stage idol Edmund Kean, Samuel
Coleridge wrote, ``To see him act is like reading Shakespeare by
flashes of lightning,'' and so it was with Cura in Verdi's
Shakespearean mode.
</P>
<P>
   Praise or censure? That depends on your point of view. Between
lightning flashes fell long spells of pitch dark. On prior
occasions in Europe, Cura had executed the notes with a
scrupulousness that had only boosted his tremendous conception of
the part. This time, rather than sing the music, he chose to
channel the character. Call it extreme music drama, and say, if you
can, whether it unfolded through or in spite of the music. Over the
radio or on a recording, it might have sounded grotesque, but it
was hair-raising to be there.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who witnessed Cura's Washington Otello is Barbara
Cook, the Broadway star of midcentury who created the roles of
Marian the Librarian in ``The Music Man'' and Cunegonde in
``Candide,'' and continues to wrap audiences around her finger in
cabaret and concert performances. (One prominent London critic has
repeatedly placed her artistry on a par with that of Callas.)
</P>
<P>
   Unlike critics, whose professional obligation to endure upward
of a hundred evenings of opera a year many have patently come to
regret, Cook has the luxury of attending purely as the spirit moves
her. For the last year or so, between engagements of her own, she
has traveled as far afield as Madrid, Paris and London to keep up
with Cura's performances.
</P>
<P>
   Why such devotion? ``It's the total package,'' Cook said
recently. ``In any era, only a very few people are at the pinnacle.
I can't think of anybody who sings as well, who acts as well, who
moves as well. It's like watching a great baseball player who has
this terrific masculine grace. Whatever things might be wrong with
Jose's performances, he has a concentration that pulls you right
into his world.''
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, viewers in more than a hundred countries will be
tuning in for their Cura fix in a live telecast of ``La Traviata,''
spread out over installments on June 3 and June 4, and shot in what
are billed as authentic Paris locations. (Cinema verite meets
Masterpiece Theater.) The prima donna is the hitherto unknown Eteri
Gvazava, of Siberia, cast, Cura says, after the sort of talent
search that produced Hollywood's Scarlett O'Hara.
</P>
<P>
   By rights, Verdi's tragedy of the fallen woman redeemed by
suffering is the soprano's opera, but this time it may be the
tenor's. Not that Alfredo Germont, the romantic but callow
bourgeois papa's boy who woos Violetta from her life of soulless
pleasure, is the sort of character one associates with Cura's
brooding macho presence.
</P>
<P>
   Cura has admitted as much, adding: ``Alfredo has gotten the
greatest courtesan in Paris to give up everything for him. There
must be a reason.'' Americans may decide for themselves in the
fall, when the show is expected to appear on PBS; a Teldec CD of
the soundtrack, conducted by Zubin Mehta, goes on sale here in
July.
</P>
<P>
   To a degree seldom if ever matched in the annals of opera, Cura
_ also a composer and conductor _ marches to his own drum. On
``Verismo,'' his latest CD for Erato, he dedicates a whole program
to a style of the late 19th and early 20th centuries commonly
thought vulgar and sensationalistic. Acting as his own conductor,
he sets out to redefine it as a school of chaste refinement.
</P>
<P>
   In the hit-and-run show stopper ``Amor ti vieta,'' from
Giordano's dismal ``Fedora,'' the delicacy of the phrasing (lines
taken in a single breath alternating with lines of similar length
taken in two) is as unusual as it is natural and discreet. There
are discoveries like this to be made throughout. And nowhere will
you find Cura clinging, in self-indulgent spaghetti-tenor fashion,
to top notes the composer actually wrote or did not.
</P>
<P>
   On his very best vocal behavior, Cura here gives the lie to
those who have said that he has no technique. What we hear, by
contrast, in such daredevil performances as the Washington
``Otello'' is a self-conscious, highly idiosyncratic technique
fraught with peril. How well it will serve Cura in the long run
remains to be seen. Self-immolation is not actually required of
sacred monsters, but longevity is not always their strong suit.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever lies ahead, Cura has already earned his place as one of
the most supremely original performers of the age. But gentler
Olympians, too, are capable of redefining the terms by which the
game is played.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the case of Fleming. For the last few seasons, it has
seemed that she can do no wrong. In Mozart and Strauss, audiences
delight in her floating pianissimo. In bel canto, she dazzles with
her coloratura and impromptu leaps to the stratosphere. William
Christie, the Baroque specialist, who recently collaborated with
her on Handel's ``Alcina,'' went wild for her rococo inflections, a
carry-over from her youthful experience in jazz. The sold-out signs
go up even when she sings a contemporary, all-American program.
</P>
<P>
   By common consent, the foundation on which Fleming's stardom
rests is the sheer beauty of her voice, a property as axiomatic as
the propositions of Euclid. John Kander _ the composer of ``The
Visit,'' due on Broadway next spring, starring Angela Lansbury, and
such indestructible hits as ``Chicago'' and ``Cabaret'' _ is the
sort of opera fan who looks for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opera has played a great role in my life, but not for the
high-C songbirds,'' Kander said recently. ``When I was still a boy,
I fell in love with the people, the people in `La Boheme,' in `Die
Meistersinger,' in `Der Rosenkavalier,' in `Pelleas et Melisande.'
Those people became very real to me. They still are.''
</P>
<P>
   And is Fleming just a high-C songbird? ``When she's done a role
a number of times, and she's really into it,'' he said, ``she gives
wonderful lessons.'' The first example that comes to his mind is
from ``Der Rosenkavalier'' this season. In the nick of time, the
Marschallin stops herself from blurting out to her young lover what
happened once when her husband barged in on her unannounced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before that one word `einmal,' `once,' she gave the dirtiest
laugh,'' Kander said. ``I loved it. A real snicker. It told me
something about that woman.'' That she's not ashamed? ``Yes, that,
and that she's had some swell times.''
</P>
<P>
   I remember that nuance, and others, not all of them vocal. From
time immemorial, the Marschallin has spent the calm and sensuous
yet depressed orchestral postlude of the first act gazing in her
mirror, facing in her reflection the relentless passage of time.
Fleming instead worked with a rose.
</P>
<P>
   By this point, she had already turned the silver rose for the
young bride Sophie von Fanninal into a bittersweet emblem of the
Marschallin's own lost youth. But that rose, in its fancy
presentation case, had just been carried from the room. On a
dressing table lay another one, cut from a garden, a gift from the
flighty hairdresser whose ministrations this morning she feels have
made her look old. Fleming picked it up and found the hard truth of
the moment that way, sweeping away an entire performance tradition
in an image many a future Marschallin could choose to follow.
</P>
<P>
   A speaking glance no one could anticipate. A gesture, an
inflection, a tone or phrase that unlocks a world. A radical
rethinking of a well-known role or the incandescent creation of a
new one. These are the stuff memories are made of. But there is
something better than memories: fresh experience in the here and
now. Now and again, lightning strikes. Keep your eyes wide open.
Dreams can wait.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
