<HEADER>
A4743 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-BOS &LR;      05-24 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS DEBATE MEANING OF PULLOUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEL AVIV _ Was it Israel's Vietnam, this hurried withdrawal from
a foreign land? A humiliation, witnessed by the suffering of
southern Lebanese struggling to flee into Israel because they
feared retribution for aligning with the Jewish state? A defeat for
a country that tried to enforce stability through occupation?
</P>
<P>
   These very points were debated late into the night here on radio
and television, with terms bandied about such as Saigon, house of
cards, embarrassment and loss.
</P>
<P>
   The themes also were picked up in the cafes and shops of this
seaside city, pulsing with shoppers, workers, students and
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a humiliation and it's not a question of pride for
the army; we simply made a mistake in going into Lebanon and now we
have finally left,'' said Gila Zvi, 33, between sips of coffee and
shakes of a colored rattle in front of her 2-month-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Experts and analysts and average Israelis who called in to talk
shows could not decide whether the pullout was a sign of weakness
or the inevitable end of a military policy that had proven too
unpopular and too difficult to maintain anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to celebrate, but also no reason to wear
sackcloth and break into tears,'' said political commentator Nahum
Barnea.
</P>
<P>
   Well-known writer Meir Shalev insisted that those who saw the
withdrawal from south Lebanon as a humiliation or sign of failure
were misguided.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at south Lebanon and did not see Saigon. I observed
my posture and it was upright. I glanced at my tail and it was not
between my legs,'' he wrote in Yediot Ahronoth, Israel's biggest
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already tried all the troubles of war, let's give the
withdrawal a chance,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the talk of whether Israel should feel embarrassed
at how it retreated or whether the occupation was merely based on a
military approach that later proved wrong, the withdrawal was being
analyzed with one eye toward the future.
</P>
<P>
   If the border remains quiet despite Hezbollah fighters just on
the other side of the fence, then Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
decision to go ahead with the unilateral pullout will be hailed by
the public, never mind those first few days when it looked like the
army had been kicked out by a bunch of motley rebels.
</P>
<P>
   But if there is fighting, if Israelis in the northern border
towns end up spending much of their days and nights in underground
shelters, then Barak will be pilloried and the withdrawal itself
will look like a defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that at this stage the army has come out of this
badly,'' said Gerald Steinberg, a national security expert at
Bar-Ilan University.
</P>
<P>
   ``If after three months nothing happens on the border, then any
analogies with Vietnam and other similar statements may
disappear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the cafes near Rabin Square, where Prime Minister Ehud Barak
last year, on the eve of his election, promised to withdraw from
Lebanon by July of this year, the issue seemed even simpler.
</P>
<P>
   It was in this square that Israelis held the first mass protest
against the 1982 invasion of Lebanon and it was here that Israelis
continued to protest the occupation zone formally established in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, 35-year-old Smadar Hazan, who was shopping with a
friend, looked shocked when asked if Israel's image as a tough
country with an even tougher army was somehow harmed by the
unilateral withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the contrary, Israel gained something,'' she said.
``Soldiers no longer will be dying in a foreign land. We are
protecting lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see it as a Vietnam, there's a big difference, that
was miles away to fight a war that wasn't their own, we were trying
to protect our border,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But as dusty tanks rolled across the border and young soldiers
screamed out, ``I'm home!'' any deeper meaning to be found in the
withdrawal gave way to joy tinged with sadness as Israel's war of
attrition drew to a close.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have waited for this day a long time, and the soldiers were
able to get out without anyone being killed or any attacks,'' Orna
Shimoni, whose son was killed in Lebanon three years ago, said on
Israel state television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet we have to remember that many sons could not come back and
say, `Mother, I'm home,' '' she said from the northern border town
of Kiryat Shmona.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
