<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4744 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-GATES-NYT &LR;      05-24 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-GATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHILE HIS LAWYERS PLEAD, GATES PLAYS HOST TO 135 EXECUTIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  (With MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST) 
 By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ While Microsoft's lawyers pleaded with a
federal judge not to break up the company, Bill Gates and other
senior company executives were painting a rosy picture of a
software-enhanced future Wednesday for chief executives of some of
the world's largest companies.
</P>
<P>
   The focus of the annual event on Microsoft's campus here was on
the Internet's impact on business and, to a lesser extent,
consumers. In the limited portion of the gathering open to the
media, the courtroom battle over Microsoft's survival was not even
mentioned.
</P>
<P>
   The guest list included notable Friends of Bill like Warren E.
Buffett; major customers like Michael Dell of Dell Computer and
Michael D. Capellas of Compaq Computer; fellow software vendors
like Carol Bartz of Autodesk Inc.; international luminaries like
Richard Branson, founder of Virgin Group; and cultural icons like
Martha Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   In all, there were 142 executives from 28 countries and 35
business sectors, according to Microsoft. Gates called the
gathering a ``learning event'' for the company as it tried to sort
out what kind of Internet-related software is a priority for
business.
</P>
<P>
   The guests declined to say whether Microsoft's plight was
discouraging open discussion of the impact of antitrust law on
technology development. But Capellas, in a brief session with
reporters, said that collaboration and standards allowing people to
exchange information in a variety of formats were essential to the
Internet's development. He added, as Gates betrayed no emotion,
``Anything that gets in the way of allowing us to build complete
solutions is a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Microsoft seemed intent on treating uncertainty about
its corporate future as taboo, its efforts to develop products for
the future it foresees and its own use of them were prominently
featured. Ever the salesman, Gates, Microsoft's chairman, delivered
an opening address peppered with phrases like ``the magic of
software.''
</P>
<P>
   Every chief executive received a new Pocket PC, the hand-held
computer from Hewlett-Packard, equipped with Microsoft software for
reading electronic books and other Web-based functions.
</P>
<P>
   The computers _ personal digital assistants in the industry's
jargon _ included pictures and biographies of all the attendees to
encourage the social mixing and informal discussion that is
typically the main attraction for such exclusive business
gatherings. The discussions closed to the media covered evergreen
subjects like ``Strategies for the Age of Speed: Reinvention as an
Ongoing Task'' as well as pressing concerns like ``Internet
Valuations: How High? How Long? How Painful?''
</P>
<P>
   Those whose attention drifted could listen to classical music or
read books that had been loaded onto the devices, including Michael
Crichton's new novel, ``Timeline.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates' remarks centered on the thesis that the Internet age was
entering a ``third stage.'' The first stage, which he identified as
running from 1995 to 1998, was characterized by corporate Web sites
that provided data for people to read and measured how many
visitors they received. The second stage, still around in most
areas, he said, features a ``mania for getting transactions onto
the Web'' in which gross sales are ``worshiped'' with little
attention to how much they cost.
</P>
<P>
   The stage now beginning, he said, will focus on Internet
activities that contribute to profitability and make better use of
``knowledge workers.'' Such workers will receive information
personalized to their needs from many sites on a variety of devices
that allow them to write and annotate through speech recognition,
as well as simply read, and the information will be used to
actually do business online.
</P>
<P>
   In a more concrete example of what is coming, he described how
Microsoft has begun holding meetings online. Smaller numbers of
workers actually attend, but many monitor the progress, sometimes
dropping in for the portion relevant to them; tidbits that apply to
the work of those not present can be captured and forwarded to
them.
</P>
<P>
   Gates also did his best to entertain his guests. A video called
``Everyone's Talking Technology'' featured, among other scenes, a
court battle before Judge Judy in which Buffett accused Gates of
deliberately disconnecting his computer rather than play out an
online hand of bridge in which he was about to lose a $2 bet to
Buffett. Judge Judy ordered Gates to pay up, expressing the belief
that Buffett might be able to make a useful investment.
</P>
<P>
   The event began Tuesday evening with a cocktail reception at the
stately Four Seasons Olympic Hotel in downtown Seattle and
continued Wednesday night with the social highlight of the
conclave, a boat cruise and visit to Gates' futuristic mansion on
the shores of Lake Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
