<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUMPKINS-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE PUMPKINS GONE TO MUSH?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Smashing Pumpkins leader Billy Corgan seemed stretched to his
musical limit at the band's packed-to-the-rafters Universal
Amphitheatre show Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On a day when Corgan announced on KROQ-FM (106.7) that the
current ``Sacred and Profane'' tour would be the Pumpkins' last,
the bald, six-foot leather-skirted singer, looking like a grinning
Uncle Fester by way of ``The Matrix,'' saw his music reduced to
deafening mush for an audience that didn't seem to mind either way.
</P>
<P>
   Smashing Pumpkins, it seems, is a studio band able to make
clean, well-produced records. On stage during a frustrating
two-hour set, however, Corgan's musicians simply aren't very
convincing. New bassist Melissa Auf Der Maur, formerly of Hole, and
rhythm guitarist James Iha consistently offered unimaginative,
rudimentary parts.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless the sweat-soaked audience at Universal danced,
screamed and waved arms in the air regardless of what was
presented. A messy, noisy cover of the 1974 David Essex hit, ``Rock
On,'' drew the same roar as Corgan's many touching and tuneful
numbers, such as ``1979,'' ``Tonight, Tonight'' and ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   The monkish Corgan clearly speaks to his enormous audience but
the band's look and sound is increasingly hard to swallow. The
leader's singing voice, tolerable on tape, frequently amounted to
little more than an abrasive, strangled wail. On the acoustic
numbers, he seemed to be over-emoting for comic effect.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Pumpkins' best-known hard-rock numbers, ``Bullet with
Butterfly Wings'' and ``Cherub Rock,'' were difficult to
distinguish as the guitars were turned up so loud that the only
thing to be heard was a painful white-noise buzz.
</P>
<P>
   Corgan said on KROQ the Pumpkins, which recently fulfilled its
contract with EMI's Virgin Records, would finish the current U.S.
tour, head to Europe, Japan, Canada, and maybe South America before
the end of the year and then call it quits. The Chicago-based band,
with worldwide sales of 23 million, will tape VH1's
``Storytellers`` in August, and an appearance on ``The Tonight Show
With Jay Leno'' is also scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   But Corgan said fans can expect more releases from the Pumpkins,
including another album's worth of songs and a live disc.
</P>
<P>
   On stage, the singer-guitarist seemed to make reference to the
forthcoming breakup when he grabbed the microphone: ``Are you ready
for the revolution? Does anyone want to testify? Whether you're a
name, or a number, things are changing.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by this gig, the change is probably for the better.
Corgan can write wonderful songs. Maybe it's time for someone else
to perform them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1911EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4749 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-LEBANON-BOS     05-24 0386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-LEBANON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERDUE WITHDRAWAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite the chaos it has engendered in southern Lebanon and the
uncertainty it has created in the region, Israel's rapid withdrawal
from its so-called security zone in Lebanon represents a
long-overdue correction of a failed policy.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's occupation of Lebanese soil began with an intervention
against Palestinian guerrillas in 1978. Then came the reckless
Israeli invasion of 1982, which began with Shi'ite residents of
southern Lebanon throwing flowers upon Israeli tanks to express
their gratitude for what they thought would be their liberation
from the PLO's state-within-a-state. Israel's folly was to overstay
its welcome, by 18 years. During that prolonged occupation, Israel
succeeded in making an enemy of many of the Lebanese who had
originally greeted the Israel Defense Forces as welcome
emancipators.
</P>
<P>
   There are obvious dangers in the current withdrawal, as is
evident from the swift disintegration of Israel's proxies, the
Southern Lebanon Army, and from the Katyusha rockets fired Tuesday
from Lebanon into the Galilee. Nonetheless, Prime Minister Ehud
Barak deserves support for keeping his promise to pull Israeli
soldiers out of Lebanon by July 7 _ with or without a peace deal
with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the withdrawal is completed, Israel has complied,
albeit belatedly, with United Nations Resolution 425. It will now
be up to the UN to fulfill the next step, Resolution 426, by
deploying its monitoring force to facilitate an assumption of
authority in southern Lebanon by the Lebanese army. And since no
such action by the government in Beirut is possible without
approval from Syria, the ultimate responsibility for peace in
southern Lebanon will fall on the true master of Lebanon, Syrian
ruler Hafez Assad.
</P>
<P>
   If Hezbollah rockets kill civilians in Israel, the retaliation
may hit Syrian targets. Assad might not appreciate the implications
of his 40,000 soldiers being the only remaining army of occupation
left in Lebanon, but he should hear from Washington, Paris, Cairo,
and Amman that he will be held responsible for any rockets fired
into Israel from Lebanon. And Assad and Barak should both be
shepherded back to the bargaining table.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1912EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
