u f BC-UNITED-UPDATE-STREET &LR;      05-24 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITED-UPDATE-STREET </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UAL, US AIRWAYS COULD HAVE BUMPY FLIGHT TO MERGER COMPLETION 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER FRIEDLIN   
 c. 2000 NYTimes.com/TheStreet.com   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As UAL (UAL:NYSE) moved Wednesday to acquire US Airways
(U:NYSE), Wall Street analysts pointed to several potential
obstacles that could derail the deal.
</P>
<P>
   They listed possible labor discord, antitrust issues and the
tough task of making the marriage work as potential pitfalls and
cited previous failed airline consolidation efforts as proof of the
difficulties that carriers face when they try to merge.
</P>
<P>
   A deal between US Airways and American Airlines fell through
last year because of enormous cost overruns. That failed bid came
one year after a code-sharing deal between the nation's biggest
airline, United, of which UAL is the parent, and Delta Air Lines
(DAL:NYSE) flopped after Delta management refused to grant the
pilots' union a voting seat on the board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, some people on Wall Street were skeptical that
United Airlines would be able to complete its deal for US Airways.
UAL said earlier on Wednesday that it would pay $4.3 billion in
cash for US Airways and assume $7.3 billion in debt and operating
leases.
</P>
<P>
   Still, investors in US Airways were enthusiastic, driving the
share up about 80 percent, because the price UAL was willing to pay
was more than double the airline's stock price on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But among the issues that tempered that enthusiasm was labor
difficulties, which could put the brakes on the merger. A unified
workforce could have difficulty agreeing to seniority lists and
bidding rights for schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Dubinsky, chairman of the United Airlines Master Executive
Council, a unit of the Air Line Pilots Association, said in a
statement that he was ``deeply disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Before today, the company and the UAL-MEC faced the enormous
challenge of reaching a satisfactory pilot contract that rewards
our pilots for the sacrifices we have made to return United to
profitability,'' he added. ``The proposed merger will make that
task even more difficult by requiring the integration of two very
different pilot groups into a single airline.'' The union
represents about 10,000 United pilots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although United's and US Airways' boards have approved this
transaction, the rank and file are the ones that have to work
together and agree to the new work ranking they may have in this
new airline (which) determines their seniority in bidding for
flying time,'' said Susan Donofrio, an analyst with Deutsche Banc
Alex. Brown. ``This has been one of the stumbling blocks of
previous potential mergers.''
</P>
<P>
   And, if labor problems don't scuttle the transaction, analysts
said regulatory concerns could.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal is not an antitrust cake walk,'' wrote James Higgins,
an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, in a research report.
``There is a real question as to whether regulators will approve
such concentration in an industry whose competitiveness is already
a concern to many.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined carriers would control 30 percent of U.S. airline
capacity, with American, the nation's second-largest carrier,
lagging behind with 20 percent capacity, Higgins said. He
downgraded his rating for UAL to an underperform from a buy. It
could not be determined if DLJ does any underwriting for the
companies.
</P>
<P>
   UAL and US Airways, however, managed to preempt regulators'
criticism over direct route overlap into and out of Washington,
D.C. In its announcement, United said it would sell some of its
assets to a US Airways board member, Robert Johnson. Johnson, the
founder, chairman and chief executive of BET Holdings II, a media
holding company, would then create a new airline, to be called DC
Air. That carrier would operate out of Washington Reagan National
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The companies did not disclose how much Johnson would be paying
for the carrier's assets.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, concerns about the possible obstacles did little to temper
the demand for shares of US Airways, which has recently faced labor
problems and larger-than-expected losses. Under the terms of the
deal, UAL will pay $60 a share for all the outstanding shares of US
Airways, a 130 percent premium based on US Airway's closing price
Tuesday of 26 5/16. Shares of US Airways of Arlington, Va.,
rocketed 21 15/16, or 83 percent, to 48 1/4 by Wednesday afternoon.
(US Airways finished up 22 11/16, or 86 percent, at 49.)
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Chicago-based UAL were off 8 7/16, or 14 percent, to
51 15/16. (UAL closed down 7 3/16, or 12 percent, at 53 3/16.)
</P>
<P>
   The news also helped buoy shares of Northwest Airlines
(NWAC:NASDAQ), which is now seen as a target should the industry
further consolidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the transaction is likely to set off a wave of
consolidation in the industry,'' Candace Browning, airline analyst
at Merrill Lynch, wrote in a report. ``Northwest, with a strategic
asset in the Pacific, strong domestic hubs and a 13.5 percent
economic interested in Continental (CAL:NYSE) is a very attractive
acquisition candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Northwest was up 2 3/4, or 11 percent, at 26 7/8. (Northwest
finished up 4 13/16, or 20 percent, at 28 15/16.)
</P>
<P>
   Browning upgraded Northwest to an accumulate/buy from a
neutral/accumulate. A Merrill Lynch spokesman said he did not know
if his company has done any underwriting for Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AMR (AMR:NYSE), parent of American, were off because
of investor concerns about lost market share following the merger
between US Airways and UAL. That concern sparked speculation that
AMR might offer a counterbid for US Airways. AMR was down 3 5/16,
or 10 percent, at 29 5/16. (AMR closed down 2 9/16, or 8 percent,
at 30 1/16.)
</P>
<P>
   UAL and US Airways said they expected to complete the deal in
2001, noting that the purchase would add to United's earnings in
the second year following the closing.
</P>
<P>
   (For use by clients of The New York Times News Service)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4755 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     05-24 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING OUT HOW MUCH   FREE SHIPPING IS WORTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: S.C., N.C., Ill.)   By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I have been told that in some families a hammock can last for
years. I am more familiar with the sort of situation in which eight
small and medium-size children who are pretending to be pirates
routinely pile onto a hammock, rock it vigorously to simulate high
seas and dangle 16 legs through the mesh to taunt imaginary sharks.
</P>
<P>
   One cannot really expect miracles from a natural cotton rope
structure supported by two spreader bars and zinc-plated hanging
hardware. Even the sturdy old oaks that suspend the ``ship'' are in
peril.
</P>
<P>
   So almost every year, I buy a new hammock, and it's always the
same model (since there's nothing wrong with the product that
pirate-proofing wouldn't fix): the ``original Pawleys Island rope
hammock,'' made in North Carolina and distributed nationwide.
According to the manufacturer's Web site, Pawleys.com, it comes in
three sizes. I buy the middle size, which can hold two adults or
450 pounds or as many as eight bloodthirsty buccaneers. The last
hammock, if I recall correctly, came from a mail-order catalog. I
paid about $100 for it, plus shipping, which set me back an
additional $10 or so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus shipping.'' In the months since buying the hammock, I
have come to realize that ``plus shipping'' is one of the ugliest
phrases in the English language. Thanks to the multitude of online
retailers who offered free shipping during last winter's holiday
shopping season, I have been conditioned to believe that I am
entitled to this perk forever.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of online shoppers share my expectations, it turns out.
Last week, Forrester Research reported that 94 percent of online
shoppers were concerned about shipping costs and that 44 percent
had abandoned an online shopping cart after they found out how much
the shipping costs would add to the total. These are, mind you, the
same shoppers who for years accepted mail-order catalogs' shipping
charges, which often add up to 15 percent to the cost of a
purchase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers have different expectations when they shop online,
not only because the retail sites raised their expectations during
the Christmas season, but also because shoppers see that they are
giving the sites something in return, information about
themselves,'' said Susy Chan, director of the e-commerce technology
program at DePaul University in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Now that she mentioned it, I did resent typing in all kinds of
valuable personal information _ name, address, phone number, name
of street where I grew up in case I forgot my password and needed a
prompt every time I bought something online. Beyond the privacy
concerns, these questions are annoyingly time-consuming. I should
be compensated.
</P>
<P>
   So last week, I started my search for a hammock at a site called
freeshipping.com (www.freeshipping.com), which has a search engine
to point shoppers toward about a million products that the site's
125 retail partners are willing to sell without charging shipping
and handling fees. Freeshipping.com's partners _ who include both
well-known retailers like Cooking.com and smaller specialty
retailers like Kideo.com, which sells personalized children's
videos _ pay freeshipping.com a commission for sales referrals.
</P>
<P>
   Freeshipping.com's founder, D.J. Vallauri, got the idea for
creating the site after starting another Web site called
Mustardstore.com (which he eventually sold). ``I kept getting
feedback from people who wanted to order a bottle of mustard that
cost a few dollars and were complaining that the shipping cost a
fortune,'' Vallauri said. ``They were right.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection at freeshipping.com _ 10 categories, including
apparel and office supplies _ is more quirky than comprehensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want people to think of this site as a first stop when
they shop to see if someone is willing to sell whatever you want to
buy without charging you for shipping,'' Vallauri said.
</P>
<P>
   After I did a search for ``hammock'' on the home page, the site
returned matches in three product categories. Although the search
results were displayed in a confusing way _ many matches, were
redundant, for instance _ I quickly found the model I wanted, at
Ezshop.com for $95.70.
</P>
<P>
   When I clicked on Buy Now, freeshipping.com sent me directly to
Ezshop.com's Web site. But after I arrived, I hesitated because
Ezshop.com said the item ``usually ships within 14 business days.''
That seemed like a long time. More important, I was shopping in an
unfamiliar store. The home page said Ezshop.com was located in
Dallas, and it listed a phone number _ unfortunately not toll-free
_ that I could call for customer service. When I phoned anyway, no
one answered.
</P>
<P>
   That made me uneasy. So I did some quick comparison shopping.
Using search engines, I found the same model at higher prices and
with shipping costs that ranged from $8.95 to $14.95 at several
other online shops. One, Smith &AMP; Hawken (www.smithandhawken.com),
was a store I know well. But there I would have to pay nearly 40
percent more; even on sale, the hammock would cost $133.95,
including shipping and handling. On the other hand, the Smith &AMP;
Hawken hammock would arrive much sooner: in 7 to 10 business days.
</P>
<P>
   Was it worth it to pay extra for security? In this sort of
situation, many experienced online shoppers will choose the brand
name they trust, said Chan, of DePaul University. ``Convenience,
the time spent and knowing that the item will arrive when it is
expected are more important than just getting a short-term benefit
like free shipping,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But brand names do not mean that much to me, not when the items
offered by two retailers are identical. The only perk that I can
think of that is more valuable than saving money would be something
along the lines of guaranteed baby-sitting on a Saturday night. Any
online retailer who offered that would earn my loyalty. Friday
night would be good, too.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of such luxuries, I sent e-mail to ask Ezshop why
shipping took so long and why the phone wasn't answered. Within two
hours, Ezshop responded: ``We seem to have had some trouble with
our phones earlier today. They are now working and we would be
happy to help you via phone. In regards to shipping, all items ship
directly from the manufacturer, and this particular manufacturer
needs this long to ship orders. Although they tend to ship much
faster, normally in five business days.''
</P>
<P>
   I ordered the hammock from Ezshop. I hope it arrives when it's
supposed to. Or else, I have been told, I may walk the plank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
