<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4758 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-PENN-GENE-THERAPY     05-24 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-PENN-GENE-THERAPY-750&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN SCALES BACK GENE THERAPY INSTITUTE IN AFTERMATH OF PATIENT'S
DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Mo.)   By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The scientist who ran a gene therapy study that
killed an 18-year-old patient at the University of Pennsylvania
will no longer conduct experiments on people, and the prestigious
gene therapy institute he founded is being scaled back, university
officials announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Dr. James M. Wilson, who as director of the
university's Institute for Human Gene Therapy has been regarded as
one of the bright young stars of his field, will restrict his work
to the study of molecules and cells, and will experiment only on
animals. Those restrictions will also apply to other scientists
working under the auspices of the institute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that Dr. Wilson was overloaded with regard to
responsibility,'' President Judith Rodin said at a news conference.
Rodin described the decision as one in a series of steps the
university was taking to improve patient safety in all experiments,
and also to reduce any appearance of conflict of interest in
scientific research.
</P>
<P>
   The move will have no immediate practical effect, because the
Food and Drug Administration has already suspended all human
experiments at the institute. Nor does it necessarily mean an end
to gene therapy clinical trials at the university. Doctors in other
disciplines may conduct such experiments, Rodin said, although they
will be reviewed by a special ethics panel from now on.
</P>
<P>
   But for Wilson, who over the past seven years had built his
institute into the nation's largest academic gene therapy program,
the decision is a major setback.
</P>
<P>
   He is facing the threat of a lawsuit by the family of the young
man who died, Jesse Gelsinger, and still must contend with an
investigation by the FDA, which uncovered a number of deficiencies
in his program in the wake of Gelsinger's death.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Rodin said, the university is re-examining its
relationship to the biotech company, Genovo, that Wilson founded.
The company contributes one-fifth of the $25 million annual budget
at the gene therapy institute, and in return has exclusive rights
to develop Wilson's discoveries into commercial products.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the gene therapy institute will stop manufacturing
the genetically altered viruses, known as vectors, that are used to
introduce genes into cells. That work will be turned over to
commercial laboratories, which have flourished in the years since
the institute was founded in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson did not grant interviews Wednesday, but instead issued a
terse statement saying that he felt confident that the steps
outlined would ``help position Penn as a model environment for the
conduct of all types of clinical research, especially gene
therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   But one leading scientist in the field, Dr. W. French Anderson,
who in 1990 conducted the first gene therapy experiment, described
Rodin's move as an overreaction. ``This is throwing the baby out
with the bathwater,'' Anderson said. ``It basically eliminates the
gene therapy program if you can't run trials.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodin's announcement came in conjunction with the release of a
report by an independent panel of experts that evaluated the gene
therapy institute at Rodin's request. The six-member panel, led by
William H. Danforth, chancellor emeritus of Washington University
in St. Louis, strongly suggested, but did not explicitly recommend,
that clinical trials at the institute be stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The experts raised serious questions about how well human gene
therapy studies were being monitored at the university. They
concluded, essentially, that either because of lack of knowledge or
financial resources the institute was not capable of complying with
the federal regulations governing clinical trials. Should clinical
trials continue under the institute's auspices, the report said,
``hundreds of standard operating procedures must be developed,
recorded and put into exact operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than beef up the institute, the university chose to
devote its resources to more intensive monitoring of all the
clinical trials it conducts. Danforth's committee also called for
the university to re-evaluate its hospital experimentation
committees, known as institutional review boards, that review
proposals for clinical trials. And it recommended that the
university review its policies on conflict of interest to avoiding
even the appearance of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Rodin said the university would follow the panel's
recommendations. But she said that Wilson had complied with
``fairly strict and unusual constraints'' regarding conflict of
interest.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Given the committee's findings, Inder Verma, a panel member who
is also the incoming president of the American Society for Gene
Therapy, said Rodin had two choices: She could either give the gene
therapy institute more staff members and outside supervision, or
restrict it to basic scientific research.
</P>
<P>
   To choose the latter path, Verma said, was ``a very reasonable
thing.'' Yet at the same time, Verma said, he and the other panel
members came away with the strong impression that before
Gelsinger's death, Wilson and his colleagues had been doing the
best they could to follow FDA rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's intention was good,'' Verma said. ``It's just that
the system required more monitoring and support.''
</P>
<P>
   Gelsinger's death in September was, as far as government
officials know, the first directly caused by gene therapy, and it
has had ripple effects throughout the 10-year-old field. In the
months since, there have been other reports of lapses in gene
therapy experiments.
</P>
<P>
   In response to those lapses, Donna Shalala, secretary of health
and human services, announced on Tuesday that the Clinton
administration was seeking authority to impose fines of up to $250
million on scientists who violated federal research rules in any
human experiment.
</P>
<P>
   And on Thursday, the Senate is to convene its second hearing to
examine accusations of lax government oversight of gene therapy
research.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Caplan, the director of the Center for Bioethics at the
Univeristy of Pennsylvania, said such scrutiny of gene therapy was
likely to continue for some time, particularly at the institute.
``Until his ship stops floundering,'' he said of Wilson, ``it is
going to be steered by somebody else for a while.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
