<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4762 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DARK-GAME-NYT &LR;      05-24 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DARK-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOANNA THE SPY: MORE BOND THAN BOND 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE HUTSKO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``This is Special Agent Perfect Dark,'' a female voice with a
British accent said in a telephone message left at my home last
week. ``I must be brief _ you never know who's listening. I need
your assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   The message caught me off guard _ for an instant, I actually
wondered how ``they'' knew that I was playing Perfect Dark at that
moment. Then I realized that it was just a public relations stunt
from Nintendo, so I immersed myself once more in the game's
alternate reality, which is every bit as exciting and nerve-racking
as a fast-paced action film.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Rare, a British company, Perfect Dark _ the name
refers to the code name used in the game for the 23-year-old
heroine, Joanna Dark _ draws its look and feel from the company's
1997 spy hit, Golden Eye, a game that featured James Bond but had
comparatively stiff animation. The company deserves kudos for
casting a female character in the lead role in an industry
dominated on both sides of the screen by young men.
</P>
<P>
   Striking a balance between sharpshooting and sleuthing, Joanna
is years ahead of Bond in her outing, set 23 years from now. The
first-person action of Perfect Dark _ which is not a Bond sequel
and has no characters from that game _ unfolds in a science
fiction-flavored landscape that features better graphics, sound
effects, weapons and gadgets than Bond's game.
</P>
<P>
   There are nine Solo Missions, each with levels of three to five
objectives, depending on the difficulty setting selected. The first
mission begins simply enough: Infiltrate the headquarters of the
secretive, sinister dataDyne company and rescue a doctor being held
hostage. In the first of many plot twists, the doctor turns out to
be a sentient robot that is imprisoning the soul of a scientist in
a roaming device that displays only the doctor's wide, staring
eyes, which are strangely, unsettlingly pretty, as if they had been
through a Cover Girl makeover.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Joanna must sneak past enemies or, more often
than not, shoot them. These bad guys are markedly smarter than
Golden Eye's villains. They hide in corners or duck behind boxes,
waiting for the vulnerable moment as you, playing Joanna, are
reloading so they can pop out and get you in their sights.
</P>
<P>
   How smart the enemies are _ and how many mission objectives
there are _ depends on the difficulty setting chosen at the start
of the mission. (A note to parents: the enemies' equally smart
mouths contribute to the game's Mature rating.)
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that the Agent setting is a walk in the park.
It's hard, not only because swarms of deadly enemies must be
eliminated, but also because shooting accurately at bad guys takes
enormous amounts of practice on the Nintendo 64 controller. As a
player more attuned to fast 3-D action games on PC's, I found that
adjusting to the Nintendo 64 controller was like trying to tie
shoelaces with fingers soaked in Novocain.
</P>
<P>
   Practice pays off. Before long it feels more natural to be
sneaking around as Joanna achieves increasingly complicated
objectives. She goes undercover to free hostages, travels
underground to infiltrate a lab and dives into the sea to recover
an alien who goes by the name of Elvis. Fans of conspiracy theories
get a visit to not only Area 51, but to Area 52, too.
</P>
<P>
   The environments depicted in Perfect Dark are gorgeous, as long
as the player has upgraded the Nintendo 64 with an optional memory
Expansion Pak, which costs $29.95 and also improves the graphics of
some other games, like Quake II and South Park Rally. Without it,
only a third of Perfect Dark can be played _ it has the multiplayer
levels but none of the single-player missions. With the Expansion
Pak installed, the game has vibrant effects.
</P>
<P>
   Light sources give off a squint-inducing glare and can be shot
out to darken a room, causing enemies to scramble. Windows shatter
with Dolby Surround Sound (if your television is equipped with it),
and, yes, blood splatters the walls and floors behind and beneath
enemies on the receiving end of your arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   An assortment of gadgets lets the player see in the dark or
decode computer-locked doors; other gadgets cloak Joanna from
sight. The most ingenious and captivating gadget is the Camspy, a
controllable spy camera that Johanna sets loose to see in places
she can't go.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect Dark is not without its frustrations. There is no Save
Game feature within levels, so dying during a mission means going
back to its beginning and starting over. (Only completed levels are
saved.) Because each game has up to five objectives, the inability
to save the game in the middle of a mission is at times
infuriating.
</P>
<P>
   One way to double Joanna's odds of completing the single-player
levels is to play in cooperative mode. That lets you invite a
friend to play at Joanna's side, helping you take out the enemies
and complete objectives. Or you can enlist the aid of one of the
game's ``simulants,'' which are designed to act like human players.
An interesting twist on the co-op mode is the counter-op mode, in
which the second player acts on behalf of one of the level's
enemies and tries to keep Joanna from getting out of the level
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Players who are frustrated from dying too often in the middle of
more complicated single-player levels can let off steam in the
game's biggest surprise of all, its multiplayer levels. In design
and execution, they evoke the feeling of two heavy-hitting PC
multiplayer games, Quake III and Unreal Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   As many as four human players seated around a single Nintendo 64
console can go head to head, each taking up a quarter of the TV
screen while following one character's actions. The game slows down
noticeably when several players are on the screen, all shooting at
once.
</P>
<P>
   Up to eight additional computer-generated players, or simulants,
can be sprinkled into the game. Or solo players can play against
one or several simulants. Simulants can be tweaked to be aggressive
or meek. Or the simulant can be insane, blowing up both itself and
you when you meet it head-on.
</P>
<P>
   With an abundance of multiplayer levels and the option of
returning to the Solo Missions and playing the game all over again
at one of the more difficult settings, Perfect Dark is one of those
rare games with lots of replay value. While faults like the
inability to save the game in the middle of levels prevent it from
being perfect, Perfect Dark comes close.
</P>
<P>
   Perfect Dark, from Nintendo for Nintendo 64; $69.95; for ages 17
and up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
