<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PELOSI, LOSING TRADE VOTE, VOWS VIGILANCE ON HUMAN RIGHTS IN
CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Rep. Nancy Pelosi, reflecting Wednesday on her
failed campaign to defeat normal trading status for China, vowed to
be ``relentless'' in holding supporters of the China trade bill to
their pledges to ensure Beijing stops suppressing human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, expected to be quickly approved by the Senate and
President Clinton, would put an end to the annual review that
Congress gave to China's trade status and would grant China the
same permanent low-tariff access to U.S. markets that most other
countries have.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the annual review means that Pelosi, Democrat from
San Francisco, would lose her yearly platform for exposing China's
human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The burden is now on the other side that won to ensure that
China stops threatening Taiwan, proliferating nuclear weapons and
suppressing the human rights on its people,'' Pelosi said in an
interview after the 237 to 197 vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be relentless in holding supporters (of the China
trade bill) to their pledges,'' she said. But, she added, ``our
experience is, the minute after the vote is cast, these side
commitments are forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, who argued that jettisoning the annual review would take
away the only leverage lawmakers have to curb China's suppression
of its people, was optimistic up to the final hours of the House
debate that the bill would fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to us is that the Republicans we thought we
could get, just weren't there,'' Pelosi said. ``We have no regrets,
everyone knows we worked as hard as we could.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi dismissed a successful amendment sponsored by Reps.
Sander Levin, D-Mich., and Doug Bereuter, R-Neb. that creates a
human rights monitoring commission for China. The planned
commission ``was camouflage to give people who support human rights
some cover to support the bill,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The human rights commission would consist of nine House members,
nine senators and five presidential appointees. It would focus on
China's human rights abuses, labor standards and religious freedoms
and submit an annual report to Congress and the president.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would also establish a task force to monitor the
U.S. ban on the importation of Chinese goods made by forced prison
labor.
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Pelosi gathered with other opponents of the bill
for chicken wings and sandwiches in the office of House Democratic
whip David E. Bonior, D-Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi embraced Wei Jingsheng, a leading Chinese dissident who
spent 19 years in prison in China for writing democratic slogans on
a wall. ``I'm sorry,'' she told him.
</P>
<P>
   Wei, who appeared downcast, replied through a translator that
the vote granting permanent normal trading status to China ``is not
only very dangerous for China, it is very dangerous for the United
States as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the vote, Pelosi delivered an impassioned speech on the
House floor, warning her colleagues not to squander U.S. leverage
over China in order to please the U.S. business community, which
had lobbied for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said there are more people in prison in China now than at
any other time and that China continues to expand its nuclear
weapons proliferation program by helping Libya.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must speak out for freedom because it is in our national
security interest to do so,'' Pelosi said. ``What credibility do we
have as a leader of the free world to speak out against human
rights abuses any where in the world if we will put deals ahead of
ideals in China?'' Pelosi asked. ``What does it profit a country if
it gains the world, but suffers the loss of its soul?''
</P>
<P>
   After the vote, Rep. Robert T. Matsui, D-Calif., who was
instrumental in gathering support for the bill, said its passage
``is a big major step in terms of engaging the Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   Matsui said the business community ``really worked in a way I
haven't seen in 22 years'' to get the bill approved.
</P>
<P>
   He said rejecting permanent trade relations for China would have
moved the United States ``more to isolationism.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi faced some formidable foes in this fight, including
leading elements of the business and agriculture sectors, the
Clinton administration _ including Vice President Al Gore _ and
Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   On Pelosi's side were organized labor and human rights and
environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before the vote on the House floor, Bonior pleaded for defeat of
the China trade bill, saying Chinese workers who make handbags for
3 cents an hour won't be able to expand American exports by buying
U.S.-made items such as cell phones and cars. China, Bonior added,
is a nation where ``injustice is law and brutality is order.''
</P>
<P>
   But House Majority Leader Richard K. Armey, R-Texas, argued that
granting permanent trading status to China would improve life for
the Chinese by exposing them to Western ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will see liberty elsewhere in the world and they will
demand it of their nation,'' Armey said. ``If we deny them the
chance, we will condemn them to a life of despair.''
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Rep. J. Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., who closed the
debate on the China bill, said the Chinese market is opening,
giving someone the opportunity to sell there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is, who will be there? Will it be the United
States or will it be Europe and Japan?'' Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the trade bill, Hastert predicted U.S.
exports to China would increase by $2 billion a year and said ``our
high tech firms would thrive in the Chinese markets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gradual Democratic reform is taking place in the hearts and
minds of the Chinese,'' Hastert said. ``More trade will expose the
Chinese to American ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address judy &LR; hearstdc.com
</P>
</TEXT>
