<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4766 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e BC-AUTHORS-KOZOL-SPI &LR;      05-24 1478
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHORS-KOZOL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR KOZOL ON A CRUSADE FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MARSHALL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Jonathan Kozol is known for his scathing critiques of
public education in America and its inequalities, his unstinting
advocacy for the poor and dispossessed, all put forth in
best-selling books that mix righteous anger and liberal polemic.
His tireless activism has made Kozol seem, after almost four
decades, as nagging as a debtor's conscience.
</P>
<P>
   But get the 63-year-old Kozol out onto the wide open spaces of
the asphalt playground at Cooper Elementary School in West Seattle
and the man seen often as a scold is instantly transformed. Never
mind the suit and tie, the wire-rimmed spectacles, the Harvard
University and Rhodes scholar pedigree. Here at Cooper, the real
Kozol emerges _ Kozol the kid.
</P>
<P>
   This smallish man with windblown gray hair is soon tossing a
blue ball back and forth with a young girl who had seemed shy as a
whisper only moments before. Or the former teacher is hunched over
at kid-level, his eyes registering intense interest, as he quizzes
children about their names, where they come from, what they like at
school. His little playground partners respond readily to his
childlike enthusiasm, the smiles that often light his face, the
natural ease of kidding around.
</P>
<P>
   Kozol is so energized by these encounters that it takes
considerable self-control for him not to demonstrate, with a bunch
of giggling young jump-ropers, his talent for double Dutch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be the only adult doing double Dutch,'' he
remarks to an adult bystander, ``and certainly not the only male.''
</P>
<P>
   There is such pure delight about Kozol when he is among
schoolchildren that all his past advocacy suddenly makes perfect
sense: The man loves kids and hates anything that threatens to
thwart their joys and dreams.
</P>
<P>
   The same message resounds through Kozol's powerful new book _
``Ordinary Resurrections: Children in the Years of Hope'' (Crown
Publishers, 375 pages, $25). This is a dramatic change of pace from
one of the country's leading social critics, a soft-spoken,
heart-tugging and highly personal inside look at a group of young
African American and Hispanic children in one of the poorest
neighborhoods in America, the Mott Haven section of New York City's
South Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are the polemics of such past Kozol books as ``Death at an
Early Age,'' (1967), ``Savage Inequalities'' (1991) and ``Amazing
Grace'' (1995). Instead, ``Ordinary Resurrections'' gives affecting
glimpses of Kozol trudging up flights of walk-up apartment stairs
in order to share his first Kool-Aid in 50 years with an 8-year-old
girl known as Pineapple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jonathan,'' the would-be grown-up instructs him several times,
``please make yourself at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Or there are glimpses, accumulated by Kozol in more than 200
visits to the neighborhood, of the heroic labors of devoted
teachers at Public School 30 or intrepid after-school workers at
the neighboring St. Ann's Episcopal church. These adults, despite
horrid odds, enwrap the children in a cocoon of love, hope,
discipline and commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all kinds of heroines and heroes in the ordinary
world,'' Kozol writes. ``The ones I like to spend my time with are
the preachers and the teachers who take on the hardest, messiest
and most exhausting work and still come out of it somehow with
souls intact and particles of merriment still percolating in their
personalities. I don't know how they do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Others might make the same observation about Kozol in the wake
of his hectic visit to Seattle, which lasted from Sunday through
Tuesday. This was not the usual sort of book-tour stop. Instead,
Kozol's visit became a kind of secular children's crusade, with the
author playing the various roles of preacher, cheerleader,
counselor, listener, advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Kozol, who is Jewish, delivered the sermon at the Sunday worship
service at the University United Methodist Temple before 400
people, then returned there that evening to a University Book
Store-sponsored talk about his new book before 900 people.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Kozol fired up an Alliance for Education luncheon
attended by 40 people, including Superintendent Joseph Olchefske
and many potential donors of private money to assist Seattle public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``You in Seattle still have the potential to live up to Dr.
King's dream in this city, which is very rare in this country,''
Kozol emphasized. ``You in Seattle have the makings of a real
democratic system of public education.''
</P>
<P>
   Kozol also met with teachers from public schools in the Queen
Anne vicinity and with students at McClure Middle School. He spent
an hour with Howard Schultz, chairman of Starbucks, whose
foundation's efforts on behalf of literacy were inspired by Kozol's
``Amazing Grace.'' And Kozol had dinner with Rudy Crew, the former
New York City schools chancellor who is now executive director of
the Institute for K-12 Leadership at the University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But the best part of the visit to Seattle, in Kozol's view, was
his time Tuesday with the students at Cooper elementary. There were
no books to sell or sign, no requests for quick answers to
difficult education questions. There was just more to learn at a
brand-new school, where he was often accompanied by principal Anne
Johnson who, although she was too shy to mention it to Kozol, had
been inspired to go into urban education by Kozol's ``Death at an
Early Age,'' as have been many teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Kozol was impressed by Cooper's building, a handsome and
spacious facility nearing the end of its first school year, and its
green surroundings of undeveloped parkland. He impulsively tested a
pencil sharpener at one point and smiled when he found it in fine
working order. But, more than physical resources, he delighted in
the school's 400 students of all colors speaking 15 different
languages, 85 percent of them from homes classified as
impoverished, yet getting along well together in classrooms,
cafeteria and playground.
</P>
<P>
   But Kozol soon discovered that the appearance of calm at Cooper
was deceiving. These children on society's low rung had been
thriving in their sudden good fortune at their new school, what
seemed a gleaming entrance into the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   But now 80 students at Cooper are likely to be transferred to
other schools as the result of the district's redrawing of
boundaries, which had the effect of adding the territory of a golf
course and industrial Harbor Island but losing children. Cooper
parents and staff are outraged, as is Kozol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people see the little children at this school as a
symbolic fight,'' the activist said. ``It would be awful to send
these kids back to other schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Kozol's anger was fueled, in part, by the contrast between
Cooper and the South Bronx elementaries that are the centerpiece of
``Ordinary Resurrections.'' It was not so much Cooper's spacious
new building as the school's ethnic mix. The South Bronx schools
have just 26 whites among 11,000 students, schools so segregated
that Kozol often likens them to the mandatorily segregated schools
of Mississippi in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   And this poor South Bronx neighborhood is also a societal
dumping ground, a place not only plagued by poverty, unemployment
(over 45 percent), heroin, AIDS and incarcerated fathers, but also
by such unwanted institutions as a medical-waste incinerator, a
sewage plant and a prison. Yet this neighborhood is also the home
to Pineapple, Elio, Tabitha and Otto, real children who participate
in everyday childhood dramas and escapades with resilient spirits.
</P>
<P>
   These children have provided comfort and delight to Kozol, a
longtime bachelor with no children of his own who has been
dispirited by the increasing decline of his parents, including a
father with Alzheimer's who no longer recognizes him. These
children had also provided a corrective, of sorts, to ``Death at an
Early Age,'' proving to Kozol that such children could at least
survive and prosper until middle school, and maybe beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``These children,'' he emphasizes, ``do not die as easily as
some of us believed, including me.''
</P>
<P>
   Kozol sits on a bench on the Cooper playground on a sun-drenched
afternoon, heartened by his time with schoolchildren, but also
pensive, reflecting on what four decades of advocacy and writing on
their behalf has wrought. He remains hopeful, yet circumspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to think,'' Kozol says, ``that these books have
made it harder for people to ever again categorize children because
of race and poverty, and harder for people to ignore the value of
their lives. Because as long as people feel free to categorize and
label children, then it is easy to segregate children, isolate
them. And everyone loses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
