<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4767 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-HISPANIC-PLAYWRIGHT-T     05-24 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-PLAYWRIGHT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYWRIGHT EXPLORES ELIAN-STYLE IDENTITY CRISIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Octavio Solis is known for giving back to his community _ fellow
writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have heard from a lot of people,'' says Katherine Owens,
co-artistic director of Undermain Theatre in Dallas. ``They talk
about Octavio's generosity with other writers. He doesn't make a
big stink about where he's at.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where he's at'' right now is the top of his profession _ and
the Dallas Theater Center's Big D Festival of the Unexpected, of
which this year's centerpiece is the world premiere of Solis'
``Dreamlandia.''
</P>
<P>
   Since his days as a student writing ``punk-flavored'' musings at
the 500 Cafe in Dallas' Exposition Park, the Texas-born Solis, 40,
has matured into a playwright of international stature. He has
written about 15 plays in almost as many years, many of which were
commissioned by well-known regional theaters such as San
Francisco's Thick Description and South Coast Repertory.
</P>
<P>
   His first major commission, ``Man of the Flesh,'' came in 1987
from Teatro Dallas. Last year, Dallas' Undermain Theatre performed
``Shiner,'' a co-commission for Solis and San Francisco playwright
Erik Ehn. Solis, recipient of a National Endowment for the Arts
Playwrighting Fellowship as well as other playwriting grants, is
working on a musical based on the Orpheus legend. Members of the
band Los Lobos are involved in the project for Los Angeles' Mark
Taper Forum. After leaving Dallas, Solis will spend a two-year
residency in Ashland, Ore., to work on a new play that he will also
direct.
</P>
<P>
   His time as a young writer in Dallas was important, Solis says,
because ``it cut my teeth in terms of realizing how much of a tool
language can be; that the language of the theater can be heightened
and poetic. I desperately wanted to get away from realism. I think
that's such a bore.''
</P>
<P>
   A bore is certainly one thing no one is likely to call
``Dreamlandia,'' which began to take shape after Solis worked with
Dallas Theater Center artistic director Richard Hamburger on Solis'
``Santos &AMP; Santos'' in 1995. After that successful production,
Hamburger wanted to work with Solis again and asked him if there
were any project he was thinking about. Solis cited ``Life Is a
Dream,'' by 17th-century Spanish playwright Pedro Calderon de la
Barca, as a seminal work in his development as a playwright and
expressed interest in working from that classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had three options,'' Solis says, ``but really I thought we
only had two: a strict translation or an adaptation more or less
true to the original. I started to do (the latter) but made a sharp
left turn on Page 1 and never looked back. I read ``Life'' once,
put it aside and started writing my play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Life Is a Dream'' is one of Calderon's most-produced works.
Like one of his contemporaries, William Shakespeare, Calderon drew
from existing stories, legends and history for his plays. ``Life''
comes from the Middle Ages story of Josephat, who is held prisoner
and isolated from the rest of the world. In ``Life,'' that man is
the ``sleeping prince,'' Segismundo. In ``Dreamlandia,'' it's
Lazaro, a young man raised on an island straddling the
Mexican-American border who struggles with his cultural identity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to sound sacrilegious, but I sort of thought,
`You know, I can improve on this play,' '' he says, laughing. ``I
feel as a writer you need to have that kind of arrogance to feel
like you can do anything, instead of holding the work as some
sacred thing. ...''
</P>
<P>
   The workshop version of ``Dreamlandia,'' called ``Suenos Suenos
Son,'' was performed at the 1997 Big D Festival. Solis says the
current version is virtually unrecognizable from its earlier
incarnation. He worked as DTC's playwright-in-residence last year,
during which he totally rewrote it, and he has since reworked it
many times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the kind of writer who thinks that everything I put
down (on paper) is finished, genius work,'' he says. ``I have to
rework and fine-tune until I get it right. I have no delusions
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not he has delusions of grandeur, he has established
a loyal and growing following of admirers.
</P>
<P>
   ``His use of language is extraordinary,'' Hamburger says. ``He
has a Shakespearean use of character.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all used to go hang out in Deep Ellum before it was
anything, and he would read his stories,'' says Owens, who was part
of the local theater scene with Solis before the playwright
ventured out of North Texas to establish a national reputation. ``I
thought he had such a remarkable amount of energy. His characters
were so vivid; he was speaking from a platform of myth that I don't
think other people have. I think he has a strong moral side, and
also a strong mythic side ... and those don't always go together.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Solis is a Latino writer, his work might be mistakenly
referred to as ``magic realism,'' a genre that incorporates
fantastic occurrences in an otherwise realistic setting often
associated with _ but not limited to _ Hispanic writers. Solis
admits to liking but not employing magic realism in his own
creations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's more irony, and a sense of humor and
brashness, that I find in my work,'' Solis says. ``In my plays, I
find that humor and irony have to be part of the tragic elements of
the play, the serious elements, the spiritual elements.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamburger agrees. ``I think the way ``Dreamlandia'' explores the
border between Texas and Mexico, between dream and reality, between
cultures, between different visions of the world, is quite
fascinating,'' he says. ``Some of the characters quite literally
don't know what is real and what is not real, which country they're
in, when they're dreaming or when they're awake, or whether they're
of Mexican or white heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Elian Gonzalez case, the play _ in which Lazaro
is torn between two worlds _ is more topical than even Solis could
have imagined when he was writing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tug of war going on between two entirely different
worlds, two nations, two world views,'' Solis says. ``And (Elian)
can barely figure out who he is. Everyone's trying to tell him,
`You're American,' no, `You're Cuban.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people have any idea of some of the things that
are going on (at the border),'' he says. ``It's an urgent world,
and a world that's going to transform the rest of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than cultural identity, Solis touches on additional issues
facing Mexico and America: NAFTA, the drug trade, ``maquiladoras''
and the killing of Mexican women, and the way Latinos are treated
in America. ``I hope to raise consciousness in people, because I'm
touching on a lot of issues,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Solis believes this will happen because of his and Hamburger's
understanding of each other. Hamburger ``knows how to bring forth
the vitality that is in the script. He just trusts it. We have a
good marriage.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
