 PERSONALS: Robin Williams and the Art of Raising Money 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
An hour of  &UR; Robin Williams &LR;  doing stand-up was the surprise treat
Sunday, May 20, at Comedy Night at the Geary, an ACT Scholarship
Fund moneymaker. Williams was a surprise to organizers, too, who
didn't know until a few days before that he'd be joining
 &UR; Johnny &LR;  &UR; Steele &LR; ,  &UR; Will Durst  &LR; and  &UR; Greg Behrendt &LR; . At $25 a
ticket, fans got a great bargain; Williams got the opportunity he
likes, to try out new material in an unadvertised gig.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also headlined at a fund-raiser saluting  &UR; Bill Clinton &LR; 
last night in Washington. He told the Washington Post about  &UR; George
W. Bush &LR; : ``Some men are born great. Some achieve greatness. And
some get it as a graduation gift.''
</P>
<P>
   And he discussed appearing at political fund-raisers. ``Four
years ago, when I had never done any of these things before, I felt
like  &UR; Ray Charles &LR;  at the Louvre. . . . Is the money soft or hard?
It is money coming from the folks, and they're getting something
for it _ the music and the comedy and God knows what.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; THE POLITICAL BIG MOUTH AND THE SOCIALITE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ed Rollins &LR;  _ who ran campaigns for  &UR; Ronald Reagan &LR; ,  &UR; Michael &LR; 
 &UR; Huffington &LR;  and  &UR; Ross Perot &LR; , but fell out with Republican Party
officials after he boasted about bribing members of the black
clergy when  &UR; Christine Todd Whitman &LR;  was running for New Jersey
governor _ has taken up with  &UR; Carolyne Roehm &LR; , who used to be a
fashion designer, has written books on flower arranging and was
most famously married to billionaire  &UR; Henry Kravis &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Each half of this couple, which has been a couple for more than
a year, brings a lot of history to the relationship. ``I haven't
seen him this happy since 1984, when he ran Ronald Reagan's
re-election campaign,'' former Reagan chief of staff  &UR; Ken &LR; 
 &UR; Duberstein &LR;  told W.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ronald Reagan and Nancy went to dinner with  &UR; Oscar de &LR; 
 &UR; la Renta &LR; , they left the staff at home,'' another friend of
Rollins' explained to the magazine. ``Now, he gets to go to all the
places he once only read about.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Roehm, she's proposed her own TV show about style. ``I
want to do something between  &UR; Audrey Hepburn &LR; 's `Garden World,'
 &UR; Jacqueline Kennedy &LR; 's `White House Tour,'  &UR; Kenneth Clark &LR; 's
`Civilization' and  &UR; Leonard Bernstein &LR; 's `The Joy of Music,' '' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   P.S. Although de la Renta was cited as a host to the Reagans, he
told Personals at the Academy of Art College fashion show Tuesday,
May 23, that he was hurrying right back to New York after the show
to throw a fund-raiser for  &UR; Hillary Clinton &LR; , a ``good friend'' who
wore his dress on the cover of Vogue and has been dressed by him
many times since. His partner in the fund-raiser is Vogue editor
 &UR; Anna Wintour &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE SHOW'S THE THING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ At the new Tate Museum in London,  &UR; Yuan Cai &LR;  and  &UR; JJ Xi &LR; , both
artists, walked into a room containing  &UR; Marcel Duchamp &LR; 's
``Fountain'' _ a urinal _ and urinated all over it. The Guardian
reported that they said their actions were a work of art that asked
viewers to re-evaluate the definition of art. A crowd of spectators
applauded, thinking the performance had been scheduled by the
museum.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; WHO SAID WHAT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ ``The street in Paris is depressing. We're not in Eastern &LR; 
 &UR; Europe here, so why do people wear nothing but trainers, duffel &LR; 
 &UR; coats, mangy skirts and old pants? It's like we're in the former &LR; 
 &UR; Soviet Union. I'd like to see a street that's inspired and &LR; 
 &UR; inspiring, with inventive and amusing clothes that are too short &LR; 
 &UR; or too long, too loud or too tight. I mean, this isn't suburbia, &LR; 
 &UR; so why does everybody look like they've fallen out of bed and &LR; 
 &UR; are wandering around in pajamas?'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Loulou de la Falaise &LR; , muse to  &UR; Yves Saint Laurent &LR; , in the
magazine V.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
