<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4769 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FOX-APPOINT-NYT     05-24 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOX-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX APPOINTS NEW PRESIDENT OF ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Fox network, confirming weeks of speculation, announced
Wednesday the appointment of Gail Berman as president of
entertainment for the network.
</P>
<P>
   Berman had been president of Regency Television, a production
studio affiliated with Fox's own 20th Century Television. Regency
this year created the television season's biggest new comedy hit,
``Malcolm in the Middle.''
</P>
<P>
   She replaces Doug Herzog, who held the position 16 months.
Berman will report to Sandy Grushow, who last November was named
chairman of the Fox television entertainment group, a unit of News
Corp. Grushow is the chief executive of both the Fox network and
its production studio.
</P>
<P>
   Berman said Wednesday she has had a strong working relationship
with Grushow for the last two years and that she expected Grushow
to ``move on to some larger issues in the company.'' As for her own
role, she said, ``I have the mandate to run the network,'' adding,
``I feel totally comfortable with the arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides ``Malcolm,'' Regency developed a number of other
successful shows during Berman's brief tenure there, including
``Roswell'' on WB, and two shows set for next season's network
schedules, ``Fearsum'' on Fox and ``Tucker'' on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   While she ran Regency Television, Berman, in an unusual
arrangement, continued to serve as executive producer for two other
series she helped create, ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and
``Angel,'' both of which have been successes for the WB network.
</P>
<P>
   She said that with this appointment she would end her
association with both those series.
</P>
<P>
   Berman started out as a producer for Broadway. Among the theater
she helped in producing were the original Broadway production of
``Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat'' in 1980, David
Rabe's ``Hurlyburly'' in 1984 and Athol Fugard's ``Blood Knot'' in
1985.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
