<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4774 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CAMBODIA-U.N.-1STLD-W     05-24 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-U.N.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED NATIONS AND CAMBODIA NEARER TO DEAL ON KHMER ROUGE TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 2nd and 3rd grafs to clarify)  
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ After months of often acrimonious exchanges
over who should ultimately control war crimes trials for the Khmer
Rouge, the United Nations has conceded to Cambodia the right to
appoint one of two prosecutors. The compromise appears to have
surmounted a major hurdle in eventually bringing former leaders of
the Khmer Rouge to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups immediately criticized the deal under which
either the Cambodian prosecutor or a co-prosecutor appointed by the
United Nations could proceed with a case if a five-judge panel does
not block it. The groups said the United Nations had compromised
its requirement that the trials be conducted by allowing the
prosecutors total independence.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to allowing co-prosecutors, the deal also provides
that the panel of judges will include three members from Cambodia
and two nominated by the United Nations. Initially, the United
Nations would have preferred to model this panel on the war crimes
tribunals used in the Balkans and Rwanda, which are outside the
control of national governments.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was arrived at in part last month through the
intercession of Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., who discussed the urgency
of establishing a tribunal with Cambodian leaders, and a long
series of negotiations between a U.N. team and Cambodia's prime
minister, Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
   The deal must be approved by the Cambodian legislature before
the tribunal can be involved in cases against former members of the
Khmer Rouge, an extreme leftist movement that decimated Cambodian
society in the 1970s. More than 1 million people were executed or
died from hard labor, dislocation, starvation and disease.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the deal signaled that Hun Sen, himself a former
lower-ranking Khmer Rouge official, had given up having total
control over the tribunal. The United Nations had opposed his
efforts because of the weakness and political vulnerability of the
Cambodian judiciary.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, U.S. and U.N. officials said, the two
prosecutors would be backed by the five judges. If the two
prosecutors cannot agree on an indictment, the five judges would
act as arbitrators. But for an indictment to be derailed, four of
the five judges would have to agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secretary-general considers the prime minister's response
a positive development,'' said Fred Eckhard, the spokesman for U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan. But the United Nations is refusing to
discuss the agreement, and plans to send its legal counsel, Hans
Corell, back to Cambodia to work out details. In the past, Hun Sen
has changed his position and undercut agreements.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Officials here and in Cambodia said that the Clinton
administration, with few foreign policy breakthroughs to its credit
as it enters its final months, strongly backed the deal, apparently
finalized this week in an exchange of letters between Hun Sen and
Annan.
</P>
<P>
   At the Lawyers Committee for Human Rights, Bruce Broomhall, the
international justice coordinator, said that this provision is a
welcome development, but overall he remains skeptical of the
agreement ``because in our assessment it is a
lowest-common-denominator solution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This rewards political intransigence by compromising on the
integrity of the tribunal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Roth, executive director of Human Rights Watch, said in
an interview that he sees many pitfalls in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're afraid that this is a precedent that will come back to
haunt the U.N. elsewhere,'' Roth said. ``The U.N. has been a very
firm custodian of fair trial standards, and prosecutions have been
conducted with scrupulous regard for due process.
</P>
<P>
   ``This arbitration panel sets a terrible precedent, because it
suggests that a U.N.-appointed international prosecutor can't be
trusted to make independent, clear decisions. This sends precisely
the wrong message.
</P>
<P>
   ``This compromise really only addresses the big issues of who
gets indicted and who gets acquitted or convicted,'' Roth, a former
prosecutor, said. ``In those big decisions, there is a sort of
check-and-balance system put into place. But there are dozens of
ways, apart from those big decisions, that the Cambodian government
can still sabotage the prosecutorial process. These are just not
addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other unresolved issues, Roth said, there seems to have
been no clear decisions on what to do about amnesty deals that Hun
Sen has made with several high Khmer Rouge officials who are now
living openly in Cambodia _ some of them with government jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
