<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4775 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CHINA-TRADE-0525-COX     05-24 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE PASSES CHINA TRADE BILL
 &HT;    With CHINA-REACT-0525.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A sharply divided U.S. House of Representatives
passed historic legislation on Wednesday ushering China into the
league of commercial powers enjoying permanent, first-rank access
to the vast U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   The 237-197 tally _19 more than needed to pass it _ advanced the
U.S.-China Trade Bill to the Senate, where it is expected to pass
with broad support in early June.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's vote marked the biggest legislative trade victory
for President Clinton since he pushed the North American Free Trade
Agreement, NAFTA, through a reluctant Congress in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of public stumping, Clinton was still lobbying
undecided lawmakers throughout the day for passage of a bill he
repeatedly called the most important foreign policy issue Congress
would face this year.
</P>
<P>
   He hailed the bill as an essential compliment to China's
impending admission to the World Trade Organization, or WTO,
expected as early as this fall, and said both developments, taken
together, would expand Chinese markets for U.S. exports ranging
from soybeans and pork to auto parts and computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be exporting, however, more than our products,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing China into the WTO and normalizing trade will
strengthen those who fight for the environment, for labor
standards, for human rights, for the rule of law,'' he said during
a televised address from the Rose Garden immediately after the
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage in China's development,'' he said, ``we will
have more positive influence with an outstretched hand than with a
clenched fist.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added that with 1.25 billion people, ``China is the
largest new market in the world.'' He said the outcome was
particularly welcome after the enactment earlier this month of a
bill to expand trade with Africa, Central America and the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would end the two-decade practice through which
Congress has made China's ability to export to this country
conditional upon an annual review of Beijing's conduct in areas
ranging from human rights and worker liberties to environmental
practices and religious freedom.
</P>
<P>
   While China's record in each of those areas remains poor by U.S.
standards, supporters of permanent normal trade relations, or PNTR,
for China said the yearly review had become a largely symbolic
exercise with little apparent impact on Beijing's behavior.
</P>
<P>
   At best, these proponents contend, the annual threat to rescind
favorable trading terms with China had become a source of added
friction in the already complicated relationship between the United
States and the most populous country on earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The annual review has not been an effective mechanism,'' said
Rep. Sander Levin, D-Mich. ``It was not used after Tiananmen,'' he
said, referring to Beijing's bloody crackdown on student-led
demonstrations in 1989, ``and there's no strategy for its effective
use in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argued that in granting PNTR status to China the
United States was ceding a powerful tool for influencing Beijing's
harshly repressive Communist regime.
</P>
<P>
   The most passionately debated trade issue to come before the
Congress in seven years, the bill was cast by its foes as a litmus
test of American values and ideals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This vote defines what kind of a nation we want to be,'' said
Rep. Eliot Engel, D-N.Y., who opposed the bill ``Are we only for
the almighty dollar or for morality and doing what's right? The
almighty dollar, or human rights?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked fellow opponent Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., who voted
against the bill: ``What credibility do we have, as the leader of
the free world, to speak about human rights abuses anywhere in the
world if we put deals above ideals?''
</P>
<P>
   And, like the annual discussion the bill is aimed at ending,
Wednesday's debate was marked by sharp criticism of China.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a police state ... a nation where injustice is law and
brutality is order,'' said House minority whip David Bonior,
D-Mich., a leading opponent of PNTR. ``Americans value trade, but
we're not willing to trade in our values.''
</P>
<P>
   What won the day, though, was the multi-premised argument that
PNTR would manifestly benefit U.S. exporters, even as increased
ties with U.S. companies helped to promote change in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I profoundly believe that it will advance the cause of human
rights for the Chinese people ... It may be the only way,'' said
House Majority Leader Richard K. Armey, R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Holding what he said was a palm-held personal computer, Armey
said China's Communist rulers would not be able to turn back the
tidal wave that advances in information technology have unleashed
across China.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is said that the pen is mightier than the sword,'' Armey
said, ``and I would argue that the PC is mightier than the shackles
of tyranny.''
</P>
<P>
   In a day of soaring emotions and equally pitched rhetoric, the
vote turned traditional House allegiances upside down, splitting
Republicans and Democrats alike, making adversaries of allies and
turning partisan foes into unlikely comrades.
</P>
<P>
   After Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., delivered a forceful appeal
for passage, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., who led the
Republican effort to approve the bill, remarked on the strange
bedfellows the issue had created.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie, we've been talking a lot lately,'' Hastert said.
``They'll be talking about us.''
</P>
<P>
   Managing the floor debate for Republican opponents, meanwhile,
was Georgia Republican Charlie Norwood, who found himself lined up
alongside the likes of Bonoir and House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt, D-Mo.
</P>
<P>
   In a barnburner that elicited a sustained ovation, Norwood said
the debate boiled down to ``jobs, bombs and bibles,'' saying the
issue touched on critical elements of this country's economic and
security future as well as the religious persecution that continues
in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``My district has lost manufacturing jobs to cheap Chinese labor
every year that I've been in Congress ... this is not just cheap
labor my friend, it's also slave labor,'' said Norwood. Meanwhile,
he said, ``persecution of anyone in China who believes in a higher
authority has gotten much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   For Rep. Pete Stark, D-Calif., opposition to PNTR for China came
down to bread and butter issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to hurt probably a couple of hundred thousand
Americans real bad. It's going to hurt those people who are going
to lose their jobs overnight,'' Stark said during Wednesday's floor
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the PNTR bill as a boon for big corporations, Stark
cast the vote as a choice between helping ``families who may be
looking for hamburger helper on the dinner table ... or for the
people who may be making millions of dollars in stock options.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States purchased some $81 billion worth of goods from
China last year, nearly $70 billion more worth of products than
U.S. companies shipped to China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has made the strengthening of U.S.-China relations a
cornerstone of his foreign policy agenda. The goal has pitted him
against elements within his own party _ particularly labor unions
that fought tooth, nail and hair for the bill's defeat _ China's
own behavior, and even the breath-taking series of errors that led
to the U.S. bombing of the Chinese Embassy last spring in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   As with NAFTA, it was Republicans who Clinton needed to carry
Wednesday's vote. This time around, Clinton found himself aligned
with the very Republican House members _ Armey, Hastert and Rep.
Thomas DeLay of Texas among them _ who led the charge less than two
years ago to impeach him on charges stemming from his relationship
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.chinapntr.gov (the view from the White House)
</P>
<P>
   www.aflcio.org (why organized labor opposes PNTR)
</P>
<P>
   www.hrw.org (human rights in China)
</P>
<P>
   www.uschina.org (the view from U.S. business interests)
</P>
<P>
   The bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
