A4777 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ROBERDS0525-COX     05-24 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERDS0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roberds ready to liquidate
 &HT;    By Tim Tresslar
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST CARROLLTON, Ohio _ The liquidation sale for failed home
furnishings retailer Roberds Inc. is expected to begin Friday at
some stores in Dayton and Atlanta and on Saturday at all the
company's remaining stores in those markets, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Brothers Retail Partners will open certain stores Friday
at noon as workers finish preparing them for the liquidation sale,
said Walter Craig, senior lead consultant for the Boston-based
liquidator. Craig was unsure which stores will open Friday. All
locations in Ohio, Indiana and Georgia will open Saturday for the
liquidation sale.
</P>
<P>
   On May 2, Roberds shuttered stores in Ohio, Indiana and Georgia
and announced it was going out of business. In January, the company
had filed for bankruptcy protection from creditors and planned to
emerge from Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization within 90 days.
However, the cash-strapped retailer's inability to secure new
inventory forced it to close.
</P>
<P>
   On May 16, U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge Thomas F. Waldron named
Gordon Brothers liquidator for six stores plus the Fairborn
warehouse in the Dayton area. The company also is conducting the
liquidation of 10 stores and a regional warehouse in the Atlanta
area.
</P>
<P>
   Roberds Vice President and Chief Financial Officer John Grigsby
said the liquidators will accept cash, checks and credit cards for
purchases. They will not accept Roberds' private-label credit card,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is to be completed by Sept. 15, or earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Brothers purchased $27 million in inventory from Roberds
and also plans to stock stores with non-Roberds merchandise, a
practice called ``augmenting.'' The Ohio Attorney General's office
had protested plans to add more inventory because it violates the
state's consumer protection laws. Waldron granted Roberds' request
to do so, saying the additional inventory will mean more money for
Roberds to reimburse customers who made down payments but did not
receive promised merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said the company will bring in merchandise of ``quality as
good or better'' than what Roberds offered before it closed. Plans
call for Gordon Brothers to buy at merchandise for the
going-out-of-business sale from Roberds' vendors, Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   The liquidator will honor deposits, merchandise credits and gift
certificates transacted since Roberds' January bankruptcy filing,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Customers needing information regarding unfilled orders can call
1-800-686-6814, extension 2510.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
