<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs on
Thursday, May 25, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Michael McGarr at the Daily News, (818) 713-3470.
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-CRASH (Los Angeles) _ The last words spoken by the crew
of Alaska Airlines Flight 261 indicated they had regained control
of the plane and were headed to LAX. But the pilot of a private
craft would soon relay the drama behind the silence: ``That plane
has just started to do a big, huge plunge,'' he said as it went
into the Pacific Ocean off Port Hueneme in January. By Dominic
Berbeo. (Will move in the ``a'' national news and ``n'' California
news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LATINOS-ACTING (Los Angeles) _ Hispanics are America's
fastest-growing minority and will spend more than $10 billion a
year on entertainment, yet the actors who represent them on TV and
in movies still struggle against stereotypes in the roles they play
and the roles they don't. A new study commissioned by the Screen
Actors Guild, ``Still Missing: Latinos In and Out of Hollywood,''
also showed that entertainment executives tend to revert to racial
biases as the periodic outcries against those tendencies die down.
By Valerie Kuklenski. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``n''
California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   BEACH-REPORT (Los Angeles) _ Heal the Bay will issue its 10th
annual report card today on Southern California beaches in Los
Angeles, Ventura, Orange and Santa Barbara counties. The
environmental group also will release a list of the Top Ten Bummers
-- the worst beaches in terms of water quality. By Erik Nelson.
(Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
