 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been double-filed _ into the ``f''
financial news and ``a'' domestic/general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By JIM JUBAK  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Buy at AEA and sell by H&AMP;Q, goes the Wall Street saying.
</P>
<P>
   AEA, of course, is the American Electronics Association's
investment conference held in early November each year, and H&AMP;Q is
the annual Chase Hambrecht &AMP; Quist technology conference, held in
May.
</P>
<P>
   The concept behind the saying is that technology stocks trade at
bargain prices both after the summer slump and before any rally
created by reports of strong third or fourth quarter sales.
</P>
<P>
   By selling into the enthusiasm generated by the technology
company presentations at H&AMP;Q, investors have been able to lock in
profits and avoid the slump that corresponds to the slow sales
reported for the June quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The theory has worked pretty well over the years. In 1999, for
example, Compaq fell 10 percent from May 11 to July 1. Dell dropped
14 percent during the same period. In 1998, Dell declined 13
percent in an even shorter span from May 11 to June 1. That year,
Compaq tumbled 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Old market truisms, however, haven't been fairing too well of
late. ``Don't fight the Fed'' is one example.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Federal Reserve started to raise interest rates on
June 30, 1999, an investor would have done just fine buying the
high price-to-earnings stocks that interest rate hikes are supposed
to slaughter. From July 1, 1999, to March 17, the Nasdaq Composite
Index was up almost 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three hikes and a tumble''? That one hasn't panned out,
either. Since the central bank's Nov. 16 decision to increase the
federal funds rate to 5.5 percent _ it had been 4.75 percent before
the June meeting _ the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 climbed 3 percent. The
Index is up 4 percent since the Feb. 2 move to 5.75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   No great gains, but certainly no correction, either. Odds are
that 2000 won't treat ``buy at AEA, sell at H&AMP;Q'' with a whole lot
more respect.
</P>
<P>
   A shift in the fundamentals of the market has taken some of the
predictive power out of the traditional admonitions against the
Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are far less dependent on banks and bank loans for
financing, and consumers now have access to much more credit from
many more sources. Those sources themselves are raising money in
ways that often bypass banks.
</P>
<P>
   In the same way, fundamental changes in the technology sector
suggest that investors might want to revisit some of the
assumptions that lie behind the ``buy at AEA, sell at H&AMP;Q'' rule.
</P>
<P>
   The expression itself dates from the days when the
personal-computer industry was the technology sector. It's an
accurate reflection of the lumpy, seasonal patterns in
personal-computer sales, which peak in the last quarter of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   From October to December, computer sales often account for as
much as 40 to 50 percent of a company's annual total. Of course,
that also means a January slump in orders, as manufacturers and
sales outlets work off inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at suppliers start to pick up in the quarter that ends in
September, as everybody begins to ramp up for the rest of the year.
Over time, this pattern has been as predictable as the hands on a
clock.
</P>
<P>
   But PC companies aren't the technology sector anymore. Dell,
Intel, and Microsoft now share leadership with companies such as
Cisco Systems, Oracle, and Nokia, none of which sell significant
amounts of their products to the personal-computer market.
</P>
<P>
   And the growth in the technology sector isn't coming from PC
companies; it's coming from areas such as wireless communications,
broadband Internet to the home, and optical networking.
</P>
<P>
   Even classic PC companies such as Intel recognize the shift.
Recently, its acquisitions have been of companies active in
communications, not in computer technologies.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it's not even clear that it's accurate to talk about a
``technology sector'' at all anymore. By some counts, technology
companies compose as high as 40 percent of the Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 Index.
</P>
<P>
   Technology mutual funds now routinely divide their technology
holdings into 10 or more sectors, such as telecommunications
equipment, semiconductor equipment, and computer services and
software, that are each as large _ in the number of companies they
encompass, anyway _ as the old PC sector.
</P>
<P>
   And technology is everywhere in this economy. General Motors is
a holding company with interests in automobiles, satellite
communications, and business-to-business Internet commerce. The
traditional auto company is now just one piece of a much larger
pie.
</P>
<P>
   General Electric, the epitome of an old economy company, is
again looking to reinvent itself by employing the Internet to cut
costs and grab markets.
</P>
<P>
   None of this means there won't be a ``technology slump'' this
summer. The old rule still has its converts, and to a degree, it
now represents a self-fulfilling prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks fall in the summer because everyone sells in
anticipation of a sell-off, which they themselves are creating. And
it is also never wise to downplay the importance of the mass
migration of brokers and analysts to the beaches of the east and
west coasts. Fewer analyst reports mean less cheerleading for
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But wise investors will take notice of the way the trend has
been changing. The slump is shorter and less predictable, it seems.
And it has less and less to do with the fundamentals of the many
technology companies that don't follow the seasonal patterns of the
PC industry.
</P>
<P>
   The summer slump may now be an opportunity to exploit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Jim Jubak is senior markets
editor at Microsoft's MoneyCentral: www.Moneycentral.msn.com. His
column, ``Jubak's Journal,'' appears there every Tuesday and
Friday.) &LR;  &QL;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
