<HEADER>
A4785 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DEPOT-BIAS0525-COX     05-24 0244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEPOT-BIAS0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot store accused in bias suit
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Home Depot is being charged with racial profiling by
an African-American customer in California who said he was falsely
arrested for trying to get a $12.80 refund.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Pina is seeking $7 million in damages in a lawsuit filed
in Los Angeles Superior Court for an incident the suit claims
occurred last year at a Home Depot in Signal Hill near Long Beach.
Pina claims he tried to return two items he had purchased the
previous day at a Home Depot in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   According to the lawsuit, Pina was arrested in the store by
local police after Home Depot's security officer accused Pina of
using a fake receipt.
</P>
<P>
   The charges were dropped days later after Pina proved he had an
original receipt that matched Home Depot's transaction records, the
lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Pina's attorney, Scott Broffman, said his client was a victim of
racial profiling at the Signal Hill store, which is in a mostly
white neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot denied the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on the outside legal experts' review of the case, there
is nothing to indicate that Home Depot's policy of
non-discrimination and its value toward treating everyone equally
was violated,'' the company said.
</P>
<P>
   The case is scheduled to go to trial on June 5, Broffman said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
