<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4796 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-SHANGHAI-FEATURE-LADN     05-24 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHANGHAI-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COWBOY WAY
</HEADLINE>
  Chan, Wilson ride out early 
mutual dislike in buddy film 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When director Tom Dey (pronounced ``Dye'') showed up on the set
of ``Shanghai Noon,'' he was understandably a little nervous. Not
so much because he was a commercial director making his first
feature film. It had more to do with a phone call he had received
from one of his stars, Owen Wilson, not long before shooting was to
commence.
</P>
<P>
   It seems Wilson and his co-star, Hong Kong action hero Jackie
Chan, weren't exactly seeing eye-to-eye on things. They weren't
even on speaking terms. So as he prepared for his first day of
location shooting in Calgary, Dey pondered how he would go about
making a buddy movie featuring two actors who weren't exactly
buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember feeling pretty worried before we started,'' Dye
says. ``We knew this movie would rise and fall based on the
chemistry between Jackie and Owen.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the reaction from studio executives at Disney, the
movie's distributor, everyone involved must have risen to the
occasion. ``Shanghai Noon'' is opening on Memorial Day weekend, one
of the peak movie-going periods of the year, and it's positioned
against ``M:I-2,'' considered to be the most potent box-office film
of the summer. Disney moved the film up from its original August
release date based on reactions from test audiences, who raved
about the interplay between Chan and Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We caught lightning in a bottle,'' Dey says, breathing a
little easier these days.
</P>
<P>
   Chan came up with the idea of ``Shanghai Noon'' while making
another buddy movie, ``Rush Hour.'' Basically, Chan wanted to make
an ``East Meets Western'' kind of movie, playing his chopsocky
sensibilities off the idea of the traditional gunslinger. Once Dey
was hired, the challenge was to find an actor who could play off
Chan's fish-out-of-water innocence much the same way Chris Tucker
did in ``Rush Hour.''
</P>
<P>
   After a number of auditions and turn-downs (Vince Vaughan was
once a leading candidate for the role), Dey gave the part to Owen
Wilson, who was hired as much for his writing ability as he was for
his acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there were too many lines that I said in the
movie that were in the original script,'' says Wilson, who co-wrote
the critically acclaimed independent films ``Bottle Rocket'' and
``Rushmore'' with writing partner Wes Anderson. ``My idea was to
create an outlaw who was pretty much just in it for the girls. He
didn't actually care all that much for the actual outlaw part of
the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's reluctant gunfighter teams up with Chan's character, a
Chinese Imperial Guard who comes to the Old West to rescue a
princess who has been kidnapped from the Forbidden City. It's a
buddy movie in the tradition of ``48 Hours'' (Wilson's favorite)
and ``Midnight Run'' (Chan's choice), featuring two characters who
learn from each other once they move beyond their initial hostility
and mistrust.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, life imitated art as the relationship between
the two leads strangely evolved much as it did in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Owen and Jackie are very different people,'' Dey says. ``Owen
is from Texas and he's got this drawl to his voice. He's kind of
lazy, kind of laconic. Jackie is everything that Owen is not. He's
extremely disciplined and hard-working and really embodies the
traditional values of the East.''
</P>
<P>
   The two actors share one trait _ shyness. And that wariness was
largely responsible for the initial rockiness between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first encounter was a bad experience because I don't talk
to strangers easily,'' Chan says. He then compares that first
meeting to what he believes is the secret of a good buddy movie,
saying, ``You start with not knowing someone, having conflicts with
him. Then you get to know him better, you work together, and you
become buddies as actors. It's a principle in life to get to know
people better.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson agrees, which is ironic given that he tried to employ
that principle when he first met Chan, only to be rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were supposed to meet for dinner and get to know each other
since the movie kind of depends on the buddy factor,'' Wilson says.
``And when he came in, he had some people with him, which was a
little awkward. So I just kind of talked to his manager and Jackie
just kind of smiled and nodded, and finally I just got up and said,
`Well, I guess I'll see you in Calgary.' And he was like, 'Oh, OK.
See you.' He didn't say, 'Oh, you've got to stay longer.' So then I
was thinking that maybe he just didn't like me. I had no idea what
to think about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Chan and Wilson were still circling each other (and Dey for that
matter) on the first day of filming. Dey decided to put their
underlying antagonism to work, choosing to shoot a jailbreak scene
that featured plenty of hostility _ both in the script and
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the one scene in the movie that I didn't want to
(shoot) and that's what we began with,'' Wilson says of the
sequence he believed was too unrealistic. ``So that made it extra
kind of awkward. But it ended up working, me screaming at Jackie,
and we made each other laugh, too. And I quickly realized that we
were pretty simpatico sense-of-humor-wise.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a real innocence that I like,'' Wilson continues. ``And
once you get to know him, you see a kind and decent person, the
same person that comes across on the screen. You can't really fake
stuff like that. It's not like you see this guy on camera and then
the camera shuts off and he's saying, 'Where's the hookers? Where's
the tequila?'''
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol did actually play a significant part in the making of
``Shanghai Noon.'' Chan threw a party for the crew one night and,
as the evening wore on, he and his stunt men began playing several
variations of a Chinese drinking game. Wilson, ever the observer,
watched (and ended up participating, naturally), and approached Dey
with the idea of including it in the movie. Filmed as each actor
sits in a separate bathtub, it ended up being one of the film's
funniest scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we shot that, it really was the complete turning point in
both the relationship between the characters and the relationship
between Owen and Jackie,'' Dey remembers. ``And it was pretty much
improvised on the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Wilson: ``They talk so much about De Niro gaining weight
for 'Raging Bull.' But what about me getting totally hammered so we
could pull off that Chinese drinking-game scene?''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson might get his due when it comes time to negotiate his
contract for a possible sequel. Disney has already commissioned
``Shanghai Noon'' screenwriters Alfred Gough and Miles Millar to
begin work on a follow-up, which Millar says will be an
action-adventure movie in the vein of ``Raiders of the Lost Ark.''
Whether the script will ever see the light of day will depend on
how well audiences respond to the original.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't help but feeling like the little engine that could,''
Dey says. ``Anything that happens now is gravy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
