<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4798 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-SHANGHAI-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      05-24 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHANGHAI-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HIGH-FLYIN' JACK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Shanghai Noon'' does little more than deliver on its promise _
Jackie Chan in the Old West _ in crisp, efficient and nicely
packaged style. It's not exactly a landmark achievement, but when
you consider how readily such surefire entertainment material
misses the mark in today's Hollywood (``Wild Wild West'' anyone?
Didn't think so), it sure is appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   The feature debut of commercials director Tom Dey (who once
wrote a magazine profile of the great Mexican cinematographer
Gabriel Figueroa, and it shows), ``Shanghai'' strikes a good
balance between humor and action, stages Chan's ridiculously
inspired fight stunts so you can enjoy them rather than get a
headache from overediting, and gives us just about every Western
gag we could want. Chan, as wayward Chinese Imperial Guard Chon
Wang, fights Indians (and inadvertantly ends up married to one),
falls off trains, tears up saloons, has horse problems, et cetera.
He makes every time-honored situation seem, if not exactly fresh,
at least re-imagined with the painstaking care of a master physical
comedian.
</P>
<P>
   And for verbal fun, there's Owen Wilson's Roy O'Bannon. Chon
Wang's sometimes reluctant, probably untrustworthy sidekick,
O'Bannon is an intelligent if not real adept aspiring outlaw who
takes it upon himself to become his Asian pal's guide to all things
Western. What makes this stock character consistently amusing is
the way that Wilson plays him with the sensibility of who he
actually is: a 21st Century Texas slacker, wise to the implications
of everything and so ironically detached he even views his
strongest desires as something of a joke.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson reportedly wrote most of his own dialogue, and much of it
bears the loopy, zen smartypants sting of the scripts he's written
with filmmaking partner Wes Anderson for ``Bottle Rocket'' and
``Rushmore.'' Hitching that fairly sophisticated humor up with
Chan's inventive kung foolery was an unlikely but felicitous
gambit. And, of course, it's not as obvious as Chan's ``Rush Hour''
pairing with Chris Tucker, whose grating style can be described as
verbal drop-kick comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The story here involves the luckless but formidable Chon Wang
and several other Imperial Guards delivering a ransom to 1870s
Nevada, where kidnapped Princess Pei Pei (Lucy Liu, dispensing with
the imperious attitude for a winning change) is being held by a
renegade traitor (Roger Yuan). Of course, Chon Wang gets separated
from his comrades, leading to multiple opportunities for trouble
and to fool around with the slapstick potential of tomahawks,
horseshoes, moose antlers and the like. Chan reportedly employed a
contemporary, 19th Century fighting for, um, that extra bit of
authenticity. It still looks like Buster Keaton, real angry, to me,
but it doesn't detract from the impression that Chan, as always,
took his work very seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing else about the movie is very serious, though, and
Western purists could conceivably be offended. On the other side of
that argument, Alfred Gough and Miles Millar's amiably ambling but
fully packed script saves room for some pointed yet anything but
sanctimonious, satirical jabs at the genre's inherent racism, which
is an always welcome development and especially apt here.
</P>
<P>
   You don't want to oversell ``Shanghai Noon'' _ it is,
fundamentally, just the old ``Kung Fu'' TV series with laughs and
better stunts. But if that at all sounds like a fun idea to you,
chances are you'll enjoy this one more than you will most of the
summer's overreaching entertainments.
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
The film: ``Shanghai Noon'' (PG-13; violence) &QL; 
The stars: Jackie Chan, Owen Wilson, Lucy Liu, Xander Berkeley,
Roger Yuan, Brandon Merrill &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Tom Dey. Written by Alfred Gough and
Miles Millar. Produced by Roger Birnbaum, Gary Barber and Jonathan
Glickman. Released by Touchstone Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: 1 hour, 50 minutes
</P>
</TEXT>
