<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4802 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-DIRTY-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      05-24 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DIRTY-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORN YESTERDAY
</HEADLINE>
  Woods can't save Showtime's version of the Mapplethorpe trial 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Sat., May 27.) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Woods is an actor who really needs a crackling script to
sell his wiry nervous energy. Give him dialogue with the brittle
snap of a dried twig and he's flat-out brilliant, as he was in
``Salvador,'' ``Nixon'' and ``True Crime.'' Hand him an
indifferently render screenplay, and he tries so hard to save or
elevate it he can become downright annoying (see _ or better yet,
don't _ ``The Boost'' or ``Another Day in Paradise'').
</P>
<P>
   In ``Dirty Pictures,'' you'll likely keep waiting for Woods to
break loose even once the credits have rolled. There's even a scene
in which his character's wife, played by Diana Scarwid, tries to
coax him into breaking from his constraints and strutting his
stuff. He underplays his one big speech, which comes pretty late
into the proceedings anyway, and even though it's apparent his
character is the smartest guy in the whole film, he's vexingly
timid in a way you just know the real Woods isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dirty Pictures'' is one of those preaching-to-the-converted
films about the sacredness of the First Amendment, focusing on the
1990 obscenity trial in Cincinnati _ the town that had a veritable
aneurysm over Larry Flynt's handiwork _ when a local art museum had
the audacity to show an exhibit of the works of the late
photographer Robert Mapplethorpe.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Mapplethorpe's work was benign enough _ some nicely lit
and composed shots of flowers and celebrities and very pretty
people. But then there were those handful of shots of homoerotic
sadomasochism that were extreme enough to put most decent folks off
their feed for a minute or two; and that's what got Contemporary
Arts Center director Dennis Barrie (Woods) hauled into court.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, ``Dirty Pictures'' is downright incoherent, a
Cuisinart of jabbering bit players _ pompous attorneys and
dramatically lit jurors alike _ mixed with real-life interview
subjects (Salman Rushdie, William F. Buckley Jr., Susan Sarandon,
Fran Liebowitz) waxing pretentious and the headline stars (Woods,
Scarwid and Craig T. Nelson as the politically motivated sheriff)
attempting to assert their characters in a jumble of narrative. The
story eventually comes into focus, but by then, it's already become
a rote, by-the-numbers ``issue'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   So we watch the requisite twisting in the wind demanded of
Barrie as politicians and lawyers get a hold of the trial. There's
never any question who's right _ the prosecutor is a puffy,
wheezing, squinty-eyed white guy; the judge dismisses defense
attorneys with fey, self-satisfied hand gestures. The film stacks
the deck further by showing Mapplethorpe's work _ but mainly his
more palatable photographs; the controversial stuff is seen in
split-second shots or simply described by sundry characters.
</P>
<P>
   Only at the very end does ``Dirty Pictures'' get provocative,
when its feel-good ending is undone by a monologue delivered by one
of the straight-laced, Moral Majority characters, who claims
victory because Barrie's marriage fell apart and the simple fact of
the trial made museum curators around the country a tad more timid.
The film has a small, salient point to make, and Liebowitz delivers
it early on when she observes of the concept of community
standards, ``There are no communities anymore _ there are only
special-interest groups.'' &QL; 
----- &QL; 
The show: ``Dirty Pictures.'' &QL; 
What: Docudrama examining Cincinnati's Robert Mapplethorpe/First
Amendment trial. &QL; 
The stars: James Wood, Craig T. Nelson, Diana Scarwid. &QL; 
Where: Showtime &QL; 
When: 9 tonight; also May 31, June 6 and 18. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
