<P>
   CHINA-TRADE-ASSESS (Washington) _ With his narrow victory on
trade with China, President Clinton has finally defined his imprint
on U.S. foreign policy: As the president who conducted the
post-Cold War experiment of using American economic power to foster
political change among America's neighbors and its potential
adversaries. It is a path he set out on in 1993, when 10 months
into his presidency he defied his own party and pushed through the
North American Free Trade agreement with Mexico and Canada. A news
analysis by David E. Sanger. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in
``i'' news file.)
