   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   ARSENIC-WATER (Washington) _ The Clinton administration has
proposed strict new regulations of arsenic in tap water, reducing
by 90 percent the public's maximum exposure to the chemical, which
causes cancer and is found at harmful levels in at least 1 out of
10 of the nation's community water supplies. About 30 million
people live in areas served by water systems that do not meet the
new standard, officials say. Los Angeles water has slightly more
arsenic than would be allowed, and other communities have much
higher concentrations. Norman, Okla., for example, has about seven
times the concentration of arsenic allowed under the proposed
standard. By John H. Cushman Jr. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``w'' news file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The federal judge trying the
Microsoft antitrust case raised serious questions about the
government's plan to break up the company, seeming to suggest that
he did not think the plan went far enough. The judge, Thomas
Penfield Jackson, praised a brief submitted by a group of computer
industry executives that calls for breaking the company into three
parts instead of two, as the government has proposed. And with an
uncharacteristically determined manner, the judge bluntly rejected
Microsoft's request for months of additional hearings on the remedy
for its antitrust violations. By Joel Brinkley. (Scheduled to move
by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.) 1,200 words.
</P>
