A4811 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-HANSON-THISTIMEAROUND     05-24 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANSON-THISTIMEAROUND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANSON GOES ITS OWN WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When they released their major-label debut, 1997's ``Middle of
Nowhere,'' the Hanson brothers were in the wrong place at the right
time.
</P>
<P>
   Because they were young 'n' cute, they were quickly and
thoughtlessly lumped in with the then-burgeoning boy-band movement
that was led by Backstreet Boys. Didn't matter that, unlike
Backstreet and later, 'N Sync, the Hanson bros _ Isaac, Taylor and
Zachary _ played their own instruments (and played them well) and
had more of a crush on the Jackson 5 than on New Kids on the Block.
</P>
<P>
   The boy-band craze helped ``Nowhere'' wind up everywhere: It
sold 5 million copies, and the band's signature hit, ``MMMBop,''
was as inescapable as their cute little mugs. But over time,
critics turned their backs and a lot of fans graduated to harder
stuff, like LFO.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to say if Hanson's second effort, ``This Time Around,'' is
gonna sell or flop. But one thing's for sure, and laugh all you
want: It ain't bad.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most impressive things about it: The brothers wrote
all the songs and even partially produced them. And while they
could have easily gone for the same digestible, funk-frosted pop
formula of their first disc, the guys opted for a grittier sound
that echoes '70s FM radio.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we're not talking the extravagances of Led Zeppelin or Yes.
Rather, songs like ``You Never Know,'' ``If Only'' and ``Runaway
Run'' are drenched in crunchy guitar riffs a la Bad Company.
Amplifying the '70s-rock vibe, John Popper from Blues Traveler
belts through a heated harmonica solo, while young guitar prodigy
Jonny Lang tears off a solo here and there.
</P>
<P>
   Modern twists, such as turntable scratches from Beck cohort DJ
Swamp, do abound, keeping ``Time'' from sounding dated.
</P>
<P>
   Vocally, the group has matured quite a bit. The honey-glazed
harmonies are still there, but you get the feeling that they're
coming from the heart this time, not a sound engineer's control
board. Isaac's voice has hardened, too, lending to these songs a
more grizzled edge.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, not everything works. The big ballads, such as
``Love Song'' and the title track, come off as factory-made space
filler to kill time between the good songs.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, this is a surprisingly good effort and, if
anything, the kids should be championed for doing it their way.
Initially, former Cars singer Ric Ocasek was brought in to produce
but was relieved when his ideas clashed with theirs. The band's new
label also reportedly put pressure on the guys to produce another
``MMMBop'' _ and they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Still only in their teens, Zac, Isaac and Taylor have discovered
the art of keeping their integrity, something most bands twice
their ages couldn't give a flip about. And that's worth a whole
lot. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
