</P>
<P>
   Modern twists, such as turntable scratches from Beck cohort DJ
Swamp, do abound, keeping ``Time'' from sounding dated.
</P>
<P>
   Vocally, the group has matured quite a bit. The honey-glazed
harmonies are still there, but you get the feeling that they're
coming from the heart this time, not a sound engineer's control
board. Isaac's voice has hardened, too, lending to these songs a
more grizzled edge.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, not everything works. The big ballads, such as
``Love Song'' and the title track, come off as factory-made space
filler to kill time between the good songs.
