<HEADER>
A4815 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-PARKS0525-COX     05-24 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARKS0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush's support needed for state conservation initiative
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's task force on conservation
is months away from issuing recommendations on state parks,
wildlife, private lands, urban sprawl and outdoor recreation. But
two broad points of debate have already emerged: money and
politics.
</P>
<P>
   It is also clear that any major conservation initiative would
need the governor's backing to get a warm reception when the state
Legislature convenes in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``This session is potentially going to be a make-it-or-break-it
for parks and conservation in the state. A lot of it rides on
Bush,'' said Andy Jones, Texas program coordinator for the
Conservation Fund, a national land-preservation group.
</P>
<P>
   A series of articles last week in the Austin American-Statesman
documented thin staffing and budgets, lack of land acquisition,
gaps in stewardship and pork-barrel politics in the state park
system.
</P>
<P>
   Reports by Texas A&AMP;M University and the Texas Historical
Commission have recommended budget increases. The staff of the
Legislature's Sunset Advisory Commission has outlined several
options for increasing the Parks and Wildlife Department's budget.
The 10-member Sunset Advisory Commission is expected to vote on
those recommendations next month.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's task force seems likely to call for more money to improve
and expand the 122 state parks, historical sites, natural areas and
fishing piers. The method of funding _ voter-approved bonds, a
dedicated share of state sales taxes or general appropriations _ is
less important than the money itself, said Carol Dinkins, a Houston
lawyer who chairs the panel and is also vice chairwoman of the
Parks and Wildlife Commission, which sets policy for the parks
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think we very much need new funding, and it needs to
be funding for acquisition, development, management and
operations,'' Dinkins said. ``Ultimately, it's going to be up to
the Legislature as to how to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is also up to the Legislature as to whether to do
that at all. Bush's position, and his willingness to use his bully
pulpit, could shape the debate. That is true even if the GOP
governor moves to the White House in January.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not elaborated beyond his two-page executive order in
February that established the task force. State and local parks
``are currently overtaxed due to increased demand, aging
infrastructure and insufficient funding,'' Bush said in his charge
to the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jones, a spokesman for Bush, said the governor would not
pre-empt the task force and would instead await its report, which
is due by Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a lot of faith in the task force members, who are all
respected leaders in their communities,'' Mike Jones said. ``They
all share the governor's concern for the quality of our environment
and, like him, they're dedicated to passing on a clean, better
Texas and passing on these beautiful natural resources we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gov. Rick Perry has not staked out a position, but a
spokesman said Perry looks forward to working on conservation
matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are carefully monitoring the sunset commission and the
governor's task force on conservation as they grapple with these
issues,'' said Eric Bearse, Perry's spokesman. ``And we will be
looking forward to working with them and their proposals once they
make them public.''
</P>
<P>
   Any sizable spending initiative is likely to be received
skeptically by Rep. Rob Junell, who chairs the powerful House
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education is going to be at the top,'' said the Democrat from
San Angelo. ``Health and human services will be next to the top.
And then we'll look at all the other things we do. When you add
money to Parks and Wildlife, you're basically taking it from
something else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Parks and Wildlife Department sought unsuccessfully last
year to get lawmakers to lift a $32 million cap on the amount of
money dedicated to parks from sales taxes on sporting goods. Junell
indicated this week that he remains philosophically opposed to such
a proposal, referring pointedly to Andrew Sansom, the department's
executive director and a proponent of dedicated funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a representative government,'' Junell said. ``Mr.
Sansom and the department would like to have an agency where the
Legislature just sends them whatever amount of money they'd like to
have and never bother them again. That's not the way our
Legislature works.''
</P>
<P>
   The method of funding is secondary, Sansom said. ``The issue on
the front burner is that we can't do all the things that are
expected of us on the revenue we have,'' he said. ``The issue of
where that money comes from is an issue for leadership to decide,
people like Chairman Junell.''
</P>
<P>
   Questions of money aside, the issue of acquiring additional
public land at all is also contentious. Conservation groups have
long urged the state to expand its holdings, but the Texas Farm
Bureau, which represents many farmers and ranchers, is opposed. Any
acquisitions should be offset by the sale of equal amounts of
public land to the private sector, said Gary Joiner, the bureau's
associate legislative director.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Wildlife Association, whose members are mainly
ranchers, supports a three-pronged approach to conservation that
includes government ownership, public-private partnerships and
private ownership, said David Langford, executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
