<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-BORDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHDRAWAL CHANGES RULES OF ENGAGEMENT ALONG BORDER
</HEADLINE>
  (With ISRAEL-LEBANON) 
 By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   METULLA, Israel _ At 6:45 Wednesday morning, after the last
Israeli tank rumbled out of southern Lebanon ending a 22-year
occupation, Maj. Kobi Dostakam closed and locked the gate of the
border fence near this community at the northern tip of Israel.
``Now let's see what happens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Through the night columns of tanks, artillery pieces and armored
personnel carriers streamed out of Lebanon, and after they crossed
into Israel on Wednesday morning, many Israeli soldiers were
ambivalent about the departure.
</P>
<P>
   Some wondered whether it would finally restore calm to the
border area, and cautioned that a possible flare-up of cross-border
violence might turn back the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may not be our last time in Lebanon,'' said Shai
Ben-Yishai, a tank platoon commander. ``We may have to go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Others nearly celebrated, hoisting Israeli flags, smiling and
waving as their armored vehicles lurched though the gate. ``It's
over!'' one soldier shouted as he arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Shai Mor, who brought home a flag of Lebanon as a souvenir of
his nine months in the town of Merj 'Uyun, said he felt both
``tremendous happiness and pain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadness because we surrendered in a way, and happiness because
maybe soldiers will stop getting killed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on his tank, Omri Israel said fighting Hezbollah
guerrillas had become an exercise in futility. ``You can't win a
guerrilla war,'' he said. ``I don't think we ran away. We left with
dignity. We withdrew in order to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah militants are now just across a double fence from
Metulla, a farming community and vacation spot that lies alongside
Kafr Kila, a southern Lebanese village that Hezbollah fighters
entered this week.
</P>
<P>
   At a border crossing abandoned by the Israelis, militants and
villagers looted stockrooms, drove off in army trucks and broke
into cars left behind by members of the Israeli-backed South
Lebanon Army who had fled to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Other Hezbollah followers paraded in armored vehicles left by
the militia, and gathered at the fence facing Metulla to wave
flags, brandish weapons and chant slogans. Israeli soldiers, who in
southern Lebanon had shot Hezbollah fighters on sight, simply
looked on.
</P>
<P>
   The new rules of engagement were in effect spelled out by the
chief of the army's Northern Command, Maj. Gen. Gabi Ashkenazi, at
a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw these people from four to five meters away,'' he said of
the men gathered across the fence. ``I looked at him, he looked at
me, I'm holding my weapon, and nothing happened. If he had fired,
he would have died. He didn't fire. And that's the reality we have
to adjust to.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Haim Sela, a resident of Metalla, discounted suggestions
that Hezbollah guerrillas might shoot across the fence, asserting
that Syria, which is the dominant power in Lebanon, did not want to
provoke an Israeli response.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't fire a single bullet at civilian communities
because Assad doesn't want war with Israel,'' he said, referring to
President Hafez al-Assad. ``The war here is over.''
</P>
<P>
   But at Kibbutz Misgav Am, a border settlement on a ridge above
Metulla, Nurit Rapoport was not convinced. Gazing into southern
Lebanon, Rapoport said she suddenly felt more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I've been stripped this morning,'' she said. ``I'm
for the withdrawal, but I feel exposed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
