A4820 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-BETTER-LIVING-REVIEW-     05-24 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BETTER-LIVING-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAVE NOTICES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Subtitled ``A Digital Odyssey Into the Electronic Dance
Underground,'' filmmaker Jon Reiss' entertaining new documentary
examines the electronic dance (or rave) community and the bizarre
yet fast-growing culture it has spawned.
</P>
<P>
   The well-paced film, which includes high-quality musical
segments by such popular techno acts as Moby, Crystal Method, DJ
Spooky and Meat Beat Manifesto, gathers interviews with ravers, DJs
and musicians who explain why they embrace a lifestyle that
includes sucking on pacifiers, dressing in bunny suits and
traveling to the middle of nowhere to leap around to throbbing
electronic beats.
</P>
<P>
   The lively, informative film makes a convincing argument that
technology is helping create a new global village. Certainly, the
rave phenomenon seems new, and the scene's multimedia presentations
include sights and sounds never experienced in, say, the rock era.
</P>
<P>
   One surprise is the amount of humor Reiss manages to dig up. An
interview with the members of Crystal Method, for instance, had
this reviewer grinning as the unexpectedly articulate musicians
discuss their personal bomb shelter and having to tell their
parents about their band name.
</P>
<P>
   Another memorable segment has British dance-music star Roni Size
discussing how the music transformed him from a teen troublemaker
to a productive and focused adult.
</P>
<P>
   Shot with a tiny digital camera and edited down to a nifty 85
minutes, Reiss gets to the heart of the intoxicating craze, which
has quietly crept into the mainstream by way of Moby, whose songs
are currently used on at least two major TV commercials.
</P>
<P>
   If the documentary has drawbacks, it's the sometimes frenetic
and one-dimensional soundtrack as well as the silly computer
graphics used as brief interludes. Also, Reiss ignores such
less-savory aspects of rave culture as the scene's rampant use of
the designer drug Ecstasy.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, ``Better Living Through Circuitry''
explores with intensity one of the most significant youth cultures
to emerge in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
The film: ``Better Living Through Circuitry'' (not rated). &QL; 
Stars: Includes performances by Moby, Crystal Method, DJ Spooky and
Meat Beat Manifest. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Jon Reiss. Produced by Brian McNelis
and Stuart Swezey. Released by Seventh Art Releasing. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 25 minutes. &QL; 
Playing: Nuart, West L.A.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2008EDT &QL; 
