<HEADER>
A4823 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TAX-REFORMS-NYT &LR;      05-24 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-REFORMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE FINANCE COMMITTEE PROPOSAL WOULD MAKE TAX SHELTERS LESS
LUCRATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corporate tax shelters, whose resurgence is costing the
government billions of dollars a year, would be much less lucrative
under revisions proposed Wednesday by the bipartisan staff of the
Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals would require companies and promoters to disclose
tax-avoidance transactions more fully, subject companies that
engage in shams to a 40 percent penalty on taxes they evaded and
penalize promoters up to half the fees they charged for creating
shams.
</P>
<P>
   The staff proposal is similar in many ways to regulations
proposed in February by Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers to
crack down on abusive tax practices of large companies. The
official estimate that abusive shelters cost the government $10
billion annually, Summers said, is ``just the tip of the iceberg.''
Some estimates, in fact, put it as high as $80 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the latest plan differs on key points. One difference
involves whether to define tax shelters by statute or to rely on
tests created under a series of rulings by Tax Court judges and
judges in other courts to determine whether a transaction was
motivated by a hope for profit or was primarily a tax-avoidance
technique.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. William Roth, R-Del., who is chairman of the Finance
Committee, wants written comments on the proposal by June 9, after
which he will decide whether to hold hearings, said Tara Bradshaw,
a committee spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   But a new law to curb corporate tax evasion is unlikely this
year because Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, who heads the House Ways
and Means Committee, has said he sees no reason to pass such
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   And Archer has strong allies. Kenneth J. Kies of
PricewaterhouseCoopers, perhaps the nation's most widely consulted
expert on corporate tax-reduction techniques, says there is no need
for new legislation to curb tax shelters because there is no
significant problem with improper corporate tax avoidance.
</P>
<P>
   Kies, former chief of staff for the congressional Joint
Committee on Taxation, said that rather than being a massive
problem, abusive tax shelters are used by no more than 50
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Kies said he based this number on a report that Treasury
prepared under the Paperwork Reduction Act. That report estimated
that only four promoters were selling tax shelters under
confidentiality agreements and that 50 corporations and 50
promoters were involved in the kinds of abusive practices it seeks
to curb.
</P>
<P>
   Tax specialists on Capitol Hill and in the Clinton
administration said Wednesday that since Summers issued the
proposed regulations to curb corporate tax shelters, the use of
confidentiality contracts had dried up. Instead promoters are
relying on clients to keep quiet about their use of tax-shelter
devices.
</P>
<P>
   Both specialists said they were confident that far more than 50
companies use abusive shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Kies' view that corporate tax shelters are a minor problem was
also disputed Wednesday by leaders of organizations representing
tax lawyers and corporate tax executives, who say there is a
significant problem of abusive corporate tax practices. Both the
American Bar Association tax section and the Tax Executives
Institute favor requiring fuller disclosure of tax shelters to the
IRS.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Sax, chairman of the association's tax section, said,
``Many parts of this proposal are welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Sax said that among the provisions he likes is one requiring the
chief financial officer or other top executives to certify the
legitimacy of any transactions that create bigger tax benefits than
profits for a company.
</P>
<P>
   This proposal, similar to one made by Treasury, grew out of
complaints by some corporate tax executives that they opposed
illegitimate tax shelters, but were overruled by chief financial
officers eager to show profits.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Murphy, executive director of the Tax Executives
Institute, which represents corporate tax officials, said it
opposes this provision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not denying there have been tax directors who say their
advice was ignored,'' Murphy said. ``But the clear consensus among
our leadership, and a sampling of our membership, is that requiring
the chief financial officer to attest to his knowledge of
transactions is a total waste of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy added that increased disclosure will be meaningless
unless it is accompanied by expanding the auditing staff of the IRS
so that the disclosures are fully investigated and improper
activities are identified and stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a right to expect that somebody will look at those
and act accordingly,'' Murphy said, adding that the institute also
favors increased staff to audit individual returns.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy said he has doubts about the need for legislation, saying
the Treasury and IRS have sufficient authority through regulations
to deal with abusive transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Finance Committee staff proposal deals only with
companies with revenues of $10 million or more. The draft
legislation would not affect wealthy individuals, although many of
the most abusive tax evasions uncovered by the IRS in recent years,
including one marketed by PricewaterhouseCoopers, could also be
used by very wealthy individuals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
