<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON DAY OF VOTE, LOBBYISTS LEAVE NOTHING TO CHANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CHINA-TRADE, CHINA-TRADE-ASSESS) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By Wednesday morning it was quite clear that the
China trade bill would pass, but no one on either side was taking
chances.
</P>
<P>
   From a stuffy conference room in the basement of the Capitol,
about 50 business lobbyists were dispatched, cell phones in hand,
in a final effort to nail down the votes of the dozen or so
lawmakers who were still thought to be undecided.
</P>
<P>
   A lobbyist for Procter &AMP; Gamble, for instance, was sent to see
Rep. Ernie Fletcher, R-Ky. The company makes Jif peanut butter in
Fletcher's district and employs 239 workers.
</P>
<P>
   An official from United Parcel Service went to see Rep. Robert
Scott, D-Va. UPS has a hub in Newport News in Scott's district.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Van Hilleary, R-Tenn., had his arm twisted by a lobbyist
from TRW, which has about 500 workers at an automotive plant in
Morristown in Hilleary's district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't afford to get overconfident,'' said Johanna Schneider
of the Business Roundtable, an organization of giant corporations,
who was working from the room in the basement, Room HC-8.
</P>
<P>
   And despite vote counts that showed them losing, the opponents
of the measure were also out in force on Wednesday. Scores of union
members from back home were on the phone, and at least a dozen
labor officials from across the country were on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Art Pulaski, president of the California AFL-CIO, paid a final
call on Rep. Henry Waxman, a Democrat from Los Angeles, who had not
tipped his hand on how he would vote.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Fletcher, Hilleary and Waxman voted for the bill.
Scott voted against it.
</P>
<P>
   They, and the handful of other lawmakers who were truly
undecided as the vote approached, were besieged in the last few
days, and the pressure peaked on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a big wave hitting the shore,'' said Rep. Vito
Fossella, R-N.Y., who did not let on until just before the vote
that he planned to support the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   He said he took a call on Wednesday morning from a driver for
UPS whom he had met at a Boy Scout function on Staten Island last
weekend. He was also called by members of the food workers union.
The driver favored the trade bill; the food workers were against
it.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since he entered Congress three years ago, he
said, he was lobbied by rank-and-file workers in financial services
companies _ at the banks and brokerage houses and insurance
companies _ who live on Staten Island, or in the slice of his
district that is in southwestern Brooklyn, and work in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally decided, I don't see how voting no is in America's
interest,'' Fossella said.
</P>
<P>
   For him and the others who were undecided _ most genuinely
trying to weigh the national security and economic implications of
the legislation as well as the direct interests of their
constituents _ all the attention was exhausting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally let people know today I needed some space to
breathe,'' said Rep. John Sweeney, a freshman Republican from
upstate New York.
</P>
<P>
   He more or less decided overnight to vote for the measure,
Sweeney said, but at 3 on Wednesday afternoon, he still had qualms
and was following the debate on television in his office, ``just to
make absolutely sure I'm making the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of policy, Sweeney said, he concluded that ``we lose
a little more than we gain if the status quo remains.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But in the end,'' he said, ``you always vote your district.''
</P>
<P>
   And his district, which includes Saratoga Springs and Glens
Falls along the upper Hudson River, was divided.
</P>
<P>
   He heard, he said, from the dairy farmers and the apple and pear
growers and small-business owners who favored the concept of
expanded trade with China. And he heard from the paperworkers and
other union members who feared losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush called recently. So did Defense
Secretary William Cohen. The congressman was given a special
briefing by the CIA. Dennis Hughes, president of the AFL-CIO in New
York, visited him on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to absolutely everybody,'' Sweeney said. ``It was
a very hard call.'' He finally voted yes.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Peter Deutsch, a Democrat from southern Florida, dropped
out of sight on Wednesday while he pondered his decision. He took
no calls and held no meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made myself available to everybody for weeks,'' Deutsch
said. ``Today I needed to think on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   He especially thought, he said, about the huge Motorola plant in
his district with its 2,000 workers and its hopes of selling
two-way radios in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few values I would put above them,'' he said.
``But national security is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Just after lunch, about three hours before the vote, Deutsch
decided to vote against the bill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
