u i BC-LEBANON-WORRIES-BOS &LR;      05-24 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-WORRIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNEASE SETS IN ALONG BORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QLAYA, Lebanon _ Amid the rubble and chaos on the morning after
Israel ended its 22-year occupation of southern Lebanon, villagers
celebrated their ``liberation'' Wednesday, but the towns set among
the rocky hills also seemed to teeter on the edge of lawlessness.
</P>
<P>
   In some places, the scene seemed dangerously close to spiraling
out of control along sectarian lines, with triumphant Shiite Muslim
militias parading in newly confiscated tanks as Christians who had
been loyal to Israel looked on in fear of what the future could
hold.
</P>
<P>
   There were no Lebanese police or soldiers visible in the streets
to fill the vacuum left by Israel's stunning and rapid retreat. UN
peacekeeping forces were also noticeably absent.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are very afraid,'' said Nimr Homsi, 24, of the
Christian town of Qlaya just north of the Israeli border. ``Look at
what they are doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Homsi, who works as a UN interpreter, pointed to three men in
fatigues, one of whom held the yellow flag of the Hezbollah
guerrillas and another who was shooting open a padlock to a store.
``They are not liberating us, they are stealing, and looting, and
intimidating us. Where is the government? Where are the police?''
</P>
<P>
   But Hezbollah, the Islamic resistance movement that succeeded in
ousting the Israeli military machine, insists its forces will
respect the law. Hezbollah, which is also an emerging and powerful
political force, has much at stake in ensuring this. But it has
also been careful to point out that it cannot control people who
have nothing to do with its goals but wave its flag, and that its
role is not to police the pullout.
</P>
<P>
   Sheikh Nabil Kaouk, Hezbollah's military commander for the
south, was waving to supporters in the streets Wednesday. When
asked about the mounting concerns of lawlessness, he replied, ``We
will provide protection to the Christians from tomorrow morning;
you will not find one weapon in this area.''
</P>
<P>
   But that seemed hard to believe at the former south Lebanon
headquarters of Israel's military and its proxy militia. By early
Wednesday, it had turned into a weapons bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   Giddy packs of teenagers and men who identified themselves as
Hezbollah guerrillas openly looted old Russian tanks, high-powered
machine guns, a flatbed truck stocked with heavy caliber
ammunition, helmets, flak jackets and anything else they could
carry.
</P>
<P>
   The massive infusion of this military hardware and firepower
into the hands of the militias raised the fear that factions within
the militias, or perhaps a splinter group, could fire into Israeli
military positions and northern residential communities just a few
hundred yards across the border.
</P>
<P>
   This, analysts from all sides agreed, could ignite a regional
conflagration involving Israel, Lebanon, and Syria, which has
35,000 troops in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   At the border near the Israeli town of Metulla, Lebanese
militias were face to face with Israeli soldiers and members of the
media trading taunts and insults through the barbed-wire and
chain-link fencing. UN officials reported that firebombs had been
thrown from the Lebanon side into the Israeli side, igniting
several South Lebanon Army-owned vehicles parked along the fence.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, that fence was all that marked what has been the last
active Israeli-Arab warfront in a half century of conflict in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak on Wednesday vowed swift and
decisive retaliation if any force attacked Israel across its
border. ``We gave our word, and we have kept our word and brought
our boys home,'' Barak said, referring to a campaign promise he
made to withdraw from Lebanon by July.
</P>
<P>
   But the United Nations will determine whether Israel has fully
withdrawn under the terms ordered by the 1978 UN Resolution 425.
Timur Goksel, political officer of the UN Interim Forces in
Lebanon, said UN peacekeepers would not actively deploy in south
Lebanon until the United Nations confirms that the withdrawal is
complete.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the heavily armed Muslim factions strutted through
largely empty streets of the enclaves loyal to Israel and its SLA
allies.
</P>
<P>
   In the Christian enclave of Qlaya, long openly loyal to the
Israeli presence in Lebanon, the few residents who did not flee
into Israel clustered in St. Georges Greek Orthodox Church and
looked out on the parading supporters of Hezbollah.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Majid Suliman, 44, a Maronite Catholic dressed in
uniform for his job as a member of the Lebanese police. He said
fewer than 16 police were assigned to all of south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are entering homes, they are stealing property, and there
is nothing we can do,'' he said of the Muslim guerrillas. ``I don't
know why the government is not coming in here.''
</P>
<P>
   One resident challenged Suliman, saying that the policeman knew
why the government was not deploying. It was commonly heard
Wednesday that Syria, which effectively controls Lebanon, had
restricted the Lebanese army, seeking to create a chaotic
atmosphere to unsettle Israel and those who supported the
occupation.
</P>
<P>
   None of the Lebanese Christians were willing to allow their
names to be published in connection with this sentiment, saying
they feared for their lives. But several said that by keeping the
zone in a state of chaos, Syria can maintain some leverage on
Israel in its attempts to negotiate the return of the Golan
Heights, which Israel captured in the 1967 war.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the nervousness among Christians in Qlaya Wednesday
was the Israeli bombing of a weapons depot just across the street
from the stone church before dawn. Afterward, the site burst with
explosions of grenades and missiles that had shattered windows in
homes nearby and blown out the church's stained glass. As of
midday, ordnance was still popping and exploding with loud thuds.
</P>
<P>
   Ghada Khouri, 24, a bandage covering a wound under her left eye
and blood still caked to her shirt, was furious that the Israelis
blew up the depot without warning nearby residents. On the floor of
her 1-year-old daughter's bedroom lay shattered glass, blown-out
doors, and missile fragments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel left us behind. We were used by them,'' said Khouri.
``We meant nothing to them, and now we have no future.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most searing images Wednesday was the scene at the
12th century Beaufort Castle. A military compound of steel and
concrete had been built into the stone Crusader castle on a
dominant hilltop in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   As Israeli soldiers retreated early Wednesday, they set off
massive explosions to destroy the castle. Wednesday, hundreds of
residents climbed the steep hillsides to sift through the rubble of
computers, of concrete slabs, of twisted steel beams, and of boxes
of ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   The remnants of the Israeli military complex, some of it still
smoldering, seemed to blend in with the remains of the stone castle
_ the ruins of two foreign invaders in Lebanon, the 12th-century
Christian Crusaders, and the 20th-century Israelis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
