<HEADLINE>
GEEK NOTES: PRICELINE WANTS YOUR BID FOR TELEPHONE CALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Priceline.com, which earned its reputation with the
name-your-own-price model for airline tickets, will soon try to
interest you in bidding for a new commodity: cheap calls to your
mother (or anyone else).
</P>
<P>
   The company began its Priceline Long Distance Service Wednesday.
As with other Priceline services, like those for airline tickets
and groceries, consumers can go to the company's Web site
(www.priceline.com) to bid on blocks of long-distance time. Bids
are accepted or rejected within 60 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   After their bids are accepted, consumers use the Priceline
credit as they would use any prepaid phone card. The customer first
dials a toll-free number, then enters a password and begins using
the time, which has already been charged to the customer's credit
card. (Consumers don't have to change their primary long-distance
carriers.) Blocks of time are available for domestic calls, for
international calls to a single country and for a combination of
domestic and international calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to boil down all the complicated long-distance
pricing schemes to a simple equation: no hidden charges, no monthly
fees, no minimum call times,'' said Daniel Schulman, Priceline's
president and chief executive. ``We think the simplicity, combined
with great savings, will appeal to a broad range of consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   One way the company is trying to keep the service inexpensive is
by routing calls over the networks of three Internet telephony
companies: Net2Phone, deltathree.com and zeroplus.com. Schulman
said Priceline had been testing the service for about a month with
10,000 consumers. The average block of time sought by each bid was
four hours, Schulman said, adding that the average saving was about
40 percent off the best available long-distance packages.
</P>
<P>
   James Vogtle, e-commerce research director at the Boston
Consulting Group, said the Priceline service could mean savings for
consumers, even beyond those offered by other carriers. ``The
long-distance market is a commodity market with lots of surplus
capacity, the kind of market where the Priceline model makes
sense,'' Vogtle said. ``Consumers just might get better prices than
they would be able to negotiate on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Bruce Headlam
</P>
<P>
   ZIPPING ALONG AT THE INDY 500 FROM THE COMFORT OF HOME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If simply watching the Indianapolis 500 on television this
Memorial Day isn't enough, the Net is offering a virtual seat
behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Excite(AT)Home has enabled a Web site (sports.excite.com) to
show the dashboard of Eddie Cheever's super-sleek car as he races
around the track at more than 220 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   The race car, which beams telemetry to Cheever's trackside crew,
will be seen on home computers as a 3-D model. A mouse click on
parts of the car will display information like tire pressure and
oil temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Before the race, online viewers can also get a driver's-eye view
of a lap around the speedway on www.indy500.com/multimedia.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Michel Marriott
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA INTRODUCES A PAGER TO ATTRACT 18- TO 24-YEAR-OLDS
</P>
<P>
   Motorola announced this week that it would introduce a two-way
pager aimed at young adults. The pager, the Talkabout T900, is
called a personal interactive communicator by the company. It will
cost less than $200, with additional monthly service starting at
$14.95.
</P>
<P>
   The T900 is about the size of a standard pager and has a
keyboard for entering e-mail messages and a form of instant
messaging. Unlike what are usually called alphanumeric pagers,
these units allow the user to get information like news, sports,
weather reports, horoscopes and driving directions.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it believed that e-mail and instant messaging
would be the key attractions for adults 18 to 24 years old. ``It
will allow active adults a way to communicate instantly to help
organize their busy lives,'' said Amy Kabcenell, a marketing
director with Motorola.
</P>
<P>
   The two-way pager market had been limited because there was only
one nationwide service provider, Skytel. That has changed with
several vendors now offering wireless services.
</P>
<P>
   The pagers will go on sale in early June.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Stephen C. Miller
</P>
<P>
   LEGO WEBCAM TURNS TOY INTO A ROBOT THAT STANDS GUARD
</P>
<P>
   Lego's popular Mindstorm line of programmable toy robots proved
that it was fun to watch robots do your bidding. The latest
addition to the Mindstorm line may prove that it's just as much fun
to have a robot watch you.
</P>
<P>
   Vision Command is a $99 Web camera that, when mounted on the
core unit of Lego's Robotics Invention System, can turn the toy
into something resembling Robby the Robot from ``Forbidden
Planet.'' Using the camera as a pair of eyes, the Mindstorm robot
can detect color or movement and, depending on its programming, can
react with any number of responses.
</P>
<P>
   The camera is tethered to the PC through a 15-foot USB cable.
Programmers can break the camera's field of vision down into eight
separate regions and program a different response for each one. The
robot might chase a ball if it detected color in one region, snap a
still photograph if it detected motion in another or utter a threat
if it saw a little brother enter the room. (Threats can be easily
recorded with the built-in microphone.)
</P>
<P>
   Simply mounted on a computer, the Vision Command can also act as
a Webcam, with all the usual still and video Webcam capabilities.
Yes, it will still threaten that little brother.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Bruce Headlam
</P>
<P>
   SHOOT-'EM-UP GAME FOR PALM-BASED UNITS
</P>
<P>
   Now, during those boring conference calls, you can use your Palm
organizer to do more than play Tetris. You can blast Wibble Bots.
</P>
<P>
   James McCombe, a programmer in Belfast, Northern Ireland, has
created Dreadling, a first-person shooter contest that shrinks the
action-game concept behind Id Software's Wolfenstein 3D and Doom
down to size.
</P>
<P>
   Dreadling has textured 3-D graphics, and the Palm's standard
five buttons are converted to the game's controls. The player can
collect fresh ammunition, new weapons and health credits while
facing monsters. The game will run on the Palm III and later
models, and on Visor and IBM WorkPad c3 organizers that run at
least version 3.0 of the Palm operating system. A sample version
can be downloaded free from www.dreadling.com, and the full version
of the game costs $19.98.
</P>
<P>
   Since the average PDA has only about two megabytes of RAM,
McCombe had to make the file as small as possible. ``The shareware
version of Dreadling requires only 80 kilobytes of memory and
requires an extra 50 kilobytes or so when running, since it
decompresses itself into available memory,'' he said in an e-mail
message. McCombe has created fairly speedy renderings of explosions
and monsters for the Palm's small screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Games of this nature normally require large amounts of
processing capability, memory and advanced graphics hardware,''
McCombe said. ``Your average computer screen has a game resolution
of 800 by 600 pixels at least, and the Palm Pilot has only 160 by
160.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Dreadling proves, that is just enough to shoot down a few
Grunt Bots before the next meeting.
</P>
<P>
   _ By J.D. Biersdorfer
</P>
</TEXT>
