<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4828 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LATIN-AMERICA0525-COX     05-24 0988
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATIN-AMERICA0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fraud charges jeopardize plans for elections in Venezuela, Peru
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Carter Center had expected to be monitoring two
elections in South America this Sunday _ one in Peru, the other in
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   But developments on Wednesday illustrated the shaky state of
democracy in the region and left the Carter Center unsure whether
either election would even be held, let alone deserve to be
monitored.
</P>
<P>
   In Peru, Alejandro Toledo, who had been challenging President
Alberto Fujimori's bid for a third term, formally withdrew this
week from Sunday's runoff election, saying it was hopelessly rigged
against him. He said he would compete only if it were postponed and
if conditions improved.
</P>
<P>
   The Carter Center was unsure for a time this week whether that
meant an election would even be held or whether Fujimori would be
declared the winner with no votes cast.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Jennifer McCoy, director of the Latin American and
Caribbean program at the Carter Center, said the latest information
is that the runoff will be held _ with only one candidate
participating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless we see some major changes, it is likely that we will
not send observers for the election this Sunday,'' McCoy said. A
formal statement withdrawing from the monitoring mission may come
as early as today, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The center monitors not only the accuracy of the election-day
vote count, but ``campaign conditions'' in the time preceding the
vote. In this campaign, McCoy said, ``access to the media has been
very inequitable. There has been harassment of the candidates.
There has been some intimidation of the press that led to some of
the press not accepting advertisements from opposition
candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Peru's national election watchdog group, Transparencia,
announced this week that it would ``abstain from observing Sunday's
election.'' And the Organization of American States' monitoring
mission announced that it was suspending cooperation with election
officials.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation remains in flux. Eduardo Stein, head of the
OAS delegation, said Tuesday that his mission had made headway in
negotiating a possible postponement of the vote with election
officials.
</P>
<P>
   In Venezuela, where president Hugo Chavez is being challenged by
Francisco Arias Cardenas _ who participated with Chavez in a failed
coup attempt in 1992 _ technical problems have marred preparations.
National Electoral Council President Estanislao Gonzalez said
earlier this week that the vote is ``in jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   He blamed an Omaha, Neb., contractor, Election Systems &AMP;
Software, for delaying delivery of vote-tabulating software and
contended the firm is part of a ``destabilizing campaign . . .
directed so that the May 28 electoral process doesn't occur.''
</P>
<P>
   McCoy said Wednesday that the Carter Center is still uncertain
whether the balloting will take place this Sunday. She said
opposition officials are concerned because they will not be able to
monitor the performance of the machines, and they fear the software
could be manipulated.
</P>
<P>
   But she said that Venezuela has a history of fraud with
hand-counted ballots, so the transition to machine tabulation is
``a step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The Carter Center is still prepared to monitor the election this
Sunday. If the vote is delayed, the center will try to organize
another observer mission for the new date, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Venezuelan campaign has been open and has afforded the
candidates good access to the press, McCoy said. On the other hand,
the campaign season was only 25 days long _ much shorter than
voters in the country are accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   The Carter Center's involvement in Venezuela runs deeper than
election monitoring alone. The center has had a continuous presence
in the country since last August to monitor the drafting and
approval of the new constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The new constitution _ adopted in December by a constituent
assembly dominated by the governing coalition _ provides for a
unicameral legislature, rather than one with two houses, prompting
some states to worry about unequal representation, McCoy said. And
it strengthens the power of the president while weakening that of
the congress, prompting fears that it represents a step back toward
Latin America's authoritarian past, she said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the document is strong in its support of
human rights and the social welfare of Venezuela's people, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   It has become commonplace for U.S. political figures to say that
democracy has now come to every country in the western hemisphere
except Cuba. But the events in Peru, election violence in Haiti,
and allegations of government manipulation of recent elections in
the Dominican Republic raise questions as to how firmly entrenched
democracy is.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy said the answer is mixed. There are strong democratic
institutions in countries such as Chile, Argentina and Brazil, she
said. Mexico, she said, has made ``a very impressive and gradual
transformation over the last decade'' away from one-party politics
to the competitive climate of the current campaign. And Central
America, wracked by civil wars in the 1980s, has also made
progress, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But problems persist in the Andean countries, McCoy said.
Colombia faces problems with guerrillas and illegal drugs. In Peru,
the president is running for a third term ``under questionable
constitutional authority,'' she said. Ecuador suffered a military
coup this year. And in Venezuela, ``the elected president is trying
to carry out a peaceful social revolution, but in a manner that
some of his critics fear is authoritarian,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In this area, she said, ``the institutionalism, or really the
entrenchment of democracy has not taken hold _ or is being
threatened at this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
