u w BC-TRIPP-CHARGES-BOS &LR;      05-24 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPP-CHARGES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS DROP CHARGES AGAINST LINDA TRIPP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A double-crossing tattletale to some and a
patriotic whistleblower to others, Linda R. Tripp on Wednesday won
a measure of vindication for revealing President Clinton's sex
scandal, as prosecutors dropped charges that she had illegally
wiretapped her friend Monica S. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp, who cast herself as having thwarted what she described as
Clinton's ``blatant attempt to fix a court case,'' was spared a
criminal trial after a Maryland state judge limited Lewinsky's
testimony against her former confidante, gutting the prosecution's
case.
</P>
<P>
   The development signaled an end to the only major criminal
charges to arise from Clinton's impeachment. On Monday, an Arkansas
ethics panel recommended that he be disbarred for his role in the
drama.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp issued a statement that said, ``The full story has not
been told, but I continue to believe I did the right thing given
the extraordinary circumstances in which I found myself.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lucianne Goldberg, a New York book agent who prompted Tripp to
secretly tape her conversations with Lewinsky, said of Tripp: ``She
has been through such an extraordinary and unfair ordeal. This has
eaten up two years of her life, and her biggest crime was telling
the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Maryland prosecutors said Tripp's biggest crime was a felony _
wiretapping a conversation without the other party's consent _ a
state offense punishable by up to 10 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp's tape of Lewinsky provided the independent counsel,
Kenneth W. Starr, with evidence that Clinton had engaged in an
affair in the White House with Lewinsky and had lied about it under
oath in a sexual-harassment suit brought by an Arkansas employee,
Paula Corbin Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence provided the foundation for Clinton's 1999
impeachment trial, the first of a president in 131 years. The
Senate cleared him on all three counts.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, a Maryland state prosecutor, Stephen Montanarelli,
said the judge's decision to bar most of Lewinsky's testimony had
undermined his effort to prove that Tripp recorded a phone
conversation with Lewinsky without her consent in December 1997.
Tripp had learned earlier that it was illegal to make such
recordings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no other witnesses to the conversation whom the
state can call to testify, and Tripp cannot be compelled to
testify,'' Montanarelli said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Diane O. Leasure, ruled this month that Lewinsky's
testimony was tainted because her recollection of the conversation
date had been influenced by Starr's staff.
</P>
<P>
   Montanarelli, arguing that Lewinsky did not need Starr's team to
refresh her memory, asked Leasure to reverse her ruling. On
Tuesday, the judge declined.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an extremely important . . . event in her life which
was, shortly after it occurred, published in detail in the national
news media,'' Montanarelli said of Lewinsky. ``We believe her, the
court does not, and that resolves the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution also was stymied by its need to present a case
against Tripp that did not involve evidence she provided to Starr.
He got that evidence in exchange for a federal grant of immunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite the federal grant of immunity, the state of Maryland
pursued its selective prosecution of me for more than two years,''
Tripp said in her statement. ``My family and I are gratified that
the federal immunity I was given provided the protection it
promised.''
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyer, Joseph Murtha, spoke more harshly of her
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actions by the state prosecutors to dismiss these charges
today do not dispel our concern that the decision to indict Linda
Tripp was politically motivated and that the case was prosecuted
solely because she blew the whistle on President Clinton's attempt
to fix a case,'' Murtha said.
</P>
<P>
   Pending is a Tripp civil suit alleging that the Clinton
administration used confidential records to smear her reputation in
retribution for her role in the Lewinsky matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2012EDT &QL; 
