A4830 &Cx1f; tth-z
u v BC-BUDGET-SPI &LR;      05-24 0383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Thursday, May 25, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Bob Schenet on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TRADE (Washington) _ The House, by a surprisingly
comfortable margin, agrees to normalize trade relations with China,
bringing the United States within reach of a new and potentially
lucrative relationship with a nation of 1.3 billion consumers.
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Pope. (Story will move in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT (Washington) _ The federal judge in the Microsoft
antitrust case gives the Justice Department two days to revise its
plan to break up the software giant, possibly into three parts
instead of two, and rejected the company's pleas for more time to
respond. (Summary from wires.)
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Richman. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   ALASKA-TAPES (Seattle) _ The last radio transmission from the
pilots of Alaska Airlines Flight 261 to air traffic controllers was
a calm ``thank you,'' after which controllers heard only chilling
reports from pilots of other planes who watched the Alaska jet make
a horrifying, inverted dive into the Pacific Ocean from 17,900
feet.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
