<HEADLINE>
NERVOUS INVESTORS STAGE RALLY IN TECH STOCKS, BUT MARKET STAYS
UNSETTLED 
</HEADLINE>
   By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The stock market ended a five-day slide Wednesday as
investors bought many of the technology stocks that had been
battered since the Federal Reserve raised its short-term interest
rate target half a percentage point last week.
</P>
<P>
   But the fear of higher interest rates, and the threat of how
much they could slow the economy in the months ahead, continued to
hurt companies that traditionally fare poorly when growth slows.
</P>
<P>
   So Intel, down 9.8 percent in the last week, rose 6.8 percent.
Microsoft, off 8.2 percent, jumped 3.8 percent, Cisco Systems,
lower by 16.5 percent in the last week, climbed 9.1 percent,
Veritas Software, off 10.3 percent, rose 12.4 percent, and Sun
Microsystems, down 17.8 percent, rallied, 6.3 percent. But Sears,
Roebuck dropped 3.5 percent; International Paper, 3.6 percent; Dow
Chemical 2.2 percent; and Union Carbide 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose 106.06 points, or 3.4 percent,
to 3,270.61, but after falling almost 6 percent Tuesday, the index
is still below the 3,321 level it plunged to in the week ending
April 14, when the index fell a record 25.3 percent. The Dow Jones
industrial average climbed 113.08 points, or 1.1 percent, to
10,535.35, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index finished
25.19 points, or 1.8 percent, higher at 1,399.05
</P>
<P>
   But there is so much uncertainty in the market right now that it
is impossible to tell whether one day's rally means anything more
than investors switched from one sector to another.
</P>
<P>
   The abandonment of technology stocks in mid-April helped lead to
a big rally in economically sensitive stocks as investors, instead
of fleeing the stock market, just moved their money to another
sector. But since the Fed's interest rate increase last Tuesday,
stocks in this sector have been tumbling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock market bulls believe you have 50 basis points or
less; the market bears believe you have 100 to 150 basis points
more to go,'' said Thomas Galvin, chief investment officer at
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, referring to how much higher the Fed
will push short-term interest rates. A basis point is one-hundredth
of a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we get some data points to shore up confidence that the
economy is slowing down, sellers will win the day,'' he said. And,
he added, it will probably not be until June 13, when May retail
sales are reported, that there is a chance for a report that could
confirm that consumers are slowing down. March retail sales fell
0.2 percent, but no one puts much stock in one month's numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty about the outlook for the stock market and the
economy is also increasing the daily volatility of trading. Barely
a day goes buy without big swings up and down, even if the market
ends up little changed on the day. Wednesday, for example, the
Nasdaq index was down almost 122 points, or 3.9 percent, before
rallying. From the low for the day to the close, the index rose 7.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, prices rose as the stock market fell earlier
in the day. But as the stock market climbed back into positive
territory, bonds gave up their gains as some investors switched
from bonds back to stocks.The yield on the Treasury's 10-year note
fell to 6.46 percent, from 6.42 percent on Tuesday. The price,
which moves in the opposite direction, fell 9/32, to 100 8/32. The
yield on the 30-year bond fell to 6.19 percent from 6.16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   One of the interesting stock rallies Wednesday was in Microsoft,
which rose 2 13/16, to 66, which means the company is worth just a
little more than a half of what it was at its high last December.
The rally came even as the federal judge trying the Microsoft
antitrust case seemed to suggest in a court hearing Wednesday that
the government's plan to break up the company did not go far
enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
