<SLUG> BC-CINCINNATI-MAY-FESTIVAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANDADDY OF MUSIC FESTIVALS THRIVES IN BIG WAY 
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Ohio, Pa., Ky.)  By JAMES R. OESTREICH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ It came as a surprise to many in 1995 that the
Cincinnati Symphony was turning 100. It is older than better-known
counterparts in Philadelphia and Cleveland. Yet the orchestra is by
no means the oldest musical institution in this city of Germanic
traditions.
</P>
<P>
   That distinction belongs to a choral event, the May Festival,
founded in 1873. The sprawling Music Hall, which opened in 1878 and
is now the home of the orchestra, was actually built for the
festival.
</P>
<P>
   So the May Festival may be more entitled than most to greet the
new millennium in a grandiose way, as James Conlon, its music
director for 21 years, decided to do this season.
</P>
<P>
   Two huge works anchor the affair _ Mahler's Eighth Symphony,
last Saturday, and Schoenberg's ``Gurrelieder,'' next Saturday _
and reinforcements, the Concert Chorus of the City of Dusseldorf,
have been brought in to add the needed heft.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the May Festival Chorus lacks substance. An amateur
group, it was founded in 1880, 700 strong, down 100 from the
combined choruses at the first festival. Having evolved with
changing times _ specifically, a decline in amateur music-making
and a concern to emulate performance practices of earlier eras _
the festival chorus now numbers 135.
</P>
<P>
   That is still large for, say, Mozart's C minor Mass (K. 427),
which was what remained of the opening concert on Friday evening
after a day of flight delays from New York. But it is good to see
so worthy a tradition survive on some level, the more so in that it
still represents a significant degree of community involvement in
what has become a year-round enterprise. And as trained by Robert
Porco, a noted choral specialist, the festival chorus acquitted
itself admirably, alternating lightness with strength where needed
and singing with generally sure intonation and good unanimity.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of that program, it was a shame to have missed
especially the chorales from Bach's Cantata No. 147, the source of
countless ``Jesu, Joy of Man's Desiring'' arrangements. To give the
audience some idea of the changing, contracting times, Conlon
performed one in a big Romantic expansion and the other more in
line with current notions of proper Baroque style.
</P>
<P>
   Such minimalist concerns hardly affect the Mahler, the
``Symphony of a Thousand.'' The festival presented the fourth
performance of this work in the United States in 1931, with Eugene
Goossens conducting more than the specified number of performers,
including some 900 voices, and the Cincinnati Symphony, which
joined the festival in 1905. Here, with the Dusseldorf chorus, the
Cincinnati Boychoir and the requisite vocal soloists, the forces
numbered 482.
</P>
<P>
   It was a good size for Music Hall, and the finely restrained
quiet singing of the adult choirs, totaling 260, was as remarkable
as many a sonorous outburst. But the endings of the two movements
were spectacular in their force, as rousing as any this longtime
Mahlerian has heard.
</P>
<P>
   In a sharply contrasted preconcert recital on Saturday, Kristine
Jepson, a mezzo-soprano and the best of an uneven lot of vocal
soloists during the weekend, performed songs by Duparc and Gene
Sheer wonderfully, with Thomas Muraco as pianist.
</P>
<P>
   This despite the oversize setting of a hall with 3,400 seats,
most of which were full for the big concerts.
</P>
<P>
   The festival's first weekend ended with a concert on Sunday
evening at the Cathedral Basilica of the Assumption in nearby
Covington, Ky. Further showing the range of community involvement,
the May Festival Youth Chorus opened the program handsomely with a
cappella numbers by Scarlatti, Monteverdi and Palestrina.
</P>
<P>
   Then the May Festival Chamber Choir, led by Porco, became the
main attraction. Justly popular works of Bach, the motet ``Jesu,
Meine Freude'' (``Jesus, My Joy'') and the Cantata No. 106,
``Gottes Zeit Ist die Allerbest Zeit'' (``God's Time Is the Best
Time of All''), were followed by a lovely rarity, Giacomo
Carissimi's oratorio ``Jephte,'' in fetching accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Now on to Orff's ``Carmina Burana,'' on Friday, and the big bang
of ``Gurrelieder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
