<SLUG> BC-AIR-MERGER-COST-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPLOYEES' SUPPORT FOR UNITED, US AIRWAYS MERGER UNCLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (Sidebar with AIR-MERGER) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When United Airlines and US Airways tried to merge in 1995,
objections from United's employees, who own 55 percent of the
company, scuttled the deal. A big question is whether employees
will block the current deal.
</P>
<P>
   James Goodwin, the chairman and chief executive of UAL Corp.,
which operates United Airlines, voiced optimism Wednesday about the
reaction of his airline's labor unions to the proposed acquisition
of the US Airways Group. He even ventured that the powerful pilot's
union, ``supports the deal strategically, but warned about other
issues,'' like combining the seniority lists for the two airlines.
</P>
<P>
   But Rick Dubinsky, the chairman of the master executive council
of the airline pilot's union at United, said the union had not
signed off on the latest merger attempt. ``I am deeply disappointed
that the company would enter into a transaction of this magnitude
without reaching full agreement with the United pilot group on all
issues,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the International Association of Machinists and
the Association of Flight Attendants, as well as the pilots' union
at US Airways, were more cautious in reacting to the deal. But an
airline union lawyer predicted that they too would have concerns
about the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe, if you go down the ranks of the airlines'
three unions, that this is going to be an easy merger,'' said the
lawyer, who insisted on anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Dubinsky and John Peterpaul, a retired vice president of
transportation at the machinists' union, are both on United's
board. But spokesmen for the machinist's union and the United
pilots insisted that even if Dubinsky or Peterpaul knew about the
proposed merger before the United board approved it on Tuesday
evening, they did not tell their union colleagues about it, nor
would they have the authority to make commitments on behalf of
their unions without consultation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick, as a member of the board, has a fiduciary responsibility
to maintain confidentiality,'' said Kenneth Bradley, a United
captain and spokesman for the United chapter of the Air Line Pilots
Association, the national pilots' union.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Palmer, a spokesman for the machinist's union, said that,
``This kind of just got sprung on us.'' Palmer added that when it
comes to United's board, Peterpaul, ``doesn't consult with us on
how he votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubinsky and Peterpaul are crucial to the deal because the
approval of at least one of the two union representatives on
United's board is required for large corporate transactions, under
the terms of the company's employee stock ownership plan. But both
men are legally obliged to vote in the interests of all
shareholders, even if this may conflict with the interests of their
unions, although balancing these interests is a matter of judgment.
Neither man was available Wednesday for interviews.
</P>
<P>
   The acceptance or rejection of the pact by United's 10,000
pilots will be critical, labor officials said. The United pilots
own 46 percent of the employee stock ownership plan set up in 1994.
Because the stock ownership plan, in turn, owns 55 percent of
United, this means that the pilots own a quarter of the company.
The machinists own 37 percent of the employee stock ownership plan,
salaried non-union employees own the remaining 17 percent. United's
flight attendants are not part of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots are also in the middle of negotiations with United on
a new labor agreement, and have been divided on how aggressively to
bargain. Dubinsky, who led a strike against United in 1985, won
election to the local union chairmanship last year with a
reputation for toughness, returning after an absence to a job he
had held twice before.
</P>
<P>
   United and its pilots have agreed this year to begin meeting
with a federal mediator on June 5, after 17 months of bargaining
with little progress. When the most recent, six-year labor contract
lapsed on April 12, United's pilots dropped back to what they were
earning in 1993, before the contract was signed.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the contract lapsed, United pilots were earning
slightly less than US Airways pilots. The United pilots are
demanding raises that would make them the highest-paid pilots in
the industry. That raises the ticklish issue of whether to pay the
same to pilots from both airlines or try to introduce a two-tier
pay structure, which the national pilots' union has tried to limit.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of seniority lists with US Airways is another
concern of United pilots. Airlines use seniority to determine who
flies popular routes at convenient times and who is stuck flying to
undesirable locations on holidays. Seniority is also an important
factor in deciding which pilots are captains and which are first
officers. This makes an enormous difference in pilots' pay:
captains earn $160,000 to $230,000 at US Airways right now, while
first officers earn $100,000 to $120,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pilot seniority is really sacred, that dictates every aspect
of a pilot's career,'' said Bradley, who flies Boeing 757s and 767s
for United.
</P>
<P>
   Combining seniority lists is seldom a straightforward question
of just figuring out who was hired first by which airline. This is
particularly true for US Airways, which is the product of a series
of airline mergers that were followed by complicated combinations
of seniority lists. US Airways' purchase of the shuttle linking
Washington, New York and Boston several years ago provoked a bitter
dispute among pilots of the airline and the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute ended up going to an arbitrator, who ruled last year
that anyone who had been a captain at the shuttle would remain a
captain of the combined airline, even if this meant putting them in
seniority lists ahead of people who had spent more years as pilots
at US Airways.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Some of the shuttle service's pilots are survivors of the
bankruptcy of Eastern Airlines, and pose some of the thorniest
issues of all for the pilots of any airline merging with US
Airways. Many of these shuttle pilots joined Eastern in the 1960s.
They lost much of their seniority when Donald Trump bought the
Eastern shuttle in 1989. Trump later sold the shuttle to a holding
company, which sold it to US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   But the former Eastern pilots from the shuttle are unlikely to
be treated as having more seniority than pilots at United Airlines,
which hired many of its pilots in the 1970s and 1980s. When United
hired 700 Eastern pilots following Eastern's bankruptcy in 1989,
the United pilots insisted that the Eastern pilots lose all their
seniority and work their way up from the bottom of United's
seniority list as though they were rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters is the plan by United and US Airways to
spin off US Airways' nonshuttle flights out of Washington into a
new airline. This would require a separate seniority list and a
decision on which pilots would go to the smaller airline, which
might be less financially stable.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Freundlich, a spokesman for the US Airways pilots, said the
pilots' master executive council at US Airways was determined to
look out for the airline's pilots in any combination of seniority
lists. ``The attitude is one of caution, and the MEC will do
everything that is necessary to protect the interests of the US
Airways pilots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways' labor contract with its pilots still has another
three years to go before either side can reopen it. Neither the
United nor US Airways pilots could readily go on strike even if
they objected to the proposed merger. The airline industry is
covered by the Railway Labor Act, which requires extensive
mediation and a cooling-off period before transportation workers
are allowed to walk off the job.
</P>
<P>
   United pilots are likely to give extra scrutiny to the deal
because the US Airways chief executive is Stephen Wolf, who was
United's chief executive in the early 1990s and had a bitter
relationship with the pilots. But Wolf said Wednesday that he would
leave as soon as a merger was concluded. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
