<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4836 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-AIRLINE-MERGER-BOS &LR;      05-24 1539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-MERGER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLOSE FEDERAL SCRUTINY OF DEAL IS EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   United Airline's acquisition of US Airways will face a tough
examination by the Justice Department over the ebbing of
competition the merger would bring about, antitrust experts say.
And the proposed merger has prompted speculation about a new round
of consolidation in the airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   United is strong in Latin America and Asia, but is weaker across
the North Atlantic. The airline has one overseas flight from Boston
to London.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Ray, managing director of John Hancock's bond and corporate
finance group and team leader of the transportation portfolio, said
it is possible that Boston would become an attractive gateway for
European expansion while benefiting from United's global network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for Boston there will be a net plus for the consumer
because of the immense United system that it will expose us to,
especially overseas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also concern that the merger could create such an
aviation giant that consumers would suffer. Massachusetts Attorney
General Thomas F. Reilly's office is working with other states to
review the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned about the air fares consumers will pay,''
said Timothy Shea, chief of the public protection bureau. ``We are
working with other states, including Pennsylvania, to review the
transaction for its impact on consumers and airline competition.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in New York on Wednesday to announce
formally the nearly $12 billion deal _ United's UAL Corp. will pay
$4.3 billion in cash and assume $1.5 billion in debt and $5.8
billion in aircraft lease agreements _ UAL chairman and chief
executive James E. Goodwin and US Air Group chairman Stephen M.
Wolf vowed to complete the deal. They said regulators should
approve because it will benefit consumers, not hurt them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will link United's extensive east-west system and US
Airways's comprehensive north-south system, and we believe it will
create the first truly efficient network that will stimulate jobs
and create a global airline better able to deliver benefits to
millions of passengers and hundreds of communities throughout the
US,'' Goodwin said.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said because there was little overlap on the two
airlines' route systems, antitrust issues should not be a concern.
But in order to alleviate those worries, US Airways would spin off
much of its Washington Reagan National Airport operations to board
member Robert Johnson, who would start a new airline, DC Air.
United, which has a hub at Washington's Dulles International
Airport, would keep the lucrative Boston-New York-Washington
shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, United vowed it would not raise ticket prices for
two years unless fuel prices or the consumer price index rose. It
also said it would not cut travel agent commissions for two years.
United has been an industry leader in cutting the commissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the antitrust laws is to make consumers not
dependent on promises from parties who want to ensure approval from
the Justice Department,'' said Thane Scott, an antitrust attorney
at the Boston law firm of Palmer &AMP; Dodge. ``Their purpose is to
make sure competition makes those promises unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will get a very, very close look from Justice,
and unlike the telecommunications industry and the intricacies of
operating system software, airline tickets are understood by
consumers,'' Scott said. ``Most consumers would not see this as
likely to improve service, lower price or increase efficiency.''
</P>
<P>
   A Justice Department spokeswoman said Wednesday that the merger
would receive very careful review.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Senator John McCain, an Arizona Republican and
the chairman of the Committee on Commerce, Science and
Transportation, said: ``Consolidation in the airline industry is
always a cause for concern, although this initiative has exciting
possibilities, such as a new, potentially low-cost carrier
operating out of Reagan National. We plan to pay particular
attention to what this means to the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   And US Representative Henry Hyde, an Illinois Republican and the
House Judiciary Committee chairman, said the proposal will be the
focus of a previously scheduled June 14 hearing on airline
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm deeply concerned that this merger may further lessen
competition in the airline industry,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hudson, executive director of the Aviation Consumer Action
Project, was even more blunt. He said: ``If this merger were
approved without major divestiture of routes and other
restrictions, the `Big Six' (United, American, Delta, Northwest,
Continental, and US Airways) will quickly become the `Big Three'
and US airline passengers will be the major losers.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were also dubious.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's Ray said: ``Size matters and one of the real issues
that will crop up is what kind of competition you have left in this
corridor.'' In order for the deal to win regulatory approval,
United would have to give up gates and landing slots at LaGuardia
and gates in Pittsburgh and Baltimore, he added.
</P>
<P>
   At Logan, United has eight gates in Terminal C and is spending
millions to expand to 10 gates. US Airways has 16 gates at Terminal
B and is in the second phase of an expansion there that will add
four more gates.
</P>
<P>
   United spokesman Kurt Ebenhoch said the airline will review
gates and terminal options at virtually all airports where both
carriers operate. ``Certainly, we want our customers to have as
seamless and hassle-free travel as we can provide and there will be
cost savings in facility consolidation, but whether that means
United will move into US Airways or vice versa will vary, but it is
too early to say what will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Kinton, director of aviation for the Massachusetts Port
Authority, which owns and operates Logan International Airport,
said the merger ``bodes well for increased service from Boston,
maybe some new international routes, and at the end of the day, you
end up with a stronger carrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not have the concerns that Pittsburgh or Charlotte
might have,'' he said, referring to US Airways hubs. But United
said it would add domestic and international one-stop flights to
Pittsburgh, Charlotte and Philadelphia. The one area where United
had been considered weak was along the eastern seaboard. United
said it also would keep its flights from Washington National
Airport to US Airways hub cities.
</P>
<P>
   Kinton said he did not know how the Boston gates would be
consolidated, but said, ``It is high on my list of priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   If United, for example, were to move to Terminal B and take over
US Airways space there, it would free up gates at Terminal C.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are new entrants out there circling Logan and they are
interested,'' Kinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The low-cost start-up JetBlue, flying new Airbus aircraft out of
John F. Kennedy International Airport, has been considering
starting service to Boston, but officials at the airline said that
the gates currently available at Logan, in Terminal D, are
unattractive because the taxiing time is too long from runway to
gate and planes can get held up on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways and Delta Air Lines have been locked in fierce
competition along the East Coast. Wednesday a Delta spokesman said
the airline would have no comment on the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will monitor the situation carefully in terms of the
implications with respect to the industry and we will explore, as
we always do, the strategic options available for Delta,'' the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines, the second-largest airline in terms of
revenue, also was mum, posting this statement on its Web site:
``There are a number of parties with more than a passing interest
in this transaction, including labor unions and employees,
government regulators, elected officials and airline customers. We
recognize the public fascination in the airline business and in
this matter, and the news media should not be lacking commentators
on the proposed merger. For the time being, however, American
Airlines will decline comment.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to regulatory approval, the merger would have to
receive the approval of unions, and the inability to merge
seniority lists has led to other planned mergers dissolving.
</P>
<P>
   The United pilots' union _ currently engaged in contract
negotiations with the airline _ Wednesday issued a statement
expressing strong concern over the proposed merger, and the US
Airways pilots' union said it needed to study the details of the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are cautious and need to determine what the career
expectation for our pilots would be under the agreement,'' said
Royt Freundlich, a spokesman for US Airways Master Executive
Council of the Air Line Pilots Association.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, reaction to the deal was muted, with UAL stock
falling 11.9 percent, or $7.1875, to close at $53.1875, and at
least one analyst downgraded the stock. But investors swarmed to US
Airways stock, seeking the $60 premium that UAL is offering. The
stock rocketed 86 percent, or $22.6875, to $49.00.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
