<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0337 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4837 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-PANDAS0525-COX     05-24 1082
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANDAS0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giant pandas are big stars at home, too
 &HT;    By Keith Graham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Chairman Mao and the giant panda.
</P>
<P>
   Both are icons of China. And it should come as no surprise that
the tourists from the hinterlands flocking into Beijing these days
pay tribute to both.
</P>
<P>
   Two stops are musts for Chinese tourists visiting their capital,
said Liu Yingling, a representative of the All China Journalists
Association.
</P>
<P>
   One is Tiananmen Square, where the visitors may see Mao's tomb
and will certainly pause to have their pictures taken before his
portrait looming over the massive plaza. In the West, the image
that persists of Tiananmen is tanks rolling over a brief flowering
of democratic protest in 1989. But for most Chinese visitors,
Tiananmen, for better or worse, remains the symbolic heart of their
nation. And Mao, though long dead, still casts a giant shadow.
</P>
<P>
   The second mandatory stop is the panda compound at the Beijing
Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   No giant portrait looms here. But if one did, it should perhaps
show Wang Wanmin.
</P>
<P>
   Wang knows little of power politics. But 22 years ago his
government assigned him to feed the pandas at the zoo, and he has
taken to the task with total devotion.
</P>
<P>
   On a breezy, sunny day, Wang was waiting near the zoo's front
gate to meet a visitor. He began to talk immediately about how he
has petted and cuddled his charges as babies, fed them milk when
their mothers couldn't and nursed them to health when they were
suffering.
</P>
<P>
   Caring for these creatures, who can grow to 350 pounds, is ``a
heavy responsibility,'' he said gravely.
</P>
<P>
   Americans may feel some attachment to their bald eagle. But the
Chinese are passionate about their pandas. And Wang is as
passionate as you are likely to meet.
</P>
<P>
   He was pleased _ but not at all surprised _ to hear that the two
pandas who arrived at Zoo Atlanta last November have become a huge
attraction, already seen by hundreds of thousands of zoo-goers.
</P>
<P>
   What's so special about these Chinese ambassadors? Wang thought
for a moment. They are rare and famous and ``their appearance is
special,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if the zookeeper had difficulty articulating his thoughts,
he made the depth of his feeling clear as he ambled through the
complex talking through a translator about each of the pandas he
and 14 other workers monitor around the clock. Wang, who wore
rubber boots, speckled khakis and a windbreaker with a panda image,
said the zoo has more than 10 pandas but some were at a breeding
farm and others were on loan to selected zoos.
</P>
<P>
   Stopping frequently, he launched into lengthy accounts of the
life stories of the five on display, their frightening moments and
especially their occasional triumphs in producing offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Yuan Yuan, he said, still has to drink milk at 8 months old, but
most of the pandas in his care eat bamboo for much of their waking
hours.
</P>
<P>
   Ying Ying has had 11 babies _ Wang recited their years of birth
_ and he flinched as he explained how part of her ear was bitten
off by a male panda.
</P>
<P>
   Le Le has had seven babies, and, according to Wang, gave birth
to the only surviving panda born in captivity in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'90s he and other workers nursed Ji Ni back to health
over a two-year period after a thoughtless visitor tossed bread and
fruit into her pen _ still in a plastic bag. ``I get very sad when
my pandas get hurt,'' Wang said.
</P>
<P>
   The zookeeper _ who had worked with hippopotamuses and horses
before coming to the panda house _ was an animal lover from
childhood. ``When I was young, I had birds, dogs, cats and
rabbits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even on his days off, he comes to the zoo. ``I cannot feel
at ease if I cannot see the pandas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He frets about the fate of the thousand or so pandas still left
in China's wild. Strict efforts are underway to preserve their
remaining habitat, but Wang confided, ``We are not too
optimistic.'' Not only are the numbers dwindling but the size is
growing smaller.
</P>
<P>
   The best hope may be teaching the roughly 200 pandas in
captivity to mate, and Wang, his brow furrowing, detailed the
efforts his zoo is making.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you cannot understand why, but it's very hard,'' he
said. ``We might think that the male is really good looking, but
she won't like him.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he is very protective of the animals and keeps a wary eye
on anyone who throws stones when the pandas are outside or thumps
on the glass of their interior cages, he does not romanticize them.
</P>
<P>
   They can be fierce. ``They look very sweet, but they can lose
their temper,'' Wang said. And the people who feed them have been
hurt many times. Wang himself has merely been scratched. But he
warned that pandas' personalities are ``difficult to predict. . . .
They are more dangerous than tigers or lions.''
</P>
<P>
   As a panda waddled in his direction, Wang turned and shouted for
her to sit. He has taught others to circle before being fed, to
somersault and to wave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The panda is quite clever,'' he said. ``A grown-up panda is
just like a 3- to 4-year-old child.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, Kang Zitong, 3 1/2 years old and peering
through a fence nearby, was at just the right age to relate to the
lumbering creatures. She had come from Xi'an, home of China's
famous terra-cotta warriors, with her parents. And she appeared
delighted just to watch the bulky but nimble animals scratch
themselves and roll in the dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the pandas is a highlight for anyone who comes to the
Beijing Zoo, said her father, an electrical plant worker named Kang
Tao.
</P>
<P>
   Even far away in Washington, it seemed the powerful appeal of
the panda could be felt this week. Opponents of a bill to normalize
trade relations with China accused supporters of being ``panda
huggers.'' Meanwhile, officials at the National Zoo were putting
final touches on a trade deal of their own with China. The last of
the zoo's pandas died last year, leaving Atlanta and San Diego as
the only American facilities to showcase them. But, in an agreement
announced Sunday, Chinese pandas will soon return, pleasing
zoo-goers in America's capital as much as they do in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   As national symbols go, China could do worse.
</P>
<P>
   Pandas ``are a treasure of the state,'' mused Gu Yankui, a
retired teacher of Chinese literature strolling the zoo grounds
with his wife. ``Pandas are liked all over the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
