<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-MERGER-FLIERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREQUENT FLIERS WILL BE BIG WINNERS IF UNITED, US AIRWAYS MERGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Sidebar with AIR-MERGER) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL    
 c .2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the proposal by the UAL Corp. to buy US Airways clears
government and shareholder hurdles, members of the US Airways
frequent-flier program could find themselves in the unaccustomed
position of winners.
</P>
<P>
   Even though much of the fine print has not been made public,
Kurt Ebenhoch, a spokesman for United Airlines, which is owned by
UAL, said Wednesday, ``By the time this deal is consummated next
year, our two airlines will be one and US Airways frequent-flier
members will become United Mileage Plus members.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference,'' he said, ``is that US Airways members will
then have the opportunity to accrue miles faster, to redeem them
for more places and to earn flights with our 22 airline partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those partners are the 11 members of the Star Alliance,
comprising United as well as airlines from Austria, Australia,
Brazil, Canada, Germany, Japan, New Zealand, Scandinavia, Singapore
and Thailand _ in short, much of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, US Airway's alliance with American Airlines, which
includes honoring each other's frequent-flier programs, remains in
force. ``Until the acquisition takes place,'' said David
Castelveter, a US Airways spokesman, ``it's business as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Although United promises to freeze some domestic fares for two
years after the acquisition, except for increases to pay for fuel
costs and inflation, some industry experts think the deal will
ultimately lead to higher prices for passengers, especially in the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the merger will be a good one,'' said Terry Trippler,
the airline writer for 1Travel.com. ``But if a lessening of
competition does not result in higher prices, it will be the first
time in history.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even outsiders agree that US Airways' frequent-flier
passengers stand to benefit by gaining access to more flights and
more destinations. ``Except for Southwest, US Airways is the only
one of the major airlines without flights to Hawaii, which is by
far the preferred destination of most frequent fliers,'' said Randy
Peterson, the editor and publisher of Inside Flier magazine. United
has daily flights to Hawaii from Chicago, San Francisco and Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``While US Airways' frequent-flier program has always been a
competent follower,'' Peterson said, ``it has never been a leader.
Now it will be aligned with a leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Trippler added that United's extensive routes to Asia and the
Pacific and South America will also be a big plus for US Airways
frequent-flier members, as will United's many more flights to
cities in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, United has far fewer flights to Florida than does US
Airways, so the acquisition is likely to give United's Mileage Plus
passengers a wider choice of flights and destinations to that
state. But Peterson and Trippler pointed out that frequent-flier
``reward'' flights to Hawaii are often very difficult to get and
Florida destinations are scarce much of the year.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways has hubs in Philadelphia, Pittsburgh, Baltimore and
Charlotte, N.C., while United hubs are in Chicago, Denver, Los
Angeles and San Francisco and at Dulles International Airport in
Washington. United has already said that it will increase flights
from Pittsburgh and possibly Philadelphia and Charlotte.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, passengers to and from Washington are likely to
benefit if DC Air _ the airline start-up that is expected to be
owned by BET Holdings II, the parent company of the Black
Entertainment Network _ becomes a low-fare carrier. BET's owner,
Robert Jackson, has been a member of the US Airways board since
1998. The airline, which will operate from Ronald Reagan National
Airport in Washington, will fill the void created by United's plan
to sell its slots and other operations there to satisfy regulators.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
