<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I Gave Dating a Chance'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Jeramy Clark &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (WaterBrook Press, $9.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No, Jeramy Clark isn't ``reeaally'' the Drill Sergeant of Love.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the not-quite-29-year-old author of ``I Gave Dating a
Chance'' says, ``I wholeheartedly believe Christians need to clean
up their dating act.'' He argues that Christians have no business
dating unbelievers _ not even casually. But despite what you hear
in some church circles, ``I don't believe you have to reject dating
to be godly in your relationships.''
</P>
<P>
   The drill from this Colorado youth minister: Get your spiritual
house in order before you start going out; push yourself to
maintain sexual purity and modesty (specific suggestions are
included); make yourself accountable to other believers for your
thoughts and behavior (a big one for Clark).
</P>
<P>
   Some of Clark's arguments _ particularly his stress on
``emotional boundaries'' in singles' relationships _ merit caution.
The book addresses everyone from young teens to young adults but
seems geared more for the older half of that range. ``I Gave Dating
a Chance'' may not be the final word, but it's a word worth
considering. &QL; 
_ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Purpose by Design'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fred Hammond &AMP; Radical for Christ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zomba Records &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amazing what a little editing can do.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1998, when last we heard from Detroit's Fred
Hammond, the burly, rich-voiced
singer/songwriter/multiinstrumentalist, he and his group were
releasing the two-CD ``(Pages of Life) Chapters I &AMP; II.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there were some commendable songs, the format made
``Pages'' feel bloated: The first CD was 16 originals cut in the
studio; the second was 13 live cuts, many of them songs that were
on the first CD. Only this time, the songs were stretched, made far
too long. It was overkill, plain and simple.
</P>
<P>
   I'm happy to report that ``Purpose by Design'' _ currently No. 3
on the national gospel charts after several weeks at No. 1 _ is a
shorter and more effective affair: 13 songs, recorded either in a
Detroit studio or live in Houston, and abrim with songs that
effortlessly build on Hammond's ability to fuse funk, gospel and
pop. Hammond can still be faulted for turning what would have been
a good 3 1/2-minute song into a not-so-good five-, six- or
seven-minute song, but he does that far less often here.
</P>
<P>
   Vigorously uptempo funk numbers such as the opening ``I Want My
Destiny'' are nicely balanced with ballads: The Stevie Wonderish
``Give Me a Clean Heart'' is a light confection built on electric
piano and acoustic guitar, and the live ballad ``Thank You Lord
(For Being There for Me)'' builds to a satisfying climax. A cover
of Sam Cooke's ``Jesus Be a Fence Around Me'' follows, and it's the
CD's high point: old-school gospel with a bright, modern sheen and
the momentum of a freight train.
</P>
<P>
   Hammond &AMP; Radical for Christ are supporting ``Purpose'' with a
summer tour. With him is John P. Kee, the North Carolina native who
went from a life of crime to being saved at a revival meeting to
forging one of the biggest careers in modern gospel with CDs such
as ``We Walk by Faith.'' &QL; 
_ Reviewed by Dave Ferman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
