NYT-05-24-00 2022EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0341 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4841 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-ASSESS-NYT     05-24 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: BUSH PATTERN ON THE ISSUES IS BROAD IDEAS WITH FEW
DETAILS
</HEADLINE>
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With his recent speeches on Social Security and
nuclear weapons defenses, Gov. George W. Bush has established a
pattern: He puts forward broad ideas with great appeal to the
Republican base and then leaves the details to be filled in later
should he be elected.
</P>
<P>
   In rapid succession, Bush pledged to introduce individual
investment accounts into Social Security but left out fundamental
details like what portion of the payroll tax he would devote to
them. And similarly this week, he opened the door to unilateral
nuclear weapons reductions coupled with a missile defense system
that would protect all 50 states and many of America's allies.
</P>
<P>
   But once again he included no specifics _ or any notion of what
it would cost.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides and supporters argue that on certain kinds of
issues this is the most effective way to lead, that locking into
particulars now ensures failure later. Yet it is also the case that
Bush's style has some other effects: it allows him to look like a
leader while making it much more difficult for his opponents to get
a handhold to grapple with him and his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore is the master of picking apart the
details of a proposal. Just remember what he did to former Sen.
Bill Bradley's health care plan in the Democratic primaries.
</P>
<P>
   But in the Social Security debate he has been left assailing
Bush's ``secret plan'' and trying to fill in the details for his
Republican opponent, as he did on Wednesday in an interview on
National Public Radio. Gore said that the transition to individual
accounts would inevitably also entail ``raising the retirement age
or cutting benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Still Douglas Hattaway, a Gore spokesman, acknowledged that it
was harder to have a real debate on the issues, when Bush ``refuses
to say what he really intends to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The move toward individual investment retirement accounts and
the idea of a missile defense shield have long been dear to
Republicans and some of their constituencies. It was Ronald Reagan,
after all, who first called for a Strategic Defense Initiative in
1983.
</P>
<P>
   But these ideas have foundered in the past, not just because of
partisan strife, but because of details. Missile defense technology
is still largely unproven. The Pentagon suffered a serious setback
in January when a missile fired from the Marshall Islands failed to
hit a mock warhead fired from a California air base.
</P>
<P>
   And the costs are high.
</P>
<P>
   The limited missile defense system under development, which
envisions bases in Alaska with 100 interceptor missiles, has been
estimated by the Congressional Budget Office to cost $60 billion. A
broader system, which Bush is considering, might cost $116 billion
or more.
</P>
<P>
   On Social Security, while many congressional plans contain some
elements of individual accounts like those proposed by Bush, the
details have been problematic. Several plans contain painful
medicine like benefit cuts, lower cost-of-living increases or an
increase in the retirement age.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, conservative Republicans found that the only way to
create such accounts and still keep Social Security solvent was to
require people to hand their accounts back to the government when
they retired and then receive a fixed annual annuity.
</P>
<P>
   That is hardly what Bush has been describing when he says his
plan will allow Americans to build wealth that they can then pass
on to their children.
</P>
<P>
   Should voters know the full costs and benefits of Bush's ideas?
Anita Dunn, who was Bradley's communications director, argues that
they should _ even if such details could make the plans a fat
target in the way Bradley's health care proposal became.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that we failed to effectively defend a
well-thought-out, comprehensive plan, does not mean that's not the
right way to go,'' Dunn said. ``It just means you should
aggressively defend your plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides and some political scientists counter that there
are some issues on which too much detail is counterproductive to
governing.
</P>
<P>
   And they point to the fate of another doomed health care plan:
the one championed by Hillary Rodham Clinton. ``Anybody who
announces something initially and provides enormously great detail
runs a terrible risk of having it fall because of particular flaws
rather than the overall genius of the idea,'' said Ross Baker, a
professor of political science at Rutgers University.
</P>
<P>
   By leaving out the details of his Social Security plan, Bush
aides say that the governor will allow Congress to help shape the
plan and have pride of authorship. They note that this is how the
governor operated in Texas, presenting basic concepts and allowing
the Legislature to shape the details.
</P>
<P>
   And on nuclear deterrence, they say, detail must be left to the
military.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be wrong for a politician to arbitrarily set the
number of missiles needed to defend the nation,'' said Ari
Fleischer, a spokesman for Bush. ``That's exactly why you have a
Pentagon.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Bush eventually have to provide more detail on these issues
as November nears? Some supporters of Bush say no, that what voters
want now _ particularly independent voters _ is a sign that a
presidential candidate will put forward ideas that may break the
gridlock in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But others say he will be forced to fill in more particulars as
time goes on or pay a price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The initial excitement in getting a new idea out is not a
measure of where the idea ends up,'' Dunn said, speaking from
Bradley's primary experience. ``It is early. He hasn't had to
debate Gore. And he hasn't been challenged.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2023EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
