<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4842 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JOHNSON-     05-24 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JOHNSON-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURY HAS ALTERED LINEBACKER'S OUTLOOK 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a conflicted corner of Ted Johnson's mind, he thought maybe
this injury thing would ruin his blossoming football career.
Johnson was on his way to a Pro Bowl. A ferocious middle linebacker
for the New England Patriots, he hadn't got there yet, but he'd be
there soon.
</P>
<P>
   But after tearing both biceps tendons, and enduring each arduous
rehabilitation, he began thinking of second careers.
</P>
<P>
   He helped his parents open an upscale restaurant next door to
the barbecue joint they already owned in a small Houston suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that would be it. Proprietor: Ted Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he'd be an in-studio TV football analyst after earning
rave reviews for the ESPN gigs he did while injured.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, that would it. Football analyst: Ted Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   What he was certain about in the less-confused segment of his
mind was that he never wanted ``quitter'' attached to his name. As
tough as it was to come back and as many post-football thoughts as
he had, being at peace with himself would have been difficult had
he not made it back to the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny. You start to explore those ideas in crazy ways,''
said Johnson during a break in his workouts at Foxboro Stadium
recently. ``Even though football is what I know, I had to take a
step back and be a realist for a minute. What if I can't make it
back? For me to stand and watch . . . it was difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played this game all my life, but it was a mental strain.
It's like the movie `Groundhog Day.' I feel like Bill Murray
sometimes where I was getting up and doing the same thing and
seeing no progress and seeing the same thing over and over again.
With me, I need to get up and have a purpose every day. I wasn't
contributing. I wasn't helping out. It's difficult for a guy who's
always enjoyed what I do. To not be able to do it . . . it got
tiresome.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aching to play
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has a purpose now, learning Bill Belichick's 3-4 defense
while trying to forget Pete Carroll's defense. Johnson said the
left biceps tendon, the one he ripped Aug. 9 during an intrasquad
scrimmage is ``90 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of the woods? Johnson knows that he'll never be that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no guarantees that it won't happen again,'' said
Johnson, who says he puts the possibility of reinjury out of his
mind when he's on the field. ``I've let it go, those thoughts of,
`What if it happens again?' Those things are out of my control. It
has made me aware of my body more. What I eat, how I sleep, and how
I work it. I take care of my body a lot more now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to back off the mentality of just lifting weights
all the time. I don't think I overtrained as some people claim, but
I don't think I was smart about it. I was taking my flexibility for
granted. I'm not a flexible guy and never have been, but it had
never been a problem. This injury shed some light on that. So now,
I stretch more, I do yoga, I see a massage therapist who works on
deep tissues. I'm always trying to get an edge medically with the
joints or whatever. I'm taking stuff geriatrics take for arthritis.
I'll do whatever I have to do to help prevent what I've been
through. But guarantees? Naw.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing can prevent what happened in Pittsburgh Dec. 6, 1998,
when Jerome Bettis steamrolled through the middle of the field and
into the end zone, leaving Johnson's right arm gimpy and lifeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bettis had a full head of steam and Lawyer (Milloy) hit me
from behind as Bettis was running,'' said Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't play in another regular-season game for 365 days,
until Dec. 5, 1999, against Dallas. Because after the
rehabilitation came the biceps injury, suffered when he reached
back to bring down teammate Kevin Faulk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin came up on me on another off-tackle play,'' he said. ``I
tend to dive for the ballcarrier if I'm out of position. You have
to make sure you're in better position. It was just me trying to
make a play, trying to trip a guy up. You just react. Your limbs
are everywhere. You just react. I don't have time to think, `I
should pull my arm back, because I don't want to get hurt.' You
don't have that kind of time.''
</P>
<P>
   That means when the situation arises, his instincts will take
over again. He will do what made him a terrific player: He will
reach out and try to make the play.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned last season for the last five games, his
friends, like former Patriot linebacker Todd Collins, were advising
against it. They thought he was jeopardizing his career.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson played with a brace that prevented him from reaching
back. It also prevented him from tackling well, though he amassed
59 tackles in five games and had two sacks in the season finale
against Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   He's tossed the braces. He will play this season like Ted
Johnson. All or nothing. It was a sense of reckless abandon that
made him one of the best run-stoppers in the league. There will be
no compromising that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played at about 60-70 percent late last year,'' said
Johnson. ``It was good enough to play. I had a brace and I was
assured it would prevent it from happening again. I didn't want to
go out there and be half-speed either, but I got through the year
as tough as that was, with no highlight reels. I just got through
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was publicly nudged to come back quickly by Carroll. But
Johnson, after a long talk with Carroll, came to understand the
former coach wasn't trying to jeopardize his well-being, but just
trying to be optimistic for the media.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson remembers having arguments with trainer Ron O'Neil, who
was being cautious, over when he would get to play. Johnson said he
never felt pressure from the organization, but he did feel pressure
because of the five-year, $25 million contract and the $8 million
signing bonus he didn't feel he was earning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be lying if I said the money didn't affect me,'' said
Johnson biting his lower lip. ``You feel guilty. People try to
rationalize it by saying if I got hurt at my job I'd be paid
workman's comp, but it was practice . . . it wasn't even a game. I
felt a tremendous amount of guilt. I think its human nature to
bring those pressures on yourself and I did. Then someone said to
me that the reason I got the money is because of what I was doing
on the field. And that nobody expects more than what you're doing.
It put it into perspective for me. I should just be the same guy. I
don't think anyone questioned that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
