<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4843 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JOHNSON-     05-24 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-JOHNSON-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 (Undated): ...questioned that.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A stickler for structure and routine, Johnson was thrown off. He
was irritable. He had difficulty feeling he was a part of the team,
despite Carroll telling him he was contributing by helping rookie
Andy Katzenmoyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just lost my focus,'' said Johnson. ``I'm a routine guy and
I wasn't held to that structure. I had an edge to me. I had a good
camp and then . . . I had some self-pity parties. I should have
been bigger than that and realized that things happen that are out
of your hands. I think I learned my lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of having surgeries. I've had four in the past two
years and that's enough. It's taken its toll. You can't do the
things you want to do. I took my health for granted, but now I
don't anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did he take the game for granted. When he wasn't on the
field, he was working on the intagibles. Coaches often say that
players learn from stepping off the field and watching. Johnson
thinks that happened. There were good things that came out of it,
but they never overshadowed the bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it did was reinforce how much I do enjoy this job and what
it provides for me,'' he said. ``To be honest with you, it's very
difficult to stay in the game when you're not in the game plan.
What I did do was get a great idea from an old coach of mine and
that was to go over all the film of my career, my second year and
up, watch every play. The good plays I marked and put them on a
highlight reel. I learned a lot doing that. I have glaring
weaknesses and glaring strengths. And I learned how to avoid the
things that get me in trouble on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   He shouted words of encouragement to Katzenmoyer and the other
linebackers, but he remembers feeling strange because ``when you're
on the sideline, everything is so obvious. It's easy to be critical
from the sideline,'' he said. ``But when you're out there, you have
all of those external forces going on. There are so many things
going on on the field that keeping your focus is so important. I'd
be yelling, do this and do that and why didn't you make that play?
I forgot, but I remembered it quickly when I got back out there,
how much more faster the game is and you have to make decisions
almost instantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I benefited from was I studied the offenses more,
their tendencies in certain situations. When you're a young player,
you tend to just focus on what your assignment is. But as you grow,
there's more to understanding what's going on on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   But five years have already ticked off his career. He enters the
season with a huge salary cap number that will rise to more than $7
million in 2001. Those numbers are attached to impact players,
which Johnson was. Now he must prove he is that again.
</P>
<P>
   He looks at his career as fragmented. ````My rookie year is my
rookie year. In my second year, I was still so young and it was the
first year I was calling the defenses, so that was unsettling,'' he
said. ``In my third year, we switch coaches (from Bill Parcells to
Carroll). so I have to learn a new defense. I've never been to the
point where I feel completely comfortable with the defense and I'm
completly healthy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year I want more field presence. The more comfortable I
am, the more field presence I'll have. When I came back last year,
it was like I was starting two-a-days again. I was still trying to
figure it out. The first game back was so crazy, I was just hoping
I was lined up right. We got through that game. I feel like I
should have a lot more to show for five years than I do now. That's
just my mindset.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New and improved
</P>
<P>
   Almost healthy again, Johnson faces another coaching change.
When Belichick was the assistant head coach in charge of the
secondary under Parcells in 1996, Johnson said he spoke to him
``five or six times, tops.'' Two months into Belichick's reign,
Johnson said he's had two conversations with Belichick, all
coach-player matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been like the guy in the `Wizard of Oz' behind the
curtain. I haven't seen him. Honestly. The guy behind the curtain
struck fear in a lot of people,'' he said. ``Maybe he doesn't want
to make himself that accessible.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson sees signs of a significant change for the better, where
the coaches coach and the players play. Little intermingling. Short
on small talk, but big on football.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this team, making a change was a good call. We're a very
young team,'' he said. ``We have Willie (McGinest), Drew (Bledsoe),
Chris (Slade), Larry (Whigham), guys who have six or seven years
logged in. But this team isn't full of 10-12 year vets. Discipline,
structure and accountability work for this team. I've seen it
before. That's what we're going to get.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different from Parcells. There's only one Parcells. You
can try to emulate him, maybe. Belichick has his own way of doing
it that can work. I'm not guaranteeing a divisional championship,
but I guarantee we'll be a more exciting team to watch. I hope our
record shows that. I think we'll be more disciplined. You'll see it
and feel it. I hope it is. If not this year than over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this league, if you don't have the three things I
mentioned, you're in trouble because the players will let you down.
The head coach sets the tone. He really does. He can take us in
what ever direction he wants to take us and we'll follow him.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Belichick gets a certain amount of respect because
he was Parcells's right-hand man. He said he thinks some players
will test Belichick and ``they'll see what they can get away with
and how he responds.''
</P>
<P>
   What Johnson also likes is the shift to the 3-4 defense, which
he played at the University of Colorado and as a young Patriot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a welcome relief for me. It's one-on-one,'' he said. ``In
a 4-3, you're in gaps and slanting and it's more double-teams. This
is one-on-one. It's lets see whose stronger and tougher. It's the
game in the purest form. You bring back the old principles instead
of trying to trick them by pulling their nose tackle off and
sending him 15 yards down the field or bringing the safety in. You
just get to the point where you hurt yourself rather than help
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wait and see
</P>
<P>
   Johnson lived as a nomad in the offseason, bouncing from friend
to friend, spending a few days at his base in Houston before
skiing, scuba diving, water skiing, golfing, and sightseeing. A
trip to Australia was canceled when ``our head coach called a March
15 mandatory meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   The offseason was spent getting his mind and body back to what
they used to be, trying to find the old Ted Johnson, but really
wanting to find the new and improved one.
</P>
<P>
   With a smile returning to his face and a new bounce to his step,
he seemed to find the one who was more understanding. The one who
didn't have to apologize for his injuries. The one who was more
focused and more determined. And that the TV and the restaurant
will have to wait.
</P>
</TEXT>
