<HEADER>
A4846 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-WITNESS-PROTECTION     05-24 1458
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WITNESS-PROTECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLING RENEWS DEBATE ON PROTECTING WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two days after a 15-year-old Providence girl was
fatally shot before she could testify in a murder trial,
Massachusetts legislators quietly refused to create a statewide
witness-protection program.
</P>
<P>
   The decision Tuesday night by the state Senate to study, rather
than provide $100,000 to fund, the long-pending proposal drew
little notice in the crush of votes on the state budget.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say the move, particularly in light of Jennifer
Rivera's death, revealed a longstanding failure by Massachusetts
and most other states to adequately protect crime victims and
bystanders who risk retribution by pointing a finger in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to ignore the impact of participating in criminal
cases and the dangers people face. We expect that people will see
this as a civic duty, but we don't help them fulfill it,'' said
Susan Herman, executive director of the National Center for Victims
of Crime in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As the search continued for Rivera's killer, a dispute raged
over whether police ignored her pleas for help, as her family
claims, or she rebuffed their repeated offers of protection, as
police maintain. As a result, even before police determine whether
Rivera was killed to keep her silent, her murder has put the
spotlight on local witness protection efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the vaunted federal Witness Protection Program that has
turned more than 7,000 ex-Mafia killers and other criminals into
protected courtroom songbirds with new identities, state and local
programs focus mainly on law-abiding citizens whose only connection
to crime is their proximity to its occurrence. Rarely do
non-criminal witnesses undergo identity changes.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen states have enacted programs to help such people,
authorities said, often after highly publicized cases involving the
deaths of witnesses. Most such programs aim to to relieve the
burden on local police and prosecutors _ and increase the
likelihood of protection _ by making funds available for temporary
or permanent relocation.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's program, for instance, was enacted last July, six
months after the murders of 8-year-old Leroy ``B.J.'' Brown Jr. and
his mother, Karen Clarke, of Bridgeport. They were allegedly killed
on orders from a man who feared their testimony in a murder case.
</P>
<P>
   Considered a national model, Connecticut's program requires the
chief state's attorney to provide protection for high-risk
witnesses and makes it easier to obtain restraining orders or
revoke bail if authorities perceive a risk to witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, in light of the dispute in the Rivera case, the
Connecticut law also requires the state to decide within three days
whether to overturn a parent's decision to reject protection for a
minor. Upon enacting the law, Governor John G. Rowland said cost
would be no object in fulfilling the state's promise to ``do
whatever is necessary'' to protect witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   California, meanwhile, in 1998 authorized $3 million in the
first year of its program. At the same time, the state sought to
decrease financial liability that might accompany creation of such
a system. Fearful of lawsuits in cases where protection is declined
and someone gets hurt, the law provides immunity to public
officials for decisions about witness protection.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts remains among the majority of states that have yet
to enact a comprehensive witness protection program, relying
instead on individual district attorneys and local police officials
to assess dangers and pay for protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our worst nightmare in the area of law enforcement,
recognizing the vulnerability of witnesses in violent cases we're
prosecuting,'' said Plymouth District Attorney Michael J. Sullivan,
who has studied the issue for state prosecutors. ``You really have
to applaud the courage of the ordinary person to go forward and
offer testimony to see justice served.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, however, say bravery should be irrelevant, and
prosecutors should be given more resources to protect witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should not be seen as a matter of special courage or
heroism that one is cooperating with police. Rather, it should be
seen as a routine public service for which one is not going to be
put in any jeopardy,'' said Eric E. Sterling, president of the
Criminal Justice Policy Foundation, a Washington think tank funded
by conservative groups.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt to create a Massachusetts program was sidetracked
despite the recommendation of the Criminal Justice Committee. The
Senate moved instead to create a special commission to study the
idea, focusing on the potential cost and how the funds would be
administered.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of a study commission reflected a concern among
Massachusetts district attorneys, who worried that the funds would
come from their budgets and recoiled at the proposal's plan to have
the attorney general supervise their decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's sponsor, Senator Cynthia S. Creem, a Newton Democrat
who is chairwoman of the Criminal Justice Committee, said she
understood those concerns but was disappointed nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like a no-brainer that this has to happen,'' said
Creem, who reduced her original $250,000 budget request to $100,000
in a fruitless attempt to win last-minute passage.
</P>
<P>
   While the Legislature studies the issue, time has run out for
Donna Bryant of Roxbury, whose family has been repeatedly
threatened since her 14-year-old son testified in an armed robbery
case. She said in an interview that she is moving her four children
out of state to avoid further incidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's there to help,'' she said. ``Nobody's trying to make
sure your life isn't in danger. When I heard about that girl
(Rivera) this  &UR; morning  &LR; I was so upset. I thought that could be me
or my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk District Attorney Ralph C. Martin II defended his
office's response to Bryant's fears. He said the family declined a
transfer to a different Boston housing project.
</P>
<P>
   On the larger issue, Martin said prosecutors are stymied by some
witnesses' refusal to accept protection, as well as by the
difficulty of predicting witness attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great if someone could come up with a formula for
how to assess the appropriate level of risk, but hell, even the CIA
couldn't do it,'' Martin said. He noted that his own office never
imagined that gang member Jeffrey Bly would kill Assistant District
Attorney Paul McLaughlin in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said his office spends at least $50,000 a year on witness
protection, mostly to relocate witnesses until after they testify,
when the risk is perceived to have diminished.
</P>
<P>
   There are no state or national statistics, but a 1996 federal
study found that law officers in eight urban areas reported that
violent acts of witness intimidation occur on a daily or weekly
basis. The study by the National Institute of Justice, the research
arm of the Justice Department, found that 81 percent of prosecutors
in the nation's largest jurisdictions said witness intimidation
inhibited prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   The study's author, Massachusetts criminologist Kerry Murphy
Healey, said the question of which witnesses receive protection has
been largely unexplored. She said a witness in a domestic violence
case is less likely to get help, in part because prosecutors are
more focused on winning higher profile cases such as homicides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decisions about who receives protection are based on the
severity of the crime witnessed, not on the severity of the danger
to which the person is likely to be subject,'' Healey said.
</P>
<P>
   To Herman, the executive director of the National Center for
Victims of Crime, the answer is improving state and local programs
so they provide more aggressive intervention and more services for
protected witnesses and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victims and witnesses should be able to make informed choices
about whether to participate, but they need help predicting,
understanding what the risks are, and they need to understand what
they can do and what the police and district attorneys are really
offering them,'' Herman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Victims and witnesses are much more than pieces of evidence,''
she said. ``In some states, and in some cities, they are getting a
lot of help. In most they are not.''
</P>
<P>
   The risk of not improving protections will be an increasing
number of people who refuse to testify, Herman said. Donna Bryant,
for one, has reconsidered her son's cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd want him to testify, but I probably wouldn't let him
now,'' she said. ``It's been too hard for me and my family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
