<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ramsey-hired lie detector backs claims couple didn't kill child
 &HT;    By Craig Schneider
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ John and Patsy Ramsey unveiled the results of a
lie-detector test Wednesday that concluded they did not kill their
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The lie-detector test, administered by a firm hired by the
Ramseys, also determined the couple were telling the truth when
they disavowed any knowledge of the killer, and when Patsy Ramsey
denied writing the ransom note in the 1996 slaying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on extensive polygraph examinations, neither John nor
Patsy Ramsey were attempting deception when they gave the indicated
answers,'' said polygraph examiner Edward Gelb, a past president of
the American Polygraph Association who has conducted more than
30,000 polygraph tests.
</P>
<P>
   But in Boulder, Colo., Police Chief Mark Beckner all but
discounted the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we would be foolish to take it very seriously,'' said
Beckner, who has insisted that the FBI administer the test to the
Ramseys. ``How seriously can you take information presented by
their own expert.''
</P>
<P>
   During a press conference in Atlanta, Patsy Ramsey said she
hoped the police would heed the results and jump-start the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish they would open their minds and their hearts and know
that we did not kill our daughter,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But John Ramsey reiterated his bitterness toward the Boulder
police. The couple have not been charged but remain under
suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not one ounce of trust in the Boulder police,'' said
John Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   During media appearances following the release of their recent
book, the Ramseys expressed a willingness to undergo a lie-detector
test. But they maintain the FBI's objectivity has been compromised
since the agency has assisted Boulder police during the probe.
</P>
<P>
   John Ramsey bristled when a reporter suggested that the FBI test
might be tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked me, `Did you kill your daughter?' What's next, a
bed of coals?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
