<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAL-RESEARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON DOCTOR EXPECTED TO HEAD WATCHDOG AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Boston anesthesiologist, Dr. Greg Koski of Massachusetts
General Hospital, is in line to head a new federal watchdog agency
to protect those who volunteer for medical research, capping a year
of mounting pressure on the government to improve policing human
experiments.
</P>
<P>
   But already there is skepticism about whether the new office
_elevated from the National Institutes of Health to the office of
Secretary of Health and Human Services Donna Shalala _ will really
be tougher on researchers and their institutions than the one it is
replacing.
</P>
<P>
   Koski, who is director of human research at Partners Healthcare,
is expected to be named shortly to the new Office of Human Research
Protection, which will have authority over all human trials funded
by the NIH and overseen by the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is heralding the new office, which
would be based in Washington, as a major strengthening of federal
oversight of human research, an assertion with which Koski agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major, major move,'' said the Harvard physician, who
oversees about 2,600 human studies at Mass. General, Brigham and
Women's Hospital, and affiliated institutions. ``It's an indication
of the importance that is attached to ensuring the protection of
everyone participating in a human study.''
</P>
<P>
   Koski acknowledged he is a top candidate for director of the
Office of Human Research Protection but declined to confirm the
appointment. A spokesman for Shalala referred inquiries to the NIH,
where a spokesman said, ``No appointment has been made yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Previously the federal government's main watchdog agency, the
Office for Protection from Research Risks, oversaw only research
funded by the NIH. A federal advisory panel last year recommended
that the job of protecting human research subjects be removed from
the funding agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``They considered that unseemly at best,'' Koski said.
</P>
<P>
   However, some government insiders, as well as nongovernment
specialists in research ethics, said the new office is
window-dressing to mask the Clinton administration's intent to back
off from strong sanctions of research institutions caught violating
human studies regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In some observers' views, the new office is intended to de-fang
the NIH Office for Protection from Research Risks, which alarmed
major academic research institutions by suspending all federal
funding for human research last year at Duke University, Virginia
Commonwealth University, West Los Angeles Veterans Administration
Medical Center, the University of Alabama at Birmingham, and other
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The academic research establishment was caught entirely
unawares and really felt blindsided'' by those actions, said one
ethicist, who asked not to be identified. ``No one had ever
suggested that they could get in trouble for violating human
research regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   The director of the NIH office, Gary B. Ellis, said he has been
``quashed'' because he and his staff have been ``too active in
protecting human subjects.'' Federal officials reportedly have
rebuffed Ellis's offer to join the new agency.
</P>
<P>
   Koski disagreed with those who say the Clinton administration
wants to relax enforcement of human protection guidelines. He cited
Shalala's proposal on Tuesday for legislation permitting officials
to fine institutions up to $1 million and individual researchers up
to $250,000 for violating human studies rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secretary made it very clear that her intention is to
strengthen the process for protection of human subjects and to
rebuild the confidence of the American people,'' Koski said.
</P>
<P>
   Even some who have been highly critical of the government's
laxness in policing human research praised the decision to elevate
this function to the secretary's office and give the new office
clear authority over human trials conducted by pharmaceutical
companies under the auspices of the FDA, as well as NIH-funded
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``That makes absolute sense,'' said Arthur Caplan, director of
the Center for Bioethics at the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
