<HEADER>
A4853 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-COLUMN0525-COX     05-24 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flag flap can't be folded up, put away
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Governors don't usually go live on statewide
television to sign a bill, much less one that has left as many
sides unhappy as the Confederate flag compromise legislation that
Gov. Jim Hodges signed Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Most bill-signings are staged to call attention to an issue.
This one was handled in a special way in an earnest, at times even
plaintive, attempt to put this thorny issue to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we bring this debate to an honorable end,'' Hodges
said.
</P>
<P>
   Three times in the course of a five-minute address, the South
Carolina governor repeated the same point, as if to invest the
stroke of his pen with a power no politician attempting to work out
a compromise has managed to attain.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate prospects for Hodges achieving his wish don't look
great.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the legislation that will move the flag from the
state Capitol dome in Columbia to another location on the Capitol
grounds have initiated a ``No votes for turncoats'' campaign to
punish those who voted for the bill. NAACP officials, unsatisfied
with the alternate flag location, have vowed to continue the
economic boycott that forced the state legislature to take action
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   If there's any real hope this compromise will bring an end to
the debate, it rests on the exhaustion of most of those who place
themselves somewhere in the middle on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that it does (settle the issue). My hope is that
it does. Then they (the NAACP) can turn their attention to
Georgia,'' said Greenville Mayor Knox White.
</P>
<P>
   Greenville, the bustling and newly cosmopolitian Upcountry
business and manufacturing center, has played a key role in the
compromise. Hodges, a Democrat, credited Greenville Republican
David Wilkins, the House speaker, with a key role in working out
the compromise that finally passed both legislative chambers with
support from both parties.
</P>
<P>
   But another Greenville Republican, Sen. David Thomas, expressed
doubts the compromise will hold.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas had a proposal, supported by the Greenville Chamber of
Commerce, that would have moved the flag to a location on the west
side of the Capitol, on the site of the old statehouse that was
burned by Sherman's army in the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   While he feels the NAACP erred in not offering more positive
suggestions for a solution, Thomas said the organization's
opposition to the present compromise is consistent with the
position it has held all along.
</P>
<P>
   Although he identifies himself with the ``heritage'' movement to
protect the flag, Thomas said the compromise location, at the
Confederate memorial at the front of the Capitol, is arguably a
more prominent spot than the top of the dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to achieve some balance with this thing,
you've got to get it out of people's faces,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   Out of people's faces, and back into the history books. That's
what a lot, probably most, South Carolinians would like to see
happen with this issue. Time will tell if they get their wish.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
