r s BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-T     05-24 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-AVALANCHE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' WANT TO WIN GAME 6, NIX GAME 7
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ The Western Conference Finals has reached a point at
which everything that doesn't ache throbs.
</P>
<P>
   Every Stars and Avalanche player has fatigued legs and bruised
bodies that can't seem to take another slash, check or double
shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``You reach a stage as a performer in these type of series where
the mind takes over the body. I think both teams are at that stage
now,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``That means that your body
can endure anything that your mind sets it out to do.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Stars have set out to do is eliminate the Colorado
Avalanche in Game 6, which begins at 7 tonight in Denver. Don't
give the Avs a sliver of hope. Don't let them think for a second
they can come back from a 3-2 series deficit and win. Don't let the
series go to a Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to a Game 7, and you don't know what can happen,''
Stars center Mike Modano said. ``You start to get bad bounces and
bad breaks that can happen. We've always been good at realizing
when you have them down, keep them down and not let anybody up and
give them a second day.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, whether the Avalanche is exactly ``down'' is up for
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Many, including the ESPN folks who did the broadcast Tuesday
night, say the Avs have outplayed the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. Do we have them down?'' Stars winger Scott
Thornton asked. ``I don't think these guys are down yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avs' players certainly don't talk as if they are. They talk
like a team that has outshot the Stars 110-56 in the past three
games, has a 7-1 mark at the Pepsi Center this playoffs and is
already packing for Game 7 on Saturday in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 7-1 at home. So if you look at the finish, it should be
a pretty win'' tonight, Avs forward Peter Forsberg said. ``We have
to play our best game of the whole playoffs here and get a win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avs simply point to the shot differential and sigh. They say
they easily could have won Games 4 and 5 and been packing for the
Stanley Cup Finals. The difference, they say, has been Stars goalie
Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock disagrees vehemently. He doesn't think Belfour's play
is the only reason the Stars aren't on the beach sipping margaritas
instead of one game away from the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, that's not fair at all,'' Hitchcock said. ``Goaltending is
a big part of your game, and I've said this before: There are
certain times in the series where your goalie has to win games for
you. My experience has always been they come up later in series for
you. We expect if we're going to win in Colorado \Rtonight\S he has
to be one of the game stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we still have to score goals; you still have to play
strong defense at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but in Game 5, Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk was able to
score the winning goal in overtime because Belfour made the huge
saves minutes before.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour hasn't been as good as Colorado goalie Patrick Roy. He's
been better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he's played very well, and we know he's won some
games for them single-handedly,'' Avs winger Dave Andreychuk said.
``I think we still feel he's beatable.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the Avs, they've put themselves in a situation
in which they have to beat him twice to avoid losing to the Stars
in the Western Conference Finals for a second consecutive season.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars came back from a 3-2 deficit last season, winning
Games 6 and 7 to advance to the Stanley Cup Finals. It's a fact
that isn't lost on the Avs or the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our situation is, for myself, unfortunately,] to find out how
Dallas was feeling last year,'' Colorado coach Bob Hartley said.
``We're in the same situation as Dallas was last year, and it's up
to us to face the challenge. We can win two games in a row, but
right now our focus is on Game 6 as a game we have to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars will try to close out the Avs without the services of
winger Jamie Langenbrunner. He will miss at least Game 6 after
injuring his right knee in the first period of Game 5. Hitchcock
said Langenbrunner had an MRI exam yesterday, but the results
wouldn't be known until today or tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see whether we can get him healthy enough to play in
Game 7,'' Hitchcock said. ``There just isn't enough time to turn
him around and play in Game 6. ... The original diagnosis was some
type of sprain, and whether he's day-to-day or week-to-week, it's
really the first 48 hours that are going to determine it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said he'll either use Jon Sim on the second line with
Thornton and Joe Nieuwendyk or insert Blake Sloan into the lineup,
which would put Roman Lyashenko on the second line.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever plays, they're likely to hear Guy Carbonneau say a few
words before the game. See, Carbonneau has this saying that fits
perfectly for games like tonight's.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get paid any more for playing extra,'' he says, ``so
you might as well win it in 16.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, 16 victories are needed to win the Stanley Cup, 12 to get
to the big dance. The Stars have 11. They have two games to get No.
12.
</P>
<P>
   If it's all the same to the rest of us, they'd rather just do it
in one.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
