<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4855 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     05-24 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MULLIN AWAITS CALL THAT MAY NOT COME 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ While Jalen Rose received his most improved
player award Wednesday, the proud veteran he replaced got his
shooting in. For all his years as a starter, an All-Star, Chris
Mullin was always last man out of the practice gym. Why change now,
just because he couldn't tell you when he might put it to use?
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what's going to come up,'' Mullin said, running
his hand through his haircut in the familiar flat-top.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird might call on him Thursday night in Game 2 of the
Eastern Conference finals against the Knicks. Probably not, though.
Rose was given Mullin's minutes this season and proved he deserved
them. Not surprisingly, Mullin accepted his demotion to 11th player
in the Pacers' 10-man rotation with dignity, with class, with his
most unattractive thoughts kept to himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's different emotions,'' he said. ``One thing I've
learned, to not act on your initial ones. Let them play out.''
</P>
<P>
   Could Patrick Ewing hold his thoughts and tongue? John Stockton?
Karl Malone? There was a time not too long ago when Chris Mullin
was equal to them all, their original Dream Team peer. Even Bird by
then could at best only match Mullin shot for shot.
</P>
<P>
   After the Pacers were beaten by the Knicks in last spring's
conference finals, he knew it was just a matter of months before
the coach would be coming to see him. Mullin wished to make it easy
for Bird, his friend, by meeting him halfway. It was awkward, he
admitted, but then Mullin said: ``I came here basically because of
you. We've had two good years. It's his time.''
</P>
<P>
   It was time for the younger man, the prospective free agent, to
grow into his game.
</P>
<P>
   Time for Mullin to do what always came naturally, play for the
team, give up the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Surrendering the court _ that was something else entirely,
though he hadn't kidded himself. Even as a kid in Brooklyn, he knew
he couldn't play forever.
</P>
<P>
   At 37, Mullin was already feeling conflicted by the commitment,
the travel, the opportunities missed at home. Why, just Tuesday,
his oldest of three boys, 8-year-old Sean, demanded to know the
reason his father would be the only one missing at a school
presentation later that night. ``You know I have a game tonight,''
Mullin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you don't even play,'' Sean said.
</P>
<P>
   Mullin didn't know what hurt more, the boy's disappointment or
the realization that his sons would never see him as he once was,
pumping in the southpaw jumpers, just as he watched Rose do in the
second half of Indiana's Game 1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kind of things, you can only look at them as helping you
in dealing with life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how much pride he's swallowed, it isn't life and it
isn't death, and how insignificant even this conference final
rematch with the Knicks seemed when the telephone rang last
Saturday and someone from the Pacers' organization delivered the
news that Malik Sealy was dead.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mullin's job to telephone his brother Terrence, who had
played with Sealy for four years at St. John's. His 30-year-old kid
brother did not want to believe him. Car crash? Dead? How could
this be? Just the day before, a letter had come to him from
Minneapolis, a season-ending update from his good friend Malik.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew Malik from working out over the summers at St.
John's,'' Mullin said. ``But Terrence loved him. I guess Malik had
a big family, lots of siblings and relatives around New York, and
Terrence used to say that seeing them reminded him of when it was
me playing for St. John's.''
</P>
<P>
   In those days, the mid-1980s, Terrence Mullin was the kid in the
green Celtics jacket whose favorite player was Bird. In many
respects, Chris Mullin was a smaller version, though his career was
never quite the storybook and was sometimes much worse. Chris
battled alcoholism early on. Still in his prime, he buried his
parents, Rod and Eileen, within a couple of years.
</P>
<P>
   Bird brought him to Indiana, and Mullin said he does not regret
a single moment. He smiles every day when he walks into Conseco
Fieldhouse, the New York gym rat in the ultimate Hoosier gym. He
wants to play again next season, somewhere. He can still shoot.
When Reggie Miller was ejected from Game 4 of the conference
semifinals in Philadelphia, Bird sent Mullin into a game that was
supposedly over. Mullin cranked up a couple of 3-pointers, a few
jumpers. The Pacers almost won.
</P>
<P>
   That is what keeps him working, shooting, outlasting all the
others on the Pacers' practice floor. There's another game Thursday
night, and even if the 8-year-old at home knows he probably won't
play, no one knows what the night will bring, what's going to come
up. It's a team game, basketball is. A game of roles. Chris
Mullin's role is to root, be ready, and keep his frustrations to
himself.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
