<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0354 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4856 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KIDS-MUSEUMS-0528-COX     05-24 1474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-MUSEUMS-0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHILDREN'S MUSEUMS BOOM IN ATTENDANCE AND NUMBERS
 &HT;    700&AMP;adds
 &HT;    For release Sunday, May 28
 &HT;    With KIDS-FLOOD and KIDS-BEST
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (l) lifestyle and (a) national
categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Jasmine's dream is to be ``a doctor or a
hairdresser.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben's is to be ``a motorcycle person.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman's is to ``be a chicken.''
</P>
<P>
   They hand-printed their wishes on paper leaves and hung them on
the dream tree at Port Discovery, which calls itself ``the
kid-powered museum'' in Baltimore's Inner Harbor district.
</P>
<P>
   Jasmine, Ben and Sherman are surfing a wave of interest in
informal family learning that has doubled the number of U.S.
children's museums in the last decade and nearly doubled the number
of people served by such museums within the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   More than 32 million people _ nearly half of them adults _
visited children's museums or saw their traveling exhibits last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a growth of 98 percent over the last three years,''
said Janet Rice Elman of Washington, D.C., executive director of
the Association of Youth Museums. ``Children's museums are the
fastest-growing cultural institutions in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred members of her group, which includes just over
200 of the more than 250 children's museums in the United States,
plus a handful from other countries, convened here for three days
earlier this month to discuss trends and research and to trade
tips.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the association's museums have opened since 1990,
pointed out its new president, Lou Casagrande, who is also
president of the Children's Museum in Boston, which was founded in
1913.
</P>
<P>
   ``We represent the values of children, family and education that
this whole country shares,'' he said. ``I think within the next 10
years, we'll have 500 museums with 50 to 75 million visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   The newest, opening in stages between April and July, is
Exploration Place, a $62 million complex of paid-admission and free
attractions for children and science lovers of all ages on a
20-acre tract along the Arkansas River in downtown Wichita, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can create 40-foot-tall wind patterns by navigating a
life-size airplane propeller, touch a 20-foot tall tornado of mist,
solve a food poisoning mystery, or climb inside a giant egg and
hear a fetal heart beat.
</P>
<P>
   Others can wear goggles that let them see how the world looks to
someone with age-related macular degeneration, explore a
three-level storybook castle, or play with award-winning toys,
which can also be purchased in the museum's gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has to worry about being bossed around or hurried,''
said Alan Edstrom, director of interdisciplinary programs and
exhibits. ``In our fossil dig area, if toddlers want to, they can
just sift through sand and rocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Exploration Place attracted more than 30,000 visitors in the
month after its first facilities opened in April. Its predecessor,
the Children's Museum of Wichita, had 42,000 _ not in a month, but
in a year.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, Robert Buck of Orlando, who has been
designing huge and tiny children's exhibits for three decades, said
his favorite is a log.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children roll back the log and they see the bugs
underneath,'' Buck said. ``This is a learning experience for a city
kid who never saw that.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the new museums are small. The Chesapeake Children's
Museum, which opened in 1994, serves about 17,000 children and
parents a year in Annapolis, Md. It shuns glitz, obtains less than
one percent of its $50,000 annual budget through its gift shop, and
stresses baby and toddler programs, like ``Early Language Fun,''
``Mom's Morning Out'' and ``Toddl-Art.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We promote that you can do a lot of things with inexpensive or
free or cast-off materials,'' said the museum's executive director,
Deborah Woods. ``I want parents to go home and find the
toilet-paper tubes and know that here is valuable material that can
lead to a resourceful and creative mix of education and play.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's intriguing is that the explosive growth in the number
of museums is all a result of grassroots efforts in local
communities as large as New York City or as small or smaller as
Monroe, La.,'' said Andy Ackerman, executive director of the
Children's Museum of Manhattan. ``Fortunately, or unfortunately,
there is no big federal program or national committee of businesses
pushing this.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional adds follow)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those who run children's museums say they offer a richer
experience than conventional schooling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schools are so stressed right now to perform on tests that a
lot of creative teaching and hands-on teaching has been
neglected,'' said Mebane (cq) Boyd, executive director of the
Wilmington Children's Museum in North Carolina. ``I think
children's museums are providing a place for that kind of
experience that the schools want to fill but don't have time for
any more.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Ackerman's museum not only keys some exhibits
to New York City curriculum, it has joined three other museums in
operating a ``hands-on'' public school in which students in grades
six through 11 rotate between the museums in eight-week stints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two things, technology and commercialization, that you might
think would move people away from what we do, are actually pushing
them toward us,'' Ackerman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the more time people are in front of the computer
screen at work, the more they want real reality, hands-on
experiences, that get them and their families out of their
houses,'' Ackerman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adults and children are so bombarded now by commercial
messages that to find an oasis where those messages are
non-existent or very subtle is like breathing fresh air,'' he said.
``We hear that all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Several museum officials stressed the value of children's
museums as a safe ``town plaza'' or ``community gathering place''
where parents and other caregivers go to show off their children
and watch or meet other adults with children.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I learned quickly when we first opened is
that over 50 percent of the people who walked through our doors
were adults, because children can't come by themselves,'' said
Paula Januzzi, founder of the new Busy Street children's museum in
Durham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another thing we found is that people don't necessarily feel
safe going out to the park or neighborhood any more to meet friends
and take their children to play with other children,'' she said.
``We are a safe haven.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   A lot of those parents are being misled, said Michael Spock of
the University of Chicago, whose pioneering work as director of the
Boston Children's Museum earned him laurels as the godfather of
modern ``hands-on'' museums decades ago. The son of the famed
pediatrician, he threw out the glass cases of exhibits and
introduced innovations like manholes that children could climb down
to see the cables and pipes that run under a street.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few neighborhoods where it really is unsafe, but I
think there have always been some relatively unsafe
neighborhoods,'' Spock said.
</P>
<P>
   He said peer pressure and the media influence some parents to
try too hard to guarantee that their children ``get the right kind
of start in life'' and scare others into worrying about ``if
something happened, how would they feel, and, secondarily, would
they be criticized by others about it or even brought into court
for not taking the proper care of their kids.''
</P>
<P>
   In museums, neighborhoods and homes, he said, ``My argument is,
we need to give kids a longer leash.''
</P>
<P>
   That might not be easy, because today more government and
private givers demand that the museums measure the ``outcomes'' and
``impact'' of their institutions on the learning of children.
</P>
<P>
   But exact measures are difficult, according to two major
studies, one guided by researchers for Case Western Reserve
University and the other by researchers from Harvard University and
Philadelphia's Please Touch Museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all trying to grapple with how you assess or evaluate
the museum experience when some of the most desirable results don't
appear until years afterwards,'' said consultant Barbara Beach of
Vienna, Va., who worked on the five-year study directed by Nina
Gibans at Case Western Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Association for Youth Museums - www.aym.org
</P>
<P>
   Summary of Bridges to Understanding Children's Museums -
www.successpublishing.com/bridges
</P>
<P>
   Exploration Place _ www.exploration.org
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT(at)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
