<HEADLINE>
STARS' BRENDEN MORROW FRETS ABOUT ANKLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL and CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stars winger Brenden Morrow's return to the Western Conference
Finals has been much celebrated, considering that he has a hairline
fracture in his right ankle.
</P>
<P>
   But Morrow, who has played in the past two games after missing
Games 2 and 3, is still feeling the effects of his injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have confidence right now in my ankle,'' Morrow said.
``Just pushing off, the strength isn't there in turning and I am
not sure if it's going to hold.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, it has. But, after playing in his normal spot on the top
line with Mike Modano and Brett Hull in Game 4, he was moved down
to the fourth line for Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not really at 100 percent, and the role I am playing now
I feel a little more comfortable doing,'' Morrow said. ``There
isn't quite as much pressure when I am not with \RModano and
Hull\S. I am not afraid to hold on to the puck now. When I played
with them I wanted to give them the puck all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrow has taken and given his share of hard hits in his two
games back. But, he doesn't believe there is an invisible target on
his body because he's playing hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I am a target anymore than anyone else,'' he
said. ``I think \RModano\S is the target.'' \Nsubheds:Been there,
won Entering Game 6 tonight in Denver, the Stars have a distinct
advantage over most playoff teams who have played in the Pepsi
Center: They have won there.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche was 7-0 at home in the playoffs before the Stars'
4-1 Game 4 victory Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just getting that win gives us the confidence that we can do
it again,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``I think if we had
been 0-2 in that building with everyone else's \Rrecord\S in
Denver, it would have been a difficult mountain for us to climb. We
know how to play that building now, which is important because you
have to play it differently than ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, pucks fly much more quickly around the boards in
Denver than in Dallas. \Nsubheds:A little woozy The Stars left Game
5 with one injured player, winger Jamie Langenbrunner. There was,
however, another player who left the ice a little woozy. Forward
Grant Marshall took a hard hit near the end of the game from
Avalanche center Chris Drury and had to be helped off the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fine. He got whacked a good one,'' Ken Hitchcock said.
``He got the wind knocked out of him. .... I think Drury
cross-checked him.'' \Nsubheds:Face it The Stars lost 42 of 71
faceoffs in Game 5. Guy Carbonneau, who won 13 of 21 faceoffs in
Game 4, won only six of 23 on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been good all playoffs _ this series anyway,'' said
Carbonneau, who has won 39 of 98 (39.8 percent) this series. ``It's
something I have to work on. I think I just have to be a little
more hungry and maybe cheat a little more than I used to. I've had
a tough time against \RJoe\S Sakic all year, so it's nothing new.''
\Nsubheds:Powered up The Stars are 3-for-22 (13.6 percent) on the
power play in the series after Brett Hull scored in the second
period of Game 5 while Serge Aubin was in the penalty box for
boarding. The Stars' first goal was scored by Jere Lehtinen just as
their power play expired and before Avs forward Adam Deadmarsh, who
was serving two minutes for high sticking, could get back into
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those power plays have been coming up big for us the last
couple of games,'' Stars center Mike Modano said. ``If you can get
one goal on that, that's a big plus. It tends to back them up a
little bit five-on-five if we're playing aggressive. We're able to
get some power plays from that, and we've been able to generate
some chances. It's forced them maybe to get a little frustrated.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
