<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4859 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-KIDS-FLOOD-0528-COX     05-24 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS-FLOOD-0528-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KIDS' MUSEUM STRUGGLES BACK AFTER HURRICANE
 &HT;    With KIDS-MUSEUMS for release Sunday, May 28
 &HT;    SPECIAL ATTN: North Carolina Papers
 &HT;    DUPLICATION ALERT: Moving in (l) lifestyle and (a) national
categories
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Candy Madrid of Rocky Mount, N.C., blinked, wiping
happy tears from her eyes, as hundreds of colleagues from across
the country cheered her museum's struggle to return to life after a
devastating flood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her museum was lost last September in Hurricane Floyd and two
staff members also lost their homes,'' Janet Rice Elman, executive
director of the Association of Youth Museums, said at the opening
of the group's national conference here. ``We're thrilled that they
are rebuilding.''
</P>
<P>
   Before it was inundated, the Rocky Mount Children's Museum had
hosted about 50,000 visitors a year and brought its exhibits to
another 35,000 to 40,000 children at scouting, day care,
after-school and community locations in 14 counties in eastern
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Madrid, the executive director, said her museum resumed its
outreach programs within a month, using traveling and temporary
exhibits loaned or donated by museums in her state's Grassroots
Science Museums Collaborative.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have received e-mails from people in museums as far away as
South America, Australia, England, wanting to help,'' she said.
``I've been telling my colleagues here to forgive me for not
getting back in touch with them, but we don't have a place to put
anything more at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum, which had 10,800 square feet of space, is joining
the city's arts center in temporarily sharing 8,000 square feet of
space in a former store in downtown Rocky Mount.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect it to open at some point between the Fourth of July
and Labor Day,'' said Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Madrid said plans for a fund-raising drive for a much larger,
permanent complex, to be shared with the city's arts center and
community theater, are well under way. The museum's Web site, with
details of what was lost and information on how to assist in the
rebuilding, is www.ci.rocky-mount.nc.us/museum/.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope to have a grand re-opening within five years,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Other museum directors, most of whom also scrape by with small
or non-existent endowments and minimal insurance, paged with
fascination through Madrid's scrapbook of photos documenting the
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a rushing river inside our building, a river nine
and a half feet high,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a 600-gallon Saltwater Living Marsh touch pool that
literally floated up, ripped out the ceiling, broke into three
parts and slid into another gallery,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dome of our planetarium kind of floated and came loose,
and tilted, and it is the only part of the structure that could be
salvaged,'' she said. ``We lost the projection system, the
furniture, every record, every exhibit, every bit of paper, the
rainforest solarium, the...''
</P>
<P>
   She broke off and summed up: ``We lost it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Without records, she and the five other full-time staffers _ the
part-timers had to be laid off _ spent days in rubber gloves,
pawing through the slimy rubble to create a precise inventory of
the losses in order to apply for insurance proceeds and federal
aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a horrible thought: You know, a fire is so much kinder
than flooding, because you don't have to see stuff again,'' Madrid
said.
</P>
<P>
   Only two collections _ some model trains and wooden model wagons
_ were salvageable. Conservators in Virginia expect to finish the
meticulous work of restoring them by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Madrid said her hardest moment came when some Girl Scouts who
had held a camp-in at the museum asked her about the 18 abandoned
pets, ranging from ferrets to iguanas, that the museum had rescued
through the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used our animals to talk about the responsibility of pet
ownership, you know, that you just don't buy this cute, cuddly
little thing, without realizing that it will grow up and you will
still be responsible,'' she said. But Madrid had to tell the
scouts, ``Sweeties, so many of our babies didn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   All but three of the 18 live animals were lost. A veterinary
student is caring temporarily for the three survivors: Lizzy, a
Burmese python who is about 15 years old, as well as Samantha, an
American alligator, and Snarf, a red tail boa constrictor, who are
each more than twice that age.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
