<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRL-CART FEUD LARGELY MUFFLED AT INDY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ If you're bound and determined to collect some
juicy quotes on the ongoing IRL-CART feud at the Indianapolis Motor
Speedway this week, you always can hang out at the Gasoline Alley
garage of Texan A.J. Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   The first four-time winner of the Indianapolis 500, Foyt has
emerged as ``de facto'' guardian angel of the history and
traditions of the Speedway, and chief advocate of Tony George's
all-oval Indy Racing League. As such, A.J. habitually rips into his
former running buddies from the Championship Auto Racing Teams at
the slightest provocation.
</P>
<P>
   A.J. makes for hot copy from here to Houston that way. But the
truth is, the underlying mood here in the wake of the return of
Target/Chip Ganassi Racing, the undisputed and reigning four-time
CART champions, has been decidedly apolitical. Yes, there were some
relieved faces and snickering on Saturday, when reigning IRL
champion Greg Ray of Plano knocked reigning CART champion Juan
Montoya of Colombia off the provisional pole with a dramatic
four-lap qualifying run.
</P>
<P>
   Ray, it could be argued, had saved face for the IRL on its most
hallowed ground by out-qualifying Montoya, the Indy 500 rookie with
the cocky sneer and the concrete right foot. But neither Ray nor
car owner John Menard walked into their post-qualifying news
conference with an Indy Racing Northern Light Series banner draped
across their shoulders. And you can't even find the
purple-and-orange CART FedEx Series logo on the press kits
circulating here for Montoya and teammate Jimmy Vasser, the 1996
series champion.
</P>
<P>
   After five years of bickering over the direction of domestic
open-wheel racing _ including the false hopes of reconciliation
first raised here last May _ the principal players have accepted
the fact that the series have gone their separate ways. Enough fans
and corporate sponsors have been alienated, enough trash talked.
When they throw the green flag to start the 84th Indy 500 on
Sunday, what we'll get is a little glimpse of the open-wheel racing
we've all been missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People keep bringing up this CART-IRL issue. And to me, that's
not a big issue,'' Ray said after securing his first Indy 500 pole.
``As a driver or an athlete in any sport, you always want to
measure yourself against the best, whether it's CART drivers or IRL
drivers. I respect all of the drivers, not just Juan Montoya and
Jimmy Vasser.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have said the last couple of years they thought that
being on pole or winning the Indy 500, it wasn't quite the same.
Well, they weren't driving it, so I'm here to tell you there's some
very good drivers and teams here. This race is just a measuring
stick.''
</P>
<P>
   IRL officials originally hoped several of CART's top guns _
including Team Rahal and defending race champion Kenny Brack _
would have crossed over. For budgetary and/or engine-related
reasons, only Chip Ganassi and Derrick Walker are here. And they
aren't here to hand out warm-and-fuzzy photos of CART president and
CEO Andrew Craig on the corner of 16th Street and Georgetown Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to show what CART drivers can do,'' said
Montoya, who _ as a gesture of respect _ was allowed by IRL
officials to waive the series' Rookie Orientation Program here.
``We're coming with my team to do our best.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Montoya admitted that he did not know how he, as CART
champion, would be received at the Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single fan has been really good, and the drivers and
teams also,'' Montoya said. ``It's a fun racetrack, a huge
racetrack. But what makes Indy special is not only the track, it's
the people that come and enjoy everything. The people _ how do you
call them? _ the Alley Cats. It's awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Vasser, who competed in the Indy 500 from 1992-95, already knew
that Indy means a great deal to a driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anybody racing in the CART FedEx
Championship that doesn't want to be racing here,'' said Vasser,
who led 20 laps of the 1995 Indy 500. ``I know a lot of drivers
that are in the CART series are envious of Juan and I, and would
like to be in our position. Hopefully in the future you'll see more
CART teams take Chip's lead.''
</P>
<P>
   And leave the juicy quotes to A.J.
\Npcredit:Triumph Books The autobiography of Johnny Rutherford is
305 pages, and he's concerned who among his many friends didn't
make the final cut.
\Nsubheds:SPOTLIGHT ON... \Nt36:Rutherford recalls a life in the
fast lane The four-color jacket has been slipped over his
autobiography, and Fort Worth's Johnny Rutherford says he can't
wait to read how the story of ``Lone Star J.R.'' has turned out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to trim this thing down, and I don't know how much
got left on the cutting room floor,'' said Rutherford, thumbing
through the hard-cover, 305-page chronicle published by Triumph
Books of Chicago. ``I've had so many friends over the years, and
I'm sure somebody's going to say I left them out. So I'm anxious to
read through it _ and see who they did leave out.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutherford, a three-time winner of the Indianapolis 500 and one
of racing's most respected ambassadors, began collaborating with
author David Craft a year ago at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
In addition to jogging each other's memories, Rutherford said he
and his wife, Betty, called in some favors while compiling the
extensive statistical records covering the various types of race
cars he has driven over three decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Betty worked very, very hard on this book, editing and trying
to put things together,'' Rutherford said. ``Her name ought to be
here \Ron the cover\S.''
</P>
<P>
   J.R. recounts the races, cars and peers of his career in an
anecdotal style. Although the interview process got tedious at
times, Rutherford said he found the experience of chronicling his
life exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's been enlightening,'' said Rutherford, who won the
third and last of his Indy 500s exactly 20 years ago today.
``There's a tendency to say, `That's behind me, that's history.'
But you remember you had a good time. If I were to check out
tomorrow or this afternoon, you know, I got no qualms or kicks. I
had a good run. But this highlights everything.''
</P>
<P>
   The book's national launch is scheduled for today, appropriately
enough Carburetion Day in Indianapolis. Rutherford, 62, is special
projects coordinator for the Indy Racing League, and his signing
tour largely will coincide with the Indy Racing Northern Light
Series schedule. The series will visit Texas Motor Speedway for the
Casino Magic 500 on June 10. Rutherford is scheduled to appear at
the Barnes &AMP; Noble store on University Drive from 7 to 9 p.m. on
June 6, and at Border Books on South Hulen from 11:30 a.m. to 1
p.m. on June 10.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to an autographed copy of the book ($24.95), each
buyer will receive an artwork poster created by Rutherford that
highlights the various stages of his racing career.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the movie rights?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I would be very surprised if anybody wants to make a movie
out of ``that'','' Rutherford said. ``But Kevin Costner _ we do
have the same, thin face ...''
\Nsubheds:PIT STOPS Hollansworth hunts ride Dallasite John
Hollansworth Jr., released by Rockwall-based TeamExtreme earlier
this year, never turned a lap at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway
this month. But Hollansworth knocked on a lot of garage doors in
Gasoline Alley in hopes of putting together a deal that will get
him up and running in the Casino Magic 500 at Texas Motor Speedway
next month.
</P>
<P>
   Hollansworth had talked to Nienhouse Motorsports about possibly
qualifying a 2000 Dallara/Aurora last weekend at IMS, where he
finished 13th as a rookie in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty confident we'll have a package starting from Texas
on,'' said Hollansworth, who is working to secure Lycos as his
primary sponsor. The only rookie to start all 10 IRL events last
year and the fastest rookie qualifier in the 1999 Indy 500,
Hollansworth was dumped by TeamExtreme after starting 14th and
finishing 21st in the season-opening Delphi Indy 200 at Orlando,
Fla. Ownership believed that Hollansworth and chief mechanic John
King were not clicking, and opted to hire series veteran Davey
Hamilton as stablemate to rookie Airton Dare. Both qualified for
Sunday's 84th Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   Hollansworth, an attorney, said he was one race into a new
three-year contract when he was replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's likely going to be some legal ramifications from that,
so it's not something I should get into,'' he said. ``But we didn't
work all the years to get here to get bounced around by management
of a team, and give up. Hopefully we'll be back there for the
remainder of the season.'' \Nsubheds:Unser backs Fisher, LSJ
Two-time Indianapolis 500 champion Al Unser Jr. will not have a
problem racing against rookie Sarah Fisher and veteran Lyn St.
James on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher and St. James are the first two women to qualify for the
same Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think racing is a science and can be taught,'' said Unser,
who is competing at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway for the first
time since failing to qualify for the 1995 race. ``Doesn't matter
about size, color or sex. It's a science and can be taught. I think
it's wonderful there's two girls in the field. I got a little
redhead at home who's 11 \RShannon Lee\S, and you betcha we're
going to get her involved in racing. I think it teaches
sportsmanship and competition, and I think it's wonderful.''
\Nsubheds:The last practice Today is Carburetion Day at the
Speedway, and the two-hour practice will be the last time the cars
will be on the track until Sunday morning. The worst-case scenario
for any driver is that he or she would crash a qualified car,
necessitating use of a backup and a move to the rear of the 33-car
field.
</P>
<P>
   But John Menard, owner of the cars driven by pole-sitter Greg
Ray of Plano and No. 4 starter Robby Gordon, has envisioned an even
bigger ``worst-case.'' Ray will be lined up directly in front of
Gordon when the green flag falls for the traditional flying start.
</P>
<P>
   ``My nightmare,'' Menard said, ``is that Robby and Greg will
crash into each at the start.'' \Nsubheds:The last word ``''No man
is an island, but the Speedway is. It pulls you in, and then it
won't let go.''''
</P>
<P>
   _ Three-time Indy 500 champion Johnny Rutherford of Fort Worth,
on the mystique of the Indianapolis Motor Speedway
nn
</P>
