<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 20:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4864 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-ARSENIC-WATER-ART-NYT     05-24 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARSENIC-WATER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA CALLS FOR SHARP CUTS IN LEVELS OF ARSENIC IN DRINKING WATER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.M., Okla., N.Y.)  (Eds: Consumer information at end.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Environmental Protection Agency on Wednesday
proposed strict new regulations of arsenic in tap water, reducing
by 90 percent the public's maximum exposure to the chemical, which
causes cancer and is found at harmful levels in at least 1 out of
10 of the nation's community water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The agency wants to lower the limit on arsenic from 50 parts per
billion to 5 parts per billion, an approach that it estimated would
cost $374 million a year and would prevent scores of cancer cases
each year and provide other major health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Water utilities, while agreeing that the rules should be
tightened, contended that this level of control would cost about
four times as much as the agency claimed and that the health
benefits were not worth such an effort. Environmentalists called
for an even stricter rule, saying the agency was accepting
unusually high cancer risks in this approach.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA missed a deadline of Jan. 1 under the Safe Drinking
Water Act of 1996, and environmentalists threatened to sue the
agency if it did not move quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The subject of arsenic has been debated at the EPA for the
better part of a decade or more,'' said Charles J. Fox, assistant
administrator of the EPA for water programs. ``We think this is
affordable, and it is important for public health protection. But
in some communities they will see increases in drinking water rates
to pay for this additional health protection.''
</P>
<P>
   The agency said the costs per household might be about $28 a
year in households in larger cities, and about $85 per household in
communities of fewer than 10,000 households. The agency makes
billions of dollars of federal loans to cities to help them meet
drinking water regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The burden would fall most heavily on states in the Southwest,
where many communities have tap water with high levels of arsenic.
Other communities in the West, the Midwest and New England would be
affected, especially those that rely on water found underground
rather than streams and other surface water for their drinking
water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Albuquerque, N.M., water system, which serves
more than 400,000 people, has an arsenic level of 14 parts per
billion, and the Norman, Okla., water system, which serves 80,000
people, has arsenic levels at about 36 parts per billion, according
to federal data complied by the Natural Resources Defense Council.
</P>
<P>
   The agency estimated that 6,600 utilities, or about 12 percent
of all water suppliers in the nation, would have to take corrective
action, and that the vast majority of them serve 10,000 homes or
fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Arsenic in drinking water comes from industrial pollution, but
more commonly from natural sources in the ground. Its occurrence
varies widely: New York City's water is already essentially
arsenic-free and meets the new standards.
</P>
<P>
   In some communities, people may face a risk as high as 1 in 100
of developing cancer from contaminated water, according to a study
published last year by the National Research Council. For decades,
Congress has called for the agency to review its rules, but the
agency has never before issued a proposal, citing uncertainties
over the costs and benefits.
</P>
<P>
   While few experts argue against taking action to improve
protections from arsenic, there is still a dispute over how
strictly the agency should regulate it. Arsenic can cause not only
lung, skin and bladder cancer but also diseases of the liver, blood
vessels and other organs.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Olson, a senior attorney at the Natural Resources Defense
Council, objected that the EPA proposal would provide a cancer risk
of 1 in 10,000, a claim that the agency confirmed. ``Although it is
a very significant step forward, it would still provide a higher
cancer risk than any other EPA rule for tap water,'' Olson said.
``I think that is a pretty serious precedent for the agency to be
undertaking.''
</P>
<P>
   His environmental advocacy group has urged the agency to adopt a
standard of 3 parts per billion, the strictest standard that is
considered feasible with existing technology.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Marsano, a spokesman for the American Water Works
Association, which represents water utilities, said the group had
called for a standard of 10 parts per billion _ twice what the EPA
was proposing, and equal to the recommendation of the World Health
Organization. He said that would bring reductions in the vast
majority of cities where arsenic was a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's draft proposal, prepared after years of discussions
with health officials, water districts and the public, was held up
at the White House for review until this month.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's new proposal is a compromise, but leaves open the
possibility of seeking higher or lower standards after a period of
public comment.
</P>
<P>
   The agency asks the public to comment on several alternatives: a
20 parts per billion standard, the 10 parts per billion standard
that the water utilities have endorsed, the 5 parts per billion
standard that the EPA favors, and the 3 parts per billion standard.
A decision is to be made within a year.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's economic studies conducted over the past few years
found that the standard of 10 parts per billion would cost only
half as much as its proposal, and that the standard of 3 parts per
billion would cost twice as much.
</P>
<P>
   For each notch that the regulatory vise is tightened, there
would be a corresponding reduction in cancers, the agency's
scientists found. But the improvements would be relatively slight.
And because most of the cancers at each level of control would be
curable, the agency deemed that the health gains were worth only so
much money spent cleaning up water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Large water systems probably would treat their water with
relatively efficient technologies like filtering and adding lime.
But systems that serve fewer than 10,000 people would probably
choose less efficient approaches like reverse osmosis, and the
costs of treatment per household would probably be higher there.
Large systems would be given three years to comply, and small
systems, five years.
</P>
<P>
   Because it recognized that the rule might be costly, Congress
specifically told the environmental agency to consider a less
stringent rule if it found the benefits of strictly controlling
arsenic too costly to justify.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CONSUMER CONFIDENCE REPORTS: Beginning last year, local water
utilities are required to send a consumer confidence report once a
year with their water utility bill. The report has information on
all contaminants, including arsenic, and the amounts found in the
local water supply.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO GET INFORMATION: Call the Environmental Protection
Agency's Safe Drinking Water Hot Line at (800) 426-4791 for the
number of your water utility and ask for a consumer confidence
report. Or check the EPA's Web site for more information:
http://www.epa.gov/safewater/dwinfo.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
