<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Witness says Lewis was `tussling,' not punching, victim
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin and Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A key witness who told police he saw Ray Lewis
punching a man who was later stabbed to death testified Wednesday
he only saw the NFL star ``tussling'' during the deadly melee in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gwen, a 26-year-old rap artist from Akron, Ohio, was
expected to be a strong witness for the prosecution. On Feb. 9,
Gwen told police he saw Lewis ``hitting'' Richard Lollar, one of
two men killed Jan. 31 after a night of post-Super Bowl partying.
</P>
<P>
   But Gwen testified Wednesday his initial account of Lewis
striking Lollar was ``a mistake.'' Instead, he said Lewis and
Lollar each grabbed at each other's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen is one of only two witnesses who have told police they saw
Lewis throwing punches during the melee. Lewis' limousine driver
Duane Fassett, who could testify as early as today, is the other.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen also testified he saw Lewis take off his gold necklace,
which prosecutors contend was an unmistakable indication he was
ready to fight. Lewis paid $45,000 for the two-foot-long white gold
necklace, studded with 28 carats of diamonds, two days before the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, Reginald Oakley, 31, of Baltimore and Joseph Sweeting,
34, of Miami are charged with murder in the stabbing deaths of
Lollar, 24, and Jacinth Baker, 21.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors brought home to jurors the horror of the fight by
displaying photos of Lollar lying dead in the street. The close-up
photo, with Lollar's eyes staring blankly, sent a relative bolting
for the courtroom doorway Tuesday and a half-dozen others consoling
each other.
</P>
<P>
   The photo, State's Exhibit No. 29, was flashed up on a screen
for the jury as Akron friend Christopher Shinholster identified
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Richard laying on the ground dead,'' Shinholster said
in a low voice. The series of photos caused some jurors to look
away.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen, who had recorded a rap CD under the name of Chino Nino,
also testified that he told Assistant District Attorney Clint
Rucker about his change in testimony during an interview with the
prosecution team on Feb. 28. Steve Sadow, a lawyer for Sweeting,
noted that prosecutors had not told the defense of the discrepancy,
which he said they were, by law, obligated to do.
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Superior Court Judge Alice D. Bonner said she was
``extremely concerned'' about the development and ordered the
prosecution team into her chambers for an accounting Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen is a key figure in the case because his words caused a
misunderstanding that led to the deadly melee. Gwen said he left
the Cobalt lounge and discovered his ride had left him but saw
Akron friend Chris Shinholster, who said he'd give him a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen complained to Shinholster, using a profanity-laced racial
epithet.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley, who was walking by, overhead Gwen and rushed back at
them, Gwen and Shinholster testified.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis walked up and grabbed Oakley around the waist, pulling him
toward the parked limousine. Gwen said he saw Oakley holding a
knife.
</P>
<P>
   Another man told them to stay back. That man held a knife but
was not a defendant, the two men testified. The two Akron men
testified this man was dressed in black, although Gwen said he wore
a leather jacket and Shinholster said he wore a mink coat. Gwen
also said that, during the ensuing fight, this man swung at him
with the knife.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, both Gwen and Shinholster admitted they
were drinking and smoking cigar-sized marijuana ``blunts.''
</P>
<P>
   After court adjourned, Rucker, when asked about this
unidentified man, said, ``We're still dealing with that,'' and
indicated that the state's investigation is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Baker and Lollar were walking behind Gwen and Shinholster. As
they passed the limo, Gwen said he heard Lollar say, ``(Expletive)
them, (racial epithet), this is OH-10,'' a reference to their
native Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley then came out of the limo and Baker smashed a champagne
bottle over his head, Gwen said, noting that he later saw Oakley
pull Baker's coat over his head and punch him four or five times in
the chest area. Baker died from stab wounds to the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Shinholster, a stocky construction worker, testified that after
Baker popped Oakley with the champagne bottle, he ran up and
appealed to the football star to control Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when Ray Lewis ran up,'' to the fight, Shinholster
said. Lewis did not have a knife, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him to grab his dude; I asked him two or three
times,'' Shinholster testified. Lewis did not break up the fight,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   He then heard Lollar scream ``Get your hands off my cousin,''
referring to Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Shinholster said he then saw Oakley shaking Baker, who appeared
to be unconscious. Shinholster ran over to Baker and grabbed him by
the foot. ``I tried to get a reaction,'' he said, adding that he
did not get one.
</P>
<P>
   He then saw Lollar walk over with his hand over his chest saying
he had been cut. ``It was in a calm manner like it was a small
cut,'' he said. But Lollar fell to the ground oozing blood and
Shinholster ran.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
