<SLUG> BC-TRADE-REPUBLICANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY REPUBLICAN VOTES SECURED VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was an unusual sight: There was Republican
loyalist and Bill Clinton nemesis Richard Armey, a congressman from
Texas, fighting passionately on the House floor for a bill Clinton
has described as his biggest legislative priority this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was the Republicans _ the same party that voted
to impeach Clinton and has held endless hearings on alleged Clinton
scandals _ who gave the president the critical base to pass the
landmark legislation expanding trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   Is this the beginning of a new era of good feeling? Have the
Capitol Hill Republicans and the White House decided to make nice
for their final six months together?
</P>
<P>
   Nah.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be like `Groundhog Day' again,'' David Wade, a
spokesman for Senator John F. Kerry of Massachusetts, said
Wednesday. ``Tomorrow morning, the hatred begins again.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Republicans and the White House have been a bit
more cooperative with each other recently. They came together on a
bill this month to increase trade with Africa and the Caribbean
Basin, and on Tuesday they agreed to a ``new markets'' package to
help ailing urban areas in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But any thawing in the working relationship between the two
sides is more a function of their separate political concerns,
Republicans and Democrats admit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The speaker and the president have been working together
pretty well for awhile,'' said John Feehery, spokesman for House
Speaker J. Dennis Hastert, a Republican of Illinois. The reason?
``The speaker wants to get things done, and the president wants to
have a legacy,'' Feehery said. ``Our interests coincide.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote was an important personal victory for Clinton, who has
a small window of opportunity to establish some kind of legislative
legacy to define his presidency with something more dignified than
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The trade bill is in a special category, congressional and White
House officials note, because it is not a straight partisan issue.
Those who opposed the measure in the House fell loosely into two
categories: Democrats concerned about the impact on organized
labor, and Republicans and Democrats who think the United States
shouldn't reward China because of its poor human rights record.
</P>
<P>
   But when the president goes back to Congress to plead for
passage of other elements of his domestic legislative agenda, he is
likely to have a tougher time with his temporary Republican allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as (the China vote) meaning something for the next four
or five months, it's hard to say,'' said White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart. ``We have an agenda. We have differences, whether it be
on Patient's Bill of Rights or prescription drugs for Medicare.
We'll have to wait and see over the next few months to see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Republicans in Congress are not finished with
their inquiries into various Clinton matters, such as the status of
numerous White House e-mails that House Republicans suspect may
have been kept hidden.
</P>
<P>
   And the investigation topics continue to emerge, even at this
late stage in Clinton's presidency. Representative William
Goodling, a Republican of Pennsylvania, is looking into why the
National Endowment for the Humanities asked Clinton to be the
speaker at this year's Jefferson Lecture in the Humanities.
</P>
<P>
   The honor is usually bestowed on an academic scholar, said Becky
Campoverde, a spokeswoman for the House Committee on Education and
the Workforce, of which Goodling is the chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton declined the request to speak at the March event. But
Goodling has nonetheless demanded from the endowment a full
accounting explaining why Clinton was invited to speak to begin
with.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
