<HEADER>
A4880 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-VIDEOGAME-REVIEWS-TEX     05-24 0438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOGAME-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF NEW VIDEO GAMES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cut me some slack for often sounding repetitive in this column.
But game companies make just a few types: fighters, role-playing
games, sports titles, Mario/Lara Croft adventure games and, well,
everything else is Doomed.
</P>
<P>
   More than any of the aforementioned genres, though, racers are
perhaps not only the most cloned but the most popular. Gamers buy
these things like they're going out of business, but there's hardly
any difference to 'em. What, you pick a vehicle, pick a highway and
try to run everyone else off the road? Do we really need 50
e-versions of Dallas' Central Expressway?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently so. Here are three new racers:
</P>
<P>
   F1 World Grand Prix (Sega for Sega Dreamcast): You really gotta
hand it to Sega: It truly is the brilliant underdog of the vid-game
world. Who else but the company that slipped into one of its hockey
games an intercom announcement about someone leaving their car
lights on would dream of this: a racing game that features the
exact same weather conditions as the event on which the game is
based. How cool is that?
</P>
<P>
   Based on the 1998 FIA Formula One Championship, Grand Prix is a
lot better than other racers simply because of the realism: the
real-life drivers such as Mike Schumacher and Eddie Irvine, the
weather, the fully modeled cars and tracks from the '98 race, and
customizable car settings. I have no idea what a gear ratio is, but
it sure is cool that I can change it around.
</P>
<P>
   Topgear Pocket 2 (Kemco/Vatical for Gameboy Color): Here's a
rarity: a Gameboy racing game that doesn't look like Ms. Pac Man.
Credit that to the big, colorful and, most important, decipherable
graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Players choose from 15 rally cars, including a Toyota GT-4 ST
(those are so cool), and 36 courses, ranging from dirt roads to
sun-paved highways and rainy, slick streets. Cars are tweakable via
various gadgets and gizmos. Mighty impressive for Gameboy.
</P>
<P>
   Excitebike 64 (Nintendo for Nintendo 64): Here comes another
motorcycle-racing game. Can I get a big WHO CARES?
</P>
<P>
   MX freaks will love this, though: You can do a bunch of midair
stunts, like cliff-hangers and heel-clickers, create your own
courses and, yep, knock the tar out of other racers. With 20
stadiums, some beautiful outdoor tracks and solid graphics, E64 is
probably the best MX-racer out there. With all the other ones
available, it's just kinda hard for me to care.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
