<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4881 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MALL-BABY-SITTING-ART     05-24 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALL-BABY-SITTING-ART-2TAKES(960)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFERING TO BABY-SIT WHILE PARENTS SHOP
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Pa., Mich., Minn., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 has being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRINCETON, N.J. _ No baby sitter? No problem.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, a growing number of movie theaters, supermarkets,
gyms and casinos are adding playrooms where parents can leave their
children for a few hours while they spend money, watch a film or
work out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents tell us they love it,'' said Dave DeMascole, manager
of the Wegmans supermarket here, which opened in August with a
large W-Kids Play Center. ``We're getting about 500 kids a week,
and there have been times when we've had to turn people away
because it's too full. It's free, and it gives them an hour or two
to shop in an enjoyable way. I have two young children myself, and
I understand, no matter how much you love them, how nice it can be
to get away from those interruptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three years, Wegmans Food Markets has opened play
centers at 29 of its 51 stores in New York, Pennsylvania and New
Jersey, and plans to open more as it expands. Wegmans is not the
only one: even in the absence of proof that in-store child care
increases profits, a 1998 survey by the Food Marketing Institute
found that almost one in five new supermarkets nationwide would
include such care.
</P>
<P>
   It has been 15 years since Ikea created a stir with its store
featuring a ``ballroom'' where children could romp in a sea of
plastic balls while their parents shopped for home furnishings. But
it is only in the last few years that on-site child care has caught
on more widely.
</P>
<P>
   Just what this trend means is open to debate. Many see it as
auspicious evidence of a more family-friendly world. Others say it
is simply _ and crassly _ a matter of businesses working harder to
turn parents into customers. Some child-care experts worry that,
however convenient for parents, the playrooms are symptomatic of a
society in which children dwell in a separate sphere devoted to
their entertainment, rather than being included in adult life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to know what to make of it,'' said Ellen Galinsky,
president of the Families and Work Institute, a nonprofit research
group in Manhattan. ``On one hand, it's certainly a positive thing
that some businesses or stores that might not have welcomed
children at all a few years ago are now making a place for them.
It's also true that businesses are looking at parent-consumers in a
more sophisticated way. But I can imagine some people seeing it as
sad, as encouragement for parents to be apart from their kids more,
to leave them outside the daily routines.''
</P>
<P>
   Two decades ago, riding the tide of baby boomer
child-centeredness, a flurry of ``mommy-and-me'' programs emerged
in which mothers and children exercised together, swam together and
did art projects together. But now, the programs tend to separate
``mommy'' from ``me.''
</P>
<P>
   Many mothers say the baby-sitting programs are a godsend in an
era when parents are harried and teen-age baby sitters are scarce
and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have anyone to watch my 3-year-old daughter, so until
this began about a year ago, the only movies I went to were kiddie
things,'' said Ingrid Roberts of Pembroke Pines, Fla., who uses the
child-care center at Muvico's Paradise 24 movie theater whenever
she can. ``For the last three Friday nights in a row, my
girlfriend's come from the beach with her daughter, and we put the
two girls in the playroom, and we see movies while they play
together there. It means a lot to me. I know she's safe, I know
she's having a ball, and I get a night out, which I really need.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Muvico Theaters in Florida began offering care centers for
children 3 to 8 at its multiplexes in Tampa, Davie and Pompano
Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had talked to moviegoers about why they didn't go more
often, and baby-sitting was one of the main reasons,'' said Randi
Emerman, a Muvico spokeswoman. ``Movies are usually spontaneous,
something you decide to do that day, but usually baby sitters have
to be lined up a week in advance. So we saw this as an amenity that
would get parents going to the movies more.''
</P>
<P>
   Muvico gives parent and child matching wristbands like those
used in hospitals, and releases the child only to an adult wearing
the wristband. The theater also gives parents a vibrating beeper so
they can be reached in an emergency without disturbing other
moviegoers.
</P>
<P>
   Wegmans has a similar system. ``We page for potty runs,'' said
Jo Natale, a corporate spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, the security can be cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one mom, in the midst of shopping, who remembered
she had to go get another child off the bus,'' Natale said. ``She
went home, then remembered she'd left the younger child with us, so
she snipped off her wristband and gave it to a neighbor to come do
the pickup. But of course we wouldn't release the child to the
neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some parents use the Wegmans in Princeton as semiregular child
care, arranging to meet friends for coffee or lunch at the store's
spacious cafe, while their children have an instant play group,
playing on the padded climbing structure, doing puzzles, or
watching a tape of ``Madeline.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one mom who drops her twin 4-year-old boys every
Monday, Wednesday and Friday, and goes to the cafe for the full
two-hour limit,'' said Ruth Sommer, the W-Kids supervisor. ``That's
fine with us. She's still spending money in the store.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not fine with Wegmans, though, when parents deposit their
children and go off to shop elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a couple isolated incidents when we've paged
someone and they weren't in the store, and we've had to explain
that that's not what this is for,'' said DeMascole, the Wegmans
manager.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
