<HEADER>
A4882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MALL-BABY &LR; - &UR; SITTING-A     05-24 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MALL-BABY </SLUG>
 - SITTING-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT  
 PRINCETON, N.J.: Wegmans manager. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   There are still a few parents _ but only a few _ strolling the
aisles with little children in their shopping carts, some because
the child does not like being left with strangers and others
because shopping together is a pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we like to do together, so we can talk about
what we're going to have for dinner and she can pick out what she
likes,'' said Lisa Gill, whose daughter, Chelsea, was happily
holding a pudding pack she had selected herself. ``I do leave her
at the child care at my gym, but shopping for food is something we
can share.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Though the child care at Wegmans is free, many of the programs
charge a fee _ about the price of a movie ticket at Muvico
theaters, and $5 to $6 an hour at many gyms and casinos. Either
way, most of the companies have only a hazy sense that the programs
are making a bottom-line difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really know how it's affecting our profits,'' said
Emerman of Muvico. ``We think it's doing well, but we look at it as
an amenity to get people going to the movies.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Generally, for-profit hourly child care has been tough going:
several baby-sitting ventures at shopping malls have folded after a
year or two. And New Horizon Kids Quest, a publicly traded company
that runs the hourly child care at Minnesota's Mall of America and
19 casinos in six states, has had its struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an easy business,'' said Susan K. Dunkley, the
president of New Horizon. ``It's so unpredictable and you need to
staff people even if there are no children there. We're doing very
well in casinos in Las Vegas, Michigan and Connecticut, but the
hosts, whether it's casinos or shopping centers, need to understand
that it's an amenity they're going to have to subsidize in some
way, shape or form.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the overall financial impact of child-care programs is
unclear, many parents who use the programs say the availability of
child care is what made them customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only reason I joined this gym,'' said Lisette
Reisman, as she picked up her daughter, Simone, this week at the
Crunch gym on the Upper West Side in Manhattan, where child care
for children 6 months to 4 years is free to members. ``I looked at
other places with child care, like Reebok and New York Sports Club,
but they all charged extra, and here it's free to members. And
Simone loves it. I always have to drag her out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
