<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4885 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-ARRAU-MUSIC-SOLOS-$AD     05-24 1431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARRAU-MUSIC-SOLOS-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISITING AN IMPETUOUS YET PROBING VIRTUOSO ON CD 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 28) 
 By JOSEPH HOROWITZ    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the 20th century, a special glamour surrounded concert
pianists. Franz Liszt, the progenitor of the piano recital a
century before, was, of course, the king of this species. But
Liszt, who stopped touring at 35, was also a major composer and an
important teacher and conductor. The performance specialist,
championing previous generations of canonized composers, was a
20th-century phenomenon, embodied by such keyboard luminaries as
Vladimir Horowitz, Rudolf Serkin and Sviatoslav Richter: recreative
interpreters divorced from the creative act.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the purest exemplars of the solo pianist were Arthur
Rubinstein, and Claudio Arrau, who may be reheard in a recent
flurry of recordings. Unlike Serkin, Rubinstein and Arrau were not
major pedagogues. Unlike Richter, they rarely performed chamber
music. Unlike Horowitz, they maintained an uninterrupted schedule
of recitals and concertos, tirelessly visiting the musical capitals
of the world, performing more than 100 times a season: a rarefied
calling.
</P>
<P>
   Rubinstein's public career lasted 82 years; he gave his final
recital and made his last recordings at 89. Arrau's career,
strangely enough, also spanned 82 years; he last played in public
at 86 and recorded at 87. It seems safe to predict that no concert
pianist will again pursue a comparable regime.
</P>
<P>
   Liszt proclaimed, ``Le concert, c'est moi.'' The Rubinstein
experience radiated joie de vivre. Arrau embodied scenarios of
suffering and redemption. His life story, stranger than fiction
(unless by Garcia Marquez), mapped an exotic and tortuous odyssey
that was itself a source of fascination, not least for a young New
York Times critic _ this writer _ whose first book, in 1982, was a
study of Arrau the man and musician.
</P>
<P>
   Arrau was born in 1903 in Chillan, Chile, a dusty seven-hour
train ride from Santiago. His earliest memory was of his home
caving in during an earthquake. The ``Chilean Mozart,'' he read
music (and scribbled clefs and notes) before he could read words.
At 8, a national celebrity, he was sent abroad with a government
stipend. He wound up in Berlin, the favorite pupil of Martin
Krause, himself a pupil of Liszt. He played for kings and queens,
and under Nikisch and Steinbach.
</P>
<P>
   Krause, a surrogate father, died in 1918. Arrau refused to
submit to another teacher. In postwar Berlin, his career as a
prodigy collapsed. He supported himself and his mother, sister and
aunt by giving lessons; the family was reduced to pawning the
necklaces and bracelets with which he had once been showered by
royalty. With the help of psychoanalysis, he arduously consolidated
a mature artistic identity.
</P>
<P>
   World War II drove Arrau to the United States and a keyboard
culture, crowned by Horowitz, into which he did not fit. He lived
in Douglaston, Queens. He died in Munich. He was buried in Chillan.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1970s, when I undertook my ``Conversations With
Arrau,'' he had begun to retreat into a world without words. More
than ever, his world was music, and it ensnared him absolutely. To
see and hear him perform the Liszt Sonata was a frightening
experience. Then, in 1989, his wife of 52 years died. He told
friends he would never perform again, and he never did.
</P>
<P>
   I had lost touch with Arrau by the time he died in 1991. My
collection of Arrau LPs gathered dust for more than a decade. But
the recent spate of Arrau CD's reanimated my interest. ``Claudio
Arrau: The Early Years'' (Marston 52023-2; two CD's) includes
everything Arrau recorded from 1921 to 1939. And Philips' Great
Pianists of the 20th Century series includes three Arrau sets (456
706-2, 456 709-2, 456 712-2): six CD's with recordings extending
from 1928 to 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Though the repertory on these discs _ embracing Albeniz, Bach,
Balakirev, Busoni (an unforgettable 1928 version of the ``Carmen''
Fantasy), Debussy, Granados, Mozart and Stravinsky _ is remarkably
catholic, Arrau's core affinities included Chopin, Liszt and
Schumann at both ends of his long career. Comparing early and late
Arrau in the same music, I again find myself gripped by evidence of
an exceptionally fruitful and eventful artistic life cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Of the early recordings, the longest is of Schumann's
``Carnaval'' (1939). This is a ``modern'' performance, literal and
straightforward. Unlike Edwin Fischer, also a Krause pupil, Arrau
does not rewrite dynamics or poetically blur rests. Unlike Fischer,
he is an impetuous virtuoso. In fact, this is a dazzling
``Carnaval.'' But it is not, like Rachmaninoff's famously
diabolical version of 1929, specifically personal.
</P>
<P>
   To judge from recordings, Arrau did not acquire a highly
distinctive interpretive signature until he was in his 60s. This is
when he began probing every musical crevice, burrowing under and
around the written note to extract expression. The outcome was
complex: slower tempos, grander rubatos and, in profusion, the
accents pianists call agogics: stresses produced by delayed attack.
Arrau's style grew microscopically detailed. The straight lines of
his earlier interpretations acquired curves and detours.
</P>
<P>
   All this would have proved anarchic but for three consolidating
features of the Arrau style. First, rubatos aside, Arrau remained a
dogged literalist. Second, he retained his youthful facility: he
mastered the performer's art of combining poised physical
relaxation with maximum emotional expenditure. (His recommended
books included Eugen Herrigel's ``Zen in the Art of Archery.'')
Third, he commanded a liquid piano sonority, unsurpassed for tonal
depth and fullness of texture. No other pianist could flood a great
space with sounds as luminous and majestic.
</P>
<P>
   For some, Arrau's marriage of refinement and angst was perverse
or ponderous. For others, Arrau was revelatory. A performance like
his 1973 version of the Chopin Preludes (in the Great Pianists
collection) does not sound like any Chopin the composer might have
imagined. Discussing this music, Arrau used words like
``desolation,'' ``exasperation,'' ``desperation'' and, for the
opening C major salvo, ``orgasmic.'' The dark opulence of Arrau's
tonal palette and the 10-fingered breadth of articulation forge a
tragedy of epic proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Of the other performances in the Great Pianists sets, Chopin's F
minor Fantasy (1977) and Brahms' ``Paganini Variations'' (1974) are
distinctively regal. The Liszt Sonata (1970) and Beethoven's
``Waldstein'' Sonata (1963) and ``Emperor'' Concerto (1984), all
Arrau specialties, were recorded too early or too late.
</P>
<P>
   Arrau, who could claim no national cultural identity, took pride
in his eclecticism. But his later style _ like those of the
conductors Toscanini and Klemperer, also fanatic literalists _
formidably (yet unwittingly) personalized everything he touched.
That said, the composer he most inhabited was Liszt.
</P>
<P>
   He utterly lacked Lisztian irony or ease. His repugnance for
pianistic display canceled the fun of the Hungarian Rhapsodies. Yet
the Arrau sound _ its velvet blues and blacks _ ennobled Liszt. And
Liszt's religious strivings found in Arrau a true believer, immune
to sham. From Krause, Arrau inherited a reverence for Liszt the
man. He even portrayed Liszt in a 1936 Mexican film biography,
``Sueno de Amor,'' and wept playing the final scene.
</P>
<P>
   Rubinstein said of Busoni that he made Liszt's compositions
``sound even more important than they actually were.'' So it was
with Arrau (who heard and worshiped Busoni). The Great Pianists
CD's include two indelible examples.
</P>
<P>
   The first is a 1971 recording of a late and obscure paraphrase
of themes from ``Aida'': not a medley, but a concentrated
exploration of several ``Egyptian'' numbers and the final duet. On
the page, this music looks unprepossessing. In Arrau's hands, it is
grandly erotic: ``Tristan'' revisited.
</P>
<P>
   The second example, a 1976 recording of the ``Transcendental
Etude'' ``Chasse-Neige,'' defines Arrau's greatness in microcosm.
The vortex of shuddering, writhing tremolos peaks tremendously,
then recedes in exhaustion. The turbulence of Romantic
introspection and the pathos of Romantic retrospection are made
unbearably real. The combination of visceral intensity and
pianistic integrity _ every tremolo is thick with incident _ is
shattering. The performance is a fearless act of surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering Arrau, listening to his seven decades of recordings,
I mainly recall his humility.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
