<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-WITNESS0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Driver's testimony is key
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy and Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ray Lewis' limousine driver is one of the state's best
bets at getting incriminating testimony against the NFL star
linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   Duane Fassett cares deeply for Lewis, can identify all the
suspects and initially told police that he saw Lewis punch at one
of the stabbing victims.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Fassett gave a slightly different story.
</P>
<P>
   Then he gave another slightly different story. And then, again.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for all three defendants are sure to hammer away at
inconsistent statements he gave during a two-month period, trying
to show the jury that Fassett wasn't sure what he saw. Fassett also
is expected to give damaging testimony against Lewis'
co-defendants, Joseph Sweeting and Reginald Oakley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's probably the most unreliable and untrustworthy person
who'll get into that witness stand,'' John Bergendahl, Sweeting's
defense attorney, said in opening statements. Bergendahl counted
off four versions of Fassett's story, calling it an ``evolutionary
process to get testimony that fits the state's version.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassett appears to be the backbone of the prosecutors' case in
the double killing, because he identified all three defendants
attacking the two victims, Jacinth Baker, 21 and Richard Lollar,
24, and has no ties to the victims' party. Statements from Fassett
and Akron, Ohio, rap artist Jeff Gwen, who testified Wednesday, led
to the murder indictments.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett has flown to Atlanta from Baltimore and may testify
today.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, Fassett, 52, appeared to be a solid witness for
prosecutors. He not only admires Lewis, but he's a two-tour Vietnam
War veteran and is able to identify Lewis' co-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``He idolizes and loves Ray Lewis,'' said Paul Howard, in his
opening statement Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the consistent statements have left ample room for defense
attorneys to counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett's lawyer, David B. Irwin of Baltimore, said Wednesday
that his client ``will do his absolute best to be straight down the
middle on exactly what he remembers.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin acknowledged that Fassett has given different versions to
police.
</P>
<P>
   ``But every witness gives inconsistent statements if they're
repeatedly asked questions over hours at a time on several
different occasions,'' he added. ``This can be because they're
tired or worried or a lot of other things.'' Fassett will give
jurors ``his best recollection of what happened,'' Irwin said.
</P>
<P>
   A review of those finds that Fassett originally said he knew
little about the deadly brawl, then more and again, more. Then he
seemed to back off and hedge in a later statement.
</P>
<P>
   And in a murder scene re-enactment in Baltimore, Fassett
recounted the events of the fatal night as if conjuring up a
vision.
</P>
<P>
   In his initial statement to police, just four hours after the
incident, Fassett said, ``I did not see (the fight); I do not know
why it occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said ``I do not know where Ray was at or what he was
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that evening, Fassett told police he was ``pretty sure''
that Oakley flipped Baker and then started punching him in the
torso. He also said he saw Sweeting hitting another man by the
tree. That man, police said, was Lollar.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Fassett said he saw Lewis throw a punch at Lollar.
</P>
<P>
   However, in that statement, he said Sweeting hit one of the
victims with a bottle. In reality, it was Baker who smashed the
bottle over Oakley's head.
</P>
<P>
   As they fled in the limo, Fassett told police, ``I could hear
someone saying `I took care of him' or `we took care of them', I
believe it was (Oakley) saying this. I am not sure if (Sweeting)
said this.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Fassett made this statement, Lewis was arrested on
murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Fassett was more definitive.
</P>
<P>
   The punch he said Lewis threw landed in Lollar's lower chest.
</P>
<P>
   Also, ``I heard (Oakley) say `I stabbed him' and (Sweeting) say
`I stabbed him, too,' '' Fassett told police.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he heard Lewis make a comment, Fassett responded,
``Nothing but `let's get out of here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But in a later statement, Fassett expanded on that: ``Let's get
the (expletive) out of here. Keep your (expletive) mouths shut. My
football career is not going to end like this.''
</P>
<P>
   This statement was used by prosecutors in the grand jury to gain
Lewis' indictment date.
</P>
<P>
   On March 30, Fulton prosecutors and Atlanta police went to
Baltimore to perform a re-enactment at the limousine service's
office. According to notes taken by homicide detective Ken Allen,
Fassett recalls what he saw as if conjuring up a vision.
</P>
<P>
   Fassett recounted the fight and then stopped, Allen wrote,
noting he then pressed Fassett to continue. At this point, Allen
wrote, Fassett's hands started shaking, he lit a cigarette and
looked toward the area where the stabbings where to have occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Allen said he continued to press Fassett, asking him what he
saw. ``I see Ray,'' Fassett finally replied. ``He is down by
(Sweeting).''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
