r e BC-FILM-PASSIONOFMIND-TE     05-24 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PASSIONOFMIND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO SLEEP, PERCHANCE TO DREAM; UH-OH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of us escape into fantasy lives, usually through something
as simple and harmless as daydreaming. Few of us find our dreams as
complicated or distressingly realistic as Marie (Demi Moore) does.
Marie's a widow and free-lance book reviewer raising a couple of
daughters in the French countryside. Life is pretty normal until
she nods off to sleep at night _ and wakes up in Manhattan, where
she's a hotshot literary agent named Marty, and her mama pajamas
have been replaced by designer silk.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it the other way around _ is Marty dreaming she's Marie?
That's the mystery behind ``Passion,'' which takes an intriguing
psychological premise and dresses it up in romance-novel colors.
Extra shadings are provided by the moody writer (Stellan Skarsgard)
who woos her in France, and the breezy nice guy (William Fichtner)
who pursues her in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other recent movies about dual realities, ``Passion''
presents us with a protagonist who knows that one of her realities
is an illusion. She's just not sure which one, and even has a
psychiatrist in each version to help her figure things out. Because
she enjoys a healthy amount of lovemaking, it's tough to see why
she would complain, except that the guys are getting jealous of
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Director Alain Berliner (''Ma Vie En Rose'') manages to tread a
fine line between the movie's Harlequin-paperback sensibilities and
its darker psychological tone, and Moore is pretty good. The
resolution is predictably unsatisfying and wraps things up too
neatly, and the movie stumbles toward sappiness a little too often.
But it's one of the better recent meditations on fate, and just
interesting enough to keep you watching in spite of its flaws. Or
did I just dream that? &QL; 
 &QL; 
FILM: ``Passion of Mind'' &QL; 
RUNNING TIME: 105 minutes &QL; 
RATING: PG-13 &QL; 
SCORE: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a movie critic for the Star-Telegram. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
