<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4894 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-LABOR0525-COX     05-24 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-LABOR0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Labor dispute may pose quandary for Gore
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Gore, who has taken heat from union
leaders over his position on free trade with China, will soon find
himself in the midst of another labor battle brewing in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees union
plan to launch a union organizing drive today at the Loews Santa
Monica Hotel, one of six major beachfront hotels in the ritzy Los
Angeles suburb, and one of the many hotels that will house
Democratic committees and organizations during the Democratic
National Convention in August.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury hotel is managed by the Loews Hotels chain out of New
York. Jonathan Tisch, the company's president and CEO, is a friend
of Gore's and one of his top fund-raisers on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, HERE, the 300,000-member restaurant and hotel union,
is aggressively backing Gore for president.
</P>
<P>
   Expecting a tough fight over the Loews, Maria Elena Durazo, a
HERE vice president and the head of Local 11 in Los Angeles, said
she hopes Gore and other Democrats _ including Tisch _ will ``take
the side of the workers'' and support the organizing effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just not going to have the kind of money to compete with
the big dollars, but I think if Mr. Tisch cares about the
Democratic Party . . . he understands how important this is,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The union's drive to organize the maids, bartenders and waiters
at the Loews hotel, part of a citywide campaign to organize
nonunion hotels, could also threaten the tranquillity of the
Democratic convention Aug. 14-17. Unlike Philadelphia, where
Republican convention organizers secured written promises of labor
peace when the party comes to town July 31, Democratic convention
organizers have received no such assurances.
</P>
<P>
   Convention organizers are seeking an agreement from Los Angeles
labor leaders not to strike or disrupt the Staples Center, where
the main convention events will take place, but it won't cover any
of the scores of hotels and off-site venues where delegates will be
staying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want our right to picket at nonconvention sites to be
respected,'' said Durazo, singling out the Loews.
</P>
<P>
   The support of organized labor is critical to Gore's election
prospects, and the vice president has been careful to nurture his
relationship with the major unions affiliated with the AFL-CIO,
which endorsed him last fall.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Gore joined striking janitors in a Santa Monica park
and voiced his support for a new contract between the janitors
union and commercial building owners.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Gore refused to cross a picket line of striking
hotel workers in Cleveland to address the National Summit on
Africa, whose members were meeting at the Grand Hyatt there.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past week, facing labor's anger over his support of
permanent normal trade relations with China, Gore has delivered two
speeches to labor groups, emphasizing his support of minimum-wage
increases, commitment to Social Security and other priorities of
organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the vice president strongly supports giving workers
the tools they need to organize,'' said Gore spokesman Chris
Lehane. ``We make every effort, when possible, to stay at union
hotels. About Tisch, he's obviously a friend and supporter and we
have great respect for him. But the vice president has a policy of
not involving himself in the private business of his supporters.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore also has a long history with Tisch, one of the heirs to
the $21.5 billion Loews empire that includes the nation's
third-largest property and casualty insurance company and Lorillard
Tobacco, makers of Kent, Newport and True cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Tisch, who declined to comment, served as a vice chairman to
Gore's 1993 inaugural committee, and he contributed $35,000 to a
fund established to make improvements to Gore's official residence
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to regulated contributions to Gore's presidential
campaign, Tisch has also contributed $65,500 in soft money to the
Democratic Party, according to the databases at the Center for
Responsive Politics. During the 1998 elections, Tisch contributed
$120,000 in soft money to the Democrats, according to the center's
records.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Kelman, a spokesman for Loews, said Tisch's political work
for Gore was ``completely separate'' from his job with Loews.
Regarding the organizing drive at the Loews Santa Monica, Kelman
said, ``It's the decision of the employees of the property to
decide whether or not to unionize.''
</P>
<P>
   The Loews Santa Monica Hotel is one of Loews Hotels' 16 luxury
hotels in the United States and Canada, four of which are
unionized.
</P>
<P>
   It occupies a prime piece of real estate on Ocean Avenue in
Santa Monica, a palm tree-lined boulevard with breathtaking views
of the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials say the housekeepers at the Loews recently
staged a work stoppage to protest working conditions, and they
point to the situation of workers such as Favian Gonzalez as proof
that Loews workers need union benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, a 29-year-old lobby bar waiter, said he was, until
recently, working as a banquet hall waiter for 12 to 14 hours a
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't know if I was going to eat or not,'' he said.
``We literally had to hide in corners and eat something real
quick.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
