<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-TOURISM-2TAKES(1160)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NORTH CAROLINA TOWN PROSPERS AS THE VALHALLA OF NASCAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Texas, Nev., Calif., Ill., Kan., N.C., Va., Ind.,
Mich., Wis.)   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOORESVILLE, N.C. _ Nothing about the reflecting glass exterior
of DEI Inc. offers a clue that inside is an exalted garage built to
harvest the fastest 720-horsepower beasts in stock car racing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet starstruck pilgrims in shorts and T shirts know this
Brobdignagian race shop with unexpectedly elegant touches was built
by Dale Earnhardt, stock car racing's all-time money-winner, and
that once past its doors, homage is paid to the deities of speed.
</P>
<P>
   They arrive in cars, vans and motor homes to gaze at a complex
created by Earnhardt and his wife, Teresa for their three drivers _
including Dale Jr., who has won three Winston Cup races this year _
and to tour the 8,000 square feet devoted to a showroom and gift
shop brimming with souvenirs like Earnhardt caps, Earnhardt robes
and Earnhardt Monopoly games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my temple,'' Nick Smith, a carpet layer from Newburgh,
Ind., said last week, raising his arms to the ceiling of the $15
million racing shop dubbed the ``Garage Mahal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of my friends came here last year and said, `You
definitely have to come here,''' Smith said. ``I've been a fan for
15 or 16 years. He's just Earnhardt. `The Intimidator.' He's the
man.''
</P>
<P>
   The splendor Earnhardt has created would be unrecognizable to
past drivers for Nascar, or the National Association for Stock Car
Auto Racing, like Earnhardt's father, Ralph, Junior Johnson and
Fireball Roberts. But so would nearly all the other one-
and-two-story racing shops in Mooresville.
</P>
<P>
   As auto racing heads into its biggest weekend of the year _ with
not only the Indianapolis 500 taking place on Sunday, but Nascar's
Coca-Cola 600 at nearby Lowe's Motor Speedway as well _ tens of
thousands of fans will converge on what has become home to the
nation's largest cluster of Nascar race shops.
</P>
<P>
   The passing of the grease monkey image here in the booming
suburbs north of Charlotte mirrors Nascar's growth into a
juggernaut with total revenues of $1.56 billion this year,
according to Paul Kagan Associates, the media research firm.
</P>
<P>
   That includes sponsors paying millions of dollars to tack their
names on cars and races, retail sales of more than $1 billion in
licensed merchandise and new TV deals worth $400 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   Tracks in Florida, Texas, Nevada and California opened recently
to exploit Nascar's popularity. New speedways near Chicago and
Kansas City will open next year, while speculation continues that a
track may be built in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Everything in Nascar starts with four-speed Chevy Monte Carlos,
Ford Tauruses and Pontiac Grand Prix that are assembled, filleted,
reassembled, engineered, tested, painted and covered with logos at
shops like Earnhardt's.
</P>
<P>
   The shops, including those not associated with Nascar, employ
1,444 workers in Mooresville, more than any other local industry.
This former textile mill town saw its last plant, one that made
denim for Burlington Industries, close last summer.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Mooresville had reinvented itself as ``Race City USA,''
because of the 24 Nascar race shops that fabricate vehicles for 32
drivers on Nascar's Winston Cup, Busch Grand National and Craftsman
Truck circuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the mills died, the shops gave Mooresville the identity it
needed and an economic engine for growth,'' said Jack Cathey, an
accounting professor at the University of North Carolina at
Charlotte, who publishes an annual Zagat-like guide and rating
service for Nascar shops.
</P>
<P>
   Once, Mooresville believed that tourists would come to the town
of 18,000 to vacation on Lake Norman. ``Everybody thought that was
the attraction of the future,'' said Dan Wallace, executive
director of the Mooresville/South Iredell Chamber of Commerce.
``Then came the racing business. Who knew?''
</P>
<P>
   The town and county have never offered tax or financial
incentives to lure the race shops to Mooresvile. They just kept
coming.
</P>
<P>
   The concentration of shops has made it common to see families
and tour groups enter Lakeside Business Park (make a left at the
Chick-Fil-A on Highway 150) to make the rounds of 12 Nascar race
shops, another dozen shops unrelated to Nascar, and the North
Carolina Auto Racing Hall of Fame. Tourism soars in the days before
the Winston Cup races at Lowe's Motor Speedway, 15 minutes away in
Concord, N.C.: the Coca-Cola 600, which takes place Sunday night,
The Winston, which was run last Saturday and the UAW-GM Quality 500
in October.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance concerns persuaded all but a few shops from offering
behind-the-scene tours, where visitors could see a dozen or more
cars per driver in various stages of construction. Tourists are
left to admire cars from behind viewing windows or they get only as
close as a lobby with souvenirs and race-used cars.
</P>
<P>
   Everett Brooks was examining one of Ricky Rudd's (NU)28
Texaco/Havoline Fords last week at Robert Yates Racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a fascination,'' said Brooks, a retired machine shop
supervisor from Petersburg, Va., who was making the rounds of shops
for the first time in three years. ``I like to see what's new. It's
unbelievable. Half the shops that are here now weren't here then.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd, who owned the shop before selling it to Yates last year to
refocus on racing, said his one regret in designing the shop in
1994 was not offering fans a viewing window. ``In hindsight, I
would have let them look in,'' he said. Next door, fans quietly
watched Roush Racing mechanics tend to Mark Martin's and Jeff
Burton's Fords for The Winston.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Dale Earnhardt Jr. won the $500,000 prize for first
place, a pedestrian walkway outside Lowe's Motor Speedway
collapsed, injuring more than 100 people leaving the 175,000-seat
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Among the fans who journeyed here for the race was Tom Bowen, a
construction worker from Battle Creek, Mich., on a Nascar holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Compared with seeing these cars on TV, this is the only chance
to see them up close,'' said Bowen, wearing a Dale Earnhardt Jr. T
shirt. ``Being this close to things I've seen all my life is
amazing. My father raced `55 Chevys and he hated Dale Earnhardt.
But he's getting old now.''
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years ago, Lakeside rejected two owners of race shops
who wanted to relocate to the hilly business park. ``We were
unfamiliar with racing and thought they'd be dirty, with wrecked
cars out front,'' said Cecile Ebert, the park's general manager.
``Turns out you can eat off the floor of these garages.''
</P>
<P>
   Ebert now comprehends the full meaning of Nascar: 60 percent of
Lakeside's 170 businesses are racing related. Even if nearby
Concord is offering incentives for shops to relocate, she's certain
teams will stay in Mooresville for its low-key lifestyle and its
proximity to interstate highways, airports and Lowe's Motor
Speedway and other southeastern tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Said Rudd, ``I live on the lake 7 miles away, so when I was
looking to build a shop, I wanted to be nearby. And my wife has a
knack for real estate.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Felix Sabates Jr., whose Team Sabco is led by the Winston Cup
drivers Sterling Marlin and Kenny Irwin, said Mooresville's shops
are too crucial to the local economy to lose to rival cities like
Concord.
</P>
<P>
   ``Iredell County won't let them take anybody away,'' said
Sabates, who has more than doubled the size of his complex since
moving to Lakeside in 1995. ``Our first shop could have fit in
here,'' he added, gesturing from behind a massive desk to his
massive second-floor office.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Berken, a carpenter from Fox Valley, Wis., walked
respectfully through the trophy room of Penske Racing South, Rusty
Wallace's shop, which lets fans peer into the working garage. ``I
took three days off to see the shops and go to the race,'' he said.
``This is as close as we've ever gotten to the cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Berken, who lives near Green Bay, is a Packers' fan. ``They'd
never let you this close to a practice field,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The behemoth of Mooresville is Earnhardt's elegant
176,000-square-foot complex. He doesn't drive for DEI _ racing
instead for Richard Childress, out of Welcome, N.C. _ but he is the
undisputed icon here, a regular presence to employees, occasional
visitors and fans admiring his and his drivers' trophies, their
race-winning cars and his knife and boat collections.
</P>
<P>
   DEI has a dining room that resembles a gentleman's club, red
velvet elevator walls, cream-colored carpeting and an array of
ceilings with reflective tiles, gold medallions and polished wood.
``That comes from my wife's experience as an interior decorator,''
Earnhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can also watch a loop of his TV commercials or buy his
leather jackets, diecast miniatures of his (NU)3 GM Goodwrench
Chevrolet, backpacks and energy bars.
</P>
<P>
   But he will not permit fans to view the mechanics at work.
``These guys work hard, and to have interruptions is no good,'' he
said. ``They're doing a job and they have business to do. I didn't
build this to give tours.''
</P>
<P>
   Not every race team can afford a $15 million shop. MB2, which
owns Kenny Schrader's M&AMP;M's Pontiac, is in a hangar-like shop too
cramped for its production needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The building doesn't make you go faster,'' said Jay Frye, the
general manager of MB2, which is contemplating a new, larger home
in nearby Concord. ``So we don't use our building as an excuse. We
see a lot of great buildings and when you look at the points
standings, we're higher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
