<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4900 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ALAMIN-TAPES0525-COX     05-24 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAMIN-TAPES0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Al-Amin attorneys probe mystery
 &HT;    By Joshua B. Good
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Could there be another suspect in the slaying of
Fulton Deputy Ricky Kinchen?
</P>
<P>
   A sheriff's dispatch tape from the night Kinchen and his partner
Aldranon English were shot reveals fellow deputies searched for a
wounded gunman and surrounded an abandoned house in Atlanta's West
End where blood was found.
</P>
<P>
   English thought he shot his assailant. And minutes after the
shooting, a man was seen bleeding and begging for a ride five
blocks from the shooting scene, recently released Atlanta police
records show.
</P>
<P>
   The only person charged in the case is Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin,
formerly known as H. Rap Brown. Federal agents caught him in
Alabama four days after the shooting. Al-Amin had not been shot and
had no wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin says he's innocent, and the case is a government
conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   The discrepancies are certain to be exploited by Jack Martin and
Bruce Harvey, Al-Amin's defense attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Martin filed a motion seeking any police evidence of
another person at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is looking for the dispatch tape, reports about the blood
and any evidence about anyone wounded in West End the night of
March 16.
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting, one 911 caller reported an injured man on
Westview. ``Caller advises perp in a vacant building on Westview
bleeding begging for a ride,'' a dispatcher typed into the log of
the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Police have not released further details about the bleeding man
or the 911 caller.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic tape of Fulton County Sheriff's Department radio
traffic is filled with discrepancies from deputies who showed up
after the shooting was over. Most important, the tape records the
account of the state's best witness _ English.
</P>
<P>
   On the recording, the night starts out routinely. English asks a
dispatcher to find out who a car is registered to. The car, which
doesn't appear to be connected to the shooting, was parked on Oak
Street in front of Al-Amin's grocery store. English and Kinchen
were there to arrest Al-Amin on a warrant from Cobb County.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, English comes back on the radio screaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officer down! Officer down! 63! Officer Down! Officer Down!
Officer Down! 63!,'' he shouts, breathing heavily as six shots are
heard.
</P>
<P>
   The number 63 is the signal for officer down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unit. Advise your unit number,'' the dispatcher says.
</P>
<P>
   ``82! 82! Radio. 82!,'' English yells as four more shots ring
out. ``At Oak Street. 1182 Oak Street. 1128 Oak Street. Radio. I've
been shot. Officer down.''
</P>
<P>
   A deputy who is not on the scene but hears English's call for
help comes on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you advise a location?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   English says: ``1182. 1182. I've been shot. 1182 Oak Street.
Officer down. 1182 Oak Street, West End. Off of West End Place.''
</P>
<P>
   Before help arrives, English tells the dispatcher that the
shooter drove away in a black Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   Separate ambulances took English and Kinchen to Grady Memorial
Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies who arrive on the scene begin to search for the
shooter. It's chaotic. Several deputies try to talk on the radio at
the same time. They give conflicting reports of where the shooter
might be. Some say he is in a car; others say he is on foot. One
report mentions the possibility of a man with an M-16 rifle in a
trench coat behind the nearby video store.
</P>
<P>
   An Atlanta officer finds blood drops around an abandoned house
at 1180 Eggleston St. Police surround the house. The SWAT team goes
inside, but no gunman is found.
</P>
<P>
   Kinchen died the next day. He had been shot by a .223-caliber
rifle and a 9mm handgun.
</P>
<P>
   In the hospital, English looked at a group of photographs of men
and identified Al-Amin as the shooter.
</P>
<P>
   A rifle and handgun were found in the woods where Al-Amin was
arrested in White Hall, Ala. Tests showed they were the same guns
used to shoot Kinchen, according to the FBI. Al-Amin's shot-up
black Mercedes was also found in Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution, defense attorneys and police would comment
about the the possibility of another suspect, citing a court order.
</P>
<P>
   But Gwinnett County District Attorney Danny Porter said it is
not unusual to have different versions of what happened in a
violent crime.
</P>
<P>
   Porter prosecuted Byron Fleming, who was convicted of killing
Gwinnett County Deputy Ken Wimberly, though three witnesses gave
varying accounts of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have to sift through lots of evidence to reach a coherent
version of what happened out there,'' Porter said of Fulton County
prosecutors. ``That's what a prosecutor's job is.''
</P>
<P>
   Who was the closest to the action? Who is more credible? How was
Kinchen shot? Who does the blood match?
</P>
<P>
   Porter said those are all questions the prosecution will try to
answer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
