<HEADER>
A4903 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-JASPERJOHNS-INDALLAS-     05-24 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPERJOHNS-INDALLAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JASPER JOHNS CAN STILL HIT THE TARGET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW MARTON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is always heartening to realize that, at least occasionally,
our youth-obsessed culture still can be stopped dead in its tracks
by an old-guard artistic presence.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper Johns is just the artist to make even the most callow of
culture's young arbiters take notice. The title of the Dallas
Museum of Art's new exhibit, ``Jasper Johns: New Paintings and
Works on Paper,'' delivers the news flash that the 69-year-old
Johns has emerged from a noticeable absence with fresh work. The
dozen paintings, drawings and prints in the exhibit are hardly an
overwhelming canon, but they do allow one to explore the new vistas
Johns has chosen and to become reacquainted with his distinctive
style.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, to absorb the full impact of this exhibition requires
a bit of history. As one of the great levers in abstract
expressionism's move toward pop art, Johns developed a distinctive
iconographic style during the 1950s, when his target and flag
motifs became legendary. In a series of influential works during
that period, he called upon assertive tints of orange and cobalt
blue _ and used wooden stretchers as striking appendages to his
canvases _ to brand his work on the collective memory.
</P>
<P>
   Johns secured his influential place in 20th-century American art
by using a highly personal, quasipsychological take on the everyday
as a guiding theme. By adopting definite symbols such as numbers or
the flag, Johns persevered in his representational style while the
entire American art movement was consumed with abstract
expressionism and that school's steadfast avoidance of identifiable
objects.
</P>
<P>
   The pieces in this DMA exhibition not only echo but expand on
Johns' early command of boisterous color and his unusual flair for
using wood and string. ``Bridge'' (1997) immediately sets the tone
for the exhibit with its cluster of harlequinlike diamond shapes
filled with pastel colors on one border, and a piece of string
draped across the canvas, a lithe ``bridge'' defying gravity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Untitled (Halloween)'' (1998) shifts the focus but keeps
certain aesthetic ingredients intact. The harlequin shapes have
been expanded to include triangles and pentagons as their colors
become muddier. A naively traced Big Dipper is reprised as well, a
constellation ally to Johns' ever-present string bridge.
</P>
<P>
   What the string traverses, and the harlequin shades revitalize,
is a Johns canvas that is an expanse colored a dark pewter. It is
the lugubrious tint of sea fog, creating a soupy opaqueness found
most often in the mist hanging over a New England fishing village
at dawn.
</P>
<P>
   Although ``Catenary'' (1998) lacks Johns' leavening use of
jester colors, the work's pond-algae tone represents a welcome
shift in hue. In fact, the thickness of Johns' application of paint
on this and the other works in his ``Catenary'' series call to mind
the aquatic rippling one perceives in Monet's ``Waterlilies.''
</P>
<P>
   As if Johns understood that the thematic territory he was plying
needed some shaking up, his ``Untitled'' (1999) brings a welcome
contrast. While keeping the motifs of string and diamonds, Johns
has pushed his palette toward a softer lilac hue. And he has made
the jarring inclusion of a lime-green, prison-barred window in one
corner balanced by a sepia-toned family portrait in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, in this new exhibit, Johns' confidence in his craft has
reached such a zenith that the ultimate in representational art _ a
family photo _ does not diminish the dexterity of his abstraction. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Jasper Johns: New Paintings and Works on Paper'' &QL; 
Through Aug. 13 &QL; 
Dallas Museum of Art _ South Quadrant Galleries &QL; 
1717 N. Harwood, Dallas &QL; 
Admission is free &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
