<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4905 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-SOCSEC-NYT &LR;      05-24 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SOCSEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S SECOND THOUGHTS ON STOCK INVESTMENTS
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD W. STEVENSON and JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore said Wednesday that the
stock market was an attractive place for Americans to invest over
the long run, but that it was the wrong place to seek a solution to
Social Security's problems.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Gore reiterated his strong opposition to Gov.
George W. Bush's proposal to allow people to invest part of their
Social Security taxes on Wall Street. And he defended his own
decision to back away from his early support for allowing the
government itself to invest in stocks on Social Security's behalf,
citing problems created by having the government as a major
shareholder of a company.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, the market has not generated returns as
consistently strong as he had once assumed it would.
</P>
<P>
   ``The learning experience that we went through convinced all of
us that it was a bad idea,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Tracing the evolution of his thinking about Social Security and
the financial markets, Gore said that he had kept an open mind to
many possible solutions to the retirement system's problems when
the Clinton administration first began examining the issue in
earnest a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the administration proposed a plan, backed by Gore,
under which the government would begin channeling hundreds of
billions of dollars in additional money into Social Security out of
general tax revenues starting in 2011. Under the plan, half of the
new money going to Social Security would be invested by the
government in stocks, up to a maximum of 15 percent of Social
Security's total reserves.
</P>
<P>
   The administration dropped the plan last year in the face of
intense opposition from Republicans, revived it in its budget
proposal early this year, then dropped it again as it became clear
that Social Security would be one of the most heatedly debated
issues of the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has sought to use Gore's on-again, off-again
support for government investment in the stock market to undermine
the vice president's assertions that Social Security benefits
should not be dependent on Wall Street. And Bush's aides said
Gore's reversal on the issue suggested that he was prepared to
sacrifice principles to make a short-term political point.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a growing sense that Al Gore has never had a
conviction which he could not easily change,'' said Ari Fleischer,
Bush's spokesman. ``He was clearly on record as advocating and
supporting government investment in the market. Now he's walking
away from something he advocated as recently as 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Some advisers to Gore said the vice president had dropped his
support for government investment in part to make it easier for him
to attack Bush's approach.
</P>
<P>
   But in the interview, on the porch of his home on the grounds of
the Naval Observatory, Gore sought to play down the degree to which
he had supported the concept, and said that in any case he had
changed his mind as he learned more about the tradeoffs it would
require.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he had been swayed in part by criticism of the idea
from Alan Greenspan, the chairman of the Federal Reserve. Greenspan
opposed the plan on the grounds that politicians would not be able
to resist using the government's role as a shareholder to favor or
punish certain industries or to meddle in corporate decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magnitude of the government's stock ownership would be
such that it would at least raise the question of whether or not we
had begun to change the fundamental nature of our economy,'' Gore
said. ``Upon reflection, it seemed to me that those problems were
quite serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Gore said, he became convinced that Wall Street's ups
and downs were large enough to create a risk that the government
might be making a bad investment. During long stretches, including
one from the late 1960s to the early 1980s, Wall Street was by no
means the one-way bet it has often been viewed as in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore receives income from some stock technically owned
by his mother, he owns no stock, and has never actively invested in
the market. He said he had chosen to stay out of the market when he
first was elected to Congress in 1976 to avoid any conflicts of
interest, not out of fear of risk, and that he supported a variety
of proposals to promote savings and investment.
</P>
<P>
   But he said investment in the markets should ``come on top of
Social Security,'' rather than as a replacement for it. And he said
that Bush's economic policies, including his big tax cut and his
need to use much of the Social Security surplus to pay for the
creation of private accounts, would undermine the fiscal discipline
that helped propel the markets upward in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's approach ``contains the seeds of its own destruction by
virtually guaranteeing a weaker economy, and thus, you would
expect, a weaker market, with lower returns than what we've seen in
these boom years,'' Gore said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
