<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0394 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4906 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CHINA-REACT-0525-COX     05-24 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-REACT-0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOR CHINESE CITIZENS, HOUSE BILL'S PASSAGE WILL IMPROVE
U.S.-CHINA RELATIONS
 &HT;    With CHINA-TRADE-0525.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By JULIE CHAO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Ordinary Chinese citizens say they know China has
human rights problems, but they're sure glad that from now on they
won't have to hear about them every year from American politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's embarrassing,'' said Chi Lianhua, 35, who works at an
insurance company, ``for such a big country to always be criticized
and have others playing the cop. We always feel like we're
inferior.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. House of Representatives vote Wednesday to approve a
landmark trade bill with China restores normal trade ties with the
world's most populous country, and ends the annual debate in
Congress over human rights and just about everything else in China.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese government had not commented on the House bill's passage
as of Wednesday night (EDT).
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the economic implications, many Chinese citizens see the
vote as a sign that the United States will finally treat the
relationship between the two countries _ which has fluctuated
dramatically for at least a decade _ as one of two equals rather
than that of a parent scolding or rewarding a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, America wasn't too friendly to China,'' said Shi
Yue, a 23-year-old bank employee. ``When it persists in pushing
human rights, that limits progress in other areas. (Passage of the
trade bill) means definite improvement in China-U.S. relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress' annual review of China's trade status has been loud
and contentious since 1989, when the Chinese government opened fire
on democracy demonstrators at Tiananmen Square. That yearly debate
``held all other issues hostage,'' said a China scholar, while
politicians and interest groups battled it out over China's
treatment of everything from dissidents and workers to religious
groups and environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``That rhetoric fueled tension in the relationship that
exaggerated all problems and contributed to oscillations,'' said
Mary Brown Bullock, who has been studying China for 30 years and is
a member of the National Committee on U.S.-China Relations.
``Passage (of the trade bill) will stabilize U.S.-China relations
in a way it has not been stable for at least 12 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The next 10 years you'll be forging a relationship between a
more mature China and the United States ... a less paternalistic
relationship,'' added Bullock, also president of Agnes Scott
College in Atlanta, and now in Beijing on one of her annual visits.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese citizens interviewed in Beijing say they see the annul
debate as anti-China forces trying to restrict China.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just politicians playing games,'' said Yang Min, who
works at a British petroleum company. ``Their main issue is not
trade. Now they will lose their bargaining counter for pressuring
China.''
</P>
<P>
   The trade bill, which is expected to easily win Senate approval,
will permanently guarantee Chinese goods the same low-tariff access
to U.S. markets as products from nearly every other nation.
</P>
<P>
   More significantly, its passage was also part of a trade
agreement reached between the two countries last November, in which
China agreed to open its market to a wide range of products in
order to gain entry into the World Trade Organization. After
Wednesday's vote, U.S. businesses will be able to take advantage of
the concessions _ including elimination of trade barriers on
everything from agriculture to semiconductors.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. companies in China were predictably elated and relieved by
the vote, which came early Thursday morning (Beijing time). United
Parcel Service expects American companies will ship a lot more
things like computers and telecommunications and medical equipment
to China, and it hopes UPS will be the carrier of choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be more high-value products to ship to
China,'' said Stephen Monaghan, UPS spokesman for the Asia-Pacific
region. ``I think that's going to have a direct impact on the trade
balance.''
</P>
<P>
   However, a Chinese labor activist feared that elimination of the
annual review of China's trade status will remove pressure on the
Chinese government _ as U.S. labor unions and other interest groups
have argued _ but not on U.S. companies running sweatshops in
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be an encouragement for them to keep doing bad
things ... and exploiting Chinese workers,'' said Han Dongfang,
arrested after the 1989 protests for organizing workers and now
living in exile in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. President Bill Clinton and others have argued that only by
engaging China and urging it to open economically can other reforms
follow, such as allowing workers to organize unions.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Chinese, Chi, the insurance company employee,
acknowledges China needs reform in many areas but doesn't like
other countries telling it what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if we won't care about it if other countries don't
press us on it,'' she said. ``Besides, human rights is just a
slogan for them.''
</P>
<P>
   (Julie Chao's E-mail address is: juliec(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For news from China's official media, see:
</P>
<P>
   www.china.org.cn/English/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
