<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4910 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-24 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUANDARY ON GENERIC AUTO PARTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MOHL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Do the use of generic parts in auto repairs compromise vehicle
safety?
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, an obscure Massachusetts board narrowly
concluded they do. After weeks of intense lobbying from insurance
companies and auto body shops, the board will now decide whether to
stand by its earlier vote or move in a different direction.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome could affect whether cheaper generics or more
expensive manufacturer parts are used for auto repairs in
Massachusetts and possibly lead to higher rates for insurance, by
some estimates as much as $37 a year more per vehicle. Other state
are facing a similar quandary.
</P>
<P>
   To keep insurance rates down in Massachusetts, state regulations
require the use of cheaper generics (or rebuilt or used brand-name
parts) unless a new brand-name part is available at a lower price
or the car being repaired has less than 15,000 miles on it. Generic
parts are supposed to be used only if they are ``of like kind and
quality'' to a brand-name part manufactured by the likes of Ford,
Toyota, and GM.
</P>
<P>
   Auto-body shops have long insisted that generic parts don't fit
properly and don't match the quality of manufacturer parts. But
their complaints usually were dismissed as sour grapes, since they
make more money installing the more expensive manufacturer parts.
</P>
<P>
   But concern about generics, sometimes called aftermarket parts,
intensified in the wake of a scathing Consumer Reports article last
year that suggested the parts may be unsafe, and a billion-dollar
court judgment in Illinois against State Farm Mutual Life Insurance
Co. for using inferior generics.
</P>
<P>
   After the State Farm decision, many Massachusetts automobile
insurers stopped using generic parts outside the state but kept
using them here because of the state regulation.
</P>
<P>
   With all the controversy, state Insurance Commissioner Linda
Ruthardt asked the appraiser board to investigate and report back
to her. They held a series of hearings that were packed with
officials from both sides of the debate but almost no real
consumers, since they largely are unaware of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month the board voted 3-2 in favor of a motion that
stated: ``All structural aftermarket parts are not of like kind and
quality to original equipment manufacturers and therefore
aftermarket structural parts compromise the overall safety of the
vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert W. Cox Jr. is chairman of the Auto Damage Appraiser
Licensing Board, which was directed by Ruthardt to investigate the
safety of generic automobile hoods, bumpers, and fenders. Cox said
one of the things the board will have to refine is what is meant by
structural aftermarket parts. Those who support the use of generic
parts say the hoods, fenders, and bumpers in question are cosmetic
parts that don't affect the safety of a vehicle. Generic parts are
used already, with little fuss, for many other auto parts,
including brake pads, batteries, spark plugs, and other
accessories.
</P>
<P>
   If the board ends up condemning generic parts as unsafe and
Ruthardt decides to ban their use, it would mean manufacturer parts
would gain a monopoly in auto repairs. Insurers have estimated an
insurance rider requiring the use of manufacturer parts for repairs
would cost drivers an extra $37 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Gillis, executive director of an organization that
certifies the quality of generic parts, said he was puzzled by the
board's initial vote. ``I don't know of anything that would have
enabled them to come to that conclusion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Colo, president of the Massachusetts Auto Body
Association, said he was surprised how strong the initial motion
was worded. But he wasn't sure what the final motion will say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're funny like that. When they reconsider, they sometimes
go the other way,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
