<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4911 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-UNITED0525-COX     05-24 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITED0525-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Effect of United Airlines merger still up in the air
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - With its bold move to buy US Airways, United Airlines
has trumped rivals Delta and American and forced them to pursue
their own acquisitions in coming months to keep pace.
</P>
<P>
   That's one widely held view of the fallout from the United-US
Airways deal, which was formally announced Wednesday by the two
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Simply put, doing nothing is not a tenable option for American
and Delta,'' said PaineWebber analyst Sam Buttrick.
</P>
<P>
   Another view is that regulatory approval is so uncertain and
airline mergers so notoriously messy that predictions of looming
consolidation are premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is approved, United is going to be screwed up for the
next three years trying to stitch it together,'' said aviation
consultant Mike Boyd of the Colorado-based Boyd Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``US Airways has high costs and labor problems,'' he said. ``By
the time the dust settles, the strategic benefits may not live up
to the hype.''
</P>
<P>
   The $11.6 billion buyout will take effect early next year _
provided it passes what is expected to be a stiff antitrust review
by the U.S. Justice Department. United is paying $60 a share for US
Airways stock, a 130 percent premium over the closing price on the
eve of the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   On paper the acquisition would give United, already strong in
the West and overseas, a powerful presence up and down the East
Coast through the absorption of US Airways' routes and hubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a perfect strategic fit for our company,'' said James
Goodwin, chairman of United parent UAL Corp.
</P>
<P>
   United's expanded route structure would put pressure on American
and Atlanta-based Delta, the No. 2 and No. 3 U.S. carriers behind
United, to broaden their own route systems or slowly lose market
clout, some analysts believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination inexorably ... alters the tenuous balance of
power in the industry,'' Buttrick said in a report issued
Wednesday. ``There is no question this transaction, if consummated,
will drive competitive response.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors seemed to agree. Stock in Northwest and Continental
airlines, viewed as possible takeover candidates in any round of
consolidation, rose Wednesday while shares in potential acquirers
Delta and American fell.
</P>
<P>
   But even analysts who believe consolidation is likely agree the
list of options for Delta and American is limited.
</P>
<P>
   For Delta, the most obvious move might be to rekindle its
on-again, off-again courtship of Continental. The two carriers have
complementary routes and mostly non-union work forces outside of
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   However, Continental in 1998 spurned a Delta buyout bid and
instead sold a controlling stake to Northwest as part of a
code-share alliance in which the two book passengers on each
others' flights. Northwest's partial ownership is an obstacle to
any new Delta bid.
</P>
<P>
   Continental management has expressed interest in buying back the
stake, but Buttrick said Northwest is unlikely to sell unless it
has an alternative deal _ such as a buyout offer from American.
</P>
<P>
   A Delta spokesman declined comment Wednesday, other than to say
the carrier's reciprocal frequent flier awards program with United
remains in place.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Delta pilots union said he expects
management will be looking at all the options.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top six airlines have been in a sort of delicate balance
of power for the past few years, and this appears to tip it,'' said
Andy Deane of the Air Line Pilots Association. ``We think it
increases the likelihood'' Delta management will attempt an
acquisition in coming months, Deane added.
</P>
<P>
   Third-tier major carriers Alaska Airlines, TWA and America West
are constantly rumored as acquisition candidates but aren't
considered big enough to have a major strategic impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though it wouldn't accomplish a great deal, Delta could
certainly acquire America West to fortify its West Coast
position,'' Buttrick said.
</P>
<P>
   American, for its part, could mount a competing buyout bid for
US Airways. American would gain many of the same strategic
advantages as United and has long been viewed as a potential US
Airways acquirer.
</P>
<P>
   A competing bid by Delta for US Airways appears impractical
because the two carriers' routes overlap heavily.
</P>
<P>
   The uncertain regulatory climate may prevent hasty moves, as
Delta and American wait to gauge the Justice Department's attitude
toward consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   United and US Airways have a ``little better than 50-50 chance''
of gaining antitrust approval for their merger, said analyst Ray
Neidl of ING Barings.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department already is challenging Northwest's
partial ownership of Continental, he and other analysts noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Approval of a United-US Airways merger without significant
modifications and conditions would be inconsistent with the DOJ's
legal challenge of the Northwest-Continental structure,'' Buttrick
said.
</P>
<P>
   United and US Airways, however, went to great lengths to craft
the deal to appease regulatory concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Most notably, United has promised to sell its operations at
Washington-Reagan National Airport _ the place where it overlaps
most with US Airways _ to US Airways board member and Black
Entertainment Network founder Robert Johnson. He would use the
assets to start a new carrier, DC Air.
</P>
<P>
   In addition United has promised to freeze fares for two years,
except to match inflation or fuel price increases. It has also
promised that no US Airways workers below the executive level will
lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a try-and-see effort,'' said US Airways Group
Chairman Stephen Wolf. ``We're going to get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Talks started last fall, when Goodwin said he approached Wolf.
US Airways, after a period of sustained profits in the late '90s,
had hit a losing streak amid higher fuel costs and intensifying
competition on the East Coast. The company's stock was down and its
major shareholder, Tiger Management, restless.
</P>
<P>
   United, which has enjoyed sustained strong profits for several
years, saw an opportunity to create what Goodwin called ``the first
truly efficient nationwide route network.''
</P>
<P>
   But airline mergers historically have been fraught with problems
ranging from operational glitches and service problems to labor
strife. US Airways itself is the product of mergers and has
suffered all those problems at various times.
</P>
<P>
   United is 55 percent employee-owned, and representatives from
the pilots and machinists unions sit on its board. Corporate bylaws
require approval of such a transaction by at least one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Dubinsky, who heads United's Air Line Pilots Association
unit, said the union has strong concerns because the airline and
the union have not reached a new contract agreement. The new
company must also take on what Dubinsky called a difficult task _
merging the US Airways pilots into the United pilot seniority list.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
