<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   House Approves Trade Bill Granting China Privileges
</P>
<P>
   By a surprisingly wide margin of 237-197, House lawmakers
granted China permanent normal trading privileges after months of
fierce lobbying that pitted business against organized labor. The
vote virtually assures the end of the annual review of China's
trade status, a ritual that Beijing considers humiliating but
opponents say maintains leverage over improving human rights. The
Senate is expected to endorse the measure as early as next month
but may question some of the amendments the House added to the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Questions Microsoft Remedy
</P>
<P>
   The federal judge trying the Microsoft antitrust case raised
serious questions about the government's plan to break up the
company, seeming to suggest that he did not think the plan went far
enough. Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson rejected Microsoft's request
for months of additional hearings. While Microsoft's lawyers
pleaded with the judge not to break up the company, Bill Gates and
other company executives were painting a rosy picture of a
software-enhanced future for chief executives of some of the
world's largest companies.
</P>
<P>
   Costco Shares Plummet on Warning
</P>
<P>
   Costco, the warehouse club retailer, posted third-quarter
results that missed Wall Street estimates and reduced its
fourth-quarter outlook, leading to a $4.2 billion fall in the
company's market value. Costco said its third-quarter profits rose
14 percent but fell a penny a share below expectations. Shares of
Costco declined $8.75, to $31.875.
</P>
<P>
   Garment Workers Lose U.S. Appeal
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court has refused to reinstate a class-action
lawsuit filed in 1998 against a garment industry union by union
members who worked at a now-defunct Brooklyn sweater factory.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco's Help Doesn't Come Cheap
</P>
<P>
   Getting a vote of confidence from Cisco Systems can be very
important to fledging technology companies. For example, Selectica,
a company that makes software to help businesses sell complex
products over the Internet was so eager to make Cisco its customer
that in a recent deal, Selectica went beyond giving Cisco its
software all the way to effectively paying Cisco to take it.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment President at Fox
</P>
<P>
   The Fox network appointed Gail Berman as president of
entertainment for the network. Berman had been president of Regency
Television, a production studio affiliated with Fox's television
studio. She replaces Doug Herzog, who held the position only 16
months. Berman will report to Sandy Grushow, who last November was
named chairman of the Fox television entertainment group.
</P>
<P>
   Heineken Expands Agency's Duties
</P>
<P>
   A humorous campaign in the United States for the flagship beer
brewed by Heineken is increasing sales. And that has sold Heineken
executives on giving the agency creating the campaign, the New York
office of Lowe Lintas &AMP; Partners Worldwide, an additional major
assignment: to develop and produce Heineken brand advertising that
is to run around the world.
</P>
<P>
   European Union Extends Beef Ban
</P>
<P>
   The European Union extended its ban of beef produced with growth
hormones. The decision reignites an ideologically charged battle
between American cattle ranchers, most of whom use hormones to
accelerate beef production, and European consumers, who generally
distrust food additives.
</P>
<P>
   New Third Rail of American Politics
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of temporary visas that permit foreigners to work
for employers that petition on their behalf shows that immigration
reform has replaced Social Security as the third rail of American
politics. Washington has come to rely on the visas as a substitute
for addressing the economic and social failings of current policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
