<HEADER>
A4915 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CISCO-MARKETPLACE-NYT     05-24 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISCO-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: CISCO'S SUPPORT IS HARDLY CHEAP 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A vote of confidence from Cisco Systems can be very important to
fledging technology companies, especially if they have initial
public offerings on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   Just how important? Ask Selectica, a San Jose, Calif., company
that makes software to help businesses sell complex products over
the Internet. Selectica was so eager to make Cisco a customer that
in a recent deal, it wound up paying Cisco to take its software.
</P>
<P>
   In January, only a couple of months before its public offering,
Selectica proudly announced that its system had been chosen to run
Cisco's World Wide Web site. Cisco, currently the world's
second-largest technology company in market value, is the leading
manufacturer of Internet equipment and will sell more than $15
billion of its routers and switches over its Web site this year.
</P>
<P>
   Selectica noted that Cisco's imprimatur had come after ``a
six-month evaluation cycle and successful pilot implementation.''
The contract gave the company instant credibility with other
potential customers _ and potential investors. In the marketing of
its stock offering to institutional investors _ the ``road show'' _
Selectica executives pointed out that they had contracts with two
of the world's leading technology companies, Cisco and Dell
Computer, which will use Selectica's software on part of its Web
site, according to investors who saw the presentations.
</P>
<P>
   That support resonated with potential investors. Even those who
are very sophisticated about technology acknowledge that the
complexity of modern software leaves them generally unable to judge
the technical merits of competing products. So the verdict of
widely respected companies like Dell and Cisco is extremely
important, said Michael Murphy, editor of the California Technology
Stock Letter.
</P>
<P>
   On March 10, Selectica became one of the hottest initial public
offerings of the year. It had first planned to offer its shares in
the range of $9 to $11 each, but scorching demand enabled the
underwriters to raise the offering price to $30. On Selectica's
first day of trading, the shares soared as high as $154. At that
price, Selectica was valued at more than $5 billion, 300 times its
revenue for the preceding 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   But there was something that Selectica did not disclose in its
press release announcing the software sales to Cisco. As part of
the deal, Selectica sold Cisco warrants for 800,000 shares of its
stock, a sweetener that has proved to be worth much more than the
software contract.
</P>
<P>
   Selectica's action is not without precedent. Big companies often
use their leverage to take stakes in would-be suppliers, especially
in the technology business. But these deals are usually portrayed
as partnership agreements or strategic investments, and they
usually take the form of a direct investment by the larger company.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Selectica, which disclosed the warrants in a few
sentences in its book-length registration statement, explicitly
linked the warrants to the licensing deal. ``On Jan. 7, in
connection with a license agreement, we issued a warrant to
purchase 800,000 shares of common stock to Cisco, one of our
customers, for $800,000,'' Selectica said.
</P>
<P>
   And by buying warrants instead of shares, Cisco assured itself
of gaining from any increase in Selectica's stock price without
taking on much risk, since it had effectively paid $1 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the agreement has proved lucrative for Cisco, which
will pay Selectica just $3 million this year for software and
technical support.
</P>
<P>
   The warrants, which have a strike price of $13 and can be
exercised beginning in January 2001, had a value of almost $24
million at Selectica's closing stock price of $42.625 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco's gain, though, was Selectica's loss. In the quarter
ending in March, Selectica reported a loss of $18 million on
revenue of $7 million, largely because of the cost of the
warrants. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, did the warrants affect Cisco's decision to choose
Selectica? Both companies say no, because Cisco would never
jeopardize its enormous Internet sales for a short-term gain of a
few million dollars. ``Cisco chose Selectica on the strength of its
technology,'' a Cisco spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   A Selectica spokeswoman said her company was chosen from a pool
of 30 competitors after a rigorous competition that lasted almost a
year. ``Anybody who really knows Cisco knows you can't buy Cisco,
especially for something that they identify as a core part of their
business,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco is not yet using Selectica's software to run its site.
That will not happen until at least October, the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal raised eyebrows even among supportive analysts. US
Bancorp Piper Jaffray, which helped underwrite Selectica's
offering, tried to quantify the effect of the Cisco warrants, along
with other, smaller sweeteners that Selectica offered Intel, Dell
and Samsung, near the end of its first research report on the
company in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a financial impact to the warrants,'' said
Michael Marzolf, a Piper Jaffray research analyst. Still, Marzolf
said the long-run marketing benefits of winning Cisco and the other
big companies as customers would outweigh the costs of the
warrants, which he estimated at $35 million, or double Selectica's
revenue for the recent fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with traditional advertising, being able to use Cisco
as a reference is extremely effective, Marzolf added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that it isn't expensive, but I do think that it
will pay off _ that it is paying off,'' Marzolf said. ``If Cisco is
using Selectica to configure routers, 3Com looks at that and says,
`This stuff works, we're going to do this for ourselves as well.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
