<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: updates, writes thru with Fox announcement to join the
debate
 &HT;    LEADING OPPOSITION CANDIDATE JOINS MEXICAN PRESIDENTIAL DEBATE
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ After a strange week of impromptu mini-debates and
public squabbling on television, Mexico's three top presidential
candidates appear to have all agreed to hold a final formal debate
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The country was left guessing about whether there would be a
debate until Wednesday evening, when top challenger and
conservative party contender Vicente Fox Quesada finally announced
he would ``participate with pleasure'' in the encounter.
</P>
<P>
   With less than six weeks to go before Mexico's July 2 election,
Fox is neck-in-neck with Francisco Labastida Ochoa, candidate of
Mexico's ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from opinion polls, Fox stands a good chance of becoming
the first non-PRI president in 71 years. He was widely hailed as
the winner of a first debate in April.
</P>
<P>
   But commentators here said Fox may have lost ground by engaging
in a game of political chicken and fumbling negotiations he
orchestrated over the debate on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Because a debate originally scheduled for Tuesday had been
cancelled over disagreements on format, Fox challenged his rivals
to meet on live television on Tuesday evening to try to revive a
formal debate.
</P>
<P>
   Fox squabbled with Labastida and leftist candidate Cuauhtemoc
Cardenas while reporters watched in disbelief. Fox tried to insist
on holding the debate later that night as originally scheduled,
noting that two Mexican TV networks had agreed to stand ready.
</P>
<P>
   He had previously accused his rivals of being afraid because
they had rejected his proposal that a speaking order for the debate
be announced shortly before the encounter. Fox also wanted
reporters to be allowed to ask questions, a format that has never
been used in Mexico campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he was also angry because Labastida and Cardenas met
alone on Tuesday for 20 minutes with the president of Mexico's
television industry association _ a group that has been accused of
being too pro-Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, however, Fox's attempts to attack his rivals
appeared to have backfired. He was widely criticized in the media
for being stubborn and refusing to yield to the other candidates'
agreement to debate on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday evening Fox relented, sending out a brief memo
attacking Labastida and Cardenas for mounting ``an alliance''
against him ``to preserve the system of corruption and privileges
that have been imposed on Mexican society for 70 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will go to the debate without any conditions, so that
(Labastida and Cardenas) won't continue to impose pretexts and will
not continue to deceive Mexican society,'' Fox's press release
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.wola.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
