<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4920 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-AIR-MERGER-1STLD-WRIT     05-24 1229
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-MERGER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED AIRLINE'S MOVE TO ACQUIRE US AIRWAYS IS FACING A NUMBER OF
TOUGH HURDLES
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS for complete write-thru, new byline, new headline; Story is
now 1,300 words longer and is on Page 1) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As United Airlines officially announced its proposed $4.3
billion acquisition of US Airways, the two companies began
confronting the obstacles and challenges that they will have to
overcome.
</P>
<P>
   In order to capture US Airways, a prize Wall Street analysts
said was a nearly perfect strategic complement, United needs to run
a gantlet of federal regulators, rank-and-file members of its
unions and its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to bet, I would bet this thing is doable,'' said
James Higgins, an airline industry analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette. ``But it is not going to be pretty getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   James Goodwin, the chairman and chief executive of United's
parent, the UAL Corp., is mindful of the challenges but optimistic
about UAL's ability to deal with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my opinion, there are two major hurdles,'' said Goodwin,
who will run the combined company. ``The first is to get US Airways
shareholders to approve this transaction. I don't think that is a
major hurdle. The real work ahead of us is the regulatory work,
which revolves around the Department of Transportation, the
Department of Justice and the European Union. Our real challenge
will be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Skepticism was apparent on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Befitting a stock that has received a takeover offer that was
about 130 percent above its closing price on Tuesday, shares of US
Airways soared Wednesday but settled well below the $60 a share
that United agreed to pay. US Airways closed at $49, up $22.6875.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, shares of United and those of its main rivals
declined. UAL fell $7.1875, to $53.1875. The AMR Corp., the parent
of American Airlines and the company most threatened by the merger,
slipped $2.5625, to $30.0625. And Delta Air Lines lost $3.6875, to
$51.50.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming United can meet all the challenges, it will then find
itself encumbered with huge amounts of debt _ $7.3 billion in debt
and lease obligations from US Airways alone _ obligations that
could threaten its financial viability if the economy were to slide
into recession sometime in 2001, the year the airline has said it
expects the deal to close.
</P>
<P>
   ``The probability of this transaction being consummated is
materially less than 100 percent,'' said Samuel Buttrick, an
airline analyst at Paine Webber. ``The probability of a significant
and swift competitive response is 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, American Airlines and Delta Air Lines, United's
biggest rivals, chose not to comment on the proposed combination.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said the competitive reaction from within the
industry might be swift and could come in several forms.
</P>
<P>
   They said the most obvious counterattack would be if American,
owned by the AMR Corp., topped United's offer for US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want US Airways, you better step in quickly,'' said
Glenn Engel, an airline analyst at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. ``And I
don't know why AMR's attitude about US Airways would have
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Higgins said that American, which considered a run at US Airways
in 1995, would be ``permanently marginalized'' if United is able to
complete the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that United did not appear to fear a higher bid.
Part of that has to do with the $60-a-share price, a figure most
consider to be generous, if not rich. In addition, United attached
a fairly low breakup fee of $160 million, which is not likely to
scare off a would-be suitor.
</P>
<P>
   Julius Maldutis, global aviation analyst at CIBC World Markets,
said that in the wake of the transaction, ``AMR, Continental
Airlines and Northwest will have to make some strategic moves.''
</P>
<P>
   The risk to United-US Airways, he said, is if all the carriers
decide to make moves in short order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that can queer the United deal is if there are
a number of mergers that are proposed that leave us with three
major carriers,'' Maldutis said. ``If that were to happen, then the
Justice Department and the Department of Transportation would have
a major migrane.''
</P>
<P>
   Antitrust experts said Wednesday that they expected the proposed
acquisition to be under review for many months by both the Justice
Department and the Transportation Department, a process that could
last into the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   The review would involve an examination of every market where
the two companies have a presence. Because it is not known who
would be leading the antitrust division at the Justice Department,
it is impossible to predict the results of that review.
</P>
<P>
   But experts and securities analysts expect that at the very
least the two companies may have to divest beyond just their
holdings in the Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, regulators most likely will consider what might happen
next.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this succeeds, which is by no means certain, it could
trigger further industry consolidation,'' said Philip Baggaley, a
managing director at the Standard &AMP; Poor's Corp. ``The regulators
will have to be thinking about follow-on combinations, as well as
the UAL-US Airways merger.''
</P>
<P>
   As an opening gambit, UAL and US Airways have agreed to sell
significant parts of its routes that operate in and out of Ronald
Reagan National Airport in Washington. But Washington has more than
one airport. United and US Airways, which rank No. 1 and No. 2 in
terms of market share at Washington Dulles International Airport,
may have to give up more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Washington, D.C., area is glaringly anti-competitive,''
said Higgins of Donaldson, Lufkin. ``I firmly believe the fix they
are proposing is highly inadequate.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin said that Robert Johnson, a US Airways board member and
the founder of Black Entertainment Television, had agreed to pay
more than $100 million for the assets at Reagan Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who has no experience operating an airline, will have a
fleet of 37 planes operating out of the airport. Ten of those, 737
200s, will be leased from United.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago is another city where United may be forced to give
ground, Baggaley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest competitive impact outside the direct overlap
would be in Chicago,'' the Standard &AMP; Poor's analyst said, ``where
both United and American have hubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there is close to competitive balance out of Chicago,
he said, because United dominates flights going West while American
has those going East.
</P>
<P>
   While regulators scrutinize the deal, Congress will also be
watching closely.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, and Sen. Herb
Kohl, D-Wis., said: ``The proposed merger between United Airlines
and US Airways will require very careful scrutiny. If this action
precipitates a wave of consolidation in an already consolidated
industry, it is hard to see how that result will be good for
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   DeWine is chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee's
subcommitee on antitrust, business rights and competition. Kohl is
the panel's ranking member.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Then there is labor.
</P>
<P>
   Objections from United's pilots in 1995 were a big factor behind
the airline's decision to back off a combination with US Airways.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the most recent deal, United has agreed to retain
virtually all 45,000 US Airways employees. Job security will likely
be popular with that carrier's unions. But seniority questions will
likely be important issues for United's unions, particularly the
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin said he was optimistic the company's unions would
support the deal. But Wednesday the pilots, whose representative on
United's board voted to reject the takeover, were far from
enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Dubinsky, chairman of the master executive council of the
pilots' union, issued a statement Wednesday expressing ``deep
disappointment'' that the company had agreed to buy US Airways
without reaching ``full agreement'' with the pilots on ``all
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters further, contract negotiations with the
pilots and United's machinists will be conducted over the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor integration issues are a real risk,'' said Higgins of
Donaldson, Lufkin. ``I am not sure that union leadership is the
question, but the rank and file. The risk is you can't make
everybody happy. And this is an industry where it doesn't take much
operational disruption to screw up earnings.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Objections from its pilots was only one reason United backed
away from a 1995 deal for US Airways. The company was also worried
about the effect a purchase would have on its balance sheet and
credit rating.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier has long coveted an investment-grade rating for its
bonds. And over the last four years it has slogged toward that
goal.
</P>
<P>
   But its bonds are now rated BB+ by Standard &AMP; Poor's, one notch
below investment grade status.
</P>
<P>
   That is almost certain to change if the US Airways deal goes
through. As part of the deal, United will assume $1.5 billion in US
Airways debt and $5.8 billion in lease obligations. And it will
also borrow $3 billion of the $4.3 billion in cash it has agreed to
pay to US Airways shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Effectively, all of the $11.6 billion of the acquisition price
would represent increased financial obligations of one sort or
another,'' Baggaley said. ``We have calculated that would raise
UAL's debt-to-capital ratio from 71 percent to 81 percent and
weaken other credit measures.''
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's said Wednesday that it had placed UAL on
credit watch with negative implications, and US Airways on credit
watch with positive implications. Moody's Investors Service took
similar action.
</P>
<P>
   The combined debt of the two airlines, including off-balance
sheet leases, is $28 billion, Baggaley said, a number that exceeds
1999's combined revenue of $26.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Riding with that much debt could be a real risk in the event the
economy sours next year or in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``A downturn would make them more vulnerable, no question,''
said Michael Mulvaney, a managing director who follows the airline
industry for Moody's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
