<HEADER>
A4922 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-1STLD-     05-24 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-LEBANON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARAK VOWS TO HOLD SYRIA RESPONSIBLE FOR GUERRILLA ATTACKS AGAINST
ISRAEL
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs 12th graf to correct spelling of Rabinovich) 
 (See also LEBANON-SCENE, ISRAEL-LEBANON-BORDER) 
 By WILLIAM A. ORME Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak warned Lebanon and Syria
on Wednesday that any cross-border attack on Israeli territory
would be considered ``an act of war,'' now that Israel has
withdrawn from Lebanon, in a rush completed before dawn on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Generals vowed to retaliate against incoming rockets or
artillery from Hezbollah guerrillas with strikes against Syrian
military targets deep inside Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The planes are ready,'' said Lt. Gen. Shaul Mofaz, the Israeli
military's chief of staff. ``The pilots are on call. Their quality
is known.''
</P>
<P>
   The warnings suggested the degree to which Israel's enthusiasm
over the safe return of its troops and the end of a costly
occupation is undercut by a portent of tension.
</P>
<P>
   Along Israel's northern border, the bombing of recent days
subsided into silence. But the few remaining residents were ordered
into their bomb shelters, and Israeli military warily watched
Hezbollah forces across the border without the hoped-for constraint
of Lebanese army troops or U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to withdraw is correct, but the implementation is
miserable,'' Dan Naveh, an opposition legislator, said in a typical
comment in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   But by and large, Barak received credit for keeping his central
campaign promise _ a full withdrawal from Lebanon _ a year after
that pledge helped secure his election.
</P>
<P>
   The few hundred remaining Israeli soldiers emerged from Lebanon
before dawn on Wednesday ``without a scratch,'' the prime minister
boasted, and some 5,000 militia allies were given asylum in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers that on Monday featured Kosovo-like portraits of
fleeing refugees on Wednesday printed their headlines in patriotic
blue. ``Mom, We've Left Lebanon!'' declared a giant banner atop
Yedioth Aronoth.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Barak appeared to be trying to tamp down the elation. ``This
is a happy day and a painful day,'' he said on television Wednesday
night. ``Happy because we brought the boys home. Sad, because a
thousand of our dear sons did not live to see this day.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak has shown a striking readiness to assign the blame for any
renewed violence to President Hafez Assad of Syria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any attack on the north will now be interpreted as an attack
by Syria,'' said Itamar Rabinovich, a former Israeli ambassador to
the United States and an expert on the Syrian regime. ``The dire
warnings to Syria reflect the general sentiment that this could
take us into the mouth of the abyss.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli presence in Lebanon acted as a constraint against an
escalation of tensions with Syria, as troops in the zone were
exposed to retaliation from the Hezbollah. But future Israeli
attacks on Lebanese targets would be conducted principally from the
air.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's overnight shift from a ground occupation strategy on
the border to reliance on an aerial offense will limit casualties
and accentuate its technological superiority, local analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``For 18 years, Israel has been fighting a guerrilla war, a war
of attrition, that nullifies all of its technological advantages,''
said Gerald Steinberg, a defense specialist at Bar-Illan
University. ``Now, by fighting from the air, Israel can use its
real capabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   While the returning Israeli soldiers were welcomed across the
country with family celebrations and politicians' applause, there
was ambivalence in the reception given the 5,000 refugees from the
South Lebanon Army.
</P>
<P>
   Some Israelis were angered that many militia members were
captured by Hezbollah forces and turned over to Lebanese
authorities. Antoine Lahad, the former commander of the militia,
said on Wednesday that Israel and the South Lebanon Army had
``worked together for 24 years, and then Israel decided within 24
hours to change direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli Interior Ministry on Wednesday hastened to provide
the militia members many of the benefits accorded immigrants here,
including work visas, health insurance, temporary housing and help
in finding jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel will be tested on how we deal with them,'' said Ephraim
Sneh, Israel's deputy defense minister.
</P>
<P>
   Barak had become caustic in his condemnation of the original
strategic logic of the occupation, contending that it had failed to
protect northern border towns while causing the needless deaths of
more than 900 Israeli soldiers and thousands of Lebanese combatants
and civilians. His implicit target has been the leader of the main
right-wing opposition party, Ariel Sharon, the former defense
minister who led a full-scale invasion into Lebanon in 1982
</P>
<P>
   Sharon on Wednesday termed the withdrawal ``a disgraceful
retreat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The government had 10 months to organize this, and if it had
been organized right, Israeli weapons would not have fallen into
Hezbollah hands,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
