<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4923 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-TRIPP-WIRETAPPING-1ST     05-24 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIPP-WIRETAPPING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARYLAND PROSECUTOR DROPS CHARGES AGAINST LINDA TRIPP 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS to add clarifying sentence to end of final graf.)  
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chief state prosecutor of Maryland decided
Wednesday to drop criminal wiretap charges against Linda Tripp, the
Pentagon employee whose secretly recorded conversations with Monica
Lewinsky exposed an affair that led to President Clinton's
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor, Stephen F. Montanarelli, said it would be
impossible to successfully pursue a trial, which was to begin on
July 10, because a judge this month suppressed testimony by
Lewinsky that, Montanarelli said, was crucial to obtaining a
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The decision concludes the only criminal case against a major
figure in the most serious Oval Office scandal since Watergate.
Tripp had faced the possibility of a 10-year prison sentence and a
$10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no choice'' but to drop the case, Montanarelli said in
an interview Wednesday, noting that in Maryland, a judge's ruling
on suppression of evidence cannot be appealed to a higher court.
``I'm not pleased, but that's the life of a prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement posted on her Web site Wednesday afternoon, Tripp
called the Maryland case an example of ``selective prosecution''
and vowed to ``continue to fight the shameful smear tactics of this
corrupt administration in civil court.'' Last year she sued the
White House and the Defense Department, maintaining that they had
used her confidential personnel records to impugn her reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Tripp did not attend a news conference held Wednesday by her
lawyer, Joseph Murtha, on the courthouse steps in Ellicott City,
the Baltimore suburb where the trial would have been held. ``We
firmly believe that Tripp did nothing wrong,'' Murtha said, ``and
that she did not violate any laws when she exposed the criminal
behavior and wrongdoing committed by President Clinton and
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Laws on taping telephone calls vary from state to state. In
Maryland, where Tripp lives, it is against the law for one party to
tape a phone conversation without the consent of the other. At a
preliminary hearing in the case, Lewinsky testified that she had
not given permission for any taping of her conversations with
Tripp, who was once her close confidante.
</P>
<P>
   Montanarelli's decision to drop the charges was widely expected
after the judge presiding over the case, Diane O. Leasure of Howard
County Circuit Court, suppressed the testimony of Lewinsky in a
decision issued on May 5.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor's office had faced the task of building a case
against Tripp that did not rely on evidence Tripp gave to Kenneth
Starr, then the Whitewater independent counsel, while she was under
a federal grant of immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Central to the case was a Lewinsky-Tripp conversation that Tripp
taped on Dec. 22, 1997. This was the last talk between the two
women that Tripp ever recorded, and it occurred, prosecutors said,
just after her lawyer had informed her that secret tape-recording
was illegal in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky testified last winter that she was certain this
conversation had in fact occurred on that December day two and a
half years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But Leasure's decision held that the testimony was not credible
and was tainted by the Starr investigation. Lewinsky's recollection
of the date of the conversation, the judge said, was influenced by
her contact with the independent counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe her, the court does not and that resolves the
matter,'' Montanarelli said Wednesday of Lewinsky's testimony that
she had an independent recollection of the date.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no other witnesses to the conversation whom the
state can call to testify,'' the prosecutor said, ``and Tripp
cannot be compelled to testify.''
</P>
<P>
   In their conversation of Dec. 22, the two women discussed what
they should say about Lewinsky's sexual relationship with the
president in the testimony that each expected to give in a sexual
misconduct suit filed by Paula Jones, a former Arkansas state
employee, against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an extremely important and memorable event in her
life,'' Montanarelli said of Lewinsky, ``which was, shortly after
it occurred, published in detail in the national news media.''
</P>
<P>
   Tripp was also charged with illegally disclosing the details of
her conversation with Lewinsky to Newsweek magazine, which
published a transcript of the talk in its issue of Feb. 2, 1998.
Maryland is dropping those charges as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
