<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: DEFENSE CHIEF QUITS
</P>
<P>
   The chief of Germany's defense staff announced his resignation
the day after Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping said the army
required drastic reform. Gen. Hans-Peter von Kirchbach favored
fewer cuts in troops and the scale of the draft than those proposed
by an independent commission. He will be replaced on July 1 by Gen.
Harald Kujat, the current head of defense planning. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA: HAIDER DEFAMED
</P>
<P>
   A Vienna court has fined a prominent political scientist, Anton
Pelinka, $4,800 for defaming Joerg Haider, leader of the rightist
Freedom Party. In a television interview Pelinka said Haider had
``trivialized'' Nazism and made certain National Socialist
positions ``more politically acceptable.'' The case was initially
filed by Dieter Boehmdorfer, then Haider's lawyer and now minister
of justice. The International Helsinki Federation for Human Rights
called the conviction ``a miscarriage of justice,'' especially in
light of the role played by the justice minister. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: 6-NATION PACT
</P>
<P>
   Russia and five other former Soviet nations agreed on new
measures to jointly fight terrorism, and drug and weapons
smuggling, including rules governing when they collectively
intervene in crises, use force and conduct peacekeeping missions.
The treaty updates a 1992 pact among Russia, Belarus, Kazakhstan,
Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan and Armenia.  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS: LOCKERBIE TRIAL RESUMES
</P>
<P>
   The chief investigator into the 1988 Lockerbie crash described
how it turned into a murder inquiry as the trial of two Libyans
accused of bombing the Pan Am flight resumed. The spread of the
wreckage over 850 square miles suggested a midair disintegration,
he testified, and, within a week, analysis determined that plastic
explosives had been used. &QL; 
 &QR;
</P>
<P>
   CZECH REPUBLIC: JEWISH PROPERTY
</P>
<P>
   The lower chamber of parliament voted to return to its original
owners property confiscated from Jews during the Nazi occupation.
Under the proposal, now going to the upper chamber, Jewish
communities would receive all immovable property confiscated
between Sept. 29, 1938, and May 8, 1945, and now state-owned. The
government estimates some 200 buildings would be returned. The
Jewish Museum in Prague would also receive 63 paintings now in the
National Gallery.  &QL; 
 &QR;
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ERITREA: ETHIOPIA ATTACKS
</P>
<P>
   As Eritrea celebrated its seventh year of independence, its
troops said they fended off a second day of attacks from Ethiopians
near the border town of Zalembessa. Fighting erupted two days ago
along the central, and most strategically important, front of the
disputed border after Ethiopian forces pushed deep inside Eritrea.
Ethiopia started an offensive nearly two weeks ago. The two
nations, once close allies, have been at war since May 1998. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA: 100 KILLED
</P>
<P>
   At least 100 people were reported killed in the northern city of
Kaduna in the latest clash between Christians and Muslims.
Religious conflicts in March led to the deaths of hundreds in
Kaduna and in Aba in the mainly Christian areas in the southeast.
The recent fighting is said to have started after Kaduna Christians
blamed a Muslim for a Christian's death.  &QR;
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   PERU: COMPUTER TESTS
</P>
<P>
   Election officials tested computers intended to assure an
accurate presidential runoff vote Sunday, as sometimes violent
street protests calling for a postponement of the vote continued.
Election observers and diplomats said privately that they hoped
officials would find flaws in the ballot counting system, giving
President Alberto K. Fujimori a reason to postpone the vote and
enabling Alejandro Toledo, his challenger, to get back in the
race. &QR;
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: NURSES STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   About 10,000 unionized nurses and nurses' aides in Alberta
staged an illegal strike. It was the latest confrontation over
state-run health in a western province where the premier, Ralph
Klein, has taken steps to increase the role of private, nonunion
health care. The nurses say they are paid about 15 percent less
than nurses in Ontario, a province with a lower per capita income.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH KOREA: THAWING RELATIONS
</P>
<P>
   In a conciliatory gesture before a meeting June 12 of the
leaders of the two Koreas, South Korea plans to allow a North
Korean-made movie to be shown in the South for the first time. As
part of a thaw in relations, a North Korean children's art troupe
arrived in Seoul for musical and dance performances to celebrate
the talks.  &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
