<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES CHINA TRADE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House voted Wednesday to liberalize trade with
China, approving a historic measure that supporters hailed as a
stimulus for widespread US business expansion, but opponents
condemned as an irreversible threat to American jobs and Chinese
human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The 237-197 vote to normalize trade relations with China on a
permanent basis was a notable victory for President Clinton, who
had turned the proposal into a personal crusade. The bill, which
requires that China lower tariffs on many computer and electronics
products, also signaled a new political force in the
high-technology community, which helped direct a lobbying blitz at
dozens of wavering congressmen in the final days before the vote.
</P>
<P>
   But the vote was a serious blow to labor unions and human rights
advocates, and it deeply divided congressional Democrats, forcing
many to choose between local interest groups and their allegiance
to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the victory depended largely on Republican leaders,
who formed an unusual alliance with Clinton to line up the
necessary number of supporters, including 164 Republicans. Minutes
after the bill passed, Republican leaders emerged from the House
chamber beaming. ``This is an incredible day,'' said House majority
whip Tom DeLay of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Clinton said: ``Today the House of
Representatives has taken an historic step toward continued
prosperity in America, reform in China and peace in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill, known as permanent normalization of trade relations,
is expected to pass the Senate in the coming weeks, despite a
pledge Wednesday from Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman
Jesse Helms to block it.
</P>
<P>
   Helms, a North Carolina Republican and a frequent critic of the
Clinton administration, said he felt ``obliged to make clear that I
do not intend to allow the Senate to simply rubber-stamp the
president's plan to reward the Chinese Communists,'' threatening to
force uncomfortable votes as the bill came to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the Senate, including both senators from
Massachusetts, have a record of supporting free trade, and few
aides expect the deal to be blocked at this late stage. Then, once
Clinton signs it into law, China will be guaranteed normal US trade
status _ instead of waiting for Congress to vote on it every year
as it does now. In exchange, China has agreed to reduce many of its
tariffs and barriers, including those that affect the financial
services, insurance, and technology industries.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the loudest opponents of the bill during Wednesday's
debate on the House floor were members from New England, despite
the region's burgeoning high-tech and financial services
industries. Representative Bernard Sanders, an Independent from
Vermont who called the vote a ``sad situation,'' opposed the deal,
largely on human rights grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbying by the White House reached a fever pitch over the
last month, as Clinton invited dozens of undecided congressmen to
the White House for a personal lobbying session.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Clinton appeal appeared to have a significant
effect: Some 10 Democrats announced their support for the
legislation Tuesday night. Several said they were swayed after
striking bargains for their districts. In one case, Representative
Martin Frost of Texas said he would support the bill after the Navy
agreed not to close the Northrop Grumman defense plant in his
district.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, some 200 business lobbyists in favor of the
bill crowded into a conference room on Capitol Hill to compare
notes on negotiations with undecided members. They sounded
increasingly confident about their victory; at one point,
Representative Philip M. Crane, a Republican of Illinois, dropped
by to boost spirits further with a pep talk.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Capitol _ where 10,000 labor union activists had
congregated in protest the month before _ about 40 free-trade
advocates carried signs and American flags Wednesday morning in a
jubilant show of last-minute support. At almost the exact same
time, opponents inside the building seemed to be bracing for
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   In the weekly Democratic caucus meeting, House minority leader
Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri announced that he hoped
disagreements over the bill would ``remain high-level,'' rather
than deteriorating into rancorous debate among Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt, who vehemently opposed the bill, told fellow Democrats
``to remember that when the vote was over, we had to be a unified
party,'' according to members who attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But just hours later, Representative Patrick J. Kennedy gave a
speech suggesting the wounds might not immediately heal. The Rhode
Island Democrat shouted, ``What would we do today if this were
apartheid? I guess we would do even more deals with P.W. Botha,''
referring to the white South African leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a travesty,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
