<HEADLINE>
CHINESE EXPECT BILL'S PASSAGE TO SPEED DEVELOPMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (With CHINA-TRADE) 
By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ News that China has taken the first step toward
permanent normal trade status with the United States was greeted
with joy here, tempered by worries about the wrenching economic
changes that are expected as China opens its markets to outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's fantastic,'' said Zhang Linan, a 24-year-old accountant
in a bank. ``I think it will be a boost for our economic
development and personally it means more choices for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Chinese have placed enormous hopes on membership in the
World Trade Organization, with its rules for market opening, as a
force for dismantling inefficient state industries and modernizing
the country.
</P>
<P>
   And since most people yearn for cooperation with the United
States, which they see as the world's economic and cultural leader,
defeat of the trade bill would have been seen as a stinging
betrayal. Reactions in Beijing were tinged with feelings of relief
that a crisis in U.S.-Chinese relations had been avoided.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so good that it passed,'' said Luo Hui, 36, a computer
programmer. ``And it's even better that it didn't fail to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Free trade and investment, Luo said, ``will bring many
opportunities here, but also will put lots of pressure on Chinese
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But if Congress hadn't passed this law,'' he added, ``it would
have been a shock, a setback, a big international incident. Now we
can get on with business.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Chinese government had not yet issued an official
reaction, top officials had to be pleased and relieved. President
Jiang Zemin and Prime Minister Zhu Rongji had both staked their
prestige on China's entry into the global trading regime and on
closer economic ties with the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Xu Xiaonian, the senior economist at the China International
Capital Corp., a government-linked investment bank, noted that
passage of the bill helps clear the way for China's entry into the
WTO, which he predicted ``will mark a new era in China's economic
opening.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's about speeding up the economic reforms and integrating
China into the world economy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The news from Washington will speed along what is already a
remarkable revival in U.S.-Chinese relations since the bombing of
China's Embassy in Belgrade last year, during the NATO campaign
against Yugoslavia. President Clinton, who earlier had been
portrayed as a great statesman for cultivating relations with
China, was all but declared an enemy after the embassy bombing,
even though the United States insisted it was an unfortunate
accident.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's efforts to push the trade bill were widely reported in
China and now he is a hero again. Still, foreign policy experts
warn of pitfalls ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the trade vote in Congress, two big problems threatened
Chinese-American relations, trade relations and Taiwan,'' said
Xiong Zhiyong, dean of the Foreign Affairs College here. ``Now
there's only one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
