<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0412 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4929 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPR-STUDY-BOS &LR;      05-24 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPR-STUDY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEST PUMPING IS TOUTED OVER TRADITIONAL CPR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pumping the chest of a cardiac arrest victim is as effective as
the universally-taught CPR method that combines pumping with
mouth-to-mouth resuscitation, according to a surprising study that
could change the way emergency dispatchers instruct people trying
to save someone.
</P>
<P>
   The study's authors recommend a radical paring of one of the
pillars of emergency medicine: 911 operators should abandon
instructing bystanders at cardiac arrest scenes to perform
combination CPR and instead urge them to immediately begin chest
pumping alone.
</P>
<P>
   The faster a victim is attended to, the more likely he or she
will be saved. A 911 operator can explain how to chest pump quicker
than he can issue instructions on standard CPR, pointed out Alfred
Hallstrom, a biostatistician at the University of Washington in
Seattle and an author of the study, which appears in the New
England Journal of Medicine. The minutes saved could mean lives
saved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instructions for chest compression take 1.4 minutes less than
for mouth-to-mouth and compression. It doesn't make sense to waste
time giving lengthier instructions, especially if we know that
chest compression alone works just as well,'' he said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Hallstrom pointed out that jettisoning mouth-to-mouth would also
eliminate a major reason why bystanders avoid CPR in the first
place: fear of the contents of another person's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Mouth-to-mouth and CPR have long been synonymous in both the
public mind and first-aid training around the world. Change will
come about slowly if at all, said the study's authors. Still,
colleagues hailed their work as groundbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   The study is of ``immense importance and will have worldwide
implications,'' wrote Dr. Gordon A. Ewy, a longtime CPR researcher
at the University of Arizona, in an editorial accompanying the
article.
</P>
<P>
   Local fire and rescue departments reacted cautiously to the
criticism _ seemingly from left field _ of a practice long
considered gospel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more time to absorb and digest this study before we
comment or give any of our policies a second look,'' said Steve
MacDonald, spokesman for the Boston Fire Department, after a copy
was provided to him.
</P>
<P>
   Among CPR researchers, however, the venerable practice of
mouth-to-mouth has been suspect for almost two decades. In the
early 1980s, Seattle embarked on an ambitious effort to train the
public in CPR. Almost 40 percent of its residents took classes.
Hallstrom and his colleagues wanted to see if Seattle had actually
improved at it. They did find that slightly more people than usual
were performing CPR by the book. But a far more stunning result
emerged: how well CPR was done had no bearing on who survived.
Those who did incomplete jobs _ such as chest pumping only _ saved
about as many people as those who met the paramedic's gold
standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that either CPR was doing nothing or you didn't
have to do very good CPR to have a real impact,'' said Hallstrom.
``We were surprised by that. Everyone assumed that doing really
rigorous CPR was essential.''
</P>
<P>
   Further CPR studies, first in dogs then pigs, confirmed that
simple chest pumping, where both hands are placed just below the
breastbone and pushed down in rapid intervals, was just as
effective as the standard procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Cardiac arrest occurs when the heart ceases to pump blood around
the body. Crucial bodily functions come to a halt. A victim can die
within mintues. In CPR, mouth-to-mouth ventillation may help
restore breathing. Chest compression may allow the heart to start
pumping blood again.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, the authors used a computer program to randomly
instruct Seattle's 911 operators to tell cardiac arrest bystanders
to either do standard CPR or chest pumping alone. The study said
14.6 percent of the victims who were given only chest pumps later
walked out of the hospital; 10.4 percent of those given standard
CPR did the same. The difference is too small for researchers to
claim chest pumping alone is superior but they can say the two
methods are equal. They also found it takes 911 operators one
minute to instruct callers on how to chest pump, compared to 2.4
minutes to explain standard CPR, which involves clearing the
airway, administering mouth-to-mouth then chest pumping and
alternating between the two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't surprise me that chest compression worked slightly
better than mouth-to-mouth and compression,'' said Hallstrom. ``It
was a reasonable conclusion to draw from our earlier studies.
Moreover, if you only give chest compression instructions you're
starting about a minute and half earlier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
