<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS RAISE RECORD $26.5 MILLION TO COME TO AID OF PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Most people shelled out just $50, but some could
not help giving or gathering $500,000. So there were different
``tiers'' of donors in kind of a class system sprayed throughout
the giant MCI Center Wednesday night, but all of them were part of
a history-making event _ the biggest political fund-raiser ever,
raising $26.5 million in three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it was the Democrats, the party of the little people, who
set the record. It was billed as a tribute to President Clinton,
and the donors, from those in black tie to those in blue jeans,
were beckoned by the Midas of fund-raisers, Terry McAuliffe, who,
in the end, squeezed 13,645 people into a space for 12,000.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe accomplished his task: beating the Republicans, who
raised a mere $21.3 million at their gala a month ago. McAuliffe
let them gloat at their treasure chest and low-balled his estimates
of what the Democrats could raise, only to be able to trumpet his
success later.
</P>
<P>
   The event featured McAuliffe's friend, Clinton, and assorted
other luminaries, including Hillary Rodham Clinton, Vice President
Al Gore and Tipper Gore.
</P>
<P>
   It also featured entertainers like Robin Williams, Stevie
Wonder, LeAnn Rimes, Lenny Kravitz and Darius Rucker.
</P>
<P>
   The money goes to the Democratic National Committee and will be
used to help Gore pay for commercials for his presidential
campaign, although he has insisted he wants to overhaul the current
campaign finance system.
</P>
<P>
   Loyal Democrats like Bill Richardson, the secretary of energy,
were on hand. He acknowledged that the money would come in handy,
especially when the advertising wars begin on television. ``I think
neither party is going to unilaterally disarm,'' he said, as he
stood by a table of donors who had raised up to $500,000. Then he
added, ``We're the party of the small donors, the grass roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Tables for dignitaries were spread across the floor of the
sports arena, where guests were served barbecue from restaurants in
Arkansas and Tennessee, home states of the president and vice
president, along with bottles of Merlot and Chardonnay. John
Vergos, whose family owns Rendezvous, a popular barbecue restaurant
in Memphis, flew in 800 pounds of barbecued chicken and beef ribs
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Up in the bleachers, guests had to buy their food at the regular
arena prices _ $3.75 for a cup of cola.
</P>
<P>
   John Bunting, 56, who works in social services in Baltimore,
paid $50 to party. He said that the Republicans were trying to cast
the presidential race as a ``personality contest and that's a much
tougher race for Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the arena, he said that much of the crowd probably
came to pay tribute to Clinton. ``It's not that Vice President Gore
falls short,'' he said, ``it's that we're talking about the king.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
