<HEADLINE>
TELEVISION PLOY BACKFIRES FOR OPPOSITION CANDIDATE
</HEADLINE>
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Hastily improvised negotiations among the main
presidential candidates demonstrated the power that television has
gained in Mexican politics when the talks went sour for the
opposition contender.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was called to discuss whether to go ahead with the
second of two presidential debates that had been canceled. Vicente
Fox, the opposition candidate who has taken the lead in opinion
polls, had tried to score points by demanding that the three main
candidates proceed with a planned debate on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Abruptly, his opponents, Francisco Labastida of the ruling party
and the leftist candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, agreed to get
together with him to discuss the rules. Fox invited TV cameras to
the negotiations, and for most of the next two hours, found himself
pummeled by Labastida and Cardenas who accused Fox of being
needlessly difficult. After hours of heated exchanges, Fox's two
opponents got up and walked out as cameras whirred.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Labastida was openly triumphant, declaring that
``Fox is going into a free fall.'' Most headlines seemed to agree,
like the one in Milenio. a daily newspaper in Mexico City, that
said, ``Fox Acts Spoiled, Live and In Color.'' And though Fox
insisted that he had achieved his goal of flushing out the
collusion of Labastida and Cardenas, his advisers acknowledged that
his performance had at least temporarily knocked the wind from his
campaign. After some hesitation, he also announced he would
participate in the next debate, scheduled for Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For a country still new to the rough-and-tumble of a real
campaign after 71 years of dominance by a single party, the
confrontation offered an exhilarating glimpse of presidential
candidates slugging it out without makeup or rules.
</P>
<P>
   While much can still change before the election on July 2, for
now, at least, the awkward meeting threatened to neutralize the
lead Fox had taken as the outsider battling against the entrenched
Institutional Revolutionary Party of Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the Reuters news agency published a nationwide
poll, with a margin of error of 3.2 percent, showing Fox backed by
46.3 percent of voters, Labastida by 41.6 percent and Cardenas by
9.3 percent. But several polls published since have been a
cacophony of contradictions, leaving Mexicans uncertain about who
is the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   The televised encounter on Tuesday capped three days of
programming in which the two Mexican networks relaxed their starchy
news formats and interviewed the three candidates from remote
locations simultaneously, a la ABC's Nightline, allowing them to
respond to each others' increasingly vituperative remarks
</P>
<P>
   ``This was something completely new for Mexico,'' said Raul
Trejo Delarbre, a Mexico City professor who studies the media.
``There were no clear rules, and nobody knew quite how to react.''
</P>
<P>
   This format reached an extreme in the televised encounter on
Tuesday, in which cameras rolled for two hours as the candidates
sat at a table in a garden, airing their differences about whether
to have a formal debate _ without a moderator or anyone else in
charge.
</P>
<P>
   A scowling Fox insisted repeatedly that all three men go forward
that night with the debate, as originally planned and subsequently
canceled. He also appeared to misrepresent an offer by Mexico's top
TV network to broadcast the event.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas and Labastida repeatedly jeered at Fox, portraying him
as obstinate for repeatedly pushing to debate on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Over Fox's objections, his opponents agreed to debate Friday
evening. Then they stood up and ended the meeting, with Fox sitting
alone, staring glumly at the cameras in silence.
</P>
<P>
   Fox agonized before deciding to participate in the debate on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our choice is to go into the debate, now on their terrain, in
which case Cuauhtemoc and Labastida will both attack me, or to take
our campaign back on the road, to the people, in which case they
will say I was afraid to debate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida, whose campaign had been losing steam, sounded
jubilant about Fox's misstep as he drove to a rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fox is going to go into free fall,'' Labastida said.
``Everyone can see he doesn't know the difference between his
fantasies and reality. He also manipulated the truth. Mexicans
don't like that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
