<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISING-FBI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMO ON RISKS TO RENO'S JOB TOUCHES OFF DISPUTE AT SENATE HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Top officials of the Justice Department and the FBI
engaged in an unusual public debate Wednesday at a Senate hearing
over a 1996 memorandum about whether Attorney General Janet Reno's
job was at risk as a result of the government's high-profile
investigation into finances of the 1996 Clinton-Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At the Senate hearing, a top FBI official, Neil Gallagher, said
that he attended a meeting four years ago with Lee Radek, a senior
Justice Department official, who, according to Gallagher, said that
he was under heavy pressure on the case and that Reno's job was
``in the balance'' as a result of the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Radek, who also testified at the hearing, said that he had no
recollection of the meeting, but that he was sure he had not made
such a remark.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed Gallagher's statement as ``a lie.'' Gallagher,
however, said he was positive of his account of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The disputed comments were referred to in a memorandum written
by FBI Director Louis Freeh, who was not at the meeting, but said
that another official had reported Radek's comments.
</P>
<P>
   The disagreement between two high-ranking officials reflects the
acute sensitivity within law enforcement circles over the campaign
finance inquiry that has resulted in guilty pleas and convictions
of lower level fund-raisers, but has never reached the upper
echelons of the Democratic Party or the White House.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials, including Freeh, have long contended that an
independent prosecutor should have investigated the case because
the Justice Department under Reno, a presidential appointee, could
never be perceived as impartial.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno and her top advisers on independent counsel matters,
like Radek, repeatedly blocked efforts to seek an outside
prosecutor, saying the law did not require Reno to refer the case
to an independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Radek's public integrity unit within the Justice Department has
managed the investigation, which congressional Republicans have
long criticized as a tepid effort.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers have continued their attacks on Reno _ even
though the independent counsel law has expired _ for her refusal to
relinquish the case to an outside prosecutor. They have said that
Reno deliberately kept the inquiry in-house to spare President
Clinton embarrassment and in effort to keep her job after Clinton
won re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh's memorandum was read at Wednesday's hearing by Sen. Arlen
Specter, R-Pa., who has led an inquiry into the Justice
Department's handling of campaign finance matters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
