<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN WAR NOVEL LACKS THE PUNCH OF PREVIOUS EFFORTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Gone for Soldiers: A Novel of the Mexican War'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Jeff Shaara &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Historical fiction &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ballantine, $26.95 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing sadder than a great literary concept that's
been pushed over the edge. Larry McMurtry's ``Lonesome Dove'' led
logically to ``Streets of Laredo,'' but ``Dead Man's Walk'' and
``Comanche Moon'' were sequels that readers had to endure rather
than savor. Similarly, Fort Worth native Patricia Highsmith created
an anti-hero for all time in ``The Talented Mr. Ripley,'' but no
one recalls that masterwork's four lackluster sequels.
</P>
<P>
   So ``Gone for Soldiers'' is legitimate cause for mourning.
Michael Shaara's justly award-winning ``The Killer Angels,'' which
chronicled the Civil War battle of Gettysburg from the
fictionalized but brutally realistic perspective of specific
real-life combatants, was a revelation. A decade or so after his
father's death, Jeff Shaara took up the same theme with the
exceptional ``Gods and Generals,'' a ``Killer Angels'' prequel that
brought Robert E. Lee, Thomas ``Stonewall'' Jackson, Joshua
Chamberlain and other Killer Angels vets to the brink of
Gettysburg.
</P>
<P>
   He followed with ``The Last Full Measure,'' taking these
now-beloved men on to Appomattox (Jackson excepted; he died before
Gettysburg). A final scene in ``The Last Full Measure,'' when Union
troops have the scattered Confederate forces at bay, was absolutely
stunning in its clarity and resonance.
</P>
<P>
   That should have been the last scene in the series. Shaara's
latest effort, ``Gone for Soldiers,'' a pre-prequel about the
Mexican War, is a listless exercise in milking a literary cow that
has given its last drops. Capt. Robert E. Lee is the central figure
as U.S. forces head south across the border and eventually breach
the walls of Mexico City. We meet, fleetingly, Jackson and George
Pickett and U.S. Grant, all prepping for their Civil War roles in
subordinate military positions, but distinguishing themselves
nonetheless. Much of the book, though, concerns itself with U.S.
commander Winfield Scott and his chief opponent, Gen. Antonio Lopez
de Santa Anna, back from the political dead to rally his people to
another humiliating defeat.
</P>
<P>
   In a near-apologetic ``To the Reader'' note before the novel
begins, Shaara calls the U.S.-Mexican war ``one of the most
overlooked stories in American history,'' which is true enough. An
exceptional PBS TV series (produced by Dallas' KERA staff) did
much, a few years ago, to remedy that. What Shaara adds with ``Gone
for Soldiers'' simply never gets going, storywise, perhaps because
the conflict it describes was so confusing.
</P>
<P>
   Scott spends as much time fighting his own generals as he does
the Mexicans; President Polk is no admirer of Scott's, and has a
government lackey on hand in Mexico to negotiate peace without
necessarily consulting the commander of the U.S. forces. Shaara
manages to turn the complex Santa Anna into a parody; there are
lengthy passages describing the one-legged general's elaborate
dinners in the field. Far less attention is given to why such an
established military loser remained beloved among the very peasants
whose lifestyle was the antithesis of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Even the battle scenes drag on. Shaara's description of the
Americans storming the great Chapultepec castle ought to be
masterful, considering his expertise with such descriptions in
``Gods and Generals'' and ``The Last Full Measure.'' But the
results in ``Gone for Soldiers'' elicit yawns, not gasps. This is
especially disappointing because most devotees of the series
probably were already familiar with Gettysburg and Shiloh and
Appomattox before they started the books, but they're far less
likely to know about Veracruz and Chapultepec. Learning ought to be
at least as engaging as reaffirming, but Shaara doesn't get the job
done.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely that ``Gone for Soldiers'' is the last of the Shaara
father/son series. Like the combatants whose exploits he has
chronicled, Shaara has clearly lost his zeal for battle.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
