<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BODACIOUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD'S BADDEST BULL, AGE 12, DIES OF KIDNEY FAILURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bodacious, who earned the reputation of ``World's Most Dangerous
Bull'' by giving cowboys a prime ride or their worst wreck, is no
longer walking the pastures.
</P>
<P>
   The muscular, 1,800-pound bull, who won three world titles, has
died of kidney failure. He was 12, or the equivalent of
approximately 60 in human years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the baddest bull that I ever saw,'' said four-time
world champion Tuff Hedemen, who made the best ride of his career
on Bodacious and also had every bone in his face shattered by the
bull.
</P>
<P>
   The cream-colored Charbray had an explosive style of jumping
that made him a rodeo celebrity. Bodacious had his own agent and
was featured in magazines and television, and appeared in
advertising for Budweiser and at rodeos and fairs. He inspired an
abundance of memorabilia, including T-shirts, caps, belt buckles,
watches, rifles and mousepads.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Andrews and her husband Sammy, renowned northeast Texas
stock contractors, owned the bull, which died May 16 in his holding
pen at the Andrews' ranch in Addielou, near the Oklahoma border. He
was buried nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Bodacious reared higher than most bulls. As a cowboy leaned
forward to stay in rhythm, Bodacious often threw back his head and
struck the rider in the face. Bodacious whipped down many cowboys
on his massive front end, including Hedeman and 1996 world champion
Terry Don West, causing facial and rib injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Bodacious never killed a cowboy, but Hedeman said the bull had
the potential of causing a fatality had he not been retired five
years ago. Hedeman, who lives in Morgan Mill, Texas, was Bodacious'
most famous foe. He finished 1-4 against the bull.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletically speaking, Bodacious was the 300-pound offensive
lineman who could also star at cornerback,'' Hedeman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bodacious finished as the top bull at the 1992 National Finals
Rodeo as a rookie. He also finished as the PRCA top bull in 1994
and both the Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association and
Professional Bull Riders in 1995. In 135 attempts, only eight
qualified rides were made on Bodacious. The bull earned a spot in
the ProRodeo Hall of Fame last year.
</P>
<P>
   After he was retired in 1995, Bodacious was used as a breeder
and sired hundreds of offspring.
</P>
<P>
   Bodacious appeared healthy until last week. He recovered from an
infection in his left hind hoof last year, and the Andrewses
considered taking Bodacious on another promotional tour later this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that he had so much medication (from his hoof injury)
last year, that it ultimately caused him to have kidney problems
and die,'' Carolyn Andrew said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked good'' until the end, Carolyn Andrews said. ``He was
fat and sassy.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
