<HEADER>
A4935 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHINA-TRADE-ART-2NDTA     05-24 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 WASHINGTON: lobby members.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Business leaders hailed the result as evidence that they could
marshal support for a trade deal despite a string of defeats in the
mid-1990s. Many had worried that after the collapse of world trade
negotiations in Seattle late last year, the sentiment against
globalization would make it difficult to get even the simplest and
most economically beneficial trade measures through Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we saw here is Congress telling the labor movement and
some of these other opponents that their shrill cry about how this
would destroy jobs just did not fit,'' said Thomas Donohue,
president of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But labor leaders denounced Wednesday's vote. ``This is a
betrayal of workers' interests,'' said George Becker, president of
the United Steelworkers of America. ``This is about moving
factories from the U.S. so that they can export back here.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuming about the Clinton administration's all-out pursuit of
China trade, Becker said the Steelworkers executive board would
meet in three weeks to discuss its political strategy in the
upcoming elections. ``Our members wrote 250,000 letters against
PNTR and that's not something you just forget,'' he said, using the
abbreviation for the trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   Local labor leaders have threatened to withhold support from two
House Democrats, Lois Capps of California and Sander Levin of
Michigan. And industrial unions have signaled that Gore's backing
for the bill has undermined enthusiasm for his presidential
candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Clinton sought to begin patching up the rift the
issue opened up between the administration and labor, by twice
inviting John J. Sweeney, president of the AFL-CIO, to join him on
Wednesday night at a big Democratic fund-raiser here. Sweeney
declined, aides said, unwilling to sit among the corporate
chieftains who championed the China bill.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We mounted a forceful and nearly successful challenge to an
array of money and forces unlike any before seen in a lobbying
campaign,'' Mr. Sweeney said.
</P>
<P>
   With the vast majority of lawmakers facing safe elections this
fall, many legislators openly put a price on their vote. For two
Texas Democrats, Silvestre Reyes and Solomon P. Ortiz, it was a
gasoline pipeline. They got a promise for speedy review and voted
yes. A Minnesota Democrat, James Oberstar, requested protection for
iron-ore workers. He did not get it and voted no.
</P>
<P>
   In the span of a month, Congress has now approved the China bill
and legislation to expand trade ties with more than 70 nations in
sub-Saharan Africa and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the administration's last major trade victory was
passage of the Uruguay Round in 1994 that created the World Trade
Organization and the North American Free Trade Agreement in 1993, a
pact that established duty-free commerce among the United States,
Canada and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's final vote cut across party lines, as 164
Republicans and 73 Democrats voted in favor; 57 Republicans, 183
Democrats and 2 independents voted against. By comparison, the
House passed NAFTA in 1993 by a vote of 234 to 200, with 102
Democrats and 132 Republicans supporting the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade is still controversial and China is controversial,''
said Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade representative who
negotiated the trade agreement with China and lobbied for it
ceaselessly in recent months. ``But we've shown that if you have a
solid agreement and real presidential backing, you can get it
through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
