<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-VIDEOGAME-WORTH-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT'S `X-BOX' CONSOLE THREATENS SONY, NINTENDO, SEGA  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Business, Lifestyle Editors)   (This 425-word ``separate-buy'' story is from the May 2000 issue of
``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be purchased
from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail
address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert,
please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``f'' financial
news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``l'' lifestyle news
files.)  
 &HT;    
 By TED C. FISHMAN  
 c.2000 Worth Magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Today's leading-edge video games take players through worlds
that go on forever. Just as soon as you think you've solved enough
puzzles, killed enough eight-headed dragons, and disarmed enough
malevolent wizards to conquer and rule, new enemies emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the business environment inhabited by the big
players in the gaming industry.
</P>
<P>
   Just when Sony, Nintendo, and Sega seemed to have the
game-console market all to themselves, along came Microsoft. In
March, the software giant announced that it was producing its own
machine to play games and DVD movies _ and to connect to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Like its competitors, Microsoft's machine, dubbed X-Box for now,
would connect to a television set easily and load software with
virtually no effort.
</P>
<P>
   And when released in the fall of 2001, it would have the best
graphics on the market, able to run faster, more visually detailed
games than Sega's already released Dreamcast console and Sony's
eagerly awaited PlayStation 2, due in American stores this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The X-Box's entry into the $20 billion a year video-game
industry will require investors to reexamine the competitive
terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Investors were initially keen on Sony stock following the
Japanese market's wildly enthusiastic reception of PlayStation 2
after its early March debut. Before long, though, Sony stock
plunged, as investors reacted to both the Microsoft news and
consumer complaints that Sony's console couldn't handle DVD movies.
</P>
<P>
   Sega fared even worse. PlayStation 2's runaway Japanese sales
dried up Dreamcast's sales there almost completely.
</P>
<P>
   As for Nintendo, once the category leader, little is known about
its next-generation machine, code-named Dolphin. Until now, the
company has stuck with cartridge games; its rivals all run
cheaper-to-make software disks.
</P>
<P>
   At least initially, Microsoft's entry into video-game hardware
is good news for consumers. As the hardware market gets more
competitive, prices will drop. That may spell trouble for Sony:
PlayStation 2's upfront development and marketing costs were
enormous.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese company was counting on recouping its investment
through increased hardware sales and licensing fees from game
designers. Competition is driving down the price of licenses,
placing hardware makers like Sony squarely in the middle of a
two-pronged price war.
</P>
<P>
   Where to turn? Warburg Dillon Read new-media analyst Michael P.
Wallace recommends that investors back the software companies that
make the most popular games, such as Electronic Arts (ERTS) and
Activision (ATVI).
</P>
<P>
   Since analysts expect that Americans will buy 40 to 50 million
new video-game machines within the next five years, that's not a
bad square to land on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Ted C. Fishman is a contributing editor of
``Worth.'') &LR;  &QL;
