<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIABYTES-FOST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MEDIA BYTES: AP HEARING PLENTY FROM JOURNALIST'S PEERS  &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A protest over a personnel move at the
Associated Press' San Francisco bureau was quelled this week _
though not by anything the AP did.
</P>
<P>
   Several Bay Area media outlets sent letters and petitions to the
AP, angry that veteran court reporter Bob Egelko had been
unceremoniously yanked from the legal beat.
</P>
<P>
   But before AP could even respond to the gripes, Egelko fled the
ranks, landing a job covering courts for the San Francisco
Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   As Egelko put it, there's not a little irony in his new post.
After all, he was yet another victim of local real estate developer
Clint Reilly's lawsuit that seeks to block the sale of The
Chronicle to the Hearst Corp. _ the owners of the Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Egelko covered the trial's opening day in federal district
court, but was not in the courtroom when Examiner Publisher Tim
White dropped the bombshell that he ``horse-traded'' the paper's
editorial coverage in exchange for Mayor Willie Brown's political
support of the Hearst acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the triggering event,'' Egelko conceded, while
declining to discuss the other reasons he was told he was pulled
from the beat. Egelko had been assigned to cover only the opening
arguments of the trial, and not sit through the testimony, so his
defenders wondered how he could be punished for following orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given whatever role the Examiner played in this, it's pretty
strange to end up there,'' Egelko said. ``Now my fate, like those
of so many others, depends on the outcome of this trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The new gig came about suddenly, Egelko said. He learned of his
demotion when he returned from vacation last Monday. The Examiner
called him Tuesday, and a week later _ on his 54th birthday _ he
took the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so unexpected and so welcomed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AP's San Francisco Bureau Chief Clay Haswell, a former editor of
the Contra Costa (Calif.) Times who came to the bureau last fall,
wouldn't discuss Egelko's situation at all. ``I don't discuss
personnel matters over the phone,'' Haswell said.
</P>
<P>
   Haswell received an earful from others in the media, including
reporters and editors at the legal newspapers the San Francisco
Daily Journal and the Recorder, The Chronicle, the Examiner, the
San Jose Mercury News and even the Los Angeles Times. Smaller
papers throughout the West, who depended on Egelko's coverage of
the Ninth Circuit Court of Appeals, were also objecting.
</P>
<P>
   The letters expressed concern that AP will weaken its coverage
of the courts. ``He's been invaluable to us,'' said Philip
Carrizosa, editor of the Daily Journal. ``He's almost like a staff
writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrizosa conceded that he couldn't exactly ask that Egelko be
returned to the beat, as who gets what assignments is ``up to AP.''
</P>
<P>
   But what makes this case different from, say, a newspaper that
took a reporter off a longtime beat is the very nature of the AP:
It is a cooperative that is owned by the 1,500-plus newspapers that
it serves.
</P>
<P>
   Egelko, an attorney who has served 16 years on the court beat,
acknowledges that none of his rights were violated, and he was not
involved in any of the protests over his situation. But he was
deeply disappointed by the move.
</P>
<P>
   SALON'S NEW LOOK: Don't adjust your dial. Salon.com has
redesigned its site, and the new look comes with some glitches.
</P>
<P>
   Software bugs have kept some pictures from showing up, some
links are dead, and some of what appears on the site looks stale.
</P>
<P>
   But it's all getting fixed and should be humming along within
two to four weeks. Already, you can see a few new features on the
site. Most notably, Salon _ which made its name as a well-written
Internet magazine _ is adding sections devoted to those two popular
Internet topics, sex and business. (It's also adding a sports
column by the Wall Street Journal's Allen Barra. And it's beefing
up its e-commerce offerings.)
</P>
<P>
   Much of the content for the new Sex and Business sections was
already on Salon in different forms; the sex stuff was tucked into
the Health section, and Sean Elder's columns, which appeared in the
now-defunct Media section, will move to Business.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Rosenberg, Salon's managing editor and vice president of
site development, hopes its beefed-up business and sex stories
aren't seen as mere pandering for eyeballs. ``Our hope, aspiration
and goal is that the highly literate journalism we do will be
maintained in these areas,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Salon received plenty of e-mail reacting to the changes, not all
of it positive. It had so many complaints about the smaller type
size that it is reverting to the old easier-to-read type.
Ironically enough, Rosenberg said, people complained at the last
redesign that Salon was forfeiting an elegant look for a more
cluttered appearance; people again think the site is chucking a
clean design for something more cluttered.
</P>
<P>
   Which I guess goes to prove that even on the Internet, people
are resistant to change.
</P>
<P>
   WHEN THE REVOLUTION COMES: In the 1960s, rock 'n' roll was
revolutionary and Rolling Stone was there to report on it. Now rock
and Rolling Stone are big businesses and Brisbane, Calif.'s Imagine
Media thinks it has found the next revolution in search of a
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, the publisher of Business 2.0 and a number of computer
game publications, plans to launch Revolution, a magazine about
dance music spun by DJs at nightclubs across the country.
</P>
<P>
   That music _ and, in turn, the magazine _ is fostered by the
Internet, and the growing popularity of swapping songs digitally.
Editor in Chief Neil Feineman had a hard time defining the music,
as it crosses many genres; a good way to get a feel for the
magazine is to check out its Web-site-in-waiting, at
 &LR; www.planetrevolution.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   The first issue of Revolution will appear on the July 4 weekend,
weighing in at 128 pages. Imagine plans a big splash, with launch
parties in New York, San Francisco and Los Angeles. The company
won't say where the June 22 San Francisco party will be, only that
it will be big, that it will be in a place that hasn't hosted a
party before and that the place could be called ``the glass
palace.'' (E-mail me if you have a clue!)
</P>
<P>
   The magazine is aiming for a circulation of 250,000, and
ultimately thinks it could take on rock icons such as Rolling Stone
_ much as the songs of Internet-savvy artists like Moby are
challenging the dominance of the traditional rock industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dance music has gone from a small divided niche subculture to
one with a huge place in the mainstream that has not been reported,
or is underreported,'' Feineman said. DJs are drawing thousands of
people in clubs from New York to Boulder, Colo., from Miami to
Omaha, Neb., he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for a magazine that puts a face on dance culture,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine represents a challenge for Imagine, which hasn't
tackled the mass market in this fashion before. But it will have
one innovation that draws inspiration from Imagine's computer game
titles: Each issue will come with a CD or two, featuring hot music
and links to artist Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Dan Fost at  &LR; fostd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
