<SLUG> BC-COMPUTINGQ&AMP;A-EINSTEIN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 COMPUTING Q&AMP;A: E-BILLING SERVICES HAVE MANY PLUSES  &HT;     By DAVID EINSTEIN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I've been paying my bills electronically for several years using
Quicken. Now I'm hearing that it may be easier if I use an online
bill-paying service. Is this true, and if it is, which services are
the best?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Bill-paying services are springing up all over the Internet, and
some of them are pretty good. Among the best _ PayMyBills.com,
Statusfactory.com and Paytrust. All of them alert you when your
bills are due and give you the option of paying them automatically.
You can view bills from the past year online. And they let you
download records of your transactions into Quicken or Microsoft
Money. Expect to pay about $9 a month for up to 25 payments.
</P>
<P>
   Is it worth switching from the bill-paying system you already
have? Maybe not. If you're satisfied with your Quicken service, it
might be best to stick with it. Same thing goes if you pay bills on
the Internet directly through your bank. But if you like the idea
of total automation, an online service could be just the thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Linux Suites Available
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I'm really tempted to give Linux a shot (I have an older PC
that's just sitting around that I could install it on). The
question is, are there any decent applications yet for Linux? I'd
like to do word processing and use the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: There are at least three office suites now available for Linux _
WordPerfect Office 2000, Applixware Office and StarOffice. All
include the usual office-suite components like a word processor,
spreadsheet and presentation program. The only real difference _
WordPerfect and Applixware will cost you (under $100 each), while
StarOffice is offered free from Sun Microsystems, which acquired
its maker last summer.
</P>
<P>
   I've been test driving a Windows version of StarOffice, and it's
pretty cool. Not as robust as Microsoft Office, but the word
processor is just dandy. You can open and save files in Microsoft
Word format, which lets you exchange documents with other Word
users. And, the best part _ it's free.
</P>
<P>
   For Web surfing, you'll need a Linux-based browser, and here
again you can get a good one gratis. Netscape offers a free Linux
version of its Communicator at  &LR; www.netscape.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Pick Hard Drive by Price
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: I'm considering getting a second hard drive for my PC. Is there
anything else besides price to consider when shopping for one?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Some drives run faster than others _ 7,200 rpm vs. 5,400 rpm,
for instance. But today's hard drives are so fast that performance
differences for common tasks are minor. And don't worry about brand
names, because any hard drive designed for a Windows PC should work
in your system.
</P>
<P>
   So, yeah, the only real consideration should be price. And
prices for hard drives have never been lower. In fact, CompUSA this
week is advertising a 20-gigabyte drive for $130.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Icons Are Movable
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: In Windows is there a way I can place the desktop icons wherever
I want and have them stay there? Right now, every time I try to
move an icon it pops back into position like a buck private bucking
for a promotion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: Your problem is that your system is using Windows' Auto Arrange
feature, which puts all the icons in nice, tidy columns. But it's
an easy problem to fix. Just right-click any empty area of the
desktop, point to Arrange Icons and click Auto Arrange to deselect
it. Then you can put your icons anywhere you want.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ADDRESS UPDATE: Several readers wrote in with an easier way to
clear the Location bar list in Netscape than the procedure I
described last week. Choose Preferences from the Edit menu, click
the Navigator category, and click Clear Location Bar at the bottom
of the window.
</P>
<P>
   One reader also suggested a free program called Communicator
Clear, which can automatically erase your Netscape history list,
cache files, location bar list, and cookie files each time you exit
your browser. You can download it at  &LR; www.hotfiles.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIP OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Ever worked on a really long document in Microsoft Word and
become frustrated when you had to scroll up and down to see
different parts of it? Try splitting the Word window in two. There
are a couple of ways to do this. Here's one: With your document
open, go to the Window menu and choose Split. Then drag the
demarcation line to where you want it and click to set it. This
will give you upper and lower windows, both of which contain your
document. You can scroll the windows individually. What's more, you
can edit the document in either window. Cool? You bet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
David Einstein is a columnist for Forbes Digital Tool. Got a
question about computing? E-mail it to  &LR; computers(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
