<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMERAS-DIGITAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DIGITAL CAMERAS COMING OF AGE  &HT;     By BECKY WARING 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Vacation season is upon us, and if you've been
sitting on the fence about buying a digital camera, now might be
the time to jump off.
</P>
<P>
   A new class of 3.3-megapixel models finally rivals good 35mm
film cameras in both image quality and features, while offering all
the advantages of digital-easy transfer to your computer for
cropping and editing, and the ability to share photos on the Web.
Even better, you can join the party for as little as $750.
</P>
<P>
   If that still seems like a lot, remember that there are no film
or processing costs with a digital camera, saving a lot of money
down the road for a little more up front.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras in this class include the Canon PowerShot S20, the Casio
QV-3000EX/3000Plus, the FujiFilm FinePix 4700, the Nikon CoolPix
990 and the Sony DSC-S70. For this review, I tried out the new
Olympus Camedia C-3000 ($799) and its big brother, the C-3030
($999). Olympus has a well-deserved reputation for making top-notch
digital as well as analog cameras, and these two lived up to their
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the many computer- and electronics-oriented companies
that have waded into the digital camera market, Olympus truly
understands the needs of the 35mm camera crowd and has taken pains
to make its digital cameras look, feel and operate as much like
traditional analog cameras as possible. The shape, size, weight and
control placements of the C-3000 and C-3030 all echo those of a
35mm model.
</P>
<P>
   The main differences are that the batteries and memory card go
where you would normally load film, and there is an LCD screen with
menu control buttons on the back. All very intuitive. I was able to
take my first pics without reading the manual, and they turned out
great.
</P>
<P>
   For any camera, however, the bottom line is picture quality. To
that end, both Olympus models have everything you would expect in a
good analog camera: excellent 32-96mm zoom lenses, full auto or
manual exposure controls (in either shutter or aperture priority,
with auto-bracketing), auto or manual white balance (corrects for
fluorescent, tungsten or outdoor lighting conditions), auto-focus
from eight inches to infinity, matrix and spot-metering, and a
self-timer.
</P>
<P>
   The C-3030 also allows manual focusing. Both cameras come with
remote controls and have flash mounts as well as built-in flash, so
you can attach a high-power bounce flash.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the 35mm camera parallels, the juicy part comes when
you start exploring the digital capabilities of these cameras. Both
Camedias offer 15 different combinations of image resolution and
compression, so you can snap pictures in everything from full
2,048-by-1,536 pixel uncompressed mode down to 640-by-480 JPEG
compressed. (Compressed images save disk space at the expense of
some fine detail.)
</P>
<P>
   At the highest quality, even an 8-by-10 print will look great.
The lowest quality is perfect for shots destined for the Web.
</P>
<P>
   If you're shooting family photos for posterity, go with the
2,048-by-1,536 HQ JPEG mode. While only 20 HQ pics will fit on the
16MB SmartMedia card that comes with the C-3030 (10 on the C-3000's
8MB card), the quality and detail are worth it. We highly recommend
buying a couple of extra SmartMedia cards for either camera, so you
can take it on vacation without having to download pics along the
way. Extra 32MB cards that hold 40 HQ pics will set you back about
$70 each. Another handy add-on is a USB SmartCard reader, about
$55.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't need such high-quality pics, storage space becomes
much less of an issue. A 16MB card holds 165 standard quality
640-by-480 JPEG pics, more than enough for purposes like online
auction photos, Web site illustrations and e-mailing to friends.
Think about what you will be using the picture for before you take
it, and choose a resolution accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   The 1.8-inch LCD panel on the back lets you preview shots (you
can even use it instead of the viewfinder), as well as see the pics
you've already taken. It's also where you'll find the menus for
settings like resolution, white balance and flash mode.
</P>
<P>
   Just be warned that it draws a lot of power. If you expect to
use it a lot, keep extra batteries on hand. Better yet, use the
optional rechargeables or power adapter.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that sets the C-3030 apart from the competition (and
the C-3000) is its recording speed.
</P>
<P>
   With 32MB of internal RAM, it can take 3.3 pictures per second
in a special five-shot sequence mode, or one second between shots
in normal operation. Most cameras in this class (including the
C-3000) make you wait at least two seconds from shot to shot while
images are recorded to the card, a big disadvantage when you are
trying to capture fast motion or fleeting baby moments. Shooting
speed remains one of the primary advantages of analog cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Both cameras also have the really neat ability to capture short
movie and sound clips, as well as still pictures. The C-3000 can
shoot a full minute of 160x120 video with sound at 15 fps, or 15
seconds at 320x240.
</P>
<P>
   The C-3030, with its bigger RAM and media card, supports 191
seconds and 46 seconds, respectively. Movies are saved in QuickTime
Motion-JPEG format. Another option is to record up to four seconds
of audio after a still picture, a handy way to identify pictures or
capture your kids' words to go with their faces.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the pictures and movies into your computer is amazingly
easy, and both PCs and Macs are fully supported. You simply install
the software, and attach the USB cable between the camera and
computer (an optional serial cable is available for the PC).
</P>
<P>
   Then, when you open the Camedia software, thumbnails of all the
pics on the card show up in a window. You can perform simple
editing tasks within the Camedia software, as well as stitch
panoramic images together (a great way to capture especially tall
or wide scenes).
</P>
<P>
   But both packages also include excellent image-editing software:
the consumer-oriented Adobe PhotoDeluxe for the C-3000 and the
pro-level Adobe Photoshop LE for the C-3030.
</P>
<P>
   While we quickly got addicted to the C-3030 due to its larger
card and faster shooting speed, most features and capabilities of
the two cameras are the same. If you're on a budget, choose the
C-3000. If you can afford the extra $200, go for the C-3030. Both
are great cameras that will make the transition from 35mm to
digital as painless as possible.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Becky Waring at  &LR; becky(AT)waring.org &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
