<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-VOTE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE BILL FOR CHINA WINS EASILY IN HOUSE 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House approved permanent trading privileges for
China Wednesday by a substantial margin, handing President Clinton
the biggest foreign policy victory of his second term and ending a
long, hard-fought battle over the issue between organized labor and
corporate America.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which would end Congress' annual review of
China's trade status in return for Beijing opening its vast markets
to hundreds of U.S. goods and services, passed 237-197.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-three Democrats joined with 164 Republicans to give
supporters 19 more than the 218 votes needed for victory.
</P>
<P>
   The measure next month is expected to pass easily in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the House vote, Clinton, who spent the day doing
some last-minute arm-twisting to secure wavering Democrats,
predicted the legislation would reap huge economic benefits for
Americans by creating more jobs through increased U.S. exports and
imports from China.
</P>
<P>
   But he also stressed its importance as a tool to help ease China
toward more social and economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be exporting more than our products. ... By this
agreement we will also export one of our most cherished values _
economic freedom,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``America will continue to defend our interests, but at this
stage in China's development we will have more positive influence
with an outstretched hand than with a clenched fist. The House
today has affirmed that belief.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure could boost the sales in China of hundreds of
American products ranging from agricultural goods, oil field
equipment and chemicals to telecommunications and financial
services.
</P>
<P>
   In return for lowering its own tariffs in a wide variety of
categories, Washington would guarantee the same normal trade breaks
to Beijing that are now enjoyed by most other U.S. trading
partners. Up until now, the lower tariff treatment has been
extended to China on a year-to-year basis, pending an annual review
by Congress of the country's human rights record and its dealings
with other nations.
</P>
<P>
   Extending the lower tariffs and other breaks on a permanent
basis would also help speed up China's entry into the World Trade
Organization, which sets and enforces the rules of global commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese membership in the WTO would also allow U.S. businesses
to take advantage of other market-opening concessions that Beijing
would be forced to make as a condition of joining the global
trading partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Entry into the WTO has been a long-sought goal of the Chinese
leadership, and Beijing would have likely gained access without the
support of the United States. But the Clinton administration
maintained that without a bilateral trade agreement prior to
China's entry into the WTO, American businesses would lose
potentially valuable markets to the European Union, which struck a
new trade agreement with Beijing just last week.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Houston, said the fact that China would
still have been allowed into the WTO no matter how the vote went
Wednesday was instrumental in some members deciding to support
permanent trade status. He said the legislation gives the United
States more leverage and protections on trade issues than it would
have gotten under normal WTO partnership rules.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, China hailed the ``wise'' vote by the House. But the
official Xinhua news agency quoted a Trade Ministry spokesman as
saying provisions in the U.S. trade bill setting up a commission to
monitor China's human rights record were ``unacceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the debate began Wednesday in Washington, opponents
of the measure acknowledged that the fight was over. Nonetheless,
they continued to urge colleagues to rethink their positions as
they offered impassioned speeches condemning Beijing's long record
of human rights abuses and its disdain for labor and environmental
regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Gene Green, D-Houston, one of five lawmakers in the
30-member Texas delegation to vote against the measure, called
China ``a great country'' that has contributed much to the world.
But he scoffed at claims that increased trade with the United
States has led China's communist regime to relax its oppressive
control over its people.
</P>
<P>
   Despite 20 years of special trade treatment by the United
States, Green said China's human rights records is still
``abysmal'' and getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Houston, and other supporters
said the bill would open up China's huge markets to U.S. companies
and do more to promote democratic change than the current annual
review process, which usually amounts to nothing more a divisive
debate in the House over human rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade,'' she said, ``is the engine of democracy throughout the
world.'' Without improved trading relations, she said, America
stands little chance of influencing Beijing's actions.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to attract more support for the bill, the president
worked closely with House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill
Archer, R-Houston, and other Republican leaders to target wavering
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Members, particularly Democrats, were summoned to the White
House for one-on-one sessions with the president. Many were willing
to support permanent trading privileges for China in return for
help from the president on local issues.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also picked up additional support, by working with House
Speaker Dennis Hastert. R-Ill., to hammer out a new community
development and job creation initiative that will help form new
public-private business partnerships in depressed inner city and
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers were also won over after Republican leaders
agreed to a provision in the bill that would establish a
congressional watchdog commission to monitor human rights abuses in
China and to recommend trade sanctions if necessary. The GOP
leadership also included another provision designed to prevent
import surges from China, which opponents fear will happen as soon
as the president signs the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, three Democrats in the Texas delegation and two
Republicans voted against the bill. In addition to Green, the
Democrats were Ciro Rodriguez of San Antonio and Nick Lampson of
Beaumont. The Republicans were Joe Barton of Ennis and Ron Paul of
Surfside. Paul had committed to vote for the bill, but changed his
mind late Tuesday because of the changes made in the bill to
attract more support.
</P>
<P>
   As the 15-minute voting process began in the House, Rep. Max
Sandlin, D-Marshall, was the only Texan who was still undecided. He
stood in the back of the chamber, talking alternately to both
supporters and opponents of the bill. With 10 seconds to go, he
stepped forward and voted for the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents argued that the China trade bill would end up
costing Americans jobs while rewarding a brutal regime that uses
forced abortions, imprisonment and forced labor to maintain its
control over the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
   Bitter over their defeat, some labor leaders warned supporters
of the legislation that they could face union opposition in the
November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress has turned its back on the American manufacturing
base and America's working families,'' said James P. Hoffa,
president of the Teamsters Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are Teamster families in every congressional district in
America, and those families vote,'' he added. ``Those who would
oppose these families have done so at their own political peril.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential
contender, said in a statement after the vote that the legislation
``will mean a stronger American economy, as well as more
opportunity for liberty and freedom in China.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill has not played a major role in the presidential race
since it is supported by both Bush and Vice President Al Gore, the
Democratic presidential contender.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
