<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PASSES CHINA TRADE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House, by a surprisingly comfortable margin,
Wednesday agreed to normalize trade relations with China, bringing
the United States within reach of a new and potentially lucrative
relationship with a nation of 1.3 billion consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The 237-197 vote to give China permanent normal trade status
provided President Clinton and business interests with a hard-won
victory on their top legislative priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``For China, this agreement will clearly increase the benefits
of cooperation and the costs of confrontation,'' Clinton said.
``America, of course, will continue to defend our interests, but at
this stage in China's development we will have more positive
influence with an outstretched hand than with a clenched fist.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Washington state lawmakers and businesses strongly endorsed
the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Co. Chairman Phil Condit said approval helps ``pave the
way for China to join the World Trade Organization and, in so
doing, will strengthen the rules-based, global trading system so
essential to the future of all of us.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also will stabilize the U.S.-China relationship in ways
that will create a solid foundation for resolving other important
issues,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It this had not passed, it would have been a devastating
defeat for United States leadership in world trade,'' said Rep.
Norm Dicks, D-Wash. ``And if we hadn't won today, Airbus (a major
competitor to Boeing) would have had an open shot at the $120
billion airline market in China.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also lobbied heavily for passage of the bill, saying
China will be the second-largest market for personal computers by
the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Davis, a Port of Seattle commissioner and president of
the Washington Council on International Trade, said she was
``jubilant'' over the result. ``It means opportunity for almost
every sector in this state,'' including aerospace, agriculture,
high-tech and natural resources including forest products.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunities are there,'' she said, adding that the
agreement also means opportunities for reform to take hold in
China.
</P>
<P>
   But the vote was a major setback for many labor unions, human
rights groups and consumer advocates who fiercely opposed the
measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Congress has turned its back on the American manufacturing
base and America's working families. ... There are Teamster
families in every congressional district in America, and those
families vote,'' said Teamsters President James P. Hoffa.
</P>
<P>
   If the trade bill is approved by the Senate, as expected, China
would be required to open its borders to more U.S. goods, services
and agriculture. It would have to lower tariffs on U.S. products
from an average of 25 percent to 9 percent by 2005 and conform to
global trading rules.
</P>
<P>
   While supporters said every corner of the country would benefit,
Washington state is poised to reap especially large rewards because
of its location as a gateway to the Pacific Rim and because of
China's strong demand for the products of the state's major
industries. Supporters also said the measure would incubate social
change and democracy in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will allow us to export not only commodities but
democracy,'' said Rep. George Nethercutt, R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout three hours of impassioned debate, opponents claimed
that giving China permanent normal trade status would cost U.S.
jobs and reward a country for abusing human rights. California
Democrat Nancy Pelosi chided members for ``putting deals above
ideals.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dicks said a defeat would have seriously undercut the United
States' status in world trade as well as put major U.S.
manufacturers at a serious disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. Jennifer Dunn, R-Wash., said ``engaging China as a
willing and confident trade partner and taking our message to her
people will prove, time and time again, to be the right course.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As one of the most trade-dependent states in the nation, the
best thing we can do for our farmers and farm communities is to
open up new export markets and help level the playing field,'' said
Rep. Doc Hastings, R-Wash. ``China is a significant market for our
state's products, like apples and wheat, and today's vote takes a
significant step toward making sure other products can share in
that success.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the eventual margin, the outcome was in doubt as late as
Tuesday despite furious lobbying by Clinton, business interests and
Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., who led the opposition, told his
colleagues during a floor speech that awarding China normal trade
status would perpetuate harsh working conditions and pay that
averages ``three cents an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're told we need this trade deal to open vast new markets
for American goods,'' Bonior said. ``But these Chinese workers
can't even afford to buy the products they make themselves. ...
Americans value trade, but we're not willing to trade in our
values.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, however, lawmakers decided that the United States
will enhance democracy and improve human rights by accellerating
trade with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every now and then,'' House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Tex.
said after the vote, ``you get to work in a very special way for
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the votes against the measure came from Democrats, but
all five of Washington state's Democrat lawmakers voted for the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not view trade with China and the advocacy of human
rights issues as contradictory,'' said Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash.
``The best foreign policy tools available to encourage political
reform abroad are policies that promote capitalism and market
reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   The measure moves next month to the Senate where its support is
both deep and wide, including the backing of Washington's Slade
Gorton and Patty Murray.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need the opportunity to review what the House has sent us,
but then I expect us to take our turn at bat,'' said Senate Finance
Committee Chairman William Roth, R-Del.
</P>
<P>
   The ride won't be completely free of bumps.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, asserted that ``I do not intend to allow the
Senate to simply rubber-stamp the president's plan to reward the
Chinese Communists in Beijing.'' He promised ``votes _ perhaps
uncomfortable votes _ on a range of issues relating to China.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Helms' threat, Senate leaders said they are confident
the bill will pass and be forwarded quickly to Clinton for his
signature.
</P>
<P>
   Wire service material is included in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
