u v BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT     05-24 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, MAY 25
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-COLLEGE-CLOSING-NYT (moved on Sunday, May 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, May 21,
about the closing of Bradford College in Haverhill, Mass., cited an
estimate erroneously for the drop since 1960 in the percentage of
students attending liberal arts colleges. Although the percentage
has declined, precise figures are not available.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-LAZIO-NYT (moved on Tuesday, May 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, May 23,
about Representative Rick A. Lazio and his campaign appearance on
the No. 6 subway line misstated the price of a MetroCard. While
Lazio said it was about $3 and the article said the cheapest card
was $4, both answers were wrong. Station vending machines sell a
card for $1.50, good for one ride.
</P>
<P>
   BC-NY-TOUR-BUSES-NYT (moved on Tuesday, May 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, May 23,
about New York City's efforts to suspend the license of a tour
company after one of its buses killed a pedestrian misstated the
surname of the victim in some copies. He was Randolph Walker, not
Walter.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-BRODY-HEALTH-NYT (moved on Monday, May 8)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, May 8,
about the 40th anniversary of the birth control pill, referred
incorrectly to the number of women who have taken the pill since
its introduction in 1960. The exact number is unknown. Johns
Hopkins University has estimated that 80 percent of American women
born since 1945 have used oral contraceptives at some time. The
erroneous figure, 468 million, applied to the number of women who
started taking the pill in any given year plus the number of women
who continued to use it from the previous year, for a total of 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-BILL-ONLINE-NYT (moved on Wednesday, May 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, May 10,
about Web-based bill-paying services misstated the affiliation of
Kellie Scott, who commented on security issues. She is a senior
vice president of the First Union Corp. and director of eChannels,
its e-commerce division _ not of Union Trust, which was bought by
First Union in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CONCERT-MASTER-NYT (moved on Wednesday, May 17)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, May 17,
about the retirement of Raymond Gniewek as concertmaster of the
Metropolitan Opera Orchestra included an erroneous historical
reference from the company. Gniewek was the orchestra's second
American-born concertmaster; Nahan Franko was the first, from 1899
into the early 1900's.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
