<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4971 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-FEDERAL-BUILDING-SECU     05-24 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEDERAL-BUILDING-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATORS IDENTIFY SECURITY BREACHES AT SEVERAL U.S. AGENCIES
</HEADLINE>
  By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Flashing fake police badges that were movie props
and other bogus law enforcement identifications, undercover
investigators effortlessly entered 19 sensitive federal buildings
including the CIA, the FBI, the Pentagon and the Justice Department
where the investigators sauntered into the attorney general's
fifth-floor suite of offices.
</P>
<P>
   The examination of security, performed by the General Accounting
Office at the request of Republican lawmakers from the House of
Representatives, was described on Tuesday in private briefings to
the agencies and will be the subject of a congressional hearing on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In written testimony prepared for the hearing, the GAO
investigators said they made the counterfeit identification cards
from software that is easily obtainable from the Internet. They
said they also claimed to be armed and carried satchels into the
buildings that were never searched or passed through metal
detectors and were large enough to carry explosives, chemical or
biological weapons or listening devices.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators said they were able to roam unescorted through
most of the buildings, including at the State and Justice
departments. In all, the investigators were able to penetrate 19
buildings and two airports using the phony badges and
identifications, though at three of the buildings, they had to try
twice before getting in.
</P>
<P>
   They also managed to park a van in the courtyard of the Justice
Department without having its contents examined.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers who disclosed the results of the inquiry
Wednesday said that it highlighted significant and systemic
security problems that continue to plague the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, the State Department has been reeling from a
series of security lapses, including the disappearance of a laptop
computer that contained highly sensitive files concerning
intelligence sources and weapons proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   Before that incident, officials discovered an eavesdropping
device in a State Department conference room and expelled a Russian
diplomat from the country. And in 1998, a man in a tweed sport coat
strolled into the executive secretary's office, six doors down from
the secretary of state's office, and left with sheaves of
classified documents while two secretaries worked nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a shocking report revealing a dangerous vulnerability
plaguing thousands of people who work in our public buildings,''
said Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who heads the House Judiciary
Committee. ``Complacency in matters of security is a serious threat
to the orderly functioning of our government.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill McCollum, R-Fla., who asked the accounting office to
perform the review, said the inquiry had demonstrated ``that far
too many of our security facilities where top secret and sensitive
information is kept have an open door policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they were troubled by the findings
and had already undertaken to correct the security lapses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the attempts to come into the department have
caused concern,'' said Gretchen Michael, a spokeswoman for the
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Michael said the department had adjusted its security procedures
as a result of the inquiry, which she said could not be disclosed
for security reasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2212EDT &QL; 
