<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4976 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-MISSING-SUPERMOM--TEX     05-24 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-SUPERMOM--TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE-SMUG DAD HUMBLED BY WEEK AS A SINGLE PARENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've always congratulated myself on being one of those men who
fully appreciate the labors of their wives. Catherine is a
free-lance editor and full-time mom, who also runs our household
with an efficiency that Lee Iaccoca in his heyday could never
aspire to. I have always freely conceded that her days are much
more demanding than mine.
</P>
<P>
   But I didn't know the half of it. A few weeks back, my wife left
us for a week to attend the funeral of her aunt, leaving my
8-year-old son, Patrick, and me to fend for ourselves. By the time
she returned, I was droopy-limbed from exhaustion, physical and
mental. We will need a large addition to our house for the shrine I
plan on building to my wife.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, the same week would have been far less
demanding. Back then, I was perfectly content to let dirty dishes
pile up until no clean dishes were left. I washed bedding once a
year, whether the sheets needed it or not. A refrigerator was fully
stocked as long as it contained a 2-week-old carton of milk and a
half-full bottle of ketchup, which doubled as spaghetti sauce in a
pinch. (For those who haven't guessed, this was during
bachelorhood.)
</P>
<P>
   But after 10 years of marriage, some of Catherine's fastidious
(notice I didn't say anal-retentive) ways have rubbed off. While
she was gone, I washed the dishes immediately after my son and I
ate. I could not walk by our unmade bed, and I told my son to make
his, too (though he ignored me, for the most part, and a couple of
times I caved in and made it myself.) Two or three hundred times a
day, I wiped the counter free of bread crumbs and jelly. I vacuumed
the day before my wife got home. (I thought about cleaning the
bathrooms, but my own fastidiousness has its limits.) I bought real
groceries; cooked a couple of real meals (ham and cheese omelettes
one night, spaghetti another. My repertoire pretty much ends
there.) I did a couple of loads of laundry. I picked my son up from
school and drove him to hockey practice and violin lessons. I
checked his homework; helped him with spelling words; made him a
special breakfast the morning of his state achievement test; goaded
him into practicing his musical instrument; and laid out his
clothes in the morning, in an attempt to prevent a third-grade
fashion felony.
</P>
<P>
   I am out of breath now, just thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   What surprised me more than anything about that week was the
relentlessness of it. Running a house, even with standards as
meager as my own, there is always something to do. Always. Daily
private time with a book or television, time that I had come to
believe was my God-given entitlement, somehow vanished. By the time
Patrick had been put to bed, I had enough energy to read a few
paragraphs of a novel, or watch a few minutes of mindless
television. Normally a night owl, I was dead asleep each night by
10.
</P>
<P>
   So it's hard, this household duty. Harder than I ever knew. And
I haven't yet mentioned the most important task in the litany of
household-running: being emotionally present for a child when he
wakes up in the morning, or comes home from school each day. Was
Patrick nervous about the achievement test? Did he think about Aunt
Thelma, who had just died? Any trouble on the playground? I know I
asked these questions while my wife was gone, but it can be hard to
listen when thinking about a grocery list.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick and I did attend a Texas Rangers baseball game that
week, which was a wonderful break for us both. No vacuuming at The
Ballpark. There we could be just a couple of guys, hanging out, a
luxury we have when my wife is around. Have I said how happy I was
when she came home?
</P>
<P>
   I know Catherine loves her life, challenging as it is. For a
week, I loved it, too. With the challenges come immense rewards.
Washing a sink full of dishes carries its own sense of
accomplishment. Tucking Patrick in at night, knowing he felt safe
and cared for, even when his mom was gone _ well, few things in
life are better.
</P>
<P>
   But the week thoroughly depleted our reserves. How single
parents do it, I have no idea. And I caution any man who thinks he
appreciates his wife's exertions as household czarina. Until
recently, I was guilty of such smugness.
</P>
<P>
   Then she left for a week.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
