<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4978 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BOOK-SNAKEBITE-SURVIV     05-24 0492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SNAKEBITE-SURVIVORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE INDIANA JONES, HE HATES SNAKES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW MARTON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Snakebite Survivor's Club: Travels Among Serpents'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   by Jeremy Seal &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nonfiction &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Harcourt, $24 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Marton &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the neurotic and the phobic _ and that covers just about
everyone _ a good self-help group usually eases the pain. British
author Jeremy Seal, however, found a more solitary catharsis for
his personal fear: writing a book.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Snakebite Survivors' Club: Travels Among Serpents,''
Seal plumbs his loathing of serpents by seeking them out. By turns
harrowing and droll, historical and all-too-human, ``Club'' uses
language and history to battle a paralyzing aversion shared by
many.
</P>
<P>
   Seal's travelogue includes stops in Scottsboro, Ala., for its
copperheads and timber rattlers; Kenya, the domain of coiled puff
adders; India, for its hooded cobras; and Australia, where the
taipan packs enough fatal venom to dispatch hordes of men.
</P>
<P>
   This is resolutely the work of a Brit, filled with wonderfully
wry turns of poetry (a snake's head is ``tapered like a coffin'')
and clinical detachment. Mostly stiff-upper-lip with hardly a
quavering confession to be found, Seal's book does introduce a zany
cast of characters, from serpent wranglers to weekend snake
shamans. ALthough the book confounds the reader with its sometimes
soporific digressions into snake lore, Seal shrewdly threads his
narrative with the chilling story of an alcoholic fundamentalist
preacher who attempts to murder his wife by forcing her hand into a
box of rattlers.
</P>
<P>
   Although Seal won't be confused with Stephen King when it comes
to ratcheting up the tension, his passages still gnaw at the
nerves. One story describes ``Kevin'' who, bitten by a taipan,
deteriorates with alarming swiftness, suffering blurred vision,
vomiting, a paralyzed tongue, a pulse that races to 120 beats per
minute and, finally, the labored breathing that precedes his final
death rattle.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, poisonous snakes do prompt occasional humor. Over
time, snake-bite cures have included leeches, the use of strychnine
as a second poison to counteract the venom (Pick your poison?) and
(a personal favorite) igniting gunpowder on the bite. Blow off the
arm, blow off the snake bite, right?
</P>
<P>
   Seal never quite escapes the feeling of being stalked by
imaginary snakes. Walking in a West Kenyan field, in the glow of a
setting sun, he is convinced that a thousand pairs of orange eyes
are swiveling in the heads of a thousand deadly serpents, all
poised to strike. It is in that moment of sweaty-palmed fear, with
Seal trying desperately to keep his feeble matches lit to frighten
away his imagined enemy, that the crushing power of his phobia _
and ours _ becomes all too real.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4979 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TEXTILE-LAWSUIT-NYT     05-24 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXTILE-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEALS COURT REJECTS MEMBERS' LAWSUIT AGAINST UNION
</HEADLINE>
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal appeals court in Manhattan has refused to
reinstate a class-action lawsuit filed in 1997 against a leading
garment industry union by union members who contended they were not
fairly represented in a complex arbitration case against the
clothing manufacturer Liz Claiborne.
</P>
<P>
   The workers, who had been employed at Mademoiselle Knitware, a
now-defunct sweater factory in Brooklyn, had filed the lawsuit
against the Union of Needletrades, Industrial and Textile
Employees, known as Unite, and two of its locals.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual dispute, which pitted the union members against
their own labor leaders at what had once been a showcase factory
for the garment industry, boiled down to the question of who
actually had the legal duty to protect the interests of the
Brooklyn workers.
</P>
<P>
   In a ruling released Tuesday, the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals affirmed the trial judge's decision last summer that
neither the parent union nor the two locals owed the Brooklyn
workers any ``duty of fair representation'' under federal labor
laws.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute involved the parent union, Unite; Local 23-25, which
represented Claiborne workers; and Local 155, which represented
workers at Mademoiselle.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Claiborne had promised a Unite official, who was also
manager of Local 23-25, that it would order a specific volume of
sweaters from Mademoiselle. When Claiborne reneged, Local 23-25
filed an arbitration case against Claiborne on behalf of the
Mademoiselle workers, who were represented by Local 155.
</P>
<P>
   The union won that arbitration case and, when Claiborne still
did not supply the promised orders, it filed a second case in 1996
to enforce the earlier ruling.
</P>
<P>
   But in May 1997, during collective bargaining talks with
Claiborne, Unite and Local 23-25 agreed to nullify the first
arbitration award, drop the second arbitration case and free
Claiborne from its commitment to order sweaters from Mademoiselle.
In turn, Claiborne agreed to pay $750,000 into a fund to be
distributed to the Local 155 workers but to be administered by
Local 23-25.
</P>
<P>
   A group of workers at Mademoiselle later accused Unite and Local
23-25 of selling them out in exchange for a separate pact,
concluded around the same time, which obligated Claiborne to pay
$13 million in damages to the parent union and the Claiborne local.
They further accused their own local of failing to protect them in
the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   But under federal labor law, the trial court found, the only
union legally obligated to protect the Mademoiselle workers was
their own collective bargaining unit, Local 155.
</P>
<P>
   That local could not be held liable in the class-action case,
however, because it had played no role in the disputed settlement,
the trial court concluded. Unite and Local 23-25, which had
negotiated the settlement, could not be held liable because neither
was the designated collective bargaining unit for the Mademoiselle
workers. Thus, neither had a legally enforceable duty to act in the
best interests of Local 155's members.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate court affirmed that interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, the duty of fair representation arises only with
respect to a union entity that is certified as the exclusive
bargaining representative of a group of employees,'' the appeals
court found.
</P>
<P>
   Jo-Ann Mort, a spokeswoman for Unite, said the union was
``delighted'' by the appeals court's refusal to reinstate the
Mademoiselle case, which Unite had long argued was without merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that this concludes this unfortunate chapter and
allows us to get back to doing what we have done all along, namely,
providing our members with the best representation possible,'' Mort
said.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Rhine, a lawyer who represented the Mademoiselle workers,
said he was considering whether to petition the U.S. Supreme Court
to take up the issue. ``There has to be a remedy if there is a
wrong,'' he said. ``But what this court is saying is that no one is
responsible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
