   (NYT13) BOSTON -- May 24, 2000 -- BOLIVAR-COLLECTOR-BOS -- In
March, Maury Bromsen officially parted with his beloved collection
of artifacts related to Simon Bolivar - the 19th-century
revolutionary leader in the struggle for South American
independence. The collection of ``Bolivariana'' - valued, he says,
at ``several millions of dollars'' - was donated to the John Carter
Brown Library at Brown University. Bromsen, 81, was surrounded by
art in his apartment, including a bust of Marquis de Lafayette,
circa 1790, right. (Pat Greenhouse/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) METULLA, Israel -- May 25, 2000 -- ISRAEL-LEBANON-2 --
Relief swept Israel after the last Israeli tank rolled out of
Lebanon at daybreak Wednesday, but joy over the safe homecoming of
the troops was tinged with dread over an uncertain future along the
volatile frontier. Israel's troop withdrawal was swift and smooth.
In less than six hours, some 1,000 Israeli soldiers blew up or
dismantled a dozen army outposts in the buffer zone Israel
controlled for 18 years. Israeli soldiers complete the pullout from
South lebanon at sunrise, Wednesday. (Rina Castelnuovo/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) DEDHAM, Mass. -- May 24, 2000 -- BARBIE-ASIANS-BOS --
When Mattel Inc. unveiled the new, enlightened ``Barbie for
President 2000'' doll, she was created in Caucasian,
African-American, and Latin-American versions. But somehow, the
Asian-American version never made it to stores. The snub has
angered many Asian-Americans - the nation's third largest minority.
Five-year-old Annie Joy Abbott displayed her ``Kira'' Barbie dolls.
(Wendy Maeda/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LARCHMONT, N.Y. -- May 24, 2000 -- BOOK-TALK -- At a
time when small, independent bookstores are being sucked down one
at a time into the whirlpool of the large chains, it would seem
quixotic, if not outlandish, to get into the independent bookstore
business. But Peter Greeman, 68, a retired advertising executive,
has bucked the trend and opened a new bookstore in Larchmont, where
he grew up. ``I have a place in my heart for this particular
bookstore,'' he said. (Susan B. Markisz/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- May 24, 2000 -- NY-ARTISTS-HOUSING-2 -- The
Westbeth housing project is showing its age. The grand experiment
in subsidized artists' housing opened in 1970, but has never looked
seedier than now, on its 30th anniversary. Still, it could reclaim
its original vision as a new wave of artists moves in. Shami
Chaikin, left, with her paintings in her apartment-work space. Her
brother, the director Joseph Chaikin, right, gives readings at
home. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- May 24, 2000 -- NY-ARTISTS-HOUSING-1 -- The
balconies facing the courtyard of the Westbeth housing project in
downtown Manhattan - the grand experiment in subsidized artists'
housing that opened in 1970 - show their age. Yet, on its 30th
anniversary, Westbeth is poised to reclaim its original vision. As
the oldest tenants die or move out, a new wave of artists are
taking their place. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) AGAWAM, Mass. -- May 24, 2000 -- TRAVEL-SIXFLAGS-BOS --
The ``Superman - Ride of Steel'' roller coaster at Six Flags New
England is generating the most buzz at the revamped theme and water
park, which opened in May. The ride rockets you along a winding,
mile-long track at up to 70 miles an hour, and drops you down a
221-foot drop that leaves you weightless for 10 seconds. (Tom
Herde/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- May 24, 2000 -- CIR-VIRTUAL-PETS-2 -- Watching
children assign personality and emotion to toys is nothing new, but
the growing category of ``sort of alive'' breaks new ground. A
matrix of sensors and chips allows My Real Baby, made by Hasbro, to
interact with people. At first, it simply stares and coos. After
the doll is played with, it asks for things, and over time, it
forms complete sentences. (Tony Cenicola/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- May 24, 2000 -- EUROPEAN-PORCELAIN -- In a
gesture that could be interpreted as either the last straw for
minimalism or an inspired embrace of refined product design,
several hundred pieces of porcelain, conceived in the 18th century
at the Nymphenburg factory in Bavaria but still in production, were
on display at Moss, the SoHo store and purveyor of avant-garde
modernism. An ornate table setting bleaches into white at Moss.
(Ruby Washington/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- May 24, 2000 -- NEW-CURRENCY -- The
Treasury Department and the Federal Reserve unvieled new five and
ten dollar bills Wednesday during a ceremony on the steps of the
Lincoln Memorial. Students from Eastern High School and Wilson High
School were recruited to turn over placards to showcase the new
bills. One student missed his cue. (Justin Lane/The New York Times)
LITE
</P>
