<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELIG-REALIGNMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELIG SAYS HE HAS VOTES FOR REALIGNMENT
</HEADLINE>
  By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yes, he does have the votes for his realignment plan,
Commissioner Bud Selig said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   After Selig postponed an owners meeting scheduled for June 13
and 14, a baseball lawyer said the commissioner did not have enough
votes to adopt the plan that would move Arizona to the American
League and Tampa Bay to the National League, among other elements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have the votes,'' Selig said by telephone from his
Milwaukee office. He postponed the meeting, he said, to explore
other possible alignments and schedules before making a final
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have only one real objective here, an unbalanced schedule,''
Selig said. ``I think this plan is the best way, but we'll look at
others.''
</P>
<P>
   The players association has to approve any change in the league
structures, and Selig acknowledged it would be a problem if the
union rejected the prevailing plan. ``But I don't think there's an
alternative,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The chief opponents of the plan among owners appear to be some
teams in the American League Central, which would have six teams
compared with four in the league's other divisions, and the
Cincinnati Reds, who don't like the idea of being in a Southeast
Division with Atlanta, Tampa Bay and Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Selig indicated that the owners' meeting would be rescheduled
for early July. A majority in each league is needed to approve a
realignment plan.  &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2218EDT &QL; 
