<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4986 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HEINEKEN-AD-COLUMN-NY     05-24 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEINEKEN-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEINEKEN TAKES ITS U.S. CAMPAIGN TO THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A humorous campaign in the United States for the flagship beer
brewed by Heineken NV is increasing sales. That has sold Heineken
executives on giving the agency creating the campaign an additional
major assignment: to develop and produce Heineken brand advertising
that is to run around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Heineken is significantly expanding its relationship with the
New York office of Lowe Lintas &AMP; Partners Worldwide, which since
April 1998 has created ads for Heineken USA. The worldwide
assignment is a new one; typically, Heineken campaigns are produced
by local agencies that vary country by country.
</P>
<P>
   The awarding of the new duties to Lowe Lintas New York points to
intensified efforts by giant marketers to improve the creative
content of their campaigns. Heineken joins advertisers like
Coca-Cola, Kellogg, McDonald's and Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to raise the bar on creative,'' Frazer Thompson,
global brand director at Heineken in Amsterdam, said in a telephone
interview. ``So the first place you turn is to the people who are
doing it well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a creative ethos at Lowe you don't find at many
agencies,'' he added. ``It can be a challenging environment, shall
we say, but that's good for a marketeer.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Heineken's headquarters intend to strongly
``encourage local markets to use'' the Lowe Lintas New York ads,
Thompson said, or they can continue running campaigns from local
agencies _ but only ``if the creative is better.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This should be seen as a challenge to the local agencies,'' he
added. ``Any work they're creating, we'll benchmark against the
global pool.''
</P>
<P>
   Agencies working for Heineken locally include offices of Bates
Worldwide; J. Walter Thompson, part of the WPP Group; and Lowe
Howard-Spink in London, which like Lowe Lintas New York is part of
the Lowe Group unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Singapore office of Bates, part of the Cordiant
Communications Group, is being named to handle additional creative
responsibilities for the Heineken brand in Asia. The brand has a
somewhat different image in that part of the world, Thompson said,
where it is typically sold at higher prices than in Europe and
North America.
</P>
<P>
   The United States campaign for Heineken, carrying the theme
``It's all about the beer,'' presents light-hearted vignettes known
as ``beer moments'' in the lives of drinkers, particularly men ages
21 to 24. The ads are different from many in the beer category,
which is replete with pitches featuring broad humor and scantily
clad ``babes.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in one television commercial, a seemingly nice guy
is revealed to be a ``weasel'': he brings Brand X beer to a party
but drinks someone else's Heineken. In another spot, titled ``The
mood swing,'' a sports fan's elation turns to gloom when a
gesturing friend knocks over his cup of Heineken.
</P>
<P>
   In a third commercial, ``The premature pour,'' an eager swain
demonstrates poor technique in failing to properly transfer the
contents of a bottle of Heineken to his glass. Another spot, ``The
male bonding incident,'' depicts an awkward moment between two
buddies when one hands the other a Heineken and their fingers
accidentally touch. Those two spots were shown last week at the
Interpublic annual meeting as part of a reel of commercials deemed
to be particularly creative.
</P>
<P>
   In the American market, ``people were saying `Heineken's a great
beer,' but they weren't saying `Heineken's a great beer for me,'''
Thompson said. ``We wanted Heineken to be more relevant, to be seen
as a beer that makes any occasion special rather than a beer for
special occasions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lowe Lintas New York campaign, he added, ``has really made a
significant difference in the last year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, we're selling more beer than we used to,
and the brand equity measures are moving in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Corona now outsells Heineken among Americans drinking
imported beers, Heineken is growing about 8 percent annually, far
exceeding the growth rate for the total United States beer market.
</P>
<P>
   Lowe Lintas New York is completing almost a dozen TV commercials
for worldwide use that carry the theme ``It has to be Heineken.''
The approach is simiar to the United States ads as Heineken
executives look ``for the cultural similarities,'' Thompson said,
``instead of the cultural differences.''
</P>
<P>
   The new spots, still in production, include ``The torment,'' in
which a sports fan waiting in line for a Heineken is unnerved as
the crowd roars in response to plays he cannot see; ``The pain
barrier,'' in which drinkers fish inside a tub filled with icy
water to retrieve bottles of Heineken; and ``The stalemate,'' a
series of commercials about two men fighting for the last bottle of
Heineken in a refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   ``This first presented itself to us around three or four months
ago,'' said Michael Silver, a managing director at Lowe Lintas who
is also executive vice president and worldwide account director on
Heineken, ``when a dialogue started about focusing on `beer
moments' for a global audience rather than just a U.S. audience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendous win for the agency,'' he added, ``and a
huge opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the assignment is fortunate because it comes only
months after the merger that created Lowe Lintas, in which
Interpublic combined the Lowe &AMP; Partners unit of Lowe with Ammirati
Puris Lintas. There are perceptions along Madison Avenue that the
merger is taking a long time to jell, and the defections of some
employees and clients are feeding those perceptions. ``I think
we've come a long way as an agency in a short time,'' said Lee
Garfinkel, chairman and chief creative for the United States
operations of Lowe Lintas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still expect we'll have some bumps along the way,'' he
added, ``but it's a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Heineken spends about $40 million annually on American
advertising. The spending for the new worldwide ads depends on how
many local markets decide to run them. Since Heineken is sold in
174 countries, widespread acceptance could bring a beer moment or
two for Lowe Lintas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
