<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4990 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FEC-CONFIRM-NYT     05-24 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEC-CONFIRM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE COMPROMISE LEADS TO CONFIRMATION OF NOMINEES 
</HEADLINE>
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate voted on Wednesday to confirm the
nomination of Bradley A. Smith to the Federal Election Commission,
although Smith, the Republican nominee for the agency, has angered
Democrats by advocating a repeal of campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was confirmed by a vote of 64 to 35, after Republican and
Democratic leaders, who squabbled for months over this nomination
and others, brokered an agreement earlier this week. Democrats had
objected to Smith's nomination, and Republicans had opposed several
of President Clinton's nominees to the federal bench. Both sides
compromised and a swap ensued.
</P>
<P>
   With the logjam broken, the Senate also moved to re-confirm
Danny Lee McDonald, who already sits on the Federal Election
Commission, and to confirm 46 other nominees for federal posts.
Although 16 judges were approved, another 36 nominations are
awaiting action in the Senate Judiciary Committee, a source of
frustration for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Smith's nomination that stirred the most acrimony,
with the majority of Democrats and a few Republicans objecting to
the selection. Campaign finance watchdog groups lobbied heavily
against Smith. In fact, the nomination was so bitterly contested,
it drew a Senate roll-call vote, which is unusual for election
commission nominees.
</P>
<P>
   Smith ``believes that all campaign contributions, spending and
influence peddling are protected without limitation,'' said Sen.
Russell D. Feingold, D-Wisc., who was one of the sponsors of
legislation to overhaul the campaign finance system. ``He has
advocated time and again the repeal of the very law he would be
sworn to uphold and enforce. How can we seriously consider
confirming his nomination to serve as a commission?''
</P>
<P>
   The commission is made up of six members, three Democrats and
three Republicans, a delicate and deliberate balance that is
intended to avoid giving any one party an advantage. That was the
reason Democrats gave for voting for Smith.
</P>
<P>
   While the president nominates a candidate, Congress must approve
the nominee. In this instance, Clinton agreed to nominate Smith in
exchange for a vote on Richard C. Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador to
the United Nations, whose confirmation had been stalled by
Republican senators, according to a Senate Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a law professor at Capital University in Ohio, has
written extensively on campaign finance, and concludes that the way
to mend the nation's campaign finance system is to get rid of the
Federal Elections Campaign Act, which restricts the flow of money
in political races while complying with constitutional free-speech
protections.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has argued that campaign finance laws approved by Congress
after Watergate have failed; in fact, more money is required to run
for office today, incumbents are more entrenched than ever and
voter participation is at a low point.
</P>
<P>
   On this, both Smith and his detractors agree. But they disagree
over the remedy.
</P>
<P>
   Smith says the $1,000 limit on campaign donations should be
eliminated, arguing that challengers must be free to raise more
money than incumbents to defeat them.
</P>
<P>
   He has also argued that money does not necessarily influence
lawmakers. Instead, he says, it is the lawmakers' constituency,
ideology and party affiliation that decide their votes.
</P>
<P>
   Most Republicans defended Smith today, calling his positions
``well-grounded in mainstream First Amendment doctrines and case
law,'' as Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., put it.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., who wrote the campaign bill with
Feingold, vehemently opposed the selection. ``Sending Brad Smith to
the FEC is akin to confirming a conscientious objector to be
secretary of defense,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   And he chastised Clinton for going along with the nomination.
``The president still had the ability and the authority to reject
this most extreme nominee for any position that I have seen in my
years here since 1987,'' McCain said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
