<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5002 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-EBAY-EXECUTION-TEX     05-24 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-EXECUTION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH ROW INMATE OFFERS TO SELL SEATS TO WITNESS EXECUTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GABRIELLE CRIST 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A Death Row inmate who killed three people
tried to sell five seats for his execution on an Internet auction
site Wednesday _ for several hours, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The auction on eBay, with bidding designated to start at $100,
closed several hours after it began about 1:20 p.m. EBay officials
had removed the site by early evening.
</P>
<P>
   No one bid on the seats during the four hours after the auction
was posted.
</P>
<P>
   ``My name is Michael Toney. Most people call me `Cowboy.' I am
on Texas' Death Row awaiting execution for a crime I did not
commit,'' the Web site stated.
</P>
<P>
   Condemned inmates in Texas are allowed to have five witnesses at
their execution. Toney decided that his seats would go to the top
eBay bidders, with the money going to his estranged children.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were not eligible to bid, the Web site stated.
</P>
<P>
   Toney, 34, was sentenced to death last year for the 1985
briefcase bombing that killed Angela Blount, 15; her father, Joe
Blount, 44; and her cousin, Michael Columbus, 18, in the Fort Worth
suburb of Lake Worth. His conviction is on appeal, so his execution
date has not been set.
</P>
<P>
   The case was unsolved for more than a decade. Then Toney, who
was in jail for another offense, bragged to another inmate about
the bombing. Investigators believe that Toney intended the bomb for
someone else but put it outside the wrong mobile home, according to
court testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Money from the eBay auction would have been used to establish a
trust for Toney's two estranged daughters, whom he said he has
``neglected for some 13 years.'' Once the trust was set up, Toney
said on the Web site, he would have waived further appeals on his
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not know what kind of people would donate money to watch
an innocent man be murdered. However, I do know there are people
out there that will,'' his Web site statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The person who helped Toney set up the Web site is an ``idiot,''
said Glen Castleberry, a spokesman for the Texas Department of
Criminal Justice. Bidders will not attend the execution,
Castleberry said, ``period, end of story.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said he could not say whether selling the seats
would have violated any written procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the woman who set up the Web site said, ``I
pretty much just did it because he asked me to.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who asked that her name not be used, testified
against Toney at his trial but has since rekindled a friendship.
</P>
<P>
   Toney told her that it would help his efforts to prove his
innocence, she said. Until the eBay auction attempt, those efforts
had been limited to an aggressive letter-writing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of several supporters outside prison, Toney has
written at least 100 letters to people including the foreman of the
jury that sentenced him to death and the victims' families.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web site, Toney again proclaimed his innocence and asked
skeptics to contact him or visit him in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Toney said two kinds of people would be likely to bid for an
execution seat: compassionate people who wants to help his
children, and sadists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, sadists are not in short supply in the cold,
cruel world of which we temporarily reside. I will thank the
compassionate and I will forgive the sadists,'' the Web site
stated.
</P>
<P>
   According to the eBay user agreement, the description of the
item being sold must pertain only to that item, said Kevin
Pursglove, director of communications for the Internet auction
company, based in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Toney's description filled more than two computer screens and
``was more of a diatribe,'' Pursglove said. Besides, Pursglove
said, he wasn't convinced that Toney had the right to sell the
seats.
</P>
<P>
   Toney's attorney, Robert Ford, said he will continue with his
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said that he didn't know about the Web site but that if he
had, he would have called eBay himself to try to get it removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Mr. Toney's actions and comments are totally
inappropriate,'' Ford said. ``Mr. Toney would serve his own case
much better if he he didn't behave in this manner.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
