<HEADER>
A5004 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BLUE-CROSS-NYT     05-24 0523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BLUE-CROSS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN TO CHANGE BLUE CROSSES CLEARS HURDLE
</HEADLINE>
 By MILT FREUDENHEIM with WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York Attorney General Eliot Spitzer withdrew his
opposition on Wednesday to plans by the big nonprofit health
insurer, Empire Blue Cross and Blue Shield, to change into a
for-profit company.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the shift, Empire would set up a multimillion-dollar
foundation dedicated to making health care broadly accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Empire had offered to give the New York Legislature the right to
approve or disapprove the conversion and a voice in deciding its
future, and to give the public a role in governing the company and
the foundation. But hospital and union officials said they would
seek to defeat the conversion plan in the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The State Insurance Department approved Empire's proposal last
year, but Spitzer delayed it, arguing that the public needed a
larger voice in the new entities. He said that after lengthy
negotiations, Empire had agreed to let the new foundation select
six of the new for-profit company's 15-member board.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates said the foundation would be valued at more
than $500 million, based on Empire's current reserves. The
foundation would not directly provide insurance, but it would try
to influence the insurance market by creating models for expanded
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 49 Blue Cross associations are still nonprofit
companies. Other Blue Cross plans in at least nine states have
converted to for-profit status. Those plans created foundations to
repay part of the tax breaks and subsidies they had received over
the years.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups and state officials pressed for the foundations
and brought lawsuits in some states. A spokeswoman for Empire said
the company structured its proposal to avert such suits.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Stocker, president of Empire, has said that it needs
the ability private companies have to sell stock and raise money
for computerized information systems so it can compete with
for-profit health insurers like Aetna Inc. and Oxford Health Plans.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Raske, president of the Greater New York Hospital
Association, and Dennis Rivera, president of 1199, the hospital
workers' union, said they would oppose the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Raske said that creating ``another investor-owned payer will
work against the interests of doctors, hospitals and consumers.''
He said the company's executives ``would be more concerned with the
price of their stock than their ability to deliver services.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera said the charitable foundation would not be sufficient
compensation for allowing the company to abandon its role as the
traditional insurer of people who could not get coverage elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Empire has promised that there would be no change in the
coverage it now provides for 4.1 million customers or in its rates,
if the conversion happens. And the company no longer has a special
duty to cover people with difficult problems, under changes in laws
and subsidies over the last few years. Now all health maintenance
organizations are required to accept all applicants at the same
rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5005 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-PACERS-HNS &LR;      05-24 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ For the Indiana Pacers, there's no time like the
present. Mostly because the Pacers seem to think they're running
out of time.
<TEXT>
<P>
   With six of their core players about to become free agents, and
with coach Larry Bird stepping down after this season, the Pacers
are getting a bit antsy about making the leap to the next level _
the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   They took the first step in that journey Tuesday night, beating
the New York Knicks in the first game of the Eastern Conference
finals, and hope to be up 2-0 in the best-of-seven series after
tonight's Game 2 at Conseco Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Of Indiana's six free agents-to-be, four are starters _ Reggie
Miller, Jalen Rose, Rik Smits and Mark Jackson. Center Sam Perkins
and Austin Croshere, who provided a glimpse of what could be by
dropping a team-high 22 points on the Knicks in Game 1, are the
other key free agents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are conscious of the scenario,'' said Rose, who Wednesday
was named the NBA's Most Improved Player. ``But we are also
conscious this is our third year and we haven't won the NBA title.
It is a priority (to win). But it is also our third year trying to
get through. That makes it a priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand a lot of teams would be content to have the
success we've had the last few years. But we're looking for
something bigger and something better. We think we have what it
takes to get over the hump. We also understand anything can
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   And against the Knicks, anything is the appropriate word.
</P>
<P>
   The fact the Pacers are playing the Knicks in the postseason for
the third straight year _ and in the conference finals for the
third time in seven years _ offers Indiana incentive enough. But
there's much, much more here.
</P>
<P>
   All the Pacers have to do is look back on Game 3 of last year's
conference finals. They appeared to have the Knicks on the ropes at
Madison Square Garden, but Larry Johnson's now-infamous four-point
play _ on which he drew a bump from the Pacers' Antonio Davis, took
an extra dribble, knocked down the 3-pointer and got the
questionable continuation call from the referees _ turned things
around in the game's final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Things like that make Miller thankful the Pacers are playing the
Knicks in this year's conference finals. Revenge, especially
against a hated opponent, is a powerful motivational tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never let your guard down against New York,'' said
Miller, who scored 19 points in Game 1. ``They've got too many
talented offensive players. They have the type of team that can
embarrass you if you let your guard down.
</P>
<P>
   ``And because of the rivalry I'm the only one who wants to say
this, but both teams don't like each other. Everybody else is
saying that, `Oh, we respect them.' No, they don't like us, and we
don't like them. Because of that, you shouldn't let your guard
down. And I don't think we will.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers have played in the Eastern Conference finals in five
of the last seven years, but they have not been able to get over
the proverbial hump, losing to New York (in 1994), Orlando in
('95), Chicago ('98) and the Knicks again last season.
</P>
<P>
   That close-but-no-cigar trend is wearing on some players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been a very good team, we've scored a lot of points,
we've been exciting, but for some reason people still want to put
us down and say we're going to be the Buffalo Bills (who lost four
consecutive Super Bowls),'' said Pacers point guard Travis Best.
``We've taken it with a grain of salt and moved on and played good
basketball. From this point on, we don't worry about what people
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird isn't accepting any excuses this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really felt we had a good enough team to get to the Finals
the last two years,'' he said. ``Obviously, Chicago got in our way
in the seventh game (winning 88-83 in '98), and then last year
against New York they (the Knicks) made the plays when they had to
make them.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this year is my final chance to get back to the Finals,
and it's the first chance for a lot of the guys in the locker room
to get there, so I think it's very important for us to get over the
hump and try to give ourselves a chance to play for the world
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't win a championship, it's a failed year,'' Bird
added. ``You didn't get what you set out to accomplish. My goal
here was to try to get the Pacers to the Finals. It's time.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
