<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARITABLE-GIVING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARITABLE GIVING SURGED AGAIN IN '99, BY AN ESTIMATED 9 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charitable giving grew faster than the economy last year,
although it did not quite keep pace with the tremendous
accumulation in wealth, according to figures released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The ebullient stock market and the prosperous economy helped
drive donations to charity up nearly $16 billion, to $190.2
billion, 9.1 percent higher than in 1998 and well ahead of the 5.7
percent growth in gross domestic product, according to the figures,
estimates presented by the AAFRC Trust for Philanthropy, the
nonprofit arm of the American Association of Fund-Raising Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   After inflation, donations increased 6.7 percent, making 1999
the fifth year in a row that they rose in ``real'' dollars.
</P>
<P>
   And, said the philanthropy trust, which uses an economic model
to estimate annual charitable contributions, donations equaled 2.1
percent of gross domestic product, the highest level by that
barometer in 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   Fund-raising executives and others called the growth
substantial. President Clinton's domestic policy adviser, Bruce
Reed, who spoke at a Manhattan news conference where the trust
issued its figures, referred to ``a new golden age of philanthropy
in America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The new figures are remarkable,'' Reed said, adding that
giving in the last seven years now totaled $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1995, charitable giving has risen 53 percent, or 40
percent after inflation. The fund-raising association's chairman,
George C. Ruotolo Jr., called the rise of recent years
``meteoric.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite last year's gains _ and huge contributions from some
Internet billionaires like Bill Gates of Microsoft _ the growth in
giving appears not to have kept up with the growth in wealth. Using
the figures released Wednesday, Edward N. Wolff, an economics
professor at New York University, calculated that giving amounted
to 0.69 percent of the nation's wealth last year _ down from 0.71
percent in 1998, although slightly ahead of the 0.68 percent of
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, philanthropy has pretty much paralleled
wealth,'' Wolff said.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Feenberg, a research associate at the National Bureau of
Economic Research and member of the fund-raising association's
advisory council on methodology, suggests that another yardstick to
measure charitable giving is its relation to personal consumption.
He too used the figures released Wednesday, and calculated that
donations last year equaled 3 percent of personal consumption
expenditures, up slightly from 1998 and a significant jump from the
2.5 percent in 1995 but still below the 3.3 percent of the late
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been steady growth over the past five years, but we
are still not back to the historic peak,'' Feenberg said, although
he cautioned that the association figures on which he was basing
his calculations were only estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Giving by foundations last year rose at more than twice the rate
of individual giving, spurred by a law that requires them to give
away at least 5 percent of their assets each year. (They are
allowed to average their assets over several years to even out
their spending.)
</P>
<P>
   The bullish equity markets, which gave most foundations large
gains in their endowments, forced them to increase their giving
sharply. Grants by noncorporate foundations jumped 16.5 percent, to
$19.8 billion from $17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Foundation Center, a New York group that gathers data on
foundations, reported that the number of them had also been surging
in recent years. By the end of 1998, there were 46,832 foundations,
up from 23,770 in 1982. (The center does not yet have figures for
1999.)
</P>
<P>
   In contrast with the extraordinarily robust growth of foundation
giving, personal giving _ which accounts for about three-quarters
of all donations _ was up 7 percent last year, to $143.7 billion
from $134.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The AAFRC Trust said philanthropic giving by individuals
amounted to 1.8 percent of personal income last year, the same as
in 1998 but up from 1.5 percent in 1995. The last time personal
giving was above the 1.8 percent level was 1973, when it reached
1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   After personal giving and donations by noncorporate foundations,
the two remaining categories of charitable contributions are
bequests and corporate giving, both of which had a good year.
Bequests rose $2.8 billion, to $15.6 billion, while corporate
giving climbed $1.4 billion, to $11 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Religious charities remained by far the largest recipients of
charitable giving by Americans, receiving nearly $82 billion, a
rise of 5.5 percent from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Education organizations, including universities, were the
second-largest recipient, with $27.5 billion, an 8.5 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The sharpest gain in percentage terms was to organizations
focused on international affairs, like Doctors Without Borders and
the U.N. Foundation, although the total still remained relatively
small. Donations to these groups rose 24 percent, to $2.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Environment and wildlife organizations also enjoyed a strong
increase, 11 percent, to $5.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The charitable giving data released Wednesday is available on
the fund-raising association's Web site (www.aafrc.org). A more
detailed picture of charitable giving in 1999 will be contained in
the association's book ``Giving U.S.A. 2000,'' which will be
available on disk in June and in book form in September.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
