u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-ADJUSTMENT     05-24 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-ADJUSTMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO BASKETBALL: FOES PLAYING MIND GAMES WITH KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ One moment the New York Knicks were locked in
mortal combat with Miami, often pulled out of bounds by their
shorts. The next, they were dazed by Indiana's bombs, retreating
for cover against another fierce playoff rival.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Camby and his teammates tried Wednesday to clear the
cobwebs. Seventy-two dizzying hours will make you do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like you have to shift gears,'' Camby said. ``You
go from a banging, physical series for seven games to a team with
new plays, new personnel, a team that can shoot the ball from the
3-point line much better than Miami.
</P>
<P>
   The lithe forward scratched his head as he sat on a wooden
bleacher at Conseco Fieldhouse. Thursday night the Knicks will
attempt to knot the best-of-7 Eastern Conference finals against the
Pacers at one victory apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have re-work your mind,'' Camby said.
</P>
<P>
   It is premature to take apart the Knicks for their wire-to-wire
102-88 loss in Game 1. Fatigue, travel and little time to prepare
for the Pacers give them legitimate excuses. Yet, as Game 2
approaches, the larger issue is whether they understand who they
are playing.
</P>
<P>
   For all the physical pain players such as Alonzo Mourning, Dan
Majerle and P.J. Brown administered, the respect between the Knicks
and the Heat deepened with each game of their riveting semifinal
series. Maybe not to a point in which you would refer to it as a
gentlemen's competition, but at least they appreciated the effort
put forth by the other side. Knicks coach Jeff Van Gundy said:
``You can't help but have empathy for who lost that series. It was
that close.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers' Reggie Miller has not been to the NBA finals. He
could care less how the Knicks felt about anything, much less
losing the series to his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indiana, the pain of losing to us last year, fueled a great
determined effort on their part,'' Van Gundy said. ``Even though we
talked about it many times, our players underestimated what it was
going to take to compete with this team. This team, I hate this
cliche _ mission _ but they have an unbelievable passion to get
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks and Heat banged bodies and made it impossible for
either side to crack 90 points. But the rules of their duel were
also understood: You walked 10 paces before you turned and fired.
In this series, you are lucky if you get nine steps before Miller
has already taken a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Player-wise, it's more personal,'' Camby said. ``Last series
was more about Riley, he used to coach the Knicks and all the
hoopla. But now it's about Reggie, his comments he made before Game
1, saying we're arrogant, we don't respect them and stuff like
that. It's a mental adjustment, no doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to overanalyze a 14-point loss, and wonder if you are
not reaching for something that is not as relevant to a contentious
playoff series as you originally thought. But even if you discount
how the Knicks need to mentally approach the Pacers, you can't
discount what they did to New York on the court Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers make a higher percentage of free throws and
3-pointers than anyone in the league. They are the fourth-best
scoring team in pro basketball. They can run or slow it down, go
inside with Rik Smits or outside with Miller. They beat teams with
their passing much easier than with their one-on-one isolations.
</P>
<P>
   Jalen Rose may be one of only a few Pacers who can create his
own shot. But the sum of their parts _ Miller, Mark Jackson, Smits,
Dale Davis and a deep bench _ make them the most genuine team still
left in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   They need to rely on each other more than Portland, the Lakers
or even the Knicks to win. And they do, rather efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a unique team,'' Van Gundy said. ``Most teams in this
league are probably more athletic than they are but there are no
more skilled teams than Indiana. This is a great offensive team.
They pass well, they shoot well, they know how to move the ball.
They can shoot at any range.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Patrick Ewing: ``This team definitely has more firepower
than Miami. Miami is a better defensive team than they are.''
</P>
<P>
   During the preseason, the Knicks met San Antonio in one of those
NBA money-making excursions in which you find out more about your
team before the season begins. Yet with the memory of their finals
loss fresh, the Knicks came out and treated the game as if it meant
something.
</P>
<P>
   ``We treated it like a seventh game all because of the pain of
losing in the finals,'' Van Gundy said. ``And they were, like,
chilling out, because it was an exhibition game.''
</P>
<P>
   He shook his head. ``Our guys just don't understand it. I think
it's not as much as adjusting to a new offense as it is a mental
adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Camby said, re-work the mind. Before Reggie turns and
fires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2248EDT &QL; 
