<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5012 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DEVILS-FLYERS-NYT     05-24 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS FORCE GAME 7 WITH 2 THIRD-PERIOD GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
  By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The crucial hockey game was scoreless
until 8 minutes 34 seconds were left. That is when Claude Lemieux,
the biggest money player in Devils history, took center stage as
his team faced elimination from the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   As he did so many times in leading the Devils to their Stanley
Cup triumph in 1995, when he was named the tournament's most
valuable player, Lemieux scored an important goal Wednesday night
as the Devils defeated the Flyers, 2-1, to force a deciding seventh
game in the Eastern Conference finals. The teams will play Friday
night in Philadelphia, where the Devils have won twice in this
series.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's intense battle featured the return of Eric
Lindros, who scored the Flyers' goal with 30 seconds to play after
missing a score by a fraction of a second earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux's goal, a backhander from the left side in the crease
after a shot by Bobby Holik, broke the scoreless tie. But Alexander
Mogilny's backhander with 2:27 left sailed over the glove of Flyers
goaltender Brian Boucher and proved to be the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros, who had not played since March 13 because of
concussions, scored from a crowd in front of goaltender Martin
Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils spent most of the first two periods in Philadelphia's
zone. They were particularly dominant in the second period, when
they limited the Flyers to only two shots. The Devils created
several chances but failed to capitalize, even on two manpower
advantages in the session.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the second period ended, Lindros put the puck in the net
from the slot in a crowd in front of Brodeur, who had 12 saves in
the game, but the officials ruled that it came just a split second
after the clock ran out. The Flyers protested, but the officials
had the video replay to prove they made the correct call.
</P>
<P>
   Several signs by Philadelphia fans, who have been rather vocal
every time the Flyers played here in this series, welcomed Lindros,
who played on the third line with Valery Zelepukin and Daymond
Langkow.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Craig Ramsay of the Flyers said before the game that
Lindros would have a more limited role than in the past, and the
coach proved it by giving Lindros 8 minutes 41 seconds of ice time
in the first 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Larry Robinson of the Devils used Steve Kelly, John Madden
and Randy McKay against Lindros for the most part. Lindros' first
big play in the game, however, came on a crunching check against
Lemieux in front of the Devils' bench around the 12th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Madden, who made his return after missing three games because of
a bruised right knee, had the first quality chance in the game, two
minutes after the opening face-off, but his shot from the slot
sailed wide. He showed his anger a few seconds later during a
stoppage by banging his stick on his right leg.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Malakhov also had a good chance with all the net to
shoot at in the 10th minute, but the Russian defenseman, who did so
well to pinch in at the right time, fanned on a centering pass by
Holik from the right side.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers got a bit of a scare with 2:02 left in the first
period when a shot by Scott Gomez hit Boucher in the mask and
apparently stunned him. He went down quickly, threw his glove away
and grabbed his mask in pain.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher (24 saves) went through several hectic moments in the
first two periods, but he held his ground, even when the Devils
attacked the net with authority.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Boucher's biggest save among the 15 he made in the first
40 minutes came in the 13th minute of the second period, when Holik
broke away alone after intercepting a pass at his blue line. Holik
tried to deke Boucher with a move from left to right, but the
rookie goaltender denied him by sprawling at his left doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher came out with another brilliant save against Holik 62
seconds into the third period, when he flipped backward, a la
Dominik Hasek, to knock away the shot and prevent Lemieux from
scoring on the rebound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
