<SLUG> BC-SPACE-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA PLEASED SO FAR WITH SHUTTLE MISSION TO SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Atlantis astronauts sailed past the half-way point
of their repair mission to the international space station on
Wednesday, wrapping up an overhaul of the faltering electrical
power system.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmonaut Yuri Usachev and astronaut Susan Helms finished the
chore as they replaced a fourth power storage battery in the
Russian segment of the two-room orbital outpost, a task they
initiated Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling station has towered nearly 80 feet above an
airlock in the shuttle's cargo bay since the Atlantis crew docked
late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The overhaul bolsters the station's power system, preparing the
orbital outpost for the arrival of the third major component in
June, the overdue Russian crew module.
</P>
<P>
   Its arrival stalled more than two years by Russian economic
problems, the crew module will equip the station for its first
resident astronauts and cosmonauts in November.
</P>
<P>
   NASA was pleased with Wednesday's milestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to get too giddy yet since we have a couple of days
to go,'' said Paul Hill of NASA, the station's lead flight
director. ``But if the rest of the mission goes as well as it
already has, we will have 100 percent success.''
</P>
<P>
   Coupled in Earth orbit in December 1998, the station's first two
segments began to experience battery losses late last year,
apparently as a result of overly aggressive charging and
discharging procedures initiated by the Russian mission control
facility.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Atlantis astronauts reached the outpost, four of
the station's six batteries as well as an assortment of
charge/discharge assemblies and voltage regulators required
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   At least three of the six batteries must function to ensure the
station's power system is robust enough for the addition of the
Russian crew module in July.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians paid the $1.3 million expense of the new battery
hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, the Atlantis crew raised the altitude of the
35-ton space station for a second time with the shuttle's steering
jets.
</P>
<P>
   The station has been sinking between one and two miles a week in
response to a rise in solar activity. The increase in solar energy
reaching the Earth causes the atmosphere to balloon away from the
planet's surface, creating new frictional drag for orbiting
satellites.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle astronauts executed a 10-mile boost Wednesday night,
the same as Tuesday's maneuvers. The second boost placed the two
spacecraft in a 224-mile high orbit.
</P>
<P>
   A final boost tonight Thursday night should place the station at
232 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Atlantis commander Jim Halsell offered assurances in
a series of brief news interviews that the air quality of the
station is healthy and the noise levels tolerable.
</P>
<P>
   The crew of a shuttle supply mission that visited the station in
June experienced headaches, itchy eyes and in one instance nausea,
later attributed to air flow problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had no operational impacts at all as a result of poor
air quality,'' Halsell told the Cable News Network. ``The air
quality has been just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   He attributed the absence of problems to enhancements in the
ventilation system made by the Atlantis astronauts as they boarded
the station Monday night. The 80-degree temperatures that greeted
the visiting astronauts have also cooled to the mid-70s, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of an audible mechanical hum in some regions of the
station, the noise levels in the outpost are lower than the
noisiest parts of the space shuttle, Halsell said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their repair efforts, the astronauts had
transferred more than a ton of supplies to the station for future
residents. Nearly a ton of discarded gear had been transferred from
the station to the shuttle.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis is scheduled to undock from the station Friday night.
The 10-day mission is schedule to end with a landing at the Kennedy
Space Center in Florida on Monday at 1:18 a.m. CDT.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
