<SLUG> BC-E-TAXES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAXPAYERS TAKING BYTE OUT OF FILING RETURNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS SIEROTY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ California taxpayers used technology in record
numbers this year to participate in e-file and direct deposit
refund programs, according to figures released Wednesday by the
Franchise Tax Board.
</P>
<P>
   The state's tax collector said the e-file program, now in its
fifth year, surpassed the 2 million mark for the first time with
2.2 million e-file returns as of May 5, up from 1.5 million for the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
   While a majority of electronic-filed returns are usually
submitted by tax professionals, this year the number of taxpayers
who filed online more than doubled to 446,959, from 207,674 last
year, the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the numbers show is that more and more people are
becoming comfortable with e-filing,'' said Carolina Beach, a
spokeswoman with the FTB in Sacramento
</P>
<P>
   By e-filing tax returns, she said forms have fewer mistakes and
taxpayers usually receive their refunds within seven to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are hoping that those taxpayers who are filing late this
year after being granted an extension would take advantage of
e-filing,'' Beach said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they owe taxes they can pay them electronically. Of
course by now they would be subject to a penalty, but this is
another option,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million Californians filed for an extension this
year and have until October to send their tax returns, she said.
</P>
<P>
   While e-filing has become more convenient and popular with
taxpayers, state officials say more than 1 million taxpayers chose
to have their refunds directly deposited into their bank accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Through May 5, 1.1 million direct deposit refunds totaling more
than $585 million were issued.
</P>
<P>
   Direct deposit was offered to all taxpayers, including paper
filers, for the first time this year. Beach said in previous years
it was available to taxpayers who used e-file or Telefile.
</P>
<P>
   ``With more taxpayers finding it easier to use, we expect both
programs to continue their phenomenal growth next year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on e-filing or direct deposit, Beach said
consumers can surf the FTB's Web site at www.ftb.ca.gov.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
