<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT ANTITRUST TRIAL SPEEDS UP, HEATS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal judge cut short the Microsoft antitrust
trial Wednesday, denying the company further hearings on a dramatic
breakup proposal and indicating _ at least in the eyes of Microsoft
general counsel Bill Neukom _ that he will order the company broken
in half.
</P>
<P>
   Neukom said if the judge does order a breakup, the company will
immediately launch an appeal, asking that the order be postponed
pending the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``On appeal, we will raise issues of procedure,'' including
due-process constitutional violations the judge may have committed
by denying the hearings request, Neukom said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's proceedings were intended to schedule hearings to
determine how best to repair and prevent Microsoft's antitrust
wrongdoing. The Redmond giant sought up to six months to prepare a
defense against a breakup proposal put forward by the Justice
Department and 17 of the 19 plaintiff states.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs urged immediate resolution. But even their
supporters, some of whom urged harsher breakups than the plaintiffs
themselves, endorsed the need for some hearings. It was widely
expected that U.S. District Court Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson
would grant Microsoft at least two months to prepare for a
mini-trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Jackson shocked Microsoft lawyers Wednesday by capping three
hours of detailed hearings with the abrupt declaration, ``I'm not
contemplating any further process.'' When company lawyers again
asked for more time, he snapped, ``This case has been pending for
two years now.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jackson asked the plaintiffs to ``present me with a
clean copy'' of their breakup plan by Thursday. Despite an angry
protest by Microsoft attorney Steven Holley, he gave Microsoft just
48 hours _ until next Wednesday, because Monday is a court holiday
_ to comment on the new filing.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Jim Cullinan said both documents will likely
be filed without any sort of hearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You heard the judge. The process is over,'' he said. The
company had hoped to call a series of new witnesses, including
chairman Bill Gates and chief executive Steve Ballmer, as well as
Wall Street investment bankers and academicians.
</P>
<P>
   The next step will be for Jackson to write an order, explaining
what remedy he prefers for Microsoft and his legal rationale for
choosing it. His discretion in fashioning a remedy is wide, but his
rationale must be clear, said Bob Lande, an antitrust expert at the
University of Baltimore law school.
</P>
<P>
   Writing the order is a demanding task that will take Jackson at
least a month, he estimated. The entry of that order concludes the
trial and is the final step before an appeal can be taken.
</P>
<P>
   Lande agreed with Neukom that Jackson's denial of any hearings
to Microsoft may be an appealable error.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's denial of more time for Microsoft was plain enough,
but what he meant by asking the plaintiffs for ``a clean copy'' of
their proposal wasn't immediately clear.
</P>
<P>
   At least one news report concluded he meant the revised proposal
should include discussions of splitting Microsoft not just into two
companies, as the plaintiffs have suggested, but into three or even
four companies, as Microsoft competitors and some economists have
advocated. The governments' plan proposes breaking Microsoft into
one operating-systems company and one applications company.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every question Jackson asked Wednesday suggested he's
entertaining thoughts of a breakup and is working out even the
smallest details in his head. And some questions did suggest he
might be receptive to a three- or four-way split. But a source
close to the Justice Department said the clean-up will consist only
of ``tweaking and fine-tuning'' and denied the new version of the
proposal will go beyond the original.
</P>
<P>
   The ``tweaks'' might include changing key definitions in the
proposal and adjusting the limits on how much Microsoft stock an
investor can own before being forbidden from investing in the other
company. Jackson raised questions about both those points during
the arguments.
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, while the plaintiffs' attorneys congratulated
each other on the courthouse steps, Microsoft attorneys and legal
experts disagreed on what Jackson had said he will do.
</P>
<P>
   Chief litigator John Warden said, ``I did not hear the court
say'' it will order the plaintiffs' proposal to be implemented.
University of Baltimore's Lande agreed, but he said, ``Based on the
tone of the hearing, I'd say there's better than a 50-percent
chance he'll order a breakup.'' Neukom said twice he thinks Jackson
will sign the plaintiffs' breakup order.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, anyone observing the proceedings Wednesday could
have seen Jackson was headed toward summarily splitting the company
up. But judges, Lande noted, have a way of disguising their real
intentions, playing devil's advocate, and asking whatever questions
come into their heads. So even at lunch break, knowledgeable
onlookers were unwilling to put money on how the hearing would end.
</P>
<P>
   Referring early-on to the governments' plan to cut Microsoft in
half, Jackson interrupted lead state trial counsel Kevin O'Connor
to demand, ``Tell me why they (those companies) would effectively
inspire competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson closely questioned special trial counsel David Boies on
the limits the two companies would have to observe on sharing
products and technology, and how they might evade them. He
expressed doubt Microsoft would be a willing participant in the
breakup, noting, ``You've given a lot of responsibility to
Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, when Boies discussed a Supreme Court case that had split
one company into three, Jackson interrupted to ask, ``Why aren't
you doing that?''
</P>
<P>
   Boies responded, ``It was one of the most difficult questions we
faced, and there were strong proponents of it. But our divestiture
plan meets the case before the court.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson heaped praise on a brief filed recently on the
plaintiffs' behalf by the Computer and Communications Industry
Association and the Software Information Industry Association, both
of which are made up of Microsoft competitors. That brief advocates
splitting Internet Explorer into its own company, for a total of
three Microsoft entities.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of Microsoft's requested hearings, Jackson queried
Microsoft attorney Jack Warden, ``Why can't I just enter judgment
on the declarations?'' referring to legal documents filed by
witnesses for the plaintiffs who say the breakup will work.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Jackson's comments and actions last night may bode,
investors did not seem disheartened. Microsoft shares rose $2.38 to
close at $65.56.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
