A5159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     05-24 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFROCKED CAPTAIN COMES BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Cold. The entire Eric Lindros saga is
cold. He probably should not even be playing, given his history of
concussions. The Philadelphia Flyers give the impression that he is
superfluous. And he may be playing for all the wrong reasons, like
retaining his value for next year.
</P>
<P>
   Wanted or unwanted, Lindros was the only Flyer to put the puck
in the net Wednesday night. Wearing his familiar No. 88, he scored
with 30.1 seconds left but the Flyers failed to eliminate the
Devils in the Eastern Finals of the Stanley Cup playoffs. The
Devils won, 2-1, on two third-period goals to avert the dreaded
handshake line ``in our building,'' as the players put it.
</P>
<P>
   The series final will be Friday night in Philadelphia, and the
joke of it is that the best player on the Flyers' roster, at 27,
one of the top players in history, seems essentially unwelcome.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that but earlier in the season the team had ripped the
captain's C from his jersey, a disgrace in hockey, which values the
captaincy more than any other sport does. Cold.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey depends on camaraderie, is just old-fashioned enough that
guys affectionately call each other by such unimaginative and
ubiquitous nicknames as ``Gordie'' and ``Clarkie'' and even the
plain old ``Marty'' for the Devils' Francophone goaltender, Martin
Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   Hockey players look to their best player for inspiration. The
Rangers used to know when Mark Messier had trouble flexing a knee,
but the man they called ``Mess'' folded his arms across his rugged
chest and gave his bland Mr. Kleen smile and pronounced that the
Rangers would win the next game. And more often than not, they did.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it should have been for Eric Lindros on Wednesday
night. There should have been an aura to his gallantry in coming
back from the latest concussion.
</P>
<P>
   He has gone through the parade of team doctors and concussion
specialists, sitting out the entire playoffs while his brain tried
to stabilize itself. This is serious business. There is
considerable reason to believe Lindros should retire, the way his
kid brother did after his concussions, but there he was Wednesday
night, taking up one of the 20 uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros has as much chance of returning to the Flyers as smooth
Roberto Baggio has of returning to Inter of Milan next season. On
Tuesday, after being inexplicably buried all season, Baggio
produced two goals that qualified Inter for the lucrative Champions
League next season. Stars can have an instant impact.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Lindros almost did. The big boy was actually
the first player to put the puck in the net, but the action came
clearly after the buzzer ending the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros looked somewhat slow, not showing the brute speed that
allowed him to outrace Mark Messier in an epic duel in the 1997
playoffs, but that was to be expected. He leveled the pesky Claude
Lemieux in the first period, and got involved in a skirmish in the
third, but the durable linesman, Kevin Collins, shooed him away
from even the possibility of a stray punch.
</P>
<P>
   For all the toughness, Lindros' self-involvement, the
machinations of his agent-father, and Lindros' criticism of the
team medical process had made him virtually persona non grata. His
return was a chilly contrast to that accorded other great players
who struggled with pain.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the reception for Willis Reed, hobbling out of the
runway to help the Knicks win the 1970 championship. Think of the
way the Yankees glanced at Mickey Mantle, playing with blood
seeping into his uniform from an infection on his backside, during
the 1961 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Bruins always hoped Bobby Orr's knee was stable
enough for him to go out on the ice. The old Islanders would glance
at wan Mike Bossy sneaking a cigarette in a corner of the room,
knowing he would find a way to ignore his bad back.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Lemieux won Stanley Cups and scoring titles and came back
from Hodgkin's Disease. And the current Flyers know that their
president, Bobby Clarke, earned all those gaps in his
jack-o'-lantern smile in the ancient Stanley Cup photos of the
Broad Street Bullies, but that he played as a diabetic.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Lindros does not lack for courage, nor does he lack in
skill, but in dynamics traditionally alien to hockey, he has a feud
with Clarke, and that sets him apart from his teammates. There has
rarely been such a public disdain of a star. Cold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
