<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HARRELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORRIS HARRELL, 80, AN INFLUENTIAL TEXAS LAWYER  
 BY ERIC V. COPAGE  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Morris Harrell, an influential Texas lawyer and former president
of the American Bar Association, died on Tuesday in Dallas, where
he lived. He was 80.
</P>
<P>
   Harrell was also a former president of the Dallas Bar
Association, the State Bar of Texas, the American College of Trial
Lawyers and the National Conference of Bar Presidents.
</P>
<P>
   A.P. Carlton, chairman of the American Bar Association's
Standing Committee on Judicial Independence, of which Harrell was a
member, said, ``Morris led the effort in trying to affect a change
in the way judges are selected in Texas, and to implement a merit
selection procedure, as opposed to partisan political selection.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris Harrell was born on April 16, 1920, in Grandview, Texas.
He received a bachelor's degree and law degree from Baylor
University in Waco, Texas. He was a Navy officer in World War II.
After the war, he joined his uncle's law office, where he remained,
with the exception of four years as a federal prosecutor, until
1955, when he joined Thompson, Knight, Wright &AMP; Simmons, then one
of the largest law firms in Dallas. In 1965, he was a co-founder of
the firm of Rain, Harrell, Emery, Young &AMP; Doke, which merged with
other firms over the years to become Locke Liddell &AMP; Sapp LLP, one
of the largest law firms in Texas. Harrell remained a practicing
trial lawyer there until the end of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Harrell was awarded the American Bar Association Medal,
which is given to people considered ``to have rendered
exceptionally distinguished service to the cause of American
jurisprudence.'' Previous recipients have included Oliver Wendell
Holmes, Thurgood Marshall, Felix Frankfurter and Sandra Day
O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   Harrell is survived by his wife of 56 years, the former Rhoda
Baylor, who is known as Rusty; a son, Jim, of Dallas; two
daughters, Julia Harrell Boone of Houston, and Rhoda Harrell
Reynolds of Dallas, and seven grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
