<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 23:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5163 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-CHINATRADE-IMPACT-LAD     05-24 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINATRADE-IMPACT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVIES, AGRICULTURE MAY REAP IMMEDIATE GAINS FROM CHINA TRADE PACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles-area business leaders hailed the
congressional vote Wednesday approving permanent normal trade
relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   While the nation's trade deficit with China is likely to widen
initially, business sectors such as the entertainment industry and
agriculture stand to see immediate gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we're going to see the impact phase in over
a period of years,'' said Jack Kyser, chief economist for the Los
Angeles County Economic Development Corp. ``The local industry that
will have the most immediate benefit is the motion picture
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the trade agreement negotiated with China as part of its
accession to the World Trade Organization, Chinese officials agreed
to double their quota of American films they allow to show in
China. The number of films allowed will go from 10 to 20 when China
enters the WTO.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles area is well-positioned to take advantage of
open trade with China, Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a market that can be significant for us, but
it's not going to happen immediately. There will be opposition to
this agreement internally in China,'' Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   Some agriculture concerns in China already are stating their
opposition because of the threat of being undercut by American
growers.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Quarles, vice president of corporate relations for Van
Nuys, Calif.-based Sunkist Growers, said citrus producers already
have begun to see increased sales resulting from the negotiations
with China.
</P>
<P>
   In March, China agreed to reopen its markets to American citrus,
which had been quarantined since 1980, ostensibly because of the
Medfly infestation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our shipments have increased substantially on a weekly basis,
and that's all without advertising and promotion. The reason we
could not advertise and promote is we were not assured of our
market access until today,'' Quarles said. ``Chinese negotiators
made clear ... that if Congress voted PNTR down, all bets were off,
so this vote was absolutely crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ackerman, chief executive officer of the Economic Alliance
of the San Fernando Valley, said the Valley's degree of trade with
China has not been thoroughly measured. The alliance plans to
conduct a study with Kyser's help to estimate the Valley's
international trade.
</P>
<P>
   Although the measure of international trade has not been broken
down to separate out the Valley, Ackerman said he believes the
results will be surprising.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're doing far more than most people realize,''
Ackerman said. ``There are thousands of companies out there that
are engaged in some form of import-export.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's especially positive for the Los Angeles economy because
we already have connections with China,'' Kyser said. ``As China
opens up and they develop a middle class, there's going to be a lot
of things we can send over to them.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the annual reports of the Port of Los Angeles, 3.4
million tons of cargo departed the port bound for China in 1996,
the most recent year for which figures are available.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, 16.2 million tons departed the Port of Long Beach for
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agriculture industry, I think, is a winner, and the
entertainment industry is a winner,'' Kyser said. ``Eventually,
you'll be able to see other industries such as technology.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
