<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AIRLINE-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AN AMBITIOUS AIRLINE MERGER 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, May 25:
</P>
<P>
   There is a morbid expression that no one ever got rich hauling
passengers. Not the railroads. Not the buses. Not the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   That is the backdrop for the proposed takeover of US Airways,
the sixth-largest domestic carrier, by United Airlines, the leading
domestic carrier. Ordinarily, a merger that decreased competition
would be worrisome. But airlines are not ordinary. Though
profitable over the past couple of years during ebullient economic
times, they struggle year in and year out to make a decent profit.
They are plagued by chronic excess capacity and gigantic losses
when the economy slips. By wringing out excess costs and creating
large networks that provide lots of travel options and convenient
schedules, mergers can do consumers more good than harm. Whether
that is true in this case will not be known until the Justice
Department completes an exhaustive review.
</P>
<P>
   United, whose employees own a majority of the company, has many
international partners and domestic routes that spread out from
centrally located ``hub'' airports. The merger gives it more routes
in lucrative eastern markets and a prized asset, the shuttle route
from Boston to New York to Washington. US Airways, by contrast,
lacks international heft and even full national reach. Its labor
costs are high and its labor relations sour. It is racking up
losses even as the rest of the industry makes record profits. For
this struggling carrier, United offers a lifeline. If Justice
decides that US Airways cannot survive on its own and that the
merged airline will offer travelers better schedules, one-stop
ticketing and more attractive frequent-flier programs, then
approval will follow.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice has taken an aggressive stance against airline
mergers, for good reason. There are often specific airports _ in
this case, in Washington, Baltimore, New York and Boston _ where
mergers threaten to strip travelers of competition. To solve this
problem at Reagan National Airport in Washington, US Airways has
announced it would turn over many of its routes to a new airline,
DC Air. Justice, however, may find other pockets of diminished
competition and demand further divestiture.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers often blame the airline deregulation of the late
1970s, and the merger wave it spawned, for flight delays, baggage
mix-ups, cramped leg room and other woes. But most of this
criticism is misplaced, according to a recent study by Clifford
Winston of the Brookings Institution and Steven Morrison of
Northeastern University. Mergers, they say, have not raised fares
and have been pursued to cut costs. Indeed, average prices have
fallen by more than 25 percent under deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   True, travelers flying to locations served by only one airline
may find themselves paying prices they consider exorbitant. There
are also some troubling allegations of anti-competitive behavior,
such as attempts by large carriers at their hub airports to drive
smaller rivals out of business by cutting prices temporarily to
punishingly low levels and then raising them when the competition
is driven away. It will be Justice's task to determine whether this
proposed merger is benign or threatens to jack up prices and
diminish service.
</P>
<P>
   Labor opposition could still derail the merger. The pilots'
union at United scuttled an earlier effort to merge the two
carriers out of fear that many of its members would lose seniority.
Meshing the employee-owners of United with the often disgruntled,
costly employees of US Airways may prove a graver threat to
completing the merger than anything thrown in the way by antitrust
authorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
