<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ENVIRONMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK BANS GAS ADDITIVE, EMISSION PERMIT SALES
</HEADLINE>
 By RAYMOND HERNANDEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki signed two major environmental
bills into law Wednesday, including a ban on the use of a common
gasoline additive that has polluted underground water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki also signed legislation that tries to limit the amount of
pollutants drifting into New York from coal-burning power plants in
Midwestern and Southern states, and causing acid rain. The measure
seeks to stop New York companies from selling their federal
pollution allowances, which they now earn by cleaning up their own
smokestacks, to polluters in those other states.
</P>
<P>
   The New York laws potentially conflict with the federal Clean
Air Act of 1990 and set the stage for a protracted legal fight with
the state's energy and petroleum producers.
</P>
<P>
   Energy industry representatives called both measures illegal and
said they were considering court challenges, asserting that New
York had no authority to supersede federal law. The law banning
pollution credit sales goes into effect immediately, and the ban on
the gas additive is to take effect in January 2004.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's aides Wednesday acknowledged the potential legal
problems with both laws, but contended the state's action should at
least send a message to Washington that there were deficiencies in
the federal law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that neither legislation is perfect,'' said
Michael McKeon, a spokesman for the governor, adding, ``We want to
see a resolution of both these issues on the national level, and we
think this pushes that debate forward. ''
</P>
<P>
   David Cohen, a spokesman for the federal Environmental
Protection Agency, said he could not comment on the legality of the
two New York laws because it's a matter for the courts to decide.
But he said that the agency had the same concerns as New York, and
that it was seeking to address them either through EPA regulations
or new federal legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We share the concerns of the state and are working toward the
same end,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   The gasoline additive being banned in New York is known as
methyl tertiary butyl esther, or MTBE.
</P>
<P>
   Under the federal 1990 Clean Air Act, oil companies had to
reformulate gasoline to increase oxygen content to burn more
cleanly and reduce toxic emissions. The oil industry ultimately
settled on MTBE as the gasoline additive that would best meet the
mandate. But because many underground gasoline stoage tanks leak,
MTBE tends to escape even faster than gasoline . As a result, MTBE
has tainted the water in an unknown number of places around the
country. A possible carcinogen, the chemical is also suspected of
being toxic to the nervous system when consumed in large
quantities, though the exact health effects are unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The New York law would force the petroleum industry to find
another additive that would achieve the oxygen-content mandate of
the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   The legality of the new law is unclear. The Clean Air Act
explicitly says states cannot mandate what kind of gasoline
additive the petroleum industry uses to meet emissions standards.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, California was the only state to ban the additive.
California is not regulated by the Clean Air Act because the state
has tougher rules that pre-date the federal act.
</P>
<P>
   New York is the first state where the ban might face a legal
challenge. The other bill that the governor signed prohibits New
York companies from selling federal permits for sulfur dioxide
emissions to polluters in 10 states, mainly in the Midwest and the
South. Pollution from companies in these states has been blamed for
acid rain in environmentally fragile areas of New York, like the
Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   The federal permits _ essentially the right to pollute _ are
awarded to companies that cut their own emissions below federal
standards. It's legal for one company to sell its unused permits to
power companies with older facilities that find it cheaper than
spending on new equipment to reduce pollution.
</P>
<P>
   The New York law imposes a fine on companies equal to the amount
of pollution permit sales, and the money would be used to develop
clean energy sources like solar power.
</P>
<P>
   The New York law drew sharp attacks from representatives of the
state's utility industry, who said it potentially violates the
interstate commerce clause of the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   The law prohibits New York power companies from selling their
pollution credits to companies in 10 Southern and Midwestern
states: Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, West Virginia, Ohio,
Michigan, Illinois, Kentucky, Indiana and Wisconsin. It also
prohibits sales to four states nearby: New Jersey, Maryland,
Pennsylvania and Delaware.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
