<HEADLINE>
CURTIS MOVING TO RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Left fielder Rusty Greer is expected to be
activated off the disabled list tomorrow when he joins the Rangers
in Minnesota. When Greer is activated, Chad Curtis will move to
right field and share playing time with Jason McDonald while Gabe
Kapler remains sidelined with a strained hip flexor, manager Johnny
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis is a right-handed hitter, and McDonald is a switch hitter
who hits much better from the left side. Oates said Curtis will
play against all left-handed pitchers and some right-handed
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curtis is an everyday big-league player,'' Oates said. ``He'll
get a lot of playing time in right.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald has speed, and Curtis had a .500 slugging percentage
going into last night's game, with 11 doubles and six homers in 136
at-bats. He gives the Rangers a better chance of a big inning early
in the game, and McDonald's speed gives them a better chance of
manufacturing runs late.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said the ideal situation would be for Curtis to play seven
innings, then have McDonald come in for the final two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good with Curtis at the plate,'' Oates said. ``He's
been in the middle of a lot of big innings for us. But so has
Jason. They've both done well. We've gotten a lot out of both of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers need for that to continue because Kapler is likely
to miss at least two more weeks after reinjuring a hip flexor
Monday while playing for Triple-A Oklahoma on
medical-rehabilitation assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be awhile,'' trainer Danny Wheat said. ``It could be
several days before he even runs.''  &QL; 
Catalanotto still hurting
</P>
<P>
   Rangers infielder Frank Catalanotto has a new glove, but it
could be several days before he's able to use it. Catalanotto is
sidelined with a strained groin muscle, a problem that has plagued
him for most of the season, and is available only for pinch-hitting
duty.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates, growing weary of the situation, said he won't let
Catalanotto play the field until the medical staff assures Oates
that Catalanotto won't reinjure the leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go like this all summer,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Catalanotto: ``I can only go when it allows me to go, and
right now it's not allowing me to go. Hopefully, it won't linger
all year. The last couple of days I've felt encouraged.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said Catalanotto's injury isn't hurting the Rangers right
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a nice little bat to go up there once a night,'' Oates
said. ``Now is the time to let him heal; everybody else is playing
well.''  &QL; 
Alicea leads off Johnny Oates was considering using Rusty Greer as
a leadoff hitter when Greer returns from the disabled list. But
Oates has scratched that idea for now. Luis Alicea, going into last
night's game, had batted lead off in 11 consecutive games and hit
.362 in that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a leadoff hitter doing very well,'' Oates said.
``Rusty will be better in the No. 2 spot with his pop and his
on-base percentage.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
