<HEADER>
A5177 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RAC-GALLOWAY-DESORMEA     05-24 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-GALLOWAY-DESORMEAUX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH JOB? TRY JOCKEY FOR SIZE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As far as his doubters go, Troy Aikman said this week at Valley
Ranch that he understands and accepts the reasoning behind the
current flak. If nothing else, it comes with the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody'' is a quarterback critic. Everybody is always ready
with an instant opinion on how the quarterback played, as opposed
to say, the left guard, the linebacker, the running back, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is arguably the toughest position in sports,'' Aikman said.
</P>
<P>
   For pressure and snap judgments by the masses, what else is
close? As we're now seeing, maybe goalie this deep in the NHL
playoffs, and you'd certainly have to add to the list a pitcher in
the playoffs or World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But there was also a little fellow at Lone Star Park at Grand
Prairie yesterday who definitely measures up _ all 5-foot-3, 114
pounds of him _ when it comes to dealing with ready-made heat in
the pursuit of his chosen profession.
</P>
<P>
   Take a ride with Kent Desormeaux, arguably the best jockey of
thoroughbred racing's current era. Climb into the saddle aboard
Fusaichi Pegasus last Saturday in the Preakness at Baltimore, the
second leg of the Triple Crown. Understand that your sport and the
multibillion-dollar industry that surrounds it, is counting on
``Fu-Peg'' to be the next Secretariat, the first super 3-year-old
of the 2000s.
</P>
<P>
   A super horse, which this one appeared to be in winning the
Kentucky Derby, is sure to draw a massive audience and attention to
a sport that doesn't come close to the overall national appeal of
something like the NFL or Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Thoroughbred racing needs another Secretariat. It didn't,
however, get him last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux and ``Fu-Peg'' ran a well-beaten second to Red
Bullet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand where Troy is coming from, but then again, he's
kinda at the mercy of how well his offensive line plays,''
Desormeaux said. ``If the guys up front aren't doing their job,
then Troy can't do what he does best.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in this sport, you can be on the perfect horse, but if
something happens with another horse that impedes your horse, and
you don't win the race, then you're going to get blamed. And even
if you've got the perfect horse, and get the perfect trip, but
another horse happens to run better, you still get blamed.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiling, Desormeaux added, ``We hear it all the time _ `what was
that pin-head thinking?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Horse racing and pro football have one common trait _ wagering.
No other team sport in this country, or maybe the world, matches
the NFL for the amount of money bet on games, legally and
illegally. In wagering, it is second only to horse racing, a sport
driven by the ``handle.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans can be passionate without any wagering. But put 10 bucks or
so on the outcome, and the howls, plus the second-guessing from the
``losers,'' grow noticeably louder.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with that,'' said Desormeaux, who has heard it all
before, many times.
</P>
<P>
   But the second-guessing of Desormeaux in the Preakness was
actually minimal, if it all. A little bit of ``did he go too wide
\Ron the turn for home\S'' was heard, but reality said Red Bullet
was simply the better horse on this particular day. Fusaichi
Pegasus was running two weeks after his monster effort in the
Derby. Red Bullet had skipped Louisville, and was well-rested for a
drying-out Preakness track rated as ``good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't go that well around the turns, which was kind of a
tipoff that the track was greasy and he wasn't taking to it,''
Desormeaux said. ``This is a huge, huge, massive beast of a horse,
and that kind of track could have been a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I still thought we'd win, and really didn't become
concerned until about the three-eighth pole \Rleading into the
stretch\S, and Jerry \RBailey on Red Bullet\S and I had one horse
in front of us. We were rubbing shoulders and eye-balling each
other, meaning the next question was, who would push the button
first?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then both of us moved at the same time. He went inside, I went
outside, but \RFusaichi Pegasus\S was struggling when I asked for
his run.''
</P>
<P>
   Just one of those days ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember the time frame between the Preakness and the Derby,
and remember Red Bullet skipped the Derby,'' Desormeaux offered.
``My horse is still a super horse, and that will be proven in the
long run.''
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux, who is Southern California-based, was in Grand
Prairie to promote next month's (June 23) All-Star Jockey
Championship, one of the best events of the summer at Lone Star.
Eleven of the nation's top jockeys will be competing. ``It's the
Rider's Cup, the real one,'' said Desormeaux, ``and we're going to
be here to put on a show for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, jockeys, like quarterbacks, are only as good as
their last ride/game. Aikman knows. Desormeaux knows. It comes with
the job. {Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram.} &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
