<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 23:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5178 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-RAC-DESORMEAUX-JOCKEY     05-24 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DESORMEAUX-JOCKEYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOCKEY'S LOSS IN PREAKNESS CAN'T COMPARE WITH SON'S HEARING DEFECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND PRAIRIE, Texas _ Other than his belief that Fusaichi
Pegasus couldn't handle the wet track in the Preakness Stakes,
jockey Kent Desormeaux won't hem and haw about why his colt lost.
That he and Fusaichi Pegasus had a wider trip around the track than
Red Bullet doesn't account for much in Desormeaux's book.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a pathetic excuse,'' Desormeaux said. ``Red
Bullet was one horse inside of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``That horse was fresh. He ran an awesome race.''
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux was at Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie yesterday for
the announcement of the 12 riders who will compete in the All-Star
Jockey Championship on June 23. He was low on excuses, but high on
other things despite difficulty in his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Desormeaux won the Kentucky Derby on Fusaichi
Pegasus, doctors had confirmed to him and his wife Sonia that their
15-month-old son, Jacob, was deaf. As much as he's being asked
about Fusaichi Pegasus and the next race in the Belmont Stakes,
Desormeaux is being asked how things are for his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still being schooled on what his hearing defects are,''
Desormeaux said. ``The `why' and how to fix it are what we're
trying to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux, 30, will be joined by Robby Albarado, Jorge Chavez,
Pat Day, Craig Perret, Laffit Pincay Jr., Edgar Prado, Jose Santos,
Shane Sellers, Mike Smith and Alex Solis in the All-Star Jockey
Championship. The only name that's yet to be added is the leading
rider at Lone Star through June 4, and that's currently Donnie
Meche by nine victories over Glenn Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Desormeaux said he and his family _ he and
Sonia also have a 7-year-old son, Joshua _ refuse to pout or make
excuses over their circumstances. Desormeaux himself lost the
hearing in his left ear after complications from skull injuries in
a spill during the races in 1992 at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   His family is trying to make things better with Jacob by
learning sign language, though they haven't given up hope that
Jacob will someday be able to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call me selfish,'' Desormeaux said, ``but I hope one day that
Jacob will hear his mother coming home through the door one day and
he can run up to her and say `Mommy, I love you.' There's nothing
more I'd like to give my wife _ and Jacob _ than that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the family is learning sign language. It's
creating togetherness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to do this together as a family,'' Desormeaux said.
``We've become so much closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jacob is getting pretty good at it. He knows how to ask for
food when he's hungry. And Josh loves to learn how to say things
\Rin sign language\S like `cat.' Josh is eager to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   His family watches the bonding and thinks it's great to see, but
sad at the same time. Desormeaux's older brother, Keith, is a
trainer based at Lone Star. He said he's extremely close to his
brother, only three years separating them in age, and sees how his
brother is growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to think that for all of us to get stronger, it's
because of what this boy is going through,'' Keith Desormeaux said.
``But that'll be the bright side of this. It'll bring this family
closer together.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot of kid in Kent. But there's no doubt that
this will play a big part in his maturation. These are the sorts of
things that make us who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Kent Desormeaux has been tried by tough times professionally. In
1998, he took criticism for possibly moving too early on Real Quiet
in the Belmont Stakes. Real Quiet would have won the Triple Crown
by winning the Belmont, but he blew a four-length lead in the
stretch and lost.
</P>
<P>
   After the race, Desormeaux was jeered by a handful of vocal
fans. It couldn't have been a scene that Desormeaux would want his
kids to see, but Desormeaux wouldn't mind if Jacob could hear it.
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux said his son has deadened nerve endings in the ears.
Doctors are fitting him with a special hearing aid. If that doesn't
work, doctors will implant a device onto the cochlea inside the ear
that will transmit radio waves into the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's profound,'' Desormeaux said.
</P>
<P>
   More profound than Fusaichi Pegasus' rematch with Red Bullet in
the Belmont. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
