<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5180 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-MATVICHUK-TEXSTAR     05-24 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-MATVICHUK-TEX </SLUG>
 STARS' MATVICHUK HAS BEEN A FORCE (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) By CHAREAN WILLIAMS c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Colorado Avalanche seems to bring out the
best in Stars defenseman Richard Matvichuk.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Matvichuk broke the Avalanche's bones. This year, he
has broken their spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter if it's Colorado or Edmonton,'' Matvichuk
said yesterday. ``I show up every night when I get to the rink
knowing that my job is to shut the top line of the opposing team
down, and that's how I look at every game.''
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk hurt the Avs' chances of winning the 1999 Western
Conference Finals when he unintentionally took out two of their
best players in Game 4. Milan Hejduk ended his season with a
cracked collarbone. Peter Forsberg was not the same after suffering
a separated left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   This year, in the Stars' 3-2 overtime victory in Game 5 on
Tuesday, Matvichuk again played the part of Avs killer.
</P>
<P>
   He was all over the place. He was behind goalie Ed Belfour
getting a big save one minute and in front of the net setting up
Joe Nieuwendyk for the game-winner in another. In between, he and
defensive partner Derian Hatcher were containing Forsberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had very strong games in Games 4 and 5 _ excellent
games,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``He's done a much better
job of moving the puck. Him and Derian are more comfortable in the
way the series is unfolding now. They've had bigger bites in every
game. Matty's defensive awareness has allowed Derian to start
roaming a little bit, so Derian's had a bigger bite in the series,
because he's been able to move up the ice again, which is good.''
</P>
<P>
   At 9:45 of the first period Tuesday, Belfour left the crease to
play the high shot of Stephane Yelle.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour thought Matvichuk was going to clear the puck, and
Matvichuk thought Belfour was going to clear it. Instead, Avs
forward Shjon Podein found an open net waiting for his shot.
Matvichuk stuck his stick down just in time for the save.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just was fortunate being in the right place at the right
time,'' Matvichuk said. ``We don't want to do that too often. We
got our communication mixed up a little bit. Luckily, it didn't go
in our net.''
</P>
<P>
   In overtime, Matvichuk's shot was deflected past Colorado goalie
Patrick Roy by Joe Nieuwendyk. It was Matvichuk's second point in
two games. He scored the Stars' fourth goal in a 4-1 victory
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I'm on the ice, my job is to keep the puck out of
my net,'' Matvichuk said. ``Fortunately, the last couple of games,
I've had a couple of offensive opportunities. There's no way I look
for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk and Hatcher have silenced Forsberg, which is the key
to stopping the Avs. Since 1996, Colorado is 19-7 in playoff games
when Forsberg scores a goal.
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg, who had four goals on 12 shots in the Western
Conference semifinals against the Detroit Red Wings, has one goal
on 18 shots in this series. He took only one shot in Game 5 _ a
slap shot from the right circle that Belfour caught with his glove
_ and it came on a second-period power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a matter of shutting them \RForsberg and second-line
center Joe Sakic\S completely down, because I don't think that can
be done,'' Matvichuk said. ``It's just a matter of containment. In
key situations in the game, if we can keep them off the scoreboard,
it's going to be to our advantage. So far, it's been to our
advantage, because they haven't had four or five goals a game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
