<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERISHO OUT OF OPTIONS; SO ARE RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Rangers' drive toward first place has
been impressive considering they've done it with one pitcher tied
behind their back.
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed Matt Perisho, the Rangers' long reliever, has gone
more than two weeks without pitching. His long layoff, and
ineffectiveness when he has pitched, have reduced his value to
manager Johnny Oates and increased Perisho's frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think something has to be done,'' Perisho said. ``I'm
all for the team, and being on a winning team is a lot of fun. But
when you're just sitting out there day after day, it's hard to feel
a part of the team. That's the hardest thing, trying to think I'm
not just out there taking up space.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Doug Melvin is sympathetic and discussed the
situation Tuesday with Perisho's agent. But, even though a roster
move is forthcoming to make room for Rusty Greer, Melvin doesn't
see it being time to make a move with Perisho. The Rangers are
leaning toward returning Danny Kolb to the minors. He hasn't
pitched in a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough situation for Matt,'' Melvin said. ``You'd like
to be able to give him a shot, but it's been tough to get him in a
ballgame. He's sort of designated as our long guy, but we haven't
had that many situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Perisho's problem is he is out of options. Melvin acknowledged
Perisho would be better off pitching in Triple A, but Perisho would
have to clear outright waivers, and the Rangers are sure he would
be claimed by another team. Oakland recently tried to send pitcher
Ron Mahay through waivers, but Florida claimed him.
</P>
<P>
   As far as trading Perisho, as the Rangers did with Robb Nen in
1993 when he was in a similar situation, Melvin said: ``There's
always that thought. You think about it. You'll move anybody if you
can get value in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you talk to clubs about pitching, they're not gung-ho
about somebody who is out of options. They want flexibility, a guy
who can be moved back and forth'' from the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Perisho isn't the only player in this situation. Seattle has
three pitchers out of options: Paul Abbott, Frankie Rodriguez and
Jose Paniagua. Toronto has John Frascatore, Boston has Rich Garces
and the New York Mets have Pat Mahomes.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' problem is they're turning a 24-year-old
left-hander who won 15 games at Triple A last year into a
seldom-used mop-up man. He went 10 days without pitching, then gave
up 10 runs against Oakland on May 5. Four days later, he gave up
five runs against Seattle. He hasn't pitched since.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to put me on waivers because they don't want
to lose me, but they can't come up with a solution that works for
both parties,'' Perisho said. ``It's not doing anybody any good.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2341EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0485 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5183 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-FRUSTRA     05-24 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-FRUSTRATED-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVALANCHE PLAYERS ARE GROWING FRUSTRATED, BUT SAY THEY REMAIN
CONFIDENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Colorado Avalanche players find themselves in the
unique position of trying to figure out how to win while knowing
they have played some of their best offensive hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Key defensive breakdowns and remarkable play from Stars goalie
Ed Belfour have the Avs on the brink of elimination. Belfour has
stopped 105 of 110 shots in the past three games and the Stars have
seven goals on 35 shots against Patrick Roy in the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think it's very odd,'' Avs winger Dave Andreychuk said
regarding their two-game losing streak and 3-2 series deficit
despite feeling as though they controlled most of Games 4 and 5.
``You have to get some breaks, some things to go your way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avs, frustrated and dismayed by their inability to beat
Belfour on all kinds of chances, firmly believe they have outworked
and outplayed the big-play defending champions in this
best-of-seven Western Conference Finals that resumes today with
Game 6 at the Pepsi Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty happy with the way we are playing,'' Avs winger
Adam Deadmarsh said. ``We are getting lots of shots on net, we're
skating very well, we're playing with lots of speed. Against
Dallas, that's what you have to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's spirits are up. We're down 3-2, but it's kind of a
different feeling around this dressing room. We know we aren't
dead, our confidence is right there, we just have to keep
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avs have reason to be confident. They've been as good or
better than the Stars in all categories except one _ goaltending.
Belfour has been spectacular. Roy has been good.
</P>
<P>
   The Avs are 7-1 at home in the playoffs, although the Stars won
the last game at the Pepsi Center, 4-1, despite being outshot,
39-15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game 6 is probably going to be the toughest game we have to
face in this year's playoffs,'' Stars center Mike Modano said.
``And I expect Denver and all of their best players are going to
play their best game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avs will attempt to put more traffic in front of Belfour and
be more physical in the crease. Mostly, they will need key
contributions from some slumbering giants if the Western Finals
series is to return to Dallas for a Game 7 for the second
consecutive:
</P>
<P>
   The Avs' once-potent power play has gone sour. Ray Bourque had
seven of his eight regular-season goals with the Avs on the man
advantage. He is still looking for his first playoff goal, and the
Avs are only 1-for-18 on the power play in the past three games.
Sandis Ozolinsh has also been a nonfactor on the power play and a
liability with the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so much talent on both of our units that we have to
trust those guys,'' Avs coach Bob Hartley said. ``Those guys will
make it happen, and we just need a goal to get our swing back in
the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Sakic and Andreychuk must cash in their chances. Neither has
scored a goal this series despite a wealth of opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have confidence in our abilities,'' Sakic said. ``We
know we've been playing well. We just have to tear it up a little
more and maybe get some more shots and more screens on Eddie.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Forsberg must play like the dominant player he is. He has
only one goal in the series, coming in the third period of Game 2
when the Avs trailed, 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's because we are playing bad,'' Forsberg
said. ``We're playing pretty good hockey. I think we can make it
better in a few areas and just go out and put the puck in the
net.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
