<SLUG> BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVS WORRIED ABOUT POWER PLAY THAT CONTINUES TO COME UP SHORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The Avalanche is officially concerned about their power
play that has generated only two goals in their past 23 tries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have much to be confident about on our power play,''
Avs winger Adam Deadmarsh said. ``We have to try to get some shots
at the net. When we do get the opportunity, we have to take it
because it's not there that often. It comes down to hard work and
winning battles, and we've got the extra guy out there so we're
going to have to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Avs have not scored on the power play since Deadmarsh
redirected a Martin Skoula shot from the point at the 14:50 mark of
the second period in Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   The Avs want to increase pressure in front of Stars goalie Ed
Belfour. Deadmarsh and Dave Andreychuk are responsible for crowding
the net, redirecting shots and screening Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to try to get second and third chances and bear down
on our chances,'' Andreychuk said. ``We are going to have to go to
the net a little bit more, start hanging around the net. That's the
way we are going to get goals.'' \Nsubheds:Sakic's help needed
Center Joe Sakic didn't score in Game 5 despite multiple chances,
including two golden opportunities to send the Avs home with a 3-2
lead instead of trailing.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he was the Avs' best offensive player in the game. He set
up Milan Hejduk's game-tying goal in the third period with some
dazzling skating. Sakic's line was busy. Hejduk finished with four
shots and while Dave Andreychuk had only one shot, he had chances
around the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Joe is on his way,'' Avalanche coach Bob Hartley said.
``I like the way that his game is picking up, how he's generating
\Roffense\S and he's skating very well. It's just a matter of being
rewarded. We need one goal from Joe and I think we could be on our
way.'' \Nsubheds:Line decisions
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hartley will likely leave center Chris Drury on the first
line with wingers Peter Forsberg and Adam Deadmarsh. He made that
change for Game 5, which put Stephane Yelle on the third line with
Dave Reid and Shjon Podein.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not set yet in our line combinations, but I don't think
you are going to see many changes or major changes,'' Hartley said.
``I like the chemistry of our team. I like the chances we
generated.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Forsberg double-shifted some with Yelle and Reid. That
line produced a goal in Game 5 when Jon Klemm scored off Yelle's
rebound. \Nsubheds:Roy remains focused Patrick Roy as allowed seven
goals on 35 shots in the past two games to drive his goals-against
average up from 1.52 to 1.76. His save percentage dropped to .928,
for the first time dipping below Ed Belfour (.932).
</P>
<P>
   Hartley called Roy's performances the past two games,
``excellent'' and said he is ``very focused.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to look at the goals, it is very misleading,'' Hartley
said. ``Brett Hull is on fire, he's firing cannonballs. You look at
their winning goal \Rin Game 5 from Joe Nieuwendyk\S, there are not
many goalies that could have done on this. Patrick knows what he
has to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
