A5189 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-OLY-TRIATHLON-TRIALS-     05-24 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-TRIATHLON-TRIALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC TRIATHLON TEAM MEMBER WENT THE EXTRA MILE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two men who swim, bike and run their way onto the U.S.
Olympic triathlon team this weekend have one unselfish soul to
thank.
</P>
<P>
   You're quite welcome, Olympian Hunter Kemper would say.
</P>
<P>
   It was Kemper who, after thinking he had earned his way onto the
U.S. team by being the first American to finish at the Sydney World
Cup, discovered at the finish line that he next had to negotiate a
two-week thicket of triathlon politics and rankings voodoo.
</P>
<P>
   He did, racing in places like New Caledonia and Perth. And as a
result, the U.S. men's team climbed to 12th in the world rankings
and gained two extra spots at the Olympic starting line in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Sydney World Cup race, though, I just wanted to go
home,'' Kemper said. ``The whole time I was in New Caledonia, I was
thinking things like, `I shouldn't be here. I should already have
my spot. I earned it in Sydney. This isn't fair.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In a nutshell, he shouldn't have. He did. And it wasn't. But the
hope is that when the next Olympics rolls around, USA Triathlon
officials will better understand the vagaries of the sport's world
rankings and how to stay in the good graces of them.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Kemper now knows that he is definitely headed to
the Sydney Games. The U.S. Olympic triathlon trials men's race on
Sunday will determine which two other athletes will join Kemper.
</P>
<P>
   The trials will begin Saturday with the women's race, scheduled
to start at 9 a.m. at Lake Carolyn at Las Colinas in Irving, Texas.
The men will swim, bike and run the same course beginning at 10
a.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Kemper, 24, knows he doesn't have to compete in the trials, but
he says that was never a consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is really off me,'' he said. ``But I want to race
because of the prize money and the exposure. Hopefully, people will
see this as a really clean and polished event and it's going to
help the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm going into the race to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   As the 1999 U.S. Olympic Committee's triathlete of the year, the
reigning national champion and the Pan Am Games silver medalist,
Kemper has as good a chance as anyone. His strength in the
triathlon is the running portion, even though Kemper began his
athletic career as an accomplished swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   At age 10, growing up in Longwood, Fla., Kemper was lured into
the IronKids Triathlon program by some swimming buddies. He won the
first triathlon he ever attended. As a 13-year-old, his success
landed him in ``Sports Illustrated'''s ``Faces in the Crowd''
section.
</P>
<P>
   But as college neared, Kemper realized that to get to the
triathlon's next level, he would have to improve as a runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a 4:38 miler coming out of high school _ a bad runner,''
he said. ``Nobody was looking at me at all. I was so bad, in fact,
that I sent my stuff to Wake Forest _ my personal bests, my times,
my highlights _ and they sent me back the women's media guide. They
thought I was a female.''
</P>
<P>
   He ended up as a walk-on on the Wake Forest track team and
shelved the triathlon for three seasons for that he could improve
his running. By his senior year, Kemper had finished second in the
10,000 meters at the Atlantic Coast Conference championships.
</P>
<P>
   Kemper graduated in 1998 and promptly became USA Triathlon's
rookie of the year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2346EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
