<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5190 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-WHITESOX-     05-24 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-WHITESOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BREAK OUT _ FOR ONE NIGHT, AT LEAST _ IN 12-4 WIN OVER
CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Their slump is consuming, the Yankees will admit
readily. They haven't hit, they haven't fielded, their best player
is hurt and they have been frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   But these are the times when you must grind your way through,
Manager Joe Torre said, and after looking defeated in the early
innings Wednesday night, the Yankees roared back with 11 runs in
their last three at-bats to beat Chicago, 12-4. The victory was
badly needed, with the Yankees set to face undefeated pitcher James
Baldwin on Thursday and the Red Sox coming to Yankee Stadium on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had 13 hits over the last three innings, 18 in all,
a season high. Paul O'Neill blew open the game with a three-run
double, Jorge Posada had three hits and two RBIs and Andy Pettitte
(3-2) pitched seven innings. Derek Jeter, the Yankees' shortstop
who is coming back from a strained abdomen, took batting practice
in Tampa, Fla., and could return to the lineup Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if the slump was going to deepen. It looked as if
the Yankees were going to lose their fourth straight. Bernie
Williams attempted to make a sliding catch of Jose Valentin's line
drive in the third inning, missed and the ball rolled behind him
and kept rolling, until Valentin had a triple that increased
Chicago's lead to 2-0. In their 42nd game, the Yankees were at
their lowest point in the season, their offense moribund, their
frustration mounting, losing again, some players believing
privately the team needs an injection of talent.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Thomas came to bat, the Yankees infield moved in with only
one out. Another hit and the Chicago lead would be three runs. But
Pettitte whipped a fastball over the inside corner to get Thomas,
then fooled Magglio Ordonez, another strikeout. A spark.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored their first run against Mike Sirotka in the
fourth inning, and Pettitte kept shutting down the White Sox,
glaring in for the signs from Posada, the brim of Pettitte's cap
casting shadow over his face.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Spencer drew a walk to open the sixth and Posada blasted a
high drive to left _ and grimaced when it curled foul just before
reaching the pole. Then Posada grounded into a double play and that
could have convinced the Yankees of a luckless fate.
</P>
<P>
   But trailing by a run, they picked at the White Sox in the
seventh. Scott Brosius coaxed a leadoff walk and Jim Leyritz,
pinch-hitting for Ricky Ledee, took a couple of close pitches and
also walkde. The hard-throwing Bob Howry relieved Sirotka. The
left-handed hitting Lance Johnson pinch-hit for Clay Bellinger.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson turned to bunt, some White Sox fans who remembered
his days in Chicago might have snickered: Johnson was a lousy
bunter then, and now, and he popped a ball foul that first baseman
Paul Konerko nearly reached. Johnson stepped out, looked to the
third base coach Willie Randolph.
</P>
<P>
   The bunt sign was off, and with the White Sox infield aligned in
bunt defense, Johnson bounced a single through the middle, scoring
Brosius with the tying run. Johnson's hit severed a tension cord
wrapped around the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch slammed a single, another run scored. Bernie
Williams lined a single to right, loading the bases. Howry was out
for the White Sox, Bill Simas was in. But O'Neill swung at a Simas
fastball and lowered his head, the way he does when he knows he has
crushed the ball.
</P>
<P>
   As O'Neill's drive soared to left-center, outfielders in
pursuit, Johnson retreated to third to prepare to tag up, Knoblauch
moved halfway between second and third, and Williams rounded
second, waiting like a picket line _ until O'Neill's liner slammed
against the fence. Johnson ran home standing, and Knoblauch did,
too, beckoning Williams with a wave of his hand, not knowing that
Williams was sliding across the plate right behind him. The
Yankees' dugout came alive with high fives and shouts.
</P>
<P>
   Two batters later, Posada blistered a line drive down the right
field line and it slammed against the foul pole. A home run, a
fitting finish to a seven-run inning, after his long foul ball the
inning before. The Yankees added two more runs in the eighth.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Yankees are still looking to add a hitter. They are not
close to making a deal, although club executives are being
persistent in their attempts to identify a trade target. At least
three players fit the profile of what Yankees' executives would
want: Baltimore's B.J. Surhoff (the Orioles could ask for Ricky
Ledee and an outfield prospect like Jackson Melian in return);
Houston's Moises Alou, who was discussed in a conversation between
executives of the Yankees and Astros in recent days; and Oakland's
Matt Stairs.
</P>
<P>
   The Athletics have asked for Alfonso Soriano or Ramiro Mendoza,
while the Yankees have countered with an offer of prospect Jake
Westbrook and another minor leaguer, which Oakland rebuffed. With
this set of talks at a stalemate, Stairs was told Wednesday he is
not being traded _ which could be construed as an artful way of
covering up the fact he was dangled in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees also have talked to teams about Detroit's Juan
Gonzalez, Kansas City's Johnny Damon, Tampa Bay's Jose Canseco, and
Minnesota's Matt Lawton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0490 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CLINTON-DISBARME     05-24 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CLINTON-DISBARMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CLINTON'S DISBARMENT CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, May 25:
</P>
<P>
   In recommending that President Clinton be disbarred for
providing false testimony in the Paula Jones sexual harassment
case, a disciplinary committee of the Arkansas Supreme Court has
called for the harshest sanction at its disposal. The Arkansas
courts will now have to decide whether disbarment is the right
penalty for the president's dishonesty, given all the
circumstances, or whether some lesser penalty such as a public
reprimand or suspension of his license to practice law is more
appropriate. But there is no doubt that Clinton must be called to
account for his legal misconduct and that this disbarment
proceeding is the appropriate forum in which to hold him
accountable.
</P>
<P>
   The false testimony at the root of this matter came in 1998
during a deposition in the lawsuit by Paula Jones alleging that
Clinton, while governor of Arkansas, had sexually harassed her. At
one point Clinton, in attempting to deflect questions designed to
show a pattern of bad behavior, denied having had sexual relations
with Monica Lewinsky. The president contended then, and continues
to maintain, that he did not technically lie because the activities
he engaged in with Lewinsky did not fit the definition of sexual
relations used in the trial. That argument was demolished by Judge
Susan Webber Wright, who presided over the Paula Jones case.
Cutting to the core issue, she found that the president had given
``intentionally false'' testimony under oath, fined him $90,000 and
referred the matter to the disciplinary committee that has now
recommended disbarment.
</P>
<P>
   The president's supporters cite what they consider mitigating
circumstances. They note that Wright ultimately dismissed the Jones
case and ruled that Clinton's disputed testimony was not germane,
so it is hard to argue that his false testimony harmed anyone. They
add that Clinton's testimony was not delivered as a lawyer but as a
private defendant in a lawsuit that he considered politically
motivated. They also argue that in Arkansas disbarment is typically
reserved for far worse crimes, like stealing from a client. All
these factors need to be considered when the case is assigned to an
Arkansas court. Indeed, the president's advocates are right that
some other lawyers caught lying under oath in Arkansas have
received reprimands rather than being disbarred.
</P>
<P>
   But the president and political allies like Sen. Charles Schumer
of New York demean the legal system when, without providing any
evidence, they depict Clinton as a victim of political bias.
Clinton's troubles did not originate in what Schumer called a
``kangaroo court.'' The president's credentials as an attorney are
under challenge because he decided, after careful planning, to
testify falsely.
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas courts will now have to make an independent
judgment on an appropriate punishment. In doing so, they should
treat Clinton as they would any other lawyer caught giving false
testimony in similar circumstances. They should not punish the
president for who he is, just to make a symbolic statement. Nor
should they grant him special leniency. Clinton deserves equal
justice under the law, no more, no less.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0491 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5194 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      05-24 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAFFORD-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIT BY BIT, BENEFITS ARE BEING CUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A snip here. A clip there. A teensy trim over there. Pretty soon
it all adds up.
</P>
<P>
   You know how it is sometimes when you go in for a haircut. While
it's happening, it doesn't always seem like much is falling to the
floor. But when you leave, you've got a lot less hair than when you
went in, and the floor is littered.
</P>
<P>
   So it is with employee benefits. Snip, snip. Clip, clip. And,
whoa, Nellie. Something looks really different.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate pressures to cut costs and raise profit margins are
pinching employee benefits _ and a lot of employees are saying,
``Ouch.''
</P>
<P>
   A survey released last month by the Society for Human Resource
Management found that from 1999 to 2000, there was a decline in the
number of employers offering paid personal days, paid vacation
days, relocation benefits, employee stock purchase plans, health
screening and prevention programs, and sign-on bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing the results, the national human resource
organization asked whether it was seeing a statistical hiccup or a
reversal of a long-running trend to beef up employee benefits.
</P>
<P>
   If it is the beginning of a downward spiral, human resource
officials say, it's a curious slip, given that the No. 1 complaint
of employers is that it's so hard to hire and keep good people.
</P>
<P>
   Employers whose benefits packages are better than their
competitors' generally earn the coveted ``employer of choice''
label and keep the best talent.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause or duration of benefits cuts, workers are
complaining. Internet gripe sites and my e-mail from readers
reflect the grumbling.
</P>
<P>
   In my own place of employment, rarely a day passes without
hearing a co-worker lament the mileage reimbursement rate paid by
the company for use of personal vehicles on business. For years,
reimbursement has remained at 24 cents a mile; that's now 7 cents a
mile below the Internal Revenue Service's current standard
deductible rate of 31 cents a mile.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the Bureau of National Affairs Inc. reported
this month that 74 percent of employers reimburse mileage at the
rate of 31 cents a mile or higher. Twelve percent pay 28 cents to
30 cents a mile. Only 8 percent of employers reimburse less than 28
cents a mile.
</P>
<P>
   It may look like nickel-and-dime stuff, a petty gripe from
workers who are lucky to be reimbursed at all. But one has only to
look at car and gasoline prices to see why employees protest the
pinch.
</P>
<P>
   When the costs are totaled, the numbers may look good on the
company balance sheet, but there's no measurement of the financial
_ and certainly not the emotional _ costs to employees of benefits'
slippage.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Losey, president of the national Society for Human
Resource Management, speculated that the employee benefits
cafeteria expanded for a while as employers tried to compete for
employees in the tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the slicing and dicing ``may be indicative that a number of
employers found the new benefits too costly or not as effective as
they hoped,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Snip, snip. Clip, clip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-24-00 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000524.0492 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-24 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
