<HEADER>
A5197 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-JESSE-PINKERTONS-KAN &LR;      05-24 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESSE-PINKERTONS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINKERTON TURNS OVER ARCHIVES FROM JESSE JAMES ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Good detectives don't like to show their hand. But
after 150 years, the storied Pinkerton agency is finally revealing
what it had on outlaws such as Jesse James and Butch Cassidy and
the Sundance Kid.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Pinkerton loaded almost 100 boxes of criminal
records, investigative notes, pictures, letters and other materials
on a truck bound for the Library of Congress in Washington, where
they will be available for historians and the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's essential that historians see this archive,'' said Jane
Adler, a Pinkerton archivist hired three years ago to organize the
material in California. ``It's a whole section of American history.
It gives an impression of an enormous enterprise with a very dark
side.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinkerton provided security for scores of banks and railroads,
investigated organized labor, protected presidents and taught
police and the FBI many tricks of its trade. The company pursued
some of the country's most notorious criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The records that were released date from the company's founding
in 1850 to 1938, in the gangster era. The material includes the
only known photo of Etta Place _ the accomplice of Butch Cassidy
and the Sundance Kid; 195 criminal investigation binders;
photographs of President Abraham Lincoln made by the Pinkerton
family; and pictures of slain outlaws.
</P>
<P>
   The collection has been appraised at $500,000, but Pinkerton
decided to donate it rather than sell it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will attract a lot of attention,'' said John Sellers, a
Library of Congress historian who has tried for years to get the
archives. ``We are looking at the prosecution and pursuit of evil
and justice, and from that standpoint it is worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of the most frustrating chapters in Pinkerton's history
revolved around the James gang that plundered banks and trains
across the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we were ever close to getting the James
brothers,'' Adler said. ``They had a lot of community support. They
stayed in remote areas and as soon as anyone went in there, they
were shot on sight, tied up or mistreated.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinkerton is releasing records on crimes the James brothers
committed, details on their gang's members, descriptions that
detectives carried of the two outlaws, wanted posters and some
sketches.
</P>
<P>
   Adler said the records had been reviewed by researchers but not
the public. She doesn't think they reveal anything new, but they
will be checked out by the Jesse James Farm and Museum at Kearney.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be interested in comparing it to the stories we have
here and to our research,'' said Beth Beckett, director of the farm
and museum.
</P>
<P>
   Pinkerton drew public scorn in 1875 when agents raided the James
farm looking for Jesse. Shrapnel from an explosive blew an arm off
his mother, Zerelda Samuels, and killed his 11-year-old
half-brother, Archie Samuels. Jesse was not home.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, there was an outcry for the family and a lot of
sympathy for them,'' Beckett said.
</P>
<P>
   Adler said she could find no records of the raid on the James
farm. Ron Casteel, a Jefferson City authority on the Jameses who
produced a 1990 documentary on their lives, said he has never
gotten much out of Pinkerton on the James brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would just as soon the whole Jesse James era disappear,''
Casteel said. ``Pinkerton scored some success, but getting Jesse
and Frank James wasn't one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   One handicap: ``They had no photos to pass around. People who
had photos were not handing them over to the Pinkertons.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinkerton had better luck catching up with another Missouri
outlaw named William Rudolph, dubbed ``The Missouri Kid.'' Rudolph
was a crafty, handsome but violent outlaw who used his blasting
skills as a miner to blow up banks around the turn of the century.
</P>
<P>
   He became the target of the biggest manhunt in Pinkerton history
after he shot a young Pinkerton detective who happened to be the
son of a company superintendent. Frightened of the pursuit, Rudolph
got himself jailed on a minor offense in hopes he would escape
notice as the much-wanted Missouri Kid.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't work, but Rudolph escaped jail and then was captured
and returned to Missouri for hanging, Adler said. Two letters
pleading for mercy he wrote to company founder Allan Pinkerton will
be part of a special Library of Congress exhibit on Rudolph and
four other Pinkerton cases next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
